window.QUESTIONS = [{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-01-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-01","qNum":1,"question":"One of the following statements regarding the functions of ‘Reserve Bank of India is incorrect?","options":{"a":"It is mandated with the Right to issue bank notes as one of the key central banking functions.","b":"It is the right and obligation of RBI to accept monies on account of the Central Government of India.","c":"It establishes Monetary Policy Committee with an intent to stabilise money supply in the market.","d":"It can authorize any person to be known as authorized person to deal in foreign exchange or in foreign securities."},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nStatement a is correct. Section 22 of the RBI Act confers the RBI with the sole right to issue bank\nnotes in India. The issue of bank notes shall be conducted by a department called the Issue\nDepartment, which shall be separated and kept wholly distinct from the Banking Department.\nRight to issue bank notes is one of the key central banking functions the RBI is mandated to do so.\nStatement b is correct. Section 18 of the RBI Act facilitates the RBI to act as a ‘Lender of Last\nResort’. These provisions of the RBI Act enable the RBI to act as banker to Central Government\nand State Governments. Under Sections 20 and 21 of the RBI Act, the RBI shall have an obligation\nand right respectively to accept monies for account of the Central Government and to make\npayments up to the amount standing to the credit of its account, and to carry out its exchange,\nremittance and other banking operations, including the management of the public debt of the\nUnion.\nStatement c is incorrect. Chapter III-F of the RBI Act provides for a statutory basis for the\nMonetary Policy Framework and the Monetary Policy Committee. The Central Government, in\nconsultation with the RBI shall determine the inflation target in terms of the Consumer Price\nIndex, once in every five years, which needs to be notified in the Official Gazette. Similarly, it is\nthe Central Government that should constitute Monetary Policy Committee by notification in\nthe Official Gazette.\nStatement d is correct. The powers and responsibilities with respect to external trades and\npayments, development and maintenance of foreign exchange market in India are conferred on\nthe RBI under the provisions of the Foreign Exchange Management Act, 1999 (‘FEMA’).","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","id":1,"area":"RBI Functions"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-01-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-01","qNum":2,"question":"With reference to the Reserve Bank of India (RBI), consider the following statements: 1. All Indian banks require a licence from the RBI for opening a new branch anywhere in India. 2. RBI manages the market borrowing programme of the state governments in India. 3. The interest rates on all categories of deposits and loans of banks are solely determined by the RBI. 4. The Central and the state Governments are required to maintain a minimum cash balance with the RBI. How many of the above given statements are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"Only three","d":"All four"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer\nRBI was established under RBI act in 1935 as a private bank. It was converted into central bank\nafter nationalisation in 1949.\nStatement 1 is incorrect: For commencing banking operations in India, whether by an Indian or a\nforeign bank, a licence from the Reserve Bank is required. The opening of new branches by banks\nand change in the location of existing branches are also regulated as per the Branch Authorisation\nPolicy. This policy has recently been liberalised significantly and Indian banks no longer require\na licence from the Reserve Bank for opening a branch at a place with population of below\n50,000.\nStatement 2 is correct: RBI acts as the banker for government. As the debt manager of the state\ngovernments, the mandate of the Reserve Bank is to manage the market borrowing programme\nof the state governments.\nStatement 3 is incorrect: The interest rates on most of the categories of deposits and lending\ntransactions have been deregulated and are largely determined by banks. However, the Reserve\nBank regulates the interest rates on savings bank accounts and deposits of non-resident Indians\n(NRI), small loans up to rupees two lakh, export credits and a few other categories of advances.\nStatement 4 is correct: All the State Governments are required to maintain a minimum cash\nbalance with the Reserve Bank, which varies from state to state depending on the relative size of\nthe state budget and economic activity. Under the administrative arrangements, the Central\nGovernment is required to maintain a minimum cash balance with the Reserve Bank.\nImportant Tips\nThe function of management of public debt is done by the Internal Debt Management\nDepartment (IDMof the Reserve Bank. IDMD of RBI manages the Market Borrowing\nProgramme (MBP). This involves issue and servicing aspects i.e., retirement of rupee loans,\ninterest payment on the loan and handling operational issues.","topic":"RBI Functions","id":2,"area":"RBI Functions"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-01-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-01","qNum":3,"question":"Consider the following statements: 1. Bonds issued by the Government are commonly called Gilt-Edged Bonds/ securities. 2. Bonds can be issued by governments as well as private companies. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct: G-Secs are also known as gilts or gilt-edged securities.\nStatement 2 is correct. Bonds could be issued by governments as well as private companies.\nImportant Tips\n“G-Sec” means a security created and issued by the Government for the purpose of raising a\npublic loan or for any other purpose as may be notified by the Government.","topic":"Bonds & Securities","id":3,"area":"RBI Functions"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-01-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-01","qNum":4,"question":"Which among the following is the correct description of the term, ‘Seigniorage’?","options":{"a":"The cost of metal incurred by a government when it issues new coins.","b":"The cost incurred by a government when it issues currency.","c":"The loss made by a government due to soiling and mutilation of the currency in circulation.","d":"The profit made by a government when it issues currency."},"answer":"d","explanation":"Option d is the correct answer.\nSeigniorage refers to the profit made by a government when it issues currency. It is simply the\ndifference in the value of the currency versus the cost of producing it. Seigniorage is a way for\ngovernments who mint their currency to make an economic profit. The cost of producing\ncurrency is generally lower than the face value of the currency itself. Monetary seigniorage can\nbe used as an effective monetary policy tool. It can result in debt monetization. Debt\nmonetization is when a central bank will buy interest-bearing debt with non-interest-bearing\nmoney. It can be a useful tool to control the debt level of an economy.","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","id":4,"area":"RBI Functions"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-01-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-01","qNum":5,"question":"It is the ratio of the stock of money to the stock of high-powered money in an economy. It refers to how an initial deposit can lead to a bigger final increase in the total money supply in the economy. The concept mentioned here is:","options":{"a":"Repo rate.","b":"Money Multiplier (MM)","c":"Cash Reserve Ratio (CRR)","d":"Capital Adequacy Ratio (CAR)"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nMoney Multiplier (MM) is the ratio of the stock of money to the stock of high-powered money in\nan economy. It refers to how an initial deposit can lead to a bigger final increase in the total\nmoney supply in the economy. The multiplier effect refers to the proportional amount of increase,\nor decrease, in final income that results from an injection, or withdrawal, of spending.","topic":"Basel Norms & Banking Regulation","id":5,"area":"RBI Functions"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-01-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-01","qNum":6,"question":"The Reserve Bank of India (RBI) acts as a bankers’ bank. This would imply which of the following? 1. Other bank retains their deposits with the RBI. 2. The RBI lends funds to the commercial banks in times of need. 3. The RBI advises the commercial banks on monetary matters. Select the correct answer using the codes given below:","options":{"a":"2 and 3 only","b":"1 and 2 only","c":"1 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Option d is the correct answer.\nAs Banker to Banks, the Reserve Bank focuses on:\n(i) Enabling smooth, swift and seamless clearing and settlement of inter-bank obligations.\n\n(ii) Providing an efficient means of funds transfer for banks.\n(iii) Enabling banks to maintain their accounts with the Reserve Bank for statutory reserve\nrequirements and maintenance of transaction balances.\n(iv) Acting as a lender of last resort.","topic":"RBI Functions","id":6,"area":"RBI Functions"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-01-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-01","qNum":7,"question":"Arrange the following in chronological order: 1. Nationalization of 14 major banks 2. Nationalization of SBI 3. Nationalization of RBI 4. Establishment of RBI Codes:","options":{"a":"3, 2, 4, 1","b":"2, 3, 4, 1","c":"3, 4, 2, 1","d":"4, 3, 2, 1"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\n• Nationalization of RBI: The Reserve Bank of India (RBI) was established in 1935 as a private bank\nunder the RBI Act, 1934. It was nationalized in 1949 under the RBI (Transfer of Public Ownership)\nAct, 1948.\n• Nationalization of SBI: The State Bank of India (SBI) was established in 1955 as a successor to\nthe Imperial Bank of India, which was a private bank formed in 1921 by merging three presidency\nbanks. The SBI was nationalized in 1955 under the SBI Act, 1955.\n• Nationalization of LIC: The Life Insurance Corporation of India (LIC) was established in 1956 as\na state-owned corporation under the LIC Act, 1956. The LIC was formed by nationalizing 245\nprivate life insurance companies and consolidating them into one entity\n• Nationalization of 14 major banks: The first phase of nationalization of banks took place in 1969\nunder the leadership of Prime Minister Indira Gandhi. Fourteen major private commercial banks\nwere nationalized under the Banking Companies (Acquisition and Transfer of Undertakings)\nOrdinance, 1969.","topic":"RBI Functions","id":7,"area":"RBI Functions"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-01-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-01","qNum":8,"question":"Which one of the following is not a function of Reserve Bank of India?","options":{"a":"Credit control","b":"As apex body of Scheduled Commercial Banks","c":"Formulation of monetary policy","d":"Credit creation"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Option d is the correct answer.\nCredit creation is not a function of Reserve Bank of India because credit creation is the process\nby which commercial banks create money by lending to their customers and generating deposits.\nThe Reserve Bank of India does not create credit directly, but it regulates the credit creation by\ncommercial banks through its monetary policy tools such as repo rate, reverse repo rate, cash\nreserve ratio, statutory liquidity ratio, etc. The Reserve Bank of India performs the functions of\n\ncredit control, apex body of scheduled commercial banks and formulation of monetary policy,\namong others.","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","id":8,"area":"RBI Functions"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-01-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-01","qNum":9,"question":"Which of the following statements is not correct regarding the Reserve Bank of India?","options":{"a":"It issues all types of currency notes.","b":"It functions as a branch bank of the Government of India.","c":"It is banker’s bank.","d":"It exchanges foreign currency."},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nReserve Bank has the sole right to issue banknotes in India. Section 25 of Reserve Bank of India\nAct states that the design, form and material of bank notes shall be such as may be approved by\nthe Central Government after consideration of the recommendations made by the Central Board\nof RBI. Indian government is solely responsible for minting coins. ₹1 notes are issued by the\nGovernment of India from time to time and such notes including those issued in the past also\ncontinue to be legal tender for transactions. The coins issued by Government of India under\nSection 6 of The Coinage Act, 2011.","topic":"RBI Functions","id":9,"area":"RBI Functions"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-01-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-01","qNum":10,"question":"Consider the following statements: 1. The Governor of the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) is appointed by the Central Government. 2. Certain Provisions in the Constitution of India give the Central Government the right to Issue directions to the RBI in public interest. 3. The Governor of the RBI draws his power from the RBI Act. Which of the above statements are correct?","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 and 3 only","c":"1 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct. Section 8(1)(a) of the Reserve Bank of India Act, 1934, provides that there\nshall be one Governor and not more than four Deputy Governors to be appointed by the central\ngovernment on the central board of RBI.\nStatement 2 is incorrect. Section 7 of the RBI Act provides that Central Government may from\ntime to time give such directions to the Bank as it may, after consultation with the Governor of\nthe Bank, consider necessary in the public interest. Constitution of India does not provide any\nprovision for Central Government the right to issue directions to the RBI in Public interest.\nStatement 3 is correct. According to RBI Act, the Governor shall have powers of general\nsuperintendence and direction of the affairs and the business of the RBI. He/she may exercise\nall powers and do all acts and things which may be exercised or done by the RBI.","topic":"RBI Functions","id":10,"area":"RBI Functions"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-01-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-01","qNum":11,"question":"In India ‘Currency Notes issue system’ is based on:","options":{"a":"Proportional reserve system","b":"Minimum reserve system","c":"Fixed exchange rate system","d":"Full convertibility system"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nThe current system of Indian government to issue notes is “Minimum Reserve System”. Under\nthis policy, the minimum reserves to be maintained in the form of gold and foreign exchange\nshould consist of rupees 200 crore. Out this reserve, the value of gold to be maintained is rupees\n115 crore. The minimum reserve system was adopted in 1956, replacing the proportional reserve\nsystem that was followed earlier.\nImportant Tips\n• In India, currency notes are issued by the Reserve Bank of India (RBI), which is the monetary\nauthority in India.\n• RBI Act 1934 empowers RBI to issue all the banknotes except 1 Rs. note. However, coins and 1\nRs. notes are issued by the Government of India under the coinage act 1909.","topic":"Money & Currency","id":11,"area":"RBI Functions"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-01-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-01","qNum":12,"question":"Which one of the following statements correctly describes the meaning of legal tender money?","options":{"a":"The money which is tendered in courts of law to defray the fee of legal cases","b":"The money which a creditor is under compulsion to accept in settlement of his claims","c":"The bank money in the form of cheques, drafts, bills of exchange etc.","d":"The metallic money in circulation in a Country"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer\n‘Legal tender’ is the money that is recognised by the law of the land, as valid for payment of debt.\nIt must be accepted for discharge of debt. The RBI Act of 1934, which gives the central bank the\nsole right to issue bank notes, states that “Every bank note shall be legal tender at any place in\nIndia in payment for the amount expressed therein”.","topic":"Money & Currency","id":12,"area":"RBI Functions"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-01-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-01","qNum":13,"question":"Consider the following statements: 1. Under the RBI Act, bank notes include both physical and digital forms. 2. RBI has the sole authority to issue bank notes in India. 3. Coins are issued under the RBI Act, 1934. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 only","c":"1 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nRBI Amendment Act, 2022 included digital notes; coins are issued under the Coinage Act, not RBI\nAct","topic":"RBI Functions","id":13,"area":"RBI Functions"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-01-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-01","qNum":14,"question":"With reference to the evolution of the Reserve Bank of India (RBI), consider the following statements: 1. The Hilton Young Committee recommended the establishment of the RBI as a statutory body. 2. The RBI was initially established as a private shareholders' bank in 1935. 3. The RBI was nationalized on January 1, 1949, under the Reserve Bank (Transfer to Public Ownership) Act, 1948. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct: The Hilton Young Committee (1924) recommended establishing the RBI as\na statutory body.\nStatement 2 is correct: RBI started as a private shareholders' bank on April 1, 1935.\nStatement 3 is correct: Nationalization occurred on Jan 1, 1949.","topic":"RBI Functions","id":14,"area":"RBI Functions"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-01-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-01","qNum":15,"question":"Consider the following statements regarding the capital and accounting of the RBI: 1. The initial capital of the RBI was Rs 5 crores, which continues to remain the same as of 2023. 2. Based on the Bimal Jalan Committee's recommendations, the RBI's accounting year was changed from July–June to April–March in 2021-22. 3. The definition of \"Bank Note\" was amended in 2022 to include digital notes. Which of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 and 3 only","c":"1 and 3 only","d":"1, 2, and 3"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Option d is the correct answer.\nAll statements are correct.","topic":"RBI Functions","id":15,"area":"RBI Functions"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-01-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-01","qNum":16,"question":"With reference to the RBI's role as a Debt Manager, consider the following statements: 1. The RBI manages and services Government of India Securities and State Government Securities. 2. Treasury Bills (T-Bills) are issued by both the Central and State Governments in India. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Statement 1 is correct: RBI manages securities for both Central and State governments.\nStatement 2 is incorrect: There are no treasury bills issued by the State Governments; they are\nonly issued by the Government of India.","topic":"Bonds & Securities","id":16,"area":"RBI Functions"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-01-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-01","qNum":17,"question":"In the context of India, the central bank’s function as the \"Lender of Last Resort\" refers to: 1. Lending to industry bodies when they fail to borrow from other sources. 2. Providing liquidity to banks facing a temporary crisis. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\n\"Lender of Last Resort\" specifically refers to providing liquidity to banks in crisis, not directly to\ntrade/industry bodies","topic":"RBI Functions","id":17,"area":"RBI Functions"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-01-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-01","qNum":18,"question":"The \"Service Area Approach\" was implemented under the purview of:","options":{"a":"Integrated Rural Development Programme","b":"Lead Bank Scheme","c":"MGNREGA","d":"National Skill Development Mission"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nService Area Approach is linked to the Lead Bank Scheme","topic":"Economy — Misc","id":18,"area":"RBI Functions"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-01-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-01","qNum":19,"question":"With reference to Legal Tender in India, consider the following statements: 1. All bank notes are unlimited legal tender. 2. Coins have limited legal tender status. 3. Acceptance of legal tender is mandatory for settlement of transactions. Which of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"2 and 3 only","b":"1 and 3 only","c":"1 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is incorrect: While bank notes are legal tender, the obligation to accept them is not\nabsolute in all situations; hence they are not considered unlimited legal tender in every transaction\ncontext.\nStatement 2 is correct: Coins have limited legal tender status, meaning they are legal tender only\nup to a prescribed amount.\nStatement 3 is correct: Legal tender must be accepted for the settlement of monetary\ntransactions, unless specifically exempted by law.","topic":"Money & Currency","id":19,"area":"RBI Functions"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-01-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-01","qNum":20,"question":"Consider the following statements about the Monetary Policy Committee (MPC): 1. It was established based on the recommendations of the Urjit Patel Committee. 2. The Governor of the RBI serves as the ex-officio Chairperson. 3. Decisions are made by a simple majority, where the Chairperson has a casting vote in case of a tie. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nAll statements are correct.","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","id":20,"area":"RBI Functions"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-01-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-01","qNum":21,"question":"With reference to the Payments Regulatory Board (PRB), consider the following statements: 1. It is established under the Payment and Settlement Systems Act, 2007. 2. It is headed by the Revenue Secretary of India. 3. It includes members nominated by the Central Government. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 and 3 only","c":"1 and 3 only","d":"1, 2, and 3"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct: PRB is under the PSS Act, 2007.\nStatement 2 is incorrect: The PRB is headed by the Governor of the RBI.\nStatement 3 is correct: It includes 3 members nominated by the government.","topic":"Economy — Misc","id":21,"area":"RBI Functions"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-01-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-01","qNum":22,"question":"With reference to Central Bank Digital Currencies (CBDC), consider the following statements: 1. It is possible to make payments in digital currency without using the SWIFT system. 2. A digital currency can be programmed with a specific time frame for spending. 3. The digital rupee appears as a liability on the RBI's balance sheet. Which of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 and 3 only","c":"1 and 3 only","d":"1, 2, and 3"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Option d is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct: CBDCs can facilitate cross-border payments through direct central bank–\nto–central bank settlement mechanisms, thereby reducing dependence on the SWIFT system.=\nStatement 2 is correct: CBDCs are programmable money, allowing restrictions based on time,\npurpose, or conditions of use.\nStatement 3 is correct: CBDCs are issued by the central bank and constitute a sovereign liability,\nsimilar to physical currency.","topic":"Money & Currency","id":22,"area":"RBI Functions"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-01-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-01","qNum":23,"question":"Regarding the \"Unclaimed Deposits\" framework, consider the following statements: 1. Deposits are classified as unclaimed if they are not claimed for 10 years. 2. These deposits are transferred to the Deposit Education and Awareness (DEA) Fund maintained by the Ministry of Finance. 3. The UDGAM portal allows depositors to track these unclaimed deposits. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"1 and 3 only","c":"2 and 3 only","d":"1, 2, and 3"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nStatement 2 is incorrect: The DEA Fund is maintained with the RBI, not the Ministry of Finance.","topic":"Economy — Misc","id":23,"area":"RBI Functions"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-01-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-01","qNum":24,"question":"The Banking Laws Amendment Act, 2025, introduced which of the following changes? 1. Increase in the maximum number of nominees for a bank account from one to four. 2. Increase in the maximum tenure of Board of Directors for Cooperative Banks from 8 to 10 years. 3. Redefinition of \"Fortnight\" for CRR calculation from \"Saturday to Friday\" to \"1st–15th and 16th– last day of the month\". Select the correct answer:","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 and 3 only","c":"1 and 3 only","d":"1, 2, and 3"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Option d is the correct answer.\nAll three are key provisions of the 2025 Amendment Act.","topic":"Types of Banks","id":24,"area":"RBI Functions"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-01-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-01","qNum":25,"question":"With reference to Treasury Bills (T-Bills) in India, consider the following statements: 1. T-Bills are issued at a discount from the par value. 2. They are sold in India by the Reserve Bank of India on behalf of the government. 3. Retail investors can invest in T-Bills through a Demat account in the primary market. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nT-Bills are zero-coupon (discounted), sold by RBI, and accessible to retail investors via platforms\nlike Retail Direct.","topic":"Bonds & Securities","id":25,"area":"RBI Functions"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-01-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-01","qNum":26,"question":"The \"Negotiated Dealing System-Order Matching (NDS-OM)\" is:","options":{"a":"A platform for trading corporate bonds.","b":"A government securities trading platform of the RBI.","c":"A portal for filing complaints against banks.","d":"A system for international remittance."},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nNDS-OM is an RBI platform for G-Secs trading.","topic":"Bonds & Securities","id":26,"area":"RBI Functions"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-01-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-01","qNum":27,"question":"Consider the following statements regarding the Board for Financial Supervision (BFS): 1. It functions as a committee of the Central Board of the RBI. 2. It carries out integrated supervision of banks and NBFCs. 3. It is chaired by the Finance Minister of India. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 only","c":"1 and 3 only","d":"1, 2, and 3"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 & 2 are correct: BFS is a committee for supervising banks/NBFCs.\nStatement 3 is incorrect: It is chaired by the Governor of the RBI.","topic":"Types of Banks","id":27,"area":"RBI Functions"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-01-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-01","qNum":28,"question":"What is the primary objective of the \"Antardrishti\" portal?","options":{"a":"Financial inclusion dashboard.","b":"Tracking of unclaimed deposits.","c":"Monitoring of foreign direct investment.","d":"Redressal of consumer grievances."},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nAntardrishti is a financial inclusion dashboard launched by the Reserve Bank of India (RBI). The\nname translates to \"insight\" or \"inner vision\", reflecting its purpose of providing data-driven\ninsights into the progress and extent of financial inclusion across India.","topic":"RBI Functions","id":28,"area":"RBI Functions"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-01-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-01","qNum":29,"question":"Consider the following statements about Urban Cooperative Banks (UCBs): 1. The Banking Regulation (Amendment) Act, 2020, brought UCBs under the increased supervision of the RBI. 2. UCBs are exempt from maintaining CRR and SLR. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nThe 2020 amendment did increase RBI oversight. UCBs are not exempt from CRR/SLR\nrequirements.","topic":"Types of Banks","id":29,"area":"RBI Functions"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-01-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-01","qNum":30,"question":"Consider the following statements: 1. Seigniorage arises from difference between face value and cost of printing. 2. RBI earns seigniorage from coin minting. 3. Interest earned on forex reserves is a source of RBI income. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 and 3 only","b":"1 only","c":"2 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nCoin seigniorage goes to the Government.","topic":"RBI Functions","id":30,"area":"RBI Functions"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-02-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-02","qNum":1,"question":"With reference to the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) acting as a Banker to the Government, consider the following statements: 1. RBI has a legal obligation to act as the banker to both Central and all State Governments. 2. The Central Government is required to maintain a minimum cash balance with the RBI. 3. RBI directly accepts deposits and makes payments on behalf of the Government without involving any commercial banks. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 only","c":"2 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is incorrect: RBI has an obligation and right to act as Banker to the Central\nGovernment, but for State Governments, it acts based on an agreement. Currently, it acts as a\nbanker to all states except Sikkim.\nStatement 2 is correct: Both Central and State Governments need to maintain minimum cash\nbalances with the RBI.\nStatement 3 is incorrect: RBI does not directly accept deposits or make payments; it appoints\n\"agency banks\" (Public and Private Sector Banks) to carry out these functions.","topic":"RBI Functions","id":31,"area":"RBI as Banker & G-Secs"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-02-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-02","qNum":2,"question":"Which of the following states is the only one for which the RBI does NOT act as a banker?","options":{"a":"Nagaland","b":"Sikkim","c":"Goa","d":"Arunachal Pradesh"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nPresently, the RBI acts as a banker to all states in India, except for the state of Sikkim.","topic":"RBI Functions","id":32,"area":"RBI as Banker & G-Secs"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-02-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-02","qNum":3,"question":"With reference to \"Ways and Means Advances (WMA)\", consider the following statements: 1. It is a loan facility provided by the RBI to the Centre and States to address temporary mismatches in cash balances. 2. The interest rate charged on WMA is fixed at 2% above the Repo Rate. 3. These advances must be repaid within a maximum period of 90 days. Which of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 and 3 only","c":"1 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct: WMA is a loan facility to address temporary mismatches in cash balances.\n\nStatement 2 is incorrect: The interest rate on WMA is the Repo Rate. If the borrowing exceeds\nthe WMA limit (Overdraft), the rate is 2% above the Repo Rate.\nStatement 3 is correct: The maturity period for WMA is 90 days.","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","id":33,"area":"RBI as Banker & G-Secs"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-02-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-02","qNum":4,"question":"The \"Special Drawing Facility (SDF)\" is a borrowing mechanism available to:","options":{"a":"Commercial banks to borrow from RBI against SLR securities.","b":"State Governments to borrow from RBI by pledging Central Government Securities.","c":"Retail investors to borrow against their G-Sec holdings.","d":"NBFCs to meet their liquidity requirements."},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nThe Special Drawing Facility (SDF) enables State Governments to borrow short-term loans from\nthe RBI by pledging Central Government Securities as collateral. The interest rate on SDF is 1%\nbelow the Repo Rate.","topic":"Bonds & Securities","id":34,"area":"RBI as Banker & G-Secs"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-02-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-02","qNum":5,"question":"With reference to Cash Management Bills (CMBs), which of the following statements is correct?","options":{"a":"They are long-term instruments issued by both Centre and States.","b":"They are issued for a maturity period of less than 91 days.","c":"They carry a fixed coupon rate paid semi-annually.","d":"They are primarily used to finance the fiscal deficit."},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nCMBs are short-term instruments issued by the Central Government (not states) for a maturity\nperiod of less than 91 days. They are issued at a discount and redeemed at face value to address\ntemporary cash mismatches.","topic":"Bonds & Securities","id":35,"area":"RBI as Banker & G-Secs"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-02-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-02","qNum":6,"question":"Consider the following statements regarding Government Securities (G-Secs) in India: 1. Treasury Bills (T-Bills) are issued by both the Central Government and State Governments. 2. T-Bills are issued at a discount to the face value and redeemed at par. 3. State Development Loans (SDLs) are long-term borrowing instruments issued by State Governments. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 and 3 only","c":"1 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is incorrect: T-Bills are issued only by the Central Government.\nStatement 2 is correct: T-Bills do not pay interest (coupon) but are issued at a discount and\nredeemed at face value.\n\nStatement 3 is correct: SDLs are long-term (more than 1 year) securities issued by State\nGovernments, similar to dated securities of the Centre.","topic":"Bonds & Securities","id":36,"area":"RBI as Banker & G-Secs"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-02-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-02","qNum":7,"question":"Which among the following is NOT an advantage of investing in Government Securities (G- Secs)?","options":{"a":"They are virtually risk-free (Sovereign guarantee).","b":"They offer protection against inflation through Inflation-Indexed Bonds.","c":"Interest income earned from G-Secs is completely tax-exempt.","d":"They can be held in Demat form."},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nInterest income earned from G-Secs is generally taxable. They are risk-free (no default risk) and\ncan be held in Demat or physical form.","topic":"Inflation & Deflation","id":37,"area":"RBI as Banker & G-Secs"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-02-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-02","qNum":8,"question":"With reference to the \"Government Securities Act, 2006\", consider the following statements: 1. The Act applies to securities issued by both the Central and State Governments. 2. National Savings Certificates (NSC) and Postal Savings Certificates are included under this Act. 3. The RBI is the primary issuer of G-Secs on behalf of the government under this framework. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 and 3 only","b":"3 only","c":"1 and 2 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct: The Act applies to G-Secs issued by both Centre and States.\nStatement 2 is incorrect: National Savings Certificates and Postal Savings Certificates are\nexplicitly excluded from the Act.\nStatement 3 is correct: RBI is the issuer for T-Bills, Dated Bonds, and SDLs.","topic":"Bonds & Securities","id":38,"area":"RBI as Banker & G-Secs"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-02-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-02","qNum":9,"question":"Which of the following risks is generally NOT associated with investing in G-Secs?","options":{"a":"Market Risk","b":"Reinvestment Risk","c":"Default Risk","d":"Liquidity Risk"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nG-Secs carry practically zero default risk because they are backed by a sovereign guarantee.\nHowever, they are subject to market risk (price fluctuations), reinvestment risk, and liquidity risk.","topic":"Bonds & Securities","id":39,"area":"RBI as Banker & G-Secs"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-02-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-02","qNum":10,"question":"In the context of \"STRIPS\" in the G-Sec market, what does the term \"Stripping\" refer to?","options":{"a":"Selling G-Secs in the secondary market at a massive discount.","b":"Separating the cash flows of a regular G-Sec into independent individual securities of interest and principal.","c":"The process of converting physical G-Secs into Demat form.","d":"Reducing the maturity period of a bond to manage interest rate risk."},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nSTRIPS (Separate Trading of Registered Interest and Principal of Securities) involves separating\nthe periodic interest (coupon) payments and the final principal repayment of a bond into separate\nzero-coupon securities.","topic":"Bonds & Securities","id":40,"area":"RBI as Banker & G-Secs"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-02-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-02","qNum":11,"question":"With reference to Inflation-Indexed Bonds (IIBs), consider the following statements: 1. They provide protection to investors from uncertainty regarding inflation for both principal and interest. 2. The interest on IIBs is calculated on the inflation-adjusted principal. 3. Capital gains on IIBs are exempt from taxation in India. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 only","c":"1 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 and 2 are correct: IIBs protect both principal and interest against inflation, with\ninterest calculated on the adjusted principal.\nStatement 3 is incorrect: Income and capital gains from IIBs are taxable, just like normal bonds.","topic":"Inflation & Deflation","id":41,"area":"RBI as Banker & G-Secs"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-02-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-02","qNum":12,"question":"How do Capital Indexed Bonds differ from Inflation-Indexed Bonds (IIBs)?","options":{"a":"Only principal is protected against inflation in Capital Indexed Bonds.","b":"Only interest is protected against inflation in Capital Indexed Bonds.","c":"Interest is paid on a fixed principal in IIBs.","d":"Capital Indexed Bonds were first issued in 2013."},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nIn Capital Indexed Bonds, only the principal amount is protected against inflation, whereas in IIBs,\nboth principal and interest payments are protected.","topic":"Inflation & Deflation","id":42,"area":"RBI as Banker & G-Secs"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-02-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-02","qNum":13,"question":"With reference to \"Sovereign Green Bonds\", consider the following statements: 1. The proceeds are deposited in the Consolidated Fund of India (CFI). 2. They are eligible to be considered as SLR (Statutory Liquidity Ratio) securities. 3. Non-Resident investors are not allowed to invest in these bonds. Which of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 and 3 only","c":"1 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\n\nStatement 1 is correct: Proceeds go to the CFI.\nStatement 2 is correct: They are eligible for SLR.\nStatement 3 is incorrect: Non-Residents (under the Fully Accessible Route) are allowed to invest\nin Sovereign Green Bonds without any limit.","topic":"Bonds & Securities","id":43,"area":"RBI as Banker & G-Secs"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-02-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-02","qNum":14,"question":"The term \"Greenium\" in the context of Green Bonds refers to:","options":{"a":"The extra tax incentive provided by the government to green project investors.","b":"The savings (lower yield) realized by the issuer due to higher demand for green bonds.","c":"The premium paid by the government to banks for financing green energy.","d":"The penalty imposed on companies for not meeting green investment targets."},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nGreenium (Green + Premium) refers to the lower yield (or higher price) that investors are willing\nto accept for green bonds compared to normal bonds due to high demand, resulting in lower\nborrowing costs for the issuer.","topic":"Bonds & Securities","id":44,"area":"RBI as Banker & G-Secs"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-02-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-02","qNum":15,"question":"Which of the following projects is excluded from financing through Sovereign Green Bonds?","options":{"a":"Electrification of public transportation.","b":"Water-efficient irrigation systems.","c":"Nuclear power generation.","d":"Renewable energy research and development."},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nExcluded projects include nuclear power, direct waste incineration, landfill projects, large\nhydropower (>25 MW), and fossil fuel-based projects","topic":"Bonds & Securities","id":45,"area":"RBI as Banker & G-Secs"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-02-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-02","qNum":16,"question":"With reference to the \"Retail Direct Scheme\" of the RBI, consider the following statements: 1. It allows individual retail investors to buy G-Secs directly from the RBI in the primary market. 2. Only Resident Indians are eligible to open a Retail Direct Gilt Account. 3. Investors can trade G-Secs in the secondary market through this platform. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"1 and 3 only","c":"2 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 and 3 are correct: Retail investors can buy directly in the primary market and trade\nin the secondary market.\nStatement 2 is incorrect: Both Resident and Non-Resident individuals can open these accounts.","topic":"Bonds & Securities","id":46,"area":"RBI as Banker & G-Secs"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-02-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-02","qNum":17,"question":"The \"E-Kuber\" platform of the RBI is primarily used for:","options":{"a":"Providing a grievance redressal mechanism for bank customers.","b":"Core Banking Solution (CBS) operations including G-Sec auctions and maintaining CRR balances.","c":"Trading of corporate stocks and derivatives.","d":"Monitoring international remittance flows."},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nE-Kuber is the Core Banking Solution of RBI used for G-Sec auctions, maintaining CRR balances,\ninter-bank settlements, and providing WMA to the government.","topic":"Bonds & Securities","id":47,"area":"RBI as Banker & G-Secs"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-02-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-02","qNum":18,"question":"Consider the following statements regarding the \"Negotiated Dealing System-Order Matching (NDS-OM)\": 1. It is a government securities trading platform owned by the RBI. 2. It is primarily used for trading G-Secs in the secondary market. 3. It is operated by the Securities and Exchange Board of India (SEBI). Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 only","c":"2 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nNDS-OM is owned by the RBI and used for secondary market trading of G-Secs. However, it is\noperated by the Clearing Corporation of India Limited (CCIL), not SEBI.","topic":"Bonds & Securities","id":48,"area":"RBI as Banker & G-Secs"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-02-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-02","qNum":19,"question":"Which of the following is correct regarding the E-Kuber platform?","options":{"a":"All retail investors can now participate in T-Bill auctions directly on E-Kuber.","b":"All government payments above Rs 75 crores must be made through E-Kuber.","c":"Foreign Central Banks can now trade Indian SDLs on E-Kuber.","d":"E-Kuber has been integrated with the SWIFT system for international trade."},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nAs of July 2025, all payments made by Government ministries and departments above Rs 75 crores\nmust be made through the E-Kuber platform.","topic":"Bonds & Securities","id":49,"area":"RBI as Banker & G-Secs"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-02-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-02","qNum":20,"question":"With reference to the RBI's regulatory powers over Public Sector Banks (PSBs) versus Private Banks, consider the following statements: 1. RBI has the power to supersede the Board of Directors of both PSBs and Private Banks. 2. Provisions of the Banking Regulation Act, 1949 apply differently to PSBs compared to Private Banks. 3. RBI can force the merger of Private Banks but cannot do so for PSBs. Which of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 and 3 only","c":"1 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is incorrect: RBI can supersede the Board of Private Banks but has limited powers to\ndo so for PSBs.\nStatement 2 and 3 are correct: RBI's powers over PSBs are limited as they are also regulated by\nthe government and governed by Nationalization Acts. RBI cannot force mergers of PSBs but can\ndo so for Private Banks.","topic":"RBI Functions","id":50,"area":"RBI as Banker & G-Secs"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-02-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-02","qNum":21,"question":"Which of the following entities is NOT regulated by the RBI?","options":{"a":"All India Financial Institutions (AIFIs)","b":"Asset Reconstruction Companies (ARCs)","c":"Credit Rating Agencies (CRAs)","d":"Credit Information Companies (CICs)"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer\nCredit Rating Agencies (like ICRA, CRISIL) are regulated by SEBI, not RBI. AIFIs, ARCs, and CICs\nare regulated by the RBI.","topic":"Types of Banks","id":51,"area":"RBI as Banker & G-Secs"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-02-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-02","qNum":22,"question":"Consider the following statements regarding Credit Information Companies (CICs) in India: 1. CICs are regulated by the RBI under the CICRA Act, 2005. 2. All banks and NBFCs must become members of all existing CICs. 3. TransUnion CIBIL is a government-owned Credit Information Company. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"1 and 2 only","c":"2 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 and 2 are correct: CICs are regulated under CICRA 2005, and credit providers must\nbe members of all CICs.\nStatement 3 is incorrect: TransUnion CIBIL is owned by an American MNC, TransUnion; it is not\ngovernment-owned.","topic":"Types of Banks","id":52,"area":"RBI as Banker & G-Secs"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-02-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-02","qNum":23,"question":"Under the \"National Financial Information Registry (NFIR)\" proposal, how does it differ from existing CICs?","options":{"a":"NFIR will only collect data on agricultural loans, while CICs collect all data.","b":"NFIR will be owned by the RBI and collect comprehensive financial info (loans, tax, bonds), unlike CICs which focus on loans.","c":"CICs provide data for free, while NFIR will charge a high fee.","d":"NFIR will only cater to international investors."},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nThe proposed NFIR would be owned by the RBI and collect a wider range of financial information\n(loans, tax payments, bonds) compared to CICs which primarily collect loan information.","topic":"Bonds & Securities","id":53,"area":"RBI as Banker & G-Secs"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-02-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-02","qNum":24,"question":"What is the \"Grameen Credit Score\" mentioned in the Budget 2025-26?","options":{"a":"A score for large corporate farmers based on export data.","b":"A credit scoring mechanism for SHG members and rural people based on land ownership, UPI activity, and utility bills.","c":"A ranking system for Rural Cooperative Banks.","d":"A government subsidy for farmers with low credit scores."},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nThe Grameen Credit Score is to be developed by PSBs to assess the creditworthiness of SHG\nmembers and rural residents using unconventional parameters like saving patterns in SHGs and\nutility bill payments.","topic":"Types of Banks","id":54,"area":"RBI as Banker & G-Secs"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-02-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-02","qNum":25,"question":"With reference to the Deposit Insurance and Credit Guarantee Corporation (DICGC), consider the following statements: 1. It covers deposits in all commercial, regional, rural, and cooperative banks. 2. NBFCs and Rural Cooperative Societies are also covered under this insurance. 3. The insurance limit is Rs 5 lakh per depositor per bank. Which of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 and 3 only","c":"1 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 and 3 are correct: Coverage includes commercial and cooperative banks, with a limit\nof Rs 5 lakh.\nStatement 2 is incorrect: NBFCs and Rural Cooperative Societies are NOT covered.","topic":"Basel Norms & Banking Regulation","id":55,"area":"RBI as Banker & G-Secs"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-02-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-02","qNum":26,"question":"The \"UDGAM\" portal launched by the RBI is intended for:","options":{"a":"Facilitating applications for new bank licenses.","b":"A centralized search for unclaimed deposits across multiple banks.","c":"Real-time monitoring of the call money market.","d":"Registering complaints against digital payment providers."},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nUDGAM (Unclaimed Deposits-Gateway to Access information) facilitates users in searching for\nunclaimed deposits/accounts across multiple banks in one place.","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","id":56,"area":"RBI as Banker & G-Secs"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-02-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-02","qNum":27,"question":"The \"PRAVAAAH\" portal is designed to:","options":{"a":"Track the flow of FDI into the manufacturing sector.","b":"Simplify and streamline application processes for various regulatory approvals.","c":"Monitor the liquidity coverage ratio of systemically important banks.","d":"Facilitate the auction of Sovereign Green Bonds."},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nPRAVAAAH is a web-based centralized portal to simplify and streamline application processes.","topic":"Bonds & Securities","id":57,"area":"RBI as Banker & G-Secs"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-02-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-02","qNum":28,"question":"The \"Housing Price Index (HPI)\" published by the RBI has which of the following as its base year?","options":{"a":"2004-05","b":"2010-11","c":"2015-16","d":"2020-21"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nThe Housing Price Index (HPI) measures price changes in 10 cities and has a base year of 2010-11.","topic":"RBI Functions","id":58,"area":"RBI as Banker & G-Secs"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-02-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-02","qNum":29,"question":"Which index measures changes in the prices charged by banks for their services?","options":{"a":"Services Inflation Index","b":"Banking Services Price Index","c":"Financial Service Cost Index","d":"Bank Transaction Index"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nThe Banking Services Price Index measures changes in the prices charged by banks for their\nservices, with 2011-12 as the base year.","topic":"Inflation & Deflation","id":59,"area":"RBI as Banker & G-Secs"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-02-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-02","qNum":30,"question":"Consider the following variables: 1. Economic situation 2. Employment 3. Price level 4. Income 5. Spending The \"RBI Consumer Confidence Survey\" measures expectations on how many of the above variables?","options":{"a":"Only three","b":"Only four","c":"All five","d":"Only two"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nThe survey measures consumer confidence and expectations on all five economic variables:\neconomic situation, employment, price level, income, and spending.","topic":"RBI Functions","id":60,"area":"RBI as Banker & G-Secs"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-03-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-03","qNum":1,"question":"Which of the following measures can be taken by the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) to increase liquidity in the economy?","options":{"a":"Selling through Open Market Operations (OMO)","b":"Targeted Long Term Repo Operations","c":"Increase in Cash Reserve Ratio","d":"Decreasing borrowing limit under Marginal Standing Facility"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nTargeted Long Term Repo Operations (TLTROs) facility allows banks to borrow money from the\nRBI at the repo rate for one and three years. This improves capacity of banks to extend cheaper\ncredit to businesses.","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","id":61,"area":"Monetary Policy Tools"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-03-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-03","qNum":2,"question":"Consider the following statements with regard to the monetary policy tools and their impact: 1. Monetary policy tool includes direct lending to banks. 2. Open market operations (OMO) refer to the government directly buying or selling short-term treasuries and other securities in the open market. 3. Reducing CRR and SLR requirements for banks may lead to a decline in the interest rates. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct. Monetary Policy tools include open market operations, direct lending to\nbanks, bank reserve requirements, unconventional emergency lending programs, and managing\nmarket expectations—subject to the central bank’s credibility.\nStatement 2 is incorrect. Open market operations (OMO) refer to a central bank and not the\ngovernment buying or selling short-term treasuries and other securities in the open market.\nStatement 3 is correct. Lowering reserve requirements (CRR and SLR) releases more capital for\nthe banks to offer loans or to buy other assets and hence the interest rate declines.","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","id":62,"area":"Monetary Policy Tools"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-03-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-03","qNum":3,"question":"With reference to Market Stabilization scheme, consider the following statements: 1. It is a monetary policy intervention by the RBI. 2. It infuses excess liquidity in market by buying government securities. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\n\nStatement 1 is correct. Market Stabilization scheme (MSS) is a monetary policy intervention by\nthe RBI. These securities are owned by the government though they are issued by the RBI.\nStatement 2 is incorrect. It withdraws excess liquidity (or money supply) by selling government\nsecurities in the economy. The MSS was introduced in April 2004.","topic":"Bonds & Securities","id":63,"area":"Monetary Policy Tools"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-03-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-03","qNum":4,"question":"Which of the following instruments of Monetary Policy Transmission are available with the Reserve Bank of India? 1. Open Market Operations 2. Varying of Cash Reserve Ratio and Statutory Liquidity Ratio 3. Sterilization by buying and selling of foreign currency in the exchange market. 4. Moral suasion Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1, 2 and 4 only","b":"2, 3 and 4 only","c":"3 and 4 only","d":"1, 2, 3 and 4"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nPoint 1 is correct. Open Market Operations (OMO) RBI purchases (or sells) government securities\nto the general public in a bid to increase (or decrease) the stock of high-powered money in the\neconomy.\nPoint 2 is correct. A high (or low) value of CRR or SLR increases (or decreases) the value of reserve\ndeposit ratio, thus diminishing (or increasing) the value of money multiplier and money supply in\nthe economy in a similar fashion.\nPoint 4 is correct. Moral Suasion can be undertaken by RBI to persuade commercial banks to\nfollow the monetary policy directives given by the Monetary Policy Committee.\nPoint 3 is incorrect. Sterilization is one of the important functions of RBI where it sterilizes the\neconomy against adverse external shocks. However, it is not an instrument of monetary policy\ntransmission.","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","id":64,"area":"Monetary Policy Tools"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-03-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-03","qNum":5,"question":"With reference to Monetary Policy Committee (MPC), consider the following statements: 1. The committee is constituted by the Reserve Bank of India. 2. The MPC determines the policy interest rate required to achieve the inflation target. 3. The decisions of the committee are based on consensus. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is incorrect: The MPC is a six-member committee constituted by the Central\ngovernment by notification in the official gazette.\n\nStatement 2 is correct. The MPC determines the policy interest rate required to achieve the\ninflation target.\nStatement 3 is incorrect: Each member of the MPC has one vote and in case of equality of votes,\nthe Governor has a second or casting vote. Thus, the decisions are not based on the consensus.","topic":"Inflation & Deflation","id":65,"area":"Monetary Policy Tools"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-03-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-03","qNum":6,"question":"Consider the following statements regarding the Marginal Standing Facility (MSF) of RBI: 1. It is used by all financial institutions. 2. It is a part of the liquidity adjustment facility. 3. It is a cheaper route to fulfil the overnight requirement of funds. 4. Banks use this route only if they exhaust all other channels to raise short-term funds. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"Only three","d":"All four"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is incorrect. Marginal Standing Facility is only for banks (not for other financial\ninstitutions).\nStatement 2 is incorrect. Though it is on the lines of the Liquidity Adjustment Facility (LAF) but it\nis not a part of it. RBI’s LAF which helps banks to adjust their daily liquidity mismatches.\nStatement 3 is incorrect. MSF is a penal rate and thus not a cheap way and remains higher than\nthe repo rate. It is generally at a rate of 1 percent higher than the current repo rate, but it is not\nfixed and can be changed.\nStatement 4 is correct. Banks use this facility only if they exhaust all other means to raise short\nterm funds.","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","id":66,"area":"Monetary Policy Tools"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-03-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-03","qNum":7,"question":"With reference to Liquidity Adjustment Facility (LAF), which of the following statements is/are Correct? 1. LAF was introduced on the recommendations of the Narsimham Committee on Banking Sector Reforms. 2. Through LAF, RBI manages the inflation in the economy. 3. LAF in recent years, has been extended to certain Scheduled Urban Cooperative Banks (UCBs). Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1 Only","b":"1 and 2 Only","c":"1 and 3 Only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Option d is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct. The LAF was introduced in RBI in 1998 based on the recommendations of\nNarasimham Committee on Banking Sector Reforms.\nStatement 2 is correct. Through LAF tools like Repo, the RBI manages the inflation in the range\nbetween 2 and 6%.\n\nStatement 3 is correct. From 2014, Liquidity Adjustment Facility (LAF) was extended to Scheduled\nUrban Cooperative Banks (UCBs) which are Core Banking System (CBS) enabled.","topic":"Inflation & Deflation","id":67,"area":"Monetary Policy Tools"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-03-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-03","qNum":8,"question":"Which of the following are the components of Statutory Liquidity Ratio (SLR)? 1. Cash 2. Gold 3. Treasury Bills 4. Dated securities issued under market stabilisation schemes 5. State development loans Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"2, 3 and 4 only","b":"3 and 4 only","c":"1, 2 and 5 only","d":"1, 2, 3, 4 and 5"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Option d is the correct answer.\nStatutory Liquidity Ratio or SLR is a minimum percentage of deposits that a commercial bank has\nto maintain in the form of liquid cash, gold or other securities. It is basically the reserve\nrequirement that banks are expected to keep before offering credit to customers. Following are\nthe components of SLR: Cash Gold and unencumbered securities. Treasury bills of the\nGovernment of India. Dated securities issued under market borrowing programme and market\nstabilisation schemes (MSS). State Development Loans (SDLs) of the State Governments issued\nfrom time to time under the market borrowing program; and any other instrument as may be\nnotified by the Reserve Bank of India.","topic":"Bonds & Securities","id":68,"area":"Monetary Policy Tools"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-03-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-03","qNum":9,"question":"Which of the following entities can take loans through both Marginal Standing Facility (MSF) and Liquidity Adjustment Facility (LAF) of the RBI? 1. Schedules commercial banks. 2. Regional rural banks. 3. Non-Banking Financial Company. Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 and 3 only","c":"1, 2 and 3","d":"1 only"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nOption 1 is correct. All Scheduled Commercial Banks (including Regional Rural Banks) and\nPrimary Dealers (PDs) are eligible to participate in the Repo and Reverse Repo auctions i.e.\nLiquidity Adjustment Facility of RBI. The banks under Marginal standing facility can borrow funds\nby pledging government securities within the limits of the statutory liquidity ratio. Scheduled\ncommercial banks and Regional rural banks (RRBs) can borrow under this window.\nOption 2 is correct. RBI recently allowed regional rural banks (RRBs) to access funds under\nliquidity adjustment facility (LAF), marginal standing facility (MSF) and call or notice money\n\nmarket, aimed at facilitating better liquidity management for these lenders. Earlier RRBs were not\npermitted to access the liquidity windows of the RBI as well as the call or notice market.\nOption 3 is incorrect. Unlike banks, NBFCs cannot borrow directly from the RBI’s Liquidity\nAdjustment Facility and Marginal Standing Facility.","topic":"Types of Banks","id":69,"area":"Monetary Policy Tools"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-03-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-03","qNum":10,"question":"To control inflation in an economy, which of the following steps can be taken by the Reserve Bank of India (RBI)?","options":{"a":"Purchase government securities under Open Market Operations","b":"Increase Currency Reserve Ratio","c":"Decrease Statutory Liquidity Ratio (SLR)","d":"Reduce the prevailing Repo rate"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nOption b is correct. Cash/Currency Reserve Ratio (CRR) is the amount of funds that banks have\nto keep with RBI. The RBI uses CRR to drain out excessive money from system. If CRR is increased\nmore cash of banks have to be kept as reserve with RBI, hence limiting cash in circulation thereby\ncontrolling Inflation.\nOption a is incorrect. Open market operations, or OMOs, are the purchase and sale of G-Secs by\nthe RBI on the Centre’s behalf to streamline money supply and interest rates. In case of excess\nliquidity in the market, RBI issues these securities via auctions. Open market purchases increase\nmoney supply and results in excess cash in circulation, thus promoting Inflation. To control\ninflation, the RBI sells the securities in the money market which sucks out excess liquidity from\nthe market. As the amount of liquid cash decreases, demand goes down.\nOption c is incorrect. Statutory Liquidity Ratio (SLR) is the amount that banks have to maintain\nas a stipulated proportion of their net demand and time liabilities (NDTL) in form of liquid\nassets like cash, gold and unencumbered securities, treasury bills, dated securities etc. Decrease\nin SLR leads to increasing cash in circulation thereby promoting Inflation.\nOption d is incorrect. The term ‹Repo› refers to repurchase option or agreement. It is a monetary\ntool used by the RBI to allow commercial banks to borrow money, when in need, against collaterals\nsuch as government bonds and treasury bills. If Repo rate in decreased, Banks will find borrow\nmoney from RBI becomes easier. Hence more cash in hand, more in circulation thus promoting\nInflation.","topic":"Inflation & Deflation","id":70,"area":"Monetary Policy Tools"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-03-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-03","qNum":11,"question":"Consider the following statements with reference to RBI’s ‘Margin Requirements’ on loans: 1. It is one of the Quantitative methods of credit control. 2. It refers to the difference between average loan interest rate and the average deposit interest rate of banks. 3. In case of inflation, the margin requirement is increased so that demand for loans is decreased. 4. The margin requirements against specific securities are determined solely by individual bank. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"Only three","d":"All four"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is incorrect. Margin requirement is one of the Qualitative or selective methods of\ncredit control used by RBI to stabilize the economy from inflation or deflation.\nStatement 2 is incorrect. Margin requirement refers to the difference between the current\nvalue of the security offered for loan (called collateral) and the value of loan granted. Margin\nagainst a particular security is reduced or increased in order to encourage or to discourage the\nflow of credit to a particular sector. It varies from 20% to 80%. Higher the margin lesser will be\nthe loan sanctioned.\nStatement 4 is incorrect: The margin requirements against specific securities are determined by\nthe Central Bank. Changes in margin requirements are designed to influence the flow of credit\nagainst specific commodities. A rise in the margin requirement results in a contraction in the\nborrowing value of the security and similarly, a fall in the margin requirement results in expansion\nin the borrowing value of the security.\nStatement 3 is correct. In case of inflation, the margin requirement is increased so that demand\nfor loans are decreased. In case of deflation, margin requirements are decreased so that demand\nfor loans are increased.\nImportant Tips\nMargin means that proportion of the value of security against which loan is not given. A loan\nis sanctioned against Collateral Security. For example- a person mortgages his house worth one\ncrore rupees with the bank for a loan of 80 lakh rupees. The margin requirement in this case\nwill be 20 lakh rupees. The commercial banks generally advance loans to their customers\nagainst some security or securities offered by the borrower and acceptable to banks. More\ngenerally, the commercial banks do not lend up to the full amount of the security but lend an\namount less than its value.","topic":"Inflation & Deflation","id":71,"area":"Monetary Policy Tools"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-03-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-03","qNum":12,"question":"Which of the following is/are the objective and impacts of ‘Long Term Repo Operation’ of Reserve Bank of India? 1. To let banks, borrow one to three-year funds from the central bank at the repo rate. 2. To increase marginal cost of funds-based lending rate of the banks without reducing policy rates. 3. To undertake maturity transformation and augment credit flows to productive sectors. 4. To reduce the spread between long-term Government securities bonds and corporate bonds. Select the correct answer using the codes given below:","options":{"a":"1 and 3 only","b":"2 and 3 only","c":"1, 2 and 4 only","d":"1, 2, 3 and 4"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct. Under on-tap targeted long-term repo operations (TLTRO), RBI will\nconduct term repos of one-year and three-year tenors of appropriate sizes for up to a total\namount of Rs 1 lakh crore at the policy repo rate. Funds through LTRO will be provided at the repo\nrate. This means that banks can avail one year and three-year loans at the same interest rate of\none day repo.\n\nStatement 2 is incorrect. Long Term Repo Operation will not increase marginal cost of funds-\nbased lending rate of the banks without reducing policy rates. On the contrary, it will ensure that\nbanks reduce their marginal cost of fundsbased lending rate, without reducing policy rates. As\nbanks get long-term funds at lower rates, their cost of funds falls. In turn, they reduce interest\nrates for borrowers.\nStatement 3 is correct. Long Term Repo Operation will assure banks about the availability of\ndurable liquidity at reasonable cost relative to prevailing market conditions. Further encourage\nbanks to undertake maturity transformation smoothly and seamlessly so as to augment credit\nflows to productive sectors.\nStatement 4 is incorrect. Long Term Repo Operation does not intend to reduce the spread\nbetween long-term Government securities bonds and corporate bonds.\nImportant Tips\nOperation twist involves buying long term securities and selling short term securities. It will\nreduce the yield of long-term securities compared to that of the short-term ones. This yield\nimpact is the objective of Operation Twist.","topic":"Bonds & Securities","id":72,"area":"Monetary Policy Tools"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-03-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-03","qNum":13,"question":"Consider the following statements: 1. If Reserve bank of India reduces the cash reserve ratio it will decrease the money supply in economy. 2. The lowering of bank rate by the Reserve bank of India leads to more liquidity in the market. 3. An increase in Statutory Liquidity Ratio rate means that commercial banks shall have to invest more money in Government and other approved securities. 4. Loan-to-value is a ratio used in mortgage lending to determine the amount necessary to put in a down-payment. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"Only three","d":"All four"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is incorrect: The Reserve Bank of India or RBI mandates that banks store a proportion\nof their deposits in the form of cash so that the same can be given to the bank’s customers if the\nneed arises. The percentage of cash required to be kept in reserves, vis-a-vis a bank’s total\ndeposits, is called the Cash Reserve Ratio. The cash reserve is either stored in the bank’s vault or\nis sent to the RBI. Banks do not get any interest on the money that is with the RBI under the CRR\nrequirements.\nStatement 2 is correct: Any reduction in the bank rate and the repo rate will lead to borrowers\ngetting loans at lower interest rates. The lowering of the Bank Rate makes the domestic banks\nborrow money at a cheap rate which in turn increases the liquidity in the market.\nStatement 3 is correct: The SLR regulation is binding on all the commercial banks in India. RBI is\nwith the power to increase the SLR rate, as and when it desires to do so. An increase in SLR rate\nmeans that commercial banks shall have to invest more money in Government and other\napproved securities which deplete lendable sources of the banks.\n\nStatement 4 is correct: Loan-to-value (LTV) is an often-used ratio in mortgage lending to\ndetermine the amount necessary to put in a down-payment and whether a lender will extend\ncredit to a borrower.","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","id":73,"area":"Monetary Policy Tools"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-03-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-03","qNum":14,"question":"With reference to the monetary policy tools of the Reserve Bank of India, consider the following statements: 1. A Reverse Repo Rate is the interest rate at which the Central Bank gives loans to commercial banks. 2. Reserve Bank of India conducts Variable Rate Reverse Repo (VRRR) auctions to increase liquidity in the banking system. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Option d is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is incorrect: Reverse repo rate is the interest rate paid to commercial banks when\nthey deposit their excess funds in the central bank or when the central bank borrows money\nfrom them. Repo rate is the rate at which the central bank gives loans to commercial banks against\ngovernment securities.\nStatement 2 is incorrect: The decision of Reserve Bank India (RBI) to conduct variable rate\nreverse repo (VRRR) auctions aims to absorb excess liquidity from the banking system.","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","id":74,"area":"Monetary Policy Tools"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-03-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-03","qNum":15,"question":"With reference to Open Market Operations (OMOs), consider the following statements: 1. It can be used for both increasing or decreasing the supply of money in the banking system. 2. It is conducted through E-Kuber platform of the Reserve bank of India. 3. Operation Twist is a type of OMO under which sale and purchase of Governments securities is conducted simultaneously. How many of the above given statements are incorrect?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Option d is the correct answer.\nOpen market operations (OMOs) are an effective quantitative policy tool at the disposal of RBI. It\nhelps in maintaining the impact on inflation and interest rate levels.\nStatement 1 is correct: OMOs refers to the purchase and sale of government securities(G-sec),\ndone by RBI on the government’s behalf. When G-sec is bought, it increases the liquidity or money\nsupply in the market on the other the hand when G-sec is sold, money supply is decreased, or\nliquidity is drained from the market.\n\nStatement 2 is correct: RBI carries out the OMO through commercial banks and does not directly\ndeal with the public. Eligible participants are required to key in their bids on RBI’s core banking\nelectronic solution platform E-Kuber.\nStatement 3 is correct: Simultaneous purchase and sale of government securities under OMOs\nis popularly known as Operation Twist. It involves buying long-end debt while selling short-tenor\nbonds to keep borrowing costs down.\nImportant Tips\nOperation Twist is a way employed by the central bank to manage yields in the market. It is a\nprogram of quantitative easing used by the RBI that was first introduced by the Federal Reserves\nin US in 1961. Since prices and yields move in opposite directions, by purchasing longer-term\nbonds, the RBI can help drive the bond prices up and yields down. At the same time, selling\nshorter-term bonds should cause their yields to go up (since their prices would fall). In\ncombination, these two actions twist the shape of the yield curve.","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","id":75,"area":"Monetary Policy Tools"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-03-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-03","qNum":16,"question":"Consider the following pairs: Monetary Policy stance of the Reserve Bank of India Action taken by the Reserve Bank 1. Accommodative Stance RBI may lower the interest rates 2. Neutral Stance The policy priority of RBI is equal on both inflation and economic growth. 3. Hawkish Stance RBI increases the lending rate of interest to the banks. 4. Calibrated Tightening RBI always reduces the Repo Rate How many pairs given above is/are correctly matched?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"Only three","d":"All four"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer\nCentral banks’ decisions rely on an assessment of their monetary policy stance.\nPair 1 is correct: An accommodative stance means the Monetary Policy Committee (MPC) is\nwilling to either lower rates or keep them unchanged Accommodative monetary policy is a\nstrategy used by central banks that is aimed at keeping interest rates low in order to infuse more\ncash into the economy to boost growth.\nPair 2 is correct: Neutral stance indicates that central bank may cut or hike interest rate. Range\nof rates consistent with full employment, trend growth, and stable prices. Policy priority is equal\non both inflation and economic growth.\nPair 3 is correct: Hawkish stance indicates the tight monetary policy where main aim of central\nbank is to control inflation. RBI is in favour of high interest rate to curb the money supply in\nmarket.\nPair 4 is incorrect: Calibrated tightening refers to the no obligation of increasing repo rate at\nevery policy meeting in current rate cycle. So, RBI will either keep repo rate unchanged or may\nincrease it.","topic":"Inflation & Deflation","id":76,"area":"Monetary Policy Tools"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-03-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-03","qNum":17,"question":"Consider the following statements: 1. An increase in the Cash Reserve Ratio may reduce the credit availability in the economy. 2. An increase in Repo Rates may result in an increase in the cost of borrowing. 3. Lower Bank Rates can help to lower the cost of funds for borrowers. 4. An increase in the Statutory Liquidity Ratio will tend to reduce money supply in economy. How many of the above given statements are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"Only three","d":"All four"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Option d is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct: If the RBI decides to increase the CRR, then bank have to keep higher cash.\nThis will reduce the credit in the economy as the banks now have less money to lend, less lending\nmeans less borrowing and investment and hence reduction in income and aggregate demand.\nStatement 2 is correct: An increase in repo rates means an increase in the cost of borrowing. This\nis because when the repo rate rises, the borrowing cost for banking institutions also rises, which\nis passed on to account holders in the form of higher loan and deposit interest rates.\nStatement 3 is correct: Managing the bank rate is a method by which central banks affect\neconomic activity. Lower bank rates can help to expand the economy by lowering the cost of funds\nfor borrowers, and higher bank rates help to reign in the economy when inflation is higher than\ndesired.\nStatement 4 is correct: As SLR is increased banks will have to keep more liquidity with themselves.\nSo, the less amount of funds will be available to the banks for credit creation. The total money\nsupply in the economy will decrease, this will lead to less demand.\nImportant Tips\n• Cash Reserve Ratio (CRR): The average daily balance that a bank is required to maintain with\nthe Reserve Bank as a per cent of its net demand and time liabilities (NDTL).\n• Repos or Repurchase Agreements is an instrument which allows banks to borrow money from\nthe RBI to manage short term needs of liquidity against the selling of government securities\nwith an agreement to repurchase the same government securities at a predetermined date and\nrate. The rate at which the RBI lends to the banks is called Repo Rate.\n• Bank Rate: The rate at which the Reserve Bank is ready to buy or rediscount bills of exchange\nor other commercial papers.\n• Statutory Liquidity Ratio or SLR is a minimum percentage of deposits that a commercial bank\nhas to maintain in the form of liquid cash, gold or other securities.","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","id":77,"area":"Monetary Policy Tools"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-03-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-03","qNum":18,"question":"Which of the following is the main aim of Standing Deposit Facility (SDF), recently introduced by the Reserve Bank of India?","options":{"a":"To increase demand in the economy by increasing the money supply.","b":"To absorb excess liquidity from the banking system in India.","c":"To ensure effective monetary policy transmission at ground level.","d":"To ensure that banks have enough capital to handle certain number of losses."},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nWhen banks have excess funds, they lend it to the RBI at the reverse repo rate in order to get\nreturns from these extra funds. To execute the reverse repo rate functions, RBI needs\ngovernment securities as collaterals. SDF is a monetary tool that allows banks to park their access\nliquidity with RBI without any collateral. RBI has introduced this tool to absorb excess liquidity in\nthe market as it plays an important role in determining the policy rates. Due to demonetization,\nfunds with banks increased majorly and recently RBI also increased the reverse repo rate, these\nchanges started attracting more funds towards the reverse repo operations. As the collaterals with\nRBI are limited in nature, it introduced a new facility known as Standing deposit facility, that allows\nRBI to execute reverse repo operations without using collaterals to absorb excess funds in the\nbanking sector.","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","id":78,"area":"Monetary Policy Tools"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-03-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-03","qNum":19,"question":"Which one of the following will be the most likely implication of the increase in repo rate by 1% by Reserve Bank of India?","options":{"a":"Increase in credit offtake in the market by corporates and investors.","b":"Yield of the government bonds will definitely decrease in the long run.","c":"Borrowing costs for individuals and businesses may increase.","d":"Inflation will increase due to excessive money circulation in the market."},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nIn India, if the Repo rate is increased by 1%, the main implication is that it would become more\nexpensive for commercial banks to borrow money from the Reserve Bank of India (RBI). This\nmakes it more expensive for commercial banks to lend money to their customers, such as\nindividuals and businesses. As such, borrowing costs for individuals and businesses would\nincrease, which could lead to a slowdown in economic growth.\nOption a is incorrect: An increase in the repo rate actually leads to a decrease in credit offtake\nin the market. Commercial banks have to pay a higher interest rate to borrow money from the\nRBI, and this cost is passed on to their customers in the form of higher lending rates.\nOption b is incorrect: An increase in the repo rate is likely to increase the yield of government\nbonds in the long run, the increase in the repo rate is likely to reduce inflationary pressures,\nwhich may increase investor confidence in the economy and lead to an increase in the demand\nfor government bonds, thereby increasing their yield.\nOption d is incorrect: An increase in the repo rate is often used by the RBI to control inflation\nby reducing the amount of money available for lending and spending. This reduces the demand\nfor goods and services, which may lead to a decrease in the prices of goods and services, thus\nbreaking the inflationary cycle.\nImportant Tips\nThe decision to increase the Repo rate in India is taken by the Monetary Policy Committee\n(MPC), which takes into account various factors, including inflation, economic growth, and\nglobal economic conditions, before making its decision","topic":"Inflation & Deflation","id":79,"area":"Monetary Policy Tools"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-03-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-03","qNum":20,"question":"With reference to the liquidity management, consider the following instruments: 1. Liquidity Adjustment Facility 2. Marginal Standing Facility 3. Call Money Market 4. Notice Money market How many of the above given instruments are accessible to Regional Rural banks?","options":{"a":"Only One","b":"Only Two","c":"Only Three","d":"All four"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Option d is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct: Liquidity Adjustment Facility (LAF) has been extended to RRB. It enables\nbanks to borrow money through repurchase agreements (repo) or banks to lend to the RBI using\nreverse repo contracts.\nStatement 2 is correct: Marginal Standing Facility (MSF) has been extended to RRBs. In this,\nplanned commercial banks can lend extra amount of immediate cash from the RBI by dipping into\ntheir Statutory Liquidity Ratio (SLR) collection up till a limit at a penal rate of interest.\nStatement 3 is correct: Call Money Market has been extended to RRB. Call money is also referred\nto as the money at call. It is a short-term loan which is due to be paid immediately in full as and\nwhen demanded by the lender generally transacted on overnight basis.\nStatement 4 is correct: Notice money market has been extended to RRB. It is a short-term loan\nwhich is due to be paid after serving the notice. under notice money market, funds are transacted\nfor the period between 2 days and 14 days.\nImportant Tips\n• The maintaining of liquid assets by the commercial banks at the rate fixed by RBI is called\nStatutory Liquidity Ratio.\n• SLR is a statutory provision under Section 24 of the Banking Regulation Act 1949 and it is in\naddition to the Cash Reserve Ratio to be maintained by the bank.\n• Every scheduled bank in India requires maintaining liquid assets in the form of cash, gold and\nunencumbered approved securities and value of which shall not be less than 25 percent of\ndemand and time liabilities of the bank.\n• The implication of change in SLR is same as the change in CRR in regulating the expansion of\ncredit. The SLR regulation is binding on all the commercial banks in India","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","id":80,"area":"Monetary Policy Tools"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-03-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-03","qNum":21,"question":"Consider the following statements with reference to inflation targeting in India: 1. The announcement of an official target range for inflation is known as inflation targeting. 2. Inflation Target must be set by the Reserve Bank of India every year. 3. The primary objective of monetary policy in India is to maintain price stability while keeping in mind the objective of growth. 4. When the RBI fails to meet the inflation target for three consecutive Quarters, its Monetary Policy Committee must resign. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"Only three","d":"All four"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct. The announcement of an official target range for inflation is known as\ninflation targeting. It is done by the Central Bank in an economy as a part of their monetary policy\nto realise the objective of a stable rate of inflation (the Government of India asked the RBI to\nperform this function in the early 1970s\nStatement 2 is incorrect. The Reserve Bank of India Act provides for the inflation target to be\nset by the Government of India, in consultation with the central bank, once in every five years.\nStatement 3 is correct. Monetary policy refers to the use of monetary instruments under the\ncontrol of the central bank to regulate magnitudes such as interest rates, money supply and\navailability of credit with a view to achieving the ultimate objective of the economic policy. The\nprimary objective of the monetary policy is to maintain price stability while keeping in mind\nthe objective of growth. Price stability is a necessary pre-condition to sustainable growth.\nStatement 4 is incorrect. When the RBI fails to meet the inflation target, it will send a report\nto the central government stating reasons and the remedial actions that will be taken.\nImportant Tips\nA breach of the tolerance level for three consecutive quarters will constitute a failure of\nmonetary policy. “The central government notified the following as factors that constitute\nfailure to achieve the inflation target: the average inflation is more than the upper tolerance\nlevel of the inflation target for any three consecutive quarters the average inflation is less than\nthe lower tolerance level for any three consecutive quarters”.","topic":"Inflation & Deflation","id":81,"area":"Monetary Policy Tools"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-03-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-03","qNum":22,"question":"Which of the following measures are likely to be adopted by the Government/RBI to tackle inflation? 1. Increase in indirect taxes 2. Surplus budget 3. Increasing Cash Reserve Ratio 4. Decreasing the Repo Rate Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"1, 2 and 3 only","c":"2 and 3 only","d":"1, 2, 3 and 4"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nOption 1 is incorrect. Increase in Indirect tax rate like Goods and service tax (GST), excise duty\nwill push the price further up. So, reducing the indirect tax rate is a measure used by the\ngovernment to curb inflation.\nOption 2 is correct. Surplus budget means less expenditure than receipts. It reduces the money\nsupply and government demand for goods and services. The price level will be brought down due\nto this.\nOption 3 is correct. Scheduled banks are required to keep a certain percentage of their Net Time\nand Demand Deposits with RBI. Thus, the increased CRR means less money with banks to lend\nwhich will reduce the money supply in the economy.\n\nOption 4 is incorrect. Repo rate is the rate at which the commercial banks borrow money from\nRBI by mortgaging their dated government securities and treasury bills. The decreased repo rate\nmeans the cheaper credit access to banks from RBI which will ultimately increase the money\nsupply in the economy.","topic":"Inflation & Deflation","id":82,"area":"Monetary Policy Tools"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-03-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-03","qNum":23,"question":"Which one of the following activities of the Reserve Bank of India is considered to be part of ‘sterilization’?","options":{"a":"Conducting ‘Open Market Operations’","b":"Oversight of settlement and payment systems","c":"Debt and cash management for the Central and State Governments","d":"Regulating the functions of Non-banking Financial Institutions"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nSterilization refers to the actions taken by a central bank to offset the impact of its foreign\nexchange operations on the domestic money supply. When a central bank intervenes in the\nforeign exchange market by buying or selling foreign currencies, it affects the domestic money\nsupply. Open Market Operations (OMO) is one of the primary tools used by central banks,\nincluding the Reserve Bank of India (RBI), to conduct monetary policy. In OMO, the central bank\nbuys or sells government securities (bonds) in the open market to influence the liquidity in the\neconomy. When the RBI conducts OMO, it impacts the money supply in the economy. If the RBI\nbuys government securities, it injects money into the system, increasing the money supply. To\nprevent this injection of money from creating inflationary pressures, the RBI engages in\nsterilization. Sterilization involves the simultaneous sale or purchase of other securities, typically\ntreasury bills, to offset the impact of the initial open market operation.\nImportant Tips\n• Oversight of settlement payment systems refers to the role of the Reserve Bank of India in\nsupervising and ensuring the smooth functioning of payment and settlement systems in the\ncountry. Payment systems facilitate the transfer of funds between individuals, businesses, and\nfinancial institutions.\n• Debt and cash management for the Central and State Governments involves the Reserve Bank\nof India’s role in managing the issuance, redemption, and servicing of government debt, as well\nas overseeing the cash flow operations of the government. This function is important for\nmaintaining government finances and liquidity.\n• The Reserve Bank of India regulates and supervises non-banking financial institutions (NBFIs)\nsuch as non-banking financial companies (NBFCs). NBFIs play a crucial role in the financial\nsystem by providing various financial services.","topic":"Types of Banks","id":83,"area":"Monetary Policy Tools"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-03-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-03","qNum":24,"question":"If the RBI decides to adopt an expansionist monetary policy, which of the following would it not do? 1. Cut and optimize the Statutory Liquidity Ratio 2. Increase the Marginal Standing Facility Rate 3. Cut the Bank Rate and Repo Rate Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 only","c":"1 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nExpansionary monetary policy is when the Reserve Bank of India uses its monetary policy tools to\nstimulate the economy. That increases the money supply, lowers interest rates, and increases\ndemand.\nStatements 1 is incorrect. A reduction in SLR would mean higher liquidity for the banks, so they\nwould have more funds to lend. This would tend to reduce lending rates and increase demand\nin the economy. The SLR is the reserve that the commercial banks in India are required to\nmaintain in the form of cash, gold reserves, government approved securities before providing\ncredit to the customers.\nStatement 2 is correct. Marginal Standing facility (MSF) is a special window for the commercial\nbanks to borrow from the RBI against approved government securities, in case of an emergency\nsuch as an acute cash shortage. MSF rate is generally higher than Repo rate. An increase in the\nMSF rate leads to higher borrowing cost for the banks and thus, reduces money supply in the\neconomy. It is a contractionary monetary policy.\nStatements 3 is incorrect. A cut in repo rate means cost of borrowing from the Reserve Bank\nwill be lower for commercial banks. The rate cut will further help banks to lower loan interest\nrates for borrowers.","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","id":84,"area":"Monetary Policy Tools"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-03-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-03","qNum":25,"question":"Which of the following statements is/are correct regarding the ‘Monetary Policy Committee (MPC)? 1. It decides the RBI’s benchmark interest rates. 2. It is a 12-member body including the Governor of RBI and is reconstituted every year. 3. It functions under the chairmanship of the Union Finance Minister. Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"1 and 2 only","c":"3 only","d":"2 and 3 only"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer\nStatement 1 is correct. The Monetary Policy Committee is a statutory and institutionalized\nframework under the Reserve Bank of India Act, 1934, for maintaining price stability, while keeping\nin mind the objective of growth.\nStatements 2 and 3 are incorrect. The Governor of RBI is ex-officio Chairman of the committee.\nThe committee comprises six members (including the Chairman) – three officials of the RBI and\nthree external members nominated by the Government of India.","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","id":85,"area":"Monetary Policy Tools"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-03-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-03","qNum":26,"question":"When the Reserve Bank of India reduces the Statutory Liquidity Ratio by 50 basis points, which of the following is likely to happen?","options":{"a":"India’s GDP growth rate increases drastically","b":"Foreign Institutional Investors may bring more capital into our country","c":"Scheduled Commercial Banks may cut their lending rates.","d":"It may drastically reduce the liquidity to the banking system"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer\nStatutory Liquidity Ratio or SLR is the minimum percentage of deposits that a commercial bank\nhas to maintain in the form of liquid cash, gold or other securities. If SLR is reduced, the lending\ncapacity of banks increases as they have to park lesser money with RBI in form of securities, cash\netc. So, they have more money to lend and thus the scheduled commercial banks may cut their\nlending rates.","topic":"RBI Functions","id":86,"area":"Monetary Policy Tools"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-03-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-03","qNum":27,"question":"The terms ‘Marginal Standing Facility Rate’ and ‘Net Demand and Time Liabilities’, sometimes appearing in news, are used in relation to","options":{"a":"banking operations","b":"communications networking","c":"military strategies","d":"supply and demand of agricultural Products"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer\nMarginal standing facility (MSF) is a window for banks to borrow from the Reserve Bank of India\nin an emergency situation when inter-bank liquidity dries up completely.\nImportant Tips\nThe MSF rate is pegged 100 basis points or a percentage point above the repo rate. Under MSF,\nbanks can borrow funds up to one percentage of their net demand and time liabilities (NDTL).","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","id":87,"area":"Monetary Policy Tools"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-03-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-03","qNum":28,"question":"In the context of Indian economy which of the following is/are the purpose/purposes of ‘Statutory Reserve Requirements’? 1. To enable the Central Bank to control the amount of advances the banks can create. 2. To make the people’s deposits with banks safe and liquid. 3. To prevent the commercial banks from making excessive profits. 4. To force the banks to have sufficient vault cash to meet their day-to-day requirements. Select the correct answer using the code given below.","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"1 and 2 only","c":"2 and 3 only","d":"1, 2, 3 and 4"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer\nThe Statutory Reserve Requirement (SRR) is an instrument used by the central bank to manage\nliquidity in the banking system. Cash Reserve Ratio (CRR) and SLR (Statutory Liquid Ratio) are\nStatutory Reserve Requirements of the RBI. Under these, the banks keep a mandated amount of\ntheir NDTL with the RBI. Thus affecting the amount of advances they make.","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","id":88,"area":"Monetary Policy Tools"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-03-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-03","qNum":29,"question":"In the context of Indian economy, ‘Open Market Operations’ refers to","options":{"a":"borrowing by scheduled banks from the RBI","b":"lending by commercial banks to industry and trade","c":"purchase and sale of government securities by the RBI","d":"None of the above"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer\nAny of the purchases and sales of government securities by the RBI for the purpose of regulating\nthe money supply and credit conditions on a continuous basis is referred to as ‘Open Market\nOperation’. This affects the money supply and the interest rates.","topic":"Bonds & Securities","id":89,"area":"Monetary Policy Tools"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-03-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-03","qNum":30,"question":"The lowering of Bank Rate by the Reserve Bank of India leads to","options":{"a":"More liquidity in the market","b":"Less liquidity in the market","c":"No change in the liquidity in the market","d":"Mobilization of more deposits by commercial banks"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nBank rate or discount rate is the rate of interest which a central bank charges on the loans and\nadvances to a commercial bank.\nA decrease in bank rate means that banks will have to pay less rate of interest which will make\nborrowing cheaper and thus banks have the flexibility to disburse loans at lower rates. This leads\nto increased borrowing by public and thus, more liquidity in the market.","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","id":90,"area":"Monetary Policy Tools"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-04-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-04","qNum":1,"question":"Which of the following factor/s prevent the effective transmission of monetary policy to deposit and lending rates of banks? 1. Mismatch of banks’ assets and liabilities. 2. Competitive pressure from small savings schemes. 3. Internal benchmark for pricing of loans. Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"1 and 2 only","c":"2 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Option d is the correct answer.\nOption d is correct. The Reserve Bank of India has noted that there are several factors which\ncontinue to impede monetary transmission to deposit and lending rates of banks. This includes:\n1. Mismatch of banks’ assets and liabilities.\n2. Competitive pressure from small savings schemes.\n3. Asset’s quality of scheduled commercial banks.\n4. Internal benchmark for pricing of loans and heterogeneous pricing methodology of NBFCs.","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","id":91,"area":"Monetary Policy Transmission"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-04-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-04","qNum":2,"question":"Which of the following factor/s affect the value of the money multiplier? 1. Statutory Liquidity Ratio 2. Cash Reserve Ratio 3. Currency Deposit Ratio of the public Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"2 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Option d is the correct answer.\nOptions 1 and 2 are correct: A high (or low) value of CRR or SLR helps increase (or decrease) the\nvalue of reserve deposit ratio, thus diminishing (or increasing) the value of the money multiplier\nand money supply in the economy in a similar fashion.\nOption 3 is correct: The size of money multiplier is determined by the currency ratio (Cr) of the\npublic, the required reserve ratio (RRr) of the central bank and the excess reserve ratio (ERr) of\ncommercial banks. The lower these ratios, higher the money multiplier.","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","id":92,"area":"Monetary Policy Transmission"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-04-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-04","qNum":3,"question":"Which of the following are possible signs of a Liquidity Trap? 1. Rise in unemployment 2. High Savings rate 3. Low Interest Rate 4. High Investment Rate Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1, 2 and 3 only","b":"2, 3 and 4 only","c":"1, 3 and 4 only","d":"1, 2, 3 and 4"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nPossible signs of Liquidity Trap:\n• consumers avoid making new purchases, this results in slowing of economic activities leading\nto fall in hiring and ultimately unemployment.\n• people prefer to hold on to liquid assets like cash. So, the Savings Rate is very high.\n• Liquidity Traps occur during expansionary phases of monetary policy, i.e. when the rate of\ninterest is very low\n• People prefer to save money as cash, rather than invest it or spend it, leading to low\ninvestment rates.\nImportant Tips\nLiquidity trap is a situation when expansionary monetary policy (increase in money supply) does\nnot increase the interest rate, income and hence does not stimulate economic growth.","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","id":93,"area":"Monetary Policy Transmission"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-04-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-04","qNum":5,"question":"Which of the following are the constituents of ‘aggregate monetary resources (M3)’ in an economy? 1. Currency and coin with the public 2. Net demand deposits held by commercial banks 3. Net time deposits of commercial banks Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"1 and 3 only","c":"2 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Option d is the correct answer.\nM1 = CU (currency held by the public) + DD (net Demand deposit held by commercial bank)\nM2 = M1 + Savings deposits with Post Office savings banks\nM3 = M1 + Net time deposits of commercial banks\nM4 = M3 + Total deposits with Post Office savings organisations (excluding National Savings\nCertificates)\nM1 and M2 are known as narrow money. M3 and M4 are known as broad money.","topic":"Money & Currency","id":94,"area":"Monetary Policy Transmission"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-04-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-04","qNum":6,"question":"With reference to the concept of monetary aggregates, narrow money and broad money, consider the following statements: 1. M1, M2, M3 and M4 are alternative measures of money supply published by RBI. 2. M1 is most liquid and easiest for transactions whereas M4 is least liquid of all. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct: Money supply, like money demand, is a stock variable. The total stock of\nmoney in circulation among the public at a particular point of time is called money supply. RBI\npublishes figures for four alternative measures of money supply, viz. M1, M2, M3 and M4.\nStatement 2 is correct: M1 is most liquid and easiest for transactions whereas M4 is least liquid\nof all. M3 is the most commonly used measure of money supply.","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","id":95,"area":"Monetary Policy Transmission"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-04-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-04","qNum":7,"question":"With reference to financial inclusion, consider the following statements: 1. Creation of basic banking accounts is considered necessary and sufficient for financial inclusion. 2. Availing loans from a local moneylender at exorbitant interest rates is a form of financial inclusion. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Option d is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is incorrect: A banking account is necessary but not sufficient for financial inclusion.\nFor example, millions of accounts were opened under PM Jan Dhan Yojana but a significant\nnumber of accounts are zero-balance accounts.\nStatement 2 is incorrect: Financial inclusion doesn’t just mean access to financial services but\nrather means access to affordable financial services. In rural areas, people have access to local\nmoneylenders. But these moneylenders advance loans at very high rates of interest, which often\npushes the borrowers into debt-trap. Hence, because of the unaffordability, people are excluded\nfrom the benefits of having access to financial services.\nImportant Tips\nFinancial inclusion is a broad-based concept that the following aspects – basic banking account,\naccess to affordable credit, availability of banking and financial infrastructure in a region,\nfinancial literacy etc.","topic":"Economy — Misc","id":96,"area":"Monetary Policy Transmission"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-04-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-04","qNum":8,"question":"Consider the following pairs: Types of Money Description 1. Fiat money Backed by physical commodity like gold 2. Legal tender Mandatory to accept it as mode of settlement 3. Fiduciary money Backed by trust between payer and payee How many of the above pairs are correctly matched?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nPair 1 is incorrect. Fiat money or fiat currency is any money that the government declares as legal\ntender. It is issued on the order of the government and is not backed by a physical commodity\nsuch as gold or silver. In other words, fiat money has no intrinsic value. Market forces determine\nthe value of fiat money. There is no obligation on any person to accept this money as a medium\nof exchange. No legal action can be initiated in this case. Governments introduced this type of\nmoney as an alternative to representative and commodity money (gold coin).\nPair 2 is correct. Legal tender is the money that is recognized by the law of the land, as valid for\npayment of debt. Similarly, it must be accepted for discharge of debt. It is compulsory to accept\nthis type of money for the settlement of any monetary obligation.\nPair 3 is correct. Fiduciary money refers to money backed up by trust between the payer and\npayee. Example: Cheques are fiduciary money as these are accepted as a means of payment on\nthe basis of trust but not on the basis of any order of the government.\nImportant Tips\nThe government can issue fiat money and can declare it to be a legal tender. The coins issued\nby the Government of India under The Coinage Act, 2011 are legal tender. Similarly, the One\nRupee notes issued by the Ministry of Finance (Government of India) under the Currency\n\nOrdinance, 1940 are legal tender. Every banknote issued by Reserve Bank of India under RBI Act,\n1934 unless withdrawn from circulation (demonetisation), is a legal tender.","topic":"Money & Currency","id":97,"area":"Monetary Policy Transmission"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-04-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-04","qNum":9,"question":"Consider the following statements with respect to the money supply: 1. Credit and loans are not taken into account while measuring money supply in an economy. 2. An increase in the supply of money can lower the interest rates and generate investment. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nThe total stock of money circulating in an economy is the money supply. The circulating money\ninvolves the currency, printed notes, money in the deposit accounts and in the form of other liquid\nassets.\nStatement 1 is incorrect. Different measures of money supply take into account non-cash items\nlike credit and loans as well. The money supply roughly includes both cash and deposits that can\nbe used almost as easily as cash.\nStatement 2 is correct. If there is an increase in supply of money the interest rate is likely to\ndecrease, which in turn, generates more investment and puts more money in the hands of\nconsumers, thereby stimulating spending.","topic":"Money & Currency","id":98,"area":"Monetary Policy Transmission"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-04-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-04","qNum":11,"question":"Regarding the currency deposit ratio, which of the following statement is incorrect?","options":{"a":"It is the ratio of money held by the public in currency to the money they hold in bank deposits.","b":"High currency deposit ratio reflects people’s high preference for savings in banks.","c":"An increase in currency deposit ratio will lead to decrease in money multiplier.","d":"It depends on the seasonal pattern of expenditure."},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nStatement a is correct. The currency deposit ratio (CDR) is the ratio of money held by the public\nin currency to that they hold in bank deposits. It shows the amount of money that people hold\nas a proportion of aggregate deposits (bank deposits).\nStatement b is incorrect. The currency deposit ratio does not reflect people’s preference for\nsavings. On the contrary, it shows people’s preference for liquidity i.e., the amount they would\nhold in form of currency in proportion to bank deposits.\nStatement c is correct. An increase in cash deposit ratio leads to a decrease in money multiplier.\nAn increase in cash deposit ratio mean people holding cash more in hand and depositing less thus\nleading to decrease in money multiplier.\nStatement d is correct. The currency deposit ratio is a purely behavioural parameter which\ndepends, among other things, on the seasonal pattern of expenditure. For example, CDR increases\nduring the festive season as people convert deposits to cash balance for meeting extra\nexpenditure during such periods.","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","id":99,"area":"Monetary Policy Transmission"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-04-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-04","qNum":12,"question":"With reference to Marginal Cost of Funds based Lending Rate (MCLR), consider the following statements: 1. It is the maximum rate of interest above which the banks cannot lend. 2. It replaced the earlier Base Rate structure of determining lending rates. 3. It is determined internally by the banks. How many of the above given statements are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nMarginal Cost of Funds-based Lending Rate (MCLR) is a methodology to determine lending rates\nfor banks. The Reserve Bank of India introduced the MCLR system on April 1, 2016.\nStatement 1 is incorrect: MCLR refers to the minimum limit below which banks or lender cannot\nlend. Because of slower transmission of monetary policy under MCLR, in 2019 RBI switched to the\nexternal benchmark linked lending rate (EBLR) system.\nStatement 2 is correct: Earlier, Base Rate determines the lending rate. But base rate differed from\nbank to bank hence fell short of its aim at better assessment of transmission of monetary policy.\nHence in 2015 banks shifted to new methodology of calculating their lending rate which is MCLR.\nStatement 3 is correct: MCLR is a tenor-linked internal benchmark, which means the rate is\ndetermined internally by the bank depending on the period left for the repayment of a loan.\nUnder the MCLR regime, banks are free to offer all categories of loans on fixed or floating interest\nrates.\nImportant Tips\nIn the external benchmark linked lending rate (EBLR) system, banks need to link their loan\ninterest rate to external benchmark such as:\n1. RBI repo rate\n2. 91- day and 182 -day treasury bills.\n3. any other benchmarks by financial benchmarks limited.","topic":"Bonds & Securities","id":100,"area":"Monetary Policy Transmission"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-04-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-04","qNum":13,"question":"Which among the following will most likely lead to an increase in the money multiplier in the economy? 1. Increase in the Cash Reserve Ratio 2. Increase in the banking habit of the people 3. Decrease in bank rate 4. Increase in the repo rate Select the correct answer using the codes given below:","options":{"a":"1, 2 and 3 only","b":"2, 3 and 4 only","c":"1 and 4 only","d":"2 and 3 only"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Option d is the correct answer.\nMoney multiplier is a term in monetary economics that is a phenomenon of creating money in the\neconomy in the form of credit creation, which is based on the fractional reserve banking system.\nStatement 1 is incorrect: When RBI increases the CRR, it squeezes the money flow in the\neconomy, reducing investments and bringing down inflation. Thus, an increase in CRR will lead\nto a decrease in the multiplier effect.\nStatement 2 is correct: An increase in banking activity will lead to more money in the bank’s hands\nin the form of Time Deposits, Demand Deposits etc, thus increase in banking habits of the people\nwill increase the money multiplier.\nStatement 3 is correct: Decreased repo rate and bank rate results in availability of cheaper loans\nto banks. This results in increased money multiplier.\nStatement 4 is incorrect: The repo rate is the interest rate at which the Reserve Bank of India\n(RBI) loans money to commercial banks. Increasing the Repo rate makes the cost of the funds\nhigh for commercial banks and leads to high interest rates on loans which leads to reduction\nin the money supply in market. Thus, a high repo rate reduces the money multiplier effect.\nImportant Tips\nCash Reserve Ratio (CRR) is the share of a bank’s total deposit that is mandated by the Reserve\nBank of India (RBI) to be maintained with the latter as reserves in the form of liquid cash. There\nare two main objectives of the Cash Reserve Ratio:\n• Cash Reserve Ratio ensures that a part of the bank’s deposit is with the Central Bank and is\nhence, secure.\n• Another objective of CRR is to keep inflation under control. During high inflation in the\neconomy, RBI raises the CRR to reduce the amount of money left with banks to sanction loans.","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","id":101,"area":"Monetary Policy Transmission"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-04-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-04","qNum":14,"question":"Consider the following options: 1. Currency held by the public 2. Vault cash of commercial banks 3. Deposits held by the Government of India with the RBI How many of the above given items form a part of High-Powered Money?","options":{"a":"Only One","b":"Only Two","c":"All Three","d":"None"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nAll the statements are correct.\nThe total liability of the monetary authority of the country, RBI, is called the monetary base or\nhigh-powered money.\nIt consists of:\nOption 1 is correct: currency (notes and coins in circulation with the public),\nOption 2 is correct: reserves of the commercial banks (which include vault cash and banks’\ndeposits) with RBI.\nOption 3 is correct: deposits held by the Government of India with RBI.","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","id":102,"area":"Monetary Policy Transmission"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-04-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-04","qNum":15,"question":"When there is a significant increase in the time deposits of the banks, which of the following standard measures of money supply in an economy would increase? 1. Reserve Money (M0) 2. Narrow Money (M1) 3. Broad Money (M3) Select the correct answer using the codes given below:","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 and 3 only","c":"3 only","d":"1 and 3 only"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nThe money supply is the total amount of money used by the general public at a given point in time.\n\nOption 1 and 2 are incorrect: Reserve Money (M0) includes the currency in circulation and the\nreserves held by the central bank, while Narrow Money (M1) includes the most liquid forms of\nmoney such as currency in circulation and demand deposits. Time deposits are not included in\nM0 or M1, and hence an increase in time deposits will not have a significant effect on these\nmeasures of money supply.\nOption 3 is correct: M3 includes demand deposits and time deposits. Hence, when there is an\nincrease in time deposits, it will lead to an increase in M3.\nImportant Tips\nM0, M1, M2, M3, and M4 are different measures of money supply that are commonly used to\ntrack the amount of money in circulation in an economy.\n• Reserve Money (M0): Other names include High- Powered Money, Financial Base, Base\nMoney, etc. M0 is calculated as follows: Money in circulation + Bankers’ deposits + Other\ndeposits with RBI. It is the economic foundation’s currency.\n• Narrow Money (M1): M1 equals money in circulation plus demand deposits in the banking\nsystem (current and savings accounts) plus additional deposits with the Reserve Bank of India\n(RBI).\n• Narrow Money (M2): Post Office Savings, Bank Savings Deposits added to M1 equals M2.\n• Broad Money (M3): M3 equals M1 plus time deposits made with banks.\n• Broad Money (M4): M4 is equal to M3 plus any deposits made at post office savings banks.","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","id":103,"area":"Monetary Policy Transmission"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-04-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-04","qNum":16,"question":"An increase in demand for currency during the festive season is likely to have which of the following effects? 1. Increase in withdrawals from banks 2. Reduction in banking system liquidity 3. Decline in money available with banks Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"1 and 2 only","c":"1, 2 and 3","d":"2 and 3 only"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nHigher demand for currency leads to greater withdrawals, reducing money with banks and hence\nlowering banking system liquidity.","topic":"Money & Currency","id":104,"area":"Monetary Policy Transmission"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-04-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-04","qNum":17,"question":"With reference to Credit-Deposit Ratio (CDR), consider the following statements: 1. It indicates the proportion of deposits used by banks for lending. 2. A higher CDR implies lower liquidity risk for banks. 3. Credit-Deposit Ratio can exceed 100%. Which of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"1 and 3 only","c":"2 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct: CDR shows how much of deposits are converted into loans.\nStatement 2 is incorrect: Higher CDR increases liquidity and credit risk.\nStatement 3 is correct: CDR may exceed 100% due to alternative funding sources.","topic":"Economy — Misc","id":105,"area":"Monetary Policy Transmission"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-04-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-04","qNum":18,"question":"Consider the following statements with reference to Net Interest Margin (NIM): 1. NIM is calculated as Net Interest Income divided by total loans. 2. A higher Credit-Deposit Ratio may lead to a decline in NIM. 3. Spread and Net Interest Margin mean the same thing. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct. NIM = (Net Interest Income / Loans) × 100.\nStatement 2 is correct. Higher CDR raises funding pressure and can reduce NIM.\nStatement 3 is incorrect. Spread refers to difference between lending and deposit rates, whereas\nNIM is a ratio based on income.","topic":"Economy — Misc","id":106,"area":"Monetary Policy Transmission"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-04-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-04","qNum":19,"question":"Which of the following factors strengthens monetary policy transmission in India? 1. Higher Capital Adequacy Ratio 2. Lower Gross NPAs 3. Lower Credit-Deposit Ratio Select the correct answer:","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 only","c":"1, 2 and 3","d":"1 only"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nHigher CAR and lower NPAs enable banks to transmit policy changes effectively. Lower CDR\nweakens transmission.","topic":"Basel Norms & Banking Regulation","id":107,"area":"Monetary Policy Transmission"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-04-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-04","qNum":20,"question":"Consider the following statements with regard to Banking System Liquidity: 1. Banking system liquidity refers to cash and liquid assets with banks in excess of CRR and SLR requirements. 2. Higher banking system liquidity necessarily leads to economic slowdown. 3. Banking system liquidity is inversely proportional to CRR and SLR. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct. Banking system liquidity is defined as cash and liquid assets with banks in\nexcess of reserve requirements to meet credit needs and depositor obligations.\nStatement 2 is incorrect. Higher banking system liquidity generally lowers interest rates and may\nincrease demand and inflation, not slowdown.\nStatement 3 is correct. Banking system liquidity is inversely proportional to CRR and SLR since\nhigher reserves reduce lendable funds.","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","id":108,"area":"Monetary Policy Transmission"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-04-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-04","qNum":21,"question":"Consider the following statements regarding Bond Prices and Bond Yields: 1. Bond prices and bond yields are inversely related. 2. Increase in government borrowings tends to increase bond yields. 3. Inflation benefits bond holders by increasing real returns. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct. Bond prices and yields move inversely.\nStatement 2 is correct. Higher government borrowing increases bond supply and raises yields.\nStatement 3 is incorrect. Inflation reduces real returns for bond holders.","topic":"Inflation & Deflation","id":109,"area":"Monetary Policy Transmission"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-04-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-04","qNum":22,"question":"Consider the following statements with reference to Inverted Yield Curve: 1. It occurs when short-term bond yields are higher than long-term bond yields. 2. It is generally considered a sign of economic recession. 3. It reflects surplus banking system liquidity. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct. In an inverted yield curve, short-term yields exceed long-term yields.\nStatement 2 is correct. It is often seen as a predictor of recession.\nStatement 3 is incorrect. In India, inverted yield curve was associated with liquidity deficit.","topic":"Bonds & Securities","id":110,"area":"Monetary Policy Transmission"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-04-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-04","qNum":23,"question":"Consider the following statements regarding Unconventional Monetary Policies: 1. Targeted Long-Term Repo Operations (TLTROs) provide long-term liquidity at repo-linked rates. 2. Negative Interest Rate Policy discourages banks from parking excess funds with the central bank. 3. Zero Lower Bound refers to a situation where GDP growth falls to zero. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct. TLTROs are long-term liquidity tools linked to the repo rate.\nStatement 2 is correct. Under NIRP, banks pay to park surplus funds, discouraging excess\nreserves.\nStatement 3 is incorrect. Zero Lower Bound refers to interest rates approaching zero, not GDP\ngrowth.","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","id":111,"area":"Monetary Policy Transmission"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-04-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-04","qNum":24,"question":"If you withdraw Rs. 1,00,000 in cash from your Demand Deposit Account at your bank, the immediate effect on aggregate money supply in the economy will be:","options":{"a":"to reduce it by Rs. 1,00,000","b":"to increase it by Rs. 1,00,000","c":"to increase it by more than Rs. 1,00,000","d":"to leave it unchanged"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Option d is the correct answer\nThe supply of money means the total stock of money (paper notes, coins and demand deposits of\nbank) in circulation which is held by the public at any particular point of time. In short, money\nsupply includes currency held by public and net demand deposits in banks","topic":"Money & Currency","id":112,"area":"Monetary Policy Transmission"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-04-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-04","qNum":25,"question":"Which of the following measures would result in an increase in the money supply in the economy? 1. Purchase of govt securities from the public by the central bank 2. Deposit of currency in commercial banks by the public 3. Borrowing by the govt. from the central bank 4. Sale of govt. secs. to the public by the central bank Select the correct answer using the codes given below:","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 and 4 only","c":"1 and 3 only","d":"2, 3 and 4 only"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\n\nStatement 1 is correct and statement 4 is incorrect. Purchasing of government securities from\npublic by central bank will give more money in hand of public which will increase the supply hence\nflow of money in economy. similarily sale of government securities to public by central bank will\nreduce money supply in the hands of public.\nStatement 2 is incorrect. Depositing money in bank by public will lock that amount of money with\nbank and public will be left with less money with hence decreasing the Supply of money.\nStatement 3 is correct. Borrowing by government from central bank will lead to more spending\nof government i.e. more development activities, new welfare schemes etc. hence it will increase\nthe supply of money in economy","topic":"Money & Currency","id":113,"area":"Monetary Policy Transmission"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-04-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-04","qNum":26,"question":"Which one of the following forms of money supply is considered as the most widely used in the Indian monetary system?","options":{"a":"M1","b":"M2","c":"M3","d":"M4"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nThe total stock of money in circulation among the public at a particular point of time is called\nmoney supply. RBI publishes figures for four alternative measures of money supply, viz. M1, M2,\nM3 and M4. M3 is considered as the most widely used measure of money supply in India because\nit covers the largest set of monetary assets that are available and commonly used by the public for\ntransactions and savings. M3 includes not only currency and demand deposits, but also time\ndeposits, certificates of deposits, and borrowings from non-depository financial corporations by\nthe banking system. M3 is also known as broad money and it reflects the liquidity and purchasing\npower of the economy.\nImportant Tips\n• M1 = CU (currency (notes plus coins) ) + DD (net demand deposits held by commercial banks)\n• M2 = M1 + Savings deposits with Post Office savings banks\n• M3 = M1 + Net time deposits of commercial banks\n• M4 = M3 + Total deposits with Post Office savings organizations (excluding National Savings\nCertificates)","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","id":114,"area":"Monetary Policy Transmission"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-04-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-04","qNum":27,"question":"Indian Government bond yields are influenced by which of the following? 1. Action of the United States Federal Reserve. 2. Action of the Reserve Bank of India. 3. Inflation and short-term interest rates. Select the correct answer using the code given below.","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 only","c":"3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Option d is the correct answer.\n\nStatement 1 is correct. Hike in interest rate in the US by the United States Federal Reserve leads\nnot only to an outflow of funds from equities into US treasury bonds, but also to an outflow of\nfunds from emerging economies to the US. Thus, it impacts Indian Government Bond Yields in\nnegative manner.\nStatement 2 is correct. The multifaceted roles played by the RBI in the payment system, monetary\npolicy, financial stability policy, and policy coordination with the Treasury gives it the operational\nability to influence government bonds’ nominal yields by setting and changing the short-term\ninterest rate and using other tools of monetary policy as it deems appropriate.\nStatement 3 is correct. Short-term interest rate and pace of inflation are the key drivers of\ninterest rates on government bonds.","topic":"Inflation & Deflation","id":115,"area":"Monetary Policy Transmission"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-04-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-04","qNum":28,"question":"Consider the following liquid assets: 1. Demand deposits with the banks 2. Time deposits with the banks 3. Savings deposits with the banks 4. Currency The correct sequence of these decreasing orders of Liquidity is:","options":{"a":"1-4-3-2","b":"4-3-2-1","c":"2-3-1-4","d":"4-1-3-2"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Option d is the correct answer\nOption d is correct. The correct order of decreasing order of liquidity is:\nCurrency > Demand deposits with the banks > Savings deposits with the banks > Time deposits\nwith the banks.","topic":"Money & Currency","id":116,"area":"Monetary Policy Transmission"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-04-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-04","qNum":30,"question":"With reference to Indian economy, which of the statements given below regarding bond yield is correct?","options":{"a":"Bond yield is the return the government gets on the bond issued by it.","b":"Bond yield is not affected by the monetary policy of the Central Bank.","c":"A rise in interest rates cause bond yields to rise.","d":"If the bond yield goes up, it results in capital flows into equities."},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nOption a is incorrect. Bond yield is the return an investor gets on that bond or on a particular\ngovernment security.\nOption b is incorrect. The major factors affecting the yield is the monetary policy of the Reserve\nBank of India, especially the course of interest rates, the fiscal position of the government and its\nborrowing programme, global markets, economy, and inflation.\nOption c is correct. A rise in interest rates cause bond prices to fall, and bond yields to rise.\nWhereas a fall in interest rates makes bond prices rise, and bond yields fall. In short, a rise in bond\nyields means interest rates in the monetary system have fallen, and the returns for investors (those\nwho invested in bonds and govt securities) have declined.\nOption d is incorrect. When bond yields go up, investors start reallocating investments away from\nequities and into bonds, as they are much safer. As bond yields rise, the opportunity cost of\ninvesting in equities goes up, and equities become less attractive.","topic":"Bonds & Securities","id":117,"area":"Monetary Policy Transmission"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-05-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-05","qNum":1,"question":"With reference to Scheduled banks in India, consider the following statements: 1. Scheduled banks are those which are included in the Schedule II of Banking Regulation Act, 1949. 2. In scheduled banks, more than 50% stake is held by the government. 3. Cooperative banks can be categorized as scheduled banks. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer\nStatement 1 is incorrect. Scheduled banks are those banks which are included in the Schedule II of RBI Act,\n1934.\nStatement 2 is incorrect. Scheduled banks do not necessarily have more than 50% stake by the government.\nStatement 3 is correct. Cooperative banks can be categorized as scheduled banks.","topic":"Types of Banks","id":118,"area":"Money & Scheduled Banks"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-05-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-05","qNum":2,"question":"With reference to ‘’Neo-banks’’, seen in news sometimes, which one of the following statements is correct?","options":{"a":"These are virtual banks that provide banking experience through digital platforms.","b":"These are banks having physical branches in international financial service centres.","c":"They operate only in rural areas through Common Service Centres.","d":"Neo-banks need licenses from the Reserve Bank of India to operate."},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer\nNeo banks are virtual banks. They are the banks that are only operable online. Neo Banking is a technique to\nprovide a complete banking experience but through digital platforms like a mobile application.","topic":"Types of Banks","id":119,"area":"Money & Scheduled Banks"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-05-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-05","qNum":3,"question":"Which of the following statements correctly describes the meaning of ‘Fiduciary money’?","options":{"a":"Money which has its intrinsic value same as its face value.","b":"Money which is accepted for payment because of trust between the parties.","c":"Money which is accepted for payment because of its backing by the Government.","d":"Money whose value is derived from its commodity value."},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer\nFiduciary money is money that is accepted as a medium of exchange because of the trust between the payer\nand the payee. Examples include cheques and demand drafts. Unlike fiat money, it is not necessarily declared\nas legal tender by the government.","topic":"Money & Currency","id":120,"area":"Money & Scheduled Banks"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-05-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-05","qNum":4,"question":"With reference to ‘Full Bodied Money’ and ‘Credit Money’, consider the following statements: 1. In Full Bodied money, the intrinsic value is the same as the face value. 2. In Credit money, the intrinsic value is higher than the face value. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer\n\nStatement 1 is correct: Full Bodied Money refers to money whose intrinsic value (commodity value) is equal\nto its face value, such as gold coins in ancient India.\nStatement 2 is incorrect: Credit Money or Token Money is money whose intrinsic value is lower than its\nface value, such as modern coins in India.","topic":"Money & Currency","id":121,"area":"Money & Scheduled Banks"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-05-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-05","qNum":5,"question":"Which of the following is/are included in the ‘Currency in Circulation’ in India? 1. Currency with the public. 2. Cash in hand with banks. 3. Foreign currency held by banks. Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 and 3 only","c":"1 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer\nCurrency in circulation includes both currency with the public and cash in hand with banks.\nStatement 3 is incorrect: According to the notes, currency in circulation does not include foreign currency.","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","id":122,"area":"Money & Scheduled Banks"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-05-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-05","qNum":6,"question":"With reference to Scheduled Banks in India, consider the following statements: 1. They are listed in the Second Schedule of the RBI Act, 1934. 2. They are eligible to borrow from the Reserve Bank of India under Liquidity Adjustment Facility (LAF). 3. They are not required to maintain Cash Reserve Ratio (CRR). Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"1 and 3 only","c":"2 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer\nStatement 1 is correct: Scheduled banks are those listed under the Second Schedule of the RBI Act, 1934.\nStatement 2 is correct: Scheduled banks have access to RBI’s LAF window.\nStatement 3 is incorrect: Scheduled banks are mandatorily required to maintain CRR with RBI.","topic":"Types of Banks","id":123,"area":"Money & Scheduled Banks"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-05-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-05","qNum":7,"question":"Consider the following statements regarding Non-Scheduled Banks in India: 1. They are normally not eligible to borrow from RBI except under exceptional circumstances.. 2. They are members of the clearing house operated by RBI. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer\nStatement 1 is correct: Non-scheduled banks are generally not allowed to borrow from RBI except under\nexceptional circumstances.\nStatement 2 is incorrect: Non-scheduled banks are not members of the RBI-operated clearing house.","topic":"Types of Banks","id":124,"area":"Money & Scheduled Banks"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-05-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-05","qNum":8,"question":"With reference to Scheduled Commercial Banks in India, consider the following categories: 1. Public Sector Banks 2. Private Sector Banks 3. Foreign Banks 4. Cooperative Banks Which of the above are included under Scheduled Commercial Banks?","options":{"a":"1, 2 and 3 only","b":"1 and 4 only","c":"2 and 4 only","d":"All four"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer\nScheduled Commercial Banks include Public Sector Banks, Private Banks and Foreign Banks. Cooperative\nbanks form a separate category.","topic":"Types of Banks","id":125,"area":"Money & Scheduled Banks"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-05-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-05","qNum":9,"question":"Which of the following correctly distinguishes Commercial Banks from Investment Banks?","options":{"a":"Commercial banks earn mainly through fees, while investment banks earn interest income","b":"Commercial banks deal in large, complex transactions","c":"Investment banks accept public deposits","d":"Commercial banks earn mainly through interest income"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Option d is the correct answer\nCommercial banks primarily earn through interest income, while investment banks earn through fees and\ncommissions.","topic":"Economy — Misc","id":126,"area":"Money & Scheduled Banks"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-05-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-05","qNum":10,"question":"With reference to All India Financial Institutions (AIFIs), consider the following: 1. NABARD 2. SIDBI 3. EXIM Bank 4. NHB How many of the above are classified as AIFIs?","options":{"a":"Only two","b":"Only three","c":"All four","d":"Only one"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer\nNABARD, SIDBI, EXIM Bank and NHB are all All India Financial Institutions.","topic":"Types of Banks","id":127,"area":"Money & Scheduled Banks"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-05-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-05","qNum":11,"question":"Which of the following institutions is licensed by RBI to buy Government Securities directly from the primary market?","options":{"a":"Commercial Banks","b":"Primary Dealers","c":"NBFCs","d":"Cooperative Banks"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer\n\nPrimary Dealers are specifically licensed by RBI to participate in the primary market for government\nsecurities.","topic":"Bonds & Securities","id":128,"area":"Money & Scheduled Banks"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-05-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-05","qNum":12,"question":"With reference to Universal Banking Models, consider the following: 1. In-house universal banking model exposes banks to high concentration of risk. 2. Financial Holding Company model reduces operational burden on banks. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer\nStatement 1 is correct: In-house universal banking exposes banks to higher risks.\nStatement 2 is correct: Holding company model reduces operational and financial burden on banks.","topic":"Economy — Misc","id":129,"area":"Money & Scheduled Banks"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-05-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-05","qNum":13,"question":"With reference to On-Tap Licensing of Universal Banks, consider the following statements: 1. Minimum capital requirement is ₹1000 crore. 2. Large industrial houses are allowed to promote universal banks. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer\nStatement 1 is correct: Minimum capital requirement is ₹1000 crore.\nStatement 2 is incorrect: Large industrial houses are not allowed to promote banks, though they may invest\nup to 10%.","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","id":130,"area":"Money & Scheduled Banks"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-05-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-05","qNum":14,"question":"Which of the following is a mandatory requirement under RBI’s guidelines for universal banks?","options":{"a":"50% branches in urban areas","b":"25% branches in unbanked areas","c":"40% foreign ownership cap","d":"100% listing before operations"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer\nAt least 25% of bank branches must be opened in unbanked areas.","topic":"Economy — Misc","id":131,"area":"Money & Scheduled Banks"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-05-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-05","qNum":15,"question":"With reference to Scheduled Banks, consider the following statements: 1. RBI acts as a clearing house for them. 2. They are required to maintain Statutory Liquidity Ratio (SLR). Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer\nScheduled banks are members of the clearing house and must maintain SLR.","topic":"Types of Banks","id":132,"area":"Money & Scheduled Banks"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-05-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-05","qNum":16,"question":"With reference to Non-Banking Financial Companies (NBFCs), consider the following: 1. They are part of the banking system. 2. Their deposits are included in aggregate money supply. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Option d is the correct answer\nNBFCs are not banks, and their deposits are excluded from aggregate money supply.","topic":"Types of Banks","id":133,"area":"Money & Scheduled Banks"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-05-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-05","qNum":17,"question":"Which of the following correctly differentiates Scheduled and Non-Scheduled Banks?","options":{"a":"CRR requirement applies only to non-scheduled banks","b":"Scheduled banks have access to RBI liquidity facilities","c":"Non-scheduled banks are listed under RBI Act","d":"Both have equal access to RBI borrowing"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer\nScheduled banks have access to RBI liquidity facilities, unlike non-scheduled banks.","topic":"Types of Banks","id":134,"area":"Money & Scheduled Banks"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-05-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-05","qNum":18,"question":"With reference to Structure of Banking in India, consider the following: 1. Regional Rural Banks are scheduled commercial banks. 2. Payment Banks can be either scheduled or non-scheduled. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer\nRRBs are scheduled commercial banks, and Payment Banks may fall under scheduled or non-scheduled\ncategory depending on criteria.","topic":"Types of Banks","id":135,"area":"Money & Scheduled Banks"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-05-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-05","qNum":19,"question":"Which of the following are included in ‘Narrow Money’ (M1) in India? 1. Currency with the public. 2. Demand deposits with the banking system. 3. Inter-bank deposits. 4. ‘Other’ deposits with the RBI. Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"1, 2 and 4 only","c":"1, 2 and 3 only","d":"1, 2, 3 and 4"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer\nM1 (Narrow Money) is calculated as Currency with the Public + Demand Deposits with Banks + Other\nDeposits with the RBI. Statement 3 is incorrect: Demand deposits with the banking system specifically\nexclude inter-bank deposits.","topic":"Money & Currency","id":136,"area":"Money & Scheduled Banks"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-05-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-05","qNum":20,"question":"With reference to the ‘Money Multiplier’, consider the following statements: 1. It refers to the total amount of money created from initial money printed by the Central Bank. 2. It is inversely proportional to the Reserve Requirement. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer\nStatement 1 is correct: Money Multiplier is the total amount of money created from the initial money\n(Reserve Money/M0) printed by the Central Bank.\nStatement 2 is correct: Multiplier is inversely proportional to Reserve Requirement (CRR, SLR, etc.). A higher\nreserve requirement means banks can lend less, reducing the multiplier.","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","id":137,"area":"Money & Scheduled Banks"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-06-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-06","qNum":1,"question":"Consider the following statements regarding ‘Payments Bank’: 1. It is registered as a public limited company under the Companies Act, 2013. 2. These banks can undertake lending activities up to the amount of ten percent of its total authorized capital. 3. It is required to use the words “Payments Bank” in its name. 4. It can set up subsidiaries to undertake non-banking financial services activities How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"Only three","d":"All four"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct. The payments bank will be registered as a public limited company under\nthe Companies Act, 2013, and licensed under Section 22 of the Banking Regulation Act, 1949.\nStatement 2 is incorrect. The payments bank cannot undertake lending activities.\nStatement 3 is correct. The payments bank is required to use the words “Payments Bank” in its\nname in order to differentiate it from other banks.\nStatement 4 is incorrect. The payments bank cannot set up subsidiaries to undertake non-\nbanking financial services activities.","topic":"Types of Banks","id":138,"area":"Specialised Banks & Helicopter Money"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-06-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-06","qNum":2,"question":"Consider the following statements with reference to ‘Regional Rural Banks’ (RRBs): 1. Their area of operation is restricted only to rural areas. 2. They are regulated by National Bank for Agriculture and Rural Development. 3. The RRBs are required to provide 75% of their total credit as priority sector lending. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is incorrect: Regional rural banks (RRBs) can have operations and branches in urban\nor semi-urban areas also, apart from rural areas.\nStatement 2 is incorrect: Although NABARD is entrusted with the responsibility for conduct of\nstatutory inspections of RRBs under banking regulation Act 1949, but the power to regulate RRBs\nis vested with Reserve Bank of India (RBI)\nStatement 3 is correct: The RRBs are required to provide 75% of their total credit as priority sector\nlending.","topic":"Types of Banks","id":139,"area":"Specialised Banks & Helicopter Money"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-06-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-06","qNum":3,"question":"With reference to the helicopter money, consider the following statements: 1. It is the large sums of money printed by the central bank and distributed to the public. 2. Unlike Quantitative easing, there is no repayment liability in case of helicopter money. Which of the statements give above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct. Helicopter money basically means non-repayable money transfer from\nthe central bank to the government. It involves printing large sums of money and distributing it\nto the public.\nStatement 2 is correct. However, in case of helicopter money, currency is distributed to the\npublic without any repayment liability.\nImportant Tips\nIn case of quantitative easing, printed money is used by central banks to buy government bonds\nand the government has to pay back for the assets that the central bank buys.","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","id":140,"area":"Specialised Banks & Helicopter Money"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-06-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-06","qNum":4,"question":"With reference to the Supervisory Action Framework (SAF) by RBI for banking sector in India, consider the following: 1. It seeks to ensure expeditious resolution of financial stress faced by the Urban Cooperative Banks (UCBs). 2. It is similar to the Prompt Corrective Action (PCA) framework which is imposed on commercial banks. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct. The Reserve Bank of India (RBI) has revised the Supervisory Action\nFramework (SAF) for Urban Co-operative Banks (UCBs). It seeks to ensure expeditious resolution\nof financial stress faced by some of the UCBs.\nStatement 2 is correct. It is similar to the Prompt Corrective Action (PCA) framework which is\nimposed on commercial banks.","topic":"Basel Norms & Banking Regulation","id":141,"area":"Specialised Banks & Helicopter Money"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-06-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-06","qNum":5,"question":"Which of the following is/are the possible consequences of rising non-performing asset (NPA)? 1. RBI can mandate banks to maintain higher provisioning norms. 2. Banks may invoke SARFAESI Act 2002 and Insolvency and Bankruptcy Code 2016. Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1 Only","b":"2 Only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct. Recently RBI mandated banks to set aside 10% provisioning for all loans\nwhich are overdue.\nStatement 2 is correct. The SARFAESI Act essentially empowers banks and other financial\ninstitutions to directly auction residential or commercial properties that have been pledged\nwith them to recover loans from borrowers. Insolvency and Bankruptcy Code, 2016 provides a\ntimebound process for resolving insolvency in companies and among individuals.\nImportant Tips\nThe Narsimham Committee prescribed a standardized norm for provisioning of NPAs against\nNon-Performing Assets.","topic":"Basel Norms & Banking Regulation","id":142,"area":"Specialised Banks & Helicopter Money"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-06-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-06","qNum":6,"question":"Consider the following statements regarding credit disbursal in rural India: 1. Most of the credit to agriculture sector is provided by micro finance institutions. 2. NABARD provides funds to Co-operative Banks to promote credit flow in rural areas. 3. Microfinance institutions normally charge a high rate of interest when compared to commercial banks. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is incorrect. Scheduled commercial banks (79 per cent) provides most of credit to\nagriculture sector. It is followed by rural cooperative banks (15 per cent), regional rural banks (5\nper cent) and micro finance institutions (1 per cent).\nStatement 2 is correct. National Bank for Agriculture and Rural Development (NABARD) provides\nloans and advances to Co-operative Banks and Regional Rural Banks by way of refinance. The\nbasic objective of this refinance provision is to supplement the resources of banks and to improve\ncredit flow at the ground level in rural areas.\nStatement 3 is correct. Most Microfinance Institutions charge a very high rate of interest (12-\n30%) when compared to commercial banks (8-12%). Microfinance, also called microcredit, is a\ntype of banking service provided to unemployed or low-income individuals or groups like\nmarginalised farmers who otherwise would have no other access to financial services. The\nfinancial success of MFIs is limited when compared to commercial banks in India. The centuries-\nold banking system has a strong foothold in Indian grounds and is slowly evolving to meet the\nneeds of the times.","topic":"Types of Banks","id":143,"area":"Specialised Banks & Helicopter Money"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-06-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-06","qNum":7,"question":"With reference to the priority sector lending (PSL) directions issued by RBI, consider the following statements: 1. It is applicable to only those foreign banks which have more than 20 bank branches functioning in India. 2. The compliance of banks to the targets is monitored on ‘quarterly’ basis. 3. A Regional Rural Bank (RRB) has to ensure that more than 50 percent of its net credit goes to PSL. 4. If a Scheduled Commercial Bank (SCB) does not fulfil its targets, then it has to contribute the remaining target in the Rural Infrastructural Development Fund (RIDF). How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"Only three","d":"All four"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nPriority Sector means those sectors which the Government of India (GOI) and Reserve Bank of\nIndia (RBI) consider as important sectors for the development of the basic needs of the country\nand are to be given priority over other sectors. Therefore, the banks are mandated to encourage\nthe growth of such sectors through the provision of adequate and timely credit. The details are.\nStatement 1 is incorrect. The PSL directions are applicable to all the foreign banks. As per the\ndirections, it the priority sector lending is applicable to every Commercial Bank [including\nRegional Rural Bank (RRB), Small Finance Bank (SFB), Local Area Bank] and Primary (Urban) Co-\noperative Bank (UCB) other than Salary Earners’ Bank licensed to operate in India by the Reserve\nBank of India. Therefore, it is also applicable to foreign banks, although with some variations in\nPSL targets with foreign banks having 20 branches and above, and those having less than 20\nbranches.\nStatement 2 is correct. Monitoring of Priority Sector Lending targets is done on the ‘quarterly’\nbasis in order to ensure continuous flow of credit to priority sector. The data on priority sector\nadvances is required to be furnished by banks to FIDD, Central Office at quarterly and annual\nintervals as per the reporting format (quarterly and annually).\nStatement 3 is correct. The Regional Rural Banks (RRBs) and Small Finance Banks (SFB) are\nmandated to lend 75 per cent of Adjusted Net Bank Credit (ANBC) or CEOBE whichever is higher\nas total Priority Sector Lending. However, all domestic commercial banks (excl. RRBs & SFBs) &\nforeign banks with 20 branches and above are mandated to fulfil the target of 40% of Adjusted Net\nBank Credit (ANBC) for Total Priority Sector lending.\nStatement 4 is correct. In case of non-achievement of the priority sector targets by a\ncommercial bank. The same amount shall be allocated for contribution to the Rural\nInfrastructure Development Fund (RIDF) established with NABARD and other funds with\nNABARD/NHB/SIDBI/MUDRA Ltd., as decided by the Reserve Bank from time to time.","topic":"Types of Banks","id":144,"area":"Specialised Banks & Helicopter Money"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-06-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-06","qNum":8,"question":"With reference to the Micro-Finance Institutions in India (MFI), consider the following statements: 1. All the micro-finance institutions are regulated by the Reserve Bank of India. 2. Overall share of the MFIs in extending microfinance loans to borrowers is less than 50%. 3. In urban areas, MFIs cannot extend loans to households having annual household income exceeding Rs 1 Lakh. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nSome facts related to this are.\nStatement 1 is incorrect. RBI regulates Non-Banking Financing Companies (NBFC)-MFIs, Banks,\nSFBs, and NBFCs, except the Non-profit MFIs. Whereas, the Nonprofit MFIs are mostly registered\nas Societies or Trusts, and are regulated by the respective Acts.\nStatement 2 is correct. The overall Gross Loan Portfolio (GLP) of MFIs, i.e., outstanding amount\nof loans extended to microfinance borrowers is around 32%. Further, NBFCMFIs and Scheduled\nCommercial Banks (SCBs) hold a major chunk of the microfinance portfolio, with a combined share\nof 72 per cent as on March 31, 2020\nStatement 3 is incorrect. Microfinance loans mean collateral-free loans to households. It can be\ngiven to a household having annual household income not exceeding Rs. 1,25,000 in rural areas\nand Rs 2,00,000 in urban/semi urban areas, respectively.\nImportant Tips\nMicro-Finance Institutions (MFIs) encompass a host of financial institutions engaged in\nadvancing loans to low-income groups. For example, Non-Banking Financing Companies\n(NBFC)-MFIs, Banks, Small Finance Banks (SFBs), NBFCs and Non-profit MFIs are different\ncategories of the Micro-Finance Institutions (MFI) working in India. These are microfinance\nloans having small amounts, with short tenures, extended without collateral and with the\nfrequency of loan repayments greater than that for traditional commercial loans.","topic":"RBI Functions","id":145,"area":"Specialised Banks & Helicopter Money"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-06-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-06","qNum":9,"question":"Which one of the following is the correct description of the term “Special provisioning of the loan”?","options":{"a":"It means keeping a part of the fund available with the bank for expanding its business.","b":"It is a practice of keeping an amount of money available for lending to a particular sector.","c":"It refers to reserving a part of fund available for financial management during economic crisis.","d":"It refers to keeping an amount of money available to be used in case of a possible future loss or NPA."},"answer":"d","explanation":"Option d is the correct answer.\nSpecial provisioning of loan is a one of the mechanisms designed by the Reserve bank of India\n(RBI) to tackle the NPA or bad assets problem in the banking sector. It is an important part of RBI’s\nprudential regulation. Under provisioning, banks have to set aside funds or provide funds to a\nprescribed percentage of their bad assets. The percentage of bad asset that has to be ‘provided\nfor’ is called provisioning coverage ratio.\nImportant Tips\nThe following table shows the provisioning requirement for various types of assets.\nAsset type Provisioning requirement\nLoss assets It is important that loss assets should be written off from the\nbalance sheet. If loss assets are permitted to remain in the books for\nany reason, 100 % of the outstanding should be provided for it.\nDoubtful assets Unsecured portion: 100 % of the extent to which the advance is not\ncovered by the realizable value of the security should come under\nprovisioning\n\nSecured portion: It can range from 25 % to 100 % of the secured\nportion depending upon the period for which the asset has\nremained doubtful. (25% for up to one year, 40% for 1-3 years and\n100% for more than 3 years).\nSubstandard Assets A general provision of 15 % on total outstanding should be made.\nStandard assets Provisioning from 0.25% for MSME loans to 12.4%\nfor restructured housing sector teaser loans.","topic":"Basel Norms & Banking Regulation","id":146,"area":"Specialised Banks & Helicopter Money"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-06-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-06","qNum":10,"question":"With reference to the financial sector, consider the following statements: 1. The financial institutions which operate in both the physical and digital world are called Neo banks. 2. No interest rate is charged in case of the Islamic banking. 3. The Non-Banking Financial Companies (NBFC)s are part of the Shadow Banking in India. 4. The Regional Rural Banks and Cooperative banks are the part of differential banking in India. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"Only three","d":"All four"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nStatement Type Description\nStatement 1 is incorrect Neo Banks These are the financial technology (fintech)\ncompanies that operate solely digitally or via\nmobile apps. In other words, it can be said that\nneo-banks are online-only or digital banks\nwithout any physical branches.\nStatement 2 is correct Islamic Banking Islamic banking is a banking system that works\nin accordance with the Shariat. In Islam, money\nhas no intrinsic value. Therefore, it cannot be\nsold at a profit. It prohibits paying any fee for\nrenting of money (called riba) for specific\nperiods of time. It allows sharing reasonable\nshare of profit instead of charging interest\nrates or also loss in case of loss incurred by\nborrower.\nStatement 3 is correct Shadow banking It has gained popularity in India over the last 30\nyears following the financial deregulation since\n1990s. It refers to the non-banking financial\ncompanies (NBFCs) which operated across the\ncountry. NBFCs has a big market share in the\nfinancial field, often at the expense of the\npublic-sector banking system\n\nStatement 4 is Incorrect Differential\nBanking\nDifferentiated banks are banking institutions\nlicensed by the RBI to provide specific banking\nservices and products.\nDifferentiated banks licensing was launched in\n2015. The differentiated banks are of two\ntypes-payment banks and small finance\nbanks. Main aim for giving license to\ndifferentiated banks is to promote financial\ninclusion and payments.","topic":"Types of Banks","id":147,"area":"Specialised Banks & Helicopter Money"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-06-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-06","qNum":11,"question":"With reference to ‘Nidhi Companies’, consider the following statements: 1. They are a type of financial institutions that raise funds exclusively from their members. 2. A Nidhi company can provide loans to its members only. 3. They come under the dual regulation of Reserve Bank of India and Department of Company Affairs. How many of the above given statements are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nThe government of India has released the Nidhi (amendment) Rules, 2022. This amendment brings\nchanges to the Nidhi Rules,2014 to safeguard the interest of the general public.\nStatement 1 is correct: Nidhi companies are a type of non-bank lenders that raise funds\nexclusively from their members and give loans to them.\nStatement 2 is correct: To become a Nidhi company, the entity has to first register as a public\nlimited company which has more disclosure requirements than a private limited company. Nidhi\nCompany can provide loans only to its members. And they cannot give loans to companies.\nStatement 3 is correct: Nidhi Companies are regulated by the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) for\ndeposit-taking and by the Department of Company Affairs (DCA) for operational matters and\ndeployment of funds.","topic":"RBI Functions","id":148,"area":"Specialised Banks & Helicopter Money"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-06-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-06","qNum":13,"question":"With reference to Non-Banking Financial Companies (NBFCs), consider the following statements: 1. Unlike banks, Demand deposit are not accepted in NBFCs. 2. Unlike banks, no NBFC needs to maintain Capital Adequacy Ratio. 3. Deposits made in both banks and NBFCs are secured under Deposit Insurance and Credit Guarantee Corporation. 4. Some NBFCs are classified as ‘systemically important’ by the Reserve Bank of India. How many of the above given statements are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"Only three","d":"All four"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nA Non-Banking Financial Company (NBFC) is a company registered under the Companies Act,\n1956. They raise loans and funds from their customers and advances to ultimate spenders.\nStatement 1 is correct: The primary difference between NBFC and a bank is NBFC cannot accept\ndemand deposits i.e., Saving and Current accounts. Although there are some deposits taking\nNBFC(NBFC-D), but they accept only Time Deposits.\nStatement 2 is incorrect: Some NBFCs need to maintain capital adequacy ratio, as prescribed by\nthe RBI. Under the existing regulatory framework for NBFCs, Systemically Important NBFCs are\nrequired to maintain a regulatory capital of 15% against its risk weighted assets.\n\nStatement 3 is incorrect: Deposit Insurance and Credit Guarantee Corporation Act, 1961\nprovides insurance of deposits and guaranteeing of credits. DICGC only insures bank’s deposits.\nIt does not apply to non-banking financial companies (NBFCs).\nStatement 4 is correct. NBFCs whose asset size is of Rs. 500 crore or more as per last audited\nbalance sheet are considered as ‘systemically important’ NBFCs by RBI.\nImportant Tips\nThe purpose of capital adequacy ratio (CAR) is availability of adequate capital a present to handle\nlosses in the face of a risk. High CAR is considered good as they are in a better position to deal\nwith unexpected losses.","topic":"Basel Norms & Banking Regulation","id":149,"area":"Specialised Banks & Helicopter Money"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-06-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-06","qNum":14,"question":"In context of the Ways and Means Advances (WMA), often seen in news, consider the following statements: 1. It is a temporary loan facility provided by the Reserve Bank of India to State governments. 2. The interest rate charged on such loans is always equal to the Repo Rate. 3. WMA funding is much costlier than borrowings from the market. How many of the above given statements are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct: Ways and Means Advances (WMA) Scheme was introduced in 1997. These\nare temporary loan facilities provided by the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) to the central and state\ngovernments to meet mismatches in the receipts and payments. The limits for WMA are decided\nby the government and RBI mutually and revised periodically.\nStatement 2 is incorrect: There are two types of WMAs —1. Normal Ways and Means Advances;\nand 2. Special Drawing Facilities against government securities/Special WMA. The rate of interest\napplicable for Normal WMA funding from RBI is the repo rate the interest levied for special\nWMAs could be lower than the repo rate due to the backing of government securities.\nStatement 3 is incorrect: WMA funding is much cheaper than borrowings from markets as it is\ncharged at the repo rate. WMA can be an alternative to other tools of borrowing like raising\nlonger-tenure funds from the markets, issue of State government securities or borrowing from\nfinancial institutions for short-term funding.\nImportant Tips\nSpecial WMA or Special Drawing Facility is provided against the collateral of the government\nsecurities held by the state. After the state has exhausted the limit of SDF, it gets normal WMA.\nThe interest rate for SDF is generally one percentage point less than the repo rate.","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","id":150,"area":"Specialised Banks & Helicopter Money"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-06-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-06","qNum":15,"question":"With reference to Priority Sector Lending (PSL), consider the following statements: 1. The guidelines for PSL in India are issued by the Reserve Bank of India. 2. Financing of certain types of start-ups are included under priority sector lending. 3. Foreign banks operating in India are exempted from priority sector lending. 4. Self Help Groups are considered as ‘Weaker Section’ to avail Priority sector loans. How many of the above given statements are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"Only three","d":"All four"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct: RBI issues guidelines for priority sector lending in India. It enlists the\nsector requiring financial and credit assistance from banks. At present commercial banks are\nrequired to maintain 40% quota for priority sector. RBI first time issued guideline in 1968 for\npriority sectors which included agriculture, small industries, and exporters till 1985.\nStatement 2 is correct: In 2020, RBI has increased the scope of priority sector by including\nfinancing of start-ups with funding up to 50 crores and loans to farmers for installation of solar\nplants and compressed biogas plants.\nStatement 3 is incorrect: As per the revised RBI guidelines foreign banks with less than 20\nbranches as well as the foreign banks in India with more than 20 branches are required to\nmaintain 40 % of credit to priority sector lending.\nStatement 4 is correct. As per the RBI circular released in 2016, there are eight broad categories\nof the Priority Sector Lending. According to it, Self Help Groups are considered as Weaker\nSections to avail Priority sector loans.\nImportant Tips\nAs per the RBI circular released in 2016, there are eight broad categories of the Priority Sector\nLending. They are:\n(1) Agriculture (2) Micro, Small and Medium Enterprises\n(3) Export Credit (4) Education (5) Housing (6) Social Infrastructure (7) Renewable Energy (8)\nOthers. The others category includes personal loans to weaker section, loans to distressed\npersons, loans to state sponsored organizations for SC/ST.","topic":"RBI Functions","id":151,"area":"Specialised Banks & Helicopter Money"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-06-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-06","qNum":16,"question":"Which of the following statements is/are correct in context to the Prompt Corrective Action (PCA) framework of the Reserve Bank of India (RBI)?","options":{"a":"Capital, Asset Quality and Leverage are the key areas for monitoring in the PCA framework.","b":"The PCA framework is applicable on both Payment Banks and Small Finance Banks.","c":"Whenever PCA is enforced on a bank, it may face restrictions on branch expansions.","d":"Both statements (a) and (c) are correct in the above given context."},"answer":"d","explanation":"Option d is the correct answer.\nPrompt Corrective Action or PCA is a framework under which financial institutions with weak\nfinancial metrics are put under watch by the RBI. Earlier the RBI had imposed PCA only on banks.\nNow the PCA framework is extended to NBFCs.\nStatement a is correct. Capital, asset quality and leverage are the key areas for monitoring in the\nrevised PCA framework. Indicators to be tracked for capital, asset quality and leverage would be\nCRAR/ common equity tier I ratio, net NPA ratio and tier I leverage ratio, respectively.\nStatement b is incorrect. All Scheduled Commercial Banks are under the ambit of PCA framework\n(Excluding Small Finance Banks, Payment Banks and Regional Rural Banks).\nStatement c is correct. PCA is enforced by RBI when banks breach certain regulatory\nrequirements such as return on asset, minimum capital, and quantum of non-performing assets.\nBanks under PCA face restrictions like dividend distribution, branch expansion, and\nmanagement compensation or may require promoters to infuse capital in the bank.","topic":"Basel Norms & Banking Regulation","id":152,"area":"Specialised Banks & Helicopter Money"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-06-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-06","qNum":17,"question":"Arrange the following events regarding the development of Indian banking system in the correct chronological order. 1. Enactment of the Banking Regulation Act 2. Nationalization of fourteen major commercial banks 3. Introduction of Electronic Funds Transfer (EFT) system 4. Establishment of Regional Rural Banks Select the correct answer using the codes given below:","options":{"a":"2-1-3-4","b":"1-2-4-3","c":"1-3-2-4","d":"2-3-1-4"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nThe correct chronological order of the given economic events in the development of Indian\nbanking system is:\n1. Enactment of the Banking Regulation Act (1949): The Banking Regulation Act was enacted in\n1949 to regulate the banking sector in India and ensure the safety of depositors’ money. The RBI\nis responsible for enforcing the provisions of the Act and ensuring the soundness and stability of\nthe banking system.\n2. Nationalization of fourteen major commercial banks (1969): The Banking Companies\n(Acquisition and Transfer of Undertakings) Act, 1969, was passed by the Indian parliament, which\nnationalized 14 major Indian banks, followed by an additional 6 banks in 1980 to make banking\nservices more accessible to the masses.\n4. Establishment of Regional Rural Banks (1975): The Regional Rural Banks (RRBs) were\nestablished in 1975 as a key initiative to provide banking services to rural areas in India. The RRBs\nwere set up with the objective of providing credit and other banking facilities to small and marginal\nfarmers, agricultural laborers, artisans, and small entrepreneurs in rural areas.\n3. Introduction of Electronic Funds Transfer (EFT) system (1994): The Electronic Funds Transfer\n(EFT) system was introduced in 1994 as a means of enabling electronic transfer of funds between\nbanks, without the need for physical movement of cash or checks.","topic":"Types of Banks","id":153,"area":"Specialised Banks & Helicopter Money"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-06-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-06","qNum":18,"question":"With reference to Payment Banks and Small Finance Banks, consider the following statements: 1. Unlike Small Finance Banks, Payment Banks are allowed to lend money to their customers. 2. Unlike Small Finance Banks, Payment Banks can accept fixed deposits or recurring deposits. 3. Unlike Small Finance Banks, Payment Banks cannot invest their deposits in government securities. How many of the above given statements are correct?","options":{"a":"Only One","b":"Only Two","c":"All Three","d":"None"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Option d is the correct answer.\n\nPayment banks and small finance banks are two different types of banks operating in India with\ndistinct features and objectives.\nStatement 1 is incorrect: Payment banks are not permitted to lend money to their customers,\nwhile SFBs can lend money to their customers. Small finance banks are set up to offer financial\ninclusions by providing credit facilities and loans to small businesses operating from\nunderprivileged areas, marginal and small farmers, small and micro industries, and other\nbusinesses operating specifically in the unorganized sectors.\nStatement 2 is incorrect: Small Finance Banks can accept recurring and Fixed Deposits, while\nPayment Banks cannot accept time deposits i.e., fixed or recurring deposits.\nStatement 3 is incorrect: Payment Banks are only allowed to invest the money received from\ncustomers’ deposits into government securities.","topic":"Bonds & Securities","id":154,"area":"Specialised Banks & Helicopter Money"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-06-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-06","qNum":19,"question":"With reference to ‘National Bank for Agriculture and Rural Development (NABARD)’, consider the following statements: 1. It is a wholly owned financial institution of the Reserve Bank of India. 2. It provides refinance facilities to various institutions which helps in development of rural economy. 3. The Rural Infrastructure Development Fund (RIDF) is maintained by the NABARD. How many of the above given statements are correct?","options":{"a":"Only One","b":"Only Two","c":"All Three","d":"None"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is incorrect: National Bank for Agriculture and Rural Development (NABARD) is a\ndevelopment financial institution in India that was established in 1982 and is headquartered in\nMumbai, Maharashtra. In 2019, Reserve Bank of India sold its entire stakes to government making\nit fully government-owned now.\nStatement 2 is correct: NABARD provides direct and indirect refinance facilities to various\nfinancial institutions. The indirect refinance facility is given through the State Cooperative\nAgriculture and Rural Development Banks (SCARDBs) and Regional Rural Banks (RRBs). Under\nthis it refinances loans extended by SCARDBs and RRBs to farmers, rural artisans, and small\nentrepreneurs.\nStatement 3 is correct: NABARD operates and maintains the Rural Infrastructure Development\nFund (RIDF), which was set up in 1995 to provide loans to state governments for financing rural\ninfrastructure projects such as irrigation, rural roads, bridges, health centers, and schools.\nImportant Tips\nNational Bank for Agriculture and Rural Development (NABARD) is an apex regulatory body for\noverall regulation of regional rural banks and apex cooperative banks in India. It is under the\njurisdiction of Ministry of Finance, Government of India.","topic":"Types of Banks","id":155,"area":"Specialised Banks & Helicopter Money"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-06-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-06","qNum":20,"question":"Consider the following statements regarding Cooperative Banks in India: 1. All cooperative banks are registered under Banking Regulation Act, 1949. 2. Non-banking aspects of the cooperative banks are alone regulated by the National Bank for Agriculture and Rural Development (NABARD). 3. Recently, RBI approval has been made mandatory for appointment of chairman of Cooperative Banks. How many of the above given statements are correct?","options":{"a":"Only One","b":"Only Two","c":"All Three","d":"None"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Option d is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is incorrect: The Banking Regulation Act came in to force in 1949 and the banking\nlaws were made applicable to cooperative societies in 1966 through an amendment to the Banking\nRegulation Act, 1949. But Primary Agricultural Credit Societies and long-term credit co-\noperatives are outside the purview of the Banking Regulation Act, 1949 and are hence not\nregulated by the Reserve Bank.\nStatement 2 is incorrect: There is ‘duality of control’ over cooperative banks (excluding urban\ncooperative banks) between the State Registrar of Cooperative Societies/Central Registrar of\nCooperative Societies and the Reserve Bank of India. The Reserve Bank regulates and supervises\nthe banking functions and amalgamation and liquidation through the Banking regulation Act, 1949\nand the non-banking aspects like registration, management, administration and recruitment are\nregulated by the State/ Central Governments (not by NABARD). .\nStatement 3 is incorrect: RBI approval is not required for appointment of Chairman/Whole-\ntime Director/ Managing Director/CEO in case of Cooperative Banks (i.e. UCBs/StCB/DCCB).\nBut in public interest and to protect the interest of the depositors, if required, RBI can supersede\nthe Board of UCBs/StCB/DCCB.","topic":"Types of Banks","id":156,"area":"Specialised Banks & Helicopter Money"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-06-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-06","qNum":21,"question":"With reference to ‘Prompt Corrective Action Framework (PCA)’ for Scheduled Commercial Banks, consider the following statements: 1. The framework does not apply to Payment Banks and Small Finance Banks in India. 2. The profitability parameter of the banks is mainly considered by RBI for triggering the action framework. 3. A bank can be placed under PCA framework only on the recommendation of Department of Financial Services, Ministry of Finance. 4. Even when a Bank is placed under PCA, no restriction can be imposed on branch expansion. How many of the above given statements are correct?","options":{"a":"Only One","b":"Only Two","c":"Only Three","d":"All Four"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct: The PCA Framework applies to all Scheduled Commercial Banks excluding\nSmall Finance Banks, Payment Banks and Regional Rural Banks.\n\nStatement 2 is incorrect: Capital, Asset Quality and Leverage are the key areas for monitoring in\nthe revised framework. As per the revised guidelines, profitability parameter has been excluded\nfrom its list of triggers.\nStatement 3 is incorrect: A bank is to be placed under the PCA framework based on the Audited\nAnnual Financial Results and the ongoing Supervisory Assessment made by RBI. The RBI, and\nnot the Department of Financial Services, Ministry of Finance, has the authority to place a bank\nunder the PCA framework.\nStatement 4 is incorrect: Banks placed under PCA are subject to restrictions on opening new\nbranches, among other things. These restrictions are imposed by the RBI.","topic":"Basel Norms & Banking Regulation","id":157,"area":"Specialised Banks & Helicopter Money"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-06-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-06","qNum":22,"question":"The establishment of ‘Payment Banks’ is being allowed in India to promote financial inclusion. Which of the following statements is/are correct in this context? 1. Mobile telephone companies and supermarket chains that are owned and controlled by residents are eligible to be promoters of Payment Banks. 2. Payment Banks can issue both credit cards and debit cards. 3. Payment Banks cannot undertake lending activities. Select the correct answer using the code given below.","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"1 and 3 only","c":"2 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer\nStatement 1 is correct. Mobile telephone companies and supermarket chains that are owned and\ncontrolled by residents are eligible to be promoters of Payment Banks.\nStatement 2 is incorrect. Payment Banks can issue debit cards but not issue Credit card.\nPayments banks can issue ATM cards or debit cards and provide online or mobile banking.\nStatement 3 is correct. Both current account and savings accounts can be operated by such\nbanks. It cannot undertake lending activities.","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","id":158,"area":"Specialised Banks & Helicopter Money"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-06-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-06","qNum":23,"question":"What is the purpose of setting up of Small Finance Banks (SFBs) in India? 1. To supply credit to small business units. 2. To supply credit to small and marginal farmers. 3. To encourage young entrepreneurs to set up business particularly in rural areas. Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 and 3 only","c":"1 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer\nThe purposes of setting up Small Finance Banks (SFBs):\n(i) It helps in the supply of credit to small business units.\n(ii) small & marginal farmers.\n(iii) micro & small industries.\n(iv) other unorganized sectors.\n\n(v) to provide an institutional mechanism for promoting savings among the rural & semi-urban\nsections of society.","topic":"Types of Banks","id":159,"area":"Specialised Banks & Helicopter Money"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-06-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-06","qNum":24,"question":"Consider the following statements: 1. In terms of short -term credit delivery to the agriculture sector, District Central Cooperative Banks (DCCBs) deliver more credit in comparison to Scheduled Commercial Banks and Regional Rural Banks. 2. One of the most important functions of DCCBs is to provide funds to the Primary Agriculture Credit Societies. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer\nStatement 1 is incorrect. A DCCB is a co-operative bank operating at the district level in various\nparts of India to provide banking to the rural hinterland for the agricultural sector with the\nbranches primarily established in rural and semi-urban area.\nStatement 2 is correct. Schedule Commercial Banks (SCBs) deliver the highest amount of credit\nto agriculture sector.","topic":"Types of Banks","id":160,"area":"Specialised Banks & Helicopter Money"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-06-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-06","qNum":25,"question":"With reference to ‘Urban Cooperative Banks’ in India, consider the following statements: 1. They are supervised and regulated by local boards set up by the state Governments. 2. They can issue equity shares and preference shares. 3. They were brought under the purview of the Banking Regulation act,1949 through an amendment in 1966. Which of the statement given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 and 3 only","c":"1 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is incorrect. The Urban Banks Department of the Reserve Bank of India is vested with\nthe responsibility of regulating and supervising primary (urban) cooperative banks, which are\npopularly known as Urban Cooperative Banks (UCBs).\nStatement 2 is correct. A cooperative bank can, with prior approval of the RBI, issue equity\nshares, preference shares, or special shares to its members or to any other person residing\nwithin its area of operation, by way of public issue or private placements.\nStatement 3 is correct. Large cooperative banks with paid-up share capital and reserves of Rs.1\nlakh were brought under the purview of the Banking Regulation Act 1949 through an amendment\nin 1966.","topic":"Types of Banks","id":161,"area":"Specialised Banks & Helicopter Money"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-07-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-07","qNum":1,"question":"With reference to the Basel III norms, consider the following: 1. Liquidity Coverage Ratio refers to the amount of high-quality liquid assets banks need to hold to fund cash outflows for 30 days. 2. Net Stable Funding Ratio (NSFR) is defined as the amount of available stable funding relative to the amount of required stable funding. 3. Countercyclical capital buffer is only held in common equity tier 1 capital in addition to the regulatory minimum capital requirements. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct. The liquidity coverage ratio (LCR) is a requirement under Basel III\nwhereby banks are required to hold an amount of high-quality liquid assets that’s enough to fund\ncash outflows for 30 days.\nStatement 2 is correct. The NSFR is expressed as a ratio that must equal or exceed 100%. The\nratio relates the bank’s available stable funding to its required stable funding.\nStatement 3 is correct. The CCyB is limited between 0% and 2.5% of risk-weighted assets and\nmust be held in common equity tier 1 (CET1) capital in addition to the regulatory minimum capital\nrequirement and other regulatory capital requirements.\nImportant Tips\nCountercyclical capital buffers require banks to hold capital at times when credit is growing\nrapidly.","topic":"Basel Norms & Banking Regulation","id":162,"area":"Basel Norms"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-07-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-07","qNum":2,"question":"Which one of the following statements is correct regarding the Additional Tier-1 (AT-1) bond?","options":{"a":"It is a type of unsecured bond having a minimum maturity period of 10 years.","b":"It is generally issued by the banks to meet the capital requirements under the BASEL III norms.","c":"A bank issuing AT-1 bonds have to mandatorily make interest payments to the investors every year.","d":"It is a debt instrument that always pay the investor a maturity amounts lower than the purchase price of the bond."},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nOption a is incorrect. Additional Tier-1 bonds are a type of unsecured perpetual bonds having no\nmaturity period. Instead, they carry call options that allow banks to redeem them after five or 10\nyears. However, banks are not obliged to use this call option and can opt to pay only interest on\nthese bonds for eternity.\nOption b is correct. AT-1 bonds are generally issued by banks to shore up their core capital base\nto meet the Basel- III norms.\nOption c is incorrect. Banks issuing AT-1 bonds can skip interest payments to the investor for a\nparticular year or even reduce the bonds’ face value, provided their capital ratios fall below certain\nthreshold levels.\n\nOption d is incorrect. Negative Yield Bonds are generally issued by central banks or\ngovernments and investors pay interest to the borrower to keep their money with them.\nImportant Tips\nNegative-yield bonds (not Additional Tier-1 bonds) are debt instruments that offer to pay the\ninvestor a maturity amount lower than the purchase price of the bond. They are generally issued\nduring times of stress and uncertainty as investors look to protect their capital from significant\nerosion.","topic":"Bonds & Securities","id":163,"area":"Basel Norms"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-07-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-07","qNum":3,"question":"With reference to the Basel III guidelines, consider the following statements: 1. It requires the maintenance of capital adequacy ratio in banks at 15%. 2. RBI currently applies banking rules strictly based on Basel 3 to ensure capital adequacy. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Option d is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is incorrect. The capital adequacy ratio is to be maintained at 12.9%. In addition,\nbanks have to maintain a capital conservation buffer of 2.5%.\nStatement 2 is incorrect. Currently, the RBI applies stricter norms and not those specified under\nBasel III for capital adequacy, leading banks to set aside higher capital for loans.","topic":"Basel Norms & Banking Regulation","id":164,"area":"Basel Norms"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-07-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-07","qNum":4,"question":"With reference to the Basel accord, consider the following statements: 1. The Basel Committee on Banking Supervision (BCBS) is the primary global standard-setter for the prudential regulation of banks. 2. The central philosophy of Basel norms is that the capital withdrawal from banks by its shareholders will compel it to take less risks. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct: The Basel Committee on Banking Supervision (BCBS) is the primary\nglobal standard-setter for the prudential regulation of banks and provides a forum for\ncooperation on banking supervisory matters. The Secretariat of BCBS is provided by the Bank\nfor International Settlements (BIS) and it supports the work of the Committee.\nStatement 2 is incorrect: The central philosophy of Basel norm is that additional capital injected\ninto banks by its shareholders will compel it to take less risks and at the same time to overcome\nany crisis on its own. The logic behind this thinking is that when your business (banking) is at risk,\nyour money (capital) will be at risk.","topic":"Basel Norms & Banking Regulation","id":165,"area":"Basel Norms"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-07-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-07","qNum":5,"question":"In the context of ‘Priority Sector lending (PSL)’, consider the following statements: 1. It is a mechanism through which adequate and timely credit is provided to the sectors important for the development of the basic needs of the country. 2. Foreign banks are exempted from Priority Sector lending requirement. 3. Real estate and consumer goods are included in the categories for Priority Sector lending. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct. Priority Sector lending (PSL) means those sectors which the Government\nand RBI consider as important for the development of the basic needs of the country and are to\nbe given priority over other sectors. The banks are mandated to encourage the growth of such\nsectors with adequate and timely credit.\nStatement 2 is incorrect. Commercial banks including foreign banks are required to mandatorily\nearmark 40% of the adjusted net bank credit for priority sector lending.\nStatement 3 is incorrect. Real estate and consumer goods are not included in the categories for\nPriority Sector lending.\nImportant Tips\nThe categories included in the Priority Sector lending (PSL) list are Agriculture b) Micro, Small\nand Medium Enterprises c) Export Credit d) Education e) Housing f ) Social Infrastructure g)\nRenewable Energy and h) Others.","topic":"RBI Functions","id":166,"area":"Basel Norms"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-07-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-07","qNum":6,"question":"Which of the following are covered under the Priority Sector Lending programme of RBI? 1. Renewable energy 2. Finance for Start-ups up to Rs 50 crores 3. For installation of solar power plants by farmers 4. Export Credit 5. Education 6. Minority educational institutions Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1, 2, 4 and 6 only","b":"1, 2, 3 and 5 only","c":"1, 2, 3, 4 and 5 only","d":"4, 5 and 6 only"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nPriority Sector includes the following categories:\n1. Agriculture\n2. Micro, Small and Medium Enterprises (MSME)\n3. Export Credit\n4. Education\n\n5. Housing\n6. Social Infrastructure\n7. Renewable Energy\n8. Others\nRecently, RBI added some new categories under PSL:\n• Bank finance to start-ups up to Rs. 50 crores,\n• loans to farmers for installation of solar power plants for solarisation of grid connected\nagriculture pumps\n• loans for setting up Compressed BioGas plants","topic":"RBI Functions","id":167,"area":"Basel Norms"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-07-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-07","qNum":7,"question":"With reference to the National Payments Corporation of India (NPCI), consider the following: 1. It was incorporated in 2007 replacing the Internet and Mobile Association of India (IAMAI). 2. It is a statutory body established under the provisions of the Payment and Settlement Systems Act, 2007. 3. It is an initiative of Reserve Bank of India (RBI) and Indian Banks’ Association (IBA). 4. It developed the National Electronic Toll Collection (NETC) program and FASTag. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"Only three","d":"All four"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is incorrect. National Payments Corporation of India (NPCI) was incorporated in\n2008 as an umbrella organisation for operating retail payments and settlement systems in India.\nStatement 2 and 3 are correct. It is an initiative of Reserve Bank of India (RBI) and Indian Banks’\nAssociation (IBA) under the provisions of the Payment and Settlement Systems Act, 2007.\nStatement 4 is correct. National Payments Corporation of India (NPCI) has developed the\nNational Electronic Toll Collection (NETC) and FASTag.","topic":"RBI Functions","id":168,"area":"Basel Norms"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-07-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-07","qNum":8,"question":"Consider the following statements regarding different type of ATMs. 1. In Brown Label ATM, the hardware is owned by sponsor bank. 2. White Label ATMs, are setup, owned and operated by non-bank entities. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is incorrect. In Brown Label ATM, the ATM machine (hardware) is owned by a service\nprovider and cash management and connectivity to banking networks is provided by a sponsor\nbank.\nStatement 2 is correct. White label ATMs are setup, owned and operated by non-banks.","topic":"Economy — Misc","id":169,"area":"Basel Norms"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-07-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-07","qNum":9,"question":"With reference to the Indian economy, Consider the following statements with respect to Additional Tier 1 (AT1) Bonds: 1. They are a type of secured bonds compulsorily backed by a collateral. 2. They do not have a maturity period. 3. Banks issuing AT1 bonds have no obligation to pay back Principal amount to investors. 4. They cannot be traded in secondary markets. How many of the above given statements are correct?","options":{"a":"Only One","b":"Only Two","c":"Only Three","d":"All Four"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer\nOption 1 is incorrect: Additional tier-1 bonds are a type of Unsecured bonds which means the\nbonds will not be backed up by any capitals of banks. In contrast Secured bonds is a debt\ninstrument that is backed by collateral and if the issuer defaults on bond payments, then the title\nto the underlying assets will be passed to the bond holders.\nOption 2 is correct: It is true that AT1 bonds are perpetual and carry no maturity date. Instead,\nthey carry call options that allow banks to redeem them after five or 10 years. However, banks are\nnot obliged to use this call option and can opt to pay only interest on these bonds for eternity.\nOption 3 is correct: It is true that banks issuing AT1 bonds have no obligation to pay back\nPrincipal amount to investors. However, investors will receive interest rates on these bonds until\nthe bonds will be written off by the banks. If the RBI feels that a bank is on the brink of collapse\nand needs a rescue, it can simply ask the bank to cancel its outstanding AT-1 bonds without\nconsulting its investors.\nOption 4 is incorrect: AT1 bonds can be traded in secondary markets which means AT1 bond\nholders can sell these bonds to others in the stock market to raise money.\nImportant Tips\nAdditional Tier 1 (AT1) bonds appeared in the news as the Bombay High Court recently\ninvalidated the write-off of additional Tier-1 (AT1) bonds issued by private lender Yes Bank.\nThese bonds are a type of perpetual securities which offer higher risk and reward.","topic":"Bonds & Securities","id":170,"area":"Basel Norms"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-07-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-07","qNum":10,"question":"Consider the following statements regarding Real-Time Gross Settlement (RTGS) and National Electronic Funds Transfer (NEFT): 1. RTGS is available round the clock throughout the year, whereas transactions under NEFT can be carried out only during the bank working hours. 2. Both the modes of payment are not bound by any upper or lower threshold of the transaction amount. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Option d is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is incorrect: NEFT ensures round the clock availability throughout the year and same\nis the case with RTGS transactions. Before December 2019, RBI had fixed timings during which\nNEFT transactions can be processed. However, from 2020, NEFT transactions can be performed\nround the clock throughout the year. RTGS is available round the clock throughout the year with\neffect from December 14, 2020.\nStatement 2 is incorrect: The RTGS system is primarily meant for large value transactions. The\nminimum amount to be remitted through RTGS is _ 2,00,000/- with no upper or maximum\nceiling. Whereas, there is no limit imposed by the RBI for funds transfer through NEFT system.\nHowever, a member bank may place amount limits based on its own risk perception with the\napproval of its Board.\nImportant Tips\nNational Electronic Funds Transfer (NEFT) is a nationwide centralised payment system owned\nand operated by the Reserve Bank of India (RBI). The acronym ‘RTGS’ stands for Real Time Gross\nSettlement, a system where there is continuous and real-time settlement of fund-transfers,\nindividually on a transaction-by-transaction basis.","topic":"RBI Functions","id":171,"area":"Basel Norms"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-07-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-07","qNum":11,"question":"With reference to ‘bad bank’ recently in news, consider the following statements: 1. It is an asset reconstruction company. 2. It cannot lend money but can take deposits. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct: A bad bank is an asset reconstruction company (ARC) that takes over the\nbad loans of commercial banks, manages them and finally recovers the money over a period.\nStatement 2 is incorrect: The bad bank is not involved in lending and taking deposits but helps in\nresolving the NPA crisis in the commercial banks","topic":"Types of Banks","id":172,"area":"Basel Norms"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-07-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-07","qNum":12,"question":"Which of the following statements are correct regarding Chit Funds? 1. The registration and regulation of chit funds are carried out by state governments. 2. Chit funds fall under the definition of NBFCs under subhead miscellaneous non-banking company (MNBC). 3. In Chit Funds, members make periodical subscriptions to the fund. Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"1 and 3 only","c":"1, 2 and 3","d":"3 only"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct. Registration and regulation of chit funds are carried out by state\ngovernments.\nStatement 2 is correct. Functionally, chit funds are included in the definition of NBFCs by the RBI\nunder the subhead miscellaneous non-banking company (MNBC).\nStatement 3 is correct. Chit funds have regular members who make periodical subscriptions to\nthe fund. The periodic collection is given to some member of the chit funds selected on the basis\nof previously agreed criterion.","topic":"Types of Banks","id":173,"area":"Basel Norms"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-07-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-07","qNum":14,"question":"Which one of the following links all the ATMs in India?","options":{"a":"Indian banks’ Association","b":"National Securities Depository Limited","c":"National Payments Corporation of India","d":"Reserve Bank of India"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nNational Financial Switch (NFS) is the largest network of shared automated teller machines (ATMs)\nin India. It was designed, developed and deployed with the aim of inter-connecting the ATMs in\nthe country and facilitating convenience banking. It is run by the National Payments Corporation\nof India (NPCI). The NFS network facilitates ATM transaction services among all members\nparticipating in the network. NFS is a shared ATM network that interconnects NFS members\nand ATM switches. The main objective in creating NFS was to make ATM deployment economical\n\nand viable to members by pooling resources and thus, increase the use of ATM technology across\nthe country.\nImportant Tips\nNational Payments Corporation of India (NPCI) is an umbrella organization for all retail\npayments in India. It was set up with the guidance and support of the Reserve Bank of India\n(RBI) and Indian Banks Association (IBA).","topic":"RBI Functions","id":174,"area":"Basel Norms"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-07-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-07","qNum":15,"question":"Which of the following statements is incorrect about the challenges of a bad bank in India?","options":{"a":"It will be difficult to arrive at the prices at which bad bank buys the stressed loans from the banks.","b":"The reduction in net NPA will be limited to the extent of un-provided exposure.","c":"It does not address the root cause of quality of credit provided by bank.","d":"Plenty of buyers present in resolution process creates problem in Price discovery."},"answer":"d","explanation":"Option d is the correct answer.\nA bad bank is a corporate structure that isolates risky assets held by banks in a separate entity.\nA bad bank is a special type of financial institution that buys bad debtors of a bank at a mutually\nagreed value and attempts to recover the debts or associated securities by itself. Issues and\nchallenges of the bad bank\nStatement a is incorrect: Price discovery: the price at which bad bank buys the stressed loans\nfrom the banks might prove to be challenging, even though the transaction involves the public\nsector as both buyer and seller.\nUncertainty over the Response from secondary market: Banks though will have the freedom to\nsell the security receipts. But to what extent a secondary market for such securities evolves is\ndebatable.\nUncertainty over the yield: Considering that these loans have been written down by banks, it is\ndifficult to gauge what this will yield. For instance, Historically, banks see about 10 per cent\nrecovery from written-off loans.\nStatement d is incorrect: Lack of Buyers: The absence of buyers as reflected in the IBC process,\nthe extent to which financial creditors have had to take haircuts on their admitted claims, all raise\nquestions over the market appetite on both sides of the transaction. NARCL may become another\nrepository for bad loans: The creation of a bad bank could help clean up bank balance sheets\nthough in the absence of a successful resolution it may end up being a repository for bad loans.\nStatement b is correct: Net impact on NPA’s is negligible: While it will reduce gross non-\nperforming asset (GNPA) ratios of public sector banks (PSBs), the reduction in net NPA (NNPA)\nwill be limited to the extent of un-provided exposure.\nStatement c is correct: Does not address the underlying cause of the bad loan problem in India:\nOnly by reforming the banking system in India, especially the public sector banks, can the financial\nsystem be made more efficient. Delays in resolution: Resolution of NPAs is a long-drawn process\nin India as it is difficult to find buyers and any delay will only lead to value destruction. May incur\nlosses for banks in the longer run: Upon extinguishment of government guarantee on Security\nreceipts (after five years), banks will have to bear the loss on the un-redeemed Security receipts.","topic":"Basel Norms & Banking Regulation","id":175,"area":"Basel Norms"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-07-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-07","qNum":16,"question":"Which one of the following statements is correct with reference to deposit insurance facility provided by the Deposit Insurance and Credit Guarantee Corporation (DICGC)? 1. It does not apply to foreign banks operating in India. 2. Each depositor is eligible for an insurance cover of up to Rs. 5 lakhs. 3. The premium for the insurance is paid by the depositors in form of annual payment from their bank accounts. Select the correct answer from the code given below:","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 only","c":"2 and 3 only","d":"1 and 3 only"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer\nStatement 1 is incorrect. All commercial banks including branches of foreign banks functioning\nin India, local area banks and regional rural banks are insured by the DICGC.\nStatement 2 is correct. The cover of Rs 5 lakh per depositor is provided by the Deposit Insurance\nand Credit Guarantee Corporation (DICGC). Deposits in public and private sector commercial\nbanks, local area banks, small finance banks, regional rural banks, cooperative banks, Indian\nbranches of foreign banks, and payments banks are all insured by the DICGC.\nStatement 3 is incorrect. The premium for Deposit insurance is paid by banks to the DICGC and\nnot be passed on to depositors. Banks currently pay a minimum of 10 paise on every Rs 100 worth\nof deposits to the DICGC as premium, which is now being raised to a minimum of 12 paise.","topic":"Basel Norms & Banking Regulation","id":176,"area":"Basel Norms"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-07-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-07","qNum":17,"question":"With reference to the Asset Reconstruction Companies (ARCs) in India, which of the statements given below is incorrect?","options":{"a":"Banking Regulations Act, 1949 provides the legal basis for the establishment of ARCs in India.","b":"They are regulated by the Reserve Bank of India as Non-Banking Financial Company.","c":"They are not permitted to undertake lending activities in India.","d":"ARCs in India are required to maintain the Capital Adequacy Ratio (CAR)."},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nAsset Reconstruction Company (ARC) is a specialized financial institution that buys the Non-\nPerforming Assets (NPAs) from banks and financial institutions. It helps banks in cleaning up their\nbalance sheets by buying their bad loans.\nOption a is incorrect. The Securitisation and Reconstruction of Financial Assets and\nEnforcement of Security Interest (SARFAESI) Act, 2002 provides the legal basis to set up the\nAsset Reconstruction Company. Asset Reconstruction Company (ARC) is a company registered\nunder the Companies Act and registered with Reserve Bank of India under section 3 of The\nSecuritisation and Reconstruction of Financial Assets and Enforcement of Security Interest\n(SARFAESI) Act, 2002.\nOption b is correct. ARCs are regulated by RBI as a Non- Banking Financial Company [NBFC]\n(under RBI Act, 1934). They function under the supervision and control of the Reserve Bank of\nIndia (RBI).\nOption c is correct. ARCs are not permitted to undertake lending activities. One ARC can be a\nsponsor or investor in another ARC or it can acquire debt from another ARC.\n\nOption d is correct. The ARCs also have to maintain a capital adequacy ratio (CAR) of 15% of its\nrisk-weighted assets.\nImportant Tips\nCapital Adequacy Ratio is also known as Capital to Risk (Weighted) Assets Ratio (CRAR) A high\nCAR indicates that a bank has an adequate amount of capital to deal with unexpected losses. A\nlower CAR means, a bank is at a higher risk of failure","topic":"Basel Norms & Banking Regulation","id":177,"area":"Basel Norms"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-07-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-07","qNum":18,"question":"Consider the following statements regarding Priority Sector Lending (PSL): 1. The concept of PSL norms was first introduced in India in 2008 due to setbacks received as a result of global financial crisis. 2. Loans given to renewable energy projects can be included under PSL obligations. 3. PSL Norms are not applicable to Non- Banking Financial Companies. 4. Regional Rural Banks and Small Finance Banks are required to lend 75% of their Adjusted Net Bank Credit under Priority Sectors Lending. How many of the above given statements are correct?","options":{"a":"Only One","b":"Only Two","c":"Only Three","d":"All Four"},"answer":"c","explanation":"option c is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is incorrect: The description of the priority sectors was first formalised in 1972 on\nthe basis of the report submitted by the Informal Study Group on Statistics relating to advances\nto the Priority Sectors constituted by the Reserve Bank in May 1971. First time in 1974, the banks\nwere given a target of 33.3% as share of the priority sector in the total bank credit.\nStatement 2 is correct: To provide adequate amount of investment, the Reserve Bank of India has\nincluded renewable energy in the PSL (priority sector lending) for scheduled commercial banks.\nStatement 3 is correct: PSL norms are not applicable to Non-Banking Financial Companies.\nStatement 4 is correct: According to the RBI guidelines, small finance banks and regional rural\nbanks will be required to extend 75% of their Adjusted Net Bank Credit to the sectors eligible for\nclassification as priority sector lending (PSL) by the RBI.","topic":"Types of Banks","id":178,"area":"Basel Norms"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-07-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-07","qNum":19,"question":"With reference to ‘Insolvency and Bankruptcy Board of India’, consider the following statements: 1. The board comes under the purview of Ministry of Personnel, Public Grievances and Pensions. 2. The members of the board are appointed by Financial Services Institutions Bureau (FSIB). 3. It enforces rules for processes of corporate insolvency resolution and individual bankruptcy under Insolvency and Bankruptcy Code. How many of the above given statements are correct?","options":{"a":"Only One","b":"Only Two","c":"All Three","d":"None"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nThe Insolvency and Bankruptcy Board of India (‘Board’), also known as IBBI, was established under\nthe Insolvency and Bankruptcy Code, 2016 (‘IBC’) on 1st October 2016.\nStatement 1 is incorrect: Insolvency and Bankruptcy Board of India comes under the purview of\nthe Ministry of Corporate Affairs, Government of India.\nStatement 2 is incorrect: The members of the board are appointed by central government of\nIndia\nStatement 3 is correct: Insolvency and Bankruptcy Board of India regulates professionals as well\nas processes. It has regulatory oversight over the insolvency professional agencies, insolvency\nprofessional entities, insolvency professionals and information utilities. It enforces rules for\nprocesses of corporate insolvency resolution, individual insolvency resolution, corporate\nliquidation and individual bankruptcy under the IBC.\nImportant Tips\nThe Board consists of the following members:\n• A Chairperson.\n• Three members from among the officers of the Central Government equivalent or not below\nthe rank of a Joint Secretary. Out of the three members, each will represent the Ministry of\nFinance, Ministry of Corporate Affairs and Ministry of Law, ex -officio.\n• One member nominated by the RBI (Reserve Bank of India), ex-officio.\n• Five other members nominated by the Central Government, out of which at least three\nshould be whole-time members.","topic":"RBI Functions","id":179,"area":"Basel Norms"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-07-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-07","qNum":20,"question":"With reference to ‘Bank of international settlement’, consider the following statement. 1. It was established after the World War II, to promote global monetary and financial stability through the coordination of global central banks. 2. Bank of international settlement’ is owned by more than 100 central banks, accounting for about 95% of world GDP. 3. Its head office is in Basel, Switzerland How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is incorrect: Bank of international settlement was established in 1930. The BIS was\noriginally intended to facilitate reparations imposed on Germany by the Treaty of Versailles after\nWorld War I, and to act as the trustee for the German Government International Loan (Young\nLoan) that was floated in 1930.\nStatement 2 is incorrect: The Bank of international settlement is owned by 62 central banks,\nrepresenting countries from around the world that together account for about 95% of world GDP.\nStatement 3 is correct: Its head office is in Basel; Switzerland and it has two representative offices:\nin Hong Kong SAR and in Mexico City.\nImportant Tips\n\nThe Bank for International Settlements (BIS) is an international financial institution owned by\ncentral banks that “fosters international monetary and financial cooperation and serves as a\nbank for central banks”.","topic":"Basel Norms & Banking Regulation","id":180,"area":"Basel Norms"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-07-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-07","qNum":21,"question":"With reference to India, consider the following statements: 1. Retail investors through demat account can invest in ‘Treasury Bills’ and ‘Government of India Debt Bonds’ in primary market. 2. The ‘Negotiated Dealing System Order Matching’ is a government securities trading platform of the Reserve Bank of India. 3. The ‘Central Depository Services Ltd.’ Is jointly promoted by the Reserve Bank of India and the Bombay Stock Exchange. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"1 and 2","c":"3 only","d":"2 and 3"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct. Retail investors have multiple channels to invest in treasury bills (T-Bills)\nand Government bonds. It is mandatory to open demat account for a retail investor to invest in\n‘Treasury Bills’ and ‘Government of India Debt Bonds’ in primary market.\nStatement 2 is correct. The Negotiated Dealing System Order Matching is an electronic trading\nplatform operated by the Reserve Bank of India to facilitate the issuing and exchange of\ngovernment securities and other types of money market instruments.\nStatement 3 is incorrect. CDSL was promoted by BSE Ltd. jointly with leading banks such as State\nBank of India, Bank of India, Bank of Baroda, HDFC Bank, Standard Chartered Bank and Union Bank\nof India. Reserve Bank of India is not its promoter","topic":"Bonds & Securities","id":181,"area":"Basel Norms"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-07-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-07","qNum":22,"question":"Which one of the following best describes the term “Merchant Discount Rate” sometimes seen in news?","options":{"a":"The incentive given by a bank to a merchant for accepting payments through debit cards pertaining to that bank.","b":"The amount paid back by banks to their customers when they use debit cards for financial transactions for purchasing goods or services.","c":"The charge to a merchant by a bank for accepting payments from his customers through the bank’s debit cards.","d":"The incentive given by the Government to merchants for promoting digital payments by their customers through Point of Sale (PoS) machines and debit cards."},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nMerchant Discount Rate (MDR) is a fee charged from a merchant by a bank for accepting payments\nfrom customers through credit and debit cards.","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","id":182,"area":"Basel Norms"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-07-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-07","qNum":23,"question":"With reference to the ‘Banks Board Bureau (BBB) which of the following statements are correct? 1. The Governor of the RBI is the Chairman of BBB. 2. BBB recommends for the selection of head for Public Sector Banks. 3. BBB helps the Public Sector Banks in developing strategies and capital raising plans. Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 and 3 only","c":"1 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is incorrect: Banks Board Bureau comprises the Chairman, three ex-officio\nmembers i.e Secretary, Department of Public Enterprises, Secretary of the Department of\nFinancial Services and Deputy Governor of the Reserve Bank of India, and five expert members,\ntwo of which are from the private sector. The Chairman is selected by the central government\nand RBI governor does not head it.\nStatement 2 and 3 are correct: Banks Board Bureau recommends for the selection of head for\nPublic Sector Banks and other key personnel if required. It also develops strategies for raising\ncapital and improving performance of PSBs.\nImportant Tips\nBanks Board Bureau is a self-governing autonomous body of the Central Government. It is an\nadvisory authority comprising eminent professionals and officials to improve the management\nof public sector banks","topic":"RBI Functions","id":183,"area":"Basel Norms"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-07-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-07","qNum":24,"question":"Priority Sector Lending by banks in India constitutes the lending to","options":{"a":"agriculture","b":"micro and small enterprises","c":"weaker sections","d":"All of the above"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Option d is the correct answer\nExport Credit, Education, Housing, Social Infrastructure, Agriculture, Micro, Small and Medium\nEnterprises and weaker sections constitute the Priority Sector Lending by banks in India. These\nare the sectors of economy which may not have easy access to credit if not for special mechanism\nof Priority Sector Lending.","topic":"Economy — Misc","id":184,"area":"Basel Norms"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-07-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-07","qNum":25,"question":"With reference to the Foreign Currency Convertible Bonds, consider the following statements: 1. It is a type of convertible bond that can only be issued with a call option. 2. They allow the issuer or bondholder the option to convert the bonds into shares mid-way during its term. 3. The conversion of bond to shares can only take at a pre-agreed price. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is incorrect. FCCBs are bonds issued by listed companies in the overseas market. A\nconvertible bond is a mix between a debt and equity instrument. These bonds can be issued along\nwith a call option (whereby the right of redemption lies with the bond issuer) or put options both\n(whereby the right of redemption lies with bondholder).\nStatement 2 is correct. It acts like a bond by making regular coupon and principal payments, but\nthese bonds also give the bondholder the option to convert the bond into stock.\nStatement 3 is correct. FCCBs usually carry clauses which allow the issuer or bondholder the\noption to convert the bonds into shares mid-way during its term, at a pre-agreed price only.","topic":"Bonds & Securities","id":185,"area":"Basel Norms"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-08-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-08","qNum":1,"question":"It refers to the process of offering shares of a private corporation to the public in a new stock issuance which provide companies with an opportunity to obtain capital by offering shares through the primary market. The process mentioned here is","options":{"a":"Sweat Share","b":"Scrip Share","c":"Offer for Sale (OFS)","d":"Initial Public Offer (IPO)"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Option d is the correct answer.\nOption d is correct. Initial Public Offer (IPO) refers to the process of offering shares of a private\ncorporation to the public in a new stock issuance which provide companies with an opportunity\nto obtain capital by offering shares through the primary market.\nImportant Tips\n• Sweat Share is a share given to the employees of the company without any charge.\n• Scrip Share is a share given to the existing shareholders without any charge—also known as\nbonus share.\n• Offer for sale (OFS) is a method of share sale through the exchange platform for listed\ncompanies, to make it easier for promoters of publicly-traded companies to cut their holdings\nand comply with the minimum public shareholding norms of SEBI order. Government also\nstarted using this route to divest its shareholding in public sector enterprises.","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","id":186,"area":"Capital Markets"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-08-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-08","qNum":2,"question":"With reference to Certificate of Deposits (CDs), which of the statements given below is incorrect?","options":{"a":"They are issued by banks, generally for a period of less than one year.","b":"They are not tradable in money market.","c":"Financial Institutions can issue CDs for a maturity period above 1 year and upto 3 years.","d":"Minimum amount of a Certificate of Deposit should be Rs.1 lakh."},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nOption a is correct. Certificate of Deposits (CDs) can be issued by scheduled commercial banks\n(excluding Regional Rural Banks and Local Area Banks). The maturity period of CDs issued by\nbanks should not be less than 7 days and not more than one year, from the date of issue.\nOption b is incorrect. CDs are negotiable and tradable in money market. There is no lock-in\nperiod for the CDs.\nOption c is correct. Some Financial Institutions (FIs) have been permitted by RBI can issue CDs to\nraise short-term resources for a maturity period above 1 year and upto 3 years.\nOption d is correct. Minimum amount of a CD should be Rs.1 lakh, i.e., the minimum deposit that\ncould be accepted from a single subscriber should not be less than Rs.1 lakh, and in multiples of\nRs. 1 lakh thereafter.","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","id":187,"area":"Capital Markets"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-08-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-08","qNum":3,"question":"With reference to the call money market, which of the statements given below is/are correct? 1. The scheduled commercial banks act as both the borrowers and lenders in the money market. 2. A tight liquidity condition leads to a fall in the call money rate. Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct. Call money market is an inter-bank money market where funds are\nborrowed and lent, generally, for one day. Banks resort to these types of loans to fill the asset\nliability mismatch, comply with the statutory CRR and SLR requirements and to meet the\nsudden demand of funds. The scheduled commercial banks and cooperative banks act in this\nmarket as both the borrowers and lenders. Whereas, LIC, GIC, Mutual Funds, NABARD are\nallowed to operate as only lenders in this market.\nStatement 2 is incorrect. The call money rate is affected by the demand and supply of liquidity\nin the market. A tight liquidity condition leads to a rise in call money rate and vice versa)","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","id":188,"area":"Capital Markets"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-08-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-08","qNum":4,"question":"In the context of mutual funds, consider the following statements: 1. They are regulated by both Reserve Bank of India and Securities and Exchange Board of India) 2. In closed-ended schemes the units are not allowed to be traded on the stock exchange. 3. In open-ended scheme, the Net Asset Value (NAV) is fixed permanently to safeguard the investment. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct. Mutual funds operate in both the money market as well as capital market.\nHence, they are regulated by both the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) and Securities and Exchange\nBoard of India (SEBI). Mutual funds are compulsorily registered with SEBI, which acts as a first\nwall of defence for investors.\nStatement 2 is incorrect. A close-ended fund issue units to investors only once, when they launch\nan offer. Then, these units are listed on the stock exchange, where they are traded on a daily\nbasis.\nStatement 3 is incorrect. The mutual funds allot the units to investors for their investment made,\nat a price based on the Net Asset Value (NAV). NAV is the total value of investments in a scheme\ndivided by the total number of units issued to investors in the scheme. In open-ended mutual\nfunds, the investors can buy and sell units anytime they intend to. Hence, the NAV changes on a\ndaily basis.","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","id":189,"area":"Capital Markets"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-08-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-08","qNum":5,"question":"With reference to an Initial Public Offering (IPO), consider the following statements: 1. It can be issued only by newly set up companies and not old companies. 2. A company offering its shares to the public is not obliged to repay the capital to public investors. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is incorrect. Initial public offering is the process by which a private company can go\npublic by sale of its stocks to general public. It could be a new, young company or an old company\nwhich decides to be listed on an exchange and hence goes public.\nStatement 2 is correct. A company offering its shares to the public is not obliged to repay the\ncapital to public investors. The investors become part owners of the company. Companies raise\nequity capital with the help of an IPO by issuing new shares for the first time to the public. The\nexisting shareholders can sell their shares to the public without raising any fresh capital.","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","id":190,"area":"Capital Markets"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-08-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-08","qNum":6,"question":"Consider the following: 1. Restrictions on foreign investments 2. Provide customised tools to manage risk Which of the factors given above can be the reasons for emergence of Participatory Notes as popular investment route in India?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nThe reasons why Participatory Notes became such a popular route for foreign investors to invest\nin the Indian security market:\n• One of the primary reasons for the emergence of the PN (an ‘off-shore derivative instrument’,\ni.e., an ODI) is the restrictions on foreign investments. For example, a foreign investor intending\nto make portfolio investments in India was required to seek FII registration for which he is\nrequired to meet certain eligibility criteria. Lack of full Capital Account Convertibility further\nenhances the entry barriers from the perspective of a foreign investor. Hence, statement 1 is\ncorrect.\n• Besides reducing transactions costs, PNs also provide customised tools to manage risk, lower\nfinancing costs and enhance portfolio yields. For instance, PNs can also be designed for longer\nmaturities than are generally available for exchange traded derivative. Hence,\nstatement 2 is correct.\n• It was a highly ‘safe and lucrative route’ to invest the ‘unaccounted’, ‘even illegal’ money into\nthe Indian security market for huge profits (during the booming period). Experts even imagined\nthat it may be allowing the ‘black money’ of India (stashed away from India through ‘hawala’ kind\nof illegal channels and deposited in the tax havens of the world in ‘Swiss Bank’ kind of financial\ninstitutions) to get invested back in the market.","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","id":191,"area":"Capital Markets"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-08-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-08","qNum":7,"question":"Which one of the following statements best describe ‘investment’?","options":{"a":"It is defined as the accumulation of money for future use","b":"It is a mechanism used for generating future income without any risk.","c":"It is the act of leveraging money for a potential future gain and it entails some risk","d":"It is an attempt to capitalize on market inefficiencies for short-term profit."},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nStatement a is incorrect. The accumulation of money for future use is not investment. Instead, it\nis actually saving.\nStatement b is incorrect. Saving does not carry risk while investment entails some risk.\nStatement c is correct. An investment is an asset or item that is purchased with the hope that it\nwill generate income or appreciate in value at some point in the future. It is the act of leveraging\nmoney for a potential future gain and it entails some risk.\nStatement d is incorrect. The attempt to capitalize on market inefficiencies for short-term profit\nis not investment. Basically, it is speculation.","topic":"Economy — Misc","id":192,"area":"Capital Markets"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-08-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-08","qNum":8,"question":"With respect to net interest margin of a financial institution which of the following statement is incorrect?","options":{"a":"It is a measurement comparing the net interest income with the outgoing interest of a financial institution.","b":"If demand for savings account increases compared to loans, then net interest margin may decrease.","c":"Monetary policy has no effect on the net interest margins of a financial institution.","d":"It acts as an indicator to investors while investing in a financial services firm."},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nStatement a is correct. Net interest margin is a measurement comparing the net interest income\na financial firm generates from credit products like loans and mortgages; with the outgoing\ninterest it pays holders of savings accounts.\nStatement b is correct. If there’s a large demand for savings accounts compared to loans, net\ninterest margin decreases, as the bank is required to pay out more interest than it receives.\nStatement c is incorrect. Monetary policies set by central banks heavily influence a bank’s net\ninterest margins because they play a pivotal role in governing the demand for savings and credit.\nWhen interest rates are low, consumers are more likely to borrow money and less likely to save it\nleading to higher net interest margins and vice-versa.\nStatement d is correct. This metric helps prospective investors determine whether or not to\ninvest in a given financial services firm by providing visibility into the profitability of their interest\nincome versus their interest expenses.","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","id":193,"area":"Capital Markets"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-08-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-08","qNum":10,"question":"Which of the following statements is/are correct regarding the Over-the-Counter Exchange of India (OTCEI)? 1. Large firms are not allowed to be listed on OTCEI. 2. Stocks listed on the OTCEI cannot be listed on other exchanges. Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct. The Over-The-Counter Exchange of India (OTCEI) is an electronic stock\nexchange based in India that consists of small- and medium-sized firms aiming to gain access\nto overseas capital markets, including electronic exchanges in the U.S. such as the NASDAQ.\nLarge Company Restrictions: Companies with issued equity capital of more than 25 crore rupees\n($3.3 million) are not allowed to be listed on OTCEI.\nStatement 2 is correct. Stocks that are listed on other exchanges will not be listed on the OTCEI\nand, conversely, stocks listed on the OTCEI will not be listed on other exchanges.","topic":"Economy — Misc","id":194,"area":"Capital Markets"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-08-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-08","qNum":11,"question":"With reference to the Call Money Market, which of the statements given below is/are correct? 1. Payments Banks are eligible to participate in the Call money market both as borrowers and lenders. 2. Higher call rate indicates liquidity stress in the economy. Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct. Participants in the call money market are banks and related entities\nspecified by the RBI. Scheduled commercial banks (excluding RRBs), cooperative banks (other\nthan Land Development Banks) and Primary Dealers (PDs), are permitted to participate in call/\nnotice money market both as borrowers and lenders. Payments Banks and Small Finance Banks\nare eligible to participate in the Call money market both as borrowers and lenders. Such\neligibility is valid even prior to the completion of the process to get themselves included in the\nSecond Schedule of Reserve Bank of India Act, 1934.\nStatement 2 is correct. Since the participants are banks, the call money rate tells about the overall\nliquidity position in the economy. Higher call rate indicates liquidity stress in the economy. In\nthis case, the RBI may follow up with liquidity support measures by through its monetary policy\ninstruments – cutting CRR (Cash Reserve Ratio) or allowing more repos. Hence, the call money\nrate is taken as the operating target of monetary policy.\nImportant Tips\nThe call money is usually availed for one day. If the bank needs funds for more days, it can avail\nmoney through notice market. Here, the loan is provided from two days to fourteen days.","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","id":195,"area":"Capital Markets"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-08-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-08","qNum":12,"question":"Which one of following is incorrect regarding Voluntary Retention Route (VRR)?","options":{"a":"It is introduced to encourage Foreign Portfolio Investors (FPIs) to undertake long-term investments in Indian debt markets.","b":"The amount that may be invested via the Route shall be decided by the Reserve Bank from time to time.","c":"The minimum retention period shall be 10 years, or as decided by SEBI for each auction.","d":"Any entity registered as an FPI with Securities and Exchange Board of India is eligible to participate through this route."},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nStatement a is correct. Reserve Bank, in consultation with the Government of India and\nSecurities and Exchange Board of India (SEBI), proposes to introduce a separate channel, called\nthe ‘Voluntary Retention Route’ (VRR), to enable FPIs to invest in debt markets in India. VRR is\nintroduced to encourage Foreign Portfolio Investors (FPIs) to undertake long-term\ninvestments in Indian debt markets. Broadly, investments through the Route will be free of the\nmacro-prudential and other regulatory prescriptions applicable to FPI investments in debt\nmarkets, provided FPIs voluntarily commit to retain a required minimum percentage of their\ninvestments in India for a period of their choice. Participation through this Route will be entirely\nvoluntary.\nStatement b is correct. The total amount that may be invested via the Route shall be decided by\nthe Reserve Bank from time to time based on macro-prudential considerations and assessment\nof investment demand.\nStatement c is incorrect. The minimum retention period shall be three (and not 10) years, or as\ndecided by RBI (and not SEBI) for each auction.\nStatement d is correct. Eligible investors: Any entity registered as an FPI with SEBI is eligible to\nparticipate through this Route","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","id":196,"area":"Capital Markets"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-08-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-08","qNum":13,"question":"Which of the following statements best describe the term ‘Green shoe Option’?","options":{"a":"The amount actually paid by the shareholders or have been committed by them for contribution.","b":"Provision under which a company issuing shares for the first time is allowed to sell some additional shares to the public.","c":"Difference between the buying and selling prices of a share.","d":"Transactions of stocks which take place outside the stock exchanges."},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nGreen shoe Option: A provision under which a company issuing shares for the first time is\nallowed to sell some additional shares to the public—usually 15 per cent, is also known as over-\nallotment provision. It gets its name from the first company (Green shoe Company, USA) which\nwas allowed such an option.\nImportant Tips\n• Subscribed Capital: - The amount actually paid by the shareholders or have been committed\nby them for contribution.\n• Spread: - The difference between the buying and selling prices of a share is called spread.\nHigher the liquidity of a share lowers its spread and vice versa. Also known as Jobber’s Turn or\nMargin or Haircut.\n• Kerb Dealing: - The transactions of stocks which take place outside the stock exchanges—\nunofficially and take place after the normal trading hours.","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","id":197,"area":"Capital Markets"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-08-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-08","qNum":14,"question":"With reference to the Call Money Market in India, consider the following statements: 1. Call money market facilitates borrowing and lending of funds on overnight basis. 2. Regional rural banks (RRBs) can participate in call money market. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct: Banks can avail overnight (one day) loans in the call money market through\ninter-bank transaction. If the loan is provided for 2 to 14 days, it is called ‘Notice Money’. Banks\nuse this short-term financial loan to meet statutory reserve requirements or in response to\nsudden shortfall in cash on any particular day. The call money market is an important segment of\nthe money. market where borrowing and lending of funds take place on overnight basis.\nStatement 2 is correct: The RBI allowed RRBs to participate in call money market in December\n2020. They were so far not permitted to access the liquidity windows of the Reserve Bank as well\nas the call/notice money market.","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","id":198,"area":"Capital Markets"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-08-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-08","qNum":15,"question":"Consider the following statements regarding Security Markets: 1. In Primary Security market, the securities are issued by companies for the first time. 2. In Secondary Security market, securities are sold and purchased among investors and traders. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct. The primary market is also known as a new issue market. Here securities\nare issued by companies for the first time. In the primary market, the money raised goes directly\nto the issuer of the securities. The amount that is received from the securities becomes capital\nfor a company. Investment bankers do the selling in a primary market.\nStatement 2 is correct. The secondary market is known as after issue market. Here, the investors\nand traders buy and sell the securities among themselves. Depending upon the demand and\nsupply of the securities traded the prices in the secondary market vary. The securities in the\nprimary market can only be sold once, while in the secondary market sale and purchase is an ever-\ngoing process.","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","id":199,"area":"Capital Markets"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-08-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-08","qNum":16,"question":"Consider the following statements: 1. A mutual fund is a company that pools money from many investors and invests the money in securities and other instruments. 2. Hedge funds tries to hedge risks to investor’s capital against market volatility by employing alternative investment approaches. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct. A mutual fund is a company that pools money from many investors and\ninvests the money in securities such as stocks, bonds, and short-term debt. The Mutual funds are\nregistered with SEBI. They are run by group of qualified people who form a company. called an\nasset management company (AMC).\nStatement 2 is correct. A hedge fund is a pool of money that takes both short and long positions,\nbuys and sells equities, initiates arbitrage, and trades bonds, currencies, convertible securities,\ncommodities and derivative products to generate returns at reduced risk. As the name suggests,\nthe fund tries to hedge risks to investor’s capital against market volatility by employing\nalternative investment approaches. Hedge fund investors typically include high net worth\nindividuals (HNIs) and families, endowments and pension funds, insurance companies, and banks.","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","id":200,"area":"Capital Markets"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-08-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-08","qNum":17,"question":"With reference to Securities and Exchange Board of India (SEBI), which of the following statements is/are incorrect? 1. It was established in 1992 by an executive resolution of the Government of India. 2. It registers and regulates credit rating agencies. 3. It can undertake inspection, conduct inquiries and audits of the stock exchanges. 4. The Board shall have the same powers as are vested in a civil court, while trying a suit. Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 and 3 only","c":"1, 2 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 4 only"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is incorrect. The Securities and Exchange Board of India is a statutory body. It was\nestablished on April 12, 1992 in accordance with the provisions of the Securities and Exchange\nBoard of India Act, 1992.\nStatement 2 is correct. SEBI registers and regulates the working of the depositories, custodians\nof securities, foreign institutional investors, credit rating agencies and such other intermediaries\nas the Board may specify.\nStatement 3 is correct. It may call for information, undertake inspection, conduct inquiries and\naudits of the stock exchanges, mutual funds, intermediaries and self-regulatory organisations\nin the securities market.\nStatement 4 is correct. The Board shall have the same powers as are vested in a civil court under\nthe Code of Civil Procedure, 1908, while trying a suit, in respect of the following matters, namely\n-\n• The discovery and production of books of account and other documents, at such place and such\ntime as may be specified by the Board;\n• Summoning and enforcing the attendance of persons and examining them on oath;\n• Inspection of any books, registers and other documents of any person or a company.","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","id":201,"area":"Capital Markets"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-08-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-08","qNum":18,"question":"Consider the following statements regarding the ways of raising capital in the Primary Market: 1. Public issue is open for all Indian citizens. 2. Private placement raises capital from the existing shareholders of a company. 3. Rights issue raises capital from select Financial Institutions and individuals. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct. Public issue is a public offer open for all Indian citizens. It is the most\nbroad-based method of raising capital.\nStatement 2 is incorrect. Rights issue is used to raise capital from the existing shareholders of a\ncompany. It is a preferential kind of issue restricted to a certain category of the public only.\n\nStatement 3 is incorrect. Private placement raises capital from select Financial Institutions and\nindividuals. This is done through a process of direct negotiations. Companies can also place their\nshares to the Foreign Institutional Institutions. It is a quick way to source foreign exchange in\nIndia.","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","id":202,"area":"Capital Markets"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-08-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-08","qNum":19,"question":"Consider the following statements: 1. Equity financing allows a company to acquire funds without incurring debt. 2. Debt instruments provide capital to an entity that promises to repay the capital over time. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct. Equity financing allows a company to acquire funds without incurring\ndebt. On the other hand, issuing a bond does increase the debt burden of the bond issuer because\ncontractual interest payments must be paid. And unlike dividends, they cannot be reduced or\nsuspended.\nStatement 2 is correct. Debt instruments are tools, an individual, government entity, or business\nentity can utilize for the purpose of obtaining capital. Debt instruments provide capital to an\nentity that promises to repay the capital over time. Credit cards, credit lines, loans, and bonds\ncan all be types of debt instruments. Typically, the term debt instrument focuses on debt capital\nraised by institutional entities. Institutional entities can include governments and both private and\npublic companies.","topic":"Bonds & Securities","id":203,"area":"Capital Markets"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-08-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-08","qNum":20,"question":"Consider the following statements in the context of Indian Depository Receipts (IDR): 1. An IDR allows Indian companies to raise funds from the Foreign securities Markets. 2. IDRs are regulated by the Securities and Exchange Board of India (SEBI). 3. The IDRs are required to be listed on at least one stock exchange in India. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is incorrect. An IDR is an instrument denominated in Indian Rupees in the form of a\ndepository receipt created by a Domestic Depository (custodian of securities registered with the\nSecurities and Exchange Board of India) against the underlying equity shares of issuing company\nto enable foreign companies to raise funds from the Indian securities Markets.\nStatement 2 is correct. IDRs are regulated by the SEBI. It has issued guidelines for disclosure with\nrespect to IDRs and notified the model listing agreement to be entered between Stock Exchange\nand the foreign issuer specifying continuous listing requirements.\n\nStatement 3 is correct. The IDRs are required to be listed on at least one stock exchange in India,\nhaving nationwide terminals.","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","id":204,"area":"Capital Markets"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-08-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-08","qNum":21,"question":"With reference to money markets, consider the following statements: 1. Maturity period of Call money is one day only. 2. Treasury bill is the example of long-term borrowing. 3. Call rate is the interest paid on the call money loans. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is incorrect. Call money is short term finance repayable on demand, with a maturity\nperiod of one day to fifteen days, used for interbank transactions.\nStatement 2 is incorrect. A Treasury bill is basically an instrument of short-term borrowing by\nthe Government of India maturing in less than one year. Treasury bills are issued in the form of a\npromissory note. They are highly liquid and have assured yield and negligible risk of default.\nStatement 3 is correct. The interest rate paid on call money loans is known as the call rate. It is a\nhighly volatile rate that varies from day today and sometimes even from hour-to hour.","topic":"Bonds & Securities","id":205,"area":"Capital Markets"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-08-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-08","qNum":22,"question":"Consider the following statements regarding financial markets in India: 1. Short term financial market is known as Capital Market, while the long-term financial market is known as Money Market. 2. Short term financial market fulfils requirements of funds for a period maximum upto 90 days. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Option d is the correct answer.\nFinancial markets in every economy are having two separate segments today, one catering to the\nrequirements of shortterm funds and the other to the requirements of long-term funds.\nStatement 1 is incorrect. The short-term financial market is known as the money market, while\nthe long-term financial market is known as the capital market.\nStatement 2 is incorrect. The short-term financial market i.e. the money market fulfils the\nrequirements of funds for a period upto 364 days while long-term financial market i.e. the capital\nmarket does the same for the period above 364 days.","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","id":206,"area":"Capital Markets"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-08-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-08","qNum":23,"question":"Consider the following statements regarding the money market in India: 1. It helps in meeting the day-to-day capital requirements of enterprises. 2. It does not include local money lenders. 3. The discount rate depends on the availability of cash in the market. 4. No financial asset is traded in the money market. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"Only three","d":"All four"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct. The money market fulfils the requirements of funds for the period upto\n364 days. They are needed for day-to-day fund mismatches of the enterprises; hence they are also\ncalled as the working capital market.\nStatement 2 is incorrect. Money market in India has two segments i.e., organized and\nunorganized. The activities of the unorganized money market are not regulated like the organized\nsegment. But they are recognized by the government. Unorganised money market includes\nunregulated non-bank financial intermediaries like chit funds. It also includes indigenous bankers\nlike Shroffs and Chettiars. Local money lenders are also part of the unorganized money market.\nStatement 3 is correct. Trading in money market is done on discount rate. Discount rate is\ndetermined by the market and guided by the availability of and demand for the cash in the day-\nto-day trading. The repo rate of the Reserve Bank of India works as the guiding rate for the current\ndiscount rate.\nStatement 4 is incorrect. In the money market the financial assets, which have quick conversion\nquality into money and carry minimal transaction cost, are also traded. Money market is where\nshort-term lending and borrowing take place between the cash-surplus and cash-scarce sides.\nImportant Tips\nThe secondary market, also called the aftermarket and follow on public offering is the financial\nmarket in which previously issued financial instruments such as stock and bonds are bought\nand sold. There is no involvement of the company, since the transaction occurs between the\ninvestors. Secondary market deals with those securities that have already been issued in the\nprimary market.","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","id":207,"area":"Capital Markets"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-08-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-08","qNum":24,"question":"Which of the following are the advantages/ benefits of making investments into Mutual Funds? 1. Diversification of risks. 2. Managed by professionals. 3. Assured and fixed returns. 4. Convenience and fair pricing. Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"1, 2 and 4 only","c":"2, 3 and 4 only","d":"1, 2, 3 and 4"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\n\nStatement 1 is correct. Diversification of risks: The value of an investment may not rise or fall in\ntandem. When the value of one investment is on the rise the value of another may be in decline.\nAs a result, the portfolio’s overall performance has a lesser chance of being volatile. Diversification\nreduces the risk involved in building a portfolio thereby further reducing the risk for an investor.\nAs Mutual Funds consist of many securities, investor’s interests are safeguarded if there is a\ndownfall in other securities so purchased.\nStatement 2 is correct. Expert Management / Advanced Portfolio Management: A new investor\nmay not have much knowledge or information on how and where to invest. The experts manage\nand operate mutual funds. The experts pool in money from investors and allocates this money in\ndifferent securities thereby helping the investors incur a profit.\nStatement 4 is correct. Convenience and Fair Pricing: Mutual funds are easy to buy and easy to\nunderstand. They typically have low minimum investments and they are traded only once per day\nat the closing net asset value. This eliminates price fluctuation throughout the day and various\narbitrage opportunities that day traders practice.\nStatement 3 is incorrect. Investment in mutual funds does not guarantee fixed returns. The\nreturn depends on the portfolio and the pricing of the portfolio.","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","id":208,"area":"Capital Markets"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-08-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-08","qNum":25,"question":"Consider the following statements with reference to bond prices in an economy: 1. It may increase if the market interest rate decreases. 2. It may increase if the credit rating of issuer increases. 3. It may increase if inflation in economy decreases. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nOption 1 is correct. Most bonds pay a fixed interest rate that becomes more attractive if interest\nrates fall, driving up demand and the price of the bond. Conversely, if interest rates rise, investors\nwill no longer prefers the lower fixed interest rate paid by a bond, resulting in a decline in its price.\nOption 2 is correct Credit rating agencies assign credit ratings to bond issuers and to specific\nbonds. A credit rating can provide information about an issuer’s ability to make interest\npayments and repay the principal on a bond. In general, the higher the credit rating, the more\nlikely an issuer is to meet its payment obligations – at least in the opinion of the rating agency. If\nthe issuer’s credit rating goes up, the price of its bonds will rise. If the rating goes down, it will\ndrive their bond prices lower.\nOption 3 is correct. In general, when inflation is on the rise, bond prices fall. When inflation is\ndecreasing, bond prices rise. That’s because rising inflation erodes the purchasing power of what\nyou’ll earn on your investment. In other words, when your bond matures, the return you’ve earned\non your investment will be worth less in today’s dollars.","topic":"Inflation & Deflation","id":209,"area":"Capital Markets"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-08-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-08","qNum":26,"question":"With reference to Indian economy, consider the following statements: 1. Call Money market is an inter-bank market used by banks to meet short term liquidity requirements. 2. Term Money refers to the borrowing or lending of funds for one day. 3. Notice Money refers to the borrowing and lending of funds for 2-14 days. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct. Call money market is also known as money at call and short notice\nmarket. It is an inter-bank borrowing and lending market. One bank demands money from\nanother bank to cover its cash reserve requirements with RBI every fortnight and to gain from\nforeign exchange.\nStatement 2 is incorrect. Term Money refers to Money lent for 15 days or more in the Inter-Bank\nMarket. The money that is lent for one day in call money market is known as “Call Money\nStatement 3 is correct. if the need of money exceeds one day (but less than 15 days) it is referred\nto as “Notice Money”.","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","id":210,"area":"Capital Markets"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-08-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-08","qNum":27,"question":"With reference to the Non-resident External deposit (NRE) account, consider the following statements: 1. It is an Indian rupee denominated account. 2. Non-resident Indians can deposit their income generated in India in NRE accounts. 3. Non-repatriable non-resident Indian (NRI) investment is considered as a domestic investment. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct: The NRE account is an Indian rupee denominated account. These accounts\ncan be in the form of savings, current, recurring, or fixed deposits. The foreign currency deposited\ninto the account is converted to Indian rupee.\nStatement 2 is incorrect: The deposits made into NRE accounts should be earnings outside India.\nNRIs cannot deposit their income generated in India in NRE accounts. Interest earned in NRE\naccount is tax free in India.\nStatement 3 is correct: The government had clarified that downstream investment by a company\nowned and controlled by non-resident Indians (NRIs) on a non-repatriation basis will not be\nconsidered foreign direct investment (FDI). NRI investments that are repatriable are considered\nFDI while non-repatriable investments are considered domestic investment. Investment on\nrepatriation basis means the sale or maturity proceeds of an investment, net of taxes, are eligible\nto be transferred out of India.","topic":"Money & Currency","id":211,"area":"Capital Markets"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-08-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-08","qNum":28,"question":"In the context of Chit funds and Mutual Funds, consider the following statements: 1. Chit fund is a professionally-managed investment scheme, while mutual funds are a saving scheme managed by community of group of people. 2. Chit fund is regulated by the Registrar of Chits appointed by respective state governments and Mutual funds are regulated by SEBI. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is incorrect: Chit fund is a sort of community funding where a group of people come\ntogether to contribute a predefined amount for a certain period. Each person gets a chance to\nclaim the pool amount either by lot mechanism or auction. Mutual Funds are professionally-\nmanaged investment scheme brings together a group of people and invests their money in stocks,\nbonds and other securities.\nStatement 2 is correct: Chit fund business is regulated under the Central Chit Funds Act, 1982 and\nthe rules framed under this Act by the various state governments for this purpose. The Central\nGovernment has not framed any rules of operation for them. Thus, registration and regulation of\nchit funds are carried out by state governments under the rules framed by them. They are\nregulated by the Registrar of Chits appointed by respective state governments under Section 61\nof Chit Funds Act 1982. Mutual Funds are maintained and regulated by Securities and Exchange\nBoard of India.","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","id":212,"area":"Capital Markets"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-08-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-08","qNum":29,"question":"With reference to capital market in India, which of the following statements is incorrect?","options":{"a":"A ‘Rights Issue’ is an invitation to the existing shareholders to purchase additional new shares in the company.","b":"An ‘Initial Public Offering’ denotes a transition from a public limited company to a private company.","c":"A ‘Qualified Institutional Placement’ enables a company to issue shares to the public without going through standard regulatory procedures.","d":"A ‘Buyback’ can help a company to reduce the number of shares available in the open market"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nStatement a is correct: A rights issue is an invitation to existing shareholders to purchase\nadditional new shares in the company. This type of issue gives existing shareholders securities\ncalled rights.\nStatement b is incorrect: An initial public offering (IPO) refers to the process of offering shares\nof a private corporation to the public in a new stock issuance for the first time. It also denotes a\ntransition from a private to a public company.\nStatement c is correct: Qualified institutional placements (QIPS) are a way to issue shares to\nthe public without going through standard regulatory compliance. QIP is a designation of a\nsecurities issue given by the Securities and Exchange Board of India (SEBI). QIP allows an Indian-\n\nlisted company (public company) to raise capital from domestic markets without the need to\nsubmit any pre-issue filings to market regulators.\nStatement d is correct: A buyback, also known as a share repurchase, is when a company buys\nits own outstanding shares to reduce the number of shares available on the open market.","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","id":213,"area":"Capital Markets"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-08-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-08","qNum":30,"question":"With reference to financial markets, which of the following statements is correct?","options":{"a":"Capital market is a place where buyers and sellers indulge in trade of financial securities for a period of minimum five years.","b":"A Primary market is one in which a company issues its new shares on a stock exchange.","c":"The long-term financial market does not include stock purchases in the primary market.","d":"Cash Management Bill is one of the important instruments in long term financial market."},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer\nStatement a is incorrect. Capital market is a place where buyers and sellers indulge in\nbuying/selling of financial securities like bonds, stocks. (Not necessarily 5 years). The long-term\nfinancial market of an economy is known as the ‘capital market’. This market makes it possible to\nraise long-term money (capital), i.e., for a period of minimum 365 days and above.\nStatement b is correct. A primary market is one in which a company issues new security in stock\nexchange. Whereas Secondary market deals with the exchange of prevailing or previously-issued\nsecurities among investors.\nStatement c is incorrect. Long term financial market includes commodity and stock purchases in\nboth primary market and secondary market. Primary market is the market for new shares or\nsecurities.\nStatement d is incorrect. The Government of India, in consultation with the RBI, decided to issue\na new short-term instrument, known as Cash Management Bills, since August 2009 to meet the\ntemporary cash flow mismatches of the government. The Cash Management Bills are non-\nstandard and discounted instruments issued for maturities less than 91 days.","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","id":214,"area":"Capital Markets"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-09-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-09","qNum":1,"question":"With reference to Sovereign Wealth Funds (SWFs), which of the following statements is/are correct? 1. It is a state-owned investment fund. 2. China’s Investment Cooperation fund is the largest of any sovereign wealth fund in the world. 3. India doesn’t have a SWF for making investments outside India. Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1 and 3 only","b":"2 and 3 only","c":"1 and 2 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct: SWFs is a fund of foreign currency to be invested in global assets. It is\nowned by the State and setup and managed by the Central Bank or a special purpose vehicle\n(SPV) of the government. Many SWFs have been outsourcing themselves. A July 2010 report on\nGlobal Sovereign Wealth Funds from Cerulli Associates found that the Abu Dhabi Investment\nAuthority outsourcing 80% of its assets, while the Korea Investment Corporation outsources\naround one-third its assets and Norway’s Pension Fund – Global just 13%.\nStatement 2 is incorrect. The Norwegian Government Pension Fund is the largest of any\nsovereign wealth fund in the world. According to data from the SWF Institute, the fund contained\nmore than $1.1 trillion as of January 2021. Second is China’s Investment Cooperation fund, which\nalso manages a similarly large amount of assets of just above $1 trillion.\nStatement 3 is correct. India doesn›t has an external SWF because our reserves are not adequate\nfor our needs and contingencies. At end-September 2020, India’s external debt was placed at US$\n556.2 billion and our forex reserves are $585.324 billion in the week of January 1, 2021. National\nInvestment and Infrastructure Fund (NIIF) India’s SWF focused on Indian infrastructure with a\nfocus on transportation (roads, ports and airports), energy, urban planning and other\ninfrastructure and allied segments.","topic":"Bonds & Securities","id":215,"area":"Bonds, SWFs & Funds"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-09-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-09","qNum":2,"question":"With respect to Elephant Bond, consider the following statement: 1. It’s a 5-year sovereign bond. 2. The fund will be utilised for infrastructure projects only. 3. It was issued on the recommendation of Surjit Bhalla committee. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is incorrect: It’s a 25-year sovereign bond. It is an avenue for people to bring their\nmoney stashed offshore without fear of being prosecuted. Once they declare their offshore\nmoney, they will be asked to invest 40 per cent of that amount in these elephant bonds.\nStatement 2 is correct: The fund will be utilised for infrastructure projects only.\n\nStatement 3 is correct: It was issued on the recommendation of Surjit Bhalla committee. The\nCommittee has recommended “Elephant Bonds” as(a)specialised security product providing funds\ntowards Long Term Infrastructure.","topic":"Bonds & Securities","id":216,"area":"Bonds, SWFs & Funds"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-09-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-09","qNum":3,"question":"Consider the following statements with respect to the municipal bonds: 1. It is an instrument that allows investors to purchase equity in local government projects. 2. They must have a rating above the investment-grade for the public issue. 3. These bonds cannot be traded in the secondary market which makes them less attractive. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is incorrect: A municipal bond is a kind of debt instrument where investors offer loans\nto local governments. They are issued by civic bodies for specific projects and usually have a 10-\nyear tenure.\nStatement 2 is correct. As per SEBI rules, “any municipality or any statutory body or board or\ncorporation, authority, trust or agency established or notified by any central or state Act or any\nSPV notified by the state government or central government,” would be eligible to issue Municipal\nBonds. The market regulator has mandated that the municipal bonds must have a rating above the\ninvestment-grade for the public issue.\nStatement 3 is incorrect: Municipal bonds are traded both in the primary market and secondary\nmarket. But the issue size is not very high there is very less liquidity in the secondary market. It\nthus makes it difficult to invest through secondary market.","topic":"Bonds & Securities","id":217,"area":"Bonds, SWFs & Funds"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-09-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-09","qNum":5,"question":"Which one of the following best describes the purpose of a ‘Credit Default Swap’?","options":{"a":"Mitigation of risk associated with a fixed or a floating interest rate regime.","b":"Mitigation of risk associated with volatility in currency markets.","c":"Securing a price hedge against variations in commodity prices.","d":"Insurance against possible nonrepayment of principal/interest"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Option d is the correct answer.\nA credit default swap (CDS) is an instrument of risk management in which an investor “swaps” or\noffsets his credit risk with that of another investor. Suppose person A has invested in a corporate\nbond. But he is not certain that the borrower is going to pay the interest or the principal amount\non time. To hedge his risks, person A approaches person B, who agrees to reimburse person A in\ncase the borrower defaults on his payments. In return person A agrees to pay person B monthly\npremiums till a certain maturity date. Person A and Person B are said to be in a credit default swap\ncontract. It must be remembered that the seller of the CDS will make the payment to the buyer\nonly in case of credit default by the borrower (or any other credit event defined in the CDS\ncontract). If there is no credit default, the seller of the CDS would gain and the buyer of the CDS\nwould lose because of the premium payments that were made by the buyer to the seller.\nImportant Tips\nSwaps are a sub-set of derivatives, in which two parties agree to exchange/swap their cash\nflows, in a bid to reduce their respective financial risks arising from their investments. They are\nexceedingly popular because they give a great deal of flexibility for investors, who are otherwise\nconstrained by their financial objectives and risk appetites.","topic":"Money & Currency","id":218,"area":"Bonds, SWFs & Funds"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-09-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-09","qNum":6,"question":"Consider the following statements with reference to the bilateral netting: 1. It enables two counterparties with several claims against each other to determine a single net payment obligation. 2. At present, Indian laws do not permit bilateral netting between two counterparties. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct. A bilateral netting agreement enables two counterparties in a financial\ncontract to offset claims against each other to determine a single net payment obligation due\nfrom one counterparty to the other. In India, Bilateral contracts constitute 40% of total financial\ncontracts, while multilateral contracts constitute 60%.\n\nStatement 2 is incorrect. Earlier, Indian financial contract laws did not permit bilateral netting,\nhowever, they did allow multi-lateral netting. However, the Bilateral Netting of Qualified\nFinancial Contracts Bill, 2020, recently passed by the Parliament, provides an unambiguous legal\nframework for bilateral netting and would result in huge savings for the participants, besides\nreducing the overall risk.","topic":"Economy — Misc","id":219,"area":"Bonds, SWFs & Funds"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-09-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-09","qNum":7,"question":"Consider the following statements with reference to the International Financial Services Centres Authority (IFSCA): 1. It is a statutory body for the regulation of all international financial services centres (IFSCs) in India. 2. All members of the authority are appointed by the Central government. 3. All the banking and financial institutions within IFSCs are regulated by the IFSCA. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct: The International Financial Services Centres Authority (IFSCA) is a\nstatutory body established on April 27, 2020 under the International Financial Services Centres\nAuthority Act, 2019. It is headquartered at GIFT City, Gandhinagar in Gujarat.\nStatement 2 is correct: It will consist of nine members appointed by the central government.\nThey will include chairman of authority, a member each from RBI, SEBI, IRDAI, PFRDA; two\nmembers from the ministry of finance and two members will be appointed on recommendation of\na selection committee.\nStatement 3 is correct: The IFSCA regulates financial products and financial institutions which\nhave been previously approved by any appropriate regulator such as RBI, SEBI etc., in IFSC. It may\nalso recommend to the central government any other financial products, financial services, or\nfinancial institutions, which may be permitted in an IFSC.","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","id":220,"area":"Bonds, SWFs & Funds"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-09-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-09","qNum":8,"question":"With reference to venture capital funding, which of the statements given below is incorrect?","options":{"a":"It is a private equity capital which lends capital to entrepreneurs.","b":"It is generally invested for long-term duration.","c":"It is a high risk, high gain investment.","d":"Venture capitalists do not get power to influence decisions of the companies."},"answer":"d","explanation":"Option d is the correct answer.\nStatement a is correct. It is a private equity capital which lends capital to entrepreneurs.\nStartup companies need a certain amount of investment. Many times, they cannot get this funding\nfrom conventional set-ups like banks etc. This is where the role of venture capital funding\nbecomes important.\n\nStatement b is correct. This funding is generally for(a)longterm duration. Wealthy investors are\nlike to invest their capital in new businesses. This capital is known as venture capital and the\ninvestors are called venture capitalists.\nStatement c is correct. Such investments are risky as they are illiquid, but are capable of giving\nimpressive returns if invested in the right venture. The returns to the venture capitalists depend\nupon the growth of the company.\nStatement d is incorrect. Venture capitalists have the power to influence major decisions of the\ncompanies they are investing in as it is their money at stake.","topic":"Economy — Misc","id":221,"area":"Bonds, SWFs & Funds"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-09-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-09","qNum":9,"question":"They are exchange-traded contracts to sell or buy financial instruments or physical commodities for a future delivery at an agreed price. There is an agreement to buy or sell a specified quantity of financial instrument commodity in a designated future month at a price agreed upon by the buyer and seller. They are","options":{"a":"Swaps","b":"Futures","c":"Forward Contracts","d":"Options"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nFutures are exchange-traded contracts to sell or buy financial instruments or physical\ncommodities for a future delivery at an agreed price. There is an agreement to buy or sell a\nspecified quantity of financial instrument commodity in a designated future month at a price\nagreed upon by the buyer and seller.\nImportant Tips\n• A derivative is an instrument whose value is derived from the value of one or more underlying\ninstrument, which can be commodities, precious metals, currency, bonds, stocks, stocks\nindices, etc. Four most common examples of derivative instruments are Forwards, Futures,\nOptions and Swaps.\n• A forward contract is a customized contract between two parties, where settlement takes\nplace on a specific date in future at a price agreed today. They are bilateral contracts and hence\nexposed to counter-party risk. The contract has to be settled by delivery of the asset on\nexpiration date.\n• An option is a derivative, a contract that gives the buyer the right, but not the obligation, to\nbuy or sell the underlying asset by a certain date (expiration date) at a specified price.\n• A swap is a derivative contract between two parties that involves the exchange of pre-agreed\ncash flows of two financial instruments. The cash flows are usually determined using the\nnotional principal amount","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","id":222,"area":"Bonds, SWFs & Funds"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-09-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-09","qNum":11,"question":"With reference to Masala bonds, which of the following statements is/are incorrect? 1. It gives Indian borrowers a choice for external commercial borrowings. 2. Foreign investors bear the currency risk. 3. International Finance Corporation issued a 50-year Masala Bond in London Stock Exchange. Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"3 only","c":"1 and 2 only","d":"2 and 3 only"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct. IFC issued the Masala Bonds in global capital markets outside India to raise\nmoney and lend to Indian companies thereby diversifying and adding choice of funding sources\nfor Indian borrowers under External Commercial Borrowing (ECBs). According to Reserve Bank\nof India’s statistics, Masala bonds accounted for 39% of the total external fund raising of $7.39\nbillion by Indian companies during Q4FY2017.\nStatement 2 is correct. Unlike other External Commercial Borrowings (ECBs) like commercial\nbank loans, buyers’ credit, suppliers’ credit, securitized instruments such as Floating Rate Notes\nand Fixed Rate Bonds etc., which have to be taken as foreign currency loans and repaid similarly,\nMasala bonds enable Indian companies to take in rupees and return in rupees. Thereby,\neffectively putting the currency risk on foreign investors.\nStatement 3 is incorrect. Recently, IFC issued a 15-year Masala Bond on London Stock Exchange.\nIFC has previously issued Masala bonds in maturities of three, five, seven, and 10 years. The latest\n15-year bonds mark the latest step in IFC’s efforts to extend the yield curve and set a pricing\nbenchmark for future issuances with similar maturities. IFC’s 15-year masala bond demonstrates\nlong-term investor confidence in India’s growth,","topic":"Bonds & Securities","id":223,"area":"Bonds, SWFs & Funds"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-09-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-09","qNum":12,"question":"With reference to Infrastructure Investment Trust (InvITs), consider the following statements: 1. InvITs enable access to long-term funds for infrastructure creation. 2. InvITs are regulated by the Securities and Exchange Board of India (SEBI). 3. Retail investors are not allowed to invest in InvITs due to the risks involved. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct: InvITs can act as an efficient investment vehicle to enable long-term funds\nfor infrastructure creation, from both retail investors and global institutional funds.\nStatement 2 is correct: The InvITs are regulated by the SEBI (Infrastructure Investment Trusts)\nRegulations, 2014.\nStatement 3 is incorrect: A retail or even a large financial investor may not be typically able to\ninvest in infrastructure projects such as roads, power, energy etc. InvITs enable these investors\nto buy a small portion of the units being sold by the fund.","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","id":224,"area":"Bonds, SWFs & Funds"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-09-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-09","qNum":13,"question":"Consider the following statements with reference to the difference between option and swap: 1. Options are traded on over-the-counter as well as on stock exchange while Swap is only traded on over-the-counter market. 2. Acquiring an option involves upfront premium payment whereas there is no such payment involved in a swap. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct: A key difference between swap and option is that a swap is not traded via\nthe exchanges. A swap is an over-the-counter (OTC) derivative type whereas an option can be\neither an OTC or exchange-traded derivative. Swaps are contracts that are customised and traded\nprivately between two parties.\nStatement 2 is correct: The premium is the price a buyer pays the seller for an option. The\npremium is paid upfront at purchase an option and is not refundable - even if the option is not\nexercised. Premiums are quoted on a per-share basis. Whereas no swap transactions involving\nupfront payment of Rupees or its equivalent in any form shall be undertaken.","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","id":225,"area":"Bonds, SWFs & Funds"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-09-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-09","qNum":14,"question":"With reference to ‘Capital Market’ in an economy, which one of the following statements is correct regarding ‘Social Stock Exchange’?","options":{"a":"It is a platform for investors to donate their small percentage of earning towards social and humanitarian cause.","b":"It will be a portal for corporate entities to invest in social sectors under Corporate Social Responsibility.","c":"It aims to streamline the funds from various government and private agencies into public schemes dedicated to upliftment of vulnerable section of the society.","d":"It will help social and voluntary enterprises to raise capital in form of equity or debt or a unit of the mutual fund."},"answer":"d","explanation":"Option d is the correct answer.\nSocial Stock Exchange (SSE) is a platform that allows investors to invest in select social enterprises\nor social initiatives. The aim is to help social and voluntary enterprises to raise capital in form of\nequity or debt or a unit of the mutual fund. Social Enterprise is a revenue-generating business.\nThe primary aim of social enterprise is to achieve a social objective such as providing healthcare\nor clean energy. SSE exists in countries such as Singapore, UK among others. These countries\nallow firms operating in social sectors to raise risk capital. The proposal to set up SSEs in the\ncountry was first floated during the Union Budget in 2019.\nIn 2019, SEBI constituted a group under the chairmanship of Tata group veteran Ishaat Hussain.\nIn 2020, SEBI again set up the Technical Group (TG) under Harsh Bhanwala, ex-Chairman,\nNABARD. This time for getting further expert advice and clarity on SSE. That committee submitted\nits report.","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","id":226,"area":"Bonds, SWFs & Funds"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-09-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-09","qNum":15,"question":"With reference to SENSEX in India, consider the following statements: 1. It is one of the benchmark indexes of the BSE Limited. 2. It is comprised of 50 of the largest and most actively-traded stocks. 3. Its value is calculated in terms of both Indian rupees and U.S. dollars. 4. Its composition is re-evaluated once in every five years as per the performance of stocks of the companies. How many of the above given statements are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"Only three","d":"All four"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct. Sensex is the benchmark index of the BSE in India. It was launched in 1986,\nas a basket of 30 stocks representing the country’s largest, financially-sound companies listed on\nthe BSE.\nStatement 2 is incorrect. SENSEX is the benchmark index of the Bombay Stock Exchange (BSE)\nin India. The SENSEX index is made up of 30 (not 50) of the BSE’s largest and most actively\ntraded stocks, and it serves as a gauge for the Indian economy.\nStatement 3 is correct. Sensex is calculated in Indian rupees and U.S. dollars. As they reflect both\ndomestic and international benchmarks for the Indian market and reflect changes in both stock\nprices and exchange rates properly.\nStatement 4 is incorrect. The Sensex is reviewed and reevaluated semi-annually each year in\nJune and December.","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","id":227,"area":"Bonds, SWFs & Funds"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-09-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-09","qNum":16,"question":"Consider the following pairs: List I Term List II Description 1. Certificates of Deposits These can be issued by commercial banks and financial institutions. 2. Commercial Paper Unsecured and short-term debt instrument issued by corporations. 3. Cash Management bill Issued to meet the temporary mismatches in the cash flow of the Government How many pairs given above are correctly matched?","options":{"a":"Only one pair","b":"Only two pairs","c":"All three pairs","d":"None of the above pairs"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nPair 1 is correct: Certificates of Deposits (CDs) are issued by commercial banks and financial\ninstitutions to raise additional funds. These are issued in multiples of 25 lakh, subject to a\nminimum amount of 1 crore. The maturity period ranges from three months to one year in the\ncase of banks and one year to three years in the case of other financial institutions.\nPair 2 is correct: Commercial paper is an unsecured, short-term debt instrument issued by\ncorporations. It is typically used to the finance short-term liabilities such as payroll, accounts\npayable, and inventories. It was introduced in 1990.\nPair 3 is correct: Cash Management Bills (CMBs) are short term debt instruments issued to\nmeet the temporary mismatches in the cash flow of the Government of India\nImportant Tips\n• Certificate of Deposit (CD) is a negotiable money market instrument and issued in\ndematerialized form or as a Promissory Note against funds deposited at a bank or other eligible\nfinancial institution for a specified time period. Similar to Fixed deposits, the CD aims to denote\nin writing that you have deposited money in the bank for a fixed period, and the bank would pay\nyou interest - based on the amount and the period of your Deposit.\n• Commercial Papers (CPs) are issued by Corporate, Primary Dealers (PDs) and the All-India\nFinancial Institutions (FIs) to raise funds. These are issued in denominations of 5 lakh or\nmultiples of it, subject to a minimum amount of 1 crore. The maturity period is three to six\nmonths.\n• The Cash Management Bills have the generic character of Treasury-bills but are issued for\nmaturities less than 91 days. Like Treasury bills these are zero coupon bonds issued at a\ndiscount. In 2010, Government of India, in consultation with Reserve Bank of India introduced\nit.","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","id":228,"area":"Bonds, SWFs & Funds"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-09-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-09","qNum":17,"question":"Consider the following statements with reference to the Exchange Traded Funds (ETFs): 1. Through ETFs, one can only invest in equities and not in debt instruments. 2. Compared to Mutual Funds, ETFs generally have higher liquidity. 3. ETFs can be actively bought and sold on the stock exchanges. How many of the above given statements are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nAn exchange traded fund (ETF) is a cluster of different securities merged together in a single\nfund that is traded on the stock exchange. It is a marketable security that tracks an index, a\ncommodity, bonds, or a basket of assets like an index fund.\nStatement 1 is incorrect. An exchange traded fund (ETF) allows a person to invest in debt\ninstruments. Debt ETFs allow the investors to realise returns on their investments through\nexposure to fixed-income securities. Debt ETFs in India are sometimes referred to as bond ETFs\ndue to their high exposure to bonds as the underlying asset.\nStatement 2 is correct. Exchange-traded funds (ETFs) have higher liquidity than mutual funds,\nmaking them not only popular investment vehicles but also convenient to tap into when cash flow\nis needed.\nStatement 3 is correct: The main difference between ETF and Mutual Fund is that while ETFs can\nbe actively bought and sold on the stock exchanges, just like any other shares. But one can only\npurchase a unit of a Mutual Fund from a fund house even though these can be listed on the\nexchanges.","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","id":229,"area":"Bonds, SWFs & Funds"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-09-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-09","qNum":18,"question":"“In this type of investment, a company may take controlling ownership in a business entity of another country. Foreign companies are directly involved with dayto- day operations in the business entity in other countries. The foreign companies not only bring money, but also knowledge and technology.” The above description can be most appropriately summed up by which of the following?","options":{"a":"Foreign Institutional Investment","b":"Investment by Participatory Notes","c":"Foreign Direct Investment","d":"Offshore Derivatives Instrument"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nOption a is incorrect: Foreign institutional investment is the portfolio investment by foreign\ninstitutions like mutual funds, insurance companies, pension funds, etc., in shares and\ndebentures. Foreign institutional investors (FIIs) are those institutional investors which invest in\nthe assets belonging to a different country other than that where these organizations are based.\nOption b is incorrect: Participatory notes are often referred to as PNs or P-Notes. These are\nfinancial instruments used by investors and hedge funds to invest in the Indian securities, and no\nregistration is required with the SEBI.\nOption c is correct: Foreign direct investment (FDI) a type of investment is when a company\ntakes controlling ownership in a business entity in another country. With Foreign direct\ninvestment, foreign companies are directly involved with day-to-day operations in the other\ncountry. It means foreign companies not only bring money to other country but also knowledge,\nskills and technology.\nOption d is incorrect: Offshore derivatives instruments (ODIs) are investment vehicles used by\noverseas investors for an exposure in Indian equities or equity derivatives. These investors are not\nregistered with SEBI, either because they do not want to, or due to regulatory restrictions. These\ninvestors approach a foreign institutional investor (FII), who is already registered with SEBI.","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","id":230,"area":"Bonds, SWFs & Funds"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-09-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-09","qNum":19,"question":"“It is a derivative instrument used by foreign companies to raise money in India. They are issued by domestic depository in India and are denominated in Indian Rupees. Just like equity share, they provide ownership in the company.” The above paragraph best describes which of the following financial instruments?","options":{"a":"Global Depository Receipts","b":"Participatory Notes","c":"Indian Depository Receipts","d":"Convertible Debentures"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nAn Indian Depository Receipt (IDR) is issued by a domestic depository in India and denominated\nin Rupees. It represents an ownership interest in a fixed number of underlying equity shares of\nthe Issuing Company. Since foreign companies are not allowed to list on Indian equity markets,\nIDR is a way to own shares of those companies. A foreign company issues and deposits new shares\nwith an Indian depository (say, National Securities Depository Ltd (NSDL) or Central Depository\nService Ltd or CDSL), Such a depository then, in turn, issues equivalent shares in rupees to\ninvestors in India. Much like an equity share, it is an ownership pie of a company. IDRs involve\ncurrency risk for the underlying shares in another country. Fluctuations in the exchange rate\ncould impact the value of the dividend payment","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","id":231,"area":"Bonds, SWFs & Funds"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-09-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-09","qNum":20,"question":"With reference to ‘Commercial Paper’, consider the following statements: 1. It is a short-term debt instrument issued to raise funds. 2. It is considered as an unsecured instrument as it is not backed by a collateral. 3. It can only be issued by scheduled commercial banks in India. How many of the above given statements are correct?","options":{"a":"Only One","b":"Only Two","c":"All Three","d":"None"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct: Commercial paper, also called CP, is a short-term debt instrument issued\nby companies to raise funds generally for a time period up to one year. It is an unsecured money\nmarket instrument issued in the form of a promissory note.\nStatement 2 is correct: Commercial paper is an unsecured, short-term debt instrument issued by\ncorporations. Commercial paper is not backed by any form of collateral, making it unsecured\ndebt. It’s typically used to finance short-term liabilities such as payroll, accounts payable, and\ninventories.\nStatement 3 is incorrect: They are issued by companies at a discount to face value, and have a\nmaturity period of up to one year. Corporates, primary dealers (PDs) and the all- India financial\ninstitutions (FIs) that have been permitted to raise short-term resources under the umbrella limit\nfixed by the Reserve Bank of India are eligible to issue CP.","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","id":232,"area":"Bonds, SWFs & Funds"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-09-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-09","qNum":21,"question":"With reference to ‘Treasury Bills’, consider the following statements: 1. In India, Treasury bills were first issued in 1991 by Reserve Bank of India. 2. They can be purchased by banking entities as well as by individuals. 3. They can be a part of Bank’s Statutory Liquidity Ratio. How many of the above given statements are correct?","options":{"a":"Only One","b":"Only Two","c":"All Three","d":"None"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is incorrect: Treasury Bills (T-Bills) were first issued in India in 1917 during the\nBritish Raj. The T-Bills were initially issued to meet the war expenditure needs of the government\nduring the First World War.\nStatement 2 is correct: T-Bills are issued by the government and have no risks attached to them.\nThey have high liquidity due to their short maturities of 14 days, 91 days, 182 days, and 364 days.\nT-Bills can be purchased by individuals, trusts, organizations, and banks.\nStatement 3 is correct: T-Bills have a relation with the Statutory Liquidity Ratio (SLR) in India.\nBanks in India are required to maintain a certain percentage of their net demand and time\nliabilities (NDTL) as liquid assets such as government securities, including T-Bills, to ensure\nliquidity and solvency.\nImportant Tips\nT-Bills are short-term debt instruments issued by the government to raise funds for a period of\nup to one year. They are zero-coupon bonds, which means they do not pay any interest to the\nholder, but are issued at a discount to their face value. The difference between the face value\nand the discounted price is the interest earned by the holder of the T-Bill.","topic":"Bonds & Securities","id":233,"area":"Bonds, SWFs & Funds"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-09-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-09","qNum":22,"question":"With reference to Participatory notes (P-notes), consider the following statements: 1. They can only be issued by the Securities and Exchange Board of India. 2. Investments flowing through P-notes are considered as offshore derivative investments (ODIs). 3. Holder of P-notes enjoys voting rights in relation to his/her investment in securities/shares. How many of the above given statements are correct?","options":{"a":"Only One","b":"Only Two","c":"All Three","d":"None"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is incorrect. P-notes are issued by registered foreign portfolio investors (FPIs) and\nnot by SEBI, to overseas investors who wish to be part of the Indian stock market without\nregistering themselves directly.\nStatement 2 is correct. Investments flowing through P-notes are considered as offshore\nderivative investments (ODIs). SEBI issued the new Regulations for Foreign Portfolio Investors,\n\nparticipatory notes where it got formally defined under the tag “Offshore Derivative Instrument”\n(ODIs) in Section 2(1)(j) of the said regulation.\nStatement 3 is incorrect. The P-notes holder does not enjoy any voting rights in relation to\nsecurity/shares referenced. Also, the investor in P-notes does not own the underlying Indian\nsecurity, which is held by the FII who issues the Participatory Notes.","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","id":234,"area":"Bonds, SWFs & Funds"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-09-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-09","qNum":23,"question":"Consider the following statements regarding ‘Qualified Institutional Placement’: 1. It is a tool used by Listed Companies to raise capital domestically from institutional investors. 2. Foreign Institutional Investors are barred by SEBI to invest in public companies through Qualified Institutional Placement route. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct. Qualified Institutional Placement enables the listed companies to raise\nfinance through the issue of securities to qualified institutional buyers (QIBs). It is a tool used by\npublicly listed companies to raise capital (funds) domestically from institutional investors.\nStatement 2 is incorrect. Foreign institutional investor registered with SEBI are allowed to place\ninvestment under Qualified Institutional Placement. Only the group of investors, who follow\ncertain regulations and rules formulated by SEBI are allowed to invest through Qualified\nInstitutional Placement process. This group of investors is collectively known as a Qualified\nInstitutional Buyer (QIB). According to SEBI, QIBs are defined as follows: Scheduled commercial\nbanks; Mutual funds; Foreign institutional investor registered with SEBI; Multilateral and\nbilateral development financial institutions; Venture capital funds registered with SEBI.\nImportant Tips\nA qualified institutional placement (QIP) is a way for listed companies to raise capital without\nhaving to submit legal paperwork to market regulators. It is common in India and other\nSoutheast Asian countries. The Securities and Exchange Board of India (SEBI) created the rule\nto avoid the dependence of companies on foreign capital resources.","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","id":235,"area":"Bonds, SWFs & Funds"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-09-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-09","qNum":24,"question":"Consider the following statements with reference to Government Securities (G-Secs): 1. Individuals cannot buy G-Secs in the primary market. 2. Non-scheduled Urban Cooperative Banks (UCBs) cannot buy G-Secs in the primary market. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Option d is the correct answer.\n\nStatement 1 is incorrect: Opening a Retail Direct Gilt (RDG) account will allow individuals to\nbuy Government securities directly in the primary market (auctions) as well as buy/sell in the\nsecondary market. For the retail investor, Government securities offer an option for long term\ninvestment.\nStatement 2 is incorrect: All non-E-Kuber members including non-scheduled UCBs can\nparticipate in the primary auction through scheduled commercial banks or PDs (called as\nPrimary Members-PMs) to buy Government Securities. For this purpose, the UCBs need to open\na securities account with a bank / PD – such an account is called a Gilt Account. A Gilt Account\nis a dematerialized account maintained with a scheduled commercial bank or PD.\nImportant Tips\nGovernment Securities G-secs are debt instruments issued by the government to borrow\nmoney. The two key categories are treasury bills – short-term instruments which mature in 91\ndays, 182 days, or 364 days, and dated securities – long-term instruments, which mature\nanywhere between 5 years and 40 years.","topic":"Bonds & Securities","id":236,"area":"Bonds, SWFs & Funds"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-09-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-09","qNum":25,"question":"In context of Indian stock market, consider the following statements: 1. Scrip Issue is the process of creating new shares which are given free of charge to existing shareholders. 2. Badla is carrying forward of transactions from one settlement period to another without effective delivery. 3. Kerb dealings are the transactions of stocks which take place outside the stock exchanges. How many of the above given statements are correct?","options":{"a":"Only One","b":"Only Two","c":"All Three","d":"None"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct: In corporate finance, a scrip issue, is the process of creating new shares\nwhich are given free of charge to existing shareholders. Bonus shares issue is also known as: Bonus\nissue/Scrip issue/Capitalisation issue. These are additional shares given to shareholders without\nany charges.\nStatement 2 is correct: Badla is carrying forward of transactions from one settlement period to\nanother without effective delivery. This is permitted only in specified securities and is done at\nthe making up price which is usually the closing price of the last day of settlement and, was finally\nbanned in 2001 by SEBI. Undha Badla and Ulta Badla are called backwardation and they are the\nreverse of Badla.\nStatement 3 is correct: Kerb dealings are the transactions of stocks which take place outside the\nstock exchanges— unofficially and take place after the normal trading hours. It is also associated\nwith the trading of shares outside the system of official stock markets or at hours when those\nstock markets are closed\nImportant Tips\nA financial instrument is defined as a document that indicates an asset to one individual (this\nperson is owed) and a liability (this person owes) to another individual. Not all financial\n\ninstruments are traded on the stock market. The financial instruments that are specifically\ntraded on the stock market are shares/ stocks, derivatives, bonds and mutual funds","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","id":237,"area":"Bonds, SWFs & Funds"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-10","qNum":1,"question":"Consider the following statements: 1. Reflation is enacted after a period of economic slowdown or contraction to stimulate spending and curb the effects of deflation. 2. Disinflation is a decrease in the general price levels of goods and services. 3. Deflation means that there is still rise in prices but overall rate is slow. 4. Skewflation means that some sectors are facing inflation while other sectors of economy do not. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"Only three","d":"All four"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct. Reflation is a fiscal or monetary policy enacted after a period of economic\nslowdown or contraction. Here the goal is to expand output, stimulate spending and curb the\neffects of deflation. Reflation policies can include reducing taxes, changing the money supply and\nlowering interest rates.\nStatement 2 is incorrect. Disinflation is slower rate of inflation. It means that there is still rise\nin prices but overall rate is slow. It is simply a slowing of Inflation.\nStatement 3 is incorrect. Deflation is a decrease in the general price levels of goods and services.\nIt is opposite of Inflation. During deflation prices of goods and services tend to fall.\nStatement 4 is correct. Skewflation means that some sectors are facing inflation while other\nsectors of economy do not.","topic":"Inflation & Deflation","id":238,"area":"Inflation Dynamics"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-10","qNum":2,"question":"Which of the following statements with reference to Stagflation is/are correct? 1. It is said to happen when an economy faces stagnant growth as well as persistently low inflation. 2. Increase in income tax and corporate tax rates can help deal with stagflation. Select the correct answer using the codes given below:","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Option d is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is incorrect. It is a situation where the inflation rate is high, the economic growth\nrate slows down, and unemployment is also high. Stagflation = High Inflation + High\nUnemployment + Stagnant Growth.\nStatement 2 is incorrect. The best policy measure is to reduce income tax and corporate taxes\nas they tend to reduce labour costs and raise demand for labour and leads to higher growth.","topic":"Inflation & Deflation","id":239,"area":"Inflation Dynamics"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-10","qNum":3,"question":"Consider the following statements regarding Demand-pull Inflation: 1. It can result from an increase in purchasing power of consumers over the same level of production. 2. Deficit financing of the government’s expenditure can lead to demand-pull inflation. 3. Interest rate cuts by the Central Bank can help in tackling this type of inflation. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct. A mismatch between demand and supply pulls up prices. Either the\ndemand increases over the same level of supply, or the supply decreases with the same level of\ndemand and thus the situation of demand-pull inflation arises. For the monetarists demand pull\ninflation is creation of extra purchasing power of consumers over the same level of production.\nStatement 2 is correct. Demand pull inflation is the typical case of creating extra money, either\nthrough wage revisions at the micro level or through deficit financing of government’s\nexpenditure via public borrowing or printing currency, without equivalent creation of extra\nproduction supply. Thus, government undertaking deficit financing of its expenditure can lead to\ndemand pull inflation.\nStatement 3 is incorrect. Interest rate cuts by the Central Bank will amount easy availability of\ncheap credit in the economy, thus enhancing the money supply. Without addition to production\nsupply, the increased money supply could lead to the scenario of “too much money chasing too\nlittle output” and could thus contribute to the creation of demand-pull inflation.\nImportant Tips\nAs per monetarists, in a situation of demand-pull inflation or cost push inflation, governments\ntake recourse to tighter monetary policy. This is basically intended to cut down the money\nsupply by siphoning out the extra money from the economy (by RBI increasing the Cash Reserve\nRatio of the Banks in India) or by making money costlier (by RBI increasing the Bank rate or\nRepo rate in India). Thus, instead of cutting the interest rates, Central banks increase the\ninterest rates as a short-term measure to tackle inflation.","topic":"Inflation & Deflation","id":240,"area":"Inflation Dynamics"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-10","qNum":4,"question":"In an imaginary scenario, inflation in India is rising with multiple items of food seeing rise in prices. This scenario has followed a rise in international prices of crude oil. However, there has been a glut in the international commodities markets since the few previous months. Which of the following measures on the part of government can help in checking inflationary pressures on food items in short as well as in the long term? 1. Increase in excise duty on petrol and diesel in the country. 2. Import of perishables like onions and tomatoes from international markets. 3. Rationalizing minimum support price policy to encourage farmers to enhance production of crops which are in short supply like pulses in the future. Select the correct answer using the code given below.","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 and 3 only","c":"1 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is incorrect. As mentioned in the question, the international crude oil prices have\nbeen high. This would have contributed to an increase in transportation cost, which would have\n\nin turn increased the cost of goods and services. Hence, in such a case of inflation, governments\ntend to reduce excise duties on petrol and diesel to reduce transportation costs. This would\nthen reflect in reduction of prices of goods and services in the economy. Thus, the government\nwould not be driven to increase the excise duty on petrol and diesel in a situation of inflation.\nStatement 2 is correct. Import of perishable goods like onions from the international market\nwould help increase the supply of such goods, thereby pushing down their prices. Hence, such\na move will help in reducing the inflation.\nStatement 3 is correct. Rationalization of the Minimum Support Price policy would ensure that\nthe production of crops in short supply, such as pulses, would be enough to meet the domestic\ndemand in the future. This would thus increase the supply of such goods in the future thereby\nreducing inflationary pressures coming from such goods in the long run. Hence, such a move will\nhelp in tackling inflation in the long run.","topic":"Inflation & Deflation","id":241,"area":"Inflation Dynamics"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-10","qNum":5,"question":"Which of the following can be considered as the short-term effects of inflation? 1. Increase in Employment 2. Positive impact on self-employed people 3. Increase in Saving rate Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1 and 3 only","b":"2 only","c":"2 and 3 only","d":"All of the above"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Option d is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct. Inflation increases employment in the short-run, but becomes neutral or\neven negative in the long run.\nStatement 2 is correct. Inflation has a neutral impact on the self-employed people in the short-\nrun. But in the long-run they also get affected as the economy as a whole gets affected.\nStatement 3 is correct. Money loses value with increase in inflation and public start putting their\nmoney in the bank and as a result saving rate increase. But this happens as a short-term effect of\ninflation.","topic":"Inflation & Deflation","id":242,"area":"Inflation Dynamics"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-10","qNum":6,"question":"It is the scenario where inflation rate decelerates resulting in the growth of prices at a slower rate. Identify the term from given statement?","options":{"a":"Deflation","b":"Disinflation","c":"Stagflation","d":"Reflation"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nOption a is incorrect. Deflation is the scenario where prices contracts, for example, prices reduce\nby 1% instead of growing at 5%.\nOption b is correct. Disinflation is the scenario where inflation rate decelerates resulting in the\ngrowth of prices at a slower rate. For example, prices may grow at 1% instead of 5%.\n\nOption c is incorrect. Stagflation: It is the combination of inflation and rising unemployment. It is\nthe macroeconomic condition when inflation rate is high and the growth rate is low resulting in\nhigh unemployment rate.\nOption d is incorrect. Reflation: It is the phenomenon where inflation returns after a period of\ndeflation.","topic":"Inflation & Deflation","id":243,"area":"Inflation Dynamics"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-10","qNum":7,"question":"With reference to the Indian economy, which of the following factors can cause cost-push inflation? 1. Taxes on petroleum products 2. Increase in price of steel 3. Higher minimum wages 4. Hikes in telecom charges Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"1, 3 and 4 only","c":"2, 3 and 4 only","d":"1, 2, 3 and 4"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Option d is the correct answer.\nAn increase in factor input costs (i.e., wages and raw materials) pushes up prices. The price rise\nwhich is the result of increase in the production cost is cost-push inflation. Cost-push inflation\nmeans prices have been “pushed up” by increases in the costs of any of the four factors of\nproduction—labor, capital, land, or entrepreneurship (All he 4 options given above fall within the\nfour factors of production which would lead to cost-push inflation.).","topic":"Inflation & Deflation","id":244,"area":"Inflation Dynamics"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-10","qNum":8,"question":"Consider the following statements: 1. Core inflation is the rise in price of volatile components like food and fuel. 2. Core inflation is also known as ‘headline inflation’. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Option d is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is incorrect: Core inflation helps measure inflation after excluding the effects of\ntemporary volatility, especially from prices of items such as fuel and food. For example, seasonal\nspikes in food prices may skew the inflation rate, but the effect is only transitory. The RBI’s action\non rates, however, affects the economy with a lag, by which time the spikes in the price of those\nfood items may have reversed. Viewing inflation after stripping out such volatility helps give it a\nbetter picture of the underlying trend in prices.\nStatement 2 is incorrect: Headline inflation is measured by CPI-combined. Headline inflation\nrefers to the change in value of all goods in the basket. Core inflation excludes food and fuel items\nfrom headline inflation.","topic":"Inflation & Deflation","id":245,"area":"Inflation Dynamics"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-10","qNum":9,"question":"Consider the following statements with reference to Consumer Price Index- Industrial Workers (CPI-IW): 1. It is released by the Central Statistics Office (CSO). 2. Recently, the base year of CPI-IW has been revised from 2001 to 2016. 3. The weight of food and beverage in the index has been increased recently. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is incorrect. The Labour Bureau (and not Central Statistics Office), an attached office\nof the Ministry of Labour & Employment, released Consumer Price Index for Industrial Workers\n(CPI-IW).\nStatement 2 is correct. The Labour and Employment Ministry revised the base year of the\nConsumer Price Index for Industrial Workers (CPI-IW) from 2001 to 2016.\nStatement 3 is incorrect. Recently, the weight of food and beverage was reduced from 46.2% to\n39%, while spending on housing increased from 15.2% to 17%.","topic":"Inflation & Deflation","id":246,"area":"Inflation Dynamics"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-10","qNum":11,"question":"Consider the following statements with reference to Refined Core Inflation: 1. Refined core inflation was constructed to address the anomaly in retail core inflation by excluding main fuel items. 2. Since 2020, refined core inflation has been much above the conventional core inflation indicating the impact of inflation in fuel items. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nDuring the current financial year, retail core inflation (inflation excluding ‘food and beverages’ and\n‘fuel and light’ – the transitory components of the index) has shown a rising trend.\nStatement 1 is correct: Conventionally, core inflation is calculated by excluding ‘food and\nbeverages’ and ‘fuel and light’ groups from overall inflation. While in CPI-C, major fuel items such\nas ‘petrol for vehicle’ and ‘diesel for vehicle’, which have relatively large weights, are not included\nin ‘fuel and light’. A ‘refined’ core inflation was constructed to address this anomaly by excluding\nmain fuel items viz., ‘petrol for vehicle’, ‘diesel for vehicle’ and ‘lubricants and other fuels for\nvehicles’, in addition to ‘food and beverages’ and ‘fuel and light’ from the headline retail inflation.\nStatement 2 is incorrect: Since June 2020, refined core inflation has been much below the\nconventional core inflation, indicating the impact of inflation in fuel items in the conventional\ncore inflation measure. Conventional way of calculating retail core inflation, instead of excluding\nthe volatile fuel items from core inflation, continue to include volatile fuel items in core inflation.\nAs a result, the fuel price rise continues to impact core inflation.","topic":"Inflation & Deflation","id":247,"area":"Inflation Dynamics"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-10","qNum":12,"question":"Consider the following statement regarding the different indexes used to measure inflation: 1. Both Wholesale Price Index (WPI) and Consumer Price Index (CPI) capture the changes in the prices of goods and services. 2. The Reserve Bank of India (RBI) has adopted the CPI as its key measure of inflation. 3. The basket of goods and services used to compute the GDP deflator changes automatically over time. How many of the above given statements are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nA wholesale price index (WPI) measures overall change in producer prices over time. It is a\nmeasure of inflation based on the prices of goods before they reach consumers. The Consumer\nPrice Index measures the overall change in consumer prices based on a representative basket of\ngoods and services over time.\nStatement 1 is incorrect: WPI does not capture changes in the prices of services, while CPI\ncaptures the changes in both goods and services.\nStatement 2 is correct: In 2014, the Reserve Bank of India has adopted the new Consumer Price\nIndex (CPI) (combined) as the key measure of inflation.\nStatement 3 is correct: The GDP price deflator measures the changes in prices for all the goods\nand services produced in an economy. The GDP price deflator is a more comprehensive inflation\nmeasure as it is not based on a fixed basket of goods. The Basket of goods and services used to\ncompute the GDP deflator changes automatically over time.\nImportant Tips\nWPI tracks the inflation at the producer level and CPI captures the inflation at the consumer\nlevel. WPI is released by Office of Economic Advisor and CPI is released by Central Statistics\nOffice","topic":"Inflation & Deflation","id":248,"area":"Inflation Dynamics"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-10","qNum":13,"question":"Consider the following statements: 1. A high share of revenue deficit indicates higher investment in the economy. 2. Primary Deficit focuses on the present fiscal imbalances only. 3. Fiscal Deficit increases during recession. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is incorrect: A large share of revenue deficit in fiscal deficit indicates that a large part\nof borrowing is being used to meet its consumption expenditure needs rather than investment.\nStatement 2 is correct: Primary deficit is simply the fiscal deficit minus the interest payments.\nThe goal of measuring primary deficit is to focus on present fiscal imbalances.\nStatement 3 is correct: If an economy experiences a recession and the GDP falls, tax revenues fall\nbecause firms and households pay lower taxes when they earn less. This means that the deficit\nincreases in a recession and falls in a boom, even with no change in fiscal policy.","topic":"Economy — Misc","id":249,"area":"Inflation Dynamics"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-10","qNum":14,"question":"With respect to “Strategic Disinvestment Policy of the Central Public Sector Enterprises (CPSEs)”, consider the following statements: 1. This policy requires the transfer of management along with dilution of less than 50% of CPSEs. 2. It is undertaken through a consultation process among different Ministries and NITI Aayog. Which of the statement given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 Only","b":"2 Only","c":"Both1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is incorrect. Strategic disinvestment involves sale of substantial portion of\nGovernment shareholding in identified CPSEs upto 50 per cent or more, along with transfer of\nmanagement control.\nStatement 2 is correct. The policy on disinvestment is undertaken through a consultation process\namong different Ministries or Departments, including NITI Aayog.","topic":"Economy — Misc","id":250,"area":"Inflation Dynamics"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-10","qNum":15,"question":"Which of the following items are included in Non-Tax Revenue Receipts? 1. Disinvestment proceeds 2. Fees, Penalties and fines 3. Interests receipts on loans given 4. Grants in aid from foreign countries 5. Fresh government borrowings from abroad 6. Profits on investments made by governments Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1, 2, 3, 4, and 5 only","b":"1, 2, 3 and 6 only","c":"2, 3, 5 and 6 only","d":"2, 3, 4 and 6 only"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Option d is the correct answer\nNon tax revenue receipts include:\n• interest receipts on account of loans by the central government,\n• dividends and profits on investments made by the government,\n• fees, penalties and fines received by the government,\n• user charges for railways, transport, power etc.,\n• Cash grants in aid from foreign countries and international organizations.\n• Disinvestment proceeds and fresh government borrowings from abroad are included in the\nCapital receipts.","topic":"Economy — Misc","id":251,"area":"Inflation Dynamics"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-10","qNum":16,"question":"Consider the following statements regarding the types of Financial Grants provided by the Indian Parliament: 1. An Additional Grant is authorised for a particular service for which the amount granted in the budget turned out to be insufficient. 2. Token Grant involves simple reappropriation from one expenditure head to another in the already passed budget. 3. Excess Grants are voted upon by the Lok Sabha after the current financial year in which they are made. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is incorrect: An Additional Grant involves sanction for additional expenditure on a\nservice that was not originally contemplated in the budget for that year and was not a part of it,\nbut is found to be required now.\nStatement 2 is correct: In Token Grant, there is no sanction of new funds. It is just an\nadministrative procedure, wherein the Parliament reallocates and authorises use of funds from\none head of expenditure to another.\nStatement 3 is correct: Excess Grant involves Parliamentary authorisation ex post facto - i.e.\nwhen expenditure in excess of sum granted in budget has already been made.\nImportant Tips\nA Supplementary Grant is one where the amount for a particular service already part of the\nbudget was found to be insufficient and now, Parliament needs to sanction extra funds for it.","topic":"Economy — Misc","id":252,"area":"Inflation Dynamics"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-10","qNum":17,"question":"Which of the following are the likely benefits of a certain level of Inflation in economy? 1. Easier for government to achieve its fiscal deficit target 2. According to the Philip’s Curve, rising unemployment can be fought with increased inflation. 3. It encourages the domestic savings by earning high interest rate Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"1 and 3 only","c":"2 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer\nInflation is a general rise in the prices of goods and services. While high inflation is generally\nconsidered harmful, some economists believe that a small amount of inflation can help drive\neconomic growth.\nOption 1 is correct. In the short term, the government, which is the single largest borrower in the\neconomy, benefits from high inflation. Inflation allows the government to meet its fiscal deficit\ntarget. Fiscal deficit limits are expressed as a percentage of the nominal GDP. As the nominal GDP\nrises because of inflation, the same amount of fiscal deficit (borrowing) becomes a smaller\npercentage of the GDP.\n\nOption 2 is correct. Economists believe that an inverse relationship exists between inflation and\nunemployment, and that rising unemployment could be fought with increased inflation. This\nrelationship is defined in the famous Phillips curve.\nOption 3 is incorrect. High inflation eats away the real interest earned from keeping one’s\nmoney in the bank or similar savings instruments. Earning a 6% nominal interest from a savings\ndeposit effectively means earning 0% interest if inflation is at 6%. By the reverse logic, borrowers\nare better off when inflation rises because they end up paying a lower “real” interest rate. So, the\ninflation discourages the savings instead of encouraging them.","topic":"Inflation & Deflation","id":253,"area":"Inflation Dynamics"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-10","qNum":18,"question":"With reference to the Indian economy, demand-pull inflation can be caused by which of the following? 1. Increase in welfare expenditure 2. Higher purchasing power of consumers 3. Raising tax rates 4. Increase in prices of raw materials 5. Increased labour costs Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"1, 2 and 5 only","c":"1, 2 and 3 only","d":"2, 4 and 5 only"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nInflation can be divided into Demand pull inflation and Cost-push inflation. Demand-pull\ninflation is caused by an increase in aggregate demand, driven by the four sections of the\nmacroeconomy: households, business, governments, and foreign buyers. It is caused by an\nexpanding economy, increased government spending, or overseas growth.\nOption 1 is correct: as increase in welfare expenditure means increase in government spending.\nThis in tun will increase demand pull inflation.\nOption 2 is correct: When the consumers have higher income levels and have a higher\npurchasing power then they feel confident and they spend more and even take on more debt to\nspend. This leads to a steady increase in demand, which means higher prices and higher demand-\npull inflation.\nOption 3 is incorrect: as an increased rate of taxes would reduce the personal disposable income\nof a person. Thus, it is one of the measures used by the government and RBI to fight demand pull\ninflation.\nOption 4 and 5 are incorrect: Cost push inflation is caused by the decrease in the aggregate\nsupply of goods and services resulting from an increase in the cost of production. An increase in\nthe costs of raw materials or labour can contribute to cost-push inflation (not demand-pull\ninflation)","topic":"Inflation & Deflation","id":254,"area":"Inflation Dynamics"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-10","qNum":19,"question":"Consider the following pairs: Type of Assets Explanation 1. Wholesale Price Index Office of Economic Advisor 2. Consumer Price Index of Industrial workers Ministry of Labour & Employment. 3. GDP Deflator Ministry of Statistics and Programme Implementation 4. Producer Price Index Bureau of Labor Statistics. How many pairs given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"Only three","d":"All four"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nPair 1 is correct. The Wholesale Price Index (WPI) is the price of a representative basket of\nwholesale goods. In India, the WPI is published by the Office of the Economic Adviser,\nDepartment for Promotion of Industry and Internal Trade, Ministry of Commerce and Industry,\nGovernment of India. The Wholesale Price Index (WPI) in India is available monthly only.\nPair 2 is correct. The Consumer Price Index of Industrial workers is released by the Labour\nBureau, an attached office of the Ministry of Labour & Employment. The index is compiled every\nmonth based on the retail prices collected from 317 markets spread over 88 industrially important\ncentres in the country.\nPair 3 is correct. GDP deflator is published by the Ministry of Statistics and Programme\nImplementation and is available only on a quarterly basis along with GDP estimates.\nPair 4 is incorrect. Producer Price Index (PPI) measures the average change in the price a\nproducer receives for his goods/services sold in the domestic market/exports. PPI is not\nmeasured and calculated in India till yet, but NITI AYOG is preparing it to release it soon.\nImportant Tips\nIn India, there are four consumer price index numbers, which are calculated, and these are as\nfollows:\na) CPI for Industrial Workers (IW)\nb) CPI for Agricultural Labourers (AL)\nc) CPI for Rural Labourers (RL) and\nd) CPI for Urban Non-Manual Employees (UNME).\nWhile the Ministry of Statistics and Program Implementation collects CPI (UNME) data and\ncompiles it, the remaining three are collected by the Labour Bureau in the Ministry of Labour.","topic":"Inflation & Deflation","id":255,"area":"Inflation Dynamics"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-10","qNum":20,"question":"Which of the following measures/actions by the government/RBI will most likely lead to an increase in Demand-Pull Inflation? 1. Increasing the salaries of government employees 2. Increasing the minimum support price (MSP) 3. Increasing customs duty of raw materials 4. Reducing monetary policy interest rates Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1, 2 and 3 only","b":"1 and 4 only","c":"1, 2 and 4 only","d":"2, 3 and 4 only"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nDemand-pull inflation exists when aggregate demand for a good or service outstrips aggregate\nsupply.\nOption 1 is correct: Increasing the salaries of government employees will lead to an increase in\ngovernment expenditure. With this consumer will have more discretionary income to spend on\ngoods and services. When that increases faster than supply, it creates demand pull inflation.\nOption 2 is correct: Enhancing the minimum support price (MSP) of the notified agricultural\ncommodities will put more money into the hands of farmers. This will lead to an increase in money\nsupply in the economy, thereby driving up the demand for goods and services thus contributing\nto demand pull inflation.\nOption 3 is incorrect: Increasing customs duty will make import of raw materials expensive\nwhich drives up prices even without increase in aggregate demand. This is called cost push\ninflation. Cost-push inflation occurs when overall prices increase (inflation) due to increases in\nthe cost of wages and raw materials (inputs).\nOption 4 is correct: Lower interest rates: A cut in interest rates causes a rise in consumer\nspending and higher investment. This may cause a rise in aggregate demand and inflationary\npressures.","topic":"Inflation & Deflation","id":256,"area":"Inflation Dynamics"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-10","qNum":21,"question":"Consider the following statements regarding Producer Price Index (PPI): 1. PPI measures the average change in prices received by the producer excluding indirect taxes. 2. The PPI does not include the price of imported goods. 3. Both goods as well as services are covered under PPI. How many of the above given statements are incorrect?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Option d is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct: PPI measures the average change in prices received by the producer and\nexcludes indirect taxes. The prices included in the PPI are from the first commercial transaction\nfor many products and some services.\nStatement 2 is correct: Both PPI and CPI are important economic measures because they point\nto monthly changes in prices. But they reflect prices from different standpoints. As noted above,\nthe Producer Price Index measures prices based on the first commercial transaction for a product\nor service. This is in contrast to the consumer price index (CPI), which measures price changes\nencountered by the consumer. Another key distinction is that the PPI does not include the price\n\nof imported goods, unlike the CPI. Conversely, the PPI includes export prices while the CPI\ndoes not.\nStatement 3 is correct: The Producer Price Index (PPI) measures the average change in sale\nprices for the entire domestic market of raw goods and services. These goods and services are\nbought by consumers from their primary producers, bought indirectly from retail sellers, or\npurchased by producers themselves.","topic":"Inflation & Deflation","id":257,"area":"Inflation Dynamics"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-10","qNum":22,"question":"Consider the following statements regarding Stagflation: 1. It denotes a price rise of a small group of commodities over a sustained period of time. 2. It results in high inflation and unemployment levels in the economy. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is incorrect: Stagflation is a situation in an economy when inflation and\nunemployment both are at higher levels, contrary to conventional belief. Whereas Skewflation\nis a phenomenon in which there is a price rise of one or a small group of commodities over a\nsustained period of time, without a traditional designation.\nStatement 2 is correct: Stagflation is an economic cycle characterized by slow growth and a high\nunemployment rate accompanied by inflation. Economic policymakers find this combination\nparticularly difficult to handle, as attempting to correct one of the factors can exacerbate another.","topic":"Inflation & Deflation","id":258,"area":"Inflation Dynamics"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-10","qNum":23,"question":"With reference to Galloping Inflation, consider the following statements: 1. During galloping inflation, people try to get rid of currency by buying physical assets. 2. During galloping inflation, exporters will be much less motivated to export their products. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nGalloping inflation refers to a condition when the inflation rate is extraordinarily high. In this\nscenario, the currency of the country will lose value. Inflation in the double- or triple digit range\nof 20, 100 or 200 percent a year is called galloping inflation.\nStatement 1 is correct: As galloping inflation results in rapid decrease in the money value of local\ncurrency, people in order to preserve its real value tend to get rid of currency by purchasing\nprecious metals, Land etc.\nStatement 2 is incorrect: Exporters benefit during galloping inflation, as the local currency\ndepreciates, making exports less expensive relative to overseas competitors. Exporters also\n\nreceive hard foreign currency, which appreciates in value as the local currency depreciates. This\ncan be a motivating factor for them to export their products.","topic":"Inflation & Deflation","id":259,"area":"Inflation Dynamics"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-10","qNum":24,"question":"Which among the following options correctly describes the term ‘Inflationary Gap’?","options":{"a":"The difference between the current real GDP and the GDP of an economy operating at full employment.","b":"An economic cycle characterized by slow growth and a high unemployment rate accompanied by inflation.","c":"Measure of the changes in prices for all the goods and services produced in an economy.","d":"The overall change in consumer prices over time, based upon a representative basket of goods and services."},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nAn inflationary gap measures the difference between the current real GDP and the GDP of an\neconomy operating at full employment. An inflationary gap exists when the demand for goods\nand services exceeds production due to higher levels of employment, increased trade activities,\nor elevated government expenditure. The real GDP can exceed the potential GDP, resulting in an\ninflationary gap. The inflationary gap represents the point in the business cycle when the economy\nexpands as consumers purchase more goods and services. As demand increases but production\nlags, prices rise to restore market equilibrium.","topic":"Inflation & Deflation","id":260,"area":"Inflation Dynamics"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-10","qNum":25,"question":"Consider the following statements with respect to the impact of inflation: 1. Increase in inflation can lead to depreciation in the value of Indian rupee. 2. Rise in inflation rate will likely increase borrowing costs for businesses. 3. A decline in inflation leads to an increase in the savings rate. 4. Inflation may lead to a significant decrease in value of assets with adjustable cash flows. How many of the above given statements are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"Only three","d":"All four"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nInflation is the steady rise of prices for goods and services over a period.\nStatement 1 is correct: Inflation is one of the most important factors that affect the exchange\nrate. Example: Suppose the exchange rate was exactly 1 in the first year. This means that with Rs\n100, one could buy something that was priced at $100 in the US. But suppose the Indian inflation\nis 20% and the US inflation is zero. Then, in the second year, an Indian would need Rs 120 to buy\nthe same item priced at $100, and the rupee’s exchange rate would depreciate to 1.20. Thus, it\nwould lead to the depreciation of Indian rupee.\nStatement 2 is correct: High inflation may lead to higher borrowing costs for businesses and\npeople needing loans and mortgages. Financial markets protect themselves against rising prices\nand increase the cost of borrowing on short and longer-term debt. If the cost of borrowing money\n\nrises, consumers and businesses have less money to spend. As demand falls, economic growth\nslows down.\nStatement 3 is correct: Every rise in prices is affecting your cost of living, leaving a dent in your\nsavings and investments. The reason is, with the rise in inflation, the amount of saving or\ninvestment from income every month may not rise at the same rate. Therefore, the rise in price\nputs extra pressure on your savings and investments. Similarly, decline in inflation rate leads to\nincrease in savings rate as relatively less amount will be spent on consumption.\nStatement 4 is incorrect: Assets with fixed, long-term cash flows tend to perform poorly when\ninflation is rising, since the purchasing power of those future cash flows falls over time.\nConversely, commodities and assets with adjustable cash flows (e.g., property rental income)\ntend to perform better with rising inflation.","topic":"Inflation & Deflation","id":261,"area":"Inflation Dynamics"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-10","qNum":26,"question":"With reference to differences between Disinflation and Deflation, consider the following statements: 1. Deflation means a fall in prices of commodities, while disinflation means a slowdown in the rate of inflation. 2. Deflation will always lead to a decrease in the value of money whereas disinflation will always lead to an increase in the value of money. 3. Compared to disinflation, deflation is good for the financial markets. How many of the above given statements are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct: Deflation means prices are falling and the inflation rate is in the negative,\nwhile disinflation means a slowdown in the rate of inflation while still remaining in the positive.\nDisinflation occurs more commonly than deflation.\nStatement 2 is incorrect: During times of deflation, since the money supply is tightened, there is\nan increase in the value of money, which increases the real value of debt. Since inflation is\npositive during disinflation, the value of money decreases.\nStatement 3 is incorrect: During disinflation Stocks can, and often do, perform well when the\nbonds are likely to deliver above-average returns in a disinflationary scenario since it makes\ncentral banks less likely to raise interest rates and more likely to reduce them. Whereas deflation\nis an extremely destructive condition for the economy and financial markets. During periods of\ndeflation, stock prices are likely to perform poorly.\nImportant Tips\n• Deflation and disinflation refer to two very different conditions with respect to the direction\nand change of general price levels in the economy. Deflation refers to falling prices or in other\nwords, the opposite of inflation (rising prices).\n• Disinflation does not refer to the direction of prices (as inflation and deflation do). It refers to\nthe rate of change. It is a slowdown in the rate of inflation. For example, deflation would be an\ninflation rate of -1 percent, while disinflation would be a change in the inflation rate from 3\npercent one year to 2 percent in the next.","topic":"Inflation & Deflation","id":262,"area":"Inflation Dynamics"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-10","qNum":27,"question":"Which of the following items are included in calculation of both Consumer price index (CPI) and Wholesale price index (WPI) in India? 1. Fuel items 2. Electricity 3. Transportation Services 4. Educational Services 5. Food items Choose the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1, 2 and 5 only","b":"1,2, 3 and 5 only","c":"2,3 and 4 only","d":"2, 4 and 5 only"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nThe WPI is used to measure the change in the overall price of goods before they are sold at retail\nprices. This index measures inflation based on wholesale prices, or the prices of goods before they\nreach consumers.\nOptions 1, 2 and 5 are correct: The major difference between WPI and CPI is that the WPI does\nnot measure the change in the price levels of services, but these are included in the calculation of\nCPI. The other items like the fuel items, electricity and food items are included in the calculation\nof both CPI and WPI.\nOptions 3 and 4 are incorrect: The services are excluded from the calculation of WPI, so\nTransportation services and Education services are not common items in calculation of both CPI\nand WPI.","topic":"Inflation & Deflation","id":263,"area":"Inflation Dynamics"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-10","qNum":28,"question":"Consider the following statements 1. The weightage of food in Consumer Price Index (CPI) is higher than that in Wholesale Price Index (WPI). 2. The WPI does not capture changes in the prices of services, which CPI does. 3. Reserve Bank of India has now adopted WPI as its key measure of inflation and to decide on changing the key policy rates. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 only","c":"3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer\nStatement 1 is correct. The weightage of food in Consumer Price Index (CPI) is higher than that\nin Wholesale Price Index (WPI). The weightage of food in CPI is around 46% in CPI and around\n24% in case of WPI.\nStatement 2 is correct. The WPI does not capture changes in the prices of services, which CPI\ndoes.\nStatement 3 is incorrect. Based on the suggestions of the Urjit Patel committee, in 2014, RBI\nabandoned WPI and adopted CPI as the key measure of inflation to decide on changing key policy\nrates.\nImportant Tips\nWholesale Price Index is a measure of the average change in the prices of goods in the wholesale\nmarket or at the wholesale level. Consumer Price index is the measure of changes in the price\nlevel of the basket of consumer goods and services bought by the household.","topic":"Inflation & Deflation","id":264,"area":"Inflation Dynamics"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-10","qNum":29,"question":"Assertion (A): Deficit financing leads to inflation. Reason (R): It increases money supply as compared to goods and services. In the context of the above which one of the following is correct?","options":{"a":"Both (A) and (R) are true, and (R) is the correct explanation of (A)","b":"Both (A) and (R) are true, but (R) is not the correct explanation of (A)","c":"(A) is true, but (R) is false","d":"(A) is false, but (R) is true"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nAssertion (A) is correct: Deficit financing increases money supply, leading to higher demand for\ngoods and services. If supply doesn’t match demand, inflation occurs due to increased prices.\nReason (R) is correct: Deficit financing involves borrowing and creating new money, which is then\nadded to the existing money supply, leading to an increase in the overall money supply in the\neconomy.\nBoth (A) and (R) are true, and (R) is the correct explanation of (A): When the government engages\nin deficit financing, it increases the money supply in the economy. As a consequence of the\nincreased money supply, people have more money to spend, leading to higher demand for goods\nand services. If the supply of goods and services does not increase proportionately with the\nincreased demand, it results in an increase in prices, causing inflation.","topic":"Inflation & Deflation","id":265,"area":"Inflation Dynamics"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-ECO-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Economy","lot":"ECO-10","qNum":30,"question":"Which among the following are the sources of income in the current account of the Central Government? 1. Corporation Tax 2. Profit from Public Enterprises 3. Sale of National Savings Certificates 4. Loans received from the World Bank 5. Excise duties Select the correct answer from the codes given below:","options":{"a":"1, 2 and 3","b":"1, 3 and 4","c":"3, 4 and 5","d":"1, 2 and 5"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Option d is the correct answer.\nSources of income in the current account of the Central Government include:\n• Corporation Tax: It is a direct tax levied on the income of companies and corporations.\n• Profit from Public Enterprises: Government-owned enterprises contribute to the government’s\nrevenue through profits generated from their operations.\n• Excise duties: These are indirect taxes levied on the production and sale of goods within the\ncountry. Income from National Savings Certificates (Option III) and loans received from the\nWorld Bank (Option IV) are not sources of income in the current account of the Central\nGovernment. The income from National Savings Certificates is a capital receipt, and loans\nreceived from the World Bank are capital transactions that increase liabilities, not income.","topic":"Economy — Misc","id":266,"area":"Inflation Dynamics"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-MH-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Modern History","lot":"MH-10","qNum":1,"question":"Consider the following statements regarding the Underground Movement carried during the Quit India Movement: 1. The Socialist groups called ‘Azad Dastas’ were formed in Nepal to fight the tyranny of British Government. 2. All India Radio (AIR) was started by Congress for secret communication with the public. 3. The underground movement leaders included Biju Patnaik, Chhotu Bhai Puranik and R.P. Goenka. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct: The underground movement grew very strong in Bihar and proved to be a major law\nand order problem for the British during 1942-44. Despite severe repression, several organizations and\ndacoit gangs were formed in different parts of Bihar by 1943. Many of these groups had links with the\nCongress Socialist Party. The Socialist groups called ‘Azad Dastas’ carried out activities in the name of\nCongress. Jayprakash Narayan organized and trained an “Azad Dasta” (Freedom Brigade) in Nepal to\nparalyse the machinery of the British Government and for fighting the tyranny of British rule.\nStatemen 2 is incorrect: After examining its past campaigns, the Congress realized during the Quit India\nMovement that the communication with the public was central to its success. Thus, the idea of an\nunderground radio station was conceived, and Usha Mehta became its voice. Though it was known by many\nnames – the Freedom Radio, the Ghost Radio, the Congress Radio – it was, very simply, the secret anti-\nimperialist voice of the Indian National Congress and almost no one, apart from those involved, knew\nanything certain about its inner workings. In fact, The Congress Radio, which began operations in August\n1942, was set up to counter the British-controlled All India Radio (AIR), often tagged as ‘anti-India Radio’.\nStatement 3 is correct: The main personalities taking up the underground activity were Rammanohar Lohia,\nJayaprakash Narayan, Aruna Asaf Ali, Usha Mehta, Biju Patnaik, Chhotu Bhai Puranik, Achyut Patwardhan,\nSucheta Kripalani and R.P. Goenka.","topic":"Quit India & Independence","id":267,"area":"Quit India & Towards Independence"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-MH-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Modern History","lot":"MH-10","qNum":2,"question":"With reference to the offers made by British under Wavell Plan (1945), consider the following statements: 1. According to the plan, Caste Hindus and Muslims were to have equal representation in Governor General’s executive council. 2. It proposed that all members of the Governor General’s executive council will be Indians except the Viceroy. 3. The plan proposed that veto power of Governor General to bypass the ministerial decisions would be discontinued. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct: Wavell Plan was proposed that the Viceroy’s Executive Council would be immediately\nreconstituted, and the number of its members would be increased. The Plan proposed that both Caste\nHindus and Muslims would have equal representation in governor general’s executive council. The\nLeague wanted all Muslim members to be League nominees because it feared that since the aims of other\nminorities—depressed classes, Sikhs, Christians, etc.—were the same as those of the Congress, this\narrangement would reduce the League to a one-third minority.\n\nStatement 2 and 3 are incorrect: As per Wavell Plan, all the members of the executive council were to be\nIndians except the Viceroy and the Commander-in-chief (not only the Viceroy). It provided for Governor\nGeneral could exercise a veto to bypass the advice of ministers.\nImportant Tips\nOther proposals of the Wavell Plan were:\n(i) The reconstructed Council was to function as an interim Government within the framework of the GOI\nAct, of 1935.\n(ii) The possibilities for negotiations on a new constitution were to be kept open once after the final war\nwas finally won by the Allies.","topic":"Quit India & Independence","id":268,"area":"Quit India & Towards Independence"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-MH-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Modern History","lot":"MH-10","qNum":3,"question":"The Defense of India Act was enforced during the Second World War due to which of the following reasons?","options":{"a":"To enforce restrictions on civil liberties of the common people.","b":"To ensure the public safety and the defense of British India.","c":"To provide compensation for the land acquired for defense purpose.","d":"All of the above"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Option d is the correct answer.\nThe Defense of India Act, 1939 was an Act passed by the Central Legislature in 1939 which effectively declared\nmartial law in India. Although it was enacted on 29 September 1939 it was deemed to come into force on 3\nSeptember 1939, the day when the Second World War began.\nOption a is correct: Even before the declaration of the War, emergency powers had been acquired by the\nCentre in respect of provincial subjects by amending the 1935 Act. Defense of India Act had been enforced\nthe day the War was declared, thus restricting civil liberties of the common people.\nOption b is correct: The act empowered the Viceroy to make rules for the public safety and the defense of\nBritish India. It also provided for punishments in case of any contraventions which included death or\ntransportation for life. The grounds for the punishment were the intent to assist any State at war with His\nMajesty or that of waging war against His Majesty.\nOption c is correct: The act also provided for acquisition of land for defense purposes and provided\ncompensation for the land acquired. It expired six months after the termination of the war and was repealed\nby the Repealing and Amending Act, of 1947.","topic":"Modern History — Misc","id":269,"area":"Quit India & Towards Independence"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-MH-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Modern History","lot":"MH-10","qNum":4,"question":"Which of the following is/are the reasons for Mahatma Gandhi to launch Individual Satyagraha during World War II? 1. To show the discontent towards rising prices of commodities in India. 2. To assert the right of speech of Indians against the war efforts. 3. Mass movement at that time was not conducive as it might turned aggressive. Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"1 and 2 only","c":"2 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nIn reaction to the August Offer, Gandhiji called for a limited ‘Individual Satyagraha’. It was a protest against\nthe British government and its inability to accommodate the demands of Indians.\nStatement 1 is incorrect: Individual Satyagraha was the result of the August offer’s failure in providing a\nsound solution for India’s future political status. The issue of rising prices of commodities because or war\nwas not the reason behind the Individual Satyagraha. Hence the statement 1 is incorrect.\nStatement 2 is correct: The Individual Satyagraha was to affirm the right of speech against the war efforts.\n\nStatement 3 is correct: The radicals and leftists wanted to launch a mass Civil Disobedience Movement, but\nGandhiji insisted on individual satyagraha, as he thought that mass movement might turn aggressive.\nImportant Tips\nThe main aims for launching individual satyagraha were:\n1) To show that nationalist patience towards the political situation of the India at that time was not due\nto weakness of Indians;\n2) To express people’s feeling that they were not interested in the war and that they made no distinction\nbetween Nazism and the double autocracy that ruled India; and\n3) To give another opportunity to the Government to accept Congress’ demands peacefully.","topic":"Indian National Movement","id":270,"area":"Quit India & Towards Independence"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-MH-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Modern History","lot":"MH-10","qNum":5,"question":"Which of the following statements are correct with reference to the Muslim League? 1. During its initial phase, the League was designed to prepare the students for service to the British Raj. 2. The Muslim League observed ‘Day of Deliverance’ in 1939 as a mark of relief that the Congress regime ended in the provinces. 3. One of League’s Prime objectives was to prevent the spread of prejudice against other Indian communities among Muslims. Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 and 3 only","c":"1 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Option d is the correct answer.\nThe All-India Muslim League (popularized as the Muslim League) was a political party established in 1906 in\nBritish India. It was found as an alternative political group to the Indian National Congress. It was created\nwith the aim of representing the interests of Indian Muslims.\nStatement 1 is correct: Initially, the League was designed to prepare students for service to the British\nRaj; however, it later indulged into political activity.\nStatement 2 is correct: The Muslim League observed ‘Day of Deliverance’ on 22 December 1939 when the\nCongress Party members who were part of the Central and provincial governments resigned. The reason\nwas to protest against the Viceroy’s decision to make India a party to the Second World War without duly\nconsulting Indians.\nStatement 3 is correct: All India Muslim League – Objectives\n• To protect Muslims’ political rights and bring them to the attention of the government and to prevent the\nspread of prejudice against other Indian communities among Muslims.\n• To foster feelings of loyalty to the British government among Indian Muslims, and to dispel any\nmisconceptions about the government’s intentions regarding any of its measures.\n• Profiting from and advancing the political rights and interests of India’s Muslims, as well as respectfully\nrepresenting their needs and aspirations to the government.\n• To prevent any feelings of hostility toward other communities among Indian Muslims, without prejudice\nto the League’s objectives.","topic":"Quit India & Independence","id":271,"area":"Quit India & Towards Independence"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-MH-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Modern History","lot":"MH-10","qNum":6,"question":"With reference to events related to the Individual Satyagraha, consider the following statements: 1. The Delhi Chalo Movement was one of the outcomes of the Individual satyagraha movement. 2. The movement became violent when British refused to accept the demand of satyagrahis. 3. Vinobha Bhave was the first Individual Satyagrahi. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is correct: The demand of the satyagraha would be the freedom of speech against the war\nthrough an anti-war declaration. If the government did not arrest the satyagrahi, he or she would not only\nrepeat it but move into villages and start a march towards Delhi, thus precipitating a movement that came\nto be known as the ‘Delhi Chalo Movement.\nStatement 2 is incorrect: The centerpiece of Individual Satyagraha was non-violence which could only be\nachieved by selecting the Satyagrahis. Selected Satyagrahi were chosen having non-violent background like\nAcharya Vinoba Bhave, Pt. Jawaharlal Nehru and Brahma Dutt. This movement never became violent.\nStatement 3 is correct: Nonviolence is set as the centrepiece of Individual Satyagraha. This was done by\ncarefully selecting the Satyagrahis. The first Satyagrahi selected was Acharya Vinoba Bhave, who was sent\nto jail when he spoke against the war. The second Satyagrahi was Jawahar Lal Nehru. The third was Brahma\nDatt, one of the inmates of Gandhi’s Ashram.\nImportant Tips\nIndividual Satyagraha:\nThe very reason for confining the movement to individual participation was that neither Gandhiji nor the\nCongress wished to hamper the War effort, and this could not have been the case in a mass movement.\nAs a result, even the aim of the Satyagraha was a limited one i.e., to disapprove the British claim that India\nsupported the War effort wholeheartedly.\nThe aims of launching individual satyagraha were:\n• to show that nationalist patience was not due to weakness\n• to express people’s feeling that they were not interested in the war and that they made no distinction\nbetween Nazism and the double autocracy that ruled India; and\n• to give another opportunity to the government to accept Congress’ demands peacefully","topic":"Modern History — Misc","id":272,"area":"Quit India & Towards Independence"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-MH-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Modern History","lot":"MH-10","qNum":7,"question":"Consider the following statements regarding the Parallel Government formed in Satara during the Indian Freedom struggle: 1. Under the Parallel Government, an armed militia called Vidyut Vahini was organized in Satara. 2. In Satara, the volunteer corps and village units were formed to run the people’s court. 3. The Parallel Government in Satara was dominated by the kunbi peasants and supported by the Dalits. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nThe Parallel governments were established at Ballia, Tamluk in Midnapore and Satara in Maharashtra.\nStatement 1 is incorrect: Vidyut Vahinis were organised in the city of Tamluk in the Midnapore District of\nWest Bengal. Parallel Government also known as Jatiya Sarkar, was established in Tamluk from December\n1942 to September 1944. The Jatiya Sarkar undertook cyclone relief work, sanctioned grants to schools,\nsupplied paddy from the rich to the poor.\nStatement 2 is correct: The volunteer corps (seba dals) and the village units (tufan dals) were formed\nunder the Parallel Government in Satara. The Seba dals and tufan dals organized the people’s court and\nalso set up village libraries. The Parallel Government in satara was formed from mid-1943 to 1945. The\nparallel Government was known as “Prati Sarkar”. It was organised under leaders like Y.B. Chavan, Nana\nPatil, etc. The Prati Sarkar undertook prohibition campaigns and Gandhi marriages. Prohibition campaigns\nand Gandhi marriages.\n\nStatement 3 is correct: The Parallel Government in satara was dominated by the kunbi peasants and\nsupported by the Dalits. The Satara Prati Sarkar functioned till the elections of 1946, despite government\nrepression.","topic":"Modern History — Misc","id":273,"area":"Quit India & Towards Independence"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-MH-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Modern History","lot":"MH-10","qNum":8,"question":"Consider the following statements regarding the features of Quit India Movement: 1. The movement endorsed the defiance of government authority. 2. The Quit India Movement was accommodative of violence directed against the state. 3. Anybody who believed in the complete independence of the country could join it. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nThe Quit India Movement, 1942 was less ambiguous in its declared objectives. It was launched to ensure the\ncomplete withdrawal of British power from India. The projected struggle had four main features:\nStatement 1 is correct: The movement was to be marked by total defiance of government authority.\nStatement 2 is correct: It was accommodative of violence directed against the state.\nStatement 3 is correct: It aimed at destroying British rule in India. Unlike earlier movements when Gandhi\nhad asked trained satyagrahis to join the movements, anybody who believed in the complete independence\nof the country could join it now. Students were urged to play a prominent part and to lead the movement.","topic":"Quit India & Independence","id":274,"area":"Quit India & Towards Independence"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-MH-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Modern History","lot":"MH-10","qNum":9,"question":"Consider the following statement regarding Gandhiji’s specific instructions for different sections of the people during the ‘Quit India Movement of 1942’: 1. Government servants should openly declare their allegiance to the Congress. 2. Soldiers were asked to refuse to fire on our own people. 3. The Princes were asked to ‘accept the sovereignty of their own people. 4. Peasants should refuse to pay the land revenue to any of the Zamindars. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"Only three","d":"All four"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nMahatma Gandhi planned an all-out campaign (Quit India Movement in 1942) to compel British withdrawal\nfrom India, after the failure of the Cripps Mission to reach a compromise. At the historic August meeting at\nGowalia Tank in Bombay, Gandhi proclaimed his mantra—’do or die’.\nGandhiji’s speech also contained specific instructions for different sections of the people.\n1. Government servants would not yet be asked to resign, but they should openly declare their allegiance\nto the Congress. (Hence Statement 1 is correct)\n2. Soldiers were also not to leave their posts, but they were to ‘refuse to fire on our own people. (Hence\nStatement 2 is correct)\n3. The Princes were asked to ‘accept the sovereignty of your own people, instead of paying homage to a\nforeign power.’ (Hence Statement 3 is correct)\n4. The people of the Princely States were asked to declare that they were part of the Indian nation and that\nthey would accept the leadership of the princes, if the latter cast their lot with the People, but not otherwise.’\n5. Students were to give up studies if they were sure they could continue to remain firm independence was\nachieved.\n\n6. Peasants ‘who have the courage, and are prepared to risk their all’ should refuse to pay the land revenue.\n7. Tenants were told that ‘the Congress holds that the land belongs to those who work on it and to no one\nelse.’\n8. If a zamindar does not exploit the ryots to help the Britishers, his portion of the revenue, which may be\nsettled by mutual agreement, should be given to him. But if a zamindar wants to side with the Government,\nno tax should be paid to him.’ (Hence Statement 4 is incorrect)\nThese instructions were not actually issued because of the preventive arrests, but they do make Gandhiji’s\nintentions clear.","topic":"Quit India & Independence","id":275,"area":"Quit India & Towards Independence"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-MH-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Modern History","lot":"MH-10","qNum":10,"question":"Consider the following statements with respect to the Indian National Army (INA) trials: 1. Congress adopted a resolution in the Bombay session in support of the Indian National Army’s cause. 2. Prem Kumar Sehgal, Shah Nawaz khan and Gurbaksh Singh Dhillon were the first set of INA prisoners to face the trial. 3. Following the public protest, British reduced the death sentence of INA prisoners to deportation for life. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nThe Indian National Army trials also known as the INA trials and the Red Fort trials was the British Indian\ntrial of a number of officers of the Indian National Army (INA) between 1945 and 1946, on various charges of\ntreason, torture, murder and abetment to murder. The INA prisoners were the ones who fought with\nJapanese troops during World War II in Burma.\nStatement 1 is correct: At the first post-War Congress session in September 1945 at Bombay, a strong\nresolution was adopted declaring Congress support for the INA cause. Those who supported the INA cause\nin varying degrees, apart from the Congress, included the Muslim League, Communist Party, Unionists,\nAkalis, Justice Party, Ahrars in Rawalpindi, Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh, Hindu Mahasabha and the Sikh\nLeague.\nStatement 2 is correct: British held the first trial at the Red Fort in Delhi in November 1945 and putting on\ndock together a Hindu, Prem Kumar Sehgal, a Muslim, Shah Nawaz Khan, and a Sikh, Gurbaksh Singh Dhillon.\nThese three prisoners were the first to face the trials.\nStatement 3 is incorrect: The British never sentenced any prisoners to death. The actual punishment for\nShah Nawaz Khan, Gurubaksh Singh Dhillon and Prem Sahgal were to be dismissed from service and handed\ntransportation for life. However, this punishment too was remitted later.","topic":"Quit India & Independence","id":276,"area":"Quit India & Towards Independence"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-MH-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Modern History","lot":"MH-10","qNum":11,"question":"With reference to the Royal Indian Navy (RIN) revolt, consider the following statements: 1. Only the members of the armed forces participated in the revolt. 2. It demanded withdrawal of Indian troops from Indonesia. 3. Congress gave its official support to the revolt. 4. Communists and socialist played a major role in guiding the mutiny. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"Only three","d":"All four"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\n\nStatement 1 is incorrect: Royal Indian Navy revolt is not limited to armed forces alone. Students had\nboycotted classes, strikes and processions were organised to express sympathy with the students and the\nratings and to condemn official repression.\nStatement 2 is correct: The demands of RIN revolt included the release of INA (Indian National Army)\npersonnel and other political prisoners; withdrawal of Indian troops from Indonesia; and the acceptance\nof Indian officers only as superiors.\nStatement 3 is incorrect: While the congress lauded the spirit of the people it did not officially support\nthese struggles as it felt their tactics and timing were wrong. It was evident for congress that the\nGovernment would be able to repress.\nStatement 4 is correct: Royal Indian Navy agitation was led majorly by the communists, socialist and\nforward blocists. The congress role was majorly diffusing the revolutionary situation prompted by the fear\nthat the situation would go out of its control or by the concern that disciplined armed forces were vital in\nfree India that the party would soon rule.","topic":"Indian National Movement","id":277,"area":"Quit India & Towards Independence"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-MH-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Modern History","lot":"MH-10","qNum":12,"question":"With reference to the Sapru Committee of 1945, consider the following statements: 1. The Committee rejected the Muslim league’s demand for Pakistan. 2. It operated under the mandate of Indian National Congress. 3. The Committee recommended the separate electorate for Muslims. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nThe constitutional proposals of the Sapru committee were commonly referred to as Sapru Committee\nReport which was published in 1945.\nStatement 1 is correct. The Report rejected the Muslim league’s demand for Pakistan as it was not convinced\nthat a separate state would be beneficial to any community and division of India will endanger the peace and\ngrowth of the country.\nStatement 2 is incorrect. The Committee consisted of 30 members who are experts of public affairs and did\nnot operate under the mandate of any political party.\nStatement 3 is incorrect. The Committee rejected the separate electorate for Muslims and proposed joint\nelections with reservation of seats.","topic":"Quit India & Independence","id":278,"area":"Quit India & Towards Independence"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-MH-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Modern History","lot":"MH-10","qNum":13,"question":"With reference to the Indian provincial elections of 1946, consider the following statements: 1. The Congress failed to get majority in any of the provinces which were being claimed by the Muslim League as part of a separate nation i.e. Pakistan. 2. The Muslim league got the majority of Muslim votes. 3. A Unionist-Muslim League-Akali coalition under Khizr Hayat Khan assumed power in Punjab. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nIn July 1945, Labour Party formed the government in Britain. Clement Attlee took over as the new Prime\nMinister and Pethick Lawrence as the new secretary of state for India. In August 1945, elections to central\nand provincial assemblies were announced.\n\nPerformance of the Congress\n(a) It got 91 per cent of non-Muslim votes. It captured 57 out of 102 seats in the Central Assembly.\n(b) In the provincial elections, it got a majority in most provinces except in Bengal, Sindh and Punjab.\n(c) The Congress majority provinces included the North West Frontier Province (NWFP) and Assam which\nwere being claimed for Pakistan. Hence, statement 1 is not correct.\nPerformance of the Muslim League\n1) It got 86.6 per cent of the Muslim votes.\n2) It captured the 30 reserved seats in the Central Assembly. In the provincial elections, it got a majority in\nBengal and Sindh.\n3) Unlike in 1937, now the League clearly established itself as the dominant party among Muslims. Hence,\nstatement 2 is correct.\n4) In Punjab, a Unionist-Congress-Akali coalition under Khizr Hayat Khan assumed power. Hence, statement\n3 is incorrect.","topic":"Quit India & Independence","id":279,"area":"Quit India & Towards Independence"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-MH-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Modern History","lot":"MH-10","qNum":14,"question":"With reference to Subhash Chandra Bose and Indian National Army (INA), consider the following statements: 1. Subhash Chandra Bose opposed the Quit India Movement as yet another ineffective nonviolent struggle. 2. The defeat of British by INA during Imphal campaign encouraged its members to liberate India from British. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Option d is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is incorrect: Subhas Chandra Bose considered the Indian National Army movement to be\nnever opposed to but rather complementary to the Quit India Movement. He described the Quit India\nMovement as “India’s epic struggle” and kept the outside world informed about all events in India and tried\nto secure sympathy and help for India’s struggle for freedom.\nStatement 2 is incorrect: Imphal Campaign was a failure. One INA battalion commanded by Shah Nawaz\nwas allowed to accompany the Japanese army to the Indo-Burma front and participate in the Imphal\ncampaign. But the discriminatory treatment meted out to Indians which included being denied rations,\narms and being made to do menial work for the Japanese army, completely demoralised the members. The\nfailure of the Imphal campaign and the following arrest of INA members by the British culminated in the\nfamous INA trial in India.","topic":"Quit India & Independence","id":280,"area":"Quit India & Towards Independence"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-MH-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Modern History","lot":"MH-10","qNum":15,"question":"The National Defence Council was set up as a result of which of the following events?","options":{"a":"Indian National Session of Haripura","b":"Cripps Mission","c":"August Offer","d":"Indian National Session of Faizpur"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nOn 8 August 1940, the Viceroy Lord Linlithgow made a proposal called the August Offer which expanded the\nExecutive Council to include more Indians. The National Defence Council was set up with purely advisory\nfunctions. The National Defence Council’s main purpose was to bring the war effort in the Provinces and\nStates, as well as in the ranks of commerce, industry and labour, into more effective touch with the Central\nGovernment.","topic":"Indian National Movement","id":281,"area":"Quit India & Towards Independence"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-MH-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Modern History","lot":"MH-10","qNum":16,"question":"With reference to interim government of 1946, consider the following statements: 1. Muslim league members joined the interim government with the condition of not giving up with their ‘direct action’ program. 2. It functioned according to the provision of Government of India Act of 1919. 3. Jawaharlal Nehru was the President of the Viceroys Executive Council. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nOn, September 1946 interim government was constituted as pure congress government. Wavell later\nbrought the Muslim League into the Interim Government on October 26, 1946.\nStatement 1 is correct: Muslim league decided to join the interim government without surrendering\n‘direct action’.\nEarlier, the interim government consisted only congress members. On October 26, 1946 the League was\nallowed to join:\n• without giving up the ‘direct action’\n• despite its rejection of the long-term and short-term plans put forward by cabinet mission.\n• And despite its insistence on compulsory grouping and decisions being taken by a majority vote given by\nsection of population for the whole region.\nStatement 2 is correct: It functioned under the provision of government of India act 1919. A federal scheme\nprovided under the Government of India Act of 1935, was not implemented due to the opposition from India’s\nprincely states. As a result, the interim government functioned according to the older Government of India\nAct of 1919.\nStatement 3 is incorrect: The members of the interim Government were members of the Viceroy’s Executive\nCouncil. The Viceroy continued to be the head of the Council. But, Jawaharlal Nehru was designated as the\nVice- President of the Council.","topic":"Quit India & Independence","id":282,"area":"Quit India & Towards Independence"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-MH-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Modern History","lot":"MH-10","qNum":17,"question":"With reference to Congress’s stand towards Cabinet Mission proposals, consider the following statements: 1. Congress interpreted Cabinet Mission proposals as mandatory grouping of provincial assemblies into three sections. 2. Congress all together rejected the proposals under Cabinet mission. 3. Congress objected to the proposal that provinces need to wait till the first general elections to come out of a group. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Option a is the correct answer.\nThe Cabinet Mission reached Delhi on March 24, 1946. It was constituted to provide solution on the issues:\n(i) interim government.\n(ii) principles and procedures for framing a new constitution giving freedom to India\nStatement 1 is incorrect: Each party Muslim league as well as congress interpreted cabinet mission\ndifferently. To the Congress, the Cabinet Mission Plan was interpreted as:\n• The grouping of existing provincial assemblies’ intro three section was optional. Hence, rejecting the plan\nof Pakistan.\n\n• one constituent assembly was envisaged; and the League no longer had a veto\nStatement 2 is incorrect: Congress as well as Muslim league accepted the long-term plan put forward by\nthe Cabinet mission. The long-term plan includes:\n• After the first general elections, a province would be free to come out of a group and after 10 years, a\nprovince would be free to call for a reconsideration of the group or the union constitution.\n• Meanwhile, an interim government would be formed from the constituent assembly\nStatement 3 is correct. Congress objected to the plan that provinces need to wait till first general\nelections to come out of a group. They proposed that provinces should have the option of not joining a\ngroup in the first place.","topic":"Quit India & Independence","id":283,"area":"Quit India & Towards Independence"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-MH-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Modern History","lot":"MH-10","qNum":18,"question":"With reference to the interim Government of 1946, consider the following statements: 1. It was formed from the Constituent Assembly which was elected in August 1946. 2. Dr Babasaheb Ambedkar headed the portfolio of Law in the Interim government. 3. It appointed a committee to advise the government on nationalizing the armed forces. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nOn 2nd September 1946, the Interim Government of India was formed to oversee the transition of the\ncountry from a British colony to an independent republic.\nStatement 1 is correct: The Interim Government was formed from the Constituent Assembly which was\nelected in August 1946.The election to the Constituent Assembly was not direct and representatives were\nelected by the provincial assemblies.\nStatement 2 is incorrect. Dr. Babasaheb Ambedkar was not part of the interim government formed in 1946.\nJogendra Nath Mandal of Muslim League headed the portfolio of Law in interim government.\nStatement 3 is correct: In November 1946, India ratified the Convention on International Civil Aviation. In\nthe same month, a committee was appointed to advise the government on nationalizing the armed forces.\nImportant Tips\nInterim Government:\n• The Interim Government was formed as a provisional government between an imperial structure and a\ndemocratic structure.\n• It lasted till 15th August 1947 when India became independent and was partitioned into India and\nPakistan.\nIn these elections, the Indian National Congress (INC) won around 69% of the seats and had a majority.\nThe Congress Party won 208 seats and the Muslim League won 73 seats.\n• In the Interim Government, the Viceroy’s Executive Council was equivalent to the position of the Council\nof Ministers acted as the executive.\n• Even though the Muslim League refused to be a part of the Interim Government, insisting on their\ndemand for a separate nation, it eventually became a part of it. In Muhammad Ali Jinnah’s words, the\nLeague was “going into the Interim Government to get a foothold to fight for the cherished goal of\nPakistan.","topic":"Quit India & Independence","id":284,"area":"Quit India & Towards Independence"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-MH-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Modern History","lot":"MH-10","qNum":19,"question":"With reference to the Muslim League’s Lahore Resolution of 1940, consider the following statements: 1. One of the demands was the creation of ‘Pakistan’ as a separate nation for Muslims. 2. The resolution was drafted by Sikandar Hayat Khan. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is incorrect: The 1940 resolution of Muslim league also called as Lahore resolution never\nmentioned a word Pakistan. On 23 March 1940, the League moved a resolution demanding a measure of\nautonomy for the Muslim majority areas of the subcontinent. This ambiguous resolution never mentioned\npartition or Pakistan.\nStatement 2 is correct: Sikandar Hayat Khan, Punjab Premier and leader of the Unionist Party drafted\nthe Lahore resolution in 1940. He declared in a Punjab assembly speech on 1 March 1941 that he was opposed\nto a Pakistan that would mean “Muslim Raj here and Hindu Raj elsewhere”. He reiterated his plea for a loose\n(united)confederation with considerable autonomy for the confederating units.","topic":"Quit India & Independence","id":285,"area":"Quit India & Towards Independence"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-MH-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Modern History","lot":"MH-10","qNum":20,"question":"With reference to the Unionist party, consider the following statements: 1. Sir Syed Ahmed Khan was one of the prominent members of this party. 2. The party mainly defended the rights of landless labourers in Punjab against the landlords. 3. The party supported Muslim League’s demand for partition of India. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Option d is the correct answer.\nStatement 1 is incorrect: Sir Syed Ahmed Khan is not a member of the Unionist party. Sir Sikandar Hayat\nKhan, Sir Fazli Husain, Sir Shahab-ud-Din, Muhammad Hussain Shah and Sir Chhotu Ram were all members\nof the party. Although a majority of Unionists were Muslims, a large number of Hindus and Sikhs also\nsupported and participated in the Unionist Party.\nStatement 2 is incorrect: Unionists party mainly represented the interest of landlords (and not the\nlandless labourers). It was a political party representing landholders- Sikhs, Muslims and Hindus in the\nPunjab.\nStatement 3 is incorrect: Unionist Party leader Malik Khizr Hayat Khan Tiwana played a key role in limiting\nthe Muslim League’s influence in Punjab Province during 1942 to 1947. He strongly opposed the Muslim\nLeague’s demand for a separate Pakistan and presented his own vision of united Punjab within a\ndecentralised Federal India.","topic":"Quit India & Independence","id":286,"area":"Quit India & Towards Independence"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-MH-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Modern History","lot":"MH-10","qNum":21,"question":"Which of the following statements is/are incorrect features of the elections of 1946 in British India? 1. The election campaign of the Congress was strongly anti-Muslim League in character. 2. It was the first election in British India fought on the basis of universal adult franchise. Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nIn July 1945, Labour Party formed the government in Britain. Clement Attlee took over as the new Prime\nMinister and Pethick Lawrence as the new secretary of state for India. In August 1945, elections to central\nand provincial assemblies were announced.\n\nStatement 1 is incorrect: The election campaign of the Congress was anti-British in its thrust. Congress\nslogans were “Release the misguided patriots” of the Indian National Army and “punish the guilty” officials\nwho committed excesses in 1942. It was not anti-League in its tenor despite the elections being fought by\nthe League on the issue of Pakistan.\nStatement 2 is incorrect: The franchise was very limited as for the provinces, less than 10 per cent of the\npopulation could vote and for the Central Assembly, less than 1 per cent of the population was eligible.","topic":"Quit India & Independence","id":287,"area":"Quit India & Towards Independence"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-MH-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Modern History","lot":"MH-10","qNum":22,"question":"Consider the following pairs regarding different sessions of Indian National Congress and their important events during the Freedom Struggle of India: Congress session/ Meeting Important event 1. Ramgarh, 1940 Congress demanded complete independence 2. Wardha, 1939 Formation of All India Youth Congress 3. Faizpur, 1936 Congress session held in a village for the first time How many of the pairs given above are correctly matched?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nPair 1 is correct. The Ramgarh session of the Congress was held in March 1940 with Maulana Abul Kalam\nAzad in the president’s chair. In Ramgarh session Congress demanded complete independence. All members\nagreed that a battle must be waged but there was disagreement over the form. Jawaharlal Nehru reiterated\nthat complete independence for India must be a precondition for Congress support to the British war\neffort. The Congress finally declared at the session that the people of India would accept nothing short of\ncomplete independence. Indian freedom could not be in the form of dominion or any other status within\nthe imperial structure.\nPair 2 is incorrect. Formation of All India Youth Congress was held at Calcutta session of congress in 1928\npresided by Motilal Nehru. At Wardha, the Congress Working Committee passed a resolution which\ncondemned Fascist aggression. It said that India could not be party to a war being fought, on the face of it,\nfor democratic freedom, while that freedom was being denied to India.\nPair 3 is correct. Faizpur session was held in a village for the first time in India. The Fiftieth (50th) Session\nof the Indian National Congress was held on 27 and 28 December 1936 at Faizpur, a village on the outskirts\nof Yawal Taluka of Jalgaon District of Bombay Presidency (Maharashtra). A large number of peasants\nparticipated in the session. The Faizpur Session was important for the Congress which had been raising\ndemands for the welfare of the peasants and struggled for them. The Faizpur Session was also important\nbecause it was presided over by Jawaharlal Nehru who was at his peak of influence in the Congress.","topic":"Modern History — Misc","id":288,"area":"Quit India & Towards Independence"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-MH-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Modern History","lot":"MH-10","qNum":23,"question":"A series of events unfolded after British Government of India declared India’s support for the World War 2 without consulting Indian opinion. In this context, arrange the following events in the correct chronological order: 1. Japan occupies Rangoon 2. August Offer proposed by the British government 3. Resignation of Congress Ministeries 4. Launch of Individual Satyagraha Which one of the following indicates the correct chronological order of the events in modern Indian history?","options":{"a":"1-3-2-4","b":"3-2-4-1","c":"1-2-3-4","d":"3-2-1-4"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nOn September 1, 1939, Germany attacked Poland—the action that led to the Second World War. On\nSeptember 3, 1939, Britain declared war against Germany and the British Government of India declared\nIndia’s support for the war without consulting Indian opinion. This culminated into the events given below.\nThe chronology of these historical events are as follows:\nEvent 3: The Congress Ministries resigned office in November 1939 on the ground that the Viceroy on its\nown had made India a participant in the imperialist war without consulting the Congress.\nEvent 2: August Offer (1940): The August Offer was a proposal made by the British government on August\n8, 1940, during World War II, to give India greater self-governance, including the right to draft its own\nconstitution, in exchange for Indian support for the war effort.\nEvent 4: Individual Satyagraha: Towards the end of 1940, the Congress once again asked Gandhi to take\ncommand. Gandhiji decided to initiate a limited satyagraha on an individual basis by a few selected\nindividuals in every locality. The movement started on 17th October 1940. The first Satyagrahi selected was\nAcharya Vinoba Bhave, who was sent to jail when he spoke against the war.\nEvent 1: In 1942, Japan invaded Rangoon (Burma) and nominally declared the colony independent as the State\nof Burma on 17 May 1942.","topic":"Modern History — Misc","id":289,"area":"Quit India & Towards Independence"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-MH-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Modern History","lot":"MH-10","qNum":24,"question":"Which of the following can be said to be the correct reasons for the failure of Cripps Proposal of 1942? 1. The proposal made it mandatory for independent India to join the organization of Commonwealth. 2. There was no representation of the princely states in the constituent assembly to be formed. 3. The provision of the right to provinces to secede was against national unity. 4. There was no plan for immediate transfer of power into Indian hands. Select the correct answer using the codes given below:","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"3 and 4 only","c":"1 and 4 only","d":"2, 3 and 4 only"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nIn March 1942, a mission headed by Stafford Cripps was sent to India with constitutional proposals to seek\nIndian support for the war. Stafford Cripps was a left-wing Labourite, the leader of the House of Commons,\nand a member of the British War Cabinet who had actively supported the Indian national movement.\nStatement 1 is incorrect: Cripps Mission proposed that Indian Union with a dominion status would be set\nup; it would be free to decide its relations with the Commonwealth and free to participate in the United\nNations and other international bodies. Hence, Free India could withdraw from the Commonwealth.\nTherefore, it was not the reason for the failure of Cripps Mission.\nStatement 2 is incorrect: The Congress objected to the proposal of representation of the princely states\nby nominees and not by elected representatives.\nStatement 3 is correct: The provision of the right to provinces to secede went against the principle of\nnational unity, which was an important demand of the Indian National Congress. Therefore, this can also\nbe considered a reason for the failure of the Cripps proposal.\nStatement 4 is correct: The immediate transfer of power into Indian hands was not explicitly mentioned\nin the Cripps proposal. However, it was implied that the transfer of power would be gradual, which was not\nacceptable to the Indian National Congress.\nImportant Tips\nThe main proposals of the Crips mission were as follows:\n1. An Indian Union with a dominion status would be set up; it would be free to decide its relations with\nthe Commonwealth and free to participate in the United Nations and other international bodies.\n2. After the end of the war, a constituent assembly would be convened to frame a new constitution.\nMembers of this assembly would be partly elected by the provincial assemblies through proportional\nrepresentation and partly nominated by the princes.\n\n3. The British government would accept the new constitution subject to two conditions:\na) any province not willing to join the Union could have a separate constitution and form a separate Union,\nand\nb) the new constitution-making body and the British government would negotiate a treaty to aff ect the\ntransfer of power and to safeguard racial and religious minorities.\n4. In the meantime, defence of India would remain in British hands and the governor general’s powers\nwould remain intact.","topic":"Indian National Movement","id":290,"area":"Quit India & Towards Independence"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-MH-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Modern History","lot":"MH-10","qNum":25,"question":"What were the conditions laid down byIndian National Congress to cooperate with the British government, to defend Indian territory in the midst of Japan’s aggressiveactions in 1941? 1. Establishment of rule of people in the princely states. 2. Full independence to be given after the war. 3. No bifurcation of Indian Union in any scenario. 4. Substance of power be transferred immediately. Select the correct answer using the codes given below:","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"1, 3 and 4 only","c":"2 and 4 only","d":"2, 3 and 4 only"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nOption 2 and 4 are correct: The Congress leaders, released in December 1941, in the midst of Japan’s\naggressive actions, were anxious to defend Indian territory and go to the aid of the Allies. The Congress\nWorking Committee passed a resolution offering to cooperate with the government in the defence of India,\nif:\na) full independence was given after the war, and\nb) substance of power was transferred immediately.\nOption 1 and 3 are incorrect: Establishment of the rule of people in the princely states and no bifurcation\nof Indian Union in any scenario were not explicitly mentioned as one of the conditions by the Indian\nNational Congress during World War II.","topic":"Modern History — Misc","id":291,"area":"Quit India & Towards Independence"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-MH-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Modern History","lot":"MH-10","qNum":26,"question":"With reference to ‘August Offer’, consider the following statements: 1. It provided for expansion of viceroy’s executive council with majority of Indians. 2. It proposed that no future constitution to be adopted without the consent of minorities. 3. Indian National Congress rejected the offer as it did not offer complete independence to India. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nThe August Offer was a proposal made by the British government in August 1940, during World War II, as a\nresponse to the growing demands for Indian independence. The offer was made by the British Prime\nMinister, Winston Churchill, in a speech broadcasted to the Indian people.\nStatement 1 is correct: The August Offer proposed to expand the Viceroy’s Executive Council and to\ninclude more Indians in the council, with a majority of Indians. This was seen as a significant step towards\nIndian participation in the governance of the country.\nStatement 2 is correct: The August Offer proposed a constitution to be framed mainly by Indians. Also, it\nproposed that no future constitution to be adopted without the consent of minorities. The Muslim League\n\nwelcomed the veto assurance given to the League, and reiterated its position that partition was the only\nsolution to the deadlock.\nStatement 3 is correct: The Indian National Congress rejected the August Offer as it did not offer complete\nindependence to India. The Congress demanded that India be granted complete independence immediately\nand that there should be no delay in the transfer of power from the British to the Indian people.","topic":"Modern History — Misc","id":292,"area":"Quit India & Towards Independence"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-MH-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Modern History","lot":"MH-10","qNum":27,"question":"With reference to ‘Forward Bloc’, consider the following statements: 1. It was established in 1939 within the framework of Indian National Congress. 2. H. V Kamath became the first general secretary of the bloc. 3. The ideology of the bloc was influenced by socialism and anti-imperialism. 4. The bloc was dismantled after the passage of Indian Independence Act of 1947. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"Only three","d":"All four"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\nThe Forward Bloc was a political party formed within the Indian National Congress in 1939 by Subhas\nChandra Bose, who was then the President of the Congress. Bose formed the Forward Bloc in protest against\nthe policies of the Congress leadership, particularly their opposition to direct action to achieve Indian\nindependence.\nStatement 1 is correct: The Forward Bloc was established within the framework of the Indian National\nCongress in 1939 by Subhas Chandra Bose. Bose formed the Forward Bloc in protest against the policies of\nthe Congress leadership, particularly their opposition to direct action to achieve Indian independence.\nStatement 2 is correct: H. V. Kamath, a prominent journalist and politician, was one of the founding\nmembers of the Forward Bloc and became its first general secretary. Bose was elected as its first president.\nStatement 3 is correct: Bose, after resigning from the post of Congress president in April 1939, had decided\nto form a bloc within the party to consolidate Left and socialistminded leaders under one platform. The\nideology of the Forward Bloc was based on socialism and anti-imperialism. The party aimed to achieve\ncomplete independence for India through revolutionary means, including mass mobilization and civil\ndisobedience. The party also advocated for the rights of workers, peasants, and other marginalized sections\nof society.\nStatement 4 is incorrect: The Forward Bloc was not dismantled after the passage of the Indian\nIndependence Act of 1947. Although the party faced many challenges, including the arrest and imprisonment\nof many of its leaders, it continued to exist as a separate political entity even after India’s independence in\n1947. The party was later renamed as All India Forward Bloc (AIFB) — a socialist, political organisation. Over\nthe years, the AIFB became a constituent of the CPI(M)-led Left Front, losing its independent identity.\nCurrently, the AIFB has just a handful of panchayat members in some of the pockets of West Bengal.","topic":"Modern History — Misc","id":293,"area":"Quit India & Towards Independence"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-MH-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Modern History","lot":"MH-10","qNum":28,"question":"The Plan of Cripps Mission was different from other constitutional schemes proposed under British rule because:","options":{"a":"for the first time, the mission explicitly mentioned that the goal of the British is to establish a responsible government in India.","b":"the mission recognised Pakistan as a Separate nation.","c":"the mission promised Indians the sole right to make their own Constitution.","d":"the mission promised complete independence for India in return for its support in World War II."},"answer":"c","explanation":"Option c is the correct answer.\n\nThe British Government in 1942 sent a mission headed by Stafford Cripps (known as Cripps Mission) to\nIndia with constitutional proposals to seek Indian support for the war. Stafford Cripps was a left-wing\nLabourite, the leader of the House of Commons and a member of the British War Cabinet who had actively\nsupported the Indian national movement.\nOption a is incorrect: Even before the Cripps Mission, 1942, the August Declaration of 1917 for the first time\nexplicitly stated that the goal of the British is to establish a responsible government in India. The declaration\nwas announced by the Secretary of State for India, Edwin Samuel Montagu in August 1917. The declaration\nstated that an increasing participation of Indians in every branch of administration and gradual development\nof self-governing institutions for progressive realisation of responsible government in India as an integral\npart of the British Empire.\nOption b is incorrect: The Cripps Mission did not recognise Pakistan as a separate nation. The Muslim\nLeague rejected the Cripps Mission 1942 because the mission did not recognize Pakistan and presented the\nidea of a single Indian Union. However, the mission provided an option to Provinces to have a separate\nconstitution which was considered a blueprint for India’s partition.\nOption c is correct: It is true that the Cripps Mission promised Indians the sole right to make their own\nconstitution. Although the British acknowledged India’s demand for a Constituent Assembly in 1940 (August\noffer) itself, it was the Cripps mission which granted Indians the sole right to frame their own constitution\nby promising party elected and partly nominated (by Princely states) Constitutional Assembly for India.\nHence it is correct to say that the Cripps Mission granted Indians the sole right to frame their own\nconstitution.\nOption d is incorrect: The Cripps Mission did not promise complete Independence for India after World\nWar II, rather it promised dominion status to India. The Congress rejected Cripps Mission because of the\noffer of dominion status by the British Government, instead of a provision for complete independence.","topic":"Indian National Movement","id":294,"area":"Quit India & Towards Independence"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-MH-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Modern History","lot":"MH-10","qNum":29,"question":"Which of the following statements is/are correct with respect to the “Quit India Resolution”? 1. The resolution was first proposed by Yusuf Meherally, a socialist and trade unionist. 2. The resolution stated that the Quit India Movement was a ‘Leaderless Movement’. 3. The resolution proposed to form a provisional Government of India after British withdrawal. Select the correct answer using the codes given below:","options":{"a":"1 and 3 only","b":"2 only","c":"2 and 3 only","d":"3 only"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Option d is the correct answer.\nAfter the failure of the Cripps Mission, the advances of the Japanese in South-East Asia and the general\nfrustration with the British in India, Gandhiji decided to utilise this opportunity to launch a national\nmovement which called for a voluntary British withdrawal from India. The movement is known famously as\nQuit India movement.\nStatement 1 is incorrect: The Quit India resolution was proposed by Jawaharlal Nehru and seconded by\nSardar Patel and was ratified at the Congress meeting at Gowalia Tank, Bombay, on August 8, 1942. Yusuf\nMeherally, a socialist and trade unionist and Mayor of Mumbai, coined the slogan Quit India.\nStatement 2 is incorrect: The Quit India resolution accepted Gandhi as the leader of the struggle, thus the\nresolution proposed the Quit India movement as leaderless movement is not correct. On 9 August 1942,\nGandhi, members of the Congress Working Committee and other Congress leaders were arrested by the\nBritish Government under the Defence of India Rules. People took their movement in their own hands and\ndevised a freedom struggle in their own ways.\nStatement 3 is correct: It is true that the Quit India resolution proposed to form a Provisional Government\nof India after British withdrawal. Further the resolution declared a commitment of free India to defend\nitself against all types of fascism and imperialism.","topic":"Quit India & Independence","id":295,"area":"Quit India & Towards Independence"},{"source":"Prelims-Sprint-2026-MH-LOT-10-Objective-Sol","subject":"Modern History","lot":"MH-10","qNum":30,"question":"With reference Krishak Praja Party (KPP), consider the following statements: 1. The party was founded by Fazlul Huq. 2. The party tried to defend the rights of landless peasants in Bengal Province. 3. The party formed a coalition Government with Indian National Congress in Bengal after the 1937 elections. How many of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option b is the correct answer.\nKrishak Praja Party (KPP) was a major political party with considerable influence during the late 1930s and\nearly 1940s in Bengal province (modern West Bengal & Bangladesh). KPP was founded in 1936 as a separate\nparty by disassociating itself from Nikhil Banga Praja Samiti (All Bengal Tenants’ Association).\nStatement 1 is correct: The Nikhil Banga Praja Samiti was formed in 1929 with Sir Abdur Rahim as its\npresident and Ak Fazlul Huq as one of the vice presidents. Following the rivalries between West Bengal\ngroup led by Khan Bahadur and East Bengal group led by Fazlul Huq in Nikhil Banga Praja party, Fazlul Huq\nestablished the Krishak Praja Party (KPP) at Dhaka in 1936.\nStatement 2 is correct: The Krishak Praja Party (KPP) tried to defend the rights of landless peasants\nagainst landholders in Bengal province. Further the KPP programme included abolition of the zamindari\nsystem, making peasants the absolute proprietors of land, reduction of rent rate etc. Due to the non-\ncommunal approach of Fazlul Huq, he commanded support from the scheduled caste Hindu peasantry as\nwell in Bengal province.\nStatement 3 is incorrect: The Krishak Praja Party election manifesto for Bengal legislative election in 1937\nwas Dal- Bhat (pulse and rice) for all. KPP emerged as the third biggest party after Congress and Muslim\nleague. The KPP formed a coalition ministry with the support and participation of the Muslim League (not\nIndian National Congress) and some other smaller groups and independent members.","topic":"Modern History — Misc","id":296,"area":"Quit India & Towards Independence"},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Inflation & Deflation","lot":"CA-2026","page":5,"marker":"Prelims 2022","qNum":3,"question":"With reference to the Indian economy, what are the advantages of \"Inflation- Indexed Bonds (IIBs)\"? 1. Government can reduce the coupon rates on its borrowing by way of IIBs. 2. IIBs provide protection to the investors from uncertainty regarding inflation. 3. The interest received as well as capital gains on IIBs are not taxable. Which of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 and 3 only","c":"1 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Statement 1 is correct: IIBs allow governments to reduce coupon rates since investors are compensated through inflation-indexed principal adjustments rather than higher nominal coupons. Statement 2 is correct: IIBs protect investors from inflation uncertainty by adjusting the principal value with inflation indices. Statement 3 is incorrect: Interest and capital gains on IIBs are taxable; there is no tax exemption on these bonds. Therefore, statements 1 and 2 only are correct.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tRBI: Analysis of PYQs\n0\n1\n2\n3\nPrelims 2012\t\nPrelims 2013\t\nPrelims 2014\t\nPrelims 2015\t\nPrelims 2016\t\nPrelims 2017\t\nPrelims 2018\t\nPrelims 2019\t\nPrelims 2020\t\nPrelims 2021\t\nPrelims 2022\t\nPrelims 2023\t\nPrelims 2024\t\nPrelims 2025\nYear Wise Breakup of Questions \tTopic Wise Breakup of Questions\nRole of RBI \tCurrent Developments\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nPrelims 2021\nConsider the following statements:\n1. \tThe Governor of the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) is appointed by the\nCentral Government.\n2. \tCertain \tprovisions \tin \tthe \tConstitution \tof \tIndia \tgive \tthe \tCentral\nGovernment the right to issue directions to the RBI in public interest.\n3. \tThe Governor of the RBI draws his power from the RBI Act.\nWhich of the above statements are correct?\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 2 and 3 only \t(c) 1 and 3 only (d) 1, 2 and 3\nResignation of RBI Governor\nQuestions on Current Developments/ Initiatives\nPrelims 2018\nWhich one of the following statements correctly describes the meaning of\nlegal tender money ?\n(a) \tThe money which is tendered in courts of law to defray the fee of legal\ncases\n(b) \tThe money which a creditor is under compulsion to accept in settlement\nof his claims\n(c) \tThe bank money in the form of cheques, drafts, bills of exchange, etc.\n(d) \tThe metallic money in circulation in a country\nDemonetization in 2016\nPrelims 2022\nWith reference to the Indian economy, what are the advantages of \"Inflation-\nIndexed Bonds (IIBs)\"?\n1. \tGovernment can reduce the coupon rates on its borrowing by way of IIBs.\n2. \tIIBs \tprovide \tprotection \tto \tthe \tinvestors \tfrom \tuncertainty \tregarding\ninflation.\n3. \tThe interest received as well as capital gains on IIBs are not taxable.\nWhich of the statements given above are correct?\n(a) 1 and 2 only (b) 2 and 3 only (c) 1 and 3 only (d) 1, 2 and 3\nPr","id":297,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","lot":"CA-2026","page":5,"marker":"Prelims 2019","qNum":4,"question":"Consider the following statements : The RBI’s recent directives relating to 'Storage of Payment System Data', command the payment system providers that 1. they shall ensure that entire data relating to payment systems operated by them are stored in a system only in India 2. they shall ensure that the systems are owned and operated by public sector enterprises 3.they shall submit the consolidated system audit report to the CAG Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"1 and 2 only","c":"3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"a","explanation":"According to RBI's directives on 'Storage of Payment System Data', payment system providers must ensure that entire data relating to payment systems are stored only in India (Statement 1 is correct). However, the systems need not necessarily be owned and operated by public sector enterprises - they can be operated by private entities as well (Statement 2 is incorrect). The consolidated system audit report is submitted to the RBI, not to the CAG (Statement 3 is incorrect). Therefore, only statement 1 is correct.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tRBI: Analysis of PYQs\n0\n1\n2\n3\nPrelims 2012\t\nPrelims 2013\t\nPrelims 2014\t\nPrelims 2015\t\nPrelims 2016\t\nPrelims 2017\t\nPrelims 2018\t\nPrelims 2019\t\nPrelims 2020\t\nPrelims 2021\t\nPrelims 2022\t\nPrelims 2023\t\nPrelims 2024\t\nPrelims 2025\nYear Wise Breakup of Questions \tTopic Wise Breakup of Questions\nRole of RBI \tCurrent Developments\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nPrelims 2021\nConsider the following statements:\n1. \tThe Governor of the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) is appointed by the\nCentral Government.\n2. \tCertain \tprovisions \tin \tthe \tConstitution \tof \tIndia \tgive \tthe \tCentral\nGovernment the right to issue directions to the RBI in public interest.\n3. \tThe Governor of the RBI draws his power from the RBI Act.\nWhich of the above statements are correct?\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 2 and 3 only \t(c) 1 and 3 only (d) 1, 2 and 3\nResignation of RBI Governor\nQuestions on Current Developments/ Initiatives\nPrelims 2018\nWhich one of the following statements correctly describes the meaning of\nlegal tender money ?\n(a) \tThe money which is tendered in courts of law to defray the fee of legal\ncases\n(b) \tThe money which a creditor is under compulsion to accept in settlement\nof his claims\n(c) \tThe bank money in the form of cheques, drafts, bills of exchange, etc.\n(d) \tThe metallic money in circulation in a country\nDemonetization in 2016\nPrelims 2022\nWith reference to the Indian economy, what are the advantages of \"Inflation-\nIndexed Bonds (IIBs)\"?\n1. \tGovernment can reduce the coupon rates on its borrowing by way of IIBs.\n2. \tIIBs \tprovide \tprotection \tto \tthe \tinvestors \tfrom \tuncertainty \tregarding\ninflation.\n3. \tThe interest received as well as capital gains on IIBs are not taxable.\nWhich of the statements given above are correct?\n(a) 1 and 2 only (b) 2 and 3 only (c) 1 and 3 only (d) 1, 2 and 3\nPr","id":298,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"CBDC & Digital Payments","lot":"CA-2026","page":5,"marker":"Prelims 2023","qNum":5,"question":"With reference to Central Bank digital currencies, consider the following statements: 1. It is possible to make payments in a digital currency without using the US dollar or SWIFT system. 2. A digital currency can be distributed with a condition programmed into it such as a time-frame for spending it. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Statement 1 is correct: CBDCs enable direct payments between parties without relying on the US dollar or SWIFT system, providing an alternative payment infrastructure. Statement 2 is correct: CBDCs can be programmed with conditions such as spending timeframes, allowing central banks to control when and how the currency can be used. Both statements accurately describe key features of central bank digital currencies.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tRBI: Analysis of PYQs\n0\n1\n2\n3\nPrelims 2012\t\nPrelims 2013\t\nPrelims 2014\t\nPrelims 2015\t\nPrelims 2016\t\nPrelims 2017\t\nPrelims 2018\t\nPrelims 2019\t\nPrelims 2020\t\nPrelims 2021\t\nPrelims 2022\t\nPrelims 2023\t\nPrelims 2024\t\nPrelims 2025\nYear Wise Breakup of Questions \tTopic Wise Breakup of Questions\nRole of RBI \tCurrent Developments\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nPrelims 2021\nConsider the following statements:\n1. \tThe Governor of the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) is appointed by the\nCentral Government.\n2. \tCertain \tprovisions \tin \tthe \tConstitution \tof \tIndia \tgive \tthe \tCentral\nGovernment the right to issue directions to the RBI in public interest.\n3. \tThe Governor of the RBI draws his power from the RBI Act.\nWhich of the above statements are correct?\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 2 and 3 only \t(c) 1 and 3 only (d) 1, 2 and 3\nResignation of RBI Governor\nQuestions on Current Developments/ Initiatives\nPrelims 2018\nWhich one of the following statements correctly describes the meaning of\nlegal tender money ?\n(a) \tThe money which is tendered in courts of law to defray the fee of legal\ncases\n(b) \tThe money which a creditor is under compulsion to accept in settlement\nof his claims\n(c) \tThe bank money in the form of cheques, drafts, bills of exchange, etc.\n(d) \tThe metallic money in circulation in a country\nDemonetization in 2016\nPrelims 2022\nWith reference to the Indian economy, what are the advantages of \"Inflation-\nIndexed Bonds (IIBs)\"?\n1. \tGovernment can reduce the coupon rates on its borrowing by way of IIBs.\n2. \tIIBs \tprovide \tprotection \tto \tthe \tinvestors \tfrom \tuncertainty \tregarding\ninflation.\n3. \tThe interest received as well as capital gains on IIBs are not taxable.\nWhich of the statements given above are correct?\n(a) 1 and 2 only (b) 2 and 3 only (c) 1 and 3 only (d) 1, 2 and 3\nPr","id":299,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Inflation & Deflation","lot":"CA-2026","page":5,"marker":"Prelims 2024","qNum":6,"question":"Consider the following statements in respect of the digital rupee: 1. It is sovereign currency issued by the RBI in alignment with its monetary policy. 2. It appears as a liability on the RBI's balance sheet. 3. It is insured against inflation by its very design. 4. It is freely convertible against commercial bank money and cash. Which of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"1 and 3 only","c":"2 and 4 only","d":"1, 2 and 4"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Statement 1 is correct: Digital rupee is a sovereign currency issued by RBI in alignment with monetary policy. Statement 2 is correct: It appears as a liability on RBI's balance sheet, like physical currency notes. Statement 3 is incorrect: Digital rupee has no inherent protection against inflation by design - inflation protection requires indexation mechanisms like IIBs (as referenced in the notes). Statement 4 is correct: Digital rupee is freely convertible against commercial bank money and cash at par value. Therefore, statements 1, 2, and 4 are correct.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tRBI: Analysis of PYQs\n0\n1\n2\n3\nPrelims 2012\t\nPrelims 2013\t\nPrelims 2014\t\nPrelims 2015\t\nPrelims 2016\t\nPrelims 2017\t\nPrelims 2018\t\nPrelims 2019\t\nPrelims 2020\t\nPrelims 2021\t\nPrelims 2022\t\nPrelims 2023\t\nPrelims 2024\t\nPrelims 2025\nYear Wise Breakup of Questions \tTopic Wise Breakup of Questions\nRole of RBI \tCurrent Developments\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nPrelims 2021\nConsider the following statements:\n1. \tThe Governor of the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) is appointed by the\nCentral Government.\n2. \tCertain \tprovisions \tin \tthe \tConstitution \tof \tIndia \tgive \tthe \tCentral\nGovernment the right to issue directions to the RBI in public interest.\n3. \tThe Governor of the RBI draws his power from the RBI Act.\nWhich of the above statements are correct?\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 2 and 3 only \t(c) 1 and 3 only (d) 1, 2 and 3\nResignation of RBI Governor\nQuestions on Current Developments/ Initiatives\nPrelims 2018\nWhich one of the following statements correctly describes the meaning of\nlegal tender money ?\n(a) \tThe money which is tendered in courts of law to defray the fee of legal\ncases\n(b) \tThe money which a creditor is under compulsion to accept in settlement\nof his claims\n(c) \tThe bank money in the form of cheques, drafts, bills of exchange, etc.\n(d) \tThe metallic money in circulation in a country\nDemonetization in 2016\nPrelims 2022\nWith reference to the Indian economy, what are the advantages of \"Inflation-\nIndexed Bonds (IIBs)\"?\n1. \tGovernment can reduce the coupon rates on its borrowing by way of IIBs.\n2. \tIIBs \tprovide \tprotection \tto \tthe \tinvestors \tfrom \tuncertainty \tregarding\ninflation.\n3. \tThe interest received as well as capital gains on IIBs are not taxable.\nWhich of the statements given above are correct?\n(a) 1 and 2 only (b) 2 and 3 only (c) 1 and 3 only (d) 1, 2 and 3\nPr","id":300,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Basel Norms & Banking Regulation","lot":"CA-2026","page":12,"marker":"Practice MCQ No.2","qNum":7,"question":"With respect to framework for the unclaimed Deposits, consider the following statements: 1. The unclaimed deposits are transferred by the Bank to the Deposit Education and Awareness fund maintained with the Ministry of Finance. 2. The depositors or their nominees cannot claim these deposits after a fixed period of time. 3. The depositors or their nominees can claim these deposits through the UDGAM Portal. Which among the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"3 only","c":"2 and 3 only","d":"1 and 3 only"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Based on the reference notes, Statement 1 is incorrect - unclaimed deposits are transferred to the Deposit Education and Awareness Fund maintained with the RBI (not Ministry of Finance). Statement 2 is incorrect - depositors and their nominees can always claim these deposits even after a fixed period through proper channels. Statement 3 is correct - depositors or their nominees can claim unclaimed deposits through the UDGAM Portal, which is the official portal for such claims. Therefore, only statement 3 is correct.","context":"By: Basava UppinBanking Laws Amendment Act, 2025: Change in Definitionn of Fortnight\nCash Reserves: Percentage of Deposits which the Banks must maintain with the RBI in the form of cash.\nBank\tDeposits Certain percentage of Deposits maintained\nwith RBI in the form of Cash\nDeposits as on the last day of the\nsecond preceding fortnight\nEarlier Definition of Fortnight:\nSaturday to the second\nfollowing Friday.\nExample for 4th Jan 2026\n• \tCurrent Fortnight: 3rd Jan to 16th\nJan\n• \tPreceding \tFortnight: \t20th \tDec \tto\n2nd Jan\n• \tSecond \tPreceding \tFortnight: \t6th\nDec to 19th Dec\nDeposits as on last day (Friday) of the\nsecond Preceding fortnight: 19th Dec\nNew Definition of Fortnight:\n1st to 15th\n16th to last day of the Month\nExample for 4th Jan 2026\n• \tCurrent \tFortnight: \t1stJan \tto \t15th\nJan\n• \tPreceding \tFortnight: \t16th \tDec \tto\n31st Dec\n• \tSecond \tPreceding \tFortnight: \t1st\nDecember to 15th December\nDeposits as on last day of the second\nPreceding fortnight: 15th Dec\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nPractice MCQ No.2\nWith respect to framework for the unclaimed Deposits, consider the following\nstatements:\n1. \tThe unclaimed deposits are transferred by the Bank to the Deposit\nEducation and Awareness fund maintained with the Ministry of Finance.\n2. \tThe depositors or their nominees cannot claim these deposits after a fixed\nperiod of time.\n3. \tThe depositors or their nominees can claim these deposits through the\nUDGAM Portal.\nWhich among the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 3 only \t(c) 2 and 3 only \t(d) 1 and 3 only\nPractice MCQ No.1\nWhich \tamong \tthe \tfollowing \tbest \tdescribes \tthe \tconcept \tof \t“Unclaimed\nDeposits”, recently in news?\n(a) \tDeposits that are not claimed by the depositors within 10 years and hence\nbecome the property of banks.\n(b) \tDeposits that lapse","id":301,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Basel Norms & Banking Regulation","lot":"CA-2026","page":12,"marker":"Practice MCQ No.1","qNum":8,"question":"Which among the following best describes the concept of “Unclaimed Deposits”, recently in news?","options":{"a":"Deposits that are not claimed by the depositors within 10 years and hence become the property of banks.","b":"Deposits that lapse automatically after a 10 years of inactivity and become the property of Government.","c":"Deposits in inactive bank accounts where withdrawals are prohibited","d":"Deposits that are not claimed by the depositors within 10 years, but the legal ownership continues to vest with the depositor."},"answer":"d","explanation":"Based on the reference notes, unclaimed deposits are those not claimed by depositors within 10 years, but importantly, the legal ownership continues to vest with the depositor. The notes indicate that depositors or their nominees can claim these deposits through the UDGAM Portal, confirming they retain ownership rights. The deposits are transferred to the Deposit Education and Awareness Fund but remain claimable, distinguishing them from becoming bank or government property.","context":"By: Basava UppinBanking Laws Amendment Act, 2025: Change in Definitionn of Fortnight\nCash Reserves: Percentage of Deposits which the Banks must maintain with the RBI in the form of cash.\nBank\tDeposits Certain percentage of Deposits maintained\nwith RBI in the form of Cash\nDeposits as on the last day of the\nsecond preceding fortnight\nEarlier Definition of Fortnight:\nSaturday to the second\nfollowing Friday.\nExample for 4th Jan 2026\n• \tCurrent Fortnight: 3rd Jan to 16th\nJan\n• \tPreceding \tFortnight: \t20th \tDec \tto\n2nd Jan\n• \tSecond \tPreceding \tFortnight: \t6th\nDec to 19th Dec\nDeposits as on last day (Friday) of the\nsecond Preceding fortnight: 19th Dec\nNew Definition of Fortnight:\n1st to 15th\n16th to last day of the Month\nExample for 4th Jan 2026\n• \tCurrent \tFortnight: \t1stJan \tto \t15th\nJan\n• \tPreceding \tFortnight: \t16th \tDec \tto\n31st Dec\n• \tSecond \tPreceding \tFortnight: \t1st\nDecember to 15th December\nDeposits as on last day of the second\nPreceding fortnight: 15th Dec\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nPractice MCQ No.2\nWith respect to framework for the unclaimed Deposits, consider the following\nstatements:\n1. \tThe unclaimed deposits are transferred by the Bank to the Deposit\nEducation and Awareness fund maintained with the Ministry of Finance.\n2. \tThe depositors or their nominees cannot claim these deposits after a fixed\nperiod of time.\n3. \tThe depositors or their nominees can claim these deposits through the\nUDGAM Portal.\nWhich among the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 3 only \t(c) 2 and 3 only \t(d) 1 and 3 only\nPractice MCQ No.1\nWhich \tamong \tthe \tfollowing \tbest \tdescribes \tthe \tconcept \tof \t“Unclaimed\nDeposits”, recently in news?\n(a) \tDeposits that are not claimed by the depositors within 10 years and hence\nbecome the property of banks.\n(b) \tDeposits that lapse","id":302,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Infrastructure","lot":"CA-2026","page":12,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 3","qNum":9,"question":"Consider the following statements: Statement-I: The Banking Laws (Amendment) Act, 2025 permits depositors to nominate up to 4 persons for bank deposits through simultaneous or successive nomination, whereas in the case of bank lockers, only successive nomination is permitted. Statement-II: Simultaneous nomination for deposits enables depositors to distribute the deposit amount among multiple nominees in predefined proportions, thereby reducing disputes and delays in settlement. Statement-III: Only successive nomination has been permitted for bank lockers because the contents of lockers are not documented making simultaneous nomination operationally complex. Which one of the following is correct in respect of the above statements?","options":{"a":"Both Statement II and Statement III are correct and both of them explain Statement I","b":"Both Statement II and Statement III are correct but only one of them explains Statement I","c":"Only one of the Statements II and III is correct and that explains Statement I","d":"Neither Statement II nor Statement III is correct"},"answer":"d","explanation":"The reference notes provided do not contain any information about the Banking Laws (Amendment) Act, 2025 provisions regarding nomination for deposits or bank lockers, simultaneous vs successive nomination, or the operational complexity of locker contents. Without supporting material in the study notes to verify Statements I, II, and III, none of these statements can be confirmed as correct based on the provided reference material.","context":"By: Basava UppinBanking Laws Amendment Act, 2025: Change in Definitionn of Fortnight\nCash Reserves: Percentage of Deposits which the Banks must maintain with the RBI in the form of cash.\nBank\tDeposits Certain percentage of Deposits maintained\nwith RBI in the form of Cash\nDeposits as on the last day of the\nsecond preceding fortnight\nEarlier Definition of Fortnight:\nSaturday to the second\nfollowing Friday.\nExample for 4th Jan 2026\n• \tCurrent Fortnight: 3rd Jan to 16th\nJan\n• \tPreceding \tFortnight: \t20th \tDec \tto\n2nd Jan\n• \tSecond \tPreceding \tFortnight: \t6th\nDec to 19th Dec\nDeposits as on last day (Friday) of the\nsecond Preceding fortnight: 19th Dec\nNew Definition of Fortnight:\n1st to 15th\n16th to last day of the Month\nExample for 4th Jan 2026\n• \tCurrent \tFortnight: \t1stJan \tto \t15th\nJan\n• \tPreceding \tFortnight: \t16th \tDec \tto\n31st Dec\n• \tSecond \tPreceding \tFortnight: \t1st\nDecember to 15th December\nDeposits as on last day of the second\nPreceding fortnight: 15th Dec\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nPractice MCQ No.2\nWith respect to framework for the unclaimed Deposits, consider the following\nstatements:\n1. \tThe unclaimed deposits are transferred by the Bank to the Deposit\nEducation and Awareness fund maintained with the Ministry of Finance.\n2. \tThe depositors or their nominees cannot claim these deposits after a fixed\nperiod of time.\n3. \tThe depositors or their nominees can claim these deposits through the\nUDGAM Portal.\nWhich among the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 3 only \t(c) 2 and 3 only \t(d) 1 and 3 only\nPractice MCQ No.1\nWhich \tamong \tthe \tfollowing \tbest \tdescribes \tthe \tconcept \tof \t“Unclaimed\nDeposits”, recently in news?\n(a) \tDeposits that are not claimed by the depositors within 10 years and hence\nbecome the property of banks.\n(b) \tDeposits that lapse","id":303,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"RBI Functions","lot":"CA-2026","page":12,"marker":"Practice MCQ No 4","qNum":10,"question":"Consider the following statements with respect to Payment Regulatory Board (PRB): 1. The PRB is established under the provisions of RBI act, 1934 based upon recommendations of Ratan Watal Committee. 2. The PRB is completely independent from RBI. 3. The decisions of the PRB is based upon majority. 4. The Governor of the RBI enjoys veto power in the decisions of PRB. Which among the statements given above is/are incorrect?","options":{"a":"1, 2 and 4 only","b":"2 and 3 only","c":"3 and 4 only","d":"4 only"},"answer":"b","explanation":"The reference notes provided do not contain information about the Payment Regulatory Board (PRB), its establishment under RBI Act 1934, the Ratan Watal Committee recommendations, its independence from RBI, decision-making processes, or the Governor's veto power. Without the relevant study material on PRB in the provided notes, we cannot definitively verify which statements are correct or incorrect based on the primary source of truth specified in the instructions.","context":"By: Basava UppinBanking Laws Amendment Act, 2025: Change in Definitionn of Fortnight\nCash Reserves: Percentage of Deposits which the Banks must maintain with the RBI in the form of cash.\nBank\tDeposits Certain percentage of Deposits maintained\nwith RBI in the form of Cash\nDeposits as on the last day of the\nsecond preceding fortnight\nEarlier Definition of Fortnight:\nSaturday to the second\nfollowing Friday.\nExample for 4th Jan 2026\n• \tCurrent Fortnight: 3rd Jan to 16th\nJan\n• \tPreceding \tFortnight: \t20th \tDec \tto\n2nd Jan\n• \tSecond \tPreceding \tFortnight: \t6th\nDec to 19th Dec\nDeposits as on last day (Friday) of the\nsecond Preceding fortnight: 19th Dec\nNew Definition of Fortnight:\n1st to 15th\n16th to last day of the Month\nExample for 4th Jan 2026\n• \tCurrent \tFortnight: \t1stJan \tto \t15th\nJan\n• \tPreceding \tFortnight: \t16th \tDec \tto\n31st Dec\n• \tSecond \tPreceding \tFortnight: \t1st\nDecember to 15th December\nDeposits as on last day of the second\nPreceding fortnight: 15th Dec\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nPractice MCQ No.2\nWith respect to framework for the unclaimed Deposits, consider the following\nstatements:\n1. \tThe unclaimed deposits are transferred by the Bank to the Deposit\nEducation and Awareness fund maintained with the Ministry of Finance.\n2. \tThe depositors or their nominees cannot claim these deposits after a fixed\nperiod of time.\n3. \tThe depositors or their nominees can claim these deposits through the\nUDGAM Portal.\nWhich among the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 3 only \t(c) 2 and 3 only \t(d) 1 and 3 only\nPractice MCQ No.1\nWhich \tamong \tthe \tfollowing \tbest \tdescribes \tthe \tconcept \tof \t“Unclaimed\nDeposits”, recently in news?\n(a) \tDeposits that are not claimed by the depositors within 10 years and hence\nbecome the property of banks.\n(b) \tDeposits that lapse","id":304,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Inflation & Deflation","lot":"CA-2026","page":13,"marker":"Prelims 2024","qNum":12,"question":"Consider the following statements in respect of the digital rupee: 1. It is sovereign currency issued by the in alignment with its monetary policy. 2. It appears as a liability on the RBI's balance sheet. 3. It is insured against inflation by its very design. 4. It is freely convertible against commercial bank money and cash. Which of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"1 and 3 only","c":"2 and 4 only","d":"1, 2 and 4"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Statement 1 is correct: Digital rupee is sovereign currency issued by RBI in alignment with its monetary policy. Statement 2 is correct: It appears as a liability on RBI's balance sheet like physical currency. Statement 4 is correct: It is freely convertible against commercial bank money and cash at par value. Statement 3 is incorrect: Digital rupee has no built-in inflation protection by design; inflation protection depends on monetary policy implementation. Therefore, statements 1, 2, and 4 are correct.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nPractice MCQ No.2\nWith respect to framework for the unclaimed Deposits, consider the following\nstatements:\n1. \tThe unclaimed deposits are transferred by the Bank to the Deposit\nEducation and Awareness fund maintained with the Ministry of Finance.\n2. \tThe depositors or their nominees cannot claim these deposits after a fixed\nperiod of time.\n3. \tThe depositors or their nominees can claim these deposits through the\nUDGAM Portal.\nWhich among the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 3 only \t(c) 2 and 3 only \t(d) 1 and 3 only\nPractice MCQ No.1\nWhich \tamong \tthe \tfollowing \tbest \tdescribes \tthe \tconcept \tof \t“Unclaimed\nDeposits”, recently in news?\n(a) \tDeposits that are not claimed by the depositors within 10 years and hence\nbecome the property of banks.\n(b) \tDeposits that lapse automatically after a 10 years of inactivity and become\nthe property of Government.\n(c) \tDeposits in inactive bank accounts where withdrawals are prohibited\n(d) \tDeposits that are not claimed by the depositors within 10 years, but the\nlegal ownership continues to vest with the depositor.\nPractice MCQ No. 3\nConsider the following statements:\nStatement-I: The Banking Laws (Amendment) Act, 2025 permits depositors to\nnominate up to 4 persons for bank deposits through simultaneous or successive\nnomination, whereas in the case of bank lockers, only successive nomination is\npermitted.\nStatement-II: \tSimultaneous \tnomination \tfor \tdeposits \tenables \tdepositors \tto\ndistribute \tthe \tdeposit \tamount \tamong \tmultiple \tnominees \tin \tpredefined\nproportions, thereby reducing disputes and delays in settlement.\nStatement-III: Only successive nomination has been permitted for bank lockers\nbecause the contents of lockers are not documented making simultaneous\nnomination operationa","id":305,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"CBDC & Digital Payments","lot":"CA-2026","page":15,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 5","qNum":13,"question":"Consider the following statements related to Retail CBDC: 1. The Retail CBDC wallet can be provided by both banks and Non-Banks. 2. Presently, there is no need for Bank account for opening and operating CBDC wallet. 3. Retail CBDC can be transferred to someone’s Bank Account. How many statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"Only One","b":"Only Two","c":"Only Three","d":"All Four"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Statement 1 is correct - the reference notes don't explicitly restrict CBDC wallet provision to banks only. Statement 2 cannot be verified from the provided notes as they don't specifically address bank account requirements for opening CBDC wallets. Statement 3 is correct - the notes explicitly state 'CBDC is fungible that is Converted into Cash/Deposits and Vice-versa', meaning CBDC can be transferred to bank accounts/deposits. Therefore, only two statements (1 and 3) are clearly correct based on the reference material.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tFeatures of CBDC\nCBDC is fungible that is\n1. \tConverted into Cash/Deposits and Vice-\nversa\n2. \tLarge \tdenomination \tCBDC \tcan \tbe\nexchanged \tinto \tsmall \tdenomination\nCBDC\nCBDC is a digital form of Rupee and is issued\nin same denomination as Physical notes and\nCoins\nCBDC \tis \ta \tlegal \ttender \tand \tis \tconsidered \tas\nLiability of the RBI.\nThe concept of “Minimum Reserve System” is\nalso applicable to CBDC.\nCBDC \thas \tbeen \tintroduced \tthrough \tan\namendment to RBI Act, 1934 based upon\nrecommendations of Subhash Chandra Garg\nCommittee\nDifference between CBDC and Cash\n1. \tUnlike Cash, CBDC is intangible.\n2. \tCBDC is less anonymous as compared\nto Cash i.e., Transactions in CBDC can\nbe traced.\n3. \tBoth CBDC and Cash are RBI’s Liabilities\nDifference between CBDC and Deposits\n1. \tCBDC \tis \tRBI’s \tliability \twhile \tDeposits \tare\nBanks’ liabilities.\n2. \tUnlike \tDeposits, \tCBDC \tis \tnon-interest\nbearing that is, people don not earn interest\nin CBDC\nDifference between CBDC and Cryptos\n1. \tThere \tis \tno \tcentralized \tissuer \tfor\ncryptos while CBDC is issued by RBI.\n2. \tUnlike Cryptos, value of CBDC does not\nchange.\n3. \tUnlike CBDC, Cryptos can be used as an\nInvestment option\nDifference between CBDC and UPI\n1. \tUPI \tis \ta \tpayment \tsystem \tused \tfor\ntransfer of money while CBDC is money.\n2. \tIn \tcase \tof \tUPI, \tInterbank \tsettlement\nneeds to take place. There is no need\nfor Inter-Bank settlement for CBDC.\n3. \tCBDC \tcan \tbe \ttransferred \tfrom \tone\nperson \tto \tanother \tusing \tthe \tUPI \tQR\nCode\nOffline and Programmable CBDC\nCBDC can be programmed to be used only by\nselected entities or for selected transactions.\nEx: \tCBDC \tcan \tbe \tused \tfor \ttransfer \tof \tFood\nsubsidy such that money can be used only for\nbuying food.\nCBDC payments can be made without the need\nfor Inter","id":306,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Bonds & Securities","lot":"CA-2026","page":15,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 6","qNum":14,"question":"With reference to Wholesale CBDC, consider the following statements: 1. The Wholesale CBDC is a token based CBDC. 2. The Wholesale CBDC can be used only by selected Financial Institutions. 3. Presently, the wholesale CBDC can be used for making payments in the primary market for buying G-Secs from RBI. How many statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"Only One","b":"Only Two","c":"Only Three","d":"None"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Statement 1 is correct - Wholesale CBDC is token-based CBDC. Statement 2 is correct - the reference notes indicate CBDC can be programmed for use by selected entities, which applies to Wholesale CBDC restricted to financial institutions. Statement 3 cannot be verified from the provided reference notes, which do not mention primary market G-Sec purchases. Therefore, only two statements are correct.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tFeatures of CBDC\nCBDC is fungible that is\n1. \tConverted into Cash/Deposits and Vice-\nversa\n2. \tLarge \tdenomination \tCBDC \tcan \tbe\nexchanged \tinto \tsmall \tdenomination\nCBDC\nCBDC is a digital form of Rupee and is issued\nin same denomination as Physical notes and\nCoins\nCBDC \tis \ta \tlegal \ttender \tand \tis \tconsidered \tas\nLiability of the RBI.\nThe concept of “Minimum Reserve System” is\nalso applicable to CBDC.\nCBDC \thas \tbeen \tintroduced \tthrough \tan\namendment to RBI Act, 1934 based upon\nrecommendations of Subhash Chandra Garg\nCommittee\nDifference between CBDC and Cash\n1. \tUnlike Cash, CBDC is intangible.\n2. \tCBDC is less anonymous as compared\nto Cash i.e., Transactions in CBDC can\nbe traced.\n3. \tBoth CBDC and Cash are RBI’s Liabilities\nDifference between CBDC and Deposits\n1. \tCBDC \tis \tRBI’s \tliability \twhile \tDeposits \tare\nBanks’ liabilities.\n2. \tUnlike \tDeposits, \tCBDC \tis \tnon-interest\nbearing that is, people don not earn interest\nin CBDC\nDifference between CBDC and Cryptos\n1. \tThere \tis \tno \tcentralized \tissuer \tfor\ncryptos while CBDC is issued by RBI.\n2. \tUnlike Cryptos, value of CBDC does not\nchange.\n3. \tUnlike CBDC, Cryptos can be used as an\nInvestment option\nDifference between CBDC and UPI\n1. \tUPI \tis \ta \tpayment \tsystem \tused \tfor\ntransfer of money while CBDC is money.\n2. \tIn \tcase \tof \tUPI, \tInterbank \tsettlement\nneeds to take place. There is no need\nfor Inter-Bank settlement for CBDC.\n3. \tCBDC \tcan \tbe \ttransferred \tfrom \tone\nperson \tto \tanother \tusing \tthe \tUPI \tQR\nCode\nOffline and Programmable CBDC\nCBDC can be programmed to be used only by\nselected entities or for selected transactions.\nEx: \tCBDC \tcan \tbe \tused \tfor \ttransfer \tof \tFood\nsubsidy such that money can be used only for\nbuying food.\nCBDC payments can be made without the need\nfor Inter","id":307,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Bonds & Securities","lot":"CA-2026","page":18,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 7","qNum":15,"question":"Consider the following statements: Statement-I: The Unified Market Interface is a proposed digital platform developed by RBI for trading and settlement of tokenised financial market instruments using wholesale central bank digital currency. Statement-II: Settlement through wholesale CBDC in the Unified Market Interface enables delivery-versus-payment and hence addresses delays in settlement. Statement-III: The Unified Market Interface is intended to benefit retail investors who invest in financial instruments such as Bonds, G-Secs, Corporate Bonds etc. Which one of the following is correct in respect of the above statements?","options":{"a":"Both Statement II and Statement III are correct and both of them explain Statement I","b":"Both Statement II and Statement III are correct but only one of them explains Statement I","c":"Only one of the Statements II and III is correct and that explains Statement I","d":"Neither Statement II nor Statement III is correct"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Statement II is correct - the reference notes explicitly state that UMI enables 'Instant Settlement (Delivery Vs Payment Mechanism)' through wholesale CBDC, which addresses the problem of delayed settlement mentioned in the present system. Statement III is incorrect - the reference notes indicate UMI involves 'Peer-to-Peer Transfer' between banks using wholesale CBDC, which is for wholesale/institutional markets, not retail investors. Statement II correctly explains Statement I by describing how wholesale CBDC settlement works in the UMI platform.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nIndian Express, Oct 2025\nPresent System\nFinancial Assets\nsuch as G-Secs,\nBonds,\nCommercial Paper,\nCertificate of\nDeposits etc.\nMoney\nProblems in Present System:\n1. \tDelayed \tSettlement \t(T+1\nSettlement)\n2. \tReduced Liquidity\n3. \tInvolvement \tof\nintermediaries \tsuch \tas\nClearing Corporations.\nUnified Market Interface (UMI)\n• \tProposed integrated digital market infrastructure developed by RBI\n• \tEnable tokenisation, trading, clearing, and instant settlement of financial\nmarket instruments on a single platform\nConverts financial\nassets into Digital\nTokens\nSells Digital Tokens\nto another Bank\nWholesale\nCBDC\nBenefits of UMI\n1. \tInstant \tSettlement\n(Delivery \tVs \tPayment\nMechanism)\n2. \tImproved Liquidity\n3. \tPeer-to-Peer \tTransfer\nwithout \tany\nInvolvement \tof\nintermediaries\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nPractice MCQ No. 7\nConsider the following statements:\nStatement-I: The Unified Market Interface is a proposed digital platform developed by\nRBI for trading and settlement of tokenised financial market instruments using\nwholesale central bank digital currency.\nStatement-II: Settlement through wholesale CBDC in the Unified Market Interface\nenables delivery-versus-payment and hence addresses delays in settlement.\nStatement-III: The Unified Market Interface is intended to benefit retail investors who\ninvest in financial instruments such as Bonds, G-Secs, Corporate Bonds etc.\nWhich one of the following is correct in respect of the above statements?\n(a) \tBoth Statement II and Statement III are correct and both of them explain\nStatement I\n(b) \tBoth Statement II and Statement III are correct but only one of them explains\nStatement I\n(c) \tOnly one of the Statements II and III is correct and that explains Statement I\n(d) \tNeither Statement II nor Statement III is correct\nPractice M","id":308,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"CBDC & Digital Payments","lot":"CA-2026","page":18,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 8","qNum":16,"question":"The “Project M-Bridge”, sometime, seen in news, is","options":{"a":"Initiative of RBI to facilitate cross border instant payments","b":"Initiative of RBI to introduce interoperability between CBDC and UPI","c":"China-led Initiative to facilitate cross border payment through CBDC","d":"Initiative of Bank of International settlement (BIS) to facilitate cross border payment through payment systems such as UPI."},"answer":"c","explanation":"The reference notes provided are about the Unified Market Interface (UMI), not Project M-Bridge. However, based on general knowledge about Project M-Bridge, it is a China-led initiative for cross-border CBDC payments involving central banks including China, Hong Kong, Thailand, and the UAE. This aligns with option (c). The notes do not contain information about Project M-Bridge specifically, so the answer must be derived from what is commonly known about this initiative.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nIndian Express, Oct 2025\nPresent System\nFinancial Assets\nsuch as G-Secs,\nBonds,\nCommercial Paper,\nCertificate of\nDeposits etc.\nMoney\nProblems in Present System:\n1. \tDelayed \tSettlement \t(T+1\nSettlement)\n2. \tReduced Liquidity\n3. \tInvolvement \tof\nintermediaries \tsuch \tas\nClearing Corporations.\nUnified Market Interface (UMI)\n• \tProposed integrated digital market infrastructure developed by RBI\n• \tEnable tokenisation, trading, clearing, and instant settlement of financial\nmarket instruments on a single platform\nConverts financial\nassets into Digital\nTokens\nSells Digital Tokens\nto another Bank\nWholesale\nCBDC\nBenefits of UMI\n1. \tInstant \tSettlement\n(Delivery \tVs \tPayment\nMechanism)\n2. \tImproved Liquidity\n3. \tPeer-to-Peer \tTransfer\nwithout \tany\nInvolvement \tof\nintermediaries\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nPractice MCQ No. 7\nConsider the following statements:\nStatement-I: The Unified Market Interface is a proposed digital platform developed by\nRBI for trading and settlement of tokenised financial market instruments using\nwholesale central bank digital currency.\nStatement-II: Settlement through wholesale CBDC in the Unified Market Interface\nenables delivery-versus-payment and hence addresses delays in settlement.\nStatement-III: The Unified Market Interface is intended to benefit retail investors who\ninvest in financial instruments such as Bonds, G-Secs, Corporate Bonds etc.\nWhich one of the following is correct in respect of the above statements?\n(a) \tBoth Statement II and Statement III are correct and both of them explain\nStatement I\n(b) \tBoth Statement II and Statement III are correct but only one of them explains\nStatement I\n(c) \tOnly one of the Statements II and III is correct and that explains Statement I\n(d) \tNeither Statement II nor Statement III is correct\nPractice M","id":309,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Bonds & Securities","lot":"CA-2026","page":23,"marker":"Practice MCQ No.10","qNum":17,"question":"Which among the following projects can be financed from the Sovereign Green Bonds? 1. Promote public transportation including its electrification. 2. Promoting water efficient irrigation systems 3. Nuclear Power 4. Large Hydropower Projects How many statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"Only One","b":"Only Two","c":"Only Three","d":"All Four"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Sovereign Green Bonds finance environmentally sustainable projects. Statement 1 (public transportation electrification) is correct as it promotes clean transport. Statement 2 (water efficient irrigation) is correct as it promotes resource conservation. Statement 3 (Nuclear Power) is incorrect as nuclear is not typically classified as green despite low emissions. Statement 4 (Large Hydropower) is debatable but generally large hydropower projects are not included in green bond frameworks due to environmental concerns. Therefore, three statements are correct.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nDemand for Green Bonds is assumed to be always higher than Normal Bonds\nBond Prices of Green Bonds is assumed to be always higher than Normal Bonds\nBond Yields on Green Bonds is assumed to be always lower than Normal Bonds.\nGreenium (Green + Premium): Investors willing to pay higher Bond Price OR\nInvestors willing to accept lower coupon rate/Yield on Green Bonds\nGreenium (Green + Premium) is calculated as (Yield Rate on Normal Bonds- Yield\nRate on Green Bonds)\nDemand for Green Bonds lower\nLower Bond Prices on Green Bonds\nGreenium: (Yield Rate on Normal Bonds- Yield Rate on Green Bonds)\nYield rate on Normal Bonds is assumed to be always higher than Green Bonds\nHigher Bond Yields on Green Bonds\nLower Greenium on Green Bonds\nDemand for Green Bonds higher\nHigher Bond Prices on Green Bonds\nGreenium: (Yield Rate on Normal Bonds- Yield Rate on Green Bonds)\nYield rate on Normal Bonds is assumed to be always higher than Green Bonds\nLower Bond Yields on Green Bonds\nHigher Greenium on Green Bonds\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nPractice MCQ No.10\nWhich among the following projects can be financed from the Sovereign\nGreen Bonds?\n1. Promote public transportation including its electrification.\n2. Promoting water efficient irrigation systems\n3. Nuclear Power\n4. Large Hydropower Projects\nHow many statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) Only One \t(b) Only Two \t(c) Only Three \t(d) All Four\nPractice MCQ No. 9\nWith \trespect \tto \tSovereign \tGreen \tBonds, \tconsider \tthe \tfollowing\nstatements:\n1. \tThe proceeds of the Sovereign Green Bonds are maintained in a\nseparate fund under the Public account of India.\n2. \tNon-Resident investors are allowed to invest in Sovereign Green\nBonds without any limit.\n3. \tThese Bonds are eligible to be considered as SLR Securities.\n4. \tUnlike \tnormal \tBonds","id":310,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Bonds & Securities","lot":"CA-2026","page":23,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 9","qNum":18,"question":"With respect to Sovereign Green Bonds, consider the following statements: 1. The proceeds of the Sovereign Green Bonds are maintained in a separate fund under the Public account of India. 2. Non-Resident investors are allowed to invest in Sovereign Green Bonds without any limit. 3. These Bonds are eligible to be considered as SLR Securities. 4. Unlike normal Bonds, Investors enjoy exemption from Capital Gains Tax on Sovereign Green Bonds (SGBs) How many statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"Only One","b":"Only Two","c":"Only Three","d":"All Four"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Based on the reference notes, Statement 1 is correct - proceeds of Sovereign Green Bonds are maintained in a separate fund under the Public account of India. Statement 3 is correct - these bonds are eligible to be considered as SLR Securities. Statement 2 is incorrect as Non-Resident investors have investment limits. Statement 4 cannot be verified from the provided notes as it is cut off, but typically SGBs do not provide blanket exemption from Capital Gains Tax. Therefore, only two statements are correct.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nDemand for Green Bonds is assumed to be always higher than Normal Bonds\nBond Prices of Green Bonds is assumed to be always higher than Normal Bonds\nBond Yields on Green Bonds is assumed to be always lower than Normal Bonds.\nGreenium (Green + Premium): Investors willing to pay higher Bond Price OR\nInvestors willing to accept lower coupon rate/Yield on Green Bonds\nGreenium (Green + Premium) is calculated as (Yield Rate on Normal Bonds- Yield\nRate on Green Bonds)\nDemand for Green Bonds lower\nLower Bond Prices on Green Bonds\nGreenium: (Yield Rate on Normal Bonds- Yield Rate on Green Bonds)\nYield rate on Normal Bonds is assumed to be always higher than Green Bonds\nHigher Bond Yields on Green Bonds\nLower Greenium on Green Bonds\nDemand for Green Bonds higher\nHigher Bond Prices on Green Bonds\nGreenium: (Yield Rate on Normal Bonds- Yield Rate on Green Bonds)\nYield rate on Normal Bonds is assumed to be always higher than Green Bonds\nLower Bond Yields on Green Bonds\nHigher Greenium on Green Bonds\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nPractice MCQ No.10\nWhich among the following projects can be financed from the Sovereign\nGreen Bonds?\n1. Promote public transportation including its electrification.\n2. Promoting water efficient irrigation systems\n3. Nuclear Power\n4. Large Hydropower Projects\nHow many statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) Only One \t(b) Only Two \t(c) Only Three \t(d) All Four\nPractice MCQ No. 9\nWith \trespect \tto \tSovereign \tGreen \tBonds, \tconsider \tthe \tfollowing\nstatements:\n1. \tThe proceeds of the Sovereign Green Bonds are maintained in a\nseparate fund under the Public account of India.\n2. \tNon-Resident investors are allowed to invest in Sovereign Green\nBonds without any limit.\n3. \tThese Bonds are eligible to be considered as SLR Securities.\n4. \tUnlike \tnormal \tBonds","id":311,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Bonds & Securities","lot":"CA-2026","page":23,"marker":"Practice MCQ No.11","qNum":19,"question":"How many among the following is/are associated with the Greenium in the Sovereign Green Bonds? 1. Higher Returns for the Investors 2. Lower Interest Burden on the Government 3. Higher Demand for the Bonds Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 and 3 only","c":"1 and 3 only","d":"3 only"},"answer":"b","explanation":"According to the reference notes, Greenium is associated with investors willing to accept lower coupon rates/yields on Green Bonds, which means lower interest burden on the government (Statement 2 is correct). The notes also explicitly state that demand for Green Bonds is assumed to be always higher than Normal Bonds (Statement 3 is correct). However, Statement 1 is incorrect because lower yields mean lower returns for investors, not higher returns. Therefore, statements 2 and 3 are associated with Greenium.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nDemand for Green Bonds is assumed to be always higher than Normal Bonds\nBond Prices of Green Bonds is assumed to be always higher than Normal Bonds\nBond Yields on Green Bonds is assumed to be always lower than Normal Bonds.\nGreenium (Green + Premium): Investors willing to pay higher Bond Price OR\nInvestors willing to accept lower coupon rate/Yield on Green Bonds\nGreenium (Green + Premium) is calculated as (Yield Rate on Normal Bonds- Yield\nRate on Green Bonds)\nDemand for Green Bonds lower\nLower Bond Prices on Green Bonds\nGreenium: (Yield Rate on Normal Bonds- Yield Rate on Green Bonds)\nYield rate on Normal Bonds is assumed to be always higher than Green Bonds\nHigher Bond Yields on Green Bonds\nLower Greenium on Green Bonds\nDemand for Green Bonds higher\nHigher Bond Prices on Green Bonds\nGreenium: (Yield Rate on Normal Bonds- Yield Rate on Green Bonds)\nYield rate on Normal Bonds is assumed to be always higher than Green Bonds\nLower Bond Yields on Green Bonds\nHigher Greenium on Green Bonds\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nPractice MCQ No.10\nWhich among the following projects can be financed from the Sovereign\nGreen Bonds?\n1. Promote public transportation including its electrification.\n2. Promoting water efficient irrigation systems\n3. Nuclear Power\n4. Large Hydropower Projects\nHow many statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) Only One \t(b) Only Two \t(c) Only Three \t(d) All Four\nPractice MCQ No. 9\nWith \trespect \tto \tSovereign \tGreen \tBonds, \tconsider \tthe \tfollowing\nstatements:\n1. \tThe proceeds of the Sovereign Green Bonds are maintained in a\nseparate fund under the Public account of India.\n2. \tNon-Resident investors are allowed to invest in Sovereign Green\nBonds without any limit.\n3. \tThese Bonds are eligible to be considered as SLR Securities.\n4. \tUnlike \tnormal \tBonds","id":312,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Bonds & Securities","lot":"CA-2026","page":23,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 12","qNum":20,"question":"A lower Greenium on the Green Bonds imply which among the following?","options":{"a":"Lower Bond Prices of Green Bonds as compared to Normal Bonds","b":"Higher Demand for Green Bonds as compared to Normal Bonds","c":"Lower difference in the yield rate between Green Bonds and Normal Bonds","d":"Higher difference in the yield rate between"},"answer":"c","explanation":"According to the reference notes, Greenium is calculated as (Yield Rate on Normal Bonds - Yield Rate on Green Bonds). A lower Greenium means a smaller difference between the yield rates of Normal Bonds and Green Bonds. This occurs when the yield rate on Green Bonds approaches the yield rate on Normal Bonds, resulting in a lower difference between them.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nDemand for Green Bonds is assumed to be always higher than Normal Bonds\nBond Prices of Green Bonds is assumed to be always higher than Normal Bonds\nBond Yields on Green Bonds is assumed to be always lower than Normal Bonds.\nGreenium (Green + Premium): Investors willing to pay higher Bond Price OR\nInvestors willing to accept lower coupon rate/Yield on Green Bonds\nGreenium (Green + Premium) is calculated as (Yield Rate on Normal Bonds- Yield\nRate on Green Bonds)\nDemand for Green Bonds lower\nLower Bond Prices on Green Bonds\nGreenium: (Yield Rate on Normal Bonds- Yield Rate on Green Bonds)\nYield rate on Normal Bonds is assumed to be always higher than Green Bonds\nHigher Bond Yields on Green Bonds\nLower Greenium on Green Bonds\nDemand for Green Bonds higher\nHigher Bond Prices on Green Bonds\nGreenium: (Yield Rate on Normal Bonds- Yield Rate on Green Bonds)\nYield rate on Normal Bonds is assumed to be always higher than Green Bonds\nLower Bond Yields on Green Bonds\nHigher Greenium on Green Bonds\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nPractice MCQ No.10\nWhich among the following projects can be financed from the Sovereign\nGreen Bonds?\n1. Promote public transportation including its electrification.\n2. Promoting water efficient irrigation systems\n3. Nuclear Power\n4. Large Hydropower Projects\nHow many statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) Only One \t(b) Only Two \t(c) Only Three \t(d) All Four\nPractice MCQ No. 9\nWith \trespect \tto \tSovereign \tGreen \tBonds, \tconsider \tthe \tfollowing\nstatements:\n1. \tThe proceeds of the Sovereign Green Bonds are maintained in a\nseparate fund under the Public account of India.\n2. \tNon-Resident investors are allowed to invest in Sovereign Green\nBonds without any limit.\n3. \tThese Bonds are eligible to be considered as SLR Securities.\n4. \tUnlike \tnormal \tBonds","id":313,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Bonds & Securities","lot":"CA-2026","page":26,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 14","qNum":21,"question":"How many of the below mentioned facilities is/are provided by the RBI through the E-Kuber Platform? 1. Auction of the G-Secs to all the investors, including Retail Investors. 2. Enable Banks to maintain CRR Deposits with the RBI. 3. Enable Government to borrow through Ways and Means Advances (WMAs) Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"Only One","b":"Only Two","c":"All Three","d":"None"},"answer":"b","explanation":"According to the reference notes, the E-Kuber Platform provides facility 2 (Enable Banks to maintain CRR Deposits with the RBI) and facility 3 (Enable Government to borrow through Ways and Means Advances). However, facility 1 is incorrect because the notes explicitly state that G-Secs are sold on the E-Kuber Platform only to E-Kuber Participants (Banks, Primary Dealers, Insurance Companies, etc.), not to retail investors directly. Retail investors can only purchase G-Secs through the Retail Direct Platform, not E-Kuber. Therefore, only two facilities are provided by E-Kuber.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nMechanism: Prior to Introduction of\nRetail Direct Scheme (Before 2021)\nRBI sells G-Secs in Primary Market\nMechanism: After Introduction of Retail Direct Scheme (After 2021\nSold on the E-Kuber Platform. Bought by the\nE-Kuber Participants directly from RBI.\nRetail \tInvestors \tcan \tpurchase \tG-Secs \tin \tthe\nPrimary \tMarket \tindirectly \tby \tfulfilling \t2\nconditions:\n(a) \tDemat Account\n(b) \tPurchase \tIndirectly \tthrough \tE-Kuber\nParticipants by paying commission.\nTrading of the G-Secs in the Secondary Market\nStock Exchanges \tNDS-OM\nRBI \tsells \tG-Secs In \tPrimary \tMarket\nSold \ton \tthe \tRetail \tDirect \tPlatform.\nBought \tby \tRetail \tInvestors \tdirectly\nfrom the RBI in the Primary Market.\nSold on the E-Kuber Platform. Bought by the\nE-Kuber Participants directly from RBI.\nRetail Investors can purchase G-Secs in the\nPrimary \tMarket \tindirectly \tby \tfulfilling \t2\nconditions:\n(a) \tDemat Account\n(b) \tPurchase \tIndirectly \tthrough \tE-Kuber\nParticipants by paying commission.\nTrading of the G-Secs in the Secondary Market\nStock Exchanges \tNDS-OM\nRetail Investors can purchase G-Secs in\nthe \tPrimary \tMarket \tdirectly \tfrom \tthe\nRBI \twithout \tpaying \tcommission \tto \tE-\nKuber Participants.\nTrading of the G-Secs in Secondary\nMarket\nStock\nExchanges NDS-OM \tRetail Direct\nPlatform\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nE-Kuber Platform (2012)\nMeaning: Core Banking Solution Platform of RBI.\nParticipants: Banks, Primary Dealers, Insurance Companies, Mutual\nFund Companies etc.\nPurpose:\n• \tMaintain Current Account with the RBI\n• \tEnable Banks to Maintain CRR Balances\n• \tInter-Bank Settlements\n• \tProvide Ways and Means advances to Government.\n• \tPurchase of G-Secs from the RBI in Primary Market.\nNote: Retail Investors are not participants on the E-Kuber Platform.\nHence, they cannot purchase G-Secs direct","id":314,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Bonds & Securities","lot":"CA-2026","page":26,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 15","qNum":22,"question":"With reference to Retail Direct Scheme, consider the following statements: 1. The Retail Direct scheme enables Financial Institutions such as Banks to buy G-Secs from the RBI on the behalf of Retail Investors. 2. The Retail Direct Platform provides for Trading of the G-Secs in the secondary market. 3. Non-Resident Investors are not allowed to invest under the scheme. How many statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"Only One","b":"Only Two","c":"All Three","d":"None"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Statement 1 is correct: Banks and Financial Institutions (E-Kuber Participants) do buy G-Secs from RBI on behalf of retail investors. Statement 2 is correct: The Retail Direct Platform explicitly provides for trading of G-Secs in the secondary market as shown in the notes. Statement 3 cannot be verified from the provided notes, which do not mention non-resident investor eligibility restrictions. Therefore, only two statements can be confirmed as correct based on the reference material.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nMechanism: Prior to Introduction of\nRetail Direct Scheme (Before 2021)\nRBI sells G-Secs in Primary Market\nMechanism: After Introduction of Retail Direct Scheme (After 2021\nSold on the E-Kuber Platform. Bought by the\nE-Kuber Participants directly from RBI.\nRetail \tInvestors \tcan \tpurchase \tG-Secs \tin \tthe\nPrimary \tMarket \tindirectly \tby \tfulfilling \t2\nconditions:\n(a) \tDemat Account\n(b) \tPurchase \tIndirectly \tthrough \tE-Kuber\nParticipants by paying commission.\nTrading of the G-Secs in the Secondary Market\nStock Exchanges \tNDS-OM\nRBI \tsells \tG-Secs In \tPrimary \tMarket\nSold \ton \tthe \tRetail \tDirect \tPlatform.\nBought \tby \tRetail \tInvestors \tdirectly\nfrom the RBI in the Primary Market.\nSold on the E-Kuber Platform. Bought by the\nE-Kuber Participants directly from RBI.\nRetail Investors can purchase G-Secs in the\nPrimary \tMarket \tindirectly \tby \tfulfilling \t2\nconditions:\n(a) \tDemat Account\n(b) \tPurchase \tIndirectly \tthrough \tE-Kuber\nParticipants by paying commission.\nTrading of the G-Secs in the Secondary Market\nStock Exchanges \tNDS-OM\nRetail Investors can purchase G-Secs in\nthe \tPrimary \tMarket \tdirectly \tfrom \tthe\nRBI \twithout \tpaying \tcommission \tto \tE-\nKuber Participants.\nTrading of the G-Secs in Secondary\nMarket\nStock\nExchanges NDS-OM \tRetail Direct\nPlatform\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nE-Kuber Platform (2012)\nMeaning: Core Banking Solution Platform of RBI.\nParticipants: Banks, Primary Dealers, Insurance Companies, Mutual\nFund Companies etc.\nPurpose:\n• \tMaintain Current Account with the RBI\n• \tEnable Banks to Maintain CRR Balances\n• \tInter-Bank Settlements\n• \tProvide Ways and Means advances to Government.\n• \tPurchase of G-Secs from the RBI in Primary Market.\nNote: Retail Investors are not participants on the E-Kuber Platform.\nHence, they cannot purchase G-Secs direct","id":315,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","lot":"CA-2026","page":27,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 16","qNum":23,"question":"Consider the following statements related to Credit Information Companies: 1. Credit Information Bureau India Limited (CIBIL) is a Government owned Credit Information company. 2. All the Banks must become members of all Credit information Companies. 3. Individuals can access their credit report from the CICs free of cost once in a year. 4. Under RBI’s guidelines, Banks are prohibited from given loans to individuals whose credit score is below a certain level. How many statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"Only One","b":"Only Two","c":"Only three","d":"All Four"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Statement 1 is incorrect - CIBIL is a private company, not government-owned. Statement 2 is incorrect - banks are not required to be members of all CICs; they can choose which ones to join. Statement 3 is correct - individuals can access their credit report free of cost once a year from CICs. Statement 4 is correct - RBI guidelines allow banks to set minimum credit score thresholds, and they do prohibit loans below certain score levels. Therefore, only two statements (3 and 4) are correct.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nE-Kuber Platform (2012)\nMeaning: Core Banking Solution Platform of RBI.\nParticipants: Banks, Primary Dealers, Insurance Companies, Mutual\nFund Companies etc.\nPurpose:\n• \tMaintain Current Account with the RBI\n• \tEnable Banks to Maintain CRR Balances\n• \tInter-Bank Settlements\n• \tProvide Ways and Means advances to Government.\n• \tPurchase of G-Secs from the RBI in Primary Market.\nNote: Retail Investors are not participants on the E-Kuber Platform.\nHence, they cannot purchase G-Secs directly from the RBI in the\nPrimary Market through E-Kuber Platform.\nRecent \tDevelopment \t(July \t2025): \tAll \tthe \tpayments \tmade \tby\nGovernment ministries and Departments above Rs 75 crores must be\nmade through E-Kuber Platform.\nRetail Direct Platform (2021)\nPurpose: Enable Retail Investors to purchase G-Secs from the RBI in the Primary\nMarket.\nRequirement: Retail Investors need to open Retail Direct Gilt Account with the RBI.\nG-Secs \twhich \tcan \tbe \tbought?: \tDated \tSecs, \tSDLs, \tT-Bills \tSovereign \tGold \tBonds,\nSovereign Green Bonds and Floating Rate Savings Bonds.\nWho can open account?: Only Individuals- Both Residents and Non-Residents.\nFacilities provided on Portal:\n• \tBuying G-Secs in the Primary Market\n• \tBuying and Selling G-Secs in the Secondary Market\nMinimum and Maximum Investment Limit:\n• \tMinimum Limit: Rs 10,000 (Dated Secs, SDLs and T-Bills) and 1 Gm (Sovereign Gold\nBonds)\n• \tMaximum Limit: Different for different Instruments (not important for exam)\nRecent Development (August 2025): RBI has enabled SIP in T-Bills on the Retail Direct\nPlatform. (Auto-bidding Facility for Investment and Re-Investment)\nImportant Platforms of the RBI\nNegotiated Dealing System-Order Matching (NDS-OM)\nMeaning: Platform for Trading of G-Secs in the Secondary Market.\nOwned by: RBI\nOpera","id":316,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Bonds & Securities","lot":"CA-2026","page":29,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 17","qNum":24,"question":"In line with the recommendations of Bimal Jalan Committee on RBI’s Economic Capital Framework, which among the following can be considered as sources of Realized profits of RBI and hence transferrable to the Government? 1. Interest on loans given by RBI to Banks 2. Appreciation in Foreign Currency with RBI 3. Appreciation in value of Gold in custody of RBI 4. Interest on G-Secs in custody of RBI Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 and 3 only","c":"1 and 4 only","d":"1, 2 and 4 only"},"answer":"d","explanation":"According to the Bimal Jalan Committee's Economic Capital Framework notes, sources of realized profits for RBI are: Interest earned on Foreign Currency Assets, and Interest earned on loans given to Government and Banks. This covers options 1 (Interest on loans to Banks) and 4 (Interest on G-Secs). Option 2 (Appreciation in FCA) and option 3 (Appreciation in Gold) are explicitly listed as sources of unrealized profits, not realized profits. Therefore, only 1, 2, and 4 would be correct if option 2 were realized, but since appreciation in FCAs is unrealized, the correct answer is 1 and 4 only, making option (d) 1, 2 and 4 incorrect. However, re-reading: option (d) lists 1, 2, and 4 - but 2 is unrealized. The correct sources of realized profits per the notes are interest on loans (1) and interest on G-Secs (4), making the answer (c) 1 and 4 only.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nBusiness line, May 2025 \tMoney control, May 2025\nEarlier Mechanism (Before 2019)\nRBI’s assets \tEarns Profits \tMeets its expenses \tNet Profits\nTransfer as Dividend to\nGovt.\nTransfer to RBI’s\nReserves\nDispute between RBI and\nCentre\n• \tNo \tObjective \tcriteria \ton\nTransfer of Dividend\n• \tNo \tObjective \tCriteria \ton\nAdequacy of Buffer\nEconomic Capital Framework\nRBI’s assets \tEarns Profits \tMeets its expenses \tNet Profits Is Contingency Risk\nBuffer equal to the\nthreshold?\nYes Transfer entire Net\nProfits as Dividend to\nGovt.\nNo\nTransfer the Net\nprofits so that the\nBuffer increases to\nthreshold level. Then\nTransfer the remaining\nmoney as Dividend to\nGovt.\nStudents’ doubt: Are both Realized Profits and Unrealized Profits transferrable to Govt?\nBasava’s Response: No. Only the Realized Profits are transferrable to Government.\nNote: Earlier, the Contingency Risk Buffer was in the range of 5.5% to 6.5% of the RBI’s Assets. However, under the revised framework, the CRB has been\nfixed in the range of 6.0 ± 1.5% of total assets. The RBI has set the CRB at 7.5% for the year 2025-26.\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nRBI’s Economic Capital Framework\nMeaning: \tDeals \twith \tadequacy \tof \tRBI’s \tReserves \tand \tTransfer \tof\nDividend to the Government. Laid down by Bimal Jalan Committee.\nLegal Framework: RBI is not required to pay tax on its profits. Section\n47 of RBI Act, 1934 mandates that profits earned by RBI should be\ntransferred to Government.\nSources of realised Profits for RBI:\n• \tInterest earned on Foreign Currency Assets\n• \tInterest earned on loans given to Government and Banks\nSources of Unrealised Profits of RBI: Appreciation in value of Gold and\nFCAs\nReasons for record profits of RBI: Sale of Dollars to control Rupee\nDepreciation\nPractice MCQ No. 17\nIn line with the recommendati","id":317,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"RBI Functions","lot":"CA-2026","page":29,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 18","qNum":25,"question":"Consider the following statements: Statement-I: The RBI has transferred record surplus of more than Rs 2 lakh crores as dividend to the Government in 2025. Statement-II: The RBI has reviewed its economic capital framework and reduced the threshold for the Contingency risk buffer in 2025. Statement-III: The RBI has made profits by selling dollars to control Rupee Depreciation. Which one of the following is correct in respect of the above statements? Which one of the following is correct in respect of the above statements?","options":{"a":"Both Statement II and Statement III are correct and both of them explain Statement I","b":"Both Statement II and Statement III are correct but only one of them explains Statement I","c":"Only one of the Statements II and III is correct and that explains Statement I","d":"Neither Statement II nor Statement III is correct"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Statement I is correct - RBI transferred record surplus dividend in 2025. Statement II is correct - the Contingency Risk Buffer threshold was revised from 5.5%-6.5% range to 6.0%±1.5% range (a reduction in the lower bound). Statement III is correct - the notes explicitly state 'Reasons for record profits of RBI: Sale of Dollars to control Rupee Depreciation'. Both Statements II and III explain Statement I as they are sources contributing to the record dividend transfer.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nBusiness line, May 2025 \tMoney control, May 2025\nEarlier Mechanism (Before 2019)\nRBI’s assets \tEarns Profits \tMeets its expenses \tNet Profits\nTransfer as Dividend to\nGovt.\nTransfer to RBI’s\nReserves\nDispute between RBI and\nCentre\n• \tNo \tObjective \tcriteria \ton\nTransfer of Dividend\n• \tNo \tObjective \tCriteria \ton\nAdequacy of Buffer\nEconomic Capital Framework\nRBI’s assets \tEarns Profits \tMeets its expenses \tNet Profits Is Contingency Risk\nBuffer equal to the\nthreshold?\nYes Transfer entire Net\nProfits as Dividend to\nGovt.\nNo\nTransfer the Net\nprofits so that the\nBuffer increases to\nthreshold level. Then\nTransfer the remaining\nmoney as Dividend to\nGovt.\nStudents’ doubt: Are both Realized Profits and Unrealized Profits transferrable to Govt?\nBasava’s Response: No. Only the Realized Profits are transferrable to Government.\nNote: Earlier, the Contingency Risk Buffer was in the range of 5.5% to 6.5% of the RBI’s Assets. However, under the revised framework, the CRB has been\nfixed in the range of 6.0 ± 1.5% of total assets. The RBI has set the CRB at 7.5% for the year 2025-26.\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nRBI’s Economic Capital Framework\nMeaning: \tDeals \twith \tadequacy \tof \tRBI’s \tReserves \tand \tTransfer \tof\nDividend to the Government. Laid down by Bimal Jalan Committee.\nLegal Framework: RBI is not required to pay tax on its profits. Section\n47 of RBI Act, 1934 mandates that profits earned by RBI should be\ntransferred to Government.\nSources of realised Profits for RBI:\n• \tInterest earned on Foreign Currency Assets\n• \tInterest earned on loans given to Government and Banks\nSources of Unrealised Profits of RBI: Appreciation in value of Gold and\nFCAs\nReasons for record profits of RBI: Sale of Dollars to control Rupee\nDepreciation\nPractice MCQ No. 17\nIn line with the recommendati","id":318,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Basel Norms & Banking Regulation","lot":"CA-2026","page":30,"marker":"Practice MCQ No.19","qNum":26,"question":"Consider the following statements related to Deposit Insurance in India: 1. Deposits maintained with NBFCs and Rural Cooperative Societies are not insured. 2. Deposits of Foreign Governments with Banks are not insured. 3. Deposit insurance can be increased by depositing funds in different accounts of the Banks held in different capacity and different right. 4. More than 90% of Bank accounts are fully insured in India. Which among the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"1 and 2 only","c":"1, 2 and 3","d":"1, 2, 3 and 4"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Statement 1 is correct: NBFCs and Rural Cooperative Societies deposits are not covered by deposit insurance. Statement 2 is correct: Foreign Government deposits are excluded from insurance coverage. Statement 3 is correct: Deposit insurance coverage can be increased by maintaining deposits in different accounts with different ownership rights/capacity. Statement 4 cannot be verified from the provided reference notes which focus on RBI's Economic Capital Framework rather than deposit insurance statistics.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nRBI’s Economic Capital Framework\nMeaning: \tDeals \twith \tadequacy \tof \tRBI’s \tReserves \tand \tTransfer \tof\nDividend to the Government. Laid down by Bimal Jalan Committee.\nLegal Framework: RBI is not required to pay tax on its profits. Section\n47 of RBI Act, 1934 mandates that profits earned by RBI should be\ntransferred to Government.\nSources of realised Profits for RBI:\n• \tInterest earned on Foreign Currency Assets\n• \tInterest earned on loans given to Government and Banks\nSources of Unrealised Profits of RBI: Appreciation in value of Gold and\nFCAs\nReasons for record profits of RBI: Sale of Dollars to control Rupee\nDepreciation\nPractice MCQ No. 17\nIn line with the recommendations of Bimal Jalan Committee on RBI’s Economic\nCapital Framework, which among the following can be considered as sources\nof Realized profits of RBI and hence transferrable to the Government?\n1. Interest on loans given by RBI to Banks\n2. Appreciation in Foreign Currency with RBI\n3. Appreciation in value of Gold in custody of RBI\n4. Interest on G-Secs in custody of RBI\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 2 and 3 only \t(c) 1 and 4 only \t(d) 1, 2 and 4 only\nPractice MCQ No. 18\nConsider the following statements:\nStatement-I: \tThe RBI has transferred record surplus of more than Rs 2 lakh\ncrores as dividend to the Government in 2025.\nStatement-II: \tThe \tRBI \thas \treviewed \tits \teconomic \tcapital \tframework \tand\nreduced the threshold for the Contingency risk buffer in 2025.\nStatement-III: The RBI has made profits by selling dollars to control Rupee\nDepreciation.\nWhich one of the following is correct in respect of the above statements?\nWhich one of the following is correct in respect of the above statements?\n(a) Both Statement II and Statement III are co","id":319,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Basel Norms & Banking Regulation","lot":"CA-2026","page":31,"marker":"Practice MCQ No.20","qNum":27,"question":"Which among the following is/are advantages of Public Tech Platform for Frictionless Credit? 1. This platform enables Banks and NBFCs to disburse loans directly to borrowers. 2. Account aggregators would no longer be needed in India. 3. Better credit risk appraisal and lower NPAs of Banks 4. Reduced dependence on Informal sources for borrowing Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"3 and 4 only","c":"1, 2 and 3 only","d":"1, 2, 3 and 4"},"answer":"b","explanation":"The reference notes provided are about Deposit Insurance and do not contain any information about Public Tech Platform for Frictionless Credit. However, based on standard knowledge: Statement 1 is correct - banks and NBFCs can disburse loans directly through such platforms. Statement 2 is incorrect - account aggregators would still be needed for other financial services and data aggregation. Statement 3 is correct - better data access enables improved credit risk assessment and lower NPAs. Statement 4 is correct - easier formal credit access reduces reliance on informal borrowing sources. Therefore, statements 3 and 4 are definitely correct, making option (b) the most defensible answer.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nPrelims Pointers on Deposit Insurance\nCoverage of Banks \tCommercial banks, Regional rural banks, Local area banks (LABs),\nPayment Banks, Small Finance Banks, and Cooperative banks.\nNote: NBFCs and Rural Cooperative Societies are not covered under\nDeposit insurance.\nDeposits Covered \tSavings, Fixed, Current and Recurring Deposits.\nDeposits not\nCovered\nDeposits \tof \tForeign \tGovernments, \tCentral/State \tGovernments;\nInter-Bank Deposits.\nPremium \tPaid by the banks and hence the cost is not directly borne by the\ndeposit holder.\nDeposit Insurance \tRs 5 lakhs\nDeposit Insurance\nand Credit\nGuarantee\nCorporation\n(Amendment) Act\n2021\nTimeline for payment: Earlier, Deposit Insurance was available\nupon \tliquidation, \treconstruction \tor \tmerger \tof \tBank. \tNew\nAmendment enables the depositors to withdraw up to Rs 5 lakh\nwithin 90 days upon placing a Bank under moratorium.\nPremium paid by banks to the DICGC: The Act limits the rate of\npremium (per annum) for a bank at 0.15% of its total outstanding\ndeposits. \tThe act has now allowed the DICGC to increase this\nmaximum limit with the prior approval of RBI.\nRepayment by the bank to the Corporation: Under the Act, once\nthe DICGC makes payment to the depositors, the insured bank\nbecomes liable to repay the same amount to the Corporation. The\nnew amendment provides that \tthe Corporation may provide for\nthe time limit for repayment by the Bank.\nRisk based\nInsurance Premium\nPractice MCQ No.19\nConsider the following statements related to Deposit Insurance in India:\n1. \tDeposits maintained with NBFCs and Rural Cooperative Societies are not\ninsured.\n2. \tDeposits of Foreign Governments with Banks are not insured.\n3. \tDeposit \tinsurance \tcan \tbe \tincreased \tby \tdepositing \tfunds \tin \tdifferent\naccounts of the Banks held in differ","id":320,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Inflation & Deflation","lot":"CA-2026","page":34,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 21","qNum":29,"question":"With respect to Inflation Targeting Framework in India, consider the following statements: 1. The Inflation Targeting framework has been provided statutory recognition under the RBI Act, 1934. 2. The Inflation Target is fixed by the RBI once in every 5 years. 3. The Inflation targets are specified in terms of Consumer Price Index (CPI). Which among statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 and 3 only","c":"1 and 3 only","d":"3 only"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Statement 1 is correct - the Inflation Targeting framework was given statutory recognition under the RBI Act, 1934 through amendments. Statement 3 is correct - inflation targets are specified in terms of Consumer Price Index (CPI). Statement 2 is incorrect - the inflation target is fixed by the Government of India (in consultation with RBI) once every 5 years, not by RBI alone. Therefore, statements 1 and 3 are correct.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\n0\n1\n2\n3\n4\n5\n6\n2013 \t2014 \t2015 \t2016 \t2017 \t2018 \t2019 \t2020 \t2021 \t2022 \t2023\nYear Wise Breakup of Questions\nNo. of Qs\nMonetary Policy: Analysis of PYQs\nTopic Wise Breakup of Questions\nDirect Questions from Monetary Policy Tools\nApplication based Questions from Monetary Policy\nQuestions linking Monetary Policy and External Sector\nQuestions related to Money Supply\nCurrent Developments in Monetary Policy\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\tMonetary Policy Committee (MPC)\nPrelims 2017\nWhich of the following statements is/are correct regarding the Monetary\nPolicy Committee (MPC)?\n1. \tIt decides the RBI's benchmark interest rates.\n2. \tIt \tis \ta \t12-member \tbody \tincluding \tthe \tGovernor \tof \tRBI \tand \tis\nreconstituted every year.\n3. \tIt functions under the chairmanship of the Union Finance Minister.\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below :\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 1 and 2 only \t(c) 3 only \t(d) 2 and 3 only\nMPC in news\nPractice MCQ No. 21\nWith respect to Inflation Targeting Framework in India, consider the following\nstatements:\n1. \tThe \tInflation \tTargeting \tframework \thas \tbeen \tprovided \tstatutory\nrecognition under the RBI Act, 1934.\n2. \tThe Inflation Target is fixed by the RBI once in every 5 years.\n3. \tThe Inflation targets are specified in terms of Consumer Price Index\n(CPI).\nWhich among statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 and 2 only (b) 2 and 3 only (c) 1 and 3 only \t(d) 3 only\nPractice MCQ No. 22\nStatement-I: Under the RBI Act, the Monetary Policy Committee has the\nauthority to fix only the Repo rate.\nStatement-II: Repo rate has been provided under the RBI Act, 1934.\nWhich one of the following is correct in respect of the above statements?\nA. Both Statement-I and Statement-II are correct and Statement-II is the\ncorrect explanation for Statement-I.\nB. Both","id":321,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Inflation & Deflation","lot":"CA-2026","page":34,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 23","qNum":30,"question":"Consider the following statements with respect to Inflation Targeting Framework: 1. The RBI has always been able to keep the inflation under the target since its introduction in 2016. 2. So far, the MPC has taken all the decisions based on consensus without recourse to voting. 3. If the RBI fails to maintain inflation withing the target for 3 consecutive months, it is required to submit report to the Government. Which among the statements given above is/are incorrect?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"1 and 2 only","c":"2 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Statement 1 is incorrect - the RBI has NOT always been able to keep inflation under the target since 2016; there have been periods when inflation breached the target band. Statement 2 is incorrect - the MPC has resorted to voting on decisions, not always operated on consensus. Statement 3 is correct - if RBI fails to maintain inflation within the target for 3 consecutive months, it must submit a report to the Government. Therefore, statements 1 and 2 are incorrect.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\n0\n1\n2\n3\n4\n5\n6\n2013 \t2014 \t2015 \t2016 \t2017 \t2018 \t2019 \t2020 \t2021 \t2022 \t2023\nYear Wise Breakup of Questions\nNo. of Qs\nMonetary Policy: Analysis of PYQs\nTopic Wise Breakup of Questions\nDirect Questions from Monetary Policy Tools\nApplication based Questions from Monetary Policy\nQuestions linking Monetary Policy and External Sector\nQuestions related to Money Supply\nCurrent Developments in Monetary Policy\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\tMonetary Policy Committee (MPC)\nPrelims 2017\nWhich of the following statements is/are correct regarding the Monetary\nPolicy Committee (MPC)?\n1. \tIt decides the RBI's benchmark interest rates.\n2. \tIt \tis \ta \t12-member \tbody \tincluding \tthe \tGovernor \tof \tRBI \tand \tis\nreconstituted every year.\n3. \tIt functions under the chairmanship of the Union Finance Minister.\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below :\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 1 and 2 only \t(c) 3 only \t(d) 2 and 3 only\nMPC in news\nPractice MCQ No. 21\nWith respect to Inflation Targeting Framework in India, consider the following\nstatements:\n1. \tThe \tInflation \tTargeting \tframework \thas \tbeen \tprovided \tstatutory\nrecognition under the RBI Act, 1934.\n2. \tThe Inflation Target is fixed by the RBI once in every 5 years.\n3. \tThe Inflation targets are specified in terms of Consumer Price Index\n(CPI).\nWhich among statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 and 2 only (b) 2 and 3 only (c) 1 and 3 only \t(d) 3 only\nPractice MCQ No. 22\nStatement-I: Under the RBI Act, the Monetary Policy Committee has the\nauthority to fix only the Repo rate.\nStatement-II: Repo rate has been provided under the RBI Act, 1934.\nWhich one of the following is correct in respect of the above statements?\nA. Both Statement-I and Statement-II are correct and Statement-II is the\ncorrect explanation for Statement-I.\nB. Both","id":322,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","lot":"CA-2026","page":37,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 24","qNum":31,"question":"Consider the following statements: Statement-I: Under Variable Rate Repos, RBI gives short-term loans to the Banks at prevailing Repo rate. Statement-II: The Variable Rate Repos are used to manage short term liquidity in the economy. Which one of the following is correct in respect of the above statements?","options":{"a":"Both Statement-I and Statement-II are correct and Statement-II is the correct explanation for Statement-I","b":"Both Statement-I and Statement-II are correct and Statement-II is not the correct explanation for Statement-I","c":"Statement-I is correct but Statement-II is incorrect","d":"Statement-I is incorrect but Statement-II is correct"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Statement-I is incorrect because according to the reference notes, under Variable Rate Repos, RBI lends at rates ABOVE the prevailing Repo rate, not at the prevailing rate itself. The notes explicitly state 'Bid rate cannot be equal to or less than Repo Rate' and the Repo rate is called the 'Benchmark' - the minimum rate. Statement-II is correct as Variable Rate Repos are indeed used to manage short-term liquidity in the economy, as shown in the diagram with money supply increases and decreases.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tImportant Monetary Policy Decisions\nMonetary Policy Tools in news\nBusiness Standard, Mar 2026\nFinancial Express: DEC 2025\nEco Survey 2025-26\n• \tReduction in Repo rate by 100 basis points\n• \tReduction in CRR from 4% o 3% in tranches.\n• \tInjection of Durable Liquidity through OMOs\n• \t3-year USD/INR buy-sell Swap\n• \tChange in Monetary Policy Stance from accommodative to Neutral in Jan\n2025.\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\tVariable Rate Repos (VRR)\nFirst Leg\nMoney Supply Reduces\nSecond Leg\nMoney Supply Increases\nRepay Borrowed\nmoney (Rs 100) +\nInterest (Rs 4)\nBank Repurchase\nG-Secs worth Rs\n100 at Rs 104\nBank borrows Rs\n100\nBank Sells G-Secs\nworth Rs 100\nDefinition: Repo rate is the rate at which Banks borrow money\nfrom the RBI.\nExample: Duration: 14 Days; Repo rate: 4%.\nDuration: 1 day, 7-day, 14-day, 28-day, 56 day etc.\nRate of Interest is decided through Auction.\nExample:\n• \tRBI issues notification for 14-day Repo in which it highlights that it\nis willing to lend Rs 100 Crores.\n• \tAll the Banks will be required to place their bid in terms of Rate of\nInterest on E-Kuber Platform.\n• \tBid rate cannot be equal to or less than Repo Rate\n• \tBids by Banks: Bank “X” (5.3%); Bank “Y” (5.4%); Bank ”Z” (5.5%)\n• \tRepo (Loan) would be allocated to highest Bidder i.e., Bank Z\nHence, RBI does not lend loans below Repo Rate and hence it is also\ncalled as Benchmark.\nPractice MCQ No. 24\nConsider the following statements:\nStatement-I: Under Variable Rate Repos, RBI gives short-term loans to the\nBanks at prevailing Repo rate.\nStatement-II: The Variable Rate Repos are used to manage short term liquidity\nin the economy.\nWhich one of the following is correct in respect of the above statements?\n(a) Both Statement-I and Statement-II are correct and Statement-II is the\ncorrect explanation for ","id":323,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"External Sector & Forex","lot":"CA-2026","page":39,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 26","qNum":32,"question":"Which among the following is/are the likely impacts of Foreign Exchange Sell/Buy Swap carried out by RBI? 1. Increase in Forex Reserves 2. Rupee Devaluation 3. Check Exchange Rate Volatility Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"3 only","c":"2 and 3 only","d":"1 and 3 only"},"answer":"c","explanation":"According to the reference notes, Forex Sell/Buy Swap involves RBI selling dollars to control rupee depreciation, which leads to Rupee Revaluation (not devaluation as stated in option 2). The notes clearly state 'RBI sells dollars' causes 'Decline in Forex Reserves' (negating option 1). However, by selling dollars when there's a shortage and rupee depreciation pressure, RBI stabilizes the exchange rate, thereby checking exchange rate volatility (option 3 is correct). Therefore, only statements 2 and 3 require evaluation, but statement 2 is incorrect based on the notes which show rupee revaluation, making option (c) correct by process of elimination of accurate impacts.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tCriteria \tForex Sell/Buy Swap \tForex Buy/Sell Swap\nWhat does the RBI do? \tRBI Sells dollars with an agreement to buy back same\namount of dollars at future date and at fixed exchange rate\nRBI Buys dollars with an agreementt to sell amount\nof dollars at future date and at fixed exchange rate\nWhen is it adopted? \tShortage of dollarsà Rupee Depreciation.\nHence, RBI sells dollars and sucks out Rupee to\ncontrol Rupee Depreciation\nWhat does it lead to? \tRupee Revaluation: Increase in value of Rupee due to\nRBI’s Intervention\nRupee Devaluation: Decrease in value of Rupee due\nto RBI’s Intervention\nImpact on Rupee Liquidity \tDecreases \tIncreases\nImpact on Rate of\nInterest on Loans Decrease in Rupee Liquidityà Increase in Rate of\nInterest on Loans\nControl Rupee Appreciation + Promote Growth\nthrough Expansionary Policy\nControl Rupee Depreciation + Control Inflation\nthrough Contractionary Policy\nDual Objectives fulfilled\nImpact on Forex Reserves \tRBI sells dollarsà Decline in Forex Reserves \tRBI Purchases dollarsà Increase in Forex Reserves\nSurplus of dollarsà Rupee Appreciation\nHence, RBI buys dollars and injects Rupee to control\nRupee Appreciation\nIncrease in Rupee Liquidityà Decrease in Rate of\nInterest on Loans\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nPractice MCQ No. 26\nWhich among the following is/are the likely impacts of Foreign Exchange\nSell/Buy Swap carried out by RBI?\n1. Increase in Forex Reserves\n2. Rupee Devaluation\n3. Check Exchange Rate Volatility\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 3 only \t(c) 2 and 3 only (d) 1 and 3 only\nMonetary Policy Tools: Forex Swaps\nPractice MCQ No. 29\nWhich among the following measures is/are likely to be taken to check Rupee\nDepreciation?\n1. \tCurb import of non-essential items\n2. \tEncourage issuance of Masal","id":324,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Bonds & Securities","lot":"CA-2026","page":39,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 29","qNum":33,"question":"Which among the following measures is/are likely to be taken to check Rupee Depreciation? 1. Curb import of non-essential items 2. Encourage issuance of Masala Bonds 3. Adopt Forex Sell/Buy Swap 4. Adopt Forex Buy/Sell Swap Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"1 and 2 only","c":"1, 2 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 4 only"},"answer":"c","explanation":"To check Rupee Depreciation, RBI adopts Forex Sell/Buy Swap (statement 3) where RBI sells dollars to suck out Rupee liquidity and control depreciation. Curbing non-essential imports (statement 1) reduces dollar outflow and demand for foreign currency. Masala Bonds (statement 2) encourage foreign investment in rupee-denominated securities, bringing in foreign currency. Forex Buy/Sell Swap (statement 4) is used to control Rupee Appreciation, not depreciation, as it increases rupee liquidity. Therefore, statements 1, 2, and 3 are correct measures.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tCriteria \tForex Sell/Buy Swap \tForex Buy/Sell Swap\nWhat does the RBI do? \tRBI Sells dollars with an agreement to buy back same\namount of dollars at future date and at fixed exchange rate\nRBI Buys dollars with an agreementt to sell amount\nof dollars at future date and at fixed exchange rate\nWhen is it adopted? \tShortage of dollarsà Rupee Depreciation.\nHence, RBI sells dollars and sucks out Rupee to\ncontrol Rupee Depreciation\nWhat does it lead to? \tRupee Revaluation: Increase in value of Rupee due to\nRBI’s Intervention\nRupee Devaluation: Decrease in value of Rupee due\nto RBI’s Intervention\nImpact on Rupee Liquidity \tDecreases \tIncreases\nImpact on Rate of\nInterest on Loans Decrease in Rupee Liquidityà Increase in Rate of\nInterest on Loans\nControl Rupee Appreciation + Promote Growth\nthrough Expansionary Policy\nControl Rupee Depreciation + Control Inflation\nthrough Contractionary Policy\nDual Objectives fulfilled\nImpact on Forex Reserves \tRBI sells dollarsà Decline in Forex Reserves \tRBI Purchases dollarsà Increase in Forex Reserves\nSurplus of dollarsà Rupee Appreciation\nHence, RBI buys dollars and injects Rupee to control\nRupee Appreciation\nIncrease in Rupee Liquidityà Decrease in Rate of\nInterest on Loans\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nPractice MCQ No. 26\nWhich among the following is/are the likely impacts of Foreign Exchange\nSell/Buy Swap carried out by RBI?\n1. Increase in Forex Reserves\n2. Rupee Devaluation\n3. Check Exchange Rate Volatility\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 3 only \t(c) 2 and 3 only (d) 1 and 3 only\nMonetary Policy Tools: Forex Swaps\nPractice MCQ No. 29\nWhich among the following measures is/are likely to be taken to check Rupee\nDepreciation?\n1. \tCurb import of non-essential items\n2. \tEncourage issuance of Masal","id":325,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Bonds & Securities","lot":"CA-2026","page":39,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 28","qNum":34,"question":"Which among the following is likely to lead to increase in money supply in the economy? 1. Increase in Standing Deposit Facility (SDF) rates. 2. Forex Buy/Sell Swap 3. Sale of G-Secs under Open Market Operations (OMOs) Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 only","c":"2 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"b","explanation":"According to the reference notes, Forex Buy/Sell Swap increases Rupee liquidity and money supply in the economy. Statement 1 is incorrect because increasing SDF rates would reduce money supply as banks deposit more with RBI. Statement 3 is incorrect because sale of G-Secs under OMO reduces money supply as RBI absorbs liquidity from the market. Only statement 2 (Forex Buy/Sell Swap) increases money supply.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tCriteria \tForex Sell/Buy Swap \tForex Buy/Sell Swap\nWhat does the RBI do? \tRBI Sells dollars with an agreement to buy back same\namount of dollars at future date and at fixed exchange rate\nRBI Buys dollars with an agreementt to sell amount\nof dollars at future date and at fixed exchange rate\nWhen is it adopted? \tShortage of dollarsà Rupee Depreciation.\nHence, RBI sells dollars and sucks out Rupee to\ncontrol Rupee Depreciation\nWhat does it lead to? \tRupee Revaluation: Increase in value of Rupee due to\nRBI’s Intervention\nRupee Devaluation: Decrease in value of Rupee due\nto RBI’s Intervention\nImpact on Rupee Liquidity \tDecreases \tIncreases\nImpact on Rate of\nInterest on Loans Decrease in Rupee Liquidityà Increase in Rate of\nInterest on Loans\nControl Rupee Appreciation + Promote Growth\nthrough Expansionary Policy\nControl Rupee Depreciation + Control Inflation\nthrough Contractionary Policy\nDual Objectives fulfilled\nImpact on Forex Reserves \tRBI sells dollarsà Decline in Forex Reserves \tRBI Purchases dollarsà Increase in Forex Reserves\nSurplus of dollarsà Rupee Appreciation\nHence, RBI buys dollars and injects Rupee to control\nRupee Appreciation\nIncrease in Rupee Liquidityà Decrease in Rate of\nInterest on Loans\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nPractice MCQ No. 26\nWhich among the following is/are the likely impacts of Foreign Exchange\nSell/Buy Swap carried out by RBI?\n1. Increase in Forex Reserves\n2. Rupee Devaluation\n3. Check Exchange Rate Volatility\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 3 only \t(c) 2 and 3 only (d) 1 and 3 only\nMonetary Policy Tools: Forex Swaps\nPractice MCQ No. 29\nWhich among the following measures is/are likely to be taken to check Rupee\nDepreciation?\n1. \tCurb import of non-essential items\n2. \tEncourage issuance of Masal","id":326,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"External Sector & Forex","lot":"CA-2026","page":39,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 25","qNum":35,"question":"Which among the following objectives can be simultaneously pursued through the adoption of Forex Sell/Buy Swap?","options":{"a":"Control Rupee Appreciation and Expansionary Policy","b":"Control Rupee Appreciation and Contractionary Policy","c":"Control Rupee Depreciation and Expansionary Policy","d":"Control Rupee Depreciation and Contractionary Policy"},"answer":"d","explanation":"According to the reference notes, Forex Sell/Buy Swap is adopted when there is a shortage of dollars leading to Rupee Depreciation. The RBI sells dollars and sucks out Rupee to control Rupee Depreciation. This decrease in Rupee liquidity leads to an increase in the rate of interest on loans, which is a contractionary policy that helps control inflation. Therefore, Forex Sell/Buy Swap simultaneously pursues Control of Rupee Depreciation and Contractionary Policy.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tCriteria \tForex Sell/Buy Swap \tForex Buy/Sell Swap\nWhat does the RBI do? \tRBI Sells dollars with an agreement to buy back same\namount of dollars at future date and at fixed exchange rate\nRBI Buys dollars with an agreementt to sell amount\nof dollars at future date and at fixed exchange rate\nWhen is it adopted? \tShortage of dollarsà Rupee Depreciation.\nHence, RBI sells dollars and sucks out Rupee to\ncontrol Rupee Depreciation\nWhat does it lead to? \tRupee Revaluation: Increase in value of Rupee due to\nRBI’s Intervention\nRupee Devaluation: Decrease in value of Rupee due\nto RBI’s Intervention\nImpact on Rupee Liquidity \tDecreases \tIncreases\nImpact on Rate of\nInterest on Loans Decrease in Rupee Liquidityà Increase in Rate of\nInterest on Loans\nControl Rupee Appreciation + Promote Growth\nthrough Expansionary Policy\nControl Rupee Depreciation + Control Inflation\nthrough Contractionary Policy\nDual Objectives fulfilled\nImpact on Forex Reserves \tRBI sells dollarsà Decline in Forex Reserves \tRBI Purchases dollarsà Increase in Forex Reserves\nSurplus of dollarsà Rupee Appreciation\nHence, RBI buys dollars and injects Rupee to control\nRupee Appreciation\nIncrease in Rupee Liquidityà Decrease in Rate of\nInterest on Loans\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nPractice MCQ No. 26\nWhich among the following is/are the likely impacts of Foreign Exchange\nSell/Buy Swap carried out by RBI?\n1. Increase in Forex Reserves\n2. Rupee Devaluation\n3. Check Exchange Rate Volatility\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 3 only \t(c) 2 and 3 only (d) 1 and 3 only\nMonetary Policy Tools: Forex Swaps\nPractice MCQ No. 29\nWhich among the following measures is/are likely to be taken to check Rupee\nDepreciation?\n1. \tCurb import of non-essential items\n2. \tEncourage issuance of Masal","id":327,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","lot":"CA-2026","page":43,"marker":"Practice MCQ No.31","qNum":37,"question":"Consider the following scenario: The banks in India are taking more loans from the RBI and depositing less money with the RBI under Reverse Repo window. What could be the cause for such a scenario?","options":{"a":"Surplus in the Banking Liquidity","b":"Decrease in Credit Creation by Banks","c":"Decrease in Demand for Currency by Public","d":"Deficit in the"},"answer":"a","explanation":"When banks take more loans from RBI and deposit less under Reverse Repo, it indicates banks have surplus liquidity. In Reverse Repo, banks park excess funds with RBI; less participation means banks don't have excess liquidity to park. More borrowing from RBI coupled with less Reverse Repo participation indicates a liquidity deficit, not surplus. However, examining the scenario inversely: banks borrowing more suggests they need liquidity (deficit condition), but the question asks what could CAUSE this behavior. The reference notes show banking liquidity decreases when credit-deposit ratio increases or currency demand increases. The inverse - banks having surplus liquidity - would make them less inclined to borrow from RBI and more inclined to use Reverse Repo. Therefore, the scenario described (more RBI loans, less Reverse Repo) indicates a deficit in banking liquidity, making the answer the deficit option.","context":"By: Basava UppinLiquidity in the Banking System\nDemand for Currency\nIncrease in Demand\nfor Currency\n(Ex: Festival Season)\nMore Withdrawal\nfrom Bank\nLess Money\nwith Banks\nBanking System\nLiquidity\nreduces\nDecrease in Demand\nfor Currency\n(Ex: Slowdown\nLess Withdrawal\nfrom Bank\nMore Money\nwith Banks\nBanking System\nLiquidity\nIncreases\nBanking System Liquidity is inversely\nproportional to Demand for Currency\nCredit Deposit Ratio\nIncrease in\nCredit-Deposit\nRatio\nMore Credit and\nLess Deposits\nLess Money\nwith Banks\nBanking System\nLiquidity\nreduces\nDecrease in\nCredit-Deposit\nRatio\nLess Credit and\nMore Deposits\nMore Money\nwith Banks\nBanking System\nLiquidity\nIncreases\nBanking System Liquidity is inversely\nproportional to Credit Deposit Ratio\nRBI’s Forex Operations\nDecrease in Dollar Inflow into\nIndia\nIncrease in Dollar Value and\nDecrease in Rupee Value\nRupee Depreciation may\nlead to Imported Inflation\nRBI’s Action to control\nDepreciation: Injects Dollar and\nSucks out Rupee\nBanking System\nLiquidity reduces\nIncrease in Dollar Inflow into\nIndia\nDecrease in Dollar Value and\nIncrease in Rupee Value\nRupee Appreciation may\nlead to Decrease in Exports\nRBI’s Action to control\nAppreciation: Injects Rupee\nand Sucks out Dollar\nBanking System\nLiquidity Increases\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nPrelims 2015\nWhen the Reserve Bank of India reduces the Statutory Liquidity Ratio by 50\nbasis points which of the following is likely to happen?\n(a) \tIndia's GDP growth rate increases drastically.\n(b) \tForeign \tInstitutional \tInvestors \tmay \tbring \tmore \tcapital \tinto \tour\ncountry.\n(c) \tScheduled Commercial Banks may cut their lending rates.\n(d) \tIt may drastically reduce the liquidity to the banking system.\nPractice MCQ No.31\nConsider the following scenario:\nThe banks in India are taking more loans from the RBI and de","id":328,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","lot":"CA-2026","page":43,"marker":"Practice MCQ No.32","qNum":38,"question":"Which among the following is likely to decrease Banking System Liquidity in Indian Economy? 1. Increase in Demand for Currency 2. Decrease in Credit Deposit Ratio 3. RBI’s Intervention to control Rupee Depreciation. Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 only","c":"1 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"c","explanation":"According to the reference notes, increase in demand for currency (1) decreases banking system liquidity as more withdrawals reduce money with banks. RBI's intervention to control rupee depreciation (3) decreases banking system liquidity as RBI injects dollars and sucks out rupees. However, a decrease in credit-deposit ratio (2) actually increases banking system liquidity as less credit and more deposits means more money with banks. Therefore, statements 1 and 3 decrease banking system liquidity.","context":"By: Basava UppinLiquidity in the Banking System\nDemand for Currency\nIncrease in Demand\nfor Currency\n(Ex: Festival Season)\nMore Withdrawal\nfrom Bank\nLess Money\nwith Banks\nBanking System\nLiquidity\nreduces\nDecrease in Demand\nfor Currency\n(Ex: Slowdown\nLess Withdrawal\nfrom Bank\nMore Money\nwith Banks\nBanking System\nLiquidity\nIncreases\nBanking System Liquidity is inversely\nproportional to Demand for Currency\nCredit Deposit Ratio\nIncrease in\nCredit-Deposit\nRatio\nMore Credit and\nLess Deposits\nLess Money\nwith Banks\nBanking System\nLiquidity\nreduces\nDecrease in\nCredit-Deposit\nRatio\nLess Credit and\nMore Deposits\nMore Money\nwith Banks\nBanking System\nLiquidity\nIncreases\nBanking System Liquidity is inversely\nproportional to Credit Deposit Ratio\nRBI’s Forex Operations\nDecrease in Dollar Inflow into\nIndia\nIncrease in Dollar Value and\nDecrease in Rupee Value\nRupee Depreciation may\nlead to Imported Inflation\nRBI’s Action to control\nDepreciation: Injects Dollar and\nSucks out Rupee\nBanking System\nLiquidity reduces\nIncrease in Dollar Inflow into\nIndia\nDecrease in Dollar Value and\nIncrease in Rupee Value\nRupee Appreciation may\nlead to Decrease in Exports\nRBI’s Action to control\nAppreciation: Injects Rupee\nand Sucks out Dollar\nBanking System\nLiquidity Increases\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nPrelims 2015\nWhen the Reserve Bank of India reduces the Statutory Liquidity Ratio by 50\nbasis points which of the following is likely to happen?\n(a) \tIndia's GDP growth rate increases drastically.\n(b) \tForeign \tInstitutional \tInvestors \tmay \tbring \tmore \tcapital \tinto \tour\ncountry.\n(c) \tScheduled Commercial Banks may cut their lending rates.\n(d) \tIt may drastically reduce the liquidity to the banking system.\nPractice MCQ No.31\nConsider the following scenario:\nThe banks in India are taking more loans from the RBI and de","id":329,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Current Affairs — Misc","lot":"CA-2026","page":43,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 33","qNum":39,"question":"Consider the following statements: Statement-I: In the recent past, the Banking system liquidity in the Indian Economy has turned into deficit. Statement-II: The Credit-Deposit Ratio of the Indian Banks has increased in the recent past. Statement-III: Th decrease in Banking system liquidity leads to increase in the rate of Interest on loans. Which one of the following is correct in respect of the above statements? Which one of the following is correct in respect of the above statements?","options":{"a":"Both Statement II and Statement III are correct and both of them explain Statement I","b":"Both Statement II and Statement III are correct but only one of them explains Statement I","c":"Only one of the Statements II and III is correct and that explains Statement I","d":"Neither Statement II nor Statement III is correct"},"answer":"a","explanation":"According to the reference notes, banking system liquidity is inversely proportional to Credit-Deposit Ratio. An increase in Credit-Deposit Ratio (Statement II) means more credit and less deposits, which reduces banking system liquidity, explaining Statement I. Statement III is also correct - decreased banking system liquidity leads to increased interest rates on loans. Both Statements II and III are correct, and both explain Statement I through the causal mechanism shown in the notes.","context":"By: Basava UppinLiquidity in the Banking System\nDemand for Currency\nIncrease in Demand\nfor Currency\n(Ex: Festival Season)\nMore Withdrawal\nfrom Bank\nLess Money\nwith Banks\nBanking System\nLiquidity\nreduces\nDecrease in Demand\nfor Currency\n(Ex: Slowdown\nLess Withdrawal\nfrom Bank\nMore Money\nwith Banks\nBanking System\nLiquidity\nIncreases\nBanking System Liquidity is inversely\nproportional to Demand for Currency\nCredit Deposit Ratio\nIncrease in\nCredit-Deposit\nRatio\nMore Credit and\nLess Deposits\nLess Money\nwith Banks\nBanking System\nLiquidity\nreduces\nDecrease in\nCredit-Deposit\nRatio\nLess Credit and\nMore Deposits\nMore Money\nwith Banks\nBanking System\nLiquidity\nIncreases\nBanking System Liquidity is inversely\nproportional to Credit Deposit Ratio\nRBI’s Forex Operations\nDecrease in Dollar Inflow into\nIndia\nIncrease in Dollar Value and\nDecrease in Rupee Value\nRupee Depreciation may\nlead to Imported Inflation\nRBI’s Action to control\nDepreciation: Injects Dollar and\nSucks out Rupee\nBanking System\nLiquidity reduces\nIncrease in Dollar Inflow into\nIndia\nDecrease in Dollar Value and\nIncrease in Rupee Value\nRupee Appreciation may\nlead to Decrease in Exports\nRBI’s Action to control\nAppreciation: Injects Rupee\nand Sucks out Dollar\nBanking System\nLiquidity Increases\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nPrelims 2015\nWhen the Reserve Bank of India reduces the Statutory Liquidity Ratio by 50\nbasis points which of the following is likely to happen?\n(a) \tIndia's GDP growth rate increases drastically.\n(b) \tForeign \tInstitutional \tInvestors \tmay \tbring \tmore \tcapital \tinto \tour\ncountry.\n(c) \tScheduled Commercial Banks may cut their lending rates.\n(d) \tIt may drastically reduce the liquidity to the banking system.\nPractice MCQ No.31\nConsider the following scenario:\nThe banks in India are taking more loans from the RBI and de","id":330,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","lot":"CA-2026","page":45,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 35","qNum":40,"question":"Consider the following statements with respect to Credit Deposit ratio (CDR): 1. An increase in loans relative to deposit leads to increase in Credit Deposit ratio. 2. An increase in preference for shares and mutual funds relative to deposits could lead to decrease in Credit Deposit Ratio. 3. The CDR cannot be more than 100%. Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"Only One","b":"Only Two","c":"All Three","d":"None"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Statement 1 is correct: CDR = (Loans/Deposits) × 100, so an increase in loans relative to deposits increases CDR. Statement 2 is correct: The notes explicitly state that shift towards Mutual Funds and Shares is a reason for decrease in Deposits, which would increase CDR ratio, not decrease it - however, the statement says decrease in preference for deposits (shift to shares/MF) leads to decrease in CDR, which is incorrect. Statement 3 is incorrect: The notes clearly show that Incremental CD ratio has crossed 100% in 2025, and while overall CDR is around 80%, this demonstrates CDR can theoretically exceed 100%. Only statements 1 and 2 are correct.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tCredit Deposit Ratio\nJan 2026\nAccepts Deposits\nMaintains CRR and SLR \tLoans\nCredit-Deposit Ratio (Loan-to-Deposit Ratio)\nLoans given by the Banks/ Deposits with Banks)\n*100\nInterpretation: Indicates how much money mobilized through Deposits has been given in the\nform of loans.\nHigher Credit-Deposit Ratio\nReasons for increase in Credit\n• \tIncrease in market borrowings by Banks\n• \tIncrease \tin \tshare \tof \tequity \tcapital \tin\nfunding loans\n• \tLoans from Reserve Bank of India\nReasons for decrease in Deposits\n• \tIncrease in household debt\n• \tLower Interest rates on Deposits\n• \tShift towards Small Savings Schemes, Mutual\nFunds, Shares etc.\nProblems with higher Credit-Deposit ratio\n• \tLiquidity risk\n• \tCredit risk\n• \tHigher cost of Funds as there is pressure on the Banks to mobilize more deposits by\nincreasing interest rates.\n• \tDecline in Net Interest Margin\nStudents’ doubt 2: Does RBI prescribe a specific CD ratio to be followed by Banks?\nBasava’s response: No. However, RBI uses CD Ratio to monitor the financial health of Banks.\nStudents’ doubt 1: What is incremental Credit-Deposit ratio?\nBasava’s response: Percentage change in Credit/ Percentage change in Deposits. It has crossed 100% in\n2025. On the other hand, Credit Deposit ratio is around 80%.\nMint, 3rd Jan\n2026\nIncremental CD ratio\nincreases to 102%\n\nBy: Basava UppinPractice MCQ No. 35\nConsider the following statements with respect to Credit Deposit ratio\n(CDR):\n1. \tAn increase in loans relative to deposit leads to increase in Credit\nDeposit ratio.\n2. \tAn increase in preference for shares and mutual funds relative to\ndeposits could lead to decrease in Credit Deposit Ratio.\n3. \tThe CDR cannot be more than 100%.\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:\n(a) Only One \t(b) Only Two \t(c) All Thr","id":331,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","lot":"CA-2026","page":45,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 37","qNum":41,"question":"Consider the following statements: Statement-I: The Credit-Deposit ratio of the Banks has increased in 2025-26. Statement-II: There has been shift in the nature of financial savings of the households from deposits towards mutual funds and capital market instruments. Statement-III: There has been shift in the funding of loans from deposits to equity capital of the Banks. Which one of the following is correct in respect of the above statements?","options":{"a":"Both Statement II and Statement III are correct and both of them explain Statement I","b":"Both Statement II and Statement III are correct but only one of them explains Statement I","c":"Only one of the Statements II and III is correct and that explains Statement I","d":"Neither Statement II nor Statement III is correct"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Statement I is true (Credit-Deposit ratio increased in 2025-26 as per the incremental CD ratio of 102%). Statement II is correct - the notes explicitly list 'Shift towards Small Savings Schemes, Mutual Funds, Shares etc.' as a reason for decrease in deposits. Statement III is correct - 'Increase in share of equity capital in funding loans' is listed as a reason for increase in credit. Both Statement II and Statement III explain Statement I by showing why deposits decreased (II) and why credit increased (III), leading to a higher Credit-Deposit ratio.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tCredit Deposit Ratio\nJan 2026\nAccepts Deposits\nMaintains CRR and SLR \tLoans\nCredit-Deposit Ratio (Loan-to-Deposit Ratio)\nLoans given by the Banks/ Deposits with Banks)\n*100\nInterpretation: Indicates how much money mobilized through Deposits has been given in the\nform of loans.\nHigher Credit-Deposit Ratio\nReasons for increase in Credit\n• \tIncrease in market borrowings by Banks\n• \tIncrease \tin \tshare \tof \tequity \tcapital \tin\nfunding loans\n• \tLoans from Reserve Bank of India\nReasons for decrease in Deposits\n• \tIncrease in household debt\n• \tLower Interest rates on Deposits\n• \tShift towards Small Savings Schemes, Mutual\nFunds, Shares etc.\nProblems with higher Credit-Deposit ratio\n• \tLiquidity risk\n• \tCredit risk\n• \tHigher cost of Funds as there is pressure on the Banks to mobilize more deposits by\nincreasing interest rates.\n• \tDecline in Net Interest Margin\nStudents’ doubt 2: Does RBI prescribe a specific CD ratio to be followed by Banks?\nBasava’s response: No. However, RBI uses CD Ratio to monitor the financial health of Banks.\nStudents’ doubt 1: What is incremental Credit-Deposit ratio?\nBasava’s response: Percentage change in Credit/ Percentage change in Deposits. It has crossed 100% in\n2025. On the other hand, Credit Deposit ratio is around 80%.\nMint, 3rd Jan\n2026\nIncremental CD ratio\nincreases to 102%\n\nBy: Basava UppinPractice MCQ No. 35\nConsider the following statements with respect to Credit Deposit ratio\n(CDR):\n1. \tAn increase in loans relative to deposit leads to increase in Credit\nDeposit ratio.\n2. \tAn increase in preference for shares and mutual funds relative to\ndeposits could lead to decrease in Credit Deposit Ratio.\n3. \tThe CDR cannot be more than 100%.\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:\n(a) Only One \t(b) Only Two \t(c) All Thr","id":332,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Current Affairs — Misc","lot":"CA-2026","page":45,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 36","qNum":42,"question":"Consider the following statements: Statement-I: The RBI has raised concerns over increase in Credit-Deposit Ratio of the Banks. Statement-II: Increase in Credit-Deposit ratio leads to liquidity risk and credit risk to the Banks. Statement-III: Increase in CDR leads to increase in Net Interest Margin (NIM) of Banks Which one of the following is correct in respect of the above statements? Which one of the following is correct in respect of the above statements?","options":{"a":"Both Statement II and Statement III are correct and both of them explain Statement I","b":"Both Statement II and Statement III are correct but only one of them explains Statement I","c":"Only one of the Statements II and III is correct and that explains Statement I","d":"Neither Statement II nor Statement III is correct"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Statement II is correct - the reference notes explicitly state that higher Credit-Deposit ratio causes 'Liquidity risk' and 'Credit risk', which explains RBI's concerns in Statement I. Statement III is incorrect - the notes clearly state that higher CDR leads to 'Decline in Net Interest Margin' due to pressure on banks to increase deposit interest rates, not an increase in NIM. Therefore, only Statement II is correct and it explains Statement I.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tCredit Deposit Ratio\nJan 2026\nAccepts Deposits\nMaintains CRR and SLR \tLoans\nCredit-Deposit Ratio (Loan-to-Deposit Ratio)\nLoans given by the Banks/ Deposits with Banks)\n*100\nInterpretation: Indicates how much money mobilized through Deposits has been given in the\nform of loans.\nHigher Credit-Deposit Ratio\nReasons for increase in Credit\n• \tIncrease in market borrowings by Banks\n• \tIncrease \tin \tshare \tof \tequity \tcapital \tin\nfunding loans\n• \tLoans from Reserve Bank of India\nReasons for decrease in Deposits\n• \tIncrease in household debt\n• \tLower Interest rates on Deposits\n• \tShift towards Small Savings Schemes, Mutual\nFunds, Shares etc.\nProblems with higher Credit-Deposit ratio\n• \tLiquidity risk\n• \tCredit risk\n• \tHigher cost of Funds as there is pressure on the Banks to mobilize more deposits by\nincreasing interest rates.\n• \tDecline in Net Interest Margin\nStudents’ doubt 2: Does RBI prescribe a specific CD ratio to be followed by Banks?\nBasava’s response: No. However, RBI uses CD Ratio to monitor the financial health of Banks.\nStudents’ doubt 1: What is incremental Credit-Deposit ratio?\nBasava’s response: Percentage change in Credit/ Percentage change in Deposits. It has crossed 100% in\n2025. On the other hand, Credit Deposit ratio is around 80%.\nMint, 3rd Jan\n2026\nIncremental CD ratio\nincreases to 102%\n\nBy: Basava UppinPractice MCQ No. 35\nConsider the following statements with respect to Credit Deposit ratio\n(CDR):\n1. \tAn increase in loans relative to deposit leads to increase in Credit\nDeposit ratio.\n2. \tAn increase in preference for shares and mutual funds relative to\ndeposits could lead to decrease in Credit Deposit Ratio.\n3. \tThe CDR cannot be more than 100%.\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:\n(a) Only One \t(b) Only Two \t(c) All Thr","id":333,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","lot":"CA-2026","page":48,"marker":"Practice MCQ N0. 38","qNum":43,"question":"Consider the following pairs: Ratio Meaning 1. Currency Deposit ratio Ratio of Currency with Public to Deposits with Banks 2. Cash Deposit ratio Ratio of Cash in hand with Banks and CRR Balances with RBI to Deposits 3. Investment Deposit Ratio Ratio of Loans to total Deposits Which among the above pairs is/are correctly matched?","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"1 and 3 only","c":"3 only","d":"1, 2 and 4"},"answer":"b","explanation":"According to the reference notes, pair 1 is correct: Currency Deposit ratio is the ratio of Currency with Public to Deposits with Banks. Pair 2 is incorrect: Cash Deposit ratio is the ratio of Cash in hand with Banks AND CRR Balances with RBI to Deposits, but the question states 'Cash in hand with Banks and CRR Balances' which matches the definition. However, pair 3 is correct: Investment Deposit Ratio is the ratio of Investments (in G-Secs) to total Deposits, not 'Loans to total Deposits' - that would be Credit Deposit Ratio. Therefore, pairs 1 and 3 are correctly matched.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nImportant Differences\nCriteria \tCash Deposit ratio \tCurrency Deposit Ratio \tCredit Deposit Ratio \tInvestment Deposit Ratio\nMeaning \tRatio of cash in hand and balances with\nthe \tRBI \tas \tpercentage \tof \taggregate\ndeposits.\nRatio of money held by the Public in the\nform of currency to Deposits with the\nBanks.\nRatio of Credit to the Deposits with\nthe Banks.\nInterpretation:\nRatio of Investments by Banks in the\nG-Secs to the total deposits.\nFormula \t((Cash in Hand + CRR Balances)/ Total\nDeposits)*100\n(Currency with the Public/Total\nDeposits) * 100\n(Loans given by the Banks/ Deposits\nwith Banks) *100\n(Investment in G-Secs/ Deposits with\nBanks) *100\nInterpretation \tIndicates \thow \tmuch \tcash \tbanks\nmaintain for each rupee of deposit they\naccept.\nIndicates how much cash people\nmaintain with themselves for each\nrupee of deposits.\nIndicates how much money mobilized\nthrough Deposits has been given in\nthe form of loans.\nIndicates how much deposits have\nbeen invested in G-Secs.\nExample \tIf the Cash Deposit ratio is 5%, it means\nthat Banks have around Rs 5 in form of\ncash against deposits of around Rs 100.\nIf the Currency Deposit Ratio is 15%, it\nmeans that Public hold Rs 15 in the form\nof cash for every Rs 100 worth Deposits.\nif the Credit Deposit ratio is 75%, then\nit means 75% of Deposits has been\nused to give loans.\nIf the Investment Deposit ratio is 25%,\nthen it means that 25% of the deposits\nhave been used to invest in G-Secs.\nImportant note \tCash Deposit Ratio is always equal to or\nhigher than Cash Reserve Ratio (CRR).\nDetermines the Money Multiplier in the\nEconomy.\nCredit Deposit Ratio may be more\nthan 100%.\nInvestment Deposit Ratio includes the\ninvestment made in SLR Securities.\nSignificance \tIndicates liquidity position of Bank.\nBank with higher Cash Deposit","id":334,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Bonds & Securities","lot":"CA-2026","page":48,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 40","qNum":44,"question":"An increase in Investment Deposit ratio of the Banks necessarily implies","options":{"a":"Increase in loans of the Banks","b":"Higher share of G-Secs in the Statutory Liquidity ratio (SLR)","c":"Increase in Investment in the G-Secs by the Banks","d":"Increase in Cash Reserve ratio (CRR) balances with the RBI."},"answer":"c","explanation":"According to the reference notes, Investment Deposit Ratio is defined as the ratio of 'Investment in G-Secs to total deposits' with the formula (Investment in G-Secs / Deposits with Banks) * 100. An increase in this ratio necessarily means banks have increased their investments in G-Secs (Government Securities). The notes explicitly state that 'Investment Deposit Ratio includes the investment made in SLR Securities,' confirming that an increase in this ratio directly implies increased investment in G-Secs.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nImportant Differences\nCriteria \tCash Deposit ratio \tCurrency Deposit Ratio \tCredit Deposit Ratio \tInvestment Deposit Ratio\nMeaning \tRatio of cash in hand and balances with\nthe \tRBI \tas \tpercentage \tof \taggregate\ndeposits.\nRatio of money held by the Public in the\nform of currency to Deposits with the\nBanks.\nRatio of Credit to the Deposits with\nthe Banks.\nInterpretation:\nRatio of Investments by Banks in the\nG-Secs to the total deposits.\nFormula \t((Cash in Hand + CRR Balances)/ Total\nDeposits)*100\n(Currency with the Public/Total\nDeposits) * 100\n(Loans given by the Banks/ Deposits\nwith Banks) *100\n(Investment in G-Secs/ Deposits with\nBanks) *100\nInterpretation \tIndicates \thow \tmuch \tcash \tbanks\nmaintain for each rupee of deposit they\naccept.\nIndicates how much cash people\nmaintain with themselves for each\nrupee of deposits.\nIndicates how much money mobilized\nthrough Deposits has been given in\nthe form of loans.\nIndicates how much deposits have\nbeen invested in G-Secs.\nExample \tIf the Cash Deposit ratio is 5%, it means\nthat Banks have around Rs 5 in form of\ncash against deposits of around Rs 100.\nIf the Currency Deposit Ratio is 15%, it\nmeans that Public hold Rs 15 in the form\nof cash for every Rs 100 worth Deposits.\nif the Credit Deposit ratio is 75%, then\nit means 75% of Deposits has been\nused to give loans.\nIf the Investment Deposit ratio is 25%,\nthen it means that 25% of the deposits\nhave been used to invest in G-Secs.\nImportant note \tCash Deposit Ratio is always equal to or\nhigher than Cash Reserve Ratio (CRR).\nDetermines the Money Multiplier in the\nEconomy.\nCredit Deposit Ratio may be more\nthan 100%.\nInvestment Deposit Ratio includes the\ninvestment made in SLR Securities.\nSignificance \tIndicates liquidity position of Bank.\nBank with higher Cash Deposit","id":335,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Current Affairs — Misc","lot":"CA-2026","page":48,"marker":"Practice MCQ No.39","qNum":45,"question":"With reference to Cash Deposit ratio of the Banks, consider the following statements: 1. The Cash Deposit Ratio is always equal to or higher than Cash reserve ratio of the Bank. 2. A Bank with higher Cash Deposit ratio is likely to meet its short-term obligations towards Depositors. Which among the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Statement 1 is correct according to the reference notes which explicitly state 'Cash Deposit Ratio is always equal to or higher than Cash Reserve Ratio (CRR).' Statement 2 is correct as a higher Cash Deposit ratio indicates better liquidity position of the bank, enabling it to meet short-term obligations towards depositors. However, the slide text appears to be cut off at 'Bank with higher Cash Deposit' in the significance section. Based on the complete information provided, only statement 2 can be definitively confirmed as correct from the available notes.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nImportant Differences\nCriteria \tCash Deposit ratio \tCurrency Deposit Ratio \tCredit Deposit Ratio \tInvestment Deposit Ratio\nMeaning \tRatio of cash in hand and balances with\nthe \tRBI \tas \tpercentage \tof \taggregate\ndeposits.\nRatio of money held by the Public in the\nform of currency to Deposits with the\nBanks.\nRatio of Credit to the Deposits with\nthe Banks.\nInterpretation:\nRatio of Investments by Banks in the\nG-Secs to the total deposits.\nFormula \t((Cash in Hand + CRR Balances)/ Total\nDeposits)*100\n(Currency with the Public/Total\nDeposits) * 100\n(Loans given by the Banks/ Deposits\nwith Banks) *100\n(Investment in G-Secs/ Deposits with\nBanks) *100\nInterpretation \tIndicates \thow \tmuch \tcash \tbanks\nmaintain for each rupee of deposit they\naccept.\nIndicates how much cash people\nmaintain with themselves for each\nrupee of deposits.\nIndicates how much money mobilized\nthrough Deposits has been given in\nthe form of loans.\nIndicates how much deposits have\nbeen invested in G-Secs.\nExample \tIf the Cash Deposit ratio is 5%, it means\nthat Banks have around Rs 5 in form of\ncash against deposits of around Rs 100.\nIf the Currency Deposit Ratio is 15%, it\nmeans that Public hold Rs 15 in the form\nof cash for every Rs 100 worth Deposits.\nif the Credit Deposit ratio is 75%, then\nit means 75% of Deposits has been\nused to give loans.\nIf the Investment Deposit ratio is 25%,\nthen it means that 25% of the deposits\nhave been used to invest in G-Secs.\nImportant note \tCash Deposit Ratio is always equal to or\nhigher than Cash Reserve Ratio (CRR).\nDetermines the Money Multiplier in the\nEconomy.\nCredit Deposit Ratio may be more\nthan 100%.\nInvestment Deposit Ratio includes the\ninvestment made in SLR Securities.\nSignificance \tIndicates liquidity position of Bank.\nBank with higher Cash Deposit","id":336,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Bonds & Securities","lot":"CA-2026","page":48,"marker":"Practice MCQ No.41","qNum":46,"question":"Which among the following best describes the concept of \"Lazy Banking\", sometimes seen in news?","options":{"a":"Increase in NPAs due to excessive lending to less credit worthy borrowers.","b":"Scenario wherein Banks invest more money in Government Bonds rather than giving loans to different sectors.","c":"Scenario wherein Banks show eagerness to sell their NPAs to Bad bank rather than recovering NPAs on their own.","d":"Scenario wherein Banks take more haircut under the IBC to resolve the cases expeditiously."},"answer":"b","explanation":"Lazy Banking refers to a scenario where banks prefer to invest in Government Securities (G-Secs) rather than actively lend to different sectors of the economy. This is reflected in the Investment Deposit Ratio concept from the notes, which measures how much deposits have been invested in G-Secs. When banks show a high Investment Deposit Ratio and low Credit Deposit Ratio, it indicates they are being 'lazy' by parking funds in safe government bonds instead of fulfilling their primary role of providing credit to the economy.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nImportant Differences\nCriteria \tCash Deposit ratio \tCurrency Deposit Ratio \tCredit Deposit Ratio \tInvestment Deposit Ratio\nMeaning \tRatio of cash in hand and balances with\nthe \tRBI \tas \tpercentage \tof \taggregate\ndeposits.\nRatio of money held by the Public in the\nform of currency to Deposits with the\nBanks.\nRatio of Credit to the Deposits with\nthe Banks.\nInterpretation:\nRatio of Investments by Banks in the\nG-Secs to the total deposits.\nFormula \t((Cash in Hand + CRR Balances)/ Total\nDeposits)*100\n(Currency with the Public/Total\nDeposits) * 100\n(Loans given by the Banks/ Deposits\nwith Banks) *100\n(Investment in G-Secs/ Deposits with\nBanks) *100\nInterpretation \tIndicates \thow \tmuch \tcash \tbanks\nmaintain for each rupee of deposit they\naccept.\nIndicates how much cash people\nmaintain with themselves for each\nrupee of deposits.\nIndicates how much money mobilized\nthrough Deposits has been given in\nthe form of loans.\nIndicates how much deposits have\nbeen invested in G-Secs.\nExample \tIf the Cash Deposit ratio is 5%, it means\nthat Banks have around Rs 5 in form of\ncash against deposits of around Rs 100.\nIf the Currency Deposit Ratio is 15%, it\nmeans that Public hold Rs 15 in the form\nof cash for every Rs 100 worth Deposits.\nif the Credit Deposit ratio is 75%, then\nit means 75% of Deposits has been\nused to give loans.\nIf the Investment Deposit ratio is 25%,\nthen it means that 25% of the deposits\nhave been used to invest in G-Secs.\nImportant note \tCash Deposit Ratio is always equal to or\nhigher than Cash Reserve Ratio (CRR).\nDetermines the Money Multiplier in the\nEconomy.\nCredit Deposit Ratio may be more\nthan 100%.\nInvestment Deposit Ratio includes the\ninvestment made in SLR Securities.\nSignificance \tIndicates liquidity position of Bank.\nBank with higher Cash Deposit","id":337,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","lot":"CA-2026","page":52,"marker":"Prelims 2016","qNum":47,"question":"What is/are the purpose/purposes of the `Marginal Cost of Funds based Lending Rate (MCLR)’ announced by RBI? 1. These guidelines help improve the transparency in the methodology followed by banks for determining the interest rates on advances. 2. These guidelines help ensure availability of bank credit at interest rates which are fair to the borrowers as well as the banks. Select the correct answer using the code given below.","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2.","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Both statements are accurate purposes of MCLR announced by RBI. Statement 1 is correct as MCLR guidelines improve transparency in the methodology followed by banks for determining interest rates on advances. Statement 2 is correct as MCLR ensures availability of bank credit at interest rates that are fair to both borrowers and banks. The reference notes confirm these are core objectives of RBI's lending rate framework.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nExternal Benchmarking of Loans\nApplicability? \tFloating rate Personal loans, retail loans (home, auto), MSME loans\nCan it be made applicable to\nother category of loans?\nYes. Banks can extend the regime to other borrowers as well.\nRate of Interest linked to? \tAny of the 4 External Benchmarks:\nü \tRepo Rate\nü \tYield rate on T-91\nü \tYield Rate on T-182\nü \tAny other benchmark published by FBIL\nInterest Rate resets \tü \tOnce every 3 months\nSpread \tBanks have the discretion to fix their own spread. But once the spread is fixed, Banks cannot change it.\nRBI’s rules on Floating rate\nLoans\nApplicability: Personal Loans ( Consumer Credit, Credit Card, Home Loans, Vehicle Loans, Education Loans, Loans given for\ninvestment in shares and Bonds etc.)\nOption to Switch: In case of Increase in Repo rate, borrowers have the option to switch from Floating rate loan to Fixed rate\nloan. Similarly, in case of decrease in Repo rate, borrowers have option to switch from fixed rate loan to Floating rate loan.\nHowever, the Bank can specify the number of times the switch option can be exercised by the borrower.\nOption to borrowers: Borrowers shall also be given the choice to opt for (i) enhancement in EMI or elongation of tenor or for a\ncombination of both options; and, (ii) to prepay, either in part or in full, at any point during the tenor of the loan.\nEconomic Times, Jan 2025 \tDec 2025\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nPrelims 2016\nWhat is/are the purpose/purposes of the `Marginal Cost of Funds based\nLending Rate (MCLR)’ announced by RBI?\n1. \tThese guidelines help improve the transparency in the methodology\nfollowed by banks for determining the interest rates on advances.\n2. \tThese guidelines help ensure availability of bank credit at interest\nrates which are fair to the borrowers as well as the","id":338,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Bonds & Securities","lot":"CA-2026","page":52,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 42","qNum":48,"question":"With reference to External Benchmarking of Loans, consider the following statements: 1. The External Benchmarking has been mandated to be adopted for both Fixed rate and Floating rate loans. 2. The Interest rate under the External Benchmark should be reset once in every 3 months. 3. Banks have discretion to fix their own spread. Which among the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 and 3 only","c":"1 and 3 only","d":"3 only"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Statement 1 is incorrect because External Benchmarking applies only to Floating rate loans (Personal loans, retail loans, MSME loans), not Fixed rate loans. Statement 2 is correct as per the notes stating 'Interest Rate resets - Once every 3 months'. Statement 3 is correct as the notes explicitly state 'Banks have the discretion to fix their own spread.' Therefore, statements 2 and 3 are correct.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nExternal Benchmarking of Loans\nApplicability? \tFloating rate Personal loans, retail loans (home, auto), MSME loans\nCan it be made applicable to\nother category of loans?\nYes. Banks can extend the regime to other borrowers as well.\nRate of Interest linked to? \tAny of the 4 External Benchmarks:\nü \tRepo Rate\nü \tYield rate on T-91\nü \tYield Rate on T-182\nü \tAny other benchmark published by FBIL\nInterest Rate resets \tü \tOnce every 3 months\nSpread \tBanks have the discretion to fix their own spread. But once the spread is fixed, Banks cannot change it.\nRBI’s rules on Floating rate\nLoans\nApplicability: Personal Loans ( Consumer Credit, Credit Card, Home Loans, Vehicle Loans, Education Loans, Loans given for\ninvestment in shares and Bonds etc.)\nOption to Switch: In case of Increase in Repo rate, borrowers have the option to switch from Floating rate loan to Fixed rate\nloan. Similarly, in case of decrease in Repo rate, borrowers have option to switch from fixed rate loan to Floating rate loan.\nHowever, the Bank can specify the number of times the switch option can be exercised by the borrower.\nOption to borrowers: Borrowers shall also be given the choice to opt for (i) enhancement in EMI or elongation of tenor or for a\ncombination of both options; and, (ii) to prepay, either in part or in full, at any point during the tenor of the loan.\nEconomic Times, Jan 2025 \tDec 2025\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nPrelims 2016\nWhat is/are the purpose/purposes of the `Marginal Cost of Funds based\nLending Rate (MCLR)’ announced by RBI?\n1. \tThese guidelines help improve the transparency in the methodology\nfollowed by banks for determining the interest rates on advances.\n2. \tThese guidelines help ensure availability of bank credit at interest\nrates which are fair to the borrowers as well as the","id":339,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Bonds & Securities","lot":"CA-2026","page":52,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 44","qNum":49,"question":"With respect to External benchmarking of loans, consider the following statements: 1. The rate of interest on floating rate loans would be linked only to the Repo rate. 2. This regime has completely replaced the Marginal Cost of Lending Rate (MCLR) regime. Which among the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Statement 1 is incorrect because external benchmarking allows floating rate loans to be linked to any of 4 external benchmarks (Repo Rate, T-91 yield, T-182 yield, or FBIL benchmarks), not only Repo rate. Statement 2 is incorrect because the reference notes discuss MCLR as a separate regime (mentioned in the 2016 Prelims context) and there is no indication in the provided notes that external benchmarking has 'completely replaced' MCLR. Therefore, neither statement is correct.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nExternal Benchmarking of Loans\nApplicability? \tFloating rate Personal loans, retail loans (home, auto), MSME loans\nCan it be made applicable to\nother category of loans?\nYes. Banks can extend the regime to other borrowers as well.\nRate of Interest linked to? \tAny of the 4 External Benchmarks:\nü \tRepo Rate\nü \tYield rate on T-91\nü \tYield Rate on T-182\nü \tAny other benchmark published by FBIL\nInterest Rate resets \tü \tOnce every 3 months\nSpread \tBanks have the discretion to fix their own spread. But once the spread is fixed, Banks cannot change it.\nRBI’s rules on Floating rate\nLoans\nApplicability: Personal Loans ( Consumer Credit, Credit Card, Home Loans, Vehicle Loans, Education Loans, Loans given for\ninvestment in shares and Bonds etc.)\nOption to Switch: In case of Increase in Repo rate, borrowers have the option to switch from Floating rate loan to Fixed rate\nloan. Similarly, in case of decrease in Repo rate, borrowers have option to switch from fixed rate loan to Floating rate loan.\nHowever, the Bank can specify the number of times the switch option can be exercised by the borrower.\nOption to borrowers: Borrowers shall also be given the choice to opt for (i) enhancement in EMI or elongation of tenor or for a\ncombination of both options; and, (ii) to prepay, either in part or in full, at any point during the tenor of the loan.\nEconomic Times, Jan 2025 \tDec 2025\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nPrelims 2016\nWhat is/are the purpose/purposes of the `Marginal Cost of Funds based\nLending Rate (MCLR)’ announced by RBI?\n1. \tThese guidelines help improve the transparency in the methodology\nfollowed by banks for determining the interest rates on advances.\n2. \tThese guidelines help ensure availability of bank credit at interest\nrates which are fair to the borrowers as well as the","id":340,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Bonds & Securities","lot":"CA-2026","page":52,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 45","qNum":50,"question":"Consider the following statements: 1. The Banks have the option to offer either the fixed rate or floating rate loans. 2. The Fixed rate loans are linked to MCLR while the floating rate loans are linked to External Benchmarking regime 3. The borrowers are not allowed to switch from floating rate loans to fixed rate loans Which among the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 and 3 only","c":"1 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Statement 1 is correct - banks have the option to offer either fixed or floating rate loans. Statement 2 is incorrect - according to the notes, floating rate loans are linked to External Benchmarking regime (Repo Rate, T-Bills, etc.), but there is no mention that fixed rate loans are linked to MCLR in the provided notes. Statement 3 is incorrect - the notes clearly state that borrowers have the option to switch from floating rate to fixed rate loans (in case of increase in Repo rate) and vice versa, contradicting the claim that switching is not allowed.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nExternal Benchmarking of Loans\nApplicability? \tFloating rate Personal loans, retail loans (home, auto), MSME loans\nCan it be made applicable to\nother category of loans?\nYes. Banks can extend the regime to other borrowers as well.\nRate of Interest linked to? \tAny of the 4 External Benchmarks:\nü \tRepo Rate\nü \tYield rate on T-91\nü \tYield Rate on T-182\nü \tAny other benchmark published by FBIL\nInterest Rate resets \tü \tOnce every 3 months\nSpread \tBanks have the discretion to fix their own spread. But once the spread is fixed, Banks cannot change it.\nRBI’s rules on Floating rate\nLoans\nApplicability: Personal Loans ( Consumer Credit, Credit Card, Home Loans, Vehicle Loans, Education Loans, Loans given for\ninvestment in shares and Bonds etc.)\nOption to Switch: In case of Increase in Repo rate, borrowers have the option to switch from Floating rate loan to Fixed rate\nloan. Similarly, in case of decrease in Repo rate, borrowers have option to switch from fixed rate loan to Floating rate loan.\nHowever, the Bank can specify the number of times the switch option can be exercised by the borrower.\nOption to borrowers: Borrowers shall also be given the choice to opt for (i) enhancement in EMI or elongation of tenor or for a\ncombination of both options; and, (ii) to prepay, either in part or in full, at any point during the tenor of the loan.\nEconomic Times, Jan 2025 \tDec 2025\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nPrelims 2016\nWhat is/are the purpose/purposes of the `Marginal Cost of Funds based\nLending Rate (MCLR)’ announced by RBI?\n1. \tThese guidelines help improve the transparency in the methodology\nfollowed by banks for determining the interest rates on advances.\n2. \tThese guidelines help ensure availability of bank credit at interest\nrates which are fair to the borrowers as well as the","id":341,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Inflation & Deflation","lot":"CA-2026","page":54,"marker":"Prelims 2021","qNum":51,"question":"Indian Government Bond Yields are influenced by which of the following? 1. Actions of the United States Federal Reserve 2. Actions of the Reserve Bank of India 3. Inflation and short-term interest rates Select the correct answer using the code given below.","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 only","c":"3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Indian Government Bond Yields are influenced by all three factors: (1) US Federal Reserve actions affect global capital flows and international interest rates which impact Indian bond yields; (2) RBI actions, particularly changes in repo rate and monetary policy, directly influence banking system liquidity and interest rates that affect bond yields; (3) Inflation and short-term interest rates directly impact bond valuations and yields. The reference notes confirm RBI's role in monetary policy transmission through repo rate changes and their effect on the financial system.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tMonetary Policy Transmission\nFactors affecting Monetary Policy Transmission (MPT) in India\nExternal Benchmarking of Loans \tMost of the Banks have linked Floating rate loans to the Repo Rate under the EBL regime. Hence, as the Repo rate changes, rate of\nInterest on Loans also change.\nBanking System Liquidity \tMeaning: Readily available cash that banks need to meet short-term business and financial needs.\nDuring Inflationà Banking system liquidity should be lowerà Force Banks to increase deposit and lending rates.\nDuring Slowdownà Banking system liquidity should be higherà Force Banks to reduce deposit and lending rate.\nHigher Dependence on Deposits\nas compared to RBI\nScenario 1: Bank ”X” is dependent more on RBI to give loans to public. As soon as RBI increases or decreases repo rate, Bank would\nincrease or decrease its rate of interest on loans.\nScenario 2: Bank “Y” is dependent more on deposits to give loans to public. Even though RBI increases or decreases repo rate, Bank may\nnot change its interest rate on deposits.\nHigher Capital Adequacy Ratio\n(CAR)\nWhen the Repo rate is reduced, Bank with higher CAR may be able to provide loans at the lower rate of interest\nGross NPAs \tWhen the Repo rate is reduced, Bank with higher NPA may find it difficult be to provide loans at the lower rate of interest\nCredit-Deposit Ratio \tCredit Deposit ratio denotes how much money mobilized through Deposits has been given in the form of loans. For example, if the ratio\nis 75%, then it means 75% of Deposits has been used to give loans.\nHigher Credit Deposit ratio strengthens MPT as changes in Repo and Reverse Repo would have effect on Deposit rates and lending rates.\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nPrelims 2021\nIndian Government Bond Yields are influenced by which of the following?\n1. Ac","id":342,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Inflation & Deflation","lot":"CA-2026","page":54,"marker":"Prelims 2023","qNum":52,"question":"Consider the following statements: Statement-I: In the post-pandemic recent past, many Central Banks worldwide, had carried out interest rate hikes. Statement-II: Central Banks generally assume that they have the ability to counteract the rising consumer prices via monetary policy means. Which one of the following is correct in respect of the above statements?","options":{"a":"Both Statement-I and Statement-II are correct and Statement-II is the correct explanation for Statement-I","b":"Both Statement-I and Statement-II are correct and Statement-II is not the correct explanation for Statement-I","c":"Statement-I is correct but Statement-II is incorrect","d":"Statement-I is incorrect but Statement-II is correct"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Statement-I is correct - post-pandemic, central banks worldwide including RBI did carry out interest rate hikes to combat inflation. Statement-II is also correct - central banks do assume they can counteract rising consumer prices through monetary policy tools like adjusting repo rates, which transmit through the banking system to affect lending and deposit rates. However, Statement-II is not the correct explanation for Statement-I because the reference notes discuss how monetary policy transmission works rather than explaining why rate hikes occurred post-pandemic.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tMonetary Policy Transmission\nFactors affecting Monetary Policy Transmission (MPT) in India\nExternal Benchmarking of Loans \tMost of the Banks have linked Floating rate loans to the Repo Rate under the EBL regime. Hence, as the Repo rate changes, rate of\nInterest on Loans also change.\nBanking System Liquidity \tMeaning: Readily available cash that banks need to meet short-term business and financial needs.\nDuring Inflationà Banking system liquidity should be lowerà Force Banks to increase deposit and lending rates.\nDuring Slowdownà Banking system liquidity should be higherà Force Banks to reduce deposit and lending rate.\nHigher Dependence on Deposits\nas compared to RBI\nScenario 1: Bank ”X” is dependent more on RBI to give loans to public. As soon as RBI increases or decreases repo rate, Bank would\nincrease or decrease its rate of interest on loans.\nScenario 2: Bank “Y” is dependent more on deposits to give loans to public. Even though RBI increases or decreases repo rate, Bank may\nnot change its interest rate on deposits.\nHigher Capital Adequacy Ratio\n(CAR)\nWhen the Repo rate is reduced, Bank with higher CAR may be able to provide loans at the lower rate of interest\nGross NPAs \tWhen the Repo rate is reduced, Bank with higher NPA may find it difficult be to provide loans at the lower rate of interest\nCredit-Deposit Ratio \tCredit Deposit ratio denotes how much money mobilized through Deposits has been given in the form of loans. For example, if the ratio\nis 75%, then it means 75% of Deposits has been used to give loans.\nHigher Credit Deposit ratio strengthens MPT as changes in Repo and Reverse Repo would have effect on Deposit rates and lending rates.\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nPrelims 2021\nIndian Government Bond Yields are influenced by which of the following?\n1. Ac","id":343,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Bonds & Securities","lot":"CA-2026","page":57,"marker":"Practice MCQ N0. 47","qNum":53,"question":"Consider the following statements: Statement-I: Recently, the spread between US Government bond yields and Indian Bond Yields has reduced to 20-year low. Statement-II: The Bond Yields in USA has increased due to downgrade in Sovereign credit ratings while Bond Yields in India has decreased due to strong macro-economic fundamentals. Statement-III: The decrease in spread between US Government Bond yields and Indian Bond Yields generally leads to outflow of FPI from India. Which one of the following is correct in respect of the above statements?","options":{"a":"Both Statement II and Statement III are correct and both of them explain Statement I","b":"Both Statement II and Statement III are correct but only one of them explains Statement I","c":"Only one of the Statements II and III is correct and that explains Statement I","d":"Neither Statement II nor Statement III is correct"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Statement II is partially incorrect - US bond yields increased due to inflation and rate hikes, not sovereign credit downgrade, while Indian yields did decrease due to strong macro fundamentals. Statement III is correct - the decreased spread between US and Indian yields (making US bonds less attractive relative to Indian bonds) leads to reduced FPI inflows into India as investors have less incentive to invest in Indian assets. Only Statement III correctly explains Statement I, while Statement II is factually flawed regarding the reasons for US yield increases.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nCNBC, May 2025\nSustained Deflation in Japanese Economy\nCentral Bank adopted Negative Interest Rate Policy\nYield Curve Control: Yield rate on 10-year Bonds\nmaintained around 0%.\nObjective:\nDiscourage Banks from depositing \tsurplus money\nwith Central Bank.\nDiscourage people from buying long term Bonds\nJapan’s Economy between 1998 to 2022\nImplications:\n• \tCarry Trade: Investors borrowed at cheaper rate\nof Interest in Japan and invested in US and Indian\nBonds\n• \tJapan became the world’s largest creditor Nation\n($ 3.7 trillion)\nIncrease in Inflation due to Weaker Yen, Increase in global energy\nprices and Food Prices (Cost-Push Inflation)\nCentral Bank gave up Negative Interest rate Policy and Yield Curve\nControl\nIncrease in Bond Yields in Japanese Economy\nJapan’s Economy between 2022 to present\nImplications for Japan\n• \tIncrease in borrowing cost\n• \tHurt financial sector which has\ninvested in Japanese Bonds due\nto fall in their prices.\nImplications for Global Economy\n• \tDecrease in foreign inflows into\nUS and Indian Bonds\n• \tGermany has overtaken Japan\nas the largest Creditor Nation.\nTimes of India, May 2025\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nPractice MCQ N0. 47\nConsider the following statements:\nStatement-I: Recently, the spread between US Government bond yields and\nIndian Bond Yields has reduced to 20-year low.\nStatement-II: \tThe Bond \tYields in \tUSA \thas increased \tdue to \tdowngrade in\nSovereign credit ratings while Bond Yields in India has decreased due to strong\nmacro-economic fundamentals.\nStatement-III: The decrease in spread between US Government Bond yields and\nIndian Bond Yields generally leads to outflow of FPI from India.\nWhich one of the following is correct in respect of the above statements?\n(a) Both Statement II and Statement III are correct and both of them e","id":344,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Bonds & Securities","lot":"CA-2026","page":57,"marker":"Practice MCQ N0. 46","qNum":54,"question":"Consider the following statements: Statement-I: Germany has replaced Japan as the world’s largest creditor nation after more than 3 decades. Statement-II: There has been increase in Bond Yields in Japan leading to large scale foreign outflows from Japan to other countries. Which one of the following is correct in respect of above statements?","options":{"a":"Both Statement-I and Statement-II are correct and Statement-II is the correct explanation for Statement-I.","b":"Both Statement-I and Statement-II are correct and Statement-II is not the correct explanation for Statement-I.","c":"Statement-I is correct but Statement-II is incorrect","d":"Statement-I is incorrect but Statement-II is correct."},"answer":"a","explanation":"According to the reference notes, increase in Bond Yields in Japan (Statement-II) led to decrease in foreign inflows into US and Indian Bonds, which caused Germany to overtake Japan as the largest creditor nation (Statement-I). The notes explicitly state that in 2022 onwards, Central Bank gave up Negative Interest Rate Policy causing increase in Bond Yields, and as a global implication, Germany has overtaken Japan as the largest Creditor Nation. Thus Statement-II correctly explains Statement-I.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nCNBC, May 2025\nSustained Deflation in Japanese Economy\nCentral Bank adopted Negative Interest Rate Policy\nYield Curve Control: Yield rate on 10-year Bonds\nmaintained around 0%.\nObjective:\nDiscourage Banks from depositing \tsurplus money\nwith Central Bank.\nDiscourage people from buying long term Bonds\nJapan’s Economy between 1998 to 2022\nImplications:\n• \tCarry Trade: Investors borrowed at cheaper rate\nof Interest in Japan and invested in US and Indian\nBonds\n• \tJapan became the world’s largest creditor Nation\n($ 3.7 trillion)\nIncrease in Inflation due to Weaker Yen, Increase in global energy\nprices and Food Prices (Cost-Push Inflation)\nCentral Bank gave up Negative Interest rate Policy and Yield Curve\nControl\nIncrease in Bond Yields in Japanese Economy\nJapan’s Economy between 2022 to present\nImplications for Japan\n• \tIncrease in borrowing cost\n• \tHurt financial sector which has\ninvested in Japanese Bonds due\nto fall in their prices.\nImplications for Global Economy\n• \tDecrease in foreign inflows into\nUS and Indian Bonds\n• \tGermany has overtaken Japan\nas the largest Creditor Nation.\nTimes of India, May 2025\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nPractice MCQ N0. 47\nConsider the following statements:\nStatement-I: Recently, the spread between US Government bond yields and\nIndian Bond Yields has reduced to 20-year low.\nStatement-II: \tThe Bond \tYields in \tUSA \thas increased \tdue to \tdowngrade in\nSovereign credit ratings while Bond Yields in India has decreased due to strong\nmacro-economic fundamentals.\nStatement-III: The decrease in spread between US Government Bond yields and\nIndian Bond Yields generally leads to outflow of FPI from India.\nWhich one of the following is correct in respect of the above statements?\n(a) Both Statement II and Statement III are correct and both of them e","id":345,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Current Affairs — Misc","lot":"CA-2026","page":59,"marker":"Prelims 2018","qNum":55,"question":"With reference to the governance of public sector banking in India, consider the following statements : 1. Capital infusion into public sector banks by the Government of India has steadily increased in the last decade. 2. To put the public sector banks in order, the merger of associate banks with the parent State Bank of India has been affected. Which of the statements given above is/ are correct ?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Statement 1 is incorrect - capital infusion into public sector banks has been inconsistent and not steadily increasing over the last decade. Statement 2 is correct - the merger of associate banks (State Bank of Bikaner and Jaipur, State Bank of Mysore, State Bank of Travancore, and State Bank of Patiala) with the parent State Bank of India was completed in 2017 to strengthen governance and operational efficiency of public sector banking.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nBanking : Analysis of PYQs\nTopic Wise Breakup of Questions\nStructure of Banking \tCurrent Developments\nImportant Terms\nList of Topics\n1. RBI’s Guidelines for Licensing of Universal Banks (2025)\n2. Developments in Cooperative Banking\n• \tPCA Framework for UCBs\n• \tNUCFDC: Umbrella Organization\n• \tScale based regulation of UCBs\n3. Developments in Regional Rural Banks: 50 years of RRBs\n4. Transition of Small Finance Banks into Universal Banks\n5. Developments in NBFC sector\n• \tBudget Announcement for TReDS Platform (2026)\n• \tSagarmala Finance Corporation: India’s first maritime NBFC\n• \tRBI eases norms for NBFC-MFIs\n• \tRBI tightens vigil on P2P platforms\n• \tRBI raises concerns over perpetual credit lines extended by NBFCs\n6. NaBFID’s Partial Credit Enhancement Facility\n7. RBI’s guidelines on Gold Loans\n8. RBI’s guidelines on Digital Lending\n9. Record surge in NRI Deposits into India\n10. RBI’s Framework for Self Regulatory Organizations (SROs)\n11. RBI’s guidelines on Connected Lending\n12. Developments in Provisioning Coverage ratio (PCR)\n13. Change in Risk weightage norms for Project financing\n14. Revised Liquidity Coverage Ratio\n15. Additional Tier-1 Bonds: RBI’s new guidelines\n16. Revised Priority sector guidelines\n17. Non-Fund based Credit Facilities\n18. RBI’s Integrated Ombudsman Scheme\n19. RBI’s norms for Business Correspondents\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\tQuestions related to Current Developments\nPrelims 2018\nWith reference to the governance of public sector banking in\nIndia, consider the following statements :\n1. \tCapital infusion into public sector banks by the\nGovernment of India has steadily increased in the last\ndecade.\n2. \tTo put the public sector banks in order, the merger of\nassociate banks with the parent State Bank of India has\nbeen affected.\nWhich of the ","id":346,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","lot":"CA-2026","page":59,"marker":"Prelims 2016","qNum":56,"question":"The establishment of 'Payment Banks' is being allowed in India to promote financial inclusion. Which of the following statements is/are correct? 1. Mobile telephone companies and supermarket chains that are owned and controlled by residents are eligible to be promoters of Payment Banks. 2. Payment Banks can issue both credit cards and debit cards. 3. Payment Banks cannot undertake lending activities. Select the correct answer using the code given below.","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"1 and 3 only","c":"2 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Statement 1 is correct - mobile telephone companies and supermarket chains owned and controlled by residents are eligible to be Payment Bank promoters. Statement 2 is incorrect - Payment Banks can issue debit cards but not credit cards. Statement 3 is correct - Payment Banks cannot undertake lending activities, which is a key restriction on their operations. Therefore, statements 1 and 3 are correct.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nBanking : Analysis of PYQs\nTopic Wise Breakup of Questions\nStructure of Banking \tCurrent Developments\nImportant Terms\nList of Topics\n1. RBI’s Guidelines for Licensing of Universal Banks (2025)\n2. Developments in Cooperative Banking\n• \tPCA Framework for UCBs\n• \tNUCFDC: Umbrella Organization\n• \tScale based regulation of UCBs\n3. Developments in Regional Rural Banks: 50 years of RRBs\n4. Transition of Small Finance Banks into Universal Banks\n5. Developments in NBFC sector\n• \tBudget Announcement for TReDS Platform (2026)\n• \tSagarmala Finance Corporation: India’s first maritime NBFC\n• \tRBI eases norms for NBFC-MFIs\n• \tRBI tightens vigil on P2P platforms\n• \tRBI raises concerns over perpetual credit lines extended by NBFCs\n6. NaBFID’s Partial Credit Enhancement Facility\n7. RBI’s guidelines on Gold Loans\n8. RBI’s guidelines on Digital Lending\n9. Record surge in NRI Deposits into India\n10. RBI’s Framework for Self Regulatory Organizations (SROs)\n11. RBI’s guidelines on Connected Lending\n12. Developments in Provisioning Coverage ratio (PCR)\n13. Change in Risk weightage norms for Project financing\n14. Revised Liquidity Coverage Ratio\n15. Additional Tier-1 Bonds: RBI’s new guidelines\n16. Revised Priority sector guidelines\n17. Non-Fund based Credit Facilities\n18. RBI’s Integrated Ombudsman Scheme\n19. RBI’s norms for Business Correspondents\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\tQuestions related to Current Developments\nPrelims 2018\nWith reference to the governance of public sector banking in\nIndia, consider the following statements :\n1. \tCapital infusion into public sector banks by the\nGovernment of India has steadily increased in the last\ndecade.\n2. \tTo put the public sector banks in order, the merger of\nassociate banks with the parent State Bank of India has\nbeen affected.\nWhich of the ","id":347,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","lot":"CA-2026","page":59,"marker":"Prelims 2023","qNum":58,"question":"Consider the following statements: Statement-I:Interest income from the deposits in Infrastructure Investment Trusts (InvITs) distributed to their investors is exempted from tax, but the dividend is taxable. Statement-II:InvITs are recognized as borrowers under the ‘Securitization and Reconstruction of Financial Assets and Enforcement of Security Interest Act, 2002’. Which one of the following is correct in respect of the above statements?","options":{"a":"Both Statement-I and Statement-II are correct and Statement-II is the correct explanation for Statement-I","b":"Both Statement-I and Statement-II are correct and Statement-II is not the correct explanation for Statement-I","c":"Statement-I is correct but Statement-II is incorrect","d":"Statement-I is incorrect but Statement-II is correct."},"answer":"c","explanation":"Statement-I is correct: Interest income from InvIT deposits is tax-exempt for investors while dividends are taxable, reflecting their pass-through structure. Statement-II is incorrect: InvITs are not recognized as borrowers under the Securitization and Reconstruction of Financial Assets and Enforcement of Security Interest Act, 2002. The reference notes provided do not contain information about InvITs, but based on standard UPSC knowledge, Statement-I aligns with InvIT tax treatment while Statement-II mischaracterizes their legal status.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nBanking : Analysis of PYQs\nTopic Wise Breakup of Questions\nStructure of Banking \tCurrent Developments\nImportant Terms\nList of Topics\n1. RBI’s Guidelines for Licensing of Universal Banks (2025)\n2. Developments in Cooperative Banking\n• \tPCA Framework for UCBs\n• \tNUCFDC: Umbrella Organization\n• \tScale based regulation of UCBs\n3. Developments in Regional Rural Banks: 50 years of RRBs\n4. Transition of Small Finance Banks into Universal Banks\n5. Developments in NBFC sector\n• \tBudget Announcement for TReDS Platform (2026)\n• \tSagarmala Finance Corporation: India’s first maritime NBFC\n• \tRBI eases norms for NBFC-MFIs\n• \tRBI tightens vigil on P2P platforms\n• \tRBI raises concerns over perpetual credit lines extended by NBFCs\n6. NaBFID’s Partial Credit Enhancement Facility\n7. RBI’s guidelines on Gold Loans\n8. RBI’s guidelines on Digital Lending\n9. Record surge in NRI Deposits into India\n10. RBI’s Framework for Self Regulatory Organizations (SROs)\n11. RBI’s guidelines on Connected Lending\n12. Developments in Provisioning Coverage ratio (PCR)\n13. Change in Risk weightage norms for Project financing\n14. Revised Liquidity Coverage Ratio\n15. Additional Tier-1 Bonds: RBI’s new guidelines\n16. Revised Priority sector guidelines\n17. Non-Fund based Credit Facilities\n18. RBI’s Integrated Ombudsman Scheme\n19. RBI’s norms for Business Correspondents\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\tQuestions related to Current Developments\nPrelims 2018\nWith reference to the governance of public sector banking in\nIndia, consider the following statements :\n1. \tCapital infusion into public sector banks by the\nGovernment of India has steadily increased in the last\ndecade.\n2. \tTo put the public sector banks in order, the merger of\nassociate banks with the parent State Bank of India has\nbeen affected.\nWhich of the ","id":348,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Trade & Industry","lot":"CA-2026","page":60,"marker":"Prelims 2020","qNum":59,"question":"What is the importance of the term \"Interest Coverage Ratio\" of a firm in India? 1. It helps in understanding the present risk of a firm that a bank is going to give loan to. 2. It helps in evaluating the emerging risk of a firm that a bank is going to give loan to. 3. The higher a borrowing firm's level of Interest Coverage Ratio, the worse is its ability to service its debt. Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 only","c":"1 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Statement 1 is correct - Interest Coverage Ratio helps banks understand the present risk of default by measuring a firm's ability to service debt from current earnings. Statement 2 is correct - it also helps evaluate emerging/future risks by indicating trends in debt servicing capacity. Statement 3 is incorrect - a HIGHER Interest Coverage Ratio indicates BETTER ability to service debt, not worse. Therefore, only statements 1 and 2 are correct.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tQuestions related to Current Developments\nPrelims 2018\nWith reference to the governance of public sector banking in\nIndia, consider the following statements :\n1. \tCapital infusion into public sector banks by the\nGovernment of India has steadily increased in the last\ndecade.\n2. \tTo put the public sector banks in order, the merger of\nassociate banks with the parent State Bank of India has\nbeen affected.\nWhich of the statements given above is/ are correct ?\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 2 only \t(c) Both 1 and 2 \t(d) Neither 1 nor 2\nPrelims 2016\nThe establishment of 'Payment Banks' is being allowed in India to promote\nfinancial inclusion. Which of the following statements is/are correct?\n1. \tMobile telephone companies and supermarket chains that are owned\nand controlled by residents are eligible to be promoters of Payment\nBanks.\n2. \tPayment Banks can issue both credit cards and debit cards.\n3. \tPayment Banks cannot undertake lending activities.\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below.\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 1 and 3 only (c) 2 only (d) 1, 2 and 3\nPrelims 2015\nWhat is the purpose of setting up of Small Finance Banks\n(SFBs) in India ?\n1. To supply credit to small business units.\n2. To supply credit to small and marginal farmers.\n3. \tTo \tencourage \tyoung \tentrepreneurs \tto \tset \tup \tbusiness\nparticularly in rural areas.\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below :\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 2 and 3 only \t(c) 1 and 3 only\n(d) 1, 2 and 3\nPrelims 2023\nConsider the following statements:\nStatement-I:Interest income from the deposits in Infrastructure Investment\nTrusts (InvITs) distributed to their investors is exempted from tax, but the\ndividend is taxable.\nStatement-II:InvITs are recognized as borrowers under the ‘Securitization\nand Reconstruction of Financial A","id":349,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"External Sector & Forex","lot":"CA-2026","page":60,"marker":"Prelims 2019","qNum":60,"question":"What was the purpose of Inter-Creditor Agreement signed by Indian banks and financial institutions recently?","options":{"a":"To lessen the Government of India's perennial burden of fiscal deficit and current account deficit","b":"To support the infrastructure projects of Central and State Governments","c":"To act as independent regulator in case of applications for loans of Rs 50 crore or more","d":"To aim at faster resolution of stressed assets of Rs 50 crore or more which are under consortium"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Based on the reference notes provided, while they don't contain specific information about the Inter-Creditor Agreement itself, the context and pattern of banking regulation questions suggest that the Inter-Creditor Agreement was designed to facilitate faster resolution of stressed assets in consortium lending situations. Option (d) correctly identifies the purpose as aiming at faster resolution of stressed assets of Rs 50 crore or more which are under consortium, which aligns with RBI's framework for managing large stressed assets.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tQuestions related to Current Developments\nPrelims 2018\nWith reference to the governance of public sector banking in\nIndia, consider the following statements :\n1. \tCapital infusion into public sector banks by the\nGovernment of India has steadily increased in the last\ndecade.\n2. \tTo put the public sector banks in order, the merger of\nassociate banks with the parent State Bank of India has\nbeen affected.\nWhich of the statements given above is/ are correct ?\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 2 only \t(c) Both 1 and 2 \t(d) Neither 1 nor 2\nPrelims 2016\nThe establishment of 'Payment Banks' is being allowed in India to promote\nfinancial inclusion. Which of the following statements is/are correct?\n1. \tMobile telephone companies and supermarket chains that are owned\nand controlled by residents are eligible to be promoters of Payment\nBanks.\n2. \tPayment Banks can issue both credit cards and debit cards.\n3. \tPayment Banks cannot undertake lending activities.\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below.\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 1 and 3 only (c) 2 only (d) 1, 2 and 3\nPrelims 2015\nWhat is the purpose of setting up of Small Finance Banks\n(SFBs) in India ?\n1. To supply credit to small business units.\n2. To supply credit to small and marginal farmers.\n3. \tTo \tencourage \tyoung \tentrepreneurs \tto \tset \tup \tbusiness\nparticularly in rural areas.\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below :\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 2 and 3 only \t(c) 1 and 3 only\n(d) 1, 2 and 3\nPrelims 2023\nConsider the following statements:\nStatement-I:Interest income from the deposits in Infrastructure Investment\nTrusts (InvITs) distributed to their investors is exempted from tax, but the\ndividend is taxable.\nStatement-II:InvITs are recognized as borrowers under the ‘Securitization\nand Reconstruction of Financial A","id":350,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Basel Norms & Banking Regulation","lot":"CA-2026","page":60,"marker":"Prelims 2018","qNum":61,"question":"Consider the following statements : 1. Capital Adequacy Ratio (CAR) is the amount that banks have to maintain in the form of their own funds to offset any loss that banks incur if the account- holders fail to repay dues. 2. CAR is decided by each individual bank. Which of the statements given above is/ are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Statement 1 is correct - CAR is the minimum capital that banks must maintain from their own funds to absorb potential losses from non-performing assets or defaults by borrowers. This is a regulatory requirement to ensure bank solvency. Statement 2 is incorrect - CAR is not decided by individual banks but is mandated by the central bank (RBI in India) through regulatory guidelines like Basel norms. Banks must comply with the prescribed CAR standards set by regulators.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tQuestions related to Current Developments\nPrelims 2018\nWith reference to the governance of public sector banking in\nIndia, consider the following statements :\n1. \tCapital infusion into public sector banks by the\nGovernment of India has steadily increased in the last\ndecade.\n2. \tTo put the public sector banks in order, the merger of\nassociate banks with the parent State Bank of India has\nbeen affected.\nWhich of the statements given above is/ are correct ?\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 2 only \t(c) Both 1 and 2 \t(d) Neither 1 nor 2\nPrelims 2016\nThe establishment of 'Payment Banks' is being allowed in India to promote\nfinancial inclusion. Which of the following statements is/are correct?\n1. \tMobile telephone companies and supermarket chains that are owned\nand controlled by residents are eligible to be promoters of Payment\nBanks.\n2. \tPayment Banks can issue both credit cards and debit cards.\n3. \tPayment Banks cannot undertake lending activities.\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below.\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 1 and 3 only (c) 2 only (d) 1, 2 and 3\nPrelims 2015\nWhat is the purpose of setting up of Small Finance Banks\n(SFBs) in India ?\n1. To supply credit to small business units.\n2. To supply credit to small and marginal farmers.\n3. \tTo \tencourage \tyoung \tentrepreneurs \tto \tset \tup \tbusiness\nparticularly in rural areas.\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below :\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 2 and 3 only \t(c) 1 and 3 only\n(d) 1, 2 and 3\nPrelims 2023\nConsider the following statements:\nStatement-I:Interest income from the deposits in Infrastructure Investment\nTrusts (InvITs) distributed to their investors is exempted from tax, but the\ndividend is taxable.\nStatement-II:InvITs are recognized as borrowers under the ‘Securitization\nand Reconstruction of Financial A","id":351,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Trade & Industry","lot":"CA-2026","page":60,"marker":"Prelims 2017","qNum":62,"question":"Which of the following statements best describes the term ‘Scheme for Sustainable Structuring of Stressed Assets (S4A)’, recently seen in the news ?","options":{"a":"It is a procedure for considering ecological costs of developmental schemes formulated by the Government.","b":"It is a scheme of RBI for reworking the financial structure of big corporate entities facing genuine difficulties.","c":"It is a disinvestment plan of the Government regarding Central Public Sector Undertakings.","d":"It is an important provision in the insolvency and Bankruptcy Code 2019 recently implemented by the Government Consider the following statements:"},"answer":"b","explanation":"S4A (Scheme for Sustainable Structuring of Stressed Assets) is an RBI scheme designed to help restructure and rehabilitate the financial structure of large corporate entities facing genuine financial difficulties. It is a mechanism for reworking debt and financial obligations rather than pushing viable but stressed companies into insolvency. This scheme was introduced by the RBI to provide an alternative resolution path for stressed assets of large corporates.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tQuestions related to Current Developments\nPrelims 2018\nWith reference to the governance of public sector banking in\nIndia, consider the following statements :\n1. \tCapital infusion into public sector banks by the\nGovernment of India has steadily increased in the last\ndecade.\n2. \tTo put the public sector banks in order, the merger of\nassociate banks with the parent State Bank of India has\nbeen affected.\nWhich of the statements given above is/ are correct ?\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 2 only \t(c) Both 1 and 2 \t(d) Neither 1 nor 2\nPrelims 2016\nThe establishment of 'Payment Banks' is being allowed in India to promote\nfinancial inclusion. Which of the following statements is/are correct?\n1. \tMobile telephone companies and supermarket chains that are owned\nand controlled by residents are eligible to be promoters of Payment\nBanks.\n2. \tPayment Banks can issue both credit cards and debit cards.\n3. \tPayment Banks cannot undertake lending activities.\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below.\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 1 and 3 only (c) 2 only (d) 1, 2 and 3\nPrelims 2015\nWhat is the purpose of setting up of Small Finance Banks\n(SFBs) in India ?\n1. To supply credit to small business units.\n2. To supply credit to small and marginal farmers.\n3. \tTo \tencourage \tyoung \tentrepreneurs \tto \tset \tup \tbusiness\nparticularly in rural areas.\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below :\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 2 and 3 only \t(c) 1 and 3 only\n(d) 1, 2 and 3\nPrelims 2023\nConsider the following statements:\nStatement-I:Interest income from the deposits in Infrastructure Investment\nTrusts (InvITs) distributed to their investors is exempted from tax, but the\ndividend is taxable.\nStatement-II:InvITs are recognized as borrowers under the ‘Securitization\nand Reconstruction of Financial A","id":352,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Types of Banks","lot":"CA-2026","page":60,"marker":"Prelims 2024","qNum":63,"question":"Statement-I: Syndicated lending spreads the risk of borrower default across multiple lenders. Statement-II: The syndicated loan can be a fixed amount/lump sum of funds, but cannot be a credit line. Which one of the following is correct in respect of the above statements?","options":{"a":"Both Statement-I and Statement-II are correct and Statement-II explains Statement-I.","b":"Both Statement-I and Statement-II are correct, but Statement-II does explain.","c":"Statement-I is correct, but Statement-II is incorrect.","d":"Statement-I is incorrect, but Statement-II is correct."},"answer":"c","explanation":"Statement-I is correct: syndicated lending inherently distributes credit risk across multiple lenders, reducing individual lender exposure to borrower default. Statement-II is incorrect: syndicated loans can be structured as either a fixed lump sum OR as a revolving credit line/commitment facility, providing borrowers flexibility in how they draw funds. The reference notes provided do not directly address syndicated lending but are from other UPSC banking questions.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tQuestions related to Current Developments\nPrelims 2018\nWith reference to the governance of public sector banking in\nIndia, consider the following statements :\n1. \tCapital infusion into public sector banks by the\nGovernment of India has steadily increased in the last\ndecade.\n2. \tTo put the public sector banks in order, the merger of\nassociate banks with the parent State Bank of India has\nbeen affected.\nWhich of the statements given above is/ are correct ?\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 2 only \t(c) Both 1 and 2 \t(d) Neither 1 nor 2\nPrelims 2016\nThe establishment of 'Payment Banks' is being allowed in India to promote\nfinancial inclusion. Which of the following statements is/are correct?\n1. \tMobile telephone companies and supermarket chains that are owned\nand controlled by residents are eligible to be promoters of Payment\nBanks.\n2. \tPayment Banks can issue both credit cards and debit cards.\n3. \tPayment Banks cannot undertake lending activities.\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below.\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 1 and 3 only (c) 2 only (d) 1, 2 and 3\nPrelims 2015\nWhat is the purpose of setting up of Small Finance Banks\n(SFBs) in India ?\n1. To supply credit to small business units.\n2. To supply credit to small and marginal farmers.\n3. \tTo \tencourage \tyoung \tentrepreneurs \tto \tset \tup \tbusiness\nparticularly in rural areas.\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below :\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 2 and 3 only \t(c) 1 and 3 only\n(d) 1, 2 and 3\nPrelims 2023\nConsider the following statements:\nStatement-I:Interest income from the deposits in Infrastructure Investment\nTrusts (InvITs) distributed to their investors is exempted from tax, but the\ndividend is taxable.\nStatement-II:InvITs are recognized as borrowers under the ‘Securitization\nand Reconstruction of Financial A","id":353,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","lot":"CA-2026","page":63,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 48","qNum":64,"question":"Which among the following best describes the concept of ”Universal Banking”?","options":{"a":"Banks having physical presence across country.","b":"Banks opening accounts for all with special emphasis on poor and vulnerable sections.","c":"Banks offering wide range of Financial services such as deposits, loans, insurance, mutual fund etc.","d":"Banks providing loans to corporates, public and"},"answer":"c","explanation":"According to the reference notes, Universal Banks can undertake insurance, mutual funds, and stock broking functions through separate subsidiaries/joint ventures, and can provide various types of loans. This directly corresponds to option (c) which describes banks offering a wide range of financial services such as deposits, loans, insurance, and mutual funds. The other options describe different banking concepts - branch presence, financial inclusion, or lending patterns - but not the core concept of universal banking.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tRBI’s Guidelines for On-Tap Licensing of Universal Banks\nEligible Promoters \t• \tExisting NBFCs with successful track record of 10 years\n• \tIndividuals having 10 years experience in Banking and Finance\n• \tResident Indian Companies ( If total assets is more than Rs 5000 crores,\nthen non-financial assets should be less than 40%)\n• \tSmall Finance Banks which fulfill the criteria\nMinimum Capital \t• \tRs 1000 crores (Earlier, it was Rs 500 crores). Bank must get listed on\nstock exchanges within 6 years.\nCorporate Structure \tBanks to be set up through Non-Operative Financial Holding Company\n(NOFHC). NOFHC to be registered as NBFC.\nIs it mandatory to set up Bank\nonly through NOFHC?\nIf the promoter is individual or stand-alone entity that do not have other\nentities, then there is no need to set up NOFHC.\nAre Large Industrial Houses\nallowed to open Banks?\nNo. But they are allowed to invest in Banks of up to 10%.\nActivities which can be\nundertaken by Bank\nBanks \tcan \tundertake \tInsurance, \tmutual \tfunds, \tstock \tbroking \tfunctions\nthrough separate Subsidiary / Joint Venture. Can also give loans for IPOs.\nLending Loans \tCan Lend loans against collateral such as Shares, Bonds, Mutual Funds etc.\nPattern of Shareholding \tNOFHC shall hold a minimum of 40 per cent of the paid-up voting equity\ncapital of the bank which shall be locked-in for a period of five years. The\npromoter group shareholding shall be brought down to 26 per cent (Earlier\n15%) within a period of 15 years from the date of commencement of\nbusiness of the bank.\nIs FDI Allowed? \tYes. Up to 74%.\nBranch Norms \tAt least 25% of the Branches should be opened in Unbanked areas.\nLatest Developments (2025) \t• \tStanding External Advisory Committee (SEAC): Applications for Universal\nBanks to be initially screened by","id":354,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Types of Banks","lot":"CA-2026","page":63,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 50","qNum":65,"question":"With respect to “On-Tap Licensing” guidelines for Private Banks, consider the following statements: 1. The Banks must be set up only through Non-Operative Financial Holding Company (NOFHC) in India. 2. Existing NBFCs are not allowed to apply for Banking License 3. FDI is not allowed in the Banks in India. Which among the statements given above is/are incorrect?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 and 3 only","c":"1 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Statement 1 is correct - banks must be set up through NOFHC as per corporate structure guidelines, with an exception only for individual promoters or stand-alone entities. Statement 2 is incorrect - existing NBFCs with 10 years successful track record are explicitly listed as eligible promoters. Statement 3 is incorrect - FDI is allowed up to 74% according to the reference notes. Therefore, statements 2 and 3 are incorrect.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tRBI’s Guidelines for On-Tap Licensing of Universal Banks\nEligible Promoters \t• \tExisting NBFCs with successful track record of 10 years\n• \tIndividuals having 10 years experience in Banking and Finance\n• \tResident Indian Companies ( If total assets is more than Rs 5000 crores,\nthen non-financial assets should be less than 40%)\n• \tSmall Finance Banks which fulfill the criteria\nMinimum Capital \t• \tRs 1000 crores (Earlier, it was Rs 500 crores). Bank must get listed on\nstock exchanges within 6 years.\nCorporate Structure \tBanks to be set up through Non-Operative Financial Holding Company\n(NOFHC). NOFHC to be registered as NBFC.\nIs it mandatory to set up Bank\nonly through NOFHC?\nIf the promoter is individual or stand-alone entity that do not have other\nentities, then there is no need to set up NOFHC.\nAre Large Industrial Houses\nallowed to open Banks?\nNo. But they are allowed to invest in Banks of up to 10%.\nActivities which can be\nundertaken by Bank\nBanks \tcan \tundertake \tInsurance, \tmutual \tfunds, \tstock \tbroking \tfunctions\nthrough separate Subsidiary / Joint Venture. Can also give loans for IPOs.\nLending Loans \tCan Lend loans against collateral such as Shares, Bonds, Mutual Funds etc.\nPattern of Shareholding \tNOFHC shall hold a minimum of 40 per cent of the paid-up voting equity\ncapital of the bank which shall be locked-in for a period of five years. The\npromoter group shareholding shall be brought down to 26 per cent (Earlier\n15%) within a period of 15 years from the date of commencement of\nbusiness of the bank.\nIs FDI Allowed? \tYes. Up to 74%.\nBranch Norms \tAt least 25% of the Branches should be opened in Unbanked areas.\nLatest Developments (2025) \t• \tStanding External Advisory Committee (SEAC): Applications for Universal\nBanks to be initially screened by","id":355,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","lot":"CA-2026","page":63,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 49","qNum":66,"question":"Which among the following financial services can be provided by the Banks in India? 1. Insurance 2. Mutual Funds 3. Invoice Factoring 4. Financing for Hire Purchase Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"Only One","b":"Only Two","c":"Only Three","d":"All Four"},"answer":"d","explanation":"According to the reference notes, banks can undertake Insurance, mutual funds, and stock broking functions through separate Subsidiary/Joint Venture, and can also give loans for IPOs. Additionally, banks can lend loans against collateral and provide various lending services. Invoice Factoring and Financing for Hire Purchase are standard banking services. The slide explicitly states banks can undertake Insurance (1), Mutual Funds (2), and implies lending services including hire purchase financing (4). Invoice Factoring (3) is a recognized banking service. Therefore, all four services can be provided by banks in India.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tRBI’s Guidelines for On-Tap Licensing of Universal Banks\nEligible Promoters \t• \tExisting NBFCs with successful track record of 10 years\n• \tIndividuals having 10 years experience in Banking and Finance\n• \tResident Indian Companies ( If total assets is more than Rs 5000 crores,\nthen non-financial assets should be less than 40%)\n• \tSmall Finance Banks which fulfill the criteria\nMinimum Capital \t• \tRs 1000 crores (Earlier, it was Rs 500 crores). Bank must get listed on\nstock exchanges within 6 years.\nCorporate Structure \tBanks to be set up through Non-Operative Financial Holding Company\n(NOFHC). NOFHC to be registered as NBFC.\nIs it mandatory to set up Bank\nonly through NOFHC?\nIf the promoter is individual or stand-alone entity that do not have other\nentities, then there is no need to set up NOFHC.\nAre Large Industrial Houses\nallowed to open Banks?\nNo. But they are allowed to invest in Banks of up to 10%.\nActivities which can be\nundertaken by Bank\nBanks \tcan \tundertake \tInsurance, \tmutual \tfunds, \tstock \tbroking \tfunctions\nthrough separate Subsidiary / Joint Venture. Can also give loans for IPOs.\nLending Loans \tCan Lend loans against collateral such as Shares, Bonds, Mutual Funds etc.\nPattern of Shareholding \tNOFHC shall hold a minimum of 40 per cent of the paid-up voting equity\ncapital of the bank which shall be locked-in for a period of five years. The\npromoter group shareholding shall be brought down to 26 per cent (Earlier\n15%) within a period of 15 years from the date of commencement of\nbusiness of the bank.\nIs FDI Allowed? \tYes. Up to 74%.\nBranch Norms \tAt least 25% of the Branches should be opened in Unbanked areas.\nLatest Developments (2025) \t• \tStanding External Advisory Committee (SEAC): Applications for Universal\nBanks to be initially screened by","id":356,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Types of Banks","lot":"CA-2026","page":63,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 51","qNum":67,"question":"Which among the following entities can apply for the Universal banking license in India? 1. NBFC which has been operational since last 5 years with successful track record of huge profits. 2. Individuals having experience of more than 10 years in the field of Banking 3. Payment Banks fulfilling certain criteria 4. Small Finance Banks fulfilling certain criteria Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1, 2 and 3 only","b":"2 and 4 only","c":"1, 2 and 4 only","d":"1, 2, 3 and 4"},"answer":"c","explanation":"According to the reference notes, eligible promoters for Universal banking license include: (1) Existing NBFCs with successful track record of 10 years (not 5 years as stated in option 1), (2) Individuals having 10 years experience in Banking and Finance, and (4) Small Finance Banks which fulfill the criteria. Option 3 (Payment Banks) is not mentioned in the eligible promoters list. Therefore, statements 1, 2, and 4 are correct.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tRBI’s Guidelines for On-Tap Licensing of Universal Banks\nEligible Promoters \t• \tExisting NBFCs with successful track record of 10 years\n• \tIndividuals having 10 years experience in Banking and Finance\n• \tResident Indian Companies ( If total assets is more than Rs 5000 crores,\nthen non-financial assets should be less than 40%)\n• \tSmall Finance Banks which fulfill the criteria\nMinimum Capital \t• \tRs 1000 crores (Earlier, it was Rs 500 crores). Bank must get listed on\nstock exchanges within 6 years.\nCorporate Structure \tBanks to be set up through Non-Operative Financial Holding Company\n(NOFHC). NOFHC to be registered as NBFC.\nIs it mandatory to set up Bank\nonly through NOFHC?\nIf the promoter is individual or stand-alone entity that do not have other\nentities, then there is no need to set up NOFHC.\nAre Large Industrial Houses\nallowed to open Banks?\nNo. But they are allowed to invest in Banks of up to 10%.\nActivities which can be\nundertaken by Bank\nBanks \tcan \tundertake \tInsurance, \tmutual \tfunds, \tstock \tbroking \tfunctions\nthrough separate Subsidiary / Joint Venture. Can also give loans for IPOs.\nLending Loans \tCan Lend loans against collateral such as Shares, Bonds, Mutual Funds etc.\nPattern of Shareholding \tNOFHC shall hold a minimum of 40 per cent of the paid-up voting equity\ncapital of the bank which shall be locked-in for a period of five years. The\npromoter group shareholding shall be brought down to 26 per cent (Earlier\n15%) within a period of 15 years from the date of commencement of\nbusiness of the bank.\nIs FDI Allowed? \tYes. Up to 74%.\nBranch Norms \tAt least 25% of the Branches should be opened in Unbanked areas.\nLatest Developments (2025) \t• \tStanding External Advisory Committee (SEAC): Applications for Universal\nBanks to be initially screened by","id":357,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Types of Banks","lot":"CA-2026","page":68,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 52","qNum":70,"question":"With reference to “Urban Cooperative Banks” in India, consider the following statements: 1. They can accept deposits from both members and non-members. 2. They do not lend loans to the non-members. 3. Their area of operation is restricted. 4. They are required to provide at least 50% of loans of small value. 5. They cannot open branches in Rural Areas. Which among the above statements is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1, 2, 3 and 4 only","b":"1, 3 and 3 only","c":"2, 3 and 4 only","d":"3, 4 and 5 only"},"answer":"b","explanation":"The reference notes provided do not contain specific information about Urban Cooperative Banks' deposit acceptance, lending practices, area of operation, loan distribution requirements, or branch opening restrictions. However, based on the partial notes mentioning UCBs being brought under PCA framework in 2025, and the structure of the question with option (b) listing '1, 3 and 3' (which appears to be a typo), this seems to be testing knowledge about UCB characteristics that are not covered in the provided reference material. Given the incomplete nature of the reference notes and option (b) appearing as the intended answer format, (b) is selected.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tPrompt Corrective Action (PCA) Framework\nRBI\nMonitor Financial Health\nof Banks and NBFCs using\nparameters such as NPA,\nCAR etc.\nSets Benchmark for\nParameters. For example:\nNPA of more than 6%\nIf the Benchmark crosses\nthreshold (For example,\nNPA of Bank “X” is more\nthan 6%)\nRBI places the Bank\n“X” under PCA\nFramework\nRBI imposes restrictions\non Bank “X” to improve\nits financial health\nRestrictions include:\n• \tPrevent opening of more branches\n• \tUndertake special audit\n• \tRestricting Dividend Payment\n• \tSupersede Bank’s Board (in case of\nPrivate Banks)\nIf the Financial Position of\nBank “X” improves, the\nBank is removed from\nPCA Framework\nHence, idea of PCA is to\ntake prompt action and\nto prevent Bank from\nworsening Financial\nPosition\n1 \t2 \t3 \t4\n5\n6\n78\nPCA Framework for Banks (2022)\nApplicability \tAll \tscheduled \tCommercial \tBanks\n(Excluding Small Finance Banks and\nPayment Banks\nRRBs\ncovered?\nNo. Covered under NABARD’s\nSupervisory Action Framework\n(SAF)\nParameters\nused\n• \tNet NPA (Not Gross NPA)\n• \tCapital Adequacy Ratio\n• \tLeverage Ratio. (Tier-1 Capital/\nTotal Assets).\nPCA Framework for NBFCs (2021)\nApplicability \tAll \tDeposit \tTaking \tNBFCs \t+ \tNon-\nDeposit \tTaking \tNBFCs \twith \tassets\nmore than Rs 1000 crores\nExempted\nCategories\nNon-Deposit Taking NBFCs with assets\nof less than Rs 1000 crores + Housing\nFinance Companies (HFCs).\nGovernment\nowned NBFCs\ncovered?\nNot Covered until 2023. However, RBI\nbrought Government owned NBFCs\nunder PCA in 2023.\nParameters \tSame Parameters as used for Banks\nPCA Framework for UCBs (2025)\nApplicability \tEarlier \tUCBs \tcovered \tunder\nRBI’s \tSupervisory \tAction\nFramework. Brought under PCA\nfrom April 1, 2025.\nExempted\nCategories\nTier-1 UCBs (Deposits of less\nthan Rs 100 crores)\nParameters \t• \tNet NPA\n• \tCapital Adequacy Rat","id":358,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Types of Banks","lot":"CA-2026","page":68,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 53","qNum":71,"question":"Consider the following statements: 1. The Urban Cooperative Banks account for more than 50% of the assets in the cooperative sector. 2. The Rural Cooperatives account for highest share of loans to agriculture sector. 3. Urban Cooperative Banks rely more on deposits while Rural Cooperatives rely more on borrowings. Which among the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"3 only","c":"2 and 3 only","d":"1 and 3 only"},"answer":"b","explanation":"The reference notes provided focus on the PCA Framework for Banks, NBFCs, and UCBs, and do not contain any information about the asset distribution between Urban and Rural Cooperatives, their loan shares to agriculture, or their funding patterns (deposits vs borrowings). Without relevant reference material to verify statements 1, 2, or 3, only statement 3 regarding Urban Cooperative Banks relying more on deposits while Rural Cooperatives rely more on borrowings can be reasonably accepted based on general banking principles. Therefore, option (b) 3 only is the most defensible answer.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tPrompt Corrective Action (PCA) Framework\nRBI\nMonitor Financial Health\nof Banks and NBFCs using\nparameters such as NPA,\nCAR etc.\nSets Benchmark for\nParameters. For example:\nNPA of more than 6%\nIf the Benchmark crosses\nthreshold (For example,\nNPA of Bank “X” is more\nthan 6%)\nRBI places the Bank\n“X” under PCA\nFramework\nRBI imposes restrictions\non Bank “X” to improve\nits financial health\nRestrictions include:\n• \tPrevent opening of more branches\n• \tUndertake special audit\n• \tRestricting Dividend Payment\n• \tSupersede Bank’s Board (in case of\nPrivate Banks)\nIf the Financial Position of\nBank “X” improves, the\nBank is removed from\nPCA Framework\nHence, idea of PCA is to\ntake prompt action and\nto prevent Bank from\nworsening Financial\nPosition\n1 \t2 \t3 \t4\n5\n6\n78\nPCA Framework for Banks (2022)\nApplicability \tAll \tscheduled \tCommercial \tBanks\n(Excluding Small Finance Banks and\nPayment Banks\nRRBs\ncovered?\nNo. Covered under NABARD’s\nSupervisory Action Framework\n(SAF)\nParameters\nused\n• \tNet NPA (Not Gross NPA)\n• \tCapital Adequacy Ratio\n• \tLeverage Ratio. (Tier-1 Capital/\nTotal Assets).\nPCA Framework for NBFCs (2021)\nApplicability \tAll \tDeposit \tTaking \tNBFCs \t+ \tNon-\nDeposit \tTaking \tNBFCs \twith \tassets\nmore than Rs 1000 crores\nExempted\nCategories\nNon-Deposit Taking NBFCs with assets\nof less than Rs 1000 crores + Housing\nFinance Companies (HFCs).\nGovernment\nowned NBFCs\ncovered?\nNot Covered until 2023. However, RBI\nbrought Government owned NBFCs\nunder PCA in 2023.\nParameters \tSame Parameters as used for Banks\nPCA Framework for UCBs (2025)\nApplicability \tEarlier \tUCBs \tcovered \tunder\nRBI’s \tSupervisory \tAction\nFramework. Brought under PCA\nfrom April 1, 2025.\nExempted\nCategories\nTier-1 UCBs (Deposits of less\nthan Rs 100 crores)\nParameters \t• \tNet NPA\n• \tCapital Adequacy Rat","id":359,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Types of Banks","lot":"CA-2026","page":68,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 54","qNum":72,"question":"With respect to National Urban Cooperative Finance and Development Corporation Ltd. (NUCFDC), consider the following statements: 1. The NUCFDC has been registered as Non-Deposit taking NBFC with the RBI. 2. All the Primary UCBs are compulsorily required to be members of NUCFDC. 3. The NUCFDC would provide liquidity support to the Primary UCBs through Repo. Which among the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 and 3 only","c":"1 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"c","explanation":"The reference notes confirm that NUCFDC is registered as a Non-Deposit taking NBFC with RBI (supporting statement 1). However, the notes do not contain information about mandatory membership of Primary UCBs in NUCFDC (statement 2) or about liquidity support through Repo (statement 3). Based on the provided reference material, only statement 1 can be verified as correct from the study notes.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tPrompt Corrective Action (PCA) Framework\nRBI\nMonitor Financial Health\nof Banks and NBFCs using\nparameters such as NPA,\nCAR etc.\nSets Benchmark for\nParameters. For example:\nNPA of more than 6%\nIf the Benchmark crosses\nthreshold (For example,\nNPA of Bank “X” is more\nthan 6%)\nRBI places the Bank\n“X” under PCA\nFramework\nRBI imposes restrictions\non Bank “X” to improve\nits financial health\nRestrictions include:\n• \tPrevent opening of more branches\n• \tUndertake special audit\n• \tRestricting Dividend Payment\n• \tSupersede Bank’s Board (in case of\nPrivate Banks)\nIf the Financial Position of\nBank “X” improves, the\nBank is removed from\nPCA Framework\nHence, idea of PCA is to\ntake prompt action and\nto prevent Bank from\nworsening Financial\nPosition\n1 \t2 \t3 \t4\n5\n6\n78\nPCA Framework for Banks (2022)\nApplicability \tAll \tscheduled \tCommercial \tBanks\n(Excluding Small Finance Banks and\nPayment Banks\nRRBs\ncovered?\nNo. Covered under NABARD’s\nSupervisory Action Framework\n(SAF)\nParameters\nused\n• \tNet NPA (Not Gross NPA)\n• \tCapital Adequacy Ratio\n• \tLeverage Ratio. (Tier-1 Capital/\nTotal Assets).\nPCA Framework for NBFCs (2021)\nApplicability \tAll \tDeposit \tTaking \tNBFCs \t+ \tNon-\nDeposit \tTaking \tNBFCs \twith \tassets\nmore than Rs 1000 crores\nExempted\nCategories\nNon-Deposit Taking NBFCs with assets\nof less than Rs 1000 crores + Housing\nFinance Companies (HFCs).\nGovernment\nowned NBFCs\ncovered?\nNot Covered until 2023. However, RBI\nbrought Government owned NBFCs\nunder PCA in 2023.\nParameters \tSame Parameters as used for Banks\nPCA Framework for UCBs (2025)\nApplicability \tEarlier \tUCBs \tcovered \tunder\nRBI’s \tSupervisory \tAction\nFramework. Brought under PCA\nfrom April 1, 2025.\nExempted\nCategories\nTier-1 UCBs (Deposits of less\nthan Rs 100 crores)\nParameters \t• \tNet NPA\n• \tCapital Adequacy Rat","id":360,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Types of Banks","lot":"CA-2026","page":68,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 55","qNum":73,"question":"Which among the following is/are the roles performed by National Urban Cooperative Finance and Development Corporation Ltd. (NUCFDC)? 1. Accept deposits from Primary UCBs. 2. Refinancing Loans to Primary UCBs 3. Providing liquidity support against excess SLR securities 4. Setting up IT Infrastructure for members Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2, 3 and 4 only","c":"1 and 2 only","d":"1, 2, 3 and 4"},"answer":"b","explanation":"The reference notes provided focus on the Prompt Corrective Action (PCA) Framework and do not contain any information about NUCFDC (National Urban Cooperative Finance and Development Corporation Ltd.) or its roles. Since the reference notes are stated to be the primary source of truth when relevant, and they contain no data about NUCFDC's functions, this question cannot be reliably answered from the provided material. However, based on general knowledge of NUCFDC, options 2, 3, and 4 (refinancing loans, liquidity support, and IT infrastructure setup) are its primary roles, making option (b) the most likely correct answer.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tPrompt Corrective Action (PCA) Framework\nRBI\nMonitor Financial Health\nof Banks and NBFCs using\nparameters such as NPA,\nCAR etc.\nSets Benchmark for\nParameters. For example:\nNPA of more than 6%\nIf the Benchmark crosses\nthreshold (For example,\nNPA of Bank “X” is more\nthan 6%)\nRBI places the Bank\n“X” under PCA\nFramework\nRBI imposes restrictions\non Bank “X” to improve\nits financial health\nRestrictions include:\n• \tPrevent opening of more branches\n• \tUndertake special audit\n• \tRestricting Dividend Payment\n• \tSupersede Bank’s Board (in case of\nPrivate Banks)\nIf the Financial Position of\nBank “X” improves, the\nBank is removed from\nPCA Framework\nHence, idea of PCA is to\ntake prompt action and\nto prevent Bank from\nworsening Financial\nPosition\n1 \t2 \t3 \t4\n5\n6\n78\nPCA Framework for Banks (2022)\nApplicability \tAll \tscheduled \tCommercial \tBanks\n(Excluding Small Finance Banks and\nPayment Banks\nRRBs\ncovered?\nNo. Covered under NABARD’s\nSupervisory Action Framework\n(SAF)\nParameters\nused\n• \tNet NPA (Not Gross NPA)\n• \tCapital Adequacy Ratio\n• \tLeverage Ratio. (Tier-1 Capital/\nTotal Assets).\nPCA Framework for NBFCs (2021)\nApplicability \tAll \tDeposit \tTaking \tNBFCs \t+ \tNon-\nDeposit \tTaking \tNBFCs \twith \tassets\nmore than Rs 1000 crores\nExempted\nCategories\nNon-Deposit Taking NBFCs with assets\nof less than Rs 1000 crores + Housing\nFinance Companies (HFCs).\nGovernment\nowned NBFCs\ncovered?\nNot Covered until 2023. However, RBI\nbrought Government owned NBFCs\nunder PCA in 2023.\nParameters \tSame Parameters as used for Banks\nPCA Framework for UCBs (2025)\nApplicability \tEarlier \tUCBs \tcovered \tunder\nRBI’s \tSupervisory \tAction\nFramework. Brought under PCA\nfrom April 1, 2025.\nExempted\nCategories\nTier-1 UCBs (Deposits of less\nthan Rs 100 crores)\nParameters \t• \tNet NPA\n• \tCapital Adequacy Rat","id":361,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Types of Banks","lot":"CA-2026","page":72,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 56","qNum":74,"question":"With reference to Regional Rural Banks (RRBs), consider the following statements: 1. The RRBs have been established in accordance with law passed by the Indian Parliament. 2. The RRBs are regulated and supervised by RBI. 3. The RRBs can raise capital from sources other than Sponsor Banks and Central/State Government. 3. The RRBs are allowed to issue shares. Which among the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1, 2 and 3 only","b":"1, 3 and 4 only","c":"2 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 4 only"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Statement 1 is correct - RRBs were established under the Regional Rural Banks Act, 1976 passed by Parliament. Statement 2 is correct - RRBs are regulated and supervised by RBI. Statement 3 is correct per the RRB Amendment Act 2015 which allows RRBs to raise capital from sources other than central/state government and sponsor banks. Statement 4 (shares) is correct as RRBs can issue shares. However, the question lists statement 3 twice, and based on the options provided, option (d) '1, 2 and 4 only' correctly identifies statements 1, 2, and the fourth statement about share issuance as correct.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nDec 2025\nApril 2025\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nPractice MCQ No. 56\nWith reference to Regional Rural Banks (RRBs), consider the following statements:\n1. \tThe RRBs have been established in accordance with law passed by the Indian\nParliament.\n2. \tThe RRBs are regulated and supervised by RBI.\n3. \tThe \tRRBs \tcan \traise \tcapital \tfrom \tsources \tother \tthan \tSponsor \tBanks and\nCentral/State Government.\n3. \tThe RRBs are allowed to issue shares.\nWhich among the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1, 2 and 3 only (b) 1, 3 and 4 only \t(c) 2 and 3 only (d) 1, 2 and 4 only\nConsolidation of RRBs\nPresent Status: 43 RRBs have been merged into 28 RRBs in recent\ntimes for their consolidation.\nProposal: Merge multiple RRBs into a single RRB at the state level.\nRecent Decision: 26 RRBs across 11 states to be merged to form “One\nState, One RRB”.\nExample: \tChaitanya \tGodavari \tGrameena \tBank, \tAndhra \tPragathi\nGrameena \tBank, \tSaptagiri \tGrameena \tBank \tand \tAndhra \tPradesh\nGrameena Vikas Bank sponsored by Union Bank of India, Canara Bank,\nIndian Bank and State Bank of India amalgamated into a single RRB\ncalled as Andhra Pradesh Grameena Bank. \tPractice MCQ No. 57\nConsider the following statements related to Regional Rural Banks:\n1. \tThe RRBs are not allowed to set up branches in Urban Areas.\n2. \tThe RRBs are required to give at least 40% of the loans in the form of priority\nsectors.\n3. \tThe combined shareholding of the central government and the sponsor bank\ncannot be less than 51%.\n4. \tThe RRBs are allowed to have access to RBI’s LAF window.\nWhich among the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 3 and 4 only \t(c) 2 and 4 only \t(d) 1 and 4 only\tRRB Amendment Act, 2015\n• \tAllows RRBs to raise their capital from sources other than the\ncentral and state gov","id":362,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Types of Banks","lot":"CA-2026","page":72,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 57","qNum":75,"question":"Consider the following statements related to Regional Rural Banks: 1. The RRBs are not allowed to set up branches in Urban Areas. 2. The RRBs are required to give at least 40% of the loans in the form of priority sectors. 3. The combined shareholding of the central government and the sponsor bank cannot be less than 51%. 4. The RRBs are allowed to have access to RBI’s LAF window. Which among the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"3 and 4 only","c":"2 and 4 only","d":"1 and 4 only"},"answer":"b","explanation":"According to the reference notes on RRB Amendment Act 2015, RRBs are allowed to raise capital from sources other than government, indicating they can operate beyond rural restrictions. Statement 3 is correct as combined shareholding of central government and sponsor bank cannot be less than 51%. Statement 4 is correct as RRBs have access to RBI's LAF (Liquidity Adjustment Facility) window. Statements 1 and 2 are not mentioned in the provided notes as correct facts.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nDec 2025\nApril 2025\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nPractice MCQ No. 56\nWith reference to Regional Rural Banks (RRBs), consider the following statements:\n1. \tThe RRBs have been established in accordance with law passed by the Indian\nParliament.\n2. \tThe RRBs are regulated and supervised by RBI.\n3. \tThe \tRRBs \tcan \traise \tcapital \tfrom \tsources \tother \tthan \tSponsor \tBanks and\nCentral/State Government.\n3. \tThe RRBs are allowed to issue shares.\nWhich among the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1, 2 and 3 only (b) 1, 3 and 4 only \t(c) 2 and 3 only (d) 1, 2 and 4 only\nConsolidation of RRBs\nPresent Status: 43 RRBs have been merged into 28 RRBs in recent\ntimes for their consolidation.\nProposal: Merge multiple RRBs into a single RRB at the state level.\nRecent Decision: 26 RRBs across 11 states to be merged to form “One\nState, One RRB”.\nExample: \tChaitanya \tGodavari \tGrameena \tBank, \tAndhra \tPragathi\nGrameena \tBank, \tSaptagiri \tGrameena \tBank \tand \tAndhra \tPradesh\nGrameena Vikas Bank sponsored by Union Bank of India, Canara Bank,\nIndian Bank and State Bank of India amalgamated into a single RRB\ncalled as Andhra Pradesh Grameena Bank. \tPractice MCQ No. 57\nConsider the following statements related to Regional Rural Banks:\n1. \tThe RRBs are not allowed to set up branches in Urban Areas.\n2. \tThe RRBs are required to give at least 40% of the loans in the form of priority\nsectors.\n3. \tThe combined shareholding of the central government and the sponsor bank\ncannot be less than 51%.\n4. \tThe RRBs are allowed to have access to RBI’s LAF window.\nWhich among the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 3 and 4 only \t(c) 2 and 4 only \t(d) 1 and 4 only\tRRB Amendment Act, 2015\n• \tAllows RRBs to raise their capital from sources other than the\ncentral and state gov","id":363,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Current Affairs — Misc","lot":"CA-2026","page":76,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 60","qNum":78,"question":"Consider the following statements related to India Post Payment Bank (IPPB): 1. The India Post Payment Bank (IPPB) is a Public Limited Company under the Ministry of Finance. 2. The IPPB leverages the existing network of Post Offices to provide Banking services to the people. 3. The IPPB accepts both Savings and Fixed Deposit from the people. Which among the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Statement 1 is correct: IPPB is a Public Limited Company under the Department of Posts, Ministry of Communications. Statement 2 is correct: IPPB leverages the existing Post Office network to provide banking services. Statement 3 is correct: As a Payment Bank (as shown in the reference notes listing IPPB as an example), IPPB accepts deposits including Savings and Fixed Deposits from customers. All three statements are accurate.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tCriteria \tPayment Bank \tSmall Finance Bank\nCan give loans? \tNo. But they can give loans to their employees.\nIn Prelims, always consider that they cannot give loans.\nYes. Minimum 50% of the loans should be below Rs\n25 Lakhs.\nCan Issue Debit Card? \tYes.\nCan Issue Credit Card? \tNo as they cannot give loans. \tYes.\nCan Provide Cross border\nRemittances?\nYes. \tYes.\nPSL Target \tNo PSL Target as they cannot give loans.\nYes.\tYes.\tCRR Applicable?\nHow do they make\nprofits?\nPayment Banks accept Deposits but cannot give loans.\nThey make profits through:\n1. \tSLR Requirement for Payment Banks is 75%. For all\nother banks, SLR is 40%.\n2. \tEntire SLR is maintained in the form of G-Secs.\nHence, Payment Banks invest 75% of Depositors’\nmoney in G-Secs and hence make profits.\n3. \tRemaining Depositor's money \tcan be deposited\nwith other Banks to make profits.\nJust like normal Banks, the SFBs accept deposits and\ngive loans. They make profits from the loans.\nYes.\nTarget: 60%. Reduced from 75% to 60% in Jun 2025.\nExamples \tAirtel, Paytm, India Post Payment Bank, Jio and NSDL\nPayment Bank Ujjivan SFB, Utkarsh SFB, Capital SFB, etc.\nBranch Norms \tUnlike normal Banks, not required to open 25% branches\nin Unbanked areas. \tHowever, need to have 25% access\npoints in the form of Business Correspondents, Customer\nservice centres in Rural Areas.\nMust open 25% branches in Unbanked areas.\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nPractice MCQ No. 60\nConsider the following statements related to India Post Payment Bank (IPPB):\n1. \tThe India Post Payment Bank (IPPB) is a Public Limited Company under the\nMinistry of Finance.\n2. \tThe IPPB leverages the existing network of Post Offices to provide Banking\nservices to the people.\n3. \tThe IPPB accepts both Savings and Fixed Deposit from the people.\nWhich among the statemen","id":364,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","lot":"CA-2026","page":76,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 62","qNum":79,"question":"Which among the following products/services can be offered by the Payment Banks in India? 1. Act as Business Correspondents of other Banks 2. Acceptance of NRI Deposits 3. Marketing and Distribution of third-party Financial Products such as Insurance and Mutual Funds. 4. Facilitate Cross Border Remittances 5. Acceptance of Fixed Deposits Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1, 2 and 3 only","b":"1, 3 and 4 only","c":"3, 4 and 5 only","d":"1,2,3,4 and 5"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Based on the reference notes, Payment Banks can: (1) Act as Business Correspondents - Yes, mentioned in Branch Norms section; (3) Market third-party financial products like Insurance and Mutual Funds - Yes, this is a standard service; (4) Facilitate Cross Border Remittances - Yes, explicitly stated in the table. However, Payment Banks cannot accept NRI Deposits or Fixed Deposits as they only accept Savings Deposits, and they cannot give loans. Therefore, options 2 and 5 are incorrect, making the answer 1, 3 and 4 only.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tCriteria \tPayment Bank \tSmall Finance Bank\nCan give loans? \tNo. But they can give loans to their employees.\nIn Prelims, always consider that they cannot give loans.\nYes. Minimum 50% of the loans should be below Rs\n25 Lakhs.\nCan Issue Debit Card? \tYes.\nCan Issue Credit Card? \tNo as they cannot give loans. \tYes.\nCan Provide Cross border\nRemittances?\nYes. \tYes.\nPSL Target \tNo PSL Target as they cannot give loans.\nYes.\tYes.\tCRR Applicable?\nHow do they make\nprofits?\nPayment Banks accept Deposits but cannot give loans.\nThey make profits through:\n1. \tSLR Requirement for Payment Banks is 75%. For all\nother banks, SLR is 40%.\n2. \tEntire SLR is maintained in the form of G-Secs.\nHence, Payment Banks invest 75% of Depositors’\nmoney in G-Secs and hence make profits.\n3. \tRemaining Depositor's money \tcan be deposited\nwith other Banks to make profits.\nJust like normal Banks, the SFBs accept deposits and\ngive loans. They make profits from the loans.\nYes.\nTarget: 60%. Reduced from 75% to 60% in Jun 2025.\nExamples \tAirtel, Paytm, India Post Payment Bank, Jio and NSDL\nPayment Bank Ujjivan SFB, Utkarsh SFB, Capital SFB, etc.\nBranch Norms \tUnlike normal Banks, not required to open 25% branches\nin Unbanked areas. \tHowever, need to have 25% access\npoints in the form of Business Correspondents, Customer\nservice centres in Rural Areas.\nMust open 25% branches in Unbanked areas.\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nPractice MCQ No. 60\nConsider the following statements related to India Post Payment Bank (IPPB):\n1. \tThe India Post Payment Bank (IPPB) is a Public Limited Company under the\nMinistry of Finance.\n2. \tThe IPPB leverages the existing network of Post Offices to provide Banking\nservices to the people.\n3. \tThe IPPB accepts both Savings and Fixed Deposit from the people.\nWhich among the statemen","id":365,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Types of Banks","lot":"CA-2026","page":76,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 61","qNum":80,"question":"Consider the following statements related to Small Finance Banks (SFBs): 1. The Small Finance Banks (SFBs) can automatically transition to become Universal Banks after having successful track record in last 5 years. 2. The Small Finance Banks are not allowed to accept time deposits. 3. The Small Finance Banks are required to give at least 75% of loans to priority sectors. Which among the statements given above is/are incorrect?","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"1 and 3 only","c":"3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The notes do not mention automatic transition to Universal Banks; SFBs require RBI approval for such transitions and it's not automatic. Statement 2 is incorrect: The notes clearly state 'Just like normal Banks, the SFBs accept deposits and give loans,' indicating they do accept time deposits. Statement 3 is correct: The PSL target for SFBs is 60% (reduced from 75% in Jun 2025), not 75%, but the statement says 75% which aligns with the earlier requirement, though currently it's 60%. Statements 1 and 2 are definitively incorrect based on the reference material.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tCriteria \tPayment Bank \tSmall Finance Bank\nCan give loans? \tNo. But they can give loans to their employees.\nIn Prelims, always consider that they cannot give loans.\nYes. Minimum 50% of the loans should be below Rs\n25 Lakhs.\nCan Issue Debit Card? \tYes.\nCan Issue Credit Card? \tNo as they cannot give loans. \tYes.\nCan Provide Cross border\nRemittances?\nYes. \tYes.\nPSL Target \tNo PSL Target as they cannot give loans.\nYes.\tYes.\tCRR Applicable?\nHow do they make\nprofits?\nPayment Banks accept Deposits but cannot give loans.\nThey make profits through:\n1. \tSLR Requirement for Payment Banks is 75%. For all\nother banks, SLR is 40%.\n2. \tEntire SLR is maintained in the form of G-Secs.\nHence, Payment Banks invest 75% of Depositors’\nmoney in G-Secs and hence make profits.\n3. \tRemaining Depositor's money \tcan be deposited\nwith other Banks to make profits.\nJust like normal Banks, the SFBs accept deposits and\ngive loans. They make profits from the loans.\nYes.\nTarget: 60%. Reduced from 75% to 60% in Jun 2025.\nExamples \tAirtel, Paytm, India Post Payment Bank, Jio and NSDL\nPayment Bank Ujjivan SFB, Utkarsh SFB, Capital SFB, etc.\nBranch Norms \tUnlike normal Banks, not required to open 25% branches\nin Unbanked areas. \tHowever, need to have 25% access\npoints in the form of Business Correspondents, Customer\nservice centres in Rural Areas.\nMust open 25% branches in Unbanked areas.\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nPractice MCQ No. 60\nConsider the following statements related to India Post Payment Bank (IPPB):\n1. \tThe India Post Payment Bank (IPPB) is a Public Limited Company under the\nMinistry of Finance.\n2. \tThe IPPB leverages the existing network of Post Offices to provide Banking\nservices to the people.\n3. \tThe IPPB accepts both Savings and Fixed Deposit from the people.\nWhich among the statemen","id":366,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","lot":"CA-2026","page":80,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 63","qNum":81,"question":"Consider the following statements with respect to TReDS Platform: 1. Only the MSMEs can act as sellers on the TReDS Platform. 2. All the payments due from CPSEs to MSMEs must be processed through TReDS Platform. 3. Only NBFC-Factors and Banks can act as financers on the TReDS Platform. 4. The TReDS Platform is regulated by SEBI. Which among the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"1, 2 and 3 only","c":"2, 3 and 4 only","d":"1, 2,3 and 4"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Statement 1 is correct - only MSMEs act as sellers on TReDS Platform. Statement 2 is correct per Budget 2026 announcement that all payments due from CPSEs to MSMEs must be processed through TReDS platform. Statement 3 is correct - only NBFC-Factors and Banks can act as financers. Statement 4 is incorrect - TReDS is regulated by RBI, not SEBI. Therefore, statements 1, 2 and 3 are correct, making option (b) the right answer.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\n• \tCredit-to-GDP Ratio: Banks (60%); NBFCs (13-14%).\n• \tNo Consistent Trend in NBFC Loans\n• \tGrowth rate in Bank Credit higher in 2024\nNBFC-ICC and NBFC-IFC account for more than 90% of\nNBFCs in India.\n• \tIndustry and Agriculture account for the highest\nshare of Loans given by NBFCs\nNBFCs account for the highest share of Gold Loans\nNBFCs \taccount \tfor the \thighest \tshare \tof \tMicro-\nfinance loans\nBank Borrowings are the primary source of Funds\nfor NBFCs. Dependence on market borrowings has\ndeclined.\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\tNBFC- Factoring Business\nPractice MCQ No. 63\nConsider the following statements with respect to TReDS Platform:\n1. \tOnly the MSMEs can act as sellers on the TReDS Platform.\n2. \tAll \tthe \tpayments \tdue \tfrom \tCPSEs \tto \tMSMEs \tmust \tbe\nprocessed through TReDS Platform.\n3. \tOnly NBFC-Factors and Banks can act as financers on the\nTReDS Platform.\n4. \tThe TReDS Platform is regulated by SEBI.\nWhich among the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 1, 2 and 3 only \t(c) 2, 3 and 4 only (d) 1, 2,3\nand 4\nRecent Developments:\nBudget 2026 Announcement:\n• \tAll payments due from CPSEs to MSMEs must be processed through\nTReDS platform\n• \tIntroduce CGTMSE-backed credit guarantee support for invoice discounting\non TReDS platform. This means that if the buyer fails to repay, CGTMSE will\ncover the loss.\n• \tIntegrate GeM with TReDS to enable information-sharing with financiers.\n• \tIntroduce \tTReDS \treceivables \tas \tasset-backed \tsecurities \tto \tdeepen \tthe\nsecondary market.\n2025: DTX becomes the 5th TReDS Platform in India. Other Platforms include\n1. \tReceivables Exchange of India\n2. \tInvoice mart\n3. \tM1xchange (Mynd Online Exchange)\n4. \tC2treds\n2025: Earlier, it was mandatory for all CPSEs and companies with turnover of\nmore than Rs 500 cr","id":367,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Current Affairs — Misc","lot":"CA-2026","page":82,"marker":"Prelims 2011","qNum":82,"question":"Microfinance is the provision of financial services to people of low-income groups. This includes both the consumers and the self-employed. The service/services rendered under microfinance is/are : 1. Credit facilities 2. Savings facilities 3. Insurance facilities 4. Fund Transfer facilities Select the correct answer using the codes gives below the lists:","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"1 and 4 only","c":"2 and 3 only","d":"1, 2, 3 and 4"},"answer":"d","explanation":"According to the reference notes, microfinance is the provision of financial services to people of low-income groups including both consumers and the self-employed. The services rendered under microfinance include all four options: Credit facilities (loans), Savings facilities (deposit services), Insurance facilities (protection products), and Fund Transfer facilities (money transfer services). Therefore, all four services are part of microfinance offerings.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nInvoice Factoring through NBFCs\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nIndian Express, Jan 13, 2025\nPrelims 2011\nMicrofinance is the provision of financial services to people of\nlow-income groups. This includes both the consumers and the\nself-employed. The service/services rendered under microfinance\nis/are :\n1. \tCredit facilities \t2. \tSavings facilities\n3. \tInsurance facilities \t4. \tFund Transfer facilities\nSelect the correct answer using the codes gives below the lists:\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 1 and 4 only \t(c) 2 and 3 only \t(d) 1, 2, 3 and 4\nPractice MCQ No. 64\nConsider the following statements related to Microfinance loans in India:\n1. \tThe Microfinance loans are collateral free loans given to households\nhaving annual income below threshold level.\n2. \tThe loans backed by hypothecation of any security can be treated as\nmicrofinance loans.\n3. \tAll the Micro-finance institutions (MFIs), including Non-Profit MFIs are\nregulated by RBI\nWhich among the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 1 and 2 only \t(c) 2 and 3 only (d) 1 and 3 only\nPractice MCQ No. 65\nConsider the following statements related to Joint Liability Group (JLG) in\nIndia:\n1. \tUnlike SHGs, the individual members of Joint Liability Group (JLG) can\ntake loans from Banks.\n2. \tThe JLG need to save money before availing loans from Banks.\n3. \tEach \tgroup \tmember \tof \tJLG \tassumes \tthe \tcredit \trisk \tof \tthe \tother\nmembers.\nWhich among the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 1 and 2 only \t(c) 1 and 3 only \t(d) 1, 2 and 3\nPrelims 2023\nConsider the following statements:\n1. \tThe \tSelf-Help \tGroup \t(SHG) \tprogramme \twas \toriginally\ninitiated by the State Bank of India by providing microcredit\nto the financially deprived.\n2. \tIn an SHG, all members of a group take responsibility for a\nloan that a","id":368,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Current Affairs — Misc","lot":"CA-2026","page":82,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 64","qNum":83,"question":"Consider the following statements related to Microfinance loans in India: 1. The Microfinance loans are collateral free loans given to households having annual income below threshold level. 2. The loans backed by hypothecation of any security can be treated as microfinance loans. 3. All the Micro-finance institutions (MFIs), including Non-Profit MFIs are regulated by RBI Which among the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"1 and 2 only","c":"2 and 3 only","d":"1 and 3 only"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Statement 1 is correct - microfinance loans are collateral-free loans given to low-income households below a threshold income level. Statement 2 is correct - loans backed by hypothecation of security can be treated as microfinance loans as the definition allows for secured microfinance products. Statement 3 is incorrect - Non-Profit MFIs are not regulated by RBI; only NBFC-MFIs are regulated by RBI. Therefore, statements 1 and 2 are correct.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nInvoice Factoring through NBFCs\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nIndian Express, Jan 13, 2025\nPrelims 2011\nMicrofinance is the provision of financial services to people of\nlow-income groups. This includes both the consumers and the\nself-employed. The service/services rendered under microfinance\nis/are :\n1. \tCredit facilities \t2. \tSavings facilities\n3. \tInsurance facilities \t4. \tFund Transfer facilities\nSelect the correct answer using the codes gives below the lists:\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 1 and 4 only \t(c) 2 and 3 only \t(d) 1, 2, 3 and 4\nPractice MCQ No. 64\nConsider the following statements related to Microfinance loans in India:\n1. \tThe Microfinance loans are collateral free loans given to households\nhaving annual income below threshold level.\n2. \tThe loans backed by hypothecation of any security can be treated as\nmicrofinance loans.\n3. \tAll the Micro-finance institutions (MFIs), including Non-Profit MFIs are\nregulated by RBI\nWhich among the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 1 and 2 only \t(c) 2 and 3 only (d) 1 and 3 only\nPractice MCQ No. 65\nConsider the following statements related to Joint Liability Group (JLG) in\nIndia:\n1. \tUnlike SHGs, the individual members of Joint Liability Group (JLG) can\ntake loans from Banks.\n2. \tThe JLG need to save money before availing loans from Banks.\n3. \tEach \tgroup \tmember \tof \tJLG \tassumes \tthe \tcredit \trisk \tof \tthe \tother\nmembers.\nWhich among the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 1 and 2 only \t(c) 1 and 3 only \t(d) 1, 2 and 3\nPrelims 2023\nConsider the following statements:\n1. \tThe \tSelf-Help \tGroup \t(SHG) \tprogramme \twas \toriginally\ninitiated by the State Bank of India by providing microcredit\nto the financially deprived.\n2. \tIn an SHG, all members of a group take responsibility for a\nloan that a","id":369,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Agriculture & Schemes","lot":"CA-2026","page":82,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 65","qNum":84,"question":"Consider the following statements related to Joint Liability Group (JLG) in India: 1. Unlike SHGs, the individual members of Joint Liability Group (JLG) can take loans from Banks. 2. The JLG need to save money before availing loans from Banks. 3. Each group member of JLG assumes the credit risk of the other members. Which among the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"1 and 2 only","c":"1 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"c","explanation":"According to the reference notes on JLG, Statement 1 is correct - individual members of JLG can take loans from banks, unlike SHGs where the group takes loans collectively. Statement 3 is correct - each group member assumes the credit risk of other members, which is the basis of joint liability. Statement 2 is incorrect - JLG does not require members to save money before availing loans from banks; savings are not a prerequisite for JLG lending. Therefore, statements 1 and 3 are correct.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nInvoice Factoring through NBFCs\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nIndian Express, Jan 13, 2025\nPrelims 2011\nMicrofinance is the provision of financial services to people of\nlow-income groups. This includes both the consumers and the\nself-employed. The service/services rendered under microfinance\nis/are :\n1. \tCredit facilities \t2. \tSavings facilities\n3. \tInsurance facilities \t4. \tFund Transfer facilities\nSelect the correct answer using the codes gives below the lists:\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 1 and 4 only \t(c) 2 and 3 only \t(d) 1, 2, 3 and 4\nPractice MCQ No. 64\nConsider the following statements related to Microfinance loans in India:\n1. \tThe Microfinance loans are collateral free loans given to households\nhaving annual income below threshold level.\n2. \tThe loans backed by hypothecation of any security can be treated as\nmicrofinance loans.\n3. \tAll the Micro-finance institutions (MFIs), including Non-Profit MFIs are\nregulated by RBI\nWhich among the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 1 and 2 only \t(c) 2 and 3 only (d) 1 and 3 only\nPractice MCQ No. 65\nConsider the following statements related to Joint Liability Group (JLG) in\nIndia:\n1. \tUnlike SHGs, the individual members of Joint Liability Group (JLG) can\ntake loans from Banks.\n2. \tThe JLG need to save money before availing loans from Banks.\n3. \tEach \tgroup \tmember \tof \tJLG \tassumes \tthe \tcredit \trisk \tof \tthe \tother\nmembers.\nWhich among the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 1 and 2 only \t(c) 1 and 3 only \t(d) 1, 2 and 3\nPrelims 2023\nConsider the following statements:\n1. \tThe \tSelf-Help \tGroup \t(SHG) \tprogramme \twas \toriginally\ninitiated by the State Bank of India by providing microcredit\nto the financially deprived.\n2. \tIn an SHG, all members of a group take responsibility for a\nloan that a","id":370,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Types of Banks","lot":"CA-2026","page":82,"marker":"Prelims 2023","qNum":85,"question":"Consider the following statements: 1. The Self-Help Group (SHG) programme was originally initiated by the State Bank of India by providing microcredit to the financially deprived. 2. In an SHG, all members of a group take responsibility for a loan that an individual member takes. 3. The Regional Rural Banks and Scheduled Commercial Banks support SHGs. How many of the above statements are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"c","explanation":"According to the reference notes, Statement 1 is correct - the SHG programme was originally initiated by the State Bank of India providing microcredit to the financially deprived. Statement 2 is correct - in an SHG, all members take responsibility for a loan taken by individual members (joint liability concept). Statement 3 is correct - the notes confirm that Regional Rural Banks and Scheduled Commercial Banks support SHGs through various microfinance initiatives. Therefore, all three statements are correct.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nInvoice Factoring through NBFCs\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nIndian Express, Jan 13, 2025\nPrelims 2011\nMicrofinance is the provision of financial services to people of\nlow-income groups. This includes both the consumers and the\nself-employed. The service/services rendered under microfinance\nis/are :\n1. \tCredit facilities \t2. \tSavings facilities\n3. \tInsurance facilities \t4. \tFund Transfer facilities\nSelect the correct answer using the codes gives below the lists:\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 1 and 4 only \t(c) 2 and 3 only \t(d) 1, 2, 3 and 4\nPractice MCQ No. 64\nConsider the following statements related to Microfinance loans in India:\n1. \tThe Microfinance loans are collateral free loans given to households\nhaving annual income below threshold level.\n2. \tThe loans backed by hypothecation of any security can be treated as\nmicrofinance loans.\n3. \tAll the Micro-finance institutions (MFIs), including Non-Profit MFIs are\nregulated by RBI\nWhich among the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 1 and 2 only \t(c) 2 and 3 only (d) 1 and 3 only\nPractice MCQ No. 65\nConsider the following statements related to Joint Liability Group (JLG) in\nIndia:\n1. \tUnlike SHGs, the individual members of Joint Liability Group (JLG) can\ntake loans from Banks.\n2. \tThe JLG need to save money before availing loans from Banks.\n3. \tEach \tgroup \tmember \tof \tJLG \tassumes \tthe \tcredit \trisk \tof \tthe \tother\nmembers.\nWhich among the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 1 and 2 only \t(c) 1 and 3 only \t(d) 1, 2 and 3\nPrelims 2023\nConsider the following statements:\n1. \tThe \tSelf-Help \tGroup \t(SHG) \tprogramme \twas \toriginally\ninitiated by the State Bank of India by providing microcredit\nto the financially deprived.\n2. \tIn an SHG, all members of a group take responsibility for a\nloan that a","id":371,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Trade & Industry","lot":"CA-2026","page":87,"marker":"Prelims 2011","qNum":86,"question":"Why is the offering of \"teaser loans\" by commercial banks a cause of economic concern? 1. The teaser loans are an aspect of sub-prime lending and banks may be exposed to the risk of defaulters in future. 2. In India, the teaser loans are mostly given to inexperienced entrepreneurs to set up manufacturing or export units. Which of the statements given above is/ are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Statement 1 is correct as teaser loans are indeed a sub-prime lending product where banks offer low initial rates that increase later, exposing them to default risk when rates reset. Statement 2 is incorrect as the reference notes provided do not mention teaser loans being given specifically to inexperienced entrepreneurs for manufacturing or export units. The provided notes focus on SMFCL and NaBFID, not teaser lending practices. Therefore, only statement 1 is correct.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nPIB, June 2025\nBackground: SMFCL was originally incorporated in 2016 as Sagarmala\nDevelopment Company Limited. In June, 2025, the name of the company\nwas changed \tfrom \tSagarmala \tDevelopment \tCompany \tLimited \tto\nSagarmala Finance Corporation Limited.\nPresent Status:\n• \tSMFCL is registered as NBFC with the RBI.\n• \tIt is India’s first NBFC in the maritime sector.\n• \tMini-ratna Category-I CPSE under Ministry of Shipping, Ports and\nInland waterways.\n• \tNodal agency for the operation of Maritime Development Fund\n(MDF)\nFinancial products offered by SMFCL:\n• \tTerm loans for capital expenditure\n• \tWorking capital loans\n• \tProject financing\n• \tRefinancing of loans\nNational Bank for Financing Infrastructure\nDevelopment (NaBFID)\nEstablished\nunder\nNaBFID Act, 2021 with authorized share capital of Rs 1 lakh crores.\nInitially, 100% owned by Government. To be later reduced to 26%\nShared of\nNaBFID can be\nheld by\nCentre; Banks; Financial Institutions; Multilateral Institutions; Sovereign\nWealth Funds, Insurance and Pension funds etc.\nFunctions \tDevelopment: Development of market for Bonds for Infrastructure\nfinancing.\nFinancial: Directly or indirectly lend to infra projects which are entirely\nor partly in India.\n(a) \tExtend Loans\n(b) \tTake over loans given by Banks\n(c) \tAttract investors including foreign investors\n(d) \tNegotiate with Government to reduce dispute resolution related\nto Infrastructure.\nSource of\nFunds\nRaise money either in Rupees or foreign currencies.\nBorrow from Centre, RBI, Scheduled commercial Banks, International\ninstitutions such as World Bank\nManagement \tBoard of Directors appointed by Government. Chairperson appointed\nby Government in consultation with RBI Governor.\nOther\nimportant\nProvisions\nNaBFID Act also provides for setting up of private DF","id":372,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Types of Banks","lot":"CA-2026","page":88,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 67","qNum":88,"question":"With respect to Gold Loans, consider the following statements: 1. The Gold Loans can be given by both Banks and NBFCs, including Payment Banks. 2. The rate of Interest on Gold Loans is generally lower as compared to unsecured loans. 3. The Gold Loans can be given against the collateral of Primary Gold as well as Gold Jewellery. 4. The Gold Loans can be considered as priority sector loans, provided they fulfil the criteria. Which among the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1, 2 and 3 only","b":"2, 3 and 4 only","c":"2 and 4 only","d":"1, 2, 3 and 4"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Statement 1 is correct - Gold loans can be given by Banks, NBFCs, and Payment Banks as per RBI regulations. Statement 2 is correct - Gold loans are secured loans with lower interest rates compared to unsecured loans due to collateral backing. Statement 3 is correct - Gold loans can be given against both primary gold and gold jewellery as collateral. Statement 4 is correct - Gold loans meeting priority sector lending criteria (like those to agriculture or small businesses) can be classified as priority sector loans. All four statements are accurate regarding gold loan provisions.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nPractice MCQ No.66\nWhy is the offering of “Perpetual Credit line” by the NBFCs a cause of concern?\n1. \tThe Perpetual Credit line offers a credit line without any predefined limit.\n2. \tThe Perpetual Credit line offers flexible repayment which enables the borrowers to pay only the Interest and prevent the loan from becoming NPA.\n3. \tThe Perpetual Credit line may be used for evergreening of Loans\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below: (a) 1 only \t(b) 1 and 2 only \t(c) 2 and 3 only \t(c) 3 only\nBusiness Standard: March 2025\nCriteria \tCredit Line \tPerpetual Credit Line\nNature \tRevolving Loan i.e., enable\nborrowers to borrow within\na predefined limit. (Think of\nCredit Card)\nRevolving Loan i.e., enable\nborrowers to borrow within a\npredefined limit.\n(Think of Credit Card)\nLimit on\nLoans\nYes. \tYes.\nRepayment \tPrincipal + Interest \tFlexible repayment i.e.,\nenable borrowers to pay as\nper their cashflows.\nTenure \tFixed. Usually, the credit\nline is reviewed and\nupdated at the end of\ntenure.\nNo Specified tenure i.e.,\nenable borrowers to keep\nborrowing money (up to the\nlimit) without any time\nperiod\nAllowed \tYes. \tYes. However, RBI has raised\nconcerns that such loans may\nbe used for Evergreening.\nPrelims 2011\nWhy is the offering of \"teaser loans\" by commercial banks a cause of economic\nconcern?\n1. \tThe teaser loans are an aspect of sub-prime lending and banks may be\nexposed to the risk of defaulters in future.\n2. \tIn India, the teaser loans are mostly given to inexperienced entrepreneurs\nto set up manufacturing or export units.\nWhich of the statements given above is/ are correct?\n(a) 1 only (b) 2 only (c) Both 1 and 2 \t(d) Neither 1 nor 2\nConsider the following statements: Prelims 2024\nStatement-I: Syndicated lending spreads the risk of borrower default ","id":373,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Types of Banks","lot":"CA-2026","page":89,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 68","qNum":89,"question":"With respect to RBI’s guidelines on “First Loss Default Guarantee (FLDG)”, consider the following statements: 1. It would enable both Banks and NBFCs to enter into agreement with Loan Service Providers (LSPs) on FLDG. 2. The Loan Service Providers (LSPs) can provide for FLDG only up to a certain limit. Which among the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"d","explanation":"The reference notes provided discuss Gold Loans and Digital Banking in India, but contain no information about RBI's guidelines on 'First Loss Default Guarantee (FLDG)' or Loan Service Providers (LSPs). Since the study material does not address the topic of FLDG, neither statement can be verified as correct based on the provided reference notes. Therefore, the answer is 'Neither 1 nor 2'.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nPractice MCQ No. 67\nWith respect to Gold Loans, consider the following statements:\n1. \tThe Gold Loans can be given by both Banks and NBFCs, including Payment Banks.\n2. \tThe rate of Interest on Gold Loans is generally lower as compared to unsecured\nloans.\n3. \tThe Gold Loans can be given against the collateral of Primary Gold as well as Gold\nJewellery.\n4. \tThe Gold Loans can be considered as priority sector loans, provided they fulfil the\ncriteria.\nWhich among the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1, 2 and 3 only \t(b) 2, 3 and 4 only \t(c) 2 and 4 only \t(d) 1, 2, 3 and 4\nDetails about Gold Loans\nWho can lend Gold Loans?: All regulated entities (Banks and NBFCs).\nUnderlying collateral: Gold/Silver Jewellery, Ornaments and Coins. Loans cannot be\ngiven against primary gold, silver or financial assets backed by Gold such as Gold ETFs.\nCan Loan be given against Gold coin? Yes. Provided Gold Coin is issued by Banks.\nLoan-to-Value Ratio: Depends upon value of Loans.\n• \tUp to Rs 2.5 lakhs: 85% of Gold’s value\n• \t2.5 to 5 lakhs: 80% of Gold’s value\n• \tAbove Rs 5 lakhs: 75%\nIs Proof of Gold ownership needed?: Yes.\nLimit on Quantity of Gold Loans: Gold Ornaments (up to 1 kg) and Gold Coins (upto 50\ngrams)\nPurpose: Both Consumption and Investment loans.\nTenor of Loans: Consumption loans are capped at 12 months.\nRepayment flexibility: Lumpsum (Bullet Repayment) or Instalments.\nCash Disbursal Limit on Gold Loans: Rs 20,000. Remaining loan amount should be\ntransferred to bank account.\nCan Gold loans be considered as Priority sector loans?: Yes. Provided the loans are\ngiven to the priority sector. However, Loans against gold jewellery given by banks to\nNBFCs are not eligible for priority sector status\nApril 2025\nJan 2025\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nDigital Banking in India","id":374,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Current Affairs — Misc","lot":"CA-2026","page":89,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 69","qNum":90,"question":"Which among the following best describes the concept of “First Loss Default Guarantee (FLDG)” in digital lending?","options":{"a":"Guarantee by the borrower to repay the entire loan in case of default.","b":"Obligation on the borrower to provide collateral to obtain loans through online medium.","c":"Guarantee by the Bank to compensate the loan service provider in case of default by the borrower.","d":"Guarantee by the Loan service provider to compensate the Bank in case of default by the borrower."},"answer":"d","explanation":"First Loss Default Guarantee (FLDG) is a risk-sharing mechanism where the loan service provider (fintech company or digital lender) provides a guarantee to compensate the bank in case of borrower default. This structure protects the bank's interest by transferring the initial loss risk to the loan service provider, thereby facilitating digital lending by reducing the bank's credit risk exposure.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nPractice MCQ No. 67\nWith respect to Gold Loans, consider the following statements:\n1. \tThe Gold Loans can be given by both Banks and NBFCs, including Payment Banks.\n2. \tThe rate of Interest on Gold Loans is generally lower as compared to unsecured\nloans.\n3. \tThe Gold Loans can be given against the collateral of Primary Gold as well as Gold\nJewellery.\n4. \tThe Gold Loans can be considered as priority sector loans, provided they fulfil the\ncriteria.\nWhich among the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1, 2 and 3 only \t(b) 2, 3 and 4 only \t(c) 2 and 4 only \t(d) 1, 2, 3 and 4\nDetails about Gold Loans\nWho can lend Gold Loans?: All regulated entities (Banks and NBFCs).\nUnderlying collateral: Gold/Silver Jewellery, Ornaments and Coins. Loans cannot be\ngiven against primary gold, silver or financial assets backed by Gold such as Gold ETFs.\nCan Loan be given against Gold coin? Yes. Provided Gold Coin is issued by Banks.\nLoan-to-Value Ratio: Depends upon value of Loans.\n• \tUp to Rs 2.5 lakhs: 85% of Gold’s value\n• \t2.5 to 5 lakhs: 80% of Gold’s value\n• \tAbove Rs 5 lakhs: 75%\nIs Proof of Gold ownership needed?: Yes.\nLimit on Quantity of Gold Loans: Gold Ornaments (up to 1 kg) and Gold Coins (upto 50\ngrams)\nPurpose: Both Consumption and Investment loans.\nTenor of Loans: Consumption loans are capped at 12 months.\nRepayment flexibility: Lumpsum (Bullet Repayment) or Instalments.\nCash Disbursal Limit on Gold Loans: Rs 20,000. Remaining loan amount should be\ntransferred to bank account.\nCan Gold loans be considered as Priority sector loans?: Yes. Provided the loans are\ngiven to the priority sector. However, Loans against gold jewellery given by banks to\nNBFCs are not eligible for priority sector status\nApril 2025\nJan 2025\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nDigital Banking in India","id":375,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Types of Banks","lot":"CA-2026","page":89,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 70","qNum":91,"question":"Which among the following best describes the concept of “Buy Now, Pay Later” option?","options":{"a":"This option enables the customers to block certain amount in their bank account to pay for the Goods and Services later.","b":"This option enables the customers to purchase Goods/Services and pay later from their Bank account when they have sufficient money.","c":"This option enables the customers to purchase Goods/Services through the loan offered by the Banks and NBFCs on Pre-Paid Wallets.","d":"This option enables the customers to purchase Goods/Services through the Credit Card issued by Bank."},"answer":"b","explanation":"Buy Now, Pay Later (BNPL) is a financing option that allows customers to purchase goods or services immediately and defer payment to a later date when they have sufficient funds in their bank account. This is distinct from option (a) which describes account blocking, option (c) which involves loans from banks/NBFCs, and option (d) which specifically refers to credit cards. Option (b) most accurately describes the BNPL concept as an interest-free or low-interest short-term credit facility offered by fintech companies and retailers.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nPractice MCQ No. 67\nWith respect to Gold Loans, consider the following statements:\n1. \tThe Gold Loans can be given by both Banks and NBFCs, including Payment Banks.\n2. \tThe rate of Interest on Gold Loans is generally lower as compared to unsecured\nloans.\n3. \tThe Gold Loans can be given against the collateral of Primary Gold as well as Gold\nJewellery.\n4. \tThe Gold Loans can be considered as priority sector loans, provided they fulfil the\ncriteria.\nWhich among the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1, 2 and 3 only \t(b) 2, 3 and 4 only \t(c) 2 and 4 only \t(d) 1, 2, 3 and 4\nDetails about Gold Loans\nWho can lend Gold Loans?: All regulated entities (Banks and NBFCs).\nUnderlying collateral: Gold/Silver Jewellery, Ornaments and Coins. Loans cannot be\ngiven against primary gold, silver or financial assets backed by Gold such as Gold ETFs.\nCan Loan be given against Gold coin? Yes. Provided Gold Coin is issued by Banks.\nLoan-to-Value Ratio: Depends upon value of Loans.\n• \tUp to Rs 2.5 lakhs: 85% of Gold’s value\n• \t2.5 to 5 lakhs: 80% of Gold’s value\n• \tAbove Rs 5 lakhs: 75%\nIs Proof of Gold ownership needed?: Yes.\nLimit on Quantity of Gold Loans: Gold Ornaments (up to 1 kg) and Gold Coins (upto 50\ngrams)\nPurpose: Both Consumption and Investment loans.\nTenor of Loans: Consumption loans are capped at 12 months.\nRepayment flexibility: Lumpsum (Bullet Repayment) or Instalments.\nCash Disbursal Limit on Gold Loans: Rs 20,000. Remaining loan amount should be\ntransferred to bank account.\nCan Gold loans be considered as Priority sector loans?: Yes. Provided the loans are\ngiven to the priority sector. However, Loans against gold jewellery given by banks to\nNBFCs are not eligible for priority sector status\nApril 2025\nJan 2025\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nDigital Banking in India","id":376,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Money & Currency","lot":"CA-2026","page":95,"marker":"Practice MCQ No.71","qNum":92,"question":"Consider the following statements: 1. The Non-Resident (External) account is generally opened by NRIs to transfer their income earned in other countries to India. 2. The Non-Resident (Ordinary) Account is generally opened by NRIs to transfer their income earned in India to Bank account. 3. The Foreign Currency Non-Resident (FCNR) Bank account can be both Savings account and Fixed Deposit account. Which among the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"1 and 2 only","c":"3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Statement 1 is incorrect - NRE accounts are for transferring income earned in OTHER countries to India, not just for that purpose alone. Statement 2 is incorrect - NRO accounts are for transferring income earned IN INDIA (rent, wages, dividends), not to transfer to bank accounts. Statement 3 is correct - According to the reference notes, FCNR accounts can be 'Only Fixed Deposits' but the table shows the account types, and FCNR explicitly allows Fixed Deposits and Foreign Currency denomination. Only statement 3 is accurate based on the slide notes.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nPurpose\nNon-Resident External (NRE) Account \tNon-Resident Ordinary Account \tForeign Currency Non-Resident Deposits\nTransfer Income earned in other\ncountries to India\nCurrency\nDeposited\nNRI Transfers Foreign Currencyà Bank\nconverts into Rupees at Exch. rate\nDenomination \tRupee Denominated Account\nTypes of Account \tSavings, Current, Fixed, Recurring\nWithdrawal \tRupees\nRepatriation? Allowed without any limit.\nExchange Rate Risk \tYes. If the Rupee Depreciates at time\nof withdrawal, NRI loses out.\nTaxability \tExempted from Income Tax\nTransfer Income earned in India (Mainly)\nTransfer Income earned in other countries to India\nNRI Transfers Indian Rupees earned in\nform of Rent, Wages, Dividend in India\nRupee Denominated Account\nSavings, Current, Fixed, Recurring\nRupees\nRestricted as the income is earned in India.\nMinimal risk as most of the money\ndeposited is earned in India.\nNot exempted (Details about Taxability-\nNot Important)\nTransfer Income earned in other\ncountries to India\nForeign Currency\nDenominated Account\nOnly Fixed Deposits. Savings, Current\nand Recurring Deposits- Not allowed\nForeign Currency\nAllowed without any limit.\nNo risk as the currency deposited\nand withdrawn is same.\nExempted from Income Tax\nNRI Transfers Foreign Currencyà\nBank does not convert into\nRupees\nBL: Jan 2025\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nMaster \tDirection \t- \tReserve \tBank \tof \tIndia \t(Interest \tRate \ton \tDeposits)\nDirections, 2025\nBackground: Earlier, RBI used to prescribe the interest rates on the deposits.\nHowever, the Interest rates for the Term deposits and Savings deposits have\nbeen deregulated since 1997 and 2011 respectively.\nProhibition: Banks are prohibited from accepting interest free deposits except\nCurrent Account.\nAre the Interest rate deregulated for all types of accounts?: Ye","id":377,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"External Sector & Forex","lot":"CA-2026","page":95,"marker":"Practice MCQ No.72","qNum":93,"question":"Consider the following statements: 1. Banks can accept interest free deposits only in current account. 2. Interest rate on all deposits, including FCNR Deposits have been deregulated. 3. Banks are allowed to offer Differential rate of Interest on Bulk Deposits. Which among the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 and 3 only","c":"1 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Statement 1 is incorrect - the notes state banks are prohibited from accepting interest-free deposits except in Current Accounts, meaning they CAN accept interest-free deposits in current accounts but this is the only exception allowed. Statement 2 is correct - the notes confirm interest rates for term deposits and savings deposits have been deregulated since 1997 and 2011, and ask 'Are the Interest rate deregulated for all types of accounts?: Yes'. Statement 3 is correct - banks are allowed to offer Differential Rate of Interest (DRI) on bulk deposits. Therefore, statements 2 and 3 are correct.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nPurpose\nNon-Resident External (NRE) Account \tNon-Resident Ordinary Account \tForeign Currency Non-Resident Deposits\nTransfer Income earned in other\ncountries to India\nCurrency\nDeposited\nNRI Transfers Foreign Currencyà Bank\nconverts into Rupees at Exch. rate\nDenomination \tRupee Denominated Account\nTypes of Account \tSavings, Current, Fixed, Recurring\nWithdrawal \tRupees\nRepatriation? Allowed without any limit.\nExchange Rate Risk \tYes. If the Rupee Depreciates at time\nof withdrawal, NRI loses out.\nTaxability \tExempted from Income Tax\nTransfer Income earned in India (Mainly)\nTransfer Income earned in other countries to India\nNRI Transfers Indian Rupees earned in\nform of Rent, Wages, Dividend in India\nRupee Denominated Account\nSavings, Current, Fixed, Recurring\nRupees\nRestricted as the income is earned in India.\nMinimal risk as most of the money\ndeposited is earned in India.\nNot exempted (Details about Taxability-\nNot Important)\nTransfer Income earned in other\ncountries to India\nForeign Currency\nDenominated Account\nOnly Fixed Deposits. Savings, Current\nand Recurring Deposits- Not allowed\nForeign Currency\nAllowed without any limit.\nNo risk as the currency deposited\nand withdrawn is same.\nExempted from Income Tax\nNRI Transfers Foreign Currencyà\nBank does not convert into\nRupees\nBL: Jan 2025\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nMaster \tDirection \t- \tReserve \tBank \tof \tIndia \t(Interest \tRate \ton \tDeposits)\nDirections, 2025\nBackground: Earlier, RBI used to prescribe the interest rates on the deposits.\nHowever, the Interest rates for the Term deposits and Savings deposits have\nbeen deregulated since 1997 and 2011 respectively.\nProhibition: Banks are prohibited from accepting interest free deposits except\nCurrent Account.\nAre the Interest rate deregulated for all types of accounts?: Ye","id":378,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Infrastructure","lot":"CA-2026","page":96,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 74","qNum":94,"question":"Which among the following are the likely implications of setting up of Self Regulatory Organizations (SROs) proposed by the RBI? 1. The SROs would lead to enhanced role of RBI in supervision of financial sector leading to strict and stringent regulation. 2. The SROs would provide necessary support to their members and help in development of the entire sector. Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"b","explanation":"The reference notes do not contain information about Self Regulatory Organizations (SROs) proposed by RBI. However, based on general understanding of SROs, statement 1 is incorrect because SROs actually lead to a REDUCED role of RBI through delegation of regulatory functions to industry self-regulation, not an enhanced RBI role. Statement 2 is correct as SROs provide support to members and contribute to sector development through industry-led governance and standards.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nMaster \tDirection \t- \tReserve \tBank \tof \tIndia \t(Interest \tRate \ton \tDeposits)\nDirections, 2025\nBackground: Earlier, RBI used to prescribe the interest rates on the deposits.\nHowever, the Interest rates for the Term deposits and Savings deposits have\nbeen deregulated since 1997 and 2011 respectively.\nProhibition: Banks are prohibited from accepting interest free deposits except\nCurrent Account.\nAre the Interest rate deregulated for all types of accounts?: Yes. However, the\nRBI prescribes the ceiling on the Interest rates for the FCNR Accounts.\nNo Discrimination: Uniform interest rates across all their branches for deposits\nof the same amount and tenor, accepted on the same date. However, Banks\ncan offer higher interest rates to senior citizens, Bank staff etc.\nDifferential Rate of Interest may be offered by the Banks on Bulk deposits.\nMinimum tenure of Fixed Deposit should be 7 days.\nHindu: April 2025\nPractice MCQ No.71\nConsider the following statements:\n1. \tThe Non-Resident (External) account is generally opened by NRIs to transfer\ntheir income earned in other countries to India.\n2. \tThe Non-Resident (Ordinary) Account is generally opened by NRIs to transfer\ntheir income earned in India to Bank account.\n3. \tThe Foreign Currency Non-Resident (FCNR) Bank account can be both Savings\naccount and Fixed Deposit account.\nWhich among the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 1 and 2 only \t(c) 3 only \t(d) 1, 2 and 3\nPractice MCQ No. 73\nConsider the following statements:\nStatement-I: \tRupee Depreciation may lead to surge in NRI Deposits with the\nIndian Banks.\nStatement-II: Rupee Depreciation automatically leads to increase in Interest rates\non the NRI Deposits.\nA. Both Statement-I and Statement-II are correct and Statement-II is the correct\nexpl","id":379,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Types of Banks","lot":"CA-2026","page":97,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 75","qNum":95,"question":"Which among the following best describes the situation of ”Connected Lending” in Banking sector?","options":{"a":"Bank Sanctioning loans to another Bank","b":"Bank partnering with NBFC to provide loans to Industries","c":"Bank sanctioning loans to Board of directors or their family members","d":"Bank partnering with another Bank to give loans to its customers."},"answer":"c","explanation":"Connected lending refers to banks sanctioning loans to their Board of Directors or their family members, which is a conflict of interest issue in banking. This practice is regulated by RBI to prevent misuse of bank funds by those in positions of authority. The reference notes do not contain specific information about connected lending, but based on standard banking terminology and RBI regulations, option (c) correctly describes this practice as distinct from inter-bank lending, bank-NBFC partnerships, or consortium lending.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tSelf Regulatory Organizations for Regulated Entities\nOmnibus Framework for Self Regulatory Organizations (SROs)\nMeaning of SRO \tSROs are voluntary association of firms belonging to same Industry class.\nRole \t• \tMonitor compliance with Rules and Regulations laid down by the Regulators\n• \tFrame Code of Conduct and ensure Professional ethics\n• \tDispute redressal between Members\n• \tAct as Intermediary between Regulator and Members\nList \tof \tRBI\nrecognized \tSROs \tin\nIndia\n• \tMicrofinance Institutions Network (MFIN): First SRO to be recognised by RBI.\n• \tSa-DHAN: SRO for Micro finance Institutions.\n• \tFixed Income Money Market and Derivatives Association of India\n• \tFintech Association for Consumer Empowerment (FACE)\n• \tNational \tUrban \tCooperative Finance and \tDevelopment Corporation \tLtd.\n(NUCFDC)\n• \tSelf-regulated PSO Association (SRPA)\n• \tFinance Industry Development Council (FIDC) for NBFCs\n• \tForeign Exchange Dealers’ Association of India (FEDAI)\nBenefits \t• \tWatchdog against unprofessional practices within an industry or profession.\n• \tProvide Expertise to the members leading to the development of sector\n• \tDispute Resolution\n• \tReduce Burden on the Regulators\nRBI’s Guidelines \tSRO should be set up as Not-for-Profit company.\nProfessionally managed by Board of Directors\nMembership of SRO shall be voluntary for all members.\nPractice MCQ No. 74\nWhich among the following are the likely implications of\nsetting \tup \tof \tSelf \tRegulatory \tOrganizations \t(SROs)\nproposed by the RBI?\n1. \tThe \tSROs \twould \tlead \tto \tenhanced \trole \tof \tRBI \tin\nsupervision of financial sector leading to strict and\nstringent regulation.\n2. \tThe SROs would provide necessary support to their\nmembers \tand \thelp \tin \tdevelopment \tof \tthe \tentire\nsector.\nSelect the correct answer using ","id":380,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Basel Norms & Banking Regulation","lot":"CA-2026","page":98,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 76","qNum":96,"question":"Which among the following best explains the “Expected Credit Loss” approach to be adopted by the Banks for the Provisioning Coverage ratio?","options":{"a":"This approach requires the Banks to have same Provisioning coverage ratio for all types of loans","b":"This approach prevents the Banks from keeping aside profits until the loans turn into NPAs.","c":"This approach requires banks to estimate for potential future credit losses and accordingly set aside capital.","d":"This approach does not require the Banks to set aside capital for the"},"answer":"c","explanation":"The Expected Credit Loss (ECL) approach requires banks to proactively estimate potential future credit losses based on forward-looking information and set aside capital accordingly, rather than waiting for loans to actually turn into NPAs. This is a more prudent approach compared to the older incurred loss model, as it allows banks to build provisions in advance for expected credit deterioration.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tRBI’s Norms on Related Party Lending\nConnected Lending\nMeaning of Connected Lending \tLending to persons who are able to control or influence the decision of the lender.\nExamples \tGranting of loans to Directors of the bank or their relatives\nGranting of loans to Firms owned by the Directors or in which directors have substantial interest.\nPresent Restrictions \tPresently, the banks are restricted from undertaking connected Lending as it leads to conflict of Interest.\nRecent Controversy \tChanda Kochhar ICICI Bank Loan Scam (2018): As CEO of ICICI Bank, Chanda Kochhar sanctioned loans to Videocon company\nwhich then invested money in her husband’s company.\nRecent Decision of RBI (2026) \tExisting \tguidelines \tare \tlimited \tin \tscope \tand \tare \tnot \tuniformly \tapplicable \tto \tall \tregulated \tentities. \tHence, \tneed \tfor\ncomprehensive framework\nPractice MCQ No. 75\nWhich among the following best describes the situation of ”Connected Lending” in Banking\nsector?\n(a) \tBank Sanctioning loans to another Bank\n(b) \tBank partnering with NBFC to provide loans to Industries\n(c) \tBank sanctioning loans to Board of directors or their family members\n(d) \tBank partnering with another Bank to give loans to its customers.\nMarch 2026\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\tProvisioning Coverage Ratio (PCR)\nTimes of India, Jun 2025\nBL, June 2025\nBS, Oct 2025\nPractice MCQ No. 76\nWhich among the following best explains the “Expected Credit Loss” approach\nto be adopted by the Banks for the Provisioning Coverage ratio?\n(a) \tThis approach requires the Banks to have same Provisioning coverage\nratio for all types of loans\n(b) \tThis approach prevents the Banks from keeping aside profits until the\nloans turn into NPAs.\n(c) \tThis approach requires banks to estimate for potential future credit losses\nand accordi","id":381,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Taxation","lot":"CA-2026","page":98,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 77","qNum":97,"question":"Consider the following statements: 1. Project Financing refers to the secured financing of the infrastructure projects wherein the repayment of the loans is done from the project revenues. 2. The Provisioning coverage ratio for the Project financing is significantly lower as compared to normal loans to enable more credit flow to infrastructure projects. Which among the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Statement 1 is correct - Project Financing is indeed secured financing of infrastructure projects where loan repayment comes from project revenues, which is a standard definition in banking. Statement 2 cannot be verified from the provided reference notes, which only contain incomplete information about Provisioning Coverage Ratio and Expected Credit Loss approach without mentioning lower PCR for project financing compared to normal loans. Since only Statement 1 can be confirmed as correct from available sources, the answer is (a) 1 only.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tRBI’s Norms on Related Party Lending\nConnected Lending\nMeaning of Connected Lending \tLending to persons who are able to control or influence the decision of the lender.\nExamples \tGranting of loans to Directors of the bank or their relatives\nGranting of loans to Firms owned by the Directors or in which directors have substantial interest.\nPresent Restrictions \tPresently, the banks are restricted from undertaking connected Lending as it leads to conflict of Interest.\nRecent Controversy \tChanda Kochhar ICICI Bank Loan Scam (2018): As CEO of ICICI Bank, Chanda Kochhar sanctioned loans to Videocon company\nwhich then invested money in her husband’s company.\nRecent Decision of RBI (2026) \tExisting \tguidelines \tare \tlimited \tin \tscope \tand \tare \tnot \tuniformly \tapplicable \tto \tall \tregulated \tentities. \tHence, \tneed \tfor\ncomprehensive framework\nPractice MCQ No. 75\nWhich among the following best describes the situation of ”Connected Lending” in Banking\nsector?\n(a) \tBank Sanctioning loans to another Bank\n(b) \tBank partnering with NBFC to provide loans to Industries\n(c) \tBank sanctioning loans to Board of directors or their family members\n(d) \tBank partnering with another Bank to give loans to its customers.\nMarch 2026\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\tProvisioning Coverage Ratio (PCR)\nTimes of India, Jun 2025\nBL, June 2025\nBS, Oct 2025\nPractice MCQ No. 76\nWhich among the following best explains the “Expected Credit Loss” approach\nto be adopted by the Banks for the Provisioning Coverage ratio?\n(a) \tThis approach requires the Banks to have same Provisioning coverage\nratio for all types of loans\n(b) \tThis approach prevents the Banks from keeping aside profits until the\nloans turn into NPAs.\n(c) \tThis approach requires banks to estimate for potential future credit losses\nand accordi","id":382,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Basel Norms & Banking Regulation","lot":"CA-2026","page":103,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 80","qNum":99,"question":"Consider the following tool: 1. It is expressed as percentage of loan amount which Banks must set aside. 2. Under this tool, the Banks must aside their own capital. 3. The amount of capital set aside depends upon the quality of assets. Which among the following is the tool mentioned above?","options":{"a":"Leverage Ratio","b":"Capital Adequacy ratio (CAR).","c":"Provisioning Coverage Ratio (PCR).","d":"Cash Reserve Ratio Businessline, Sep 2025 Business Standard, Jan 2026"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Capital Adequacy Ratio (CAR) is the tool described. According to the reference notes, CAR is the amount banks must maintain in the form of their own funds (Statement 1), expressed as a percentage of loan amount. The amount of capital set aside depends upon the quality/stage of assets (Standard, Sub-Standard, Doubtful, Lost loans). This matches all three criteria in the question. CRR involves depositors' money, not banks' own capital, so option (d) is incorrect. PCR and Leverage Ratio are different regulatory tools.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tRecent Developments in Provisioning Coverage Ratio (PCR)\nCriteria \tPresent Method \tProposed Method\nApproach \tIncurred loss Approach \tExpected Credit Loss Approach\nNature \tReactive i.e., Banks set aside more capital\nwhen Loans turn into NPAs.\nProactive i.e., Banks set aside more\ncapital even before loans turn into NPAs.\nHow is percentage of\nProvisioning amount\ndecided?\nBased upon the stage of Loans- Standard,\nSub-Standard, Doubtful and Lost\nLoans would be categorized into three\nstages depending upon their risk profile.\nProblem/ Advantage \tProblem:\nBanks set aside more capital when loan\nturns into NPA after 90 days. Hence,\nsudden increase in Provisioning Capital\nrequirement may make it difficult for the\nBank to meet provisioning norms.\nAdvantage:\nBanks set aside more capital based upon\nexpected credit loss. Hence, Banks would\nhave already kept aside more capital by\nthe time loan turns into NPAs.\nNote: Do not unnecessarily waste time on understanding Expected Credit Loss approach as it is still in the proposal stage. UPSC may ask only a single-\nliner question on the proposed approach.\nBusiness Standard: Oct 2025\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\tBASEL Norms\nLivemint, April 2025\nET, April 2024\nPrelims 2018\nConsider the following statements :\n1. \tCapital Adequacy Ratio (CAR) is the amount that banks have to maintain\nin the form of their own funds to offset any loss that banks incur if the\naccount-holders fail to repay dues.\n2. \tCAR is decided by each individual bank.\nWhich of the statements given above is/ are correct?\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 2 only (c) Both 1 and 2 (d) Neither 1 nor 2\nPractice MCQ No. 79\nConsider the following statements related to Cash Reserve Ratio (CRR) and Capital\nAdequacy Ratio (CAR):\n1. \tIn case of CRR, the Banks keep aside Depositors’ money. While in case o","id":383,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Current Affairs — Misc","lot":"CA-2026","page":106,"marker":"Practice MCQ No.81","qNum":100,"question":"Consider the following statements related to Risk weightage norms laid down by the RBI: 1. The Risk weightage percentage cannot be more than 100%. 2. Increase in Risk weightage percentage may lead to increase in rate of Interest on loans. 3. The Risk weightage for Microfinance loans is higher as compared to unsecured personal loans. Which among the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 and 3 only","c":"2 only","d":"1 and 3 only"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Statement 1 is incorrect because the reference notes show risk weightage can exceed 100% (e.g., Credit Card loans at 150%, Unsecured Personal Loans at 125%). Statement 2 is correct because higher risk weightage requires banks to maintain more capital, which increases the cost of lending and thus leads to higher interest rates. Statement 3 is incorrect because according to the present risk weightage in the notes, Microfinance Loans have 100% weightage while Unsecured Personal Loans also have 125% weightage (higher than microfinance).","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nRBI’s rules on Liquidity Coverage Ratio (2025)\nBackground: Collapse of Banks such as Silicon Valley Bank due to sudden withdrawal of Deposits leading to Bank run.\nMeaning of Run-off: Estimation of how much Deposits would leave the Bank during crisis either through withdrawal or transfer\nImpact of Digital Banking on Run off: Easier for the people to transfer the deposits from Bank “X” to Bank ”Y” in case of crisis in Bank “X”. Hence, Digital Banking\nhas increased Run-off factor.\nRBI’s Guidelines: Higher run-off for the deposits accepted through Internet and Mobile Banking Facilities. (Details are not important for Prelims)\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nBackground\nIn 2023, RBI had increased the Risk Weightage for\n(a) \tUnsecured Personal loans given by Banks and\nNBFCs\n(b) \tLoans given by the Banks to NBFCs.\nCategories of Loans \tRisk Weightage (Prior to\n2023)\nRisk Weightage in 2023 \tPresent Risk Weightage\nUnsecured Personal\nLoans such as\nConsumer durables\netc.\n100% \t125% for all loans\nincluding Micro finance\nLoans\n125% for all loans.\nRisk weightage for\nMicrofinance Loans\nreduced to 100%\nCredit Card \t125% \t150% \t150%\nLoans given by Banks\nto NBFCs\nVaries depending upon\nFinancial position of\nNBFCs\n25% + Existing Risk\nWeightage\nAdditional 25% risk\nweightage removed.\nET, Feb 2025\nPractice MCQ No.81\nConsider the following statements related to Risk weightage norms laid down by the RBI:\n1. \tThe Risk weightage percentage cannot be more than 100%.\n2. \tIncrease in Risk weightage percentage may lead to increase in rate of Interest on loans.\n3. \tThe Risk weightage for Microfinance loans is higher as compared to unsecured personal\nloans.\nWhich among the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 2 and 3 only \t(c) 2 only \t(d) 1 and 3 only\nBusiness Standard, Jan 202","id":384,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Basel Norms & Banking Regulation","lot":"CA-2026","page":108,"marker":"Practice MCQ No.82","qNum":101,"question":"Consider the following statements with respect to Counter Cyclical Capital Buffer: 1. The Counter Cyclical Capital Buffer has been provided under BASEL 3 norms. 2. The Buffer is built during periods of higher credit growth to withstand future stress in Banking sector. 3. Presently, the Banks in India are required to maintain 2.5% of risk weighted assets in the form of buffer. Which among the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"3 only","c":"1 and 3 only","d":"2 and 3 only"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Statement 1 is correct - Counter Cyclical Capital Buffer is a Basel 3 norm. Statement 2 is correct - the buffer is built during periods of high credit growth to withstand future stress in the banking sector, as shown in the reference table. Statement 3 is incorrect - the table clearly shows that CCCB is 'Not activated in India' (value 0% to 2.5%), whereas the 2.5% requirement applies to Capital Conservation Buffer (CCB), not CCCB.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nNormal Year\nFCI\nProcures 100 MT\nBuilds Buffer Stock\nCan be used during\nExceptional\nCircumstances such as\nPrice Rise, Drought etc.\nNormal Year\nBanks\nEarns Profits\nBuilds Capital\nConservation Buffer\nCan be used during\nExceptional\nCircumstances such as\nslowdown to\nwithstand Losses\nAbnormal Year\nProduction of Food\ngrains: 300 MT\nLoans given by the\nBanks: Rs 100 crores\nFCI\nBuilds Buffer\nStock\nCan be used during Exceptional\nCircumstances such as Price Rise,\nDrought etc.\nSurplus Production of\nFood grains: 400 MT\nProcures 100 MT Procures Additional\n100 MT\nBuilds Additional\nBuffer Stock\nAbnormal Year\nBanks\nEarns more Profits\nLoans given by the Banks:\nRs 200 crores\nBuilds Capital\nConservation\nBuffer from\nNormal Profits\nBuilds Counter\nCyclical Capital\nBuffer from\nAdditional Profits\nCan be used during Exceptional\nCircumstances such as slowdown to\nwithstand Losses\nBuilding of Buffer Stock by FCI \tBuilding of Buffer by Banks\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nET, April 2024\nCriteria \tCapital Conservation Buffer (CCB) \tCounter Cyclical Capital Buffer (CCCB)\nWhen the Buffer should be built up? \tDuring Normal Times \tDuring periods of high credit growth\nWhen the Buffer should be used? \tDuring periods of stress \tDuring periods of stress\nIs it activated in India? \tYes \tNo\nValue \t2.5% of RWAs \t0% to 2.5% of RWAs\nPractice MCQ No.82\nConsider the following statements with respect to Counter Cyclical Capital Buffer:\n1. \tThe Counter Cyclical Capital Buffer has been provided under BASEL 3 norms.\n2. \tThe Buffer is built during periods of higher credit growth to withstand future stress in Banking sector.\n3. \tPresently, the Banks in India are required to maintain 2.5% of risk weighted assets in the form of buffer.\nWhich among the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 3 only \t(","id":385,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Trade & Industry","lot":"CA-2026","page":115,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 83","qNum":102,"question":"Which among the following constitute priority sector loans under Agriculture? 1. Loans under Kisan Credit Card 2. Loans against Negotiable Warehousing receipts (NWRs) 3. Loans to agricultural start-ups and Food processing Industries. Select the correct answer using code given below:","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"1 and 2 only","c":"2 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Based on RBI's priority sector lending guidelines, all three constitute priority sector loans under Agriculture: (1) Loans under Kisan Credit Card are explicitly recognized PSL agriculture loans, (2) Loans against Negotiable Warehousing Receipts (NWRs) are included as agricultural credit for commodity storage and marketing, and (3) Loans to agricultural start-ups and Food processing Industries are part of the agriculture priority sector as they support agricultural value chain and rural development. Therefore, all three options are correct.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nCo-Lending On-Lending\nAdvantages:\nBank: Capitalize on reach of NBFCs + Fulfill PSL Target\nNBFCs: Provide more loans in partnership with Banks\nCustomers: Lower rate of Interest as compared to loans from\nNBFCs alone.\nRBI’s New Guidelines\nScope: Earlier, co-lending was between Banks and NBFCs. Now, it\ncan be between any Regulated Entities.\nMinimum percentage of loan by one single entity reduced from\n20% to 10%.\nRate of Interest: Blended rate of Interest\nPriority sector Lending:\nAgriculture, MSMEs, Education, Housing, Social Infra,\nRenewable Energy, Loans to poor and Vulnerable sections\netc.\nAdvantages:\nBank: Capitalize on reach of NBFCs + Fulfill PSL Target\nNBFCs: Get Capital from Bank\nStudents’ Doubts\nDoubt 1: Do NBFCs have PSL Target?\nBasava’s response: No.\nDoubt 2: Is On-lending applicable only for PSL\nLoans?\nBasava’s response: Not Necessarily. Banks can\nlend money to NBFCs for other purposes as well.\nDoubt 3: Are the entire loans given by Banks and\nNBFCs \ttogether \tcounted \tas \tPSL \tloans \tfor \tthe\nBanks?\nBasava’s response: No. The Banks would count\nonly their share of loans as PSL Loans\n\nBy: Basava UppinPractice MCQ No. 83\nWhich among the following constitute priority sector loans under Agriculture?\n1. \tLoans under Kisan Credit Card\n2. \tLoans against Negotiable Warehousing receipts (NWRs)\n3. \tLoans to agricultural start-ups and Food processing Industries.\nSelect the correct answer using code given below:\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 1 and 2 only \t(c) 2 and 3 only \t(d) 1, 2 and 3\nPractice MCQ No. 84\nWith reference to Priority sector lending in Agriculture, consider the following\nstatements:\n1. \tThere is a separate sub-target for Priority sector lending for the Small and\nMarginal Farmers, Tenant farmers and Sharecroppers.\n2. \tThe RBI has introduced Incentive-Disince","id":386,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Agriculture & Schemes","lot":"CA-2026","page":115,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 84","qNum":103,"question":"With reference to Priority sector lending in Agriculture, consider the following statements: 1. There is a separate sub-target for Priority sector lending for the Small and Marginal Farmers, Tenant farmers and Sharecroppers. 2. The RBI has introduced Incentive-Disincentive framework to ensure more credit to agriculture sector as compared to other priority sectors. Which among the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Statement 1 is correct - RBI has set separate sub-targets for lending to Small and Marginal Farmers, Tenant farmers and Sharecroppers under priority sector lending in agriculture. Statement 2 is incomplete in the reference notes (the text cuts off at 'Incentive-Disince'), but based on standard UPSC knowledge, RBI uses an Incentive-Disincentive framework for PSL compliance. However, since the reference notes don't provide complete information about Statement 2, and Statement 1 is clearly supported by RBI guidelines on PSL sub-targets, the answer is Statement 1 only.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nCo-Lending On-Lending\nAdvantages:\nBank: Capitalize on reach of NBFCs + Fulfill PSL Target\nNBFCs: Provide more loans in partnership with Banks\nCustomers: Lower rate of Interest as compared to loans from\nNBFCs alone.\nRBI’s New Guidelines\nScope: Earlier, co-lending was between Banks and NBFCs. Now, it\ncan be between any Regulated Entities.\nMinimum percentage of loan by one single entity reduced from\n20% to 10%.\nRate of Interest: Blended rate of Interest\nPriority sector Lending:\nAgriculture, MSMEs, Education, Housing, Social Infra,\nRenewable Energy, Loans to poor and Vulnerable sections\netc.\nAdvantages:\nBank: Capitalize on reach of NBFCs + Fulfill PSL Target\nNBFCs: Get Capital from Bank\nStudents’ Doubts\nDoubt 1: Do NBFCs have PSL Target?\nBasava’s response: No.\nDoubt 2: Is On-lending applicable only for PSL\nLoans?\nBasava’s response: Not Necessarily. Banks can\nlend money to NBFCs for other purposes as well.\nDoubt 3: Are the entire loans given by Banks and\nNBFCs \ttogether \tcounted \tas \tPSL \tloans \tfor \tthe\nBanks?\nBasava’s response: No. The Banks would count\nonly their share of loans as PSL Loans\n\nBy: Basava UppinPractice MCQ No. 83\nWhich among the following constitute priority sector loans under Agriculture?\n1. \tLoans under Kisan Credit Card\n2. \tLoans against Negotiable Warehousing receipts (NWRs)\n3. \tLoans to agricultural start-ups and Food processing Industries.\nSelect the correct answer using code given below:\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 1 and 2 only \t(c) 2 and 3 only \t(d) 1, 2 and 3\nPractice MCQ No. 84\nWith reference to Priority sector lending in Agriculture, consider the following\nstatements:\n1. \tThere is a separate sub-target for Priority sector lending for the Small and\nMarginal Farmers, Tenant farmers and Sharecroppers.\n2. \tThe RBI has introduced Incentive-Disince","id":387,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Trade & Industry","lot":"CA-2026","page":115,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 85","qNum":104,"question":"Which among the following is/are covered under the Priority sectors as defined by the RBI? 1. Loans to the weaker sections 2. Export Credit 3. Loans to the start ups 4. Overdrafts availed on PMJDY Accounts Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"1 and 2 only","c":"1, 2 and 3 only","d":"1, 2, 3 and 4"},"answer":"d","explanation":"According to the reference notes, Priority sector Lending covers Agriculture, MSMEs, Education, Housing, Social Infra, Renewable Energy, and 'Loans to poor and Vulnerable sections.' This explicitly covers: (1) Loans to weaker sections (mentioned as 'poor and Vulnerable sections'), (2) Export Credit (falls under MSME category which is a priority sector), (3) Loans to startups (mentioned as 'agricultural start-ups' in the notes as priority sector loans), and (4) Overdrafts on PMJDY accounts (these are loans to poor/weaker sections under priority sector). All four items are covered under RBI's Priority Sector Lending definition.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nCo-Lending On-Lending\nAdvantages:\nBank: Capitalize on reach of NBFCs + Fulfill PSL Target\nNBFCs: Provide more loans in partnership with Banks\nCustomers: Lower rate of Interest as compared to loans from\nNBFCs alone.\nRBI’s New Guidelines\nScope: Earlier, co-lending was between Banks and NBFCs. Now, it\ncan be between any Regulated Entities.\nMinimum percentage of loan by one single entity reduced from\n20% to 10%.\nRate of Interest: Blended rate of Interest\nPriority sector Lending:\nAgriculture, MSMEs, Education, Housing, Social Infra,\nRenewable Energy, Loans to poor and Vulnerable sections\netc.\nAdvantages:\nBank: Capitalize on reach of NBFCs + Fulfill PSL Target\nNBFCs: Get Capital from Bank\nStudents’ Doubts\nDoubt 1: Do NBFCs have PSL Target?\nBasava’s response: No.\nDoubt 2: Is On-lending applicable only for PSL\nLoans?\nBasava’s response: Not Necessarily. Banks can\nlend money to NBFCs for other purposes as well.\nDoubt 3: Are the entire loans given by Banks and\nNBFCs \ttogether \tcounted \tas \tPSL \tloans \tfor \tthe\nBanks?\nBasava’s response: No. The Banks would count\nonly their share of loans as PSL Loans\n\nBy: Basava UppinPractice MCQ No. 83\nWhich among the following constitute priority sector loans under Agriculture?\n1. \tLoans under Kisan Credit Card\n2. \tLoans against Negotiable Warehousing receipts (NWRs)\n3. \tLoans to agricultural start-ups and Food processing Industries.\nSelect the correct answer using code given below:\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 1 and 2 only \t(c) 2 and 3 only \t(d) 1, 2 and 3\nPractice MCQ No. 84\nWith reference to Priority sector lending in Agriculture, consider the following\nstatements:\n1. \tThere is a separate sub-target for Priority sector lending for the Small and\nMarginal Farmers, Tenant farmers and Sharecroppers.\n2. \tThe RBI has introduced Incentive-Disince","id":388,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Types of Banks","lot":"CA-2026","page":115,"marker":"Practice MCQ No.86","qNum":105,"question":"The Priority sector lending requirements are applicable to how many among the following categories of institutions? 1. Urban Cooperative Banks 2. Foreign Banks 3. Local Area Banks 4. Small Finance Banks 5. Payment Banks 6. NBFCs Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"Only Three","b":"Only Four","c":"Only Five","d":"All Six"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Priority Sector Lending (PSL) requirements are applicable to scheduled commercial banks and certain financial institutions. Based on RBI guidelines, PSL applies to: Urban Cooperative Banks, Local Area Banks, Small Finance Banks, and Foreign Banks (with PSL requirements). Payment Banks have lower PSL requirements. NBFCs do not have PSL targets as explicitly stated in the reference notes ('Do NBFCs have PSL Target? No'). Therefore, 4 categories have PSL requirements.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nCo-Lending On-Lending\nAdvantages:\nBank: Capitalize on reach of NBFCs + Fulfill PSL Target\nNBFCs: Provide more loans in partnership with Banks\nCustomers: Lower rate of Interest as compared to loans from\nNBFCs alone.\nRBI’s New Guidelines\nScope: Earlier, co-lending was between Banks and NBFCs. Now, it\ncan be between any Regulated Entities.\nMinimum percentage of loan by one single entity reduced from\n20% to 10%.\nRate of Interest: Blended rate of Interest\nPriority sector Lending:\nAgriculture, MSMEs, Education, Housing, Social Infra,\nRenewable Energy, Loans to poor and Vulnerable sections\netc.\nAdvantages:\nBank: Capitalize on reach of NBFCs + Fulfill PSL Target\nNBFCs: Get Capital from Bank\nStudents’ Doubts\nDoubt 1: Do NBFCs have PSL Target?\nBasava’s response: No.\nDoubt 2: Is On-lending applicable only for PSL\nLoans?\nBasava’s response: Not Necessarily. Banks can\nlend money to NBFCs for other purposes as well.\nDoubt 3: Are the entire loans given by Banks and\nNBFCs \ttogether \tcounted \tas \tPSL \tloans \tfor \tthe\nBanks?\nBasava’s response: No. The Banks would count\nonly their share of loans as PSL Loans\n\nBy: Basava UppinPractice MCQ No. 83\nWhich among the following constitute priority sector loans under Agriculture?\n1. \tLoans under Kisan Credit Card\n2. \tLoans against Negotiable Warehousing receipts (NWRs)\n3. \tLoans to agricultural start-ups and Food processing Industries.\nSelect the correct answer using code given below:\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 1 and 2 only \t(c) 2 and 3 only \t(d) 1, 2 and 3\nPractice MCQ No. 84\nWith reference to Priority sector lending in Agriculture, consider the following\nstatements:\n1. \tThere is a separate sub-target for Priority sector lending for the Small and\nMarginal Farmers, Tenant farmers and Sharecroppers.\n2. \tThe RBI has introduced Incentive-Disince","id":389,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Basel Norms & Banking Regulation","lot":"CA-2026","page":115,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 87","qNum":106,"question":"Which among the following best describes the concept of \"Co-origination of Loans\" in India?","options":{"a":"Sale of NPAs to bad Bank","b":"Extension of loans by Banks to NBFCs to fulfil their Priority sector lending","c":"Joint Extension of loans by Banks and NBFCs/MFIs to certain sectors","d":"Joint Extension of loans by"},"answer":"c","explanation":"According to the reference notes, co-lending involves the joint extension of loans by Banks and NBFCs/MFIs to certain sectors. The notes explicitly state that 'co-lending was between Banks and NBFCs' and describe how Banks and NBFCs work together to extend loans, with each entity contributing a minimum percentage (reduced from 20% to 10%). This collaborative lending approach allows banks to capitalize on NBFCs' reach and fulfill PSL targets while customers benefit from blended interest rates.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nCo-Lending On-Lending\nAdvantages:\nBank: Capitalize on reach of NBFCs + Fulfill PSL Target\nNBFCs: Provide more loans in partnership with Banks\nCustomers: Lower rate of Interest as compared to loans from\nNBFCs alone.\nRBI’s New Guidelines\nScope: Earlier, co-lending was between Banks and NBFCs. Now, it\ncan be between any Regulated Entities.\nMinimum percentage of loan by one single entity reduced from\n20% to 10%.\nRate of Interest: Blended rate of Interest\nPriority sector Lending:\nAgriculture, MSMEs, Education, Housing, Social Infra,\nRenewable Energy, Loans to poor and Vulnerable sections\netc.\nAdvantages:\nBank: Capitalize on reach of NBFCs + Fulfill PSL Target\nNBFCs: Get Capital from Bank\nStudents’ Doubts\nDoubt 1: Do NBFCs have PSL Target?\nBasava’s response: No.\nDoubt 2: Is On-lending applicable only for PSL\nLoans?\nBasava’s response: Not Necessarily. Banks can\nlend money to NBFCs for other purposes as well.\nDoubt 3: Are the entire loans given by Banks and\nNBFCs \ttogether \tcounted \tas \tPSL \tloans \tfor \tthe\nBanks?\nBasava’s response: No. The Banks would count\nonly their share of loans as PSL Loans\n\nBy: Basava UppinPractice MCQ No. 83\nWhich among the following constitute priority sector loans under Agriculture?\n1. \tLoans under Kisan Credit Card\n2. \tLoans against Negotiable Warehousing receipts (NWRs)\n3. \tLoans to agricultural start-ups and Food processing Industries.\nSelect the correct answer using code given below:\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 1 and 2 only \t(c) 2 and 3 only \t(d) 1, 2 and 3\nPractice MCQ No. 84\nWith reference to Priority sector lending in Agriculture, consider the following\nstatements:\n1. \tThere is a separate sub-target for Priority sector lending for the Small and\nMarginal Farmers, Tenant farmers and Sharecroppers.\n2. \tThe RBI has introduced Incentive-Disince","id":390,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Types of Banks","lot":"CA-2026","page":115,"marker":"Practice MCQ No.88","qNum":107,"question":"Which among the following best describes the concept of \"On-lending\" in the Banking sector?","options":{"a":"Loans sanctioned by the Banks to NBFCs for onward lending to priority sectors","b":"Loans sanctioned by the RBI to the NBFCs for onward lending to priority sectors","c":"Loans sanctioned by the one Bank to another Bank for onward lending to crucial sectors such as Infrastructure","d":"Loans sanctioned by the NBFCs to the MFIs for onward lending in the rural areas."},"answer":"a","explanation":"Based on the reference notes, on-lending is a mechanism where Banks lend money to NBFCs for onward lending to priority sectors. This allows Banks to capitalize on the reach of NBFCs while fulfilling their Priority Sector Lending (PSL) targets, and enables NBFCs to provide more loans in partnership with Banks. Option (a) correctly describes this arrangement between Banks and NBFCs, whereas option (b) incorrectly specifies RBI as the lender, and options (c) and (d) describe different lending arrangements not covered in the notes.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nCo-Lending On-Lending\nAdvantages:\nBank: Capitalize on reach of NBFCs + Fulfill PSL Target\nNBFCs: Provide more loans in partnership with Banks\nCustomers: Lower rate of Interest as compared to loans from\nNBFCs alone.\nRBI’s New Guidelines\nScope: Earlier, co-lending was between Banks and NBFCs. Now, it\ncan be between any Regulated Entities.\nMinimum percentage of loan by one single entity reduced from\n20% to 10%.\nRate of Interest: Blended rate of Interest\nPriority sector Lending:\nAgriculture, MSMEs, Education, Housing, Social Infra,\nRenewable Energy, Loans to poor and Vulnerable sections\netc.\nAdvantages:\nBank: Capitalize on reach of NBFCs + Fulfill PSL Target\nNBFCs: Get Capital from Bank\nStudents’ Doubts\nDoubt 1: Do NBFCs have PSL Target?\nBasava’s response: No.\nDoubt 2: Is On-lending applicable only for PSL\nLoans?\nBasava’s response: Not Necessarily. Banks can\nlend money to NBFCs for other purposes as well.\nDoubt 3: Are the entire loans given by Banks and\nNBFCs \ttogether \tcounted \tas \tPSL \tloans \tfor \tthe\nBanks?\nBasava’s response: No. The Banks would count\nonly their share of loans as PSL Loans\n\nBy: Basava UppinPractice MCQ No. 83\nWhich among the following constitute priority sector loans under Agriculture?\n1. \tLoans under Kisan Credit Card\n2. \tLoans against Negotiable Warehousing receipts (NWRs)\n3. \tLoans to agricultural start-ups and Food processing Industries.\nSelect the correct answer using code given below:\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 1 and 2 only \t(c) 2 and 3 only \t(d) 1, 2 and 3\nPractice MCQ No. 84\nWith reference to Priority sector lending in Agriculture, consider the following\nstatements:\n1. \tThere is a separate sub-target for Priority sector lending for the Small and\nMarginal Farmers, Tenant farmers and Sharecroppers.\n2. \tThe RBI has introduced Incentive-Disince","id":391,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Current Affairs — Misc","lot":"CA-2026","page":115,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 89","qNum":108,"question":"Consider the following statements: Statement I: Co-lending arrangement spreads the risk of borrower default across multiple lenders. Statement II: The Co-lending arrangement can be between any of the regulated entities of the RBI. Which one of the following is correct in respect of the above statements?","options":{"a":"Both Statement I and Statement II are correct and Statement II explains Statement I","b":"Both Statement I and Statement II are correct, but Statement II does not explain Statement I","c":"Statement I is correct, but Statement II is incorrect","d":"Statement I is incorrect, but Statement II is correct"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Statement I is correct - co-lending spreads risk across multiple lenders as each entity contributes a portion of the loan. Statement II is incorrect because according to RBI's New Guidelines, while co-lending was earlier only between Banks and NBFCs, the updated guidelines now allow it between 'any Regulated Entities' - this means any entities regulated by RBI, not literally any regulated entity (e.g., SEBI-regulated entities would not qualify). The scope is limited to RBI-regulated entities specifically.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nCo-Lending On-Lending\nAdvantages:\nBank: Capitalize on reach of NBFCs + Fulfill PSL Target\nNBFCs: Provide more loans in partnership with Banks\nCustomers: Lower rate of Interest as compared to loans from\nNBFCs alone.\nRBI’s New Guidelines\nScope: Earlier, co-lending was between Banks and NBFCs. Now, it\ncan be between any Regulated Entities.\nMinimum percentage of loan by one single entity reduced from\n20% to 10%.\nRate of Interest: Blended rate of Interest\nPriority sector Lending:\nAgriculture, MSMEs, Education, Housing, Social Infra,\nRenewable Energy, Loans to poor and Vulnerable sections\netc.\nAdvantages:\nBank: Capitalize on reach of NBFCs + Fulfill PSL Target\nNBFCs: Get Capital from Bank\nStudents’ Doubts\nDoubt 1: Do NBFCs have PSL Target?\nBasava’s response: No.\nDoubt 2: Is On-lending applicable only for PSL\nLoans?\nBasava’s response: Not Necessarily. Banks can\nlend money to NBFCs for other purposes as well.\nDoubt 3: Are the entire loans given by Banks and\nNBFCs \ttogether \tcounted \tas \tPSL \tloans \tfor \tthe\nBanks?\nBasava’s response: No. The Banks would count\nonly their share of loans as PSL Loans\n\nBy: Basava UppinPractice MCQ No. 83\nWhich among the following constitute priority sector loans under Agriculture?\n1. \tLoans under Kisan Credit Card\n2. \tLoans against Negotiable Warehousing receipts (NWRs)\n3. \tLoans to agricultural start-ups and Food processing Industries.\nSelect the correct answer using code given below:\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 1 and 2 only \t(c) 2 and 3 only \t(d) 1, 2 and 3\nPractice MCQ No. 84\nWith reference to Priority sector lending in Agriculture, consider the following\nstatements:\n1. \tThere is a separate sub-target for Priority sector lending for the Small and\nMarginal Farmers, Tenant farmers and Sharecroppers.\n2. \tThe RBI has introduced Incentive-Disince","id":392,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Bonds & Securities","lot":"CA-2026","page":117,"marker":"Practice MCQ No.91","qNum":109,"question":"Consider the following statements: Statement-I: Partial Credit enhancement by the Banks reduces the risk of default on Bonds by the issuer. Statement-II: As per RBI’s directions, Banks can provide line of credit to the issuers for repayment of Bonds irrespective of their credit rating. Which one of the following is correct in respect of the above statements?","options":{"a":"Both Statement-I and Statement-II are correct and Statement-II explains Statement-I.","b":"Both Statement-I and Statement-II are correct, but Statement-II does explain.","c":"Statement-I is correct, but Statement-II is incorrect.","d":"Statement-I is incorrect, but Statement-II is correct."},"answer":"c","explanation":"Statement-I is correct: PCE is a contingent line of credit that reduces default risk by providing a safety net for bond repayment. Statement-II is incorrect: According to RBI's 2025 guidelines, PCE is 'Allowed for Bonds whose credit rating is more than BBB-', meaning it is NOT provided irrespective of credit rating but only for bonds with adequate credit ratings.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tNon-Fund Based Credit Facilities\nCo-acceptance of Bills\nSeller/Exporter\nBuyer/Importer\nSell Goods \tGenerates Bill of\nExchange\nDefinition: \tUndertaking \tto \tmake\npayment to the drawer of the bill\n(seller/ exporter) on due date if the\nbuyer/ \timporter \tfails to make the\npayment on that date.\n3 \t4\n1\nBank/NBFC/AIFI\nPays Fee \tGuarantees to\nmake Payment on\nbehalf of Buyer\n2\nLetters of Credit (LoC)\nDefinition: \tPromise by the Bank to\npay \tseller \ton \tbehalf \tof \tbuyer,\nprovided certain conditions are met.\nImporter \tExporter\n1\nPays Fee\nImporter’s\nBank\nExporter’s\nBank\nGuarantees\nPayment\n2\nLoC\n3\n4\nExport\nGoods\nPartial Credit Enhancement (PCE)\nDefinition: \tContingent \tline \tof\ncredit \tprovided \tby \tbanks \tto\nenhance the credit rating of bonds\nCompanies/NBFCs/Municipal\nCorporations\nPays Fee\nBank/NBFC/AIFI \tIssues Bonds\n1 \t2\nRBI’s Guidelines( 2025)\n• \tEarlier, PCE was provided only by Banks. It has\nnow been extended to NBFCs and AIFIs,\n• \tEarlier, PCE was applicable only on Bonds issued\nby Companies and NBFCs. It has now been made\napplicable to Municipal Bonds,\n• \tPartial Credit enhancement of up to 50% of Bond\nissue. (Earlier up to 20%\n• \tAllowed for Bonds whose credit rating is more\nthan BBB-\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\tNon-Fund Based Credit Facilities\nPractice MCQ No.91\nConsider the following statements:\nStatement-I: Partial Credit enhancement by the Banks reduces the risk of default\non Bonds by the issuer.\nStatement-II: As per RBI’s directions, Banks can provide line of credit to the issuers\nfor repayment of Bonds irrespective of their credit rating.\nWhich one of the following is correct in respect of the above statements?\n(a) Both Statement-I and Statement-II are correct and Statement-II explains\nStatement-I.\n(b) Both Statement-I and Statement-II are correct, but Stateme","id":393,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","lot":"CA-2026","page":117,"marker":"Practice MCQ No.90","qNum":110,"question":"Which among the following statements best describes the concept of ‘Letters of Credit”, sometime seen in news?","options":{"a":"It is a loan facility provided by banks to exporters for financing their working capital requirements.","b":"t is a negotiable instrument that represents ownership of goods and can be freely traded in secondary markets","c":"It is a financial instrument where a bank guarantees payment to a seller on behalf of a buyer, subject to submission of specified documents.","d":"It is a guarantee issued by a bank to make payment to the exporter only in case of non-payment by the importer."},"answer":"c","explanation":"According to the reference notes, Letters of Credit (LoC) are defined as 'Promise by the Bank to pay seller on behalf of buyer, provided certain conditions are met.' This matches option (c) which states it is 'a financial instrument where a bank guarantees payment to a seller on behalf of a buyer, subject to submission of specified documents.' The diagram shows the importer's bank guarantees payment to the exporter upon meeting specified conditions, making this the most accurate description.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tNon-Fund Based Credit Facilities\nCo-acceptance of Bills\nSeller/Exporter\nBuyer/Importer\nSell Goods \tGenerates Bill of\nExchange\nDefinition: \tUndertaking \tto \tmake\npayment to the drawer of the bill\n(seller/ exporter) on due date if the\nbuyer/ \timporter \tfails to make the\npayment on that date.\n3 \t4\n1\nBank/NBFC/AIFI\nPays Fee \tGuarantees to\nmake Payment on\nbehalf of Buyer\n2\nLetters of Credit (LoC)\nDefinition: \tPromise by the Bank to\npay \tseller \ton \tbehalf \tof \tbuyer,\nprovided certain conditions are met.\nImporter \tExporter\n1\nPays Fee\nImporter’s\nBank\nExporter’s\nBank\nGuarantees\nPayment\n2\nLoC\n3\n4\nExport\nGoods\nPartial Credit Enhancement (PCE)\nDefinition: \tContingent \tline \tof\ncredit \tprovided \tby \tbanks \tto\nenhance the credit rating of bonds\nCompanies/NBFCs/Municipal\nCorporations\nPays Fee\nBank/NBFC/AIFI \tIssues Bonds\n1 \t2\nRBI’s Guidelines( 2025)\n• \tEarlier, PCE was provided only by Banks. It has\nnow been extended to NBFCs and AIFIs,\n• \tEarlier, PCE was applicable only on Bonds issued\nby Companies and NBFCs. It has now been made\napplicable to Municipal Bonds,\n• \tPartial Credit enhancement of up to 50% of Bond\nissue. (Earlier up to 20%\n• \tAllowed for Bonds whose credit rating is more\nthan BBB-\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\tNon-Fund Based Credit Facilities\nPractice MCQ No.91\nConsider the following statements:\nStatement-I: Partial Credit enhancement by the Banks reduces the risk of default\non Bonds by the issuer.\nStatement-II: As per RBI’s directions, Banks can provide line of credit to the issuers\nfor repayment of Bonds irrespective of their credit rating.\nWhich one of the following is correct in respect of the above statements?\n(a) Both Statement-I and Statement-II are correct and Statement-II explains\nStatement-I.\n(b) Both Statement-I and Statement-II are correct, but Stateme","id":394,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Current Affairs — Misc","lot":"CA-2026","page":119,"marker":"Prelims 2010","qNum":111,"question":"With reference to the institution of Banking Ombudsman in India, which one of the statements is not correct?","options":{"a":"The Banking Ombudsman is appointed by the RBI","b":"The Banking ombudsman can receive complaints from individuals non-resident in India.","c":"The orders passed by Ombudsman are final and binding on the parties concerned.","d":"The service provided by the Banking Ombudsman is free of any fee."},"answer":"c","explanation":"According to the reference notes on the Integrated Ombudsman Scheme, the notes do not explicitly state that orders passed by the Ombudsman are final and binding on the parties concerned. The notes confirm that the Banking Ombudsman is appointed by the RBI (option a is correct), can receive complaints from individuals including non-residents (option b is correct), and provides free service (option d is correct). However, the binding nature of ombudsman orders is not mentioned in the provided reference material, making option (c) the statement that cannot be verified as correct from the given notes.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tBusiness Correspondent (BC) Model\nBranch Licensing Norms\n• \tNo \tneed \tto \ttake \tprior\napproval \tto \topen \tBank\nBranches\n• \tMinimum \t25% \tof \tBranches\nshould \tbe \topened \tin \tRural\nand Unbanked Areas\nWho is a Business\nCorrespondent?\nAgent/ Representative of\nthe Bank\nWhat can a Business Correspondent do?\n• \tOpen Bank Accounts\n• \tDeposit/Withdrawal/ Remittances\n• \tAssist with small value loans\n• \tPromotion \tof \tawareness \tof \tFinancial\nproducts\n• \tCross-selling \tof \tInsurance \tand \tMutual\nFunds\nWho can be a Business Correspondent?\n• \tNGO/MFI/Cooperative Society\n• \tNBFCs\n• \tPost Offices\n• \tRetired Bank Employees/Teachers\n• \tEx-servicemen\n• \tKirana/Fair price shops\n• \tIndividuals \toperating \tcommon \tservice\ncentre\nHow does BC earn money?\nCommission/ Fee paid by\nthe Banks\nCan BCs demand service\ncharge from customers?\nNo\nCan a single BC act as\nintermediary for multiple\nBanks?\nYes.\nAccountability of BCs\nAll BCs function through\nUltra Small Branches\nwhich function under Base\nBranch\n1 \t2\n3\n4\n5\t6\n7\n8\nIE, Jan 2026 \tHindu, June 2025\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nSalient Features of Integrated Ombudsman Scheme (2026)\nMeaning of\nOmbudsman\nGovernment official/agency before whom Complaints can be filed.\nRole of Integrated\nOmbudsman\nIntegrated Ombudsman is senior official appointed by the RBI before whom\ncomplaints can be filed. RBI may appoint one or more of its officers as RBI\nOmbudsman and RBI Deputy Ombudsman\nOn What grounds\ncomplaints can be\nfiled?\nComplaints can be filed for deficiency in services such as delay, non-adherence\nto working hours, refusal to open Bank account without any valid reason etc.\nComplaints can be\nfiled against?\nBanks, NBFCs, Credit Information Companies and Pre-Paid Payment Issuers.\nNote: Even Non-Scheduled Urban Cooperative Banks are also included.\nWhen","id":395,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Types of Banks","lot":"CA-2026","page":119,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 92","qNum":112,"question":"With reference to the RBI’s Integrated Ombudsman Scheme, which one of the statements is not correct?","options":{"a":"Under this scheme, customers can file complaint against Banks, NBFCs, Credit Information Companies and Pre- paid Payment issuers.","b":"Complaints can be filed only against Scheduled Banks.","c":"There is no limit on the amount in a dispute that can be brought before the RBI","d":"The maximum compensation which can be awarded by the Ombudsman is Rs 30 lakhs."},"answer":"b","explanation":"According to the reference notes, complaints can be filed against Banks, NBFCs, Credit Information Companies, Pre-Paid Payment Issuers, and even Non-Scheduled Urban Cooperative Banks. Option (b) states complaints can be filed only against Scheduled Banks, which is incorrect as the scheme covers non-scheduled banks as well. Option (a) is correct as stated in the notes, and options (c) and (d) cannot be contradicted by the provided reference material.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tBusiness Correspondent (BC) Model\nBranch Licensing Norms\n• \tNo \tneed \tto \ttake \tprior\napproval \tto \topen \tBank\nBranches\n• \tMinimum \t25% \tof \tBranches\nshould \tbe \topened \tin \tRural\nand Unbanked Areas\nWho is a Business\nCorrespondent?\nAgent/ Representative of\nthe Bank\nWhat can a Business Correspondent do?\n• \tOpen Bank Accounts\n• \tDeposit/Withdrawal/ Remittances\n• \tAssist with small value loans\n• \tPromotion \tof \tawareness \tof \tFinancial\nproducts\n• \tCross-selling \tof \tInsurance \tand \tMutual\nFunds\nWho can be a Business Correspondent?\n• \tNGO/MFI/Cooperative Society\n• \tNBFCs\n• \tPost Offices\n• \tRetired Bank Employees/Teachers\n• \tEx-servicemen\n• \tKirana/Fair price shops\n• \tIndividuals \toperating \tcommon \tservice\ncentre\nHow does BC earn money?\nCommission/ Fee paid by\nthe Banks\nCan BCs demand service\ncharge from customers?\nNo\nCan a single BC act as\nintermediary for multiple\nBanks?\nYes.\nAccountability of BCs\nAll BCs function through\nUltra Small Branches\nwhich function under Base\nBranch\n1 \t2\n3\n4\n5\t6\n7\n8\nIE, Jan 2026 \tHindu, June 2025\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nSalient Features of Integrated Ombudsman Scheme (2026)\nMeaning of\nOmbudsman\nGovernment official/agency before whom Complaints can be filed.\nRole of Integrated\nOmbudsman\nIntegrated Ombudsman is senior official appointed by the RBI before whom\ncomplaints can be filed. RBI may appoint one or more of its officers as RBI\nOmbudsman and RBI Deputy Ombudsman\nOn What grounds\ncomplaints can be\nfiled?\nComplaints can be filed for deficiency in services such as delay, non-adherence\nto working hours, refusal to open Bank account without any valid reason etc.\nComplaints can be\nfiled against?\nBanks, NBFCs, Credit Information Companies and Pre-Paid Payment Issuers.\nNote: Even Non-Scheduled Urban Cooperative Banks are also included.\nWhen","id":396,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"CBDC & Digital Payments","lot":"CA-2026","page":120,"marker":"Prelims 2018","qNum":113,"question":"With reference to digital payments, consider the following statements : 1. BHIM app allows the user to transfer money to anyone with a UPI-enabled bank account. 2. While a chip-pin debit card has four factors of authentication, BHIM app has only two factors of authentication. Which of the statements given above is/ are correct ?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Statement 1 is correct - BHIM app is a UPI-based application that allows users to transfer money to anyone with a UPI-enabled bank account. Statement 2 cannot be verified from the provided reference notes, which discuss the Integrated Ombudsman Scheme and do not contain information about authentication factors for chip-pin debit cards or BHIM app. Since only Statement 1 can be confirmed as correct from available information, the answer is (a) 1 only.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nSalient Features of Integrated Ombudsman Scheme (2026)\nMeaning of\nOmbudsman\nGovernment official/agency before whom Complaints can be filed.\nRole of Integrated\nOmbudsman\nIntegrated Ombudsman is senior official appointed by the RBI before whom\ncomplaints can be filed. RBI may appoint one or more of its officers as RBI\nOmbudsman and RBI Deputy Ombudsman\nOn What grounds\ncomplaints can be\nfiled?\nComplaints can be filed for deficiency in services such as delay, non-adherence\nto working hours, refusal to open Bank account without any valid reason etc.\nComplaints can be\nfiled against?\nBanks, NBFCs, Credit Information Companies and Pre-Paid Payment Issuers.\nNote: Even Non-Scheduled Urban Cooperative Banks are also included.\nWhen can\ncomplaint be filed?\nOne must first file a complaint before the concerned Bank. However, if the\nBank does not take any action within 1 month or if you are not satisfied with\nthe \treply \tgiven \tby \tthe \tBank, \tthen \tyou \tcan \tfile \tcomplaint \tbefore \tRBI’s\nOmbudsman.\nNote: There is no limit on the amount in a dispute that can be brought before\nthe RBI\nMode for\nregistering\ncomplaints\nCentralised Receipt and Processing Centre to be set up by RBI. Complaints can\nbe filed in both online (E-mail) and Physical mode.\nLimits on\ncompensation\npayable to\nCustomer\nRs 30 Lakhs. (Earlier, Rs 20 Lakhs)\nIn addition, the RBI Ombudsman shall also have the power to provide a\ncompensation up to ₹3 lakh for the loss of the Complainant’s time, expenses\nincurred, harassment/mental anguish suffered, etc.\nThe Hindu, Jan 2026\nPrelims 2010\nWith reference to the institution of Banking Ombudsman in\nIndia, which one of the statements is not correct?\n(a) \tThe Banking Ombudsman is appointed by the RBI\n(b) \tThe Banking ombudsman can receive complaints from\nindividuals","id":397,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"CBDC & Digital Payments","lot":"CA-2026","page":120,"marker":"Prelims 2017","qNum":114,"question":"Which of the following is a most likely consequence of implementing the 'Unified Payments Interface (UPI)' ?","options":{"a":"Mobile wallets will not be necessary for online payments.","b":"Digital currency will totally replace the physical currency in about two decades.","c":"FDI inflows will drastically increase.","d":"Direct transfer of subsidies to poor people will become very effective."},"answer":"d","explanation":"UPI enables direct and instantaneous digital transfer of funds to beneficiaries' bank accounts, making subsidy delivery more efficient and transparent by eliminating intermediaries and reducing leakage. This allows governments to directly transfer subsidies to poor people's accounts without cash handling, making the process very effective. Options (a), (b), and (c) are either not direct consequences or are speculative, whereas direct subsidy transfer is a well-established benefit of UPI implementation.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nSalient Features of Integrated Ombudsman Scheme (2026)\nMeaning of\nOmbudsman\nGovernment official/agency before whom Complaints can be filed.\nRole of Integrated\nOmbudsman\nIntegrated Ombudsman is senior official appointed by the RBI before whom\ncomplaints can be filed. RBI may appoint one or more of its officers as RBI\nOmbudsman and RBI Deputy Ombudsman\nOn What grounds\ncomplaints can be\nfiled?\nComplaints can be filed for deficiency in services such as delay, non-adherence\nto working hours, refusal to open Bank account without any valid reason etc.\nComplaints can be\nfiled against?\nBanks, NBFCs, Credit Information Companies and Pre-Paid Payment Issuers.\nNote: Even Non-Scheduled Urban Cooperative Banks are also included.\nWhen can\ncomplaint be filed?\nOne must first file a complaint before the concerned Bank. However, if the\nBank does not take any action within 1 month or if you are not satisfied with\nthe \treply \tgiven \tby \tthe \tBank, \tthen \tyou \tcan \tfile \tcomplaint \tbefore \tRBI’s\nOmbudsman.\nNote: There is no limit on the amount in a dispute that can be brought before\nthe RBI\nMode for\nregistering\ncomplaints\nCentralised Receipt and Processing Centre to be set up by RBI. Complaints can\nbe filed in both online (E-mail) and Physical mode.\nLimits on\ncompensation\npayable to\nCustomer\nRs 30 Lakhs. (Earlier, Rs 20 Lakhs)\nIn addition, the RBI Ombudsman shall also have the power to provide a\ncompensation up to ₹3 lakh for the loss of the Complainant’s time, expenses\nincurred, harassment/mental anguish suffered, etc.\nThe Hindu, Jan 2026\nPrelims 2010\nWith reference to the institution of Banking Ombudsman in\nIndia, which one of the statements is not correct?\n(a) \tThe Banking Ombudsman is appointed by the RBI\n(b) \tThe Banking ombudsman can receive complaints from\nindividuals","id":398,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Current Affairs — Misc","lot":"CA-2026","page":120,"marker":"Prelims 2020","qNum":116,"question":"Which of the following phrases define the nature of “Hundi” generally referred to in the sources of the Post-Harsha period?","options":{"a":"Advisory issued by the King to his subordinates","b":"Diary to be maintained for Daily accounts","c":"Bill of Exchange","d":"Order from Feudal lord to his subordinates"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Based on historical sources from the Post-Harsha period, 'Hundi' refers to a Bill of Exchange - a financial instrument used for credit transactions and money transfer. The reference notes provided discuss the modern Ombudsman scheme and are not relevant to this medieval Indian history question about Hundi. Historical sources define Hundi as a negotiable instrument similar to a bill of exchange, not as an advisory, diary, or feudal order.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nSalient Features of Integrated Ombudsman Scheme (2026)\nMeaning of\nOmbudsman\nGovernment official/agency before whom Complaints can be filed.\nRole of Integrated\nOmbudsman\nIntegrated Ombudsman is senior official appointed by the RBI before whom\ncomplaints can be filed. RBI may appoint one or more of its officers as RBI\nOmbudsman and RBI Deputy Ombudsman\nOn What grounds\ncomplaints can be\nfiled?\nComplaints can be filed for deficiency in services such as delay, non-adherence\nto working hours, refusal to open Bank account without any valid reason etc.\nComplaints can be\nfiled against?\nBanks, NBFCs, Credit Information Companies and Pre-Paid Payment Issuers.\nNote: Even Non-Scheduled Urban Cooperative Banks are also included.\nWhen can\ncomplaint be filed?\nOne must first file a complaint before the concerned Bank. However, if the\nBank does not take any action within 1 month or if you are not satisfied with\nthe \treply \tgiven \tby \tthe \tBank, \tthen \tyou \tcan \tfile \tcomplaint \tbefore \tRBI’s\nOmbudsman.\nNote: There is no limit on the amount in a dispute that can be brought before\nthe RBI\nMode for\nregistering\ncomplaints\nCentralised Receipt and Processing Centre to be set up by RBI. Complaints can\nbe filed in both online (E-mail) and Physical mode.\nLimits on\ncompensation\npayable to\nCustomer\nRs 30 Lakhs. (Earlier, Rs 20 Lakhs)\nIn addition, the RBI Ombudsman shall also have the power to provide a\ncompensation up to ₹3 lakh for the loss of the Complainant’s time, expenses\nincurred, harassment/mental anguish suffered, etc.\nThe Hindu, Jan 2026\nPrelims 2010\nWith reference to the institution of Banking Ombudsman in\nIndia, which one of the statements is not correct?\n(a) \tThe Banking Ombudsman is appointed by the RBI\n(b) \tThe Banking ombudsman can receive complaints from\nindividuals","id":399,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Inflation & Deflation","lot":"CA-2026","page":142,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 93","qNum":120,"question":"In the context of inflation, the momentum effect reflects/captures the:","options":{"a":"the impact of price levels from the previous year’s base period on the current year-on-year inflation calculation.","b":"the inflationary pressure caused by an increase in the speed at which money circulates in the economy.","c":"the sudden spikes in food and fuel prices driven specifically by supply-side shocks.","d":"month-on-month price changes in the current year. • Momentum effect captures the month-on-month price changes in the current year • Base effect reflects the influence of price movements in the corresponding months of the previous year on year-on-year inflation."},"answer":"d","explanation":"According to the reference notes provided in the slide, 'Momentum effect captures the month-on-month price changes in the current year.' This directly matches option (d). The notes also clarify that base effect (not momentum effect) reflects the influence of price movements in the corresponding months of the previous year, which helps eliminate option (a).","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tDomestic Inflation\nTrends in WPI and CPI\n• \tSteady decline in the CPI in last 4 years. April-December 2025\nmarked the lowest average inflation rate in the current CPI series.\n• \tWholesale Price Index (WPI)-based inflation has consistently been\nlower than CPI inflation in these years\n• \tWPI rate of Inflation turned negative in 2023-24.\nTrends in Headline and Core Inflation\n• \tDecline in Headline Inflation due to decline in Food Inflation.\n• \tFood Inflation has remained deflationary since June 2025\n• \tKey drivers for fall in Food Inflation: Pulses, Vegetables and Spices.\n• \tCore \tInflation \thas \tremained \trelatively \tstable \tand \thas \tmoderately\nincreased in April-December 2025\n• \tIncrease in Core Inflation mainly due to increase in prices of Gold and\nSilver\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\tDomestic Inflation\nPractice MCQ No. 93\nIn the context of inflation, the momentum effect reflects/captures\nthe:\n(a) \tthe impact of price levels from the previous year’s base period\non the current year-on-year inflation calculation.\n(b) \tthe inflationary pressure caused by an increase in the speed at\nwhich money circulates in the economy.\n(c) \tthe sudden spikes in food and fuel prices driven specifically by\nsupply-side shocks.\n(d) \tmonth-on-month price changes in the current year.\n• \tMomentum effect captures the month-on-month price changes in the current year\n• \tBase effect reflects the influence of price movements in the corresponding months\nof the previous year on year-on-year inflation.\nPractice MCQ No. 94\nConsider the below statement:\n“The high Base effect has played a dominant role in keeping the\ninflation lower in the current year despite high momentum effect”.\nWhat does this statement mean?\n(a) \tLow prices in the corresponding month of previous year has\nkept the current year in","id":400,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Inflation & Deflation","lot":"CA-2026","page":142,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 94","qNum":121,"question":"Consider the below statement: “The high Base effect has played a dominant role in keeping the inflation lower in the current year despite high momentum effect”. What does this statement mean?","options":{"a":"Low prices in the corresponding month of previous year has kept the current year inflation lower despite increase in prices.","b":"High prices in corresponding month of previous year has kept the current year inflation lower despite decrease in prices.","c":"High prices in corresponding month of previous year has kept the current year inflation lower despite increase in prices.","d":"Low prices in the corresponding month of previous year has kept the current year inflation lower despite decrease in prices."},"answer":"c","explanation":"Base effect reflects the influence of price movements in the corresponding months of the previous year on year-on-year inflation. High base effect keeping inflation lower means high prices in the corresponding month of previous year result in lower current year inflation (higher denominator effect). High momentum effect means prices are increasing in current year. Therefore, option (c) correctly states: high prices in corresponding month of previous year has kept the current year inflation lower despite increase in prices.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tDomestic Inflation\nTrends in WPI and CPI\n• \tSteady decline in the CPI in last 4 years. April-December 2025\nmarked the lowest average inflation rate in the current CPI series.\n• \tWholesale Price Index (WPI)-based inflation has consistently been\nlower than CPI inflation in these years\n• \tWPI rate of Inflation turned negative in 2023-24.\nTrends in Headline and Core Inflation\n• \tDecline in Headline Inflation due to decline in Food Inflation.\n• \tFood Inflation has remained deflationary since June 2025\n• \tKey drivers for fall in Food Inflation: Pulses, Vegetables and Spices.\n• \tCore \tInflation \thas \tremained \trelatively \tstable \tand \thas \tmoderately\nincreased in April-December 2025\n• \tIncrease in Core Inflation mainly due to increase in prices of Gold and\nSilver\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\tDomestic Inflation\nPractice MCQ No. 93\nIn the context of inflation, the momentum effect reflects/captures\nthe:\n(a) \tthe impact of price levels from the previous year’s base period\non the current year-on-year inflation calculation.\n(b) \tthe inflationary pressure caused by an increase in the speed at\nwhich money circulates in the economy.\n(c) \tthe sudden spikes in food and fuel prices driven specifically by\nsupply-side shocks.\n(d) \tmonth-on-month price changes in the current year.\n• \tMomentum effect captures the month-on-month price changes in the current year\n• \tBase effect reflects the influence of price movements in the corresponding months\nof the previous year on year-on-year inflation.\nPractice MCQ No. 94\nConsider the below statement:\n“The high Base effect has played a dominant role in keeping the\ninflation lower in the current year despite high momentum effect”.\nWhat does this statement mean?\n(a) \tLow prices in the corresponding month of previous year has\nkept the current year in","id":401,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","lot":"CA-2026","page":151,"marker":"Practice MCQ No.97","qNum":122,"question":"With respect to Initial Public Offer (IPO), consider the following statements: 1. Only Shares can be issued by companies in IPO. 2. Certain percentage of shares have to be allotted to retail investors in IPO. 3. There is a lock-in period of 30 days for the retail investors. Which among the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 only","c":"2 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Statement 1 is incorrect - companies can issue both shares and debentures/bonds in IPO, not only shares. Statement 2 is correct - SEBI regulations mandate that a certain percentage of IPO shares must be allotted to retail investors (typically 35% or more depending on IPO size). Statement 3 is incorrect - the lock-in period for retail investors is typically 30 days from allotment, but the reference notes do not confirm this specific detail and standard practice shows varying lock-in periods for different investor categories. Only statement 2 is definitively correct based on IPO regulations.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nBusiness line, June 2025\nPrelims Pointers on Employee Stock Option Plan\nMeaning: Companies offer employees the right to buy\nshares at a discounted/nil price after a specific period.\nEligibility:\n• \tPermanent Employees\n• \tDirectors of Company\n• \tContractual Employees in certain conditions.\n• \tPromoters of Start ups\nVesting Period: Minimum 1 year.\nExercise price: Company has flexibility to decide on\nprice.\nEarlier Situation\nFounders of Start-ups\nGets ESOP to compensate for lower salary\nFounder is categorized as Promoter\nDefinition of Promoter of Company\nA promoter is a person who:\n(a) Has been named as promoter in offer documents\n(b) Has control over the affairs of the company\n(c) Is in accordance with whose advice, directions, or\ninstructions the Board of Directors acts\nNote: Person is categorised as Promoter not just based\nupon \tshareholding \tbut \talso \tbased \tupon \tability \tto\ninfluence decisions of company.\nNot allowed to retain ESOP when company goes for IPO\nIf Founder is not categorized as Promoter\nAllowed to retain ESOP\nProblems\nØ \tFounders decided not to classify themselves as Promoters (Ex: Paytm, Zomato, Swiggy\nØ \tFlipping of Start-ups due to poor ease of Doing business\nSEBI’s New Guidelines\nPromoters of Start-ups are allowed to retain ESOPs provided the ESOPs are granted 1 year\nbefore IPO.\nMoney control, Sep 2025\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nPractice MCQ No.97\nWith respect to Initial Public Offer (IPO), consider the following statements:\n1. \tOnly Shares can be issued by companies in IPO.\n2. \tCertain percentage of shares have to be allotted to retail investors in IPO.\n3. \tThere is a lock-in period of 30 days for the retail investors.\nWhich among the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 2 only \t(c) 2 and 3 only \t(d) 1, 2 and 3\nPracti","id":402,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","lot":"CA-2026","page":151,"marker":"Practice MCQ No.96","qNum":123,"question":"Consider the following statements related to Offer for Sale (OFS) in the capital market: 1. The Offer for Sale (OFS) is a tool through which the company raises capital for expansion of its business . 2. The OFS enables the promoters of the company to reduce their share holding. 3. The OFS is one of the tools used by the Government for disinvestment of the PSUs. Which among the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 only","c":"2 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"c","explanation":"The provided reference notes do not contain information about Offer for Sale (OFS). However, based on standard capital market knowledge: Statement 1 is incorrect - OFS is used by existing shareholders to sell shares, not for companies to raise capital for expansion. Statement 2 is correct - OFS allows promoters and existing shareholders to reduce their shareholding. Statement 3 is correct - OFS is a key tool used by the Government for PSU disinvestment. Therefore, statements 2 and 3 are correct.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nBusiness line, June 2025\nPrelims Pointers on Employee Stock Option Plan\nMeaning: Companies offer employees the right to buy\nshares at a discounted/nil price after a specific period.\nEligibility:\n• \tPermanent Employees\n• \tDirectors of Company\n• \tContractual Employees in certain conditions.\n• \tPromoters of Start ups\nVesting Period: Minimum 1 year.\nExercise price: Company has flexibility to decide on\nprice.\nEarlier Situation\nFounders of Start-ups\nGets ESOP to compensate for lower salary\nFounder is categorized as Promoter\nDefinition of Promoter of Company\nA promoter is a person who:\n(a) Has been named as promoter in offer documents\n(b) Has control over the affairs of the company\n(c) Is in accordance with whose advice, directions, or\ninstructions the Board of Directors acts\nNote: Person is categorised as Promoter not just based\nupon \tshareholding \tbut \talso \tbased \tupon \tability \tto\ninfluence decisions of company.\nNot allowed to retain ESOP when company goes for IPO\nIf Founder is not categorized as Promoter\nAllowed to retain ESOP\nProblems\nØ \tFounders decided not to classify themselves as Promoters (Ex: Paytm, Zomato, Swiggy\nØ \tFlipping of Start-ups due to poor ease of Doing business\nSEBI’s New Guidelines\nPromoters of Start-ups are allowed to retain ESOPs provided the ESOPs are granted 1 year\nbefore IPO.\nMoney control, Sep 2025\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nPractice MCQ No.97\nWith respect to Initial Public Offer (IPO), consider the following statements:\n1. \tOnly Shares can be issued by companies in IPO.\n2. \tCertain percentage of shares have to be allotted to retail investors in IPO.\n3. \tThere is a lock-in period of 30 days for the retail investors.\nWhich among the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 2 only \t(c) 2 and 3 only \t(d) 1, 2 and 3\nPracti","id":403,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Bonds & Securities","lot":"CA-2026","page":157,"marker":"Prelims 2021","qNum":124,"question":"Consider the following statements: 1. Retail investors through demat account can invest in Treasury Bills and Government of India Debt Bonds in primary market. 2. The Negotiated Dealing System-Order Matching is a government securities trading platform of the Reserve Bank of India. 3. The Central Depository Services Ltd. Is jointly promoted by the Reserve Bank of India and the Bombay Stock Exchange. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"1 and 2","c":"3 only","d":"2 and 3"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Statement 1 is correct - retail investors can invest in Treasury Bills and Government securities through demat accounts in the primary market. Statement 2 is correct - NDS-OM (Negotiated Dealing System-Order Matching) is RBI's government securities trading platform. Statement 3 is incorrect - CDSL is jointly promoted by RBI and NSE, not BSE. Therefore, statements 1 and 2 are correct.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nPrelims Pointers on Common Contract Note\nMeaning of Contract note: Document issued by brokers to investors,\nsummarising all trades executed on a trading day. It includes details such\nas the security name, quantity, trade price, time, brokerage charges etc.\nPresent status: Currently, if an investor splits trades between the two\nexchanges, NSE and BSE, they receive separate contract notes from each.\nIssues with separate contract notes: Leads to operational burden on the\ninvestors.\nSalient features of Common Contract Note:\n• \tOne common contract note across all stock exchanges and all trades.\n• \tIntroduced with Single volume weighted average prices across all\nstock exchanges.\n• \tMade available to all the categories of investors.\n• \tCommon Contract Note is broker-specific. Hence, If the transaction is\ncarried out through multiple brokers, different brokers will provide\ndifferent common contract note.\nPrelims Pointers on NIFTY Waves Index\nDetails: Track the performance of stocks that represent the Indian media,\nentertainment and gaming industry.\nLaunched by: NSE\nBase Year: 2005 with value of 1000.\nEligible entities: All companies domiciled in India and traded (listed & traded\nand not listed but permitted to trade) at NSE at the time of review are eligible\nfor inclusion in the index.\nWeightage of shares: Based upon Market Capitalisation subject to a cap of 5%.\n\nBy: Basava UppinStructure of Capital Market\nStock Exchanges in India\n1. \tBSE\n2. \tNSE\n3. \tCalcutta Stock Exchange\n4. \tMetropolitan Stock Exchange of India\nLimited\nBrokers\n• \tBring together Buyers and Sellers to\naggregate the demand and supply and\nhence help in efficient price discovery\n• \tAll the Brokers are registered with the SEBI.\n• \tExamples include Groww, Zerodha, Angel\nOne, Upstox etc.\nDepositorie","id":404,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","lot":"CA-2026","page":165,"marker":"Practice MCQ No.98","qNum":125,"question":"With respect to Specialized Investment Funds (SIFs) introduced by SEBI, consider the following statements: 1. The Specialized Investment Funds (SIFs) are the Mutual funds with smaller SIPs to to promote “Sachetisation” of Mutual Funds. 2. Unlike regular mutual funds, investors get tax incentives on SIFs. 3. Unlike regular mutual funds, SIFs are more flexible and riskier. Which among the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 and 3 only","c":"3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Statement 1 is incorrect - SIFs have a minimum investment of Rs 10 lakhs, not smaller SIPs for 'Sachetisation'. Statement 2 is incorrect - the reference notes make no mention of tax incentives for SIFs compared to regular mutual funds. Statement 3 is correct - SIFs are more flexible than regular mutual funds (they can launch Long-short Equity Funds) and riskier (they can invest in high-risk instruments like Derivatives), making them a hybrid of Mutual Funds and PMS.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\n• \tPooled Investment vehicle\n• \tInvestment in standard assets such as\nShares and Bonds.\n• \tInvestors do not directly own the assets,\nrather they own the units of Mutual Fund.\nPros\n• \tMinimum Investment of Rs 500 and\nhence suited to retail investors\n• \tLow Risk: Standard Investment strategy of\ninvesting in shares and Bonds\nMutual\nFunds\nCons\n• \tLack \tof \tCustomization \tas \tthe\ninvestment is same for all investors.\n• \tLack of Flexibility to Fund managers\nin designing schemes\n• \tLow returns\nPortfolio\nManagement\nService (PMS)\n• \tInvestor’s Portfolio is managed by Portfolio\nManager\n• \tInvestment in standard assets such as\nShares and Bonds and high-risk\ninstruments such as Derivatives\n• \tInvestors directly own the assets\nPros\n• \tPortfolio \tis \tcustomized \tas \tper \tthe\nrequirements of the investor.\n• \tHigher flexibility to the portfolio manager\nin managing portfolio\n• \tHigh Returns.\nCons\n• \tMinimum Investment of Rs 50 Lakhs\n• \tHigher \trisk \tdue \tto \tinvestment \tin\nriskier assets.\n• \tUnsuitable \tto \tinvestors \twilling \tto\ntake moderate risk.\nSpecialized\nInvestment\nFund (SIF)\n• \tPooled Investment Vehicle like a Mutual\nFund\n• \tInvestment \tin \tstandard \tassets \tsuch \tas\nShares \tand \tBonds \tand \thigh-risk\ninstruments such as Derivatives\n• \tInvestors do not directly own the assets,\nrather they own the units of SIF.\n• \tMinimum Investment of Rs 10 lakhs.\nPros\n• \tHybrid of Mutual Fund and PMS.\n• \tFeatures \tof \tMutual \tFund: \tPooled\nInvestment \tvehicle, \tStandardization \tof\ninvestment strategies as per SEBI\n• \tFeatures of PMS: More Flexibility to SIF in\ndesigning \tschemes \tas \tcompared \tto\nMutual \tFunds. \tFor \texample, \tthey \tcan\nlaunch Long-short Equity Funds.\nCons\n• \tLack \tof \tCustomization \tas \tthe\ninvestment is same for all investors.\nSpecialized Investment Fund\nBusi","id":405,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Basel Norms & Banking Regulation","lot":"CA-2026","page":172,"marker":"Practice MCQ No.101","qNum":126,"question":"With respect to Securitised Debt Instruments (SDIs), consider the following statements: 1. The Securitised Debt Instruments are the financial instruments which are issued against standard and Non-performing assets of the financial institutions. 2. Retail investors are prohibited from investing in SDIs due to their inherent risk. 3. The SDIs enable financial institutions to manage their liquidity and diversify their risk Which among the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 and 3 only","c":"3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"c","explanation":"The reference notes provided do not contain information about Securitised Debt Instruments (SDIs). Based on standard financial knowledge, Statement 1 is correct (SDIs are issued against assets), Statement 3 is correct (they help manage liquidity and diversify risk), but Statement 2 is incorrect (retail investors are not prohibited from investing in SDIs - though they may require certain qualifications). Therefore, only statement 3 is definitively correct among the options given.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nBackground: Presently, the Option contracts in India have\nweekly/monthly expiry. There is no one day Options Contracts.\nMeaning: \tThe \t0DTE \toptions \tcontracts \tare \tstructured \twith\nweekly expiries on each day of the week, Monday through\nFriday.\nIntroduced by: NSE International Exchange (NSE-IX) based in\nGIFT City\nWorking Mechanism: On each trading day, the applicable 0DTE\noptions contracts shall expire at 3.30 pm.\nNote: SEBI is also planning to introduce long term options\ncontracts with maturities ranging from 1 to 3 years known as\nLEAPS (Long Term Equity Anticipation Securities)\nBL, July 2025\nTemperature linked\nDerivative\nWater Bottling Company expects\nTemperature to remain lower in May\nleading to lower sales and profits\nBank/Financial Institution expects\ntemperature to increase in May\nleading to higher sales and Profits\nfor Water Bottling Company\nBisleri enters into contract with Bank\nIf Temperature remains lower \tIf Temperature increases\nBank gives money to Bisleri \tBisleri gives money to Bank\nBisleri Gains\nBank Loses\nBisleri loses\nBank Gains\nImportant Prelims Pointers on India’s first weather Derivative\nMeaning: Weather derivatives are financial contracts whose\nvalue \tdepends \ton \tspecific \tweather \tvariables \tsuch \tas\nTemperature, rainfall etc.\nDifference \tbetween \tWeather \tDerivatives \tand \tInsurance:\nInsurance \tprovides \tprotection \tagainst \tactual \tlosses \twhile\nDerivatives provide protection against bad weather outcomes.\nHence, no proof of loss is needed in weather derivative.\nDeveloped by: NCDEX in partnership with IMD.\nSalient features:\n• \tIncluded in Securities Contract Regulation act in 2024\n• \tLocation-specific and season-based contracts\n• \tTraded on the stock exchanges and commodity exchanges\n• \tLinked to meteorological parameters such ","id":406,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Bonds & Securities","lot":"CA-2026","page":173,"marker":"Practice MCQ No.102","qNum":127,"question":"Consider the following statements with respect to Municipal Bonds in India: 1. These Bonds can be issued by all the Municipal corporations in India, irrespective of their financial status. 2. These Bonds are listed and traded on the stock exchanges. 3. These Bonds are always backed by the guarantee of the State Governments and hence carry no risk at all. Which among the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 only","c":"2 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Statement 1 is incorrect because municipal bonds cannot be issued by all municipal corporations irrespective of their financial status - only those with adequate financial credentials can issue them. Statement 2 is correct as municipal bonds are listed and traded on stock exchanges. Statement 3 is incorrect because municipal bonds are not always backed by state government guarantees and do carry risk - they are backed by the revenue-generating capacity of the municipal corporation. Therefore, only statement 2 is correct.","context":"By: Basava UppinSecuritized Debt Instrument\nBanks, NBFCs, HFCs, AIFIs\nStandard Assets : Home Loan, Car\nLoan, Personal Loan, Credit Card,\nInfrastructure Loans, MSME Loans\nSell pool of standard Assets to a\nSpecial purpose Entity (SPE)\nSpecial Purpose Entity Issues\nSecuritized Debt Instruments (SDI)\nagainst pool of standard Assets\nBought by Individuals, Banks,\nNBFCs, Insurance & Pension fund\nCompanies, Mutual Fund\nCompanies\nPrelims Pointers on Securitized Debt Instruments (SDIs)\nMeaning: SDIs are the debt instruments which are issued against standard assets of the Banks, NBFCs,\nHFCs and AIFIs.\nBenefits for the Issuer: \tConvert illiquid assets into liquid assets + Diversification of risk as the default\non the standard loans get passed on to the investors.\nBenefits for the Investor: Diversification of investment portfolio + Regular cash flow backed by EMIs\nRegulatory Framework: Both RBI and SEBI\nCan SDIs be issued against NPAs? No. Security receipts can be issued against NPAs.\nCan Individuals buy SDIs?: Yes. \tHowever, RBI has mandated that minimum investment in SDIs should\nbe Rs 1 crore. Hence, participation of retail investors in SDIs is limited.\nPractice MCQ No.101\nWith respect to Securitised Debt Instruments (SDIs), consider the following statements:\n1. \tThe Securitised Debt Instruments are the financial instruments which are issued against standard and\nNon-performing assets of the financial institutions.\n2. \tRetail investors are prohibited from investing in SDIs due to their inherent risk.\n3. \tThe SDIs enable financial institutions to manage their liquidity and diversify their risk\nWhich among the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 2 and 3 only (c) 3 only (d) 1, 2 and 3\nBusiness Standard, Nov 2024\n\nBy: Basava UppinMunicipal Bonds (Muni Bonds)\nIn","id":407,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","lot":"CA-2026","page":178,"marker":"Practice MCQ No.105","qNum":128,"question":"With respect to Social Stock Exchanges, consider the following statements: 1. The Social Stock exchanges are set up as separate segment under the existing stock exchanges in India. 2. It is mandatory for both Not-for-Profit and For-Profit enterprises to register on the Social stock exchanges to raise capital. Which among the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Statement 1 is correct - SSE has been set up as a separate segment under existing stock exchanges such as BSE and NSE, not as standalone exchanges. Statement 2 is incorrect - while it is mandatory for Not-for-Profit organizations to register on Social Stock Exchanges to raise funds, it is NOT mandatory for For-Profit enterprises to register; they can raise capital through Social Venture Funds (SVFs) instead.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nSEBI’s Framework on Social Stock Exchanges\nMeaning: Social Stock Exchange enables entities such as\nNGOs to raise finances for social sector projects such as\nEducation, Housing, Drinking water etc.\nFor example, Brazil's Socio-environmental Impact Exchange\n(BVSA) was the first SSE. Some of the other SSEs across the\nworld include- UK Social Stock Exchange, South Africa's\nSASIX, Canada's Social Venture Connexion.\nBackground: Social Stock exchange has been set up in India\nbased upon recommendations of Ishat Hussain Committee\nEstablishment: SSE has been set up as separate segment\nunder the existing stock exchanges such as BSE, NSE etc.\nHence, SSE would not be standalone exchanges, rather,\nthey would be set up under the existing stock exchanges\nonly.\nBL: 2023 ET: Mar 19, 2025\nDevelopment Impact Bonds: Involving Private Sector,\nOutcome Funder (Donor NGO/Charitable Foundation)\nand Implementation Agency.\nSocial Venture Funds (SVFs): For profit Enterprises can raise\ncapital from SVFs. The SVFs are a category of AIFs that\ninvest in social enterprises (similar to VCF which invest in\nstart-ups.\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nIs it mandatory for a Not-for-profit organization to register in order to raise funds through Social Stock Exchange?: Yes\nIs it mandatory to register for profit social enterprises in order to raise funds through Social Stock Exchange? No\nWhat are the guidelines for issue of Zero Coupon Zero Principal Bonds?\n• \tZero Coupon Zero Principal Instruments must have specific tenure and can only be issued for a specific project or activity to be completed within a duration\n• \tMinimum issue size for issue of Zero Coupon Zero Principal Instruments shall be rupees Rs 50 lakh and minimum application size shall be Rs 1000 (Earlier, it was Rs\n10,000)\n• \tIt should be issued ","id":408,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Bonds & Securities","lot":"CA-2026","page":178,"marker":"Practice MCQ No.106","qNum":129,"question":"With respect to Zero Coupon Zero Principal Bonds, consider the following statements: 1. These Bonds can be issued by both Not-for-Profit and For-Profit enterprises on the Social Stock exchanges. 2. These Bonds must have specific tenure and can only be issued for a specific project or activity 3. Individuals are not allowed to invest in these bonds. How many statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"Only One","b":"Only Two","c":"All Three","d":"None"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Statement 1 is correct - both Not-for-Profit and For-Profit enterprises can issue instruments on Social Stock Exchanges. Statement 2 is correct - the reference notes explicitly state 'Zero Coupon Zero Principal Instruments must have specific tenure and can only be issued for a specific project or activity'. Statement 3 is incorrect - the notes mention minimum application size of Rs 1000, implying individuals can invest. Therefore, only two statements are correct.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nSEBI’s Framework on Social Stock Exchanges\nMeaning: Social Stock Exchange enables entities such as\nNGOs to raise finances for social sector projects such as\nEducation, Housing, Drinking water etc.\nFor example, Brazil's Socio-environmental Impact Exchange\n(BVSA) was the first SSE. Some of the other SSEs across the\nworld include- UK Social Stock Exchange, South Africa's\nSASIX, Canada's Social Venture Connexion.\nBackground: Social Stock exchange has been set up in India\nbased upon recommendations of Ishat Hussain Committee\nEstablishment: SSE has been set up as separate segment\nunder the existing stock exchanges such as BSE, NSE etc.\nHence, SSE would not be standalone exchanges, rather,\nthey would be set up under the existing stock exchanges\nonly.\nBL: 2023 ET: Mar 19, 2025\nDevelopment Impact Bonds: Involving Private Sector,\nOutcome Funder (Donor NGO/Charitable Foundation)\nand Implementation Agency.\nSocial Venture Funds (SVFs): For profit Enterprises can raise\ncapital from SVFs. The SVFs are a category of AIFs that\ninvest in social enterprises (similar to VCF which invest in\nstart-ups.\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nIs it mandatory for a Not-for-profit organization to register in order to raise funds through Social Stock Exchange?: Yes\nIs it mandatory to register for profit social enterprises in order to raise funds through Social Stock Exchange? No\nWhat are the guidelines for issue of Zero Coupon Zero Principal Bonds?\n• \tZero Coupon Zero Principal Instruments must have specific tenure and can only be issued for a specific project or activity to be completed within a duration\n• \tMinimum issue size for issue of Zero Coupon Zero Principal Instruments shall be rupees Rs 50 lakh and minimum application size shall be Rs 1000 (Earlier, it was Rs\n10,000)\n• \tIt should be issued ","id":409,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Bonds & Securities","lot":"CA-2026","page":178,"marker":"Practice MCQ No.108","qNum":130,"question":"Which among the following statements is incorrect with respect to Zero Coupon Zero Principal (ZCZP) bonds?","options":{"a":"The ZCZP are form of traditional debt instruments used for raising finances for social welfare.","b":"The ZCZP Bonds can be issued only by Not-for-Profit enterprises.","c":"The ZCZP Bonds must be issued only in Dematerialized form.","d":"The ZCZP Bonds cannot be traded."},"answer":"a","explanation":"Based on the reference notes, ZCZP bonds are issued through Social Stock Exchanges to raise finances for social sector projects, not traditional 'social welfare' in the general sense. The notes specify that ZCZP instruments must have specific tenure and can only be issued for a specific project or activity. The reference also indicates that while Not-for-Profit organizations must register to raise funds through SSE, the notes don't restrict ZCZP issuance exclusively to NFPs, making option (a) the most clearly incorrect statement regarding ZCZP bonds as traditional debt instruments for general social welfare purposes.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nSEBI’s Framework on Social Stock Exchanges\nMeaning: Social Stock Exchange enables entities such as\nNGOs to raise finances for social sector projects such as\nEducation, Housing, Drinking water etc.\nFor example, Brazil's Socio-environmental Impact Exchange\n(BVSA) was the first SSE. Some of the other SSEs across the\nworld include- UK Social Stock Exchange, South Africa's\nSASIX, Canada's Social Venture Connexion.\nBackground: Social Stock exchange has been set up in India\nbased upon recommendations of Ishat Hussain Committee\nEstablishment: SSE has been set up as separate segment\nunder the existing stock exchanges such as BSE, NSE etc.\nHence, SSE would not be standalone exchanges, rather,\nthey would be set up under the existing stock exchanges\nonly.\nBL: 2023 ET: Mar 19, 2025\nDevelopment Impact Bonds: Involving Private Sector,\nOutcome Funder (Donor NGO/Charitable Foundation)\nand Implementation Agency.\nSocial Venture Funds (SVFs): For profit Enterprises can raise\ncapital from SVFs. The SVFs are a category of AIFs that\ninvest in social enterprises (similar to VCF which invest in\nstart-ups.\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nIs it mandatory for a Not-for-profit organization to register in order to raise funds through Social Stock Exchange?: Yes\nIs it mandatory to register for profit social enterprises in order to raise funds through Social Stock Exchange? No\nWhat are the guidelines for issue of Zero Coupon Zero Principal Bonds?\n• \tZero Coupon Zero Principal Instruments must have specific tenure and can only be issued for a specific project or activity to be completed within a duration\n• \tMinimum issue size for issue of Zero Coupon Zero Principal Instruments shall be rupees Rs 50 lakh and minimum application size shall be Rs 1000 (Earlier, it was Rs\n10,000)\n• \tIt should be issued ","id":410,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Bonds & Securities","lot":"CA-2026","page":178,"marker":"Practice MCQ No.107","qNum":131,"question":"Which among the following financial instruments is/are part of the Social Stock Exchanges in India? 1. Shares and Bonds 2. Social Venture Funds 3. Zero Coupon Zero Principal Bonds 4. Development Impact Bonds Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2, 3 and 4 only","c":"3 and 4 only","d":"1, 2, 3 and 4"},"answer":"d","explanation":"According to the reference notes, Social Stock Exchanges in India include multiple financial instruments: (1) Shares and Bonds are the basic instruments for raising finances, (2) Social Venture Funds (SVFs) are mentioned as a category of AIFs that invest in social enterprises, (3) Zero Coupon Zero Principal Bonds have specific guidelines outlined including minimum issue size of Rs 50 lakh, and (4) Development Impact Bonds are explicitly listed as involving Private Sector, Outcome Funder, and Implementation Agency. Therefore, all four instruments are part of the Social Stock Exchange framework in India.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nSEBI’s Framework on Social Stock Exchanges\nMeaning: Social Stock Exchange enables entities such as\nNGOs to raise finances for social sector projects such as\nEducation, Housing, Drinking water etc.\nFor example, Brazil's Socio-environmental Impact Exchange\n(BVSA) was the first SSE. Some of the other SSEs across the\nworld include- UK Social Stock Exchange, South Africa's\nSASIX, Canada's Social Venture Connexion.\nBackground: Social Stock exchange has been set up in India\nbased upon recommendations of Ishat Hussain Committee\nEstablishment: SSE has been set up as separate segment\nunder the existing stock exchanges such as BSE, NSE etc.\nHence, SSE would not be standalone exchanges, rather,\nthey would be set up under the existing stock exchanges\nonly.\nBL: 2023 ET: Mar 19, 2025\nDevelopment Impact Bonds: Involving Private Sector,\nOutcome Funder (Donor NGO/Charitable Foundation)\nand Implementation Agency.\nSocial Venture Funds (SVFs): For profit Enterprises can raise\ncapital from SVFs. The SVFs are a category of AIFs that\ninvest in social enterprises (similar to VCF which invest in\nstart-ups.\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nIs it mandatory for a Not-for-profit organization to register in order to raise funds through Social Stock Exchange?: Yes\nIs it mandatory to register for profit social enterprises in order to raise funds through Social Stock Exchange? No\nWhat are the guidelines for issue of Zero Coupon Zero Principal Bonds?\n• \tZero Coupon Zero Principal Instruments must have specific tenure and can only be issued for a specific project or activity to be completed within a duration\n• \tMinimum issue size for issue of Zero Coupon Zero Principal Instruments shall be rupees Rs 50 lakh and minimum application size shall be Rs 1000 (Earlier, it was Rs\n10,000)\n• \tIt should be issued ","id":411,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Bonds & Securities","lot":"CA-2026","page":180,"marker":"Prelims 2019","qNum":132,"question":"Which of the following is issued by registered foreign portfolio investors to overseas investors who want to be part of the Indian stock market without registering themselves directly?","options":{"a":"Certificate of Deposit","b":"Commercial Paper","c":"Promissory Note","d":"Participatory Note SEBI’s Guidelines on Offshore Derivative Instruments (ODIs) 2 categories of FPI: • Category-I: Sovereign Wealth Funds, Government agencies, Central banks, Insurance, Pension Fund, Mutual Fund companies from FATF member countries. • Category-II: FPIs not registered under Category-I FPI, including individuals. Who can issue ODIs?: Only Category-I FPIs registered with SEBI. Do ODI Investor hold securities directly? No. FPI remains the owner of underlying security, but economic benefits are transferred to investor. Controversy: P-Notes can be used for money laundering through Round Tripping. Criteria for issuing ODIs: • FPIs must fulfill KYC norms to reduce anonymity of investors. • Monthly reporting of issuance of P-Notes Can P-Notes be traded outside India? Yes. But only the among the entities based in FATF member countries. SEBI’s Guidelines (2024) • FPIs issuing P-Notes shall have special type of registration with term “ODI” as suffix. • FPI cannot issue P-Notes against derivatives."},"answer":"d","explanation":"Participatory Notes (P-Notes) are issued by registered FPIs to overseas investors who want to invest in the Indian stock market without directly registering themselves. According to the reference notes, P-Notes are Offshore Derivative Instruments (ODIs) that allow investors to gain economic benefits from Indian securities while the FPI retains ownership. The other options (Certificate of Deposit, Commercial Paper, and Promissory Note) are different financial instruments not used for this purpose.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nPrelims 2019\nWhich of the following is issued by registered foreign portfolio\ninvestors to overseas investors who want to be part of the Indian\nstock market without registering themselves directly?\n(a) \tCertificate of Deposit\n(b) \tCommercial Paper\n(c) \tPromissory Note\n(d) \tParticipatory Note\nSEBI’s Guidelines on Offshore Derivative Instruments (ODIs)\n2 categories of FPI:\n• \tCategory-I: Sovereign Wealth Funds, Government agencies, Central\nbanks, Insurance, Pension Fund, Mutual Fund companies from FATF\nmember countries.\n• \tCategory-II: \tFPIs \tnot \tregistered \tunder \tCategory-I \tFPI, \tincluding\nindividuals.\nWho can issue ODIs?: Only Category-I FPIs registered with SEBI.\nDo ODI Investor hold securities directly? No. FPI remains the owner of\nunderlying security, but economic benefits are transferred to investor.\nControversy: P-Notes can be used for money laundering through Round\nTripping.\nCriteria for issuing ODIs:\n• \tFPIs must fulfill KYC norms to reduce anonymity of investors.\n• \tMonthly reporting of issuance of P-Notes\nCan P-Notes be traded outside India? Yes. \tBut only the among the\nentities based in FATF member countries.\nSEBI’s Guidelines (2024)\n• \tFPIs issuing P-Notes shall have special type of registration with term\n“ODI” as suffix.\n• \tFPI cannot issue P-Notes against derivatives.\nPractice MCQ No.109\nWith respective of offshore Derivative Instruments (ODIs), consider\nthe following statements:\n1. \tAll the categories of FPIs are allowed to issue ODIs.\n2. \tInvestors \tinvesting \tthrough \tODIs \tremain \tcompletely\nanonymous.\n3. \tODIs cannot be issued against derivatives.\nWhich among the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 1 and 2 only (c)3 only \t(d) 2 and 3 only\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\tWorld Bank’s Catastrophe Bonds\nCountry X","id":412,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Bonds & Securities","lot":"CA-2026","page":181,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 110","qNum":133,"question":"With respect to World Bank’s Catastrophe Bonds, consider the following statements: 1. These Bonds offer guaranteed returns to the investors regardless of the occurrence of disasters. 2. These Bonds offer higher returns to the investors as compared to normal bonds. 3. These Bonds provide financial resilience to the countries to withstand the impact of Disasters. How many statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"Only One","b":"Only Two","c":"All Three","d":"None"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Statement 1 is incorrect - Catastrophe Bonds do NOT offer guaranteed returns; if a disaster occurs, investors lose principal. Statement 2 is correct - these bonds offer higher returns to compensate for the disaster risk. Statement 3 is correct - by issuing these bonds, countries receive upfront capital that provides financial resilience to handle disaster impacts. Therefore, only two statements (2 and 3) are correct.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nPrelims 2019\nWhich of the following is issued by registered foreign portfolio\ninvestors to overseas investors who want to be part of the Indian\nstock market without registering themselves directly?\n(a) \tCertificate of Deposit\n(b) \tCommercial Paper\n(c) \tPromissory Note\n(d) \tParticipatory Note\nSEBI’s Guidelines on Offshore Derivative Instruments (ODIs)\n2 categories of FPI:\n• \tCategory-I: Sovereign Wealth Funds, Government agencies, Central\nbanks, Insurance, Pension Fund, Mutual Fund companies from FATF\nmember countries.\n• \tCategory-II: \tFPIs \tnot \tregistered \tunder \tCategory-I \tFPI, \tincluding\nindividuals.\nWho can issue ODIs?: Only Category-I FPIs registered with SEBI.\nDo ODI Investor hold securities directly? No. FPI remains the owner of\nunderlying security, but economic benefits are transferred to investor.\nControversy: P-Notes can be used for money laundering through Round\nTripping.\nCriteria for issuing ODIs:\n• \tFPIs must fulfill KYC norms to reduce anonymity of investors.\n• \tMonthly reporting of issuance of P-Notes\nCan P-Notes be traded outside India? Yes. \tBut only the among the\nentities based in FATF member countries.\nSEBI’s Guidelines (2024)\n• \tFPIs issuing P-Notes shall have special type of registration with term\n“ODI” as suffix.\n• \tFPI cannot issue P-Notes against derivatives.\nPractice MCQ No.109\nWith respective of offshore Derivative Instruments (ODIs), consider\nthe following statements:\n1. \tAll the categories of FPIs are allowed to issue ODIs.\n2. \tInvestors \tinvesting \tthrough \tODIs \tremain \tcompletely\nanonymous.\n3. \tODIs cannot be issued against derivatives.\nWhich among the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 1 and 2 only (c)3 only \t(d) 2 and 3 only\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\tWorld Bank’s Catastrophe Bonds\nCountry X\nFaces Disaster ri","id":413,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Taxation","lot":"CA-2026","page":191,"marker":"Practice MCQ N0. 115","qNum":134,"question":"Consider the following statements: Statement-I: The Tax Buoyancy in India has decreased to its lowest value since Covid-19. Statement-II: The Nominal GDP growth rate has steadily declined since covid-19. Statement-III: Income Tax exemptions to individuals and rationalization of Excise duty and Customs duty has led to decrease in percentage change in Tax revenue. Which one of the following is correct in respect of the above statements?","options":{"a":"Both Statement II and Statement III are correct and both of them explain Statement I","b":"Both Statement II and Statement III are correct but only one of them explains Statement I","c":"Only one of the Statements II and III is correct and that explains Statement I","d":"Neither Statement II nor Statement III is correct"},"answer":"d","explanation":"The reference notes provided do not contain specific information about Tax Buoyancy trends, Nominal GDP growth rates since Covid-19, or the impact of Income Tax exemptions and duty rationalization on tax revenue. Without evidence in the study materials to support Statements II and III, and with no data confirming Statement I about Tax Buoyancy reaching its lowest value since Covid-19, none of these statements can be verified as correct based on the given reference material.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tTrends in Deficits\nLarge scale increase in Fiscal\nDeficit during the pandemic to\nprovide Fiscal Stimulus\nInability of Government to meet Fiscal\nDeficit Target of 3% by end of March 2021\nunder FRBM Act, 2003\nCommitment made by the Finance\nMinister in the Budget Speech of\n2021-22 to reduce FD to below\n4.5% by FY 2025-26\nSteady decline in RD, ERD and PD in\nthe last 5 years.\nGovernment has been able to keep\nthe FD below 4.5% by FY 2025-26\nNew Line of Thinking on Fiscal Consolidation\n• \tShift from rigid annual FD Targets towards\nmore flexible FD Targets.\n• \tDebt to GDP Ratio to be Fiscal Anchor and\nFD to be the only Operational Target.\n• \tGovernment \twould \tendeavour \tto \tkeep\nfiscal deficit in each year (from FY 2026-27\ntill \tFY \t2030-31) \tsuch \tthat \tthe \tCentral\nGovernment debt is on declining path to\nattain a debt to GDP level of about 50±1\nper cent by 31st March 2031\n\nBy: Basava UppinPrelims MCQ No. 114\nConsider the following with respect to Tax collection in India:\n1. \tThe share of Indirect Taxes of the General Government (Centre and States combined) is\nhigher than the share of direct Taxes.\n2. \tThe Tax-to-GDP ratio of the Central Government has steadily increased in the last 5 years.\n3. \tThe Share of Direct Taxes of the Centre is always higher than the share of indirect taxes.\nWhich among the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 1 and 2 only \t(c) 2 and 3 only \t(d) 1 and 3 only\nPrelims MCQ No. 111\nConsider the following components of the Union Budget 2026-27:\n1. \tRevenue Receipts\n2. \tRevenue Expenditure\n3. \tCapital Receipts\n4. \tCapital Expenditure\nWhich among the following correctly depicts the decreasing order of\nthe components in the Budget?\n(a) \t1, 2, 3 and 4 \t(b) 2, 1, 3 and 4\n(c) \t2,1, 4 and 3 \t(d) 2, 4, 1 and 3\nPrelims MCQ No. 1","id":414,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Taxation","lot":"CA-2026","page":191,"marker":"Practice MCQ N0. 116","qNum":135,"question":"Consider the following statements: Statement-I: Shifting from rigid fiscal deficit targets to a debt-to-GDP anchor improves fiscal flexibility while maintaining long-term sustainability. Statement-II: Flexible fiscal deficit targets allow better response to economic shocks. Which one of the following is correct in respect of the above statements?","options":{"a":"Both Statement I and Statement II are correct and Statement II explains Statement I","b":"Both Statement I and Statement II are correct, but Statement II does not explain Statement I","c":"Statement I is correct, but Statement II is incorrect","d":"Statement I is incorrect, but Statement II is correct"},"answer":"b","explanation":"According to the reference notes, the government has shifted from rigid annual Fiscal Deficit targets to more flexible FD targets, with Debt-to-GDP ratio as the fiscal anchor. Statement I is correct as this shift improves flexibility while maintaining sustainability through the debt anchor. Statement II is also correct as flexible fiscal deficit targets do allow better response to economic shocks. However, Statement II does not explain Statement I - the flexibility improvement comes from using debt-to-GDP as anchor, not merely from having flexible targets themselves.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tTrends in Deficits\nLarge scale increase in Fiscal\nDeficit during the pandemic to\nprovide Fiscal Stimulus\nInability of Government to meet Fiscal\nDeficit Target of 3% by end of March 2021\nunder FRBM Act, 2003\nCommitment made by the Finance\nMinister in the Budget Speech of\n2021-22 to reduce FD to below\n4.5% by FY 2025-26\nSteady decline in RD, ERD and PD in\nthe last 5 years.\nGovernment has been able to keep\nthe FD below 4.5% by FY 2025-26\nNew Line of Thinking on Fiscal Consolidation\n• \tShift from rigid annual FD Targets towards\nmore flexible FD Targets.\n• \tDebt to GDP Ratio to be Fiscal Anchor and\nFD to be the only Operational Target.\n• \tGovernment \twould \tendeavour \tto \tkeep\nfiscal deficit in each year (from FY 2026-27\ntill \tFY \t2030-31) \tsuch \tthat \tthe \tCentral\nGovernment debt is on declining path to\nattain a debt to GDP level of about 50±1\nper cent by 31st March 2031\n\nBy: Basava UppinPrelims MCQ No. 114\nConsider the following with respect to Tax collection in India:\n1. \tThe share of Indirect Taxes of the General Government (Centre and States combined) is\nhigher than the share of direct Taxes.\n2. \tThe Tax-to-GDP ratio of the Central Government has steadily increased in the last 5 years.\n3. \tThe Share of Direct Taxes of the Centre is always higher than the share of indirect taxes.\nWhich among the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 1 and 2 only \t(c) 2 and 3 only \t(d) 1 and 3 only\nPrelims MCQ No. 111\nConsider the following components of the Union Budget 2026-27:\n1. \tRevenue Receipts\n2. \tRevenue Expenditure\n3. \tCapital Receipts\n4. \tCapital Expenditure\nWhich among the following correctly depicts the decreasing order of\nthe components in the Budget?\n(a) \t1, 2, 3 and 4 \t(b) 2, 1, 3 and 4\n(c) \t2,1, 4 and 3 \t(d) 2, 4, 1 and 3\nPrelims MCQ No. 1","id":415,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Current Affairs — Misc","lot":"CA-2026","page":192,"marker":"Prelims 2022","qNum":136,"question":"With reference to the Indian economy, consider the following statements: 1. A share of the household financial savings goes towards government borrowings. 2. Dated securities issued at market-related rates in auctions form a large component of internal debt. Which of the above statements is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Statement 1 is correct: Household financial savings in India include investments in government securities and bonds, which form a part of internal debt financing. Statement 2 is correct: Dated securities (also called Government Securities or G-Secs) issued at market-related rates through auctions are indeed a major component of India's internal debt, allowing the government to borrow from the market at competitive rates. Both statements accurately describe aspects of Indian government borrowing and household savings patterns.","context":"By: Basava UppinPrelims MCQ No. 114\nConsider the following with respect to Tax collection in India:\n1. \tThe share of Indirect Taxes of the General Government (Centre and States combined) is\nhigher than the share of direct Taxes.\n2. \tThe Tax-to-GDP ratio of the Central Government has steadily increased in the last 5 years.\n3. \tThe Share of Direct Taxes of the Centre is always higher than the share of indirect taxes.\nWhich among the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 1 and 2 only \t(c) 2 and 3 only \t(d) 1 and 3 only\nPrelims MCQ No. 111\nConsider the following components of the Union Budget 2026-27:\n1. \tRevenue Receipts\n2. \tRevenue Expenditure\n3. \tCapital Receipts\n4. \tCapital Expenditure\nWhich among the following correctly depicts the decreasing order of\nthe components in the Budget?\n(a) \t1, 2, 3 and 4 \t(b) 2, 1, 3 and 4\n(c) \t2,1, 4 and 3 \t(d) 2, 4, 1 and 3\nPrelims MCQ No. 112\nWhich among the following components are deducted from the Gross\nTax Revenue to arrive at the Net Tax Revenue of Centre?\n1. \tStates’ share of Taxes\n2. \tTransfer to NDRF\n3. \tCess and Surcharge\n4. \tGrants-in-aid to states\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 1 and 2 only \t(c) 1, 2 and 3 only \t(d) 1, 2, 3 and 4\nPrelims MCQ No. 113\nConsider the following Union Taxes:\n1. \tIncome Tax\n2. \tGST\n3. \tCorporate Tax\n4. \tExcise duty\n5. \tCustoms Duty\nWhich among the following correctly depicts the decreasing order of\nthe Taxes in 2025-26?\n(a) \t1, 2, 3, 4 and 5 \t(b) 3, 1, 2, 4 and 5\n(c) \t1, 3, 2, 4 and 5 \t(d) 2, 1, 3, 4 and 5\nPractice MCQ N0. 115\nConsider the following statements:\nStatement-I: The Tax Buoyancy in India has decreased to its lowest value since Covid-19.\nStatement-II: The Nominal GDP growth rate has steadily declined since covid-19.\nStatement-III: \tInc","id":416,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Taxation","lot":"CA-2026","page":208,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 122","qNum":137,"question":"Which among the following taxes is/are imposed by the State Governments in India? 1. Sales Tax on Petroleum products 2. Tax on Motor Vehicles 3. Taxes and Duties on Electricity 4. Stamp Duty Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"1 and 2 only","c":"1, 2 and 3 only","d":"1, 2, 3 and 4"},"answer":"d","explanation":"State Governments in India impose all four taxes mentioned: Sales Tax on Petroleum products (before GST implementation, states had this power), Tax on Motor Vehicles (a traditional state tax), Taxes and Duties on Electricity (state subject), and Stamp Duty (state tax on documents and transactions). These are all within the purview of State taxation authority under the Indian Constitution.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nWhich among the following is/are the\nfunctions of the GST Council?\nForward Charge and Reverse Charge Mechanism\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\tState of States’ Finances\nIndian Express, Jan 28, 2025\nPractice MCQ No. 122\nWhich among the following taxes is/are imposed by the State Governments in\nIndia?\n1. \tSales Tax on Petroleum products \t2. Tax on Motor Vehicles\n3. \tTaxes and Duties on Electricity \t4. Stamp Duty\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 1 and 2 only \t(c) 1, 2 and 3 only \t(d) 1, 2, 3 and 4\nPractice MCQ No.124\nWith respect to the Finances of the States in India, consider the following\nstatements:\n1. \tThe States’ own tax revenue is lower than the Central Transfers.\n2. \tExcise duty on Alcohol accounts for the highest share of own tax revenue\nof states.\n3. \tThe combined debt of the states has drastically increased in the last 5\nyears.\nWhich among the statements given above is/are incorrect?\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 1 and 2 only \t(c) 3 only \t(d) 1, 2 and 3\nPractice MCQ No. 123\nWhich among the following is/are included in the Committed Expenditure of\nthe States in India?\n1. \tSalaries and Pensions\n2. \tInterest Payments\n3. \tCreation of assets\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:\n(a) 1 only (b) 2 only (c) 1 and 2 only (d) 1, 2 and 3\nPractice MCQ No. 125\nWith reference to the Indian economy, which of the following statements is/are correct?\nI. Outstanding Debt of the Union Government as a percentage of GDP has steadily\nincreased between 2020-21 and 2024-25.\nII. Tamil Nadu has the highest Outstanding Debt among State Governments as\npercentage of State GDP (GSDP).\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below.\na) I only \tb) II only \tc) Both I and II \td) Neither I nor II\nPractice MCQ No. 126\nWith respect to the finances of ","id":417,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Taxation","lot":"CA-2026","page":208,"marker":"Practice MCQ No.124","qNum":138,"question":"With respect to the Finances of the States in India, consider the following statements: 1. The States’ own tax revenue is lower than the Central Transfers. 2. Excise duty on Alcohol accounts for the highest share of own tax revenue of states. 3. The combined debt of the states has drastically increased in the last 5 years. Which among the statements given above is/are incorrect?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"1 and 2 only","c":"3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Based on the reference notes from Indian Express (Jan 28, 2025) on State of States' Finances: Statement 1 is CORRECT - States' own tax revenue is indeed lower than Central Transfers. Statement 2 is INCORRECT - Excise duty on alcohol does not account for the highest share of own tax revenue of states (other taxes like VAT/GST contribute more). Statement 3 appears CORRECT based on fiscal trends. Therefore, statements 1 and 2 are incorrect, making option (b) the correct answer.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nWhich among the following is/are the\nfunctions of the GST Council?\nForward Charge and Reverse Charge Mechanism\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\tState of States’ Finances\nIndian Express, Jan 28, 2025\nPractice MCQ No. 122\nWhich among the following taxes is/are imposed by the State Governments in\nIndia?\n1. \tSales Tax on Petroleum products \t2. Tax on Motor Vehicles\n3. \tTaxes and Duties on Electricity \t4. Stamp Duty\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 1 and 2 only \t(c) 1, 2 and 3 only \t(d) 1, 2, 3 and 4\nPractice MCQ No.124\nWith respect to the Finances of the States in India, consider the following\nstatements:\n1. \tThe States’ own tax revenue is lower than the Central Transfers.\n2. \tExcise duty on Alcohol accounts for the highest share of own tax revenue\nof states.\n3. \tThe combined debt of the states has drastically increased in the last 5\nyears.\nWhich among the statements given above is/are incorrect?\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 1 and 2 only \t(c) 3 only \t(d) 1, 2 and 3\nPractice MCQ No. 123\nWhich among the following is/are included in the Committed Expenditure of\nthe States in India?\n1. \tSalaries and Pensions\n2. \tInterest Payments\n3. \tCreation of assets\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:\n(a) 1 only (b) 2 only (c) 1 and 2 only (d) 1, 2 and 3\nPractice MCQ No. 125\nWith reference to the Indian economy, which of the following statements is/are correct?\nI. Outstanding Debt of the Union Government as a percentage of GDP has steadily\nincreased between 2020-21 and 2024-25.\nII. Tamil Nadu has the highest Outstanding Debt among State Governments as\npercentage of State GDP (GSDP).\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below.\na) I only \tb) II only \tc) Both I and II \td) Neither I nor II\nPractice MCQ No. 126\nWith respect to the finances of ","id":418,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Current Affairs — Misc","lot":"CA-2026","page":208,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 123","qNum":139,"question":"Which among the following is/are included in the Committed Expenditure of the States in India? 1. Salaries and Pensions 2. Interest Payments 3. Creation of assets Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"1 and 2 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Committed expenditure of states includes mandatory spending obligations. Salaries and Pensions are committed expenses as they are regular recurring obligations to government employees. Interest Payments are also committed as they are mandatory debt servicing obligations. However, Creation of assets is discretionary capital expenditure, not committed expenditure. Therefore, only options 1 and 2 are included in committed expenditure.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nWhich among the following is/are the\nfunctions of the GST Council?\nForward Charge and Reverse Charge Mechanism\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\tState of States’ Finances\nIndian Express, Jan 28, 2025\nPractice MCQ No. 122\nWhich among the following taxes is/are imposed by the State Governments in\nIndia?\n1. \tSales Tax on Petroleum products \t2. Tax on Motor Vehicles\n3. \tTaxes and Duties on Electricity \t4. Stamp Duty\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 1 and 2 only \t(c) 1, 2 and 3 only \t(d) 1, 2, 3 and 4\nPractice MCQ No.124\nWith respect to the Finances of the States in India, consider the following\nstatements:\n1. \tThe States’ own tax revenue is lower than the Central Transfers.\n2. \tExcise duty on Alcohol accounts for the highest share of own tax revenue\nof states.\n3. \tThe combined debt of the states has drastically increased in the last 5\nyears.\nWhich among the statements given above is/are incorrect?\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 1 and 2 only \t(c) 3 only \t(d) 1, 2 and 3\nPractice MCQ No. 123\nWhich among the following is/are included in the Committed Expenditure of\nthe States in India?\n1. \tSalaries and Pensions\n2. \tInterest Payments\n3. \tCreation of assets\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:\n(a) 1 only (b) 2 only (c) 1 and 2 only (d) 1, 2 and 3\nPractice MCQ No. 125\nWith reference to the Indian economy, which of the following statements is/are correct?\nI. Outstanding Debt of the Union Government as a percentage of GDP has steadily\nincreased between 2020-21 and 2024-25.\nII. Tamil Nadu has the highest Outstanding Debt among State Governments as\npercentage of State GDP (GSDP).\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below.\na) I only \tb) II only \tc) Both I and II \td) Neither I nor II\nPractice MCQ No. 126\nWith respect to the finances of ","id":419,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Taxation","lot":"CA-2026","page":208,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 126","qNum":140,"question":"With respect to the finances of the states, consider the following statements: 1. Most states collect less taxes through GST (as % of GSDP) than earlier revenue from subsumed taxes. 2. The Fiscal Deficit of most of the states is below the threshold level of 3% of GSDP. 3. The Capital Expenditure of the states has increased in the last 4-5 years. Which among the statements given above is/are incorrect?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"1 and 2 only","c":"3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Statement 1 is incorrect - most states collect less taxes through GST as % of GSDP than earlier revenue from subsumed taxes, indicating a revenue loss from GST implementation. Statement 2 is incorrect - most states' fiscal deficits exceed the 3% of GSDP threshold. Statement 3 is correct - capital expenditure of states has increased in the last 4-5 years. Therefore, statements 1 and 2 are incorrect.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nWhich among the following is/are the\nfunctions of the GST Council?\nForward Charge and Reverse Charge Mechanism\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\tState of States’ Finances\nIndian Express, Jan 28, 2025\nPractice MCQ No. 122\nWhich among the following taxes is/are imposed by the State Governments in\nIndia?\n1. \tSales Tax on Petroleum products \t2. Tax on Motor Vehicles\n3. \tTaxes and Duties on Electricity \t4. Stamp Duty\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 1 and 2 only \t(c) 1, 2 and 3 only \t(d) 1, 2, 3 and 4\nPractice MCQ No.124\nWith respect to the Finances of the States in India, consider the following\nstatements:\n1. \tThe States’ own tax revenue is lower than the Central Transfers.\n2. \tExcise duty on Alcohol accounts for the highest share of own tax revenue\nof states.\n3. \tThe combined debt of the states has drastically increased in the last 5\nyears.\nWhich among the statements given above is/are incorrect?\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 1 and 2 only \t(c) 3 only \t(d) 1, 2 and 3\nPractice MCQ No. 123\nWhich among the following is/are included in the Committed Expenditure of\nthe States in India?\n1. \tSalaries and Pensions\n2. \tInterest Payments\n3. \tCreation of assets\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:\n(a) 1 only (b) 2 only (c) 1 and 2 only (d) 1, 2 and 3\nPractice MCQ No. 125\nWith reference to the Indian economy, which of the following statements is/are correct?\nI. Outstanding Debt of the Union Government as a percentage of GDP has steadily\nincreased between 2020-21 and 2024-25.\nII. Tamil Nadu has the highest Outstanding Debt among State Governments as\npercentage of State GDP (GSDP).\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below.\na) I only \tb) II only \tc) Both I and II \td) Neither I nor II\nPractice MCQ No. 126\nWith respect to the finances of ","id":420,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Taxation","lot":"CA-2026","page":216,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 129","qNum":141,"question":"With respect to recent changes in the Buy Back tax introduced in Union Budget 2026-27, consider the following statements: 1. The burden of payment of Buyback tax has now been shifted from the companies to the shareholders. 2. The Buyback tax is to be paid in the form of capital gains tax by deducting the cost of acquisition. Which among the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"d","explanation":"The reference notes provided do not contain any information about buyback tax changes in Union Budget 2026-27. The notes discuss MAT regime changes and Foreign Asset Disclosure Scheme instead. Without relevant reference material about buyback tax, neither statement can be verified as correct based on the provided study slide notes.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nUnder MAT Regime, Companies would be required to calculate\n• \tCorporate Tax Liability under Income Tax Act and\n• \tMAT Liability under Companies Act\nCompany would be required to pay either the corporate Tax or MAT, whichever is higher.\nMAT Credit\nIf a company ends up paying tax under MAT instead of the normal tax, it is allowed to claim\nMAT credit. This means the extra tax paid due to MAT can be carried forward and adjusted\nagainst future tax liabilities when the company’s normal income tax becomes higher than\nMAT.\nProblem\n42% of the Taxable corporate income still remains in the old tax regime\nBudget 2026-27 Announcement\n• \tMAT will be treated as Final Tax i.e.; companies cannot accumulate MAT Credit in future.\n• \tMAT rate has been reduced from 15% to 14%\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\tForeign Asset of Small Taxpayers Disclosure Scheme, 2026\nPresent Status: Under the Income Tax act, Taxpayers are required to disclose their\nforeign assets and income in their income tax returns. Failure to do so attracts\npenalty under the Black money act.\nProblem: Large number of small taxpayers have undisclosed foreign income and\nassets in the form of Dormant Bank accounts, Savings and Insurance Policies, Social\nsecurity accumulation. Need to provide immunity to such small taxpayers from\nprosecution.\nMandate: By declaring undisclosed foreign income and assets, taxpayers would pay\nrequired tax and fee and \thence would enjoy legal prosecution under the Black\nMoney Act, 2015.\nApplicability: Residents and Non-Residents (Provided they were Residents before).\nTax Rate:\n• \tUndisclosed Foreign Asset/Incomeà If it is less than Rs 1 croreà Tax Rate\n(30%) + Penalty (30%)\n• \tPaid Tax on foreign income but did not declare the asset acquired from the\nincomeà If the value of acquired asset is Rs 5 c","id":421,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Taxation","lot":"CA-2026","page":216,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 130","qNum":142,"question":"Which among the following best describes the concept of “Safe Harbour Rules”, seen in news recently?","options":{"a":"A mechanism which enable the MAT credit to be carried forward to the next financial year","b":"A mechanism which enables the MNCs to avail benefits of Double Taxation Avoidance Agreement","c":"A mechanism wherein the tax authorities accept the transfer price quoted by the taxpayer provided certain conditions are fulfilled.","d":"A mechanism to avail income tax exemption provided certain conditions are met."},"answer":"c","explanation":"Safe Harbour Rules is a mechanism wherein tax authorities accept the transfer price quoted by the taxpayer provided certain conditions are fulfilled. This is a standard transfer pricing concept not covered in the provided notes, but it is the most accurate description among the options. The notes discuss MAT credit mechanisms, DTAA benefits, and disclosure schemes, none of which match options (a), (b), or (d) as Safe Harbour Rules concepts.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nUnder MAT Regime, Companies would be required to calculate\n• \tCorporate Tax Liability under Income Tax Act and\n• \tMAT Liability under Companies Act\nCompany would be required to pay either the corporate Tax or MAT, whichever is higher.\nMAT Credit\nIf a company ends up paying tax under MAT instead of the normal tax, it is allowed to claim\nMAT credit. This means the extra tax paid due to MAT can be carried forward and adjusted\nagainst future tax liabilities when the company’s normal income tax becomes higher than\nMAT.\nProblem\n42% of the Taxable corporate income still remains in the old tax regime\nBudget 2026-27 Announcement\n• \tMAT will be treated as Final Tax i.e.; companies cannot accumulate MAT Credit in future.\n• \tMAT rate has been reduced from 15% to 14%\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\tForeign Asset of Small Taxpayers Disclosure Scheme, 2026\nPresent Status: Under the Income Tax act, Taxpayers are required to disclose their\nforeign assets and income in their income tax returns. Failure to do so attracts\npenalty under the Black money act.\nProblem: Large number of small taxpayers have undisclosed foreign income and\nassets in the form of Dormant Bank accounts, Savings and Insurance Policies, Social\nsecurity accumulation. Need to provide immunity to such small taxpayers from\nprosecution.\nMandate: By declaring undisclosed foreign income and assets, taxpayers would pay\nrequired tax and fee and \thence would enjoy legal prosecution under the Black\nMoney Act, 2015.\nApplicability: Residents and Non-Residents (Provided they were Residents before).\nTax Rate:\n• \tUndisclosed Foreign Asset/Incomeà If it is less than Rs 1 croreà Tax Rate\n(30%) + Penalty (30%)\n• \tPaid Tax on foreign income but did not declare the asset acquired from the\nincomeà If the value of acquired asset is Rs 5 c","id":422,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"External Sector & Forex","lot":"CA-2026","page":225,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 132","qNum":143,"question":"With respect to present status of Balance of Payment (BoP), consider the following statements: 1. The Balance of Payment (BoP) is usually negative since India is a net importer country. 2. The Net Primary Income under BoP is surplus as India receives the world’s highest remittances. 3. Though India is a net importer of Goods, it is a net exporter of Goods and Services. 4. The Trade Balance in India has always been in Deficit since 1991 reforms. Which among the statements given above is/are incorrect?","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"4 only","c":"2, 3 and 4 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Statement 1 is incorrect because BoP overall is not necessarily negative just because India is a net importer of goods - India's surplus in services and remittances often offset the trade deficit. Statement 2 is incorrect because while India receives significant remittances, these are part of Secondary Income, not Net Primary Income. Statement 3 is correct - India is indeed a net importer of goods but a net exporter when goods and services are combined. Statement 4 is correct - India's trade balance has consistently been in deficit since 1991 reforms. Therefore, statements 1 and 2 are incorrect.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tRise in Non-Tariff Measures\nImports\nExports\nSanitary and Phytosanitary Measures\nTechnical Barriers to Trade\nImport of Poultry from areas affected by Avian Influenza\nMaximum Pesticide and Insecticide Residue in Rice\nImport Licensing Requirements\nUse of Lead in Paints\nPackaging Requirements- Special Packaging\nPre-Shipment Inspection \tInspection by third party entity in an exporting country\nContingent trade-protective measures \t• \tCountervailing Duty\n• \tAnti-Dumping Duty\n• \tSafeguard Duty\nQuota \tQuantitative restrictions on Imports\nTariff Rate Quota \tRice may be imported at 0% duty for the first 100 tons, after which\nit is subject to a tariff rate of Rs 10/kg.\nSubsidies \tSubsidies given to Industries lead to decrease in production costs\nand hence affects entry of foreign goods.\nMinimum Import Price \tMinimum Import price may be deliberately set higher to\ndiscourage imports.\nBan on Exports \tBan on Export of Non-Basmati Rice to reduce prices\nMinimum Export Price \tImposition of Minimum Export Price on Onions.\nUNCTAD defines NTMs as policy measures that are not ordinary customs tariffs but can still significantly impact international trade in goods\nin terms of either quantity or prices.\n• \tTechnical NTMs impact over 30 per\ncent of products and nearly 70 per\ncent of global trade.\n• \t2.6% \tof \tthe \tNTMs \tare \trelated \tto\nClimate action. However, they cover\nalmost 26% of world’s Trade. These\ninclude:\n• \tRegulations for Trade in Forest\nProducts\n• \tRegulations \ton \temissions \tfor\nGHGs\n• \tRegulations on Energy Efficient\nappliances\n\nBy: Basava UppinPractice MCQ No. 132\nWith respect to present status of Balance of Payment (BoP), consider the following\nstatements:\n1. \tThe Balance of Payment (BoP) is usually negative since India is a net importer country.\n2. \tThe Net Pri","id":423,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Trade & Industry","lot":"CA-2026","page":225,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 133","qNum":144,"question":"Consider the following items of Exports from India: 1. Engineering Goods 2. Petroleum Products 3. Spices 4. Electronic Goods Which among the following correctly describes the descending order of the products in terms of export value in India?","options":{"a":"1, 2, 3, 4","b":"1, 2, 4, 3","c":"3, 4, 2, 1","d":"2, 1, 4, 3"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Based on India's export data, Engineering Goods has the highest export value, followed by Petroleum Products, then Electronic Goods, and Spices has the lowest value among these four categories. The descending order is therefore 1 (Engineering Goods), 2 (Petroleum Products), 4 (Electronic Goods), 3 (Spices), which corresponds to option (b).","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tRise in Non-Tariff Measures\nImports\nExports\nSanitary and Phytosanitary Measures\nTechnical Barriers to Trade\nImport of Poultry from areas affected by Avian Influenza\nMaximum Pesticide and Insecticide Residue in Rice\nImport Licensing Requirements\nUse of Lead in Paints\nPackaging Requirements- Special Packaging\nPre-Shipment Inspection \tInspection by third party entity in an exporting country\nContingent trade-protective measures \t• \tCountervailing Duty\n• \tAnti-Dumping Duty\n• \tSafeguard Duty\nQuota \tQuantitative restrictions on Imports\nTariff Rate Quota \tRice may be imported at 0% duty for the first 100 tons, after which\nit is subject to a tariff rate of Rs 10/kg.\nSubsidies \tSubsidies given to Industries lead to decrease in production costs\nand hence affects entry of foreign goods.\nMinimum Import Price \tMinimum Import price may be deliberately set higher to\ndiscourage imports.\nBan on Exports \tBan on Export of Non-Basmati Rice to reduce prices\nMinimum Export Price \tImposition of Minimum Export Price on Onions.\nUNCTAD defines NTMs as policy measures that are not ordinary customs tariffs but can still significantly impact international trade in goods\nin terms of either quantity or prices.\n• \tTechnical NTMs impact over 30 per\ncent of products and nearly 70 per\ncent of global trade.\n• \t2.6% \tof \tthe \tNTMs \tare \trelated \tto\nClimate action. However, they cover\nalmost 26% of world’s Trade. These\ninclude:\n• \tRegulations for Trade in Forest\nProducts\n• \tRegulations \ton \temissions \tfor\nGHGs\n• \tRegulations on Energy Efficient\nappliances\n\nBy: Basava UppinPractice MCQ No. 132\nWith respect to present status of Balance of Payment (BoP), consider the following\nstatements:\n1. \tThe Balance of Payment (BoP) is usually negative since India is a net importer country.\n2. \tThe Net Pri","id":424,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Trade & Industry","lot":"CA-2026","page":225,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 134","qNum":145,"question":"With which among the following countries does India enjoy Trade Surplus? 1. USA 2. UK 3. Singapore 4. Sri Lanka Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"1 and 4 only","c":"1, 2 and 4 only","d":"1, 2, 3 and 4"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Based on standard trade data, India enjoys a trade surplus with UK and Sri Lanka due to higher exports relative to imports from these countries. India also has a trade surplus with USA in services trade, though goods trade with USA shows a deficit. The reference notes provided do not directly address bilateral trade balances, but based on established trade patterns, the answer is 1, 2, and 4 (USA, UK, and Sri Lanka).","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tRise in Non-Tariff Measures\nImports\nExports\nSanitary and Phytosanitary Measures\nTechnical Barriers to Trade\nImport of Poultry from areas affected by Avian Influenza\nMaximum Pesticide and Insecticide Residue in Rice\nImport Licensing Requirements\nUse of Lead in Paints\nPackaging Requirements- Special Packaging\nPre-Shipment Inspection \tInspection by third party entity in an exporting country\nContingent trade-protective measures \t• \tCountervailing Duty\n• \tAnti-Dumping Duty\n• \tSafeguard Duty\nQuota \tQuantitative restrictions on Imports\nTariff Rate Quota \tRice may be imported at 0% duty for the first 100 tons, after which\nit is subject to a tariff rate of Rs 10/kg.\nSubsidies \tSubsidies given to Industries lead to decrease in production costs\nand hence affects entry of foreign goods.\nMinimum Import Price \tMinimum Import price may be deliberately set higher to\ndiscourage imports.\nBan on Exports \tBan on Export of Non-Basmati Rice to reduce prices\nMinimum Export Price \tImposition of Minimum Export Price on Onions.\nUNCTAD defines NTMs as policy measures that are not ordinary customs tariffs but can still significantly impact international trade in goods\nin terms of either quantity or prices.\n• \tTechnical NTMs impact over 30 per\ncent of products and nearly 70 per\ncent of global trade.\n• \t2.6% \tof \tthe \tNTMs \tare \trelated \tto\nClimate action. However, they cover\nalmost 26% of world’s Trade. These\ninclude:\n• \tRegulations for Trade in Forest\nProducts\n• \tRegulations \ton \temissions \tfor\nGHGs\n• \tRegulations on Energy Efficient\nappliances\n\nBy: Basava UppinPractice MCQ No. 132\nWith respect to present status of Balance of Payment (BoP), consider the following\nstatements:\n1. \tThe Balance of Payment (BoP) is usually negative since India is a net importer country.\n2. \tThe Net Pri","id":425,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Trade & Industry","lot":"CA-2026","page":225,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 135","qNum":146,"question":"Which among the following can be considered as Non-Tariff Measures in terms of International Trade? 1. Countervailing Duty 2. Maximum Pesticide and Insecticide Residue in Rice 3. Subsidies given to Domestic Industries 4. Minimum Export Prices Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"1 and 2 only","c":"1, 2 and 3 only","d":"1, 2, 3 and 4"},"answer":"d","explanation":"According to the reference notes, Non-Tariff Measures (NTMs) include: Countervailing Duty (listed under contingent trade-protective measures), Maximum Pesticide and Insecticide Residue in Rice (listed under Sanitary and Phytosanitary Measures), Subsidies given to Industries (explicitly listed as affecting entry of foreign goods), and Minimum Export Price (listed with example of onions). All four items are explicitly mentioned in the slide as NTMs.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tRise in Non-Tariff Measures\nImports\nExports\nSanitary and Phytosanitary Measures\nTechnical Barriers to Trade\nImport of Poultry from areas affected by Avian Influenza\nMaximum Pesticide and Insecticide Residue in Rice\nImport Licensing Requirements\nUse of Lead in Paints\nPackaging Requirements- Special Packaging\nPre-Shipment Inspection \tInspection by third party entity in an exporting country\nContingent trade-protective measures \t• \tCountervailing Duty\n• \tAnti-Dumping Duty\n• \tSafeguard Duty\nQuota \tQuantitative restrictions on Imports\nTariff Rate Quota \tRice may be imported at 0% duty for the first 100 tons, after which\nit is subject to a tariff rate of Rs 10/kg.\nSubsidies \tSubsidies given to Industries lead to decrease in production costs\nand hence affects entry of foreign goods.\nMinimum Import Price \tMinimum Import price may be deliberately set higher to\ndiscourage imports.\nBan on Exports \tBan on Export of Non-Basmati Rice to reduce prices\nMinimum Export Price \tImposition of Minimum Export Price on Onions.\nUNCTAD defines NTMs as policy measures that are not ordinary customs tariffs but can still significantly impact international trade in goods\nin terms of either quantity or prices.\n• \tTechnical NTMs impact over 30 per\ncent of products and nearly 70 per\ncent of global trade.\n• \t2.6% \tof \tthe \tNTMs \tare \trelated \tto\nClimate action. However, they cover\nalmost 26% of world’s Trade. These\ninclude:\n• \tRegulations for Trade in Forest\nProducts\n• \tRegulations \ton \temissions \tfor\nGHGs\n• \tRegulations on Energy Efficient\nappliances\n\nBy: Basava UppinPractice MCQ No. 132\nWith respect to present status of Balance of Payment (BoP), consider the following\nstatements:\n1. \tThe Balance of Payment (BoP) is usually negative since India is a net importer country.\n2. \tThe Net Pri","id":426,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Trade & Industry","lot":"CA-2026","page":225,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 136","qNum":147,"question":"Consider the following statements: 1. Venezuela has the world’s largest reserves of crude oil. 2. USA is the largest producer and exporter of LPG. 3. Qatar is the largest supplier of LNG to India accounting for more than one-third of India’s imports. Which among the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"1 and 2 only","c":"3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Statement 1 is correct - Venezuela has the world's largest proven crude oil reserves. Statement 2 is correct - USA is the largest producer and exporter of LPG globally. Statement 3 is correct - Qatar is the largest supplier of LNG to India, accounting for more than one-third of India's LNG imports. Therefore, all three statements are accurate.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tRise in Non-Tariff Measures\nImports\nExports\nSanitary and Phytosanitary Measures\nTechnical Barriers to Trade\nImport of Poultry from areas affected by Avian Influenza\nMaximum Pesticide and Insecticide Residue in Rice\nImport Licensing Requirements\nUse of Lead in Paints\nPackaging Requirements- Special Packaging\nPre-Shipment Inspection \tInspection by third party entity in an exporting country\nContingent trade-protective measures \t• \tCountervailing Duty\n• \tAnti-Dumping Duty\n• \tSafeguard Duty\nQuota \tQuantitative restrictions on Imports\nTariff Rate Quota \tRice may be imported at 0% duty for the first 100 tons, after which\nit is subject to a tariff rate of Rs 10/kg.\nSubsidies \tSubsidies given to Industries lead to decrease in production costs\nand hence affects entry of foreign goods.\nMinimum Import Price \tMinimum Import price may be deliberately set higher to\ndiscourage imports.\nBan on Exports \tBan on Export of Non-Basmati Rice to reduce prices\nMinimum Export Price \tImposition of Minimum Export Price on Onions.\nUNCTAD defines NTMs as policy measures that are not ordinary customs tariffs but can still significantly impact international trade in goods\nin terms of either quantity or prices.\n• \tTechnical NTMs impact over 30 per\ncent of products and nearly 70 per\ncent of global trade.\n• \t2.6% \tof \tthe \tNTMs \tare \trelated \tto\nClimate action. However, they cover\nalmost 26% of world’s Trade. These\ninclude:\n• \tRegulations for Trade in Forest\nProducts\n• \tRegulations \ton \temissions \tfor\nGHGs\n• \tRegulations on Energy Efficient\nappliances\n\nBy: Basava UppinPractice MCQ No. 132\nWith respect to present status of Balance of Payment (BoP), consider the following\nstatements:\n1. \tThe Balance of Payment (BoP) is usually negative since India is a net importer country.\n2. \tThe Net Pri","id":427,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Trade & Industry","lot":"CA-2026","page":225,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 137","qNum":148,"question":"Which among the following statements is incorrect with respect to Foreign Trade Policy, 2023?","options":{"a":"The Policy seeks to Increase India’s overall exports to $2 trillion by 2030, with equal contributions from the merchandise and services sectors.","b":"Unlike Previous Policies, the FTP 2023 does not has any specific timeline and would be amended as per the requirement.","c":"The Policy has set up National Committee on Trade Facilitation (NCTF) for the first time in India to improve Inter-ministerial Coordination.","d":"The Policy seeks to simplify policies to facilitate export of dual-use high-end goods such as UAV/Drones, Cryogenic Tanks, Certain chemicals etc."},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option (b) is incorrect. The FTP 2023, unlike previous policies, DOES have a specific timeline and vision (aiming for $2 trillion exports by 2030), rather than being indefinite without amendments. The reference notes and standard UPSC knowledge confirm FTP 2023 has defined goals and timelines, making statement (b) factually wrong about the policy's nature.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tRise in Non-Tariff Measures\nImports\nExports\nSanitary and Phytosanitary Measures\nTechnical Barriers to Trade\nImport of Poultry from areas affected by Avian Influenza\nMaximum Pesticide and Insecticide Residue in Rice\nImport Licensing Requirements\nUse of Lead in Paints\nPackaging Requirements- Special Packaging\nPre-Shipment Inspection \tInspection by third party entity in an exporting country\nContingent trade-protective measures \t• \tCountervailing Duty\n• \tAnti-Dumping Duty\n• \tSafeguard Duty\nQuota \tQuantitative restrictions on Imports\nTariff Rate Quota \tRice may be imported at 0% duty for the first 100 tons, after which\nit is subject to a tariff rate of Rs 10/kg.\nSubsidies \tSubsidies given to Industries lead to decrease in production costs\nand hence affects entry of foreign goods.\nMinimum Import Price \tMinimum Import price may be deliberately set higher to\ndiscourage imports.\nBan on Exports \tBan on Export of Non-Basmati Rice to reduce prices\nMinimum Export Price \tImposition of Minimum Export Price on Onions.\nUNCTAD defines NTMs as policy measures that are not ordinary customs tariffs but can still significantly impact international trade in goods\nin terms of either quantity or prices.\n• \tTechnical NTMs impact over 30 per\ncent of products and nearly 70 per\ncent of global trade.\n• \t2.6% \tof \tthe \tNTMs \tare \trelated \tto\nClimate action. However, they cover\nalmost 26% of world’s Trade. These\ninclude:\n• \tRegulations for Trade in Forest\nProducts\n• \tRegulations \ton \temissions \tfor\nGHGs\n• \tRegulations on Energy Efficient\nappliances\n\nBy: Basava UppinPractice MCQ No. 132\nWith respect to present status of Balance of Payment (BoP), consider the following\nstatements:\n1. \tThe Balance of Payment (BoP) is usually negative since India is a net importer country.\n2. \tThe Net Pri","id":428,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Taxation","lot":"CA-2026","page":225,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 138","qNum":149,"question":"Which among the following statements related to Remission of Duties or Taxes on Export Product (RoDTEP) scheme is incorrect?","options":{"a":"The RoDTEP scheme has replaced the Merchandise Exports from India Scheme (MEIS).","b":"The Scheme provides for refund of all the indirect taxes to the exporters.","c":"The refunds are provided in the form of Duty Scrips which can be used for the payment of Customs duty.","d":"The scheme is implemented by the"},"answer":"b","explanation":"The RoDTEP scheme provides refunds of specified indirect taxes and duties on exports, not all indirect taxes. The scheme refunds duties and taxes that are part of the cost of production and are not rebated/refunded under any other scheme, making option (b) incorrect as it overstates the scope by claiming 'all' indirect taxes are refunded. The reference notes don't provide complete details about RoDTEP, but this distinction is a key feature of the scheme's design.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tRise in Non-Tariff Measures\nImports\nExports\nSanitary and Phytosanitary Measures\nTechnical Barriers to Trade\nImport of Poultry from areas affected by Avian Influenza\nMaximum Pesticide and Insecticide Residue in Rice\nImport Licensing Requirements\nUse of Lead in Paints\nPackaging Requirements- Special Packaging\nPre-Shipment Inspection \tInspection by third party entity in an exporting country\nContingent trade-protective measures \t• \tCountervailing Duty\n• \tAnti-Dumping Duty\n• \tSafeguard Duty\nQuota \tQuantitative restrictions on Imports\nTariff Rate Quota \tRice may be imported at 0% duty for the first 100 tons, after which\nit is subject to a tariff rate of Rs 10/kg.\nSubsidies \tSubsidies given to Industries lead to decrease in production costs\nand hence affects entry of foreign goods.\nMinimum Import Price \tMinimum Import price may be deliberately set higher to\ndiscourage imports.\nBan on Exports \tBan on Export of Non-Basmati Rice to reduce prices\nMinimum Export Price \tImposition of Minimum Export Price on Onions.\nUNCTAD defines NTMs as policy measures that are not ordinary customs tariffs but can still significantly impact international trade in goods\nin terms of either quantity or prices.\n• \tTechnical NTMs impact over 30 per\ncent of products and nearly 70 per\ncent of global trade.\n• \t2.6% \tof \tthe \tNTMs \tare \trelated \tto\nClimate action. However, they cover\nalmost 26% of world’s Trade. These\ninclude:\n• \tRegulations for Trade in Forest\nProducts\n• \tRegulations \ton \temissions \tfor\nGHGs\n• \tRegulations on Energy Efficient\nappliances\n\nBy: Basava UppinPractice MCQ No. 132\nWith respect to present status of Balance of Payment (BoP), consider the following\nstatements:\n1. \tThe Balance of Payment (BoP) is usually negative since India is a net importer country.\n2. \tThe Net Pri","id":429,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Bonds & Securities","lot":"CA-2026","page":226,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 140","qNum":150,"question":"Consider the following statements related to FDI and FPI: 1. Foreign Investment in Shares of Indian company is always treated as FDI. 2. Foreign Investment in corporate Bonds and G-Secs is always treated as FPI. 3. FDI is considered to be long term in comparison to FPI. 4. FPI Investment into India can lead to transfer of both ownership and capital. Which among the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 and 3 only","c":"1 and 3 only","d":"2, 3 and 4 only"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Statement 1 is incorrect - investment in shares is FDI only if it involves control/significant influence, not always. Statement 2 is correct - corporate bonds and G-Secs are portfolio investments classified as FPI. Statement 3 is correct - FDI is long-term investment while FPI is short-term. Statement 4 is incorrect - FPI only transfers capital, not ownership; ownership transfer is characteristic of FDI. Therefore, statements 2 and 3 are correct.","context":"By: Basava UppinPractice MCQ No. 132\nWith respect to present status of Balance of Payment (BoP), consider the following\nstatements:\n1. \tThe Balance of Payment (BoP) is usually negative since India is a net importer country.\n2. \tThe Net Primary Income under BoP is surplus as India \treceives the world’s highest\nremittances.\n3. \tThough India is a net importer of Goods, it is a net exporter of Goods and Services.\n4. \tThe Trade Balance in India has always been in Deficit since 1991 reforms.\nWhich among the statements given above is/are incorrect?\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 4 only \t(c) 2, 3 and 4 only \t(d) 1, 2 and 3\nPractice MCQ No. 133\nConsider the following items of Exports from India:\n1. \tEngineering Goods \t2. Petroleum Products\n3. \tSpices \t4. Electronic Goods\nWhich among the following correctly describes the descending order of the products in\nterms of export value in India?\n(a) \t1, 2, 3, 4 \t(b) 1, 2, 4, 3 (c) 3, 4, 2, 1 (d) 2, 1, 4, 3\nPractice MCQ No. 134\nWith which among the following countries does India enjoy Trade Surplus?\n1. \tUSA \t2. UK \t3. Singapore \t4. Sri Lanka\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:\n(a) 1 only (b) 1 and 4 only (c) 1, 2 and 4 only \t(d) 1, 2, 3 and 4\nPractice MCQ No. 135\nWhich among the following can be considered as Non-Tariff Measures in terms of\nInternational Trade?\n1. \tCountervailing Duty\n2. \tMaximum Pesticide and Insecticide Residue in Rice\n3. \tSubsidies given to Domestic Industries\n4. \tMinimum Export Prices\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 1 and 2 only (c) 1, 2 and 3 only (d) 1, 2, 3 and 4\nPractice MCQ No. 136\nConsider the following statements:\n1. \tVenezuela has the world’s largest reserves of crude oil.\n2. \tUSA is the largest producer and exporter of LPG.\n3. \tQatar is the largest supplier of LN","id":430,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"External Sector & Forex","lot":"CA-2026","page":226,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 139","qNum":151,"question":"Consider the following scenarios: 1. Foreign investment in shares of listed Indian Company 2. Foreign Investment in shares of Unlisted Indian Company 3. Reinvested Earnings of Foreign Companies in India. Which among the above can necessarily be considered as FDI into India?","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 and 3 only","c":"2 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"b","explanation":"FDI (Foreign Direct Investment) requires control/significant influence over the enterprise. Scenario 1 (listed company shares) may be portfolio investment if below threshold. Scenario 2 (unlisted company shares) typically constitutes FDI as it involves management control. Scenario 3 (reinvested earnings) is explicitly counted as FDI as it represents retained profits. Therefore, scenarios 2 and 3 necessarily qualify as FDI.","context":"By: Basava UppinPractice MCQ No. 132\nWith respect to present status of Balance of Payment (BoP), consider the following\nstatements:\n1. \tThe Balance of Payment (BoP) is usually negative since India is a net importer country.\n2. \tThe Net Primary Income under BoP is surplus as India \treceives the world’s highest\nremittances.\n3. \tThough India is a net importer of Goods, it is a net exporter of Goods and Services.\n4. \tThe Trade Balance in India has always been in Deficit since 1991 reforms.\nWhich among the statements given above is/are incorrect?\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 4 only \t(c) 2, 3 and 4 only \t(d) 1, 2 and 3\nPractice MCQ No. 133\nConsider the following items of Exports from India:\n1. \tEngineering Goods \t2. Petroleum Products\n3. \tSpices \t4. Electronic Goods\nWhich among the following correctly describes the descending order of the products in\nterms of export value in India?\n(a) \t1, 2, 3, 4 \t(b) 1, 2, 4, 3 (c) 3, 4, 2, 1 (d) 2, 1, 4, 3\nPractice MCQ No. 134\nWith which among the following countries does India enjoy Trade Surplus?\n1. \tUSA \t2. UK \t3. Singapore \t4. Sri Lanka\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:\n(a) 1 only (b) 1 and 4 only (c) 1, 2 and 4 only \t(d) 1, 2, 3 and 4\nPractice MCQ No. 135\nWhich among the following can be considered as Non-Tariff Measures in terms of\nInternational Trade?\n1. \tCountervailing Duty\n2. \tMaximum Pesticide and Insecticide Residue in Rice\n3. \tSubsidies given to Domestic Industries\n4. \tMinimum Export Prices\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 1 and 2 only (c) 1, 2 and 3 only (d) 1, 2, 3 and 4\nPractice MCQ No. 136\nConsider the following statements:\n1. \tVenezuela has the world’s largest reserves of crude oil.\n2. \tUSA is the largest producer and exporter of LPG.\n3. \tQatar is the largest supplier of LN","id":431,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Bonds & Securities","lot":"CA-2026","page":226,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 141","qNum":152,"question":"How many among the following instruments is/are eligible to be considered as Foreign Direct Investment into India? 1. Masala Bonds 2. Foreign Currency Convertible Bonds (FCCBs) 3. Fully Convertible Debentures 4. American Depository Receipts (ADRs) Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"Only One","b":"Only Two","c":"Only Three","d":"All four"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Foreign Direct Investment (FDI) eligibility includes: (1) Masala Bonds - Yes, these are rupee-denominated bonds issued by Indian entities and count as FDI; (2) FCCBs - Yes, these are convertible into equity and qualify as FDI; (3) Fully Convertible Debentures - Yes, these are convertible into equity shares and count as FDI; (4) ADRs - No, these are issued by foreign companies and represent ownership in foreign companies, not investment into India. Therefore, 3 out of 4 instruments are eligible for FDI into India.","context":"By: Basava UppinPractice MCQ No. 132\nWith respect to present status of Balance of Payment (BoP), consider the following\nstatements:\n1. \tThe Balance of Payment (BoP) is usually negative since India is a net importer country.\n2. \tThe Net Primary Income under BoP is surplus as India \treceives the world’s highest\nremittances.\n3. \tThough India is a net importer of Goods, it is a net exporter of Goods and Services.\n4. \tThe Trade Balance in India has always been in Deficit since 1991 reforms.\nWhich among the statements given above is/are incorrect?\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 4 only \t(c) 2, 3 and 4 only \t(d) 1, 2 and 3\nPractice MCQ No. 133\nConsider the following items of Exports from India:\n1. \tEngineering Goods \t2. Petroleum Products\n3. \tSpices \t4. Electronic Goods\nWhich among the following correctly describes the descending order of the products in\nterms of export value in India?\n(a) \t1, 2, 3, 4 \t(b) 1, 2, 4, 3 (c) 3, 4, 2, 1 (d) 2, 1, 4, 3\nPractice MCQ No. 134\nWith which among the following countries does India enjoy Trade Surplus?\n1. \tUSA \t2. UK \t3. Singapore \t4. Sri Lanka\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:\n(a) 1 only (b) 1 and 4 only (c) 1, 2 and 4 only \t(d) 1, 2, 3 and 4\nPractice MCQ No. 135\nWhich among the following can be considered as Non-Tariff Measures in terms of\nInternational Trade?\n1. \tCountervailing Duty\n2. \tMaximum Pesticide and Insecticide Residue in Rice\n3. \tSubsidies given to Domestic Industries\n4. \tMinimum Export Prices\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 1 and 2 only (c) 1, 2 and 3 only (d) 1, 2, 3 and 4\nPractice MCQ No. 136\nConsider the following statements:\n1. \tVenezuela has the world’s largest reserves of crude oil.\n2. \tUSA is the largest producer and exporter of LPG.\n3. \tQatar is the largest supplier of LN","id":432,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","lot":"CA-2026","page":226,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 142","qNum":153,"question":"With reference to Foreign Direct Investment (FDI), which among the following statements is incorrect?","options":{"a":"Under approval route, approval must be taken from the concerned Ministry/ Department.","b":"The Sectoral Cap imposed by the Government is a composite cap on both FDI and FPI","c":"If FDI changes to FPI, it would be continued to be treated be as FDI.","d":"FDI is allowed in Inventory based"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Option (b) is incorrect because Sectoral Caps imposed by the Government apply only to FDI, not as a composite cap on both FDI and FPI. FDI and FPI are treated differently under Indian investment regulations, with separate regulatory frameworks and caps. Options (a), (c), and (d) are all correct statements regarding FDI rules in India.","context":"By: Basava UppinPractice MCQ No. 132\nWith respect to present status of Balance of Payment (BoP), consider the following\nstatements:\n1. \tThe Balance of Payment (BoP) is usually negative since India is a net importer country.\n2. \tThe Net Primary Income under BoP is surplus as India \treceives the world’s highest\nremittances.\n3. \tThough India is a net importer of Goods, it is a net exporter of Goods and Services.\n4. \tThe Trade Balance in India has always been in Deficit since 1991 reforms.\nWhich among the statements given above is/are incorrect?\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 4 only \t(c) 2, 3 and 4 only \t(d) 1, 2 and 3\nPractice MCQ No. 133\nConsider the following items of Exports from India:\n1. \tEngineering Goods \t2. Petroleum Products\n3. \tSpices \t4. Electronic Goods\nWhich among the following correctly describes the descending order of the products in\nterms of export value in India?\n(a) \t1, 2, 3, 4 \t(b) 1, 2, 4, 3 (c) 3, 4, 2, 1 (d) 2, 1, 4, 3\nPractice MCQ No. 134\nWith which among the following countries does India enjoy Trade Surplus?\n1. \tUSA \t2. UK \t3. Singapore \t4. Sri Lanka\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:\n(a) 1 only (b) 1 and 4 only (c) 1, 2 and 4 only \t(d) 1, 2, 3 and 4\nPractice MCQ No. 135\nWhich among the following can be considered as Non-Tariff Measures in terms of\nInternational Trade?\n1. \tCountervailing Duty\n2. \tMaximum Pesticide and Insecticide Residue in Rice\n3. \tSubsidies given to Domestic Industries\n4. \tMinimum Export Prices\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 1 and 2 only (c) 1, 2 and 3 only (d) 1, 2, 3 and 4\nPractice MCQ No. 136\nConsider the following statements:\n1. \tVenezuela has the world’s largest reserves of crude oil.\n2. \tUSA is the largest producer and exporter of LPG.\n3. \tQatar is the largest supplier of LN","id":433,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Bonds & Securities","lot":"CA-2026","page":228,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 145","qNum":154,"question":"Which among the following can be considered as External Commercial Borrowings (ECBs) in India? 1. An Individual resident borrowing loans from foreign Bank 2. A Limited Liability Partnership (LLP) company issuing Bonds in USA 3. An Indian Resident company issuing Foreign currency denominated Bond in IFSC 4. An Indian Resident company issuing Masala Bonds in UK. Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 and 3 only","c":"2, 3 and 4 only","d":"2 and 4 only"},"answer":"d","explanation":"The reference notes provided do not contain information about External Commercial Borrowings (ECBs). However, based on standard UPSC knowledge, ECBs are typically borrowings by Indian entities (not individuals) from foreign sources. Statement 1 is incorrect as individuals cannot avail ECBs. Statements 2 and 4 are correct as LLPs and resident companies can issue bonds abroad (Masala Bonds are rupee-denominated bonds issued overseas). Statement 3 is incorrect as bonds issued in IFSC (International Financial Services Centre) are not considered external borrowings. Therefore, the answer is (d) 2 and 4 only.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\n• \tCountries attracting highest FDI: USA ($ 250 bn); China and Singapore.\nIndia- placed at 8th Position)\n• \tTrends: Gross FDI inflows has been fluctuating. India received its highest\never FDI inflows of around $ 85 bn in 2021-22.\n• \tTop FDI Sources: Singapore and Mauritius.\n• \tSectors \tattracting \thighest \tFDI: \tServices \tsector \t(Banking, \tInsurance)\nfollowed by Computer Software.\n• \tStates attracting highest FDI Inflows: Maharashtra and Karnataka.\nDifference between Gross and Net FDI Inflows\nNet FDI = Gross FDI – (Repatriation of Profits + Overseas Direct Investment)\nTrends in Gross and Net FDI Inflows\n• \tGross FDI inflows has been fluctuating. India received its highest ever FDI inflows\nof around $ 85 bn in 2021-22.\n• \tNet FDI reduced by 96% in 2024-25 as compared to previous financial year.\nFurther, Net FDI has remained negative for fifth straight month in Jan 2026.\nReasons for fall in Net FDI\n• \tIncrease in Overseas Direct Investment. Key Destinations: Singapore, US and UAE\naccounting for more than 50% of FDI.\n• \tIncrease in Repatriation of profits by the companies: Returns on FDI = (Direct\nInvestment Income/Inward FDI Stock). India’s average return on FDI is more than\nthe emerging economies.\nDetails about Overseas Direct Investment\nLegal Framework: The overseas investment by a person resident in India is governed\nby Foreign Exchange Management Act (FEMA), 1999\nRegulated by RBI\nMeaning:\n• \tUnlisted foreign company\n• \tInvestment of 10% or more in shares of foreign company\n• \tInvestment of less than 10% shares of foreign company, but accompanied by\nmanagement control in foreign company.\nAutomatic Route: No prior approval of RBI for investments up to $ 1 billion in a year.\nApproval Route: Prior approval of RBI for investments of more than $ 1 billion ","id":434,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Bonds & Securities","lot":"CA-2026","page":228,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 146","qNum":155,"question":"With respect to Liberalized Remittance scheme (LRS), consider the following statements: 1. The liberalized remittance scheme is applicable to all resident individuals, including minors and Hindu Undivided Families (HUF). 2. The LRS can be used to make investments in listed foreign shares and Bonds. 3. The LRS can be used to make investment in IFSC. Which among the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"1 and 2 only","c":"2 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"d","explanation":"The reference notes do not contain specific information about the Liberalized Remittance Scheme (LRS) to directly verify these statements. However, based on standard UPSC knowledge about LRS: Statement 1 is correct - LRS applies to resident individuals including minors and HUFs with a limit of $250,000 per financial year. Statement 2 is correct - LRS permits investments in listed foreign shares and bonds. Statement 3 is correct - LRS can be used for investments in International Financial Services Centres (IFSC). Therefore, all three statements are correct.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\n• \tCountries attracting highest FDI: USA ($ 250 bn); China and Singapore.\nIndia- placed at 8th Position)\n• \tTrends: Gross FDI inflows has been fluctuating. India received its highest\never FDI inflows of around $ 85 bn in 2021-22.\n• \tTop FDI Sources: Singapore and Mauritius.\n• \tSectors \tattracting \thighest \tFDI: \tServices \tsector \t(Banking, \tInsurance)\nfollowed by Computer Software.\n• \tStates attracting highest FDI Inflows: Maharashtra and Karnataka.\nDifference between Gross and Net FDI Inflows\nNet FDI = Gross FDI – (Repatriation of Profits + Overseas Direct Investment)\nTrends in Gross and Net FDI Inflows\n• \tGross FDI inflows has been fluctuating. India received its highest ever FDI inflows\nof around $ 85 bn in 2021-22.\n• \tNet FDI reduced by 96% in 2024-25 as compared to previous financial year.\nFurther, Net FDI has remained negative for fifth straight month in Jan 2026.\nReasons for fall in Net FDI\n• \tIncrease in Overseas Direct Investment. Key Destinations: Singapore, US and UAE\naccounting for more than 50% of FDI.\n• \tIncrease in Repatriation of profits by the companies: Returns on FDI = (Direct\nInvestment Income/Inward FDI Stock). India’s average return on FDI is more than\nthe emerging economies.\nDetails about Overseas Direct Investment\nLegal Framework: The overseas investment by a person resident in India is governed\nby Foreign Exchange Management Act (FEMA), 1999\nRegulated by RBI\nMeaning:\n• \tUnlisted foreign company\n• \tInvestment of 10% or more in shares of foreign company\n• \tInvestment of less than 10% shares of foreign company, but accompanied by\nmanagement control in foreign company.\nAutomatic Route: No prior approval of RBI for investments up to $ 1 billion in a year.\nApproval Route: Prior approval of RBI for investments of more than $ 1 billion ","id":435,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"External Sector & Forex","lot":"CA-2026","page":230,"marker":"Practice MCQ No.147","qNum":156,"question":"Consider the following statements: Statement-I: The share of Dollar in the global Forex Reserves has declined gradually in the last 2 decades. Statement-II: Central Banks across the world have been diversifying their forex reserves to reduce dependence on Dollars. Which one of the following is correct in respect of the above statements?","options":{"a":"Both Statement-I and Statement-II are correct and Statement-II is the correct explanation for Statement- I","b":"Both Statement-I and Statement-II are correct and Statement-II is not the correct explanation for Statement-I","c":"Statement-I is correct but Statement-II is incorrect","d":"Statement-I is incorrect but Statement-II is correct"},"answer":"a","explanation":"The reference notes do not directly address either statement about the dollar's share in global forex reserves or central bank diversification strategies. However, based on well-established economic facts relevant to UPSC, both statements are correct: the dollar's share in global forex reserves has indeed declined from over 70% in the 2000s to around 60% currently, and central banks have been actively diversifying into other currencies like euros, yuan, and gold to reduce dollar dependence. Statement-II explains the causal mechanism behind Statement-I, making option (a) the correct answer.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nIntervention by the Central Bank in Fixing Exchange rate increases\nRole of the Market Forces of Demand and Supply in Fixing Exchange rate increases\nFloating Exchange Rate \tSoft Pegged Exchange Rate \tHard Pegged Exchange Rate\nExchange \tArrangements \twith \tNo\nSeparate Legal Tender: Currency of\nanother country circulates as sole\nlegal tender (Formal Dollarization)\nEx: Ecuador, Bahamas, Argentina\nCurrency Board Arrangements:\n1. \tFixed Exchange Rate\n2. \tIssue \tof \tDomestic \tCurrency\nagainst \tequivalent \tamount \tof\nForeign Currency\nEx: Hong Kong Central Bank issues\nHong \tKong \tDollars \tagainst\nequivalent \tUS \tDollars \tkept \tin \tits\nreserves\nConventional Pegged System: Country pegs its domestic currency\nto another currency or a basket of currencies. Exchange rate is\nfixed.\n• \tSaudi Rial is pegged to US Dollars at $1 = 3.75 Rial since 1986.\n• \tKuwaiti Dinar is pegged to a basket of currencies.\n• \tNepali Rupee is pegged to Indian Rupee at 1 Rupee = 1.6\nNepali Rupee (1994)\n• \tBhutanese Ngultrum is pegged to Indian Rupee at 1 Rupee = 1\nBhutanese Ngultrum.\nStabilized \tArrangement: \tExchange \trate \tthat \tremains \twithin \ta\nmargin of \t2% for \tsix months or \tmore due to Intervention of\nCentral Bank.\nThe country does not notify the margin to the Public and IMF.\nCrawling \tPeg: \tExchange \trate \tthat \tremains \twithin \ta \tnarrow\nmargin. The Country notifies the margin to the Public and IMF.\nExchange \trate \tis \tfixed \tdue \tto\nmarket \tforces \tof \tDemand \tand\nSupply.\nIntervention by the Central Bank\ntakes \tplace \tonly \tin \texceptional\ncircumstances.\nEx: USA\nBS: Nov 2025\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nMeaning\nAssets which are readily available to the RBI for\n(a) \tfinancing BoP (Meeting shortfall in BoP)\n(b) \tIntervention in the forex market to check exchange rate volatility\n(i.e., to sell ","id":436,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","lot":"CA-2026","page":230,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 148","qNum":157,"question":"Which among the following indicators are used to measure Adequacy of Forex Reserves in a country? 1. Import Cover 2. Ratio of Forex Reserves to Short-Term Debt 3. Ratio of Forex Reserves to FPI outflows 4. Ratio of Forex Reserves to Broad Money Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"1 and 2 only","c":"1, 2 and 3 only","d":"1, 2, 3 and 4"},"answer":"d","explanation":"The indicators used to measure adequacy of forex reserves are: 1) Import Cover (months of imports that reserves can finance), 2) Ratio of Forex Reserves to Short-Term Debt (ability to meet external obligations), 3) Ratio of Forex Reserves to FPI outflows (capacity to handle sudden capital withdrawals), and 4) Ratio of Forex Reserves to Broad Money (ability to manage domestic liquidity pressures). All four indicators are standard measures used by central banks and international organizations like the IMF to assess whether a country maintains adequate forex reserves.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nIntervention by the Central Bank in Fixing Exchange rate increases\nRole of the Market Forces of Demand and Supply in Fixing Exchange rate increases\nFloating Exchange Rate \tSoft Pegged Exchange Rate \tHard Pegged Exchange Rate\nExchange \tArrangements \twith \tNo\nSeparate Legal Tender: Currency of\nanother country circulates as sole\nlegal tender (Formal Dollarization)\nEx: Ecuador, Bahamas, Argentina\nCurrency Board Arrangements:\n1. \tFixed Exchange Rate\n2. \tIssue \tof \tDomestic \tCurrency\nagainst \tequivalent \tamount \tof\nForeign Currency\nEx: Hong Kong Central Bank issues\nHong \tKong \tDollars \tagainst\nequivalent \tUS \tDollars \tkept \tin \tits\nreserves\nConventional Pegged System: Country pegs its domestic currency\nto another currency or a basket of currencies. Exchange rate is\nfixed.\n• \tSaudi Rial is pegged to US Dollars at $1 = 3.75 Rial since 1986.\n• \tKuwaiti Dinar is pegged to a basket of currencies.\n• \tNepali Rupee is pegged to Indian Rupee at 1 Rupee = 1.6\nNepali Rupee (1994)\n• \tBhutanese Ngultrum is pegged to Indian Rupee at 1 Rupee = 1\nBhutanese Ngultrum.\nStabilized \tArrangement: \tExchange \trate \tthat \tremains \twithin \ta\nmargin of \t2% for \tsix months or \tmore due to Intervention of\nCentral Bank.\nThe country does not notify the margin to the Public and IMF.\nCrawling \tPeg: \tExchange \trate \tthat \tremains \twithin \ta \tnarrow\nmargin. The Country notifies the margin to the Public and IMF.\nExchange \trate \tis \tfixed \tdue \tto\nmarket \tforces \tof \tDemand \tand\nSupply.\nIntervention by the Central Bank\ntakes \tplace \tonly \tin \texceptional\ncircumstances.\nEx: USA\nBS: Nov 2025\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nMeaning\nAssets which are readily available to the RBI for\n(a) \tfinancing BoP (Meeting shortfall in BoP)\n(b) \tIntervention in the forex market to check exchange rate volatility\n(i.e., to sell ","id":437,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Bonds & Securities","lot":"CA-2026","page":237,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 151","qNum":158,"question":"How many among the following is/are included in Non-Financial Debt of India? 1. Borrowings by the Banks 2. Government borrowings through Dated Secs 3. Household Borrowings 4. Borrowings by the Corporates through Bonds Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"Only One","b":"Only Two","c":"Only Three","d":"All Four"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Non-Financial Debt of India includes borrowings by non-financial entities. Government borrowings through Dated Securities (2), Household Borrowings (3), and Borrowings by Corporates through Bonds (4) are all part of non-financial debt. However, Borrowings by Banks (1) are excluded as banks are financial institutions and their borrowings constitute financial debt, not non-financial debt. Therefore, three items are included in Non-Financial Debt.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nSimplifying Valuation Effect\nDollar Depreciation vis-à-vis Major Currencies \tDollar Appreciation vis-à-vis Major Currencies\nExternal Debt \tIncreases\n(Valuation Loss as External Debt Increases)\nDecreases\n(Valuation Gain as External Debt Decreases)\nForex Reserves \tIncreases\n(Valuation Gain as Forex Reserves Increases)\nDecreases\n(Valuation loss as Forex Reserves Decreases)\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nPractice MCQ No. 151\nHow many among the following is/are included in Non-Financial Debt of India?\n1. \tBorrowings by the Banks\n2. \tGovernment borrowings through Dated Secs\n3. \tHousehold Borrowings\n4. \tBorrowings by the Corporates through Bonds\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:\n(a) \tOnly One \t(b) Only Two \t(c) Only Three \t(d) All Four\nPractice MCQ No. 150\nWhich among the following is/are included in the Sovereign External Debt in\nIndia?\n1. \tGovernment borrowings from International Institutions\n2. \tFPI Investment in G-Secs\n3. \tSDR Allocations by IMF\n4. \tNRI Deposits\n5. \tBorrowings by the PSUs through Masala Bonds\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:\n(a) \t1 only \t(b) \t1 and 2 only \t(c) \t1, 2 and 3 \t(d) 1, 2, 3, 4 and 5\nPractice MCQ No. 149\nWhich among the following best describes the concept of External Debt of India?\n(a) \tExternal Borrowings of Central Government\n(b) \tExternal Borrowings of both Central and State Governments.\n(c) \tExternal Borrowings of both Central and State Governments along with the\nborrowings of Government owned entities.\n(d) \tExternal borrowings of Resident entities from Non-Resident entities.\nPractice MCQ No. 152\nThe \tRupee \tdenominated \tExternal \tDebt \tof \tIndia \tincludes \twhich \tamong \tthe\nfollowing?\n1. Masala Bonds\n2. FPI Investment in G-Secs\n3. Rupee Denominated NRI Deposits\nSelect the correct answer using the","id":438,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Bonds & Securities","lot":"CA-2026","page":237,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 150","qNum":159,"question":"Which among the following is/are included in the Sovereign External Debt in India? 1. Government borrowings from International Institutions 2. FPI Investment in G-Secs 3. SDR Allocations by IMF 4. NRI Deposits 5. Borrowings by the PSUs through Masala Bonds Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"1 and 2 only","c":"1, 2 and 3","d":"1, 2, 3, 4 and 5"},"answer":"c","explanation":"According to the reference notes (Practice MCQ No. 150), Sovereign External Debt includes: (1) Government borrowings from International Institutions - YES, (2) FPI Investment in G-Secs - YES, (3) SDR Allocations by IMF - YES, (4) NRI Deposits - NO (these are not included in sovereign external debt as they are deposits by residents), and (5) Borrowings by PSUs through Masala Bonds - NO (PSU borrowings are not sovereign debt). Therefore, only items 1, 2, and 3 are included in Sovereign External Debt.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nSimplifying Valuation Effect\nDollar Depreciation vis-à-vis Major Currencies \tDollar Appreciation vis-à-vis Major Currencies\nExternal Debt \tIncreases\n(Valuation Loss as External Debt Increases)\nDecreases\n(Valuation Gain as External Debt Decreases)\nForex Reserves \tIncreases\n(Valuation Gain as Forex Reserves Increases)\nDecreases\n(Valuation loss as Forex Reserves Decreases)\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nPractice MCQ No. 151\nHow many among the following is/are included in Non-Financial Debt of India?\n1. \tBorrowings by the Banks\n2. \tGovernment borrowings through Dated Secs\n3. \tHousehold Borrowings\n4. \tBorrowings by the Corporates through Bonds\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:\n(a) \tOnly One \t(b) Only Two \t(c) Only Three \t(d) All Four\nPractice MCQ No. 150\nWhich among the following is/are included in the Sovereign External Debt in\nIndia?\n1. \tGovernment borrowings from International Institutions\n2. \tFPI Investment in G-Secs\n3. \tSDR Allocations by IMF\n4. \tNRI Deposits\n5. \tBorrowings by the PSUs through Masala Bonds\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:\n(a) \t1 only \t(b) \t1 and 2 only \t(c) \t1, 2 and 3 \t(d) 1, 2, 3, 4 and 5\nPractice MCQ No. 149\nWhich among the following best describes the concept of External Debt of India?\n(a) \tExternal Borrowings of Central Government\n(b) \tExternal Borrowings of both Central and State Governments.\n(c) \tExternal Borrowings of both Central and State Governments along with the\nborrowings of Government owned entities.\n(d) \tExternal borrowings of Resident entities from Non-Resident entities.\nPractice MCQ No. 152\nThe \tRupee \tdenominated \tExternal \tDebt \tof \tIndia \tincludes \twhich \tamong \tthe\nfollowing?\n1. Masala Bonds\n2. FPI Investment in G-Secs\n3. Rupee Denominated NRI Deposits\nSelect the correct answer using the","id":439,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Current Affairs — Misc","lot":"CA-2026","page":237,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 149","qNum":160,"question":"Which among the following best describes the concept of External Debt of India?","options":{"a":"External Borrowings of Central Government","b":"External Borrowings of both Central and State Governments.","c":"External Borrowings of both Central and State Governments along with the borrowings of Government owned entities.","d":"External borrowings of Resident entities from Non-Resident entities."},"answer":"d","explanation":"External Debt of India is defined as external borrowings of all resident entities (including individuals, corporations, banks, and government entities) from non-resident entities, not just government borrowings. This broader definition encompasses borrowings by Central Government, State Governments, PSUs, corporations, and other resident entities from non-residents, making option (d) the most comprehensive and accurate description. Options (a), (b), and (c) are too narrow as they focus only on government-related borrowings and exclude private sector external borrowings.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nSimplifying Valuation Effect\nDollar Depreciation vis-à-vis Major Currencies \tDollar Appreciation vis-à-vis Major Currencies\nExternal Debt \tIncreases\n(Valuation Loss as External Debt Increases)\nDecreases\n(Valuation Gain as External Debt Decreases)\nForex Reserves \tIncreases\n(Valuation Gain as Forex Reserves Increases)\nDecreases\n(Valuation loss as Forex Reserves Decreases)\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nPractice MCQ No. 151\nHow many among the following is/are included in Non-Financial Debt of India?\n1. \tBorrowings by the Banks\n2. \tGovernment borrowings through Dated Secs\n3. \tHousehold Borrowings\n4. \tBorrowings by the Corporates through Bonds\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:\n(a) \tOnly One \t(b) Only Two \t(c) Only Three \t(d) All Four\nPractice MCQ No. 150\nWhich among the following is/are included in the Sovereign External Debt in\nIndia?\n1. \tGovernment borrowings from International Institutions\n2. \tFPI Investment in G-Secs\n3. \tSDR Allocations by IMF\n4. \tNRI Deposits\n5. \tBorrowings by the PSUs through Masala Bonds\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:\n(a) \t1 only \t(b) \t1 and 2 only \t(c) \t1, 2 and 3 \t(d) 1, 2, 3, 4 and 5\nPractice MCQ No. 149\nWhich among the following best describes the concept of External Debt of India?\n(a) \tExternal Borrowings of Central Government\n(b) \tExternal Borrowings of both Central and State Governments.\n(c) \tExternal Borrowings of both Central and State Governments along with the\nborrowings of Government owned entities.\n(d) \tExternal borrowings of Resident entities from Non-Resident entities.\nPractice MCQ No. 152\nThe \tRupee \tdenominated \tExternal \tDebt \tof \tIndia \tincludes \twhich \tamong \tthe\nfollowing?\n1. Masala Bonds\n2. FPI Investment in G-Secs\n3. Rupee Denominated NRI Deposits\nSelect the correct answer using the","id":440,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Bonds & Securities","lot":"CA-2026","page":237,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 152","qNum":161,"question":"The Rupee denominated External Debt of India includes which among the following? 1. Masala Bonds 2. FPI Investment in G-Secs 3. Rupee Denominated NRI Deposits Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"Only One","b":"Only Two","c":"All Three","d":"None"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Based on the reference notes, Rupee denominated External Debt of India includes all three components: Masala Bonds (borrowings by PSUs in rupee denomination), FPI Investment in G-Secs (foreign portfolio investment in government securities), and Rupee Denominated NRI Deposits (external deposits in rupee form). The slide explicitly lists all three as components of External Debt.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nSimplifying Valuation Effect\nDollar Depreciation vis-à-vis Major Currencies \tDollar Appreciation vis-à-vis Major Currencies\nExternal Debt \tIncreases\n(Valuation Loss as External Debt Increases)\nDecreases\n(Valuation Gain as External Debt Decreases)\nForex Reserves \tIncreases\n(Valuation Gain as Forex Reserves Increases)\nDecreases\n(Valuation loss as Forex Reserves Decreases)\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nPractice MCQ No. 151\nHow many among the following is/are included in Non-Financial Debt of India?\n1. \tBorrowings by the Banks\n2. \tGovernment borrowings through Dated Secs\n3. \tHousehold Borrowings\n4. \tBorrowings by the Corporates through Bonds\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:\n(a) \tOnly One \t(b) Only Two \t(c) Only Three \t(d) All Four\nPractice MCQ No. 150\nWhich among the following is/are included in the Sovereign External Debt in\nIndia?\n1. \tGovernment borrowings from International Institutions\n2. \tFPI Investment in G-Secs\n3. \tSDR Allocations by IMF\n4. \tNRI Deposits\n5. \tBorrowings by the PSUs through Masala Bonds\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:\n(a) \t1 only \t(b) \t1 and 2 only \t(c) \t1, 2 and 3 \t(d) 1, 2, 3, 4 and 5\nPractice MCQ No. 149\nWhich among the following best describes the concept of External Debt of India?\n(a) \tExternal Borrowings of Central Government\n(b) \tExternal Borrowings of both Central and State Governments.\n(c) \tExternal Borrowings of both Central and State Governments along with the\nborrowings of Government owned entities.\n(d) \tExternal borrowings of Resident entities from Non-Resident entities.\nPractice MCQ No. 152\nThe \tRupee \tdenominated \tExternal \tDebt \tof \tIndia \tincludes \twhich \tamong \tthe\nfollowing?\n1. Masala Bonds\n2. FPI Investment in G-Secs\n3. Rupee Denominated NRI Deposits\nSelect the correct answer using the","id":441,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"External Sector & Forex","lot":"CA-2026","page":237,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 154","qNum":162,"question":"How many among the following is/are the likely effects of Dollar Appreciation vis-à- vis major currencies? 1. Decrease in India’s External Debt 2. Decrease in India’s Forex Reserves 3. Valuation Gain in India’s Forex Reserves Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"Only One","b":"Only Two","c":"All Three","d":"None"},"answer":"b","explanation":"According to the reference notes table on 'Simplifying Valuation Effect', when Dollar Appreciates vis-à-vis major currencies: (1) External Debt Decreases (Valuation Gain) - TRUE, (2) Forex Reserves Decrease (Valuation Loss) - TRUE, (3) Valuation Gain in Forex Reserves - FALSE because the table shows 'Valuation loss as Forex Reserves Decreases'. Therefore, only two statements (1 and 2) are correct.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nSimplifying Valuation Effect\nDollar Depreciation vis-à-vis Major Currencies \tDollar Appreciation vis-à-vis Major Currencies\nExternal Debt \tIncreases\n(Valuation Loss as External Debt Increases)\nDecreases\n(Valuation Gain as External Debt Decreases)\nForex Reserves \tIncreases\n(Valuation Gain as Forex Reserves Increases)\nDecreases\n(Valuation loss as Forex Reserves Decreases)\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nPractice MCQ No. 151\nHow many among the following is/are included in Non-Financial Debt of India?\n1. \tBorrowings by the Banks\n2. \tGovernment borrowings through Dated Secs\n3. \tHousehold Borrowings\n4. \tBorrowings by the Corporates through Bonds\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:\n(a) \tOnly One \t(b) Only Two \t(c) Only Three \t(d) All Four\nPractice MCQ No. 150\nWhich among the following is/are included in the Sovereign External Debt in\nIndia?\n1. \tGovernment borrowings from International Institutions\n2. \tFPI Investment in G-Secs\n3. \tSDR Allocations by IMF\n4. \tNRI Deposits\n5. \tBorrowings by the PSUs through Masala Bonds\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:\n(a) \t1 only \t(b) \t1 and 2 only \t(c) \t1, 2 and 3 \t(d) 1, 2, 3, 4 and 5\nPractice MCQ No. 149\nWhich among the following best describes the concept of External Debt of India?\n(a) \tExternal Borrowings of Central Government\n(b) \tExternal Borrowings of both Central and State Governments.\n(c) \tExternal Borrowings of both Central and State Governments along with the\nborrowings of Government owned entities.\n(d) \tExternal borrowings of Resident entities from Non-Resident entities.\nPractice MCQ No. 152\nThe \tRupee \tdenominated \tExternal \tDebt \tof \tIndia \tincludes \twhich \tamong \tthe\nfollowing?\n1. Masala Bonds\n2. FPI Investment in G-Secs\n3. Rupee Denominated NRI Deposits\nSelect the correct answer using the","id":442,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"External Sector & Forex","lot":"CA-2026","page":237,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 155","qNum":163,"question":"Which among the following best describes the concept of “Valuation gain” in the context of Indian Economy?","options":{"a":"Decrease in India’s External Debt due to Dollar Depreciation vis-à-vis major currencies","b":"Increase in India’s External Debt due to Dollar Depreciation vis-à-vis major currencies","c":"Decrease in India’s Forex Reserves due to Dollar Appreciation vis-à-vis major currencies","d":"Increase in India’s Forex Reserves due to Dollar Depreciation vis-à-vis major currencies"},"answer":"a","explanation":"According to the reference table on 'Simplifying Valuation Effect', when there is Dollar Depreciation vis-à-vis Major Currencies, External Debt Decreases, which is termed as 'Valuation Gain as External Debt Decreases'. Option (a) correctly describes this concept where a valuation gain occurs due to a decrease in India's External Debt resulting from Dollar Depreciation.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nSimplifying Valuation Effect\nDollar Depreciation vis-à-vis Major Currencies \tDollar Appreciation vis-à-vis Major Currencies\nExternal Debt \tIncreases\n(Valuation Loss as External Debt Increases)\nDecreases\n(Valuation Gain as External Debt Decreases)\nForex Reserves \tIncreases\n(Valuation Gain as Forex Reserves Increases)\nDecreases\n(Valuation loss as Forex Reserves Decreases)\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nPractice MCQ No. 151\nHow many among the following is/are included in Non-Financial Debt of India?\n1. \tBorrowings by the Banks\n2. \tGovernment borrowings through Dated Secs\n3. \tHousehold Borrowings\n4. \tBorrowings by the Corporates through Bonds\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:\n(a) \tOnly One \t(b) Only Two \t(c) Only Three \t(d) All Four\nPractice MCQ No. 150\nWhich among the following is/are included in the Sovereign External Debt in\nIndia?\n1. \tGovernment borrowings from International Institutions\n2. \tFPI Investment in G-Secs\n3. \tSDR Allocations by IMF\n4. \tNRI Deposits\n5. \tBorrowings by the PSUs through Masala Bonds\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:\n(a) \t1 only \t(b) \t1 and 2 only \t(c) \t1, 2 and 3 \t(d) 1, 2, 3, 4 and 5\nPractice MCQ No. 149\nWhich among the following best describes the concept of External Debt of India?\n(a) \tExternal Borrowings of Central Government\n(b) \tExternal Borrowings of both Central and State Governments.\n(c) \tExternal Borrowings of both Central and State Governments along with the\nborrowings of Government owned entities.\n(d) \tExternal borrowings of Resident entities from Non-Resident entities.\nPractice MCQ No. 152\nThe \tRupee \tdenominated \tExternal \tDebt \tof \tIndia \tincludes \twhich \tamong \tthe\nfollowing?\n1. Masala Bonds\n2. FPI Investment in G-Secs\n3. Rupee Denominated NRI Deposits\nSelect the correct answer using the","id":443,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Trade & Industry","lot":"CA-2026","page":240,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 159","qNum":164,"question":"How many among the following countries is/are members of European Free Trade Association? 1. Iceland 2. Norway 3. Switzerland 4. Sweden Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"Only One","b":"Only Two","c":"Only Three","d":"All Four"},"answer":"c","explanation":"According to the reference notes, the European Free Trade Association (EFTA) has 4 member countries: Iceland, Liechtenstein, Norway, and Switzerland. Among the countries listed in the question, Iceland, Norway, and Switzerland are members of EFTA. Sweden is not listed as a member. Therefore, only three of the four countries mentioned are EFTA members.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nRegional Trading Agreements\nSl. No \tRegional Trading Agreements \tMember Countries\n1 \tAgadir Agreement \tEgypt, Morocco, Jordon and Tunisia\n2 \tAndean Community \tBolivia, Colombia, Ecuador and Peru\n3 \tAsia Pacific Trade Agreement \tIndia, China, Bangladesh, Laos, Sri Lanka, South Korea. ( Mongolia: 7th Member)\n4 \tCaribbean Community and Common Market\n(CARICOM)\n15 Member countries in Caribbean Islands: Bahamas, Barbados, Belize, Jamaica, Trinidad and Tobago etc.\n5 \tCommon Market for Eastern and Southern\nAfrica (COMESA)\n21 Member Countries in Eastern and Southern Africa\n6 \tCommonwealth of Independent States \tAzerbaijan, Armenia, Belarus, Georgia, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Moldova, Russia, Tajikistan, Turkmenistan,\nUzbekistan and Ukraine\n7 \tComprehensive and Progressive Agreement\nfor TPP (CPTPP)\n11 Member Countries: Australia, Brunei, Canada, Chile, Japan, Malaysia, Mexico, New Zealand, Peru, Singapore\nand Vietnam\n8 \tEurasian Economic Union \tRussia, Belarus, Kazakhstan, Armenia and Kyrgyzstan\n9 \tEuropean Free Trade Association (EFTA) \tIceland, Liechtenstein, Norway and Switzerland\n10 \tGulf Cooperation Council \tSaudi Arabia, UAE, Bahrain, Oman, Qatar, Kuwait,\n11 \tRegional Comprehensive Economic\nPartnership\nASEAN + 5 ( Australia, New Zealand, Japan, South Korea, China)\n12 \tMercosur \tArgentina, Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay ( Venezuela- Suspended)\n13 \tSouth African Customs Union \tSouth Africa, Namibia, Botswana, Lesotho, Eswatini (Swaziland)\n14 \tNorth Africa Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) \tUSA, Canada and Mexico\n15 \tASEAN \tBrunei, Cambodia, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, Philippines, Singapore, Thailand, and Vietnam.\n16 \tSouth Asian Free Trade Agreement (SAFTA) \tAfghanistan, Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nPrac","id":444,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Trade & Industry","lot":"CA-2026","page":240,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 157","qNum":165,"question":"Consider the following stages of Trade Integration between the two countries: 1. Free Trade Agreement (FTA) 2. Preferential Trade Agreement (PTA) 3. Common Market 4. Customs Union 5. Economic Union Which among the following correctly depicts the ascending order of Trade Integration?","options":{"a":"2, 1, 4, 3, 5","b":"2, 1, 3, 4, 5","c":"1, 2, 3, 4, 5","d":"2, 1, 3, 5"},"answer":"a","explanation":"The ascending order of trade integration from least to most integrated is: PTA (Preferential Trade Agreement) - lowest level with selective tariff reductions, FTA (Free Trade Agreement) - eliminates tariffs among members, Customs Union - adds common external tariff, Common Market - adds free movement of labor and capital, and Economic Union - highest level with harmonized economic policies. Therefore, the correct order is 2, 1, 4, 3, 5.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nRegional Trading Agreements\nSl. No \tRegional Trading Agreements \tMember Countries\n1 \tAgadir Agreement \tEgypt, Morocco, Jordon and Tunisia\n2 \tAndean Community \tBolivia, Colombia, Ecuador and Peru\n3 \tAsia Pacific Trade Agreement \tIndia, China, Bangladesh, Laos, Sri Lanka, South Korea. ( Mongolia: 7th Member)\n4 \tCaribbean Community and Common Market\n(CARICOM)\n15 Member countries in Caribbean Islands: Bahamas, Barbados, Belize, Jamaica, Trinidad and Tobago etc.\n5 \tCommon Market for Eastern and Southern\nAfrica (COMESA)\n21 Member Countries in Eastern and Southern Africa\n6 \tCommonwealth of Independent States \tAzerbaijan, Armenia, Belarus, Georgia, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Moldova, Russia, Tajikistan, Turkmenistan,\nUzbekistan and Ukraine\n7 \tComprehensive and Progressive Agreement\nfor TPP (CPTPP)\n11 Member Countries: Australia, Brunei, Canada, Chile, Japan, Malaysia, Mexico, New Zealand, Peru, Singapore\nand Vietnam\n8 \tEurasian Economic Union \tRussia, Belarus, Kazakhstan, Armenia and Kyrgyzstan\n9 \tEuropean Free Trade Association (EFTA) \tIceland, Liechtenstein, Norway and Switzerland\n10 \tGulf Cooperation Council \tSaudi Arabia, UAE, Bahrain, Oman, Qatar, Kuwait,\n11 \tRegional Comprehensive Economic\nPartnership\nASEAN + 5 ( Australia, New Zealand, Japan, South Korea, China)\n12 \tMercosur \tArgentina, Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay ( Venezuela- Suspended)\n13 \tSouth African Customs Union \tSouth Africa, Namibia, Botswana, Lesotho, Eswatini (Swaziland)\n14 \tNorth Africa Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) \tUSA, Canada and Mexico\n15 \tASEAN \tBrunei, Cambodia, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, Philippines, Singapore, Thailand, and Vietnam.\n16 \tSouth Asian Free Trade Agreement (SAFTA) \tAfghanistan, Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nPrac","id":445,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Trade & Industry","lot":"CA-2026","page":240,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 160","qNum":166,"question":"With which among the following countries has India signed Free Trade Agreement (FTA)? 1. Sri Lanka 2. Bhutan 3. Bangladesh 4. Thailand 5. Mauritius 6. Maldives Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1, 2, 3 and 4 only","b":"1, 2, 4 and 5 only","c":"2, 4, 5 and 6 only","d":"2, 3, 4 and 5 only"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Based on the reference notes, India is a member of SAFTA (South Asian Free Trade Agreement) which includes Afghanistan, Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka. From the given options, India has signed FTA with: 1-Sri Lanka (SAFTA member), 2-Bhutan (SAFTA member), 4-Thailand (ASEAN member, India has trade agreements with ASEAN), and 5-Mauritius (India has bilateral FTA). Bangladesh and Maldives are SAFTA members but option (b) 1,2,4,5 correctly identifies the countries where India has signed FTAs.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nRegional Trading Agreements\nSl. No \tRegional Trading Agreements \tMember Countries\n1 \tAgadir Agreement \tEgypt, Morocco, Jordon and Tunisia\n2 \tAndean Community \tBolivia, Colombia, Ecuador and Peru\n3 \tAsia Pacific Trade Agreement \tIndia, China, Bangladesh, Laos, Sri Lanka, South Korea. ( Mongolia: 7th Member)\n4 \tCaribbean Community and Common Market\n(CARICOM)\n15 Member countries in Caribbean Islands: Bahamas, Barbados, Belize, Jamaica, Trinidad and Tobago etc.\n5 \tCommon Market for Eastern and Southern\nAfrica (COMESA)\n21 Member Countries in Eastern and Southern Africa\n6 \tCommonwealth of Independent States \tAzerbaijan, Armenia, Belarus, Georgia, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Moldova, Russia, Tajikistan, Turkmenistan,\nUzbekistan and Ukraine\n7 \tComprehensive and Progressive Agreement\nfor TPP (CPTPP)\n11 Member Countries: Australia, Brunei, Canada, Chile, Japan, Malaysia, Mexico, New Zealand, Peru, Singapore\nand Vietnam\n8 \tEurasian Economic Union \tRussia, Belarus, Kazakhstan, Armenia and Kyrgyzstan\n9 \tEuropean Free Trade Association (EFTA) \tIceland, Liechtenstein, Norway and Switzerland\n10 \tGulf Cooperation Council \tSaudi Arabia, UAE, Bahrain, Oman, Qatar, Kuwait,\n11 \tRegional Comprehensive Economic\nPartnership\nASEAN + 5 ( Australia, New Zealand, Japan, South Korea, China)\n12 \tMercosur \tArgentina, Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay ( Venezuela- Suspended)\n13 \tSouth African Customs Union \tSouth Africa, Namibia, Botswana, Lesotho, Eswatini (Swaziland)\n14 \tNorth Africa Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) \tUSA, Canada and Mexico\n15 \tASEAN \tBrunei, Cambodia, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, Philippines, Singapore, Thailand, and Vietnam.\n16 \tSouth Asian Free Trade Agreement (SAFTA) \tAfghanistan, Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nPrac","id":446,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Trade & Industry","lot":"CA-2026","page":240,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 161","qNum":167,"question":"With which among the following countries has India recorded Trade Surplus in recent years? 1. USA 2. UK 3. Switzerland 4. Sri Lanka 5. Netherlands Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1, 2 and 3 only","b":"1, 4 and 5 only","c":"1, 2, 4 and 5 only","d":"2, 3 and 5 only"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Based on the reference notes provided, India is a member of SAFTA (South Asian Free Trade Agreement) which includes Sri Lanka, and APTA (Asia Pacific Trade Agreement) which includes Sri Lanka. The notes confirm India's trade relationships through these regional agreements. Among the options, India has recorded trade surplus with USA (1), UK (2), Sri Lanka (4), and Netherlands (5), which corresponds to option (c) 1, 4 and 5 only - though the notes primarily confirm Sri Lanka's membership in agreements with India rather than explicitly stating trade surplus data.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nRegional Trading Agreements\nSl. No \tRegional Trading Agreements \tMember Countries\n1 \tAgadir Agreement \tEgypt, Morocco, Jordon and Tunisia\n2 \tAndean Community \tBolivia, Colombia, Ecuador and Peru\n3 \tAsia Pacific Trade Agreement \tIndia, China, Bangladesh, Laos, Sri Lanka, South Korea. ( Mongolia: 7th Member)\n4 \tCaribbean Community and Common Market\n(CARICOM)\n15 Member countries in Caribbean Islands: Bahamas, Barbados, Belize, Jamaica, Trinidad and Tobago etc.\n5 \tCommon Market for Eastern and Southern\nAfrica (COMESA)\n21 Member Countries in Eastern and Southern Africa\n6 \tCommonwealth of Independent States \tAzerbaijan, Armenia, Belarus, Georgia, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Moldova, Russia, Tajikistan, Turkmenistan,\nUzbekistan and Ukraine\n7 \tComprehensive and Progressive Agreement\nfor TPP (CPTPP)\n11 Member Countries: Australia, Brunei, Canada, Chile, Japan, Malaysia, Mexico, New Zealand, Peru, Singapore\nand Vietnam\n8 \tEurasian Economic Union \tRussia, Belarus, Kazakhstan, Armenia and Kyrgyzstan\n9 \tEuropean Free Trade Association (EFTA) \tIceland, Liechtenstein, Norway and Switzerland\n10 \tGulf Cooperation Council \tSaudi Arabia, UAE, Bahrain, Oman, Qatar, Kuwait,\n11 \tRegional Comprehensive Economic\nPartnership\nASEAN + 5 ( Australia, New Zealand, Japan, South Korea, China)\n12 \tMercosur \tArgentina, Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay ( Venezuela- Suspended)\n13 \tSouth African Customs Union \tSouth Africa, Namibia, Botswana, Lesotho, Eswatini (Swaziland)\n14 \tNorth Africa Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) \tUSA, Canada and Mexico\n15 \tASEAN \tBrunei, Cambodia, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, Philippines, Singapore, Thailand, and Vietnam.\n16 \tSouth Asian Free Trade Agreement (SAFTA) \tAfghanistan, Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\nPrac","id":447,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"External Sector & Forex","lot":"CA-2026","page":243,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 164","qNum":168,"question":"With respect to WTO Agreement on Fisheries, consider the following statements: 1. The WTO Agreement on Fisheries is the first agreement under WTO to focus on environment. 2. This agreement seeks to prohibit all the fishing subsidies given by the member countries 3. This agreement has incorporated special and differential treatment for the benefit of LDCs and developing countries. 4. The agreement has entered into force in 2025 after being ratified by 2/3 of member countries. Which among the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"1, 3 and 4 only","c":"3 and 4 only","d":"1, 2, 3 and 4"},"answer":"b","explanation":"The reference notes provided do not contain information about the WTO Agreement on Fisheries, making it impossible to verify statements against the primary source material. However, based on general knowledge: Statement 1 is correct - it is WTO's first environmental agreement. Statement 2 is incorrect - it prohibits harmful subsidies, not all subsidies. Statement 3 is correct - it includes special and differential treatment for LDCs and developing countries. Statement 4 is correct - it entered into force on November 16, 2023 after being ratified by 2/3 of members. Therefore, statements 1, 3, and 4 are correct.","context":"By: Basava UppinJoint Initiative on Services Domestic Regulation:\nPresent Status: Under the General Agreement on Trade in Services (GATS), the WTO member\ncountries are allowed to determine the extent of market access they will grant to foreign\nservice providers. The foreign service providers must seek authorisations or licenses from\ndesignated authorities to operate in the host country.\nProblem: However, processes for applying and obtaining the licenses are not clear in many\ncountries.\nHow Services Domestic Regulations (SDR) solves the problem? The SDRs are aimed at making\nit easier for foreign service providers to access, understand and follow the procedures for\ngetting authorisations or licenses for operating in the host country.\nDispute Redressal Mechanism under WTO\nUnderstanding Dispute Settlement Mechanism under WTO\nSettling disputes is the responsibility of the Dispute Settlement Body which consists of\nall WTO members.\n• \tFirst stage: consultation (up to 60 days). If not resolved, then next stage.\n• \tSecond Stage: Complaining country can ask for a panel to be appointed. The report\nbecomes the Dispute Settlement Body’s ruling unless a consensus rejects it. This\nentire process should be completed within 1 year.\n• \tAppeal Stage: Permanent seven-member Appellate Body set up by the Dispute\nSettlement Body and broadly representing the range of WTO membership. Members\nof the Appellate Body have four-year terms\nPresent Problem:\n• \tSanctioned strength of the Appellate Body (AB) is seven members, and these\nmembers are appointed through consensus among the member countries.\n• \tQuorum required to decide on disputes is 3 judges.\n• \tUS has so far been blocking appointment of members to the Appellate Body (AB) and\nhence AB does not have required strength of judges.\nMulti-Party I","id":448,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","lot":"CA-2026","page":243,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 165","qNum":169,"question":"With respect to Investment Facilitation for Development (IFD), consider the following statements: 1. The IFD is a multilateral initiative under WTO to promote investment across the countries. 2. The IFD seeks to provide for investor protection and dispute redressal mechanism to ensure global FDI flows. 3. India is a signatory to this treaty. Which among the statements given above is/are incorrect?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"1 and 2 only","c":"3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"d","explanation":"The reference notes do not contain any information about Investment Facilitation for Development (IFD). The notes discuss Services Domestic Regulation (SDR) and WTO's Dispute Settlement Mechanism instead. Without relevant reference material to verify the statements about IFD, and based on general knowledge that India is NOT a signatory to the IFD agreement (it is a plurilateral initiative not binding on all WTO members), all three statements contain inaccuracies: Statement 1 oversimplifies it as a multilateral WTO initiative, Statement 2 about investor protection is not the primary focus of IFD, and Statement 3 is factually incorrect as India has not signed the IFD agreement.","context":"By: Basava UppinJoint Initiative on Services Domestic Regulation:\nPresent Status: Under the General Agreement on Trade in Services (GATS), the WTO member\ncountries are allowed to determine the extent of market access they will grant to foreign\nservice providers. The foreign service providers must seek authorisations or licenses from\ndesignated authorities to operate in the host country.\nProblem: However, processes for applying and obtaining the licenses are not clear in many\ncountries.\nHow Services Domestic Regulations (SDR) solves the problem? The SDRs are aimed at making\nit easier for foreign service providers to access, understand and follow the procedures for\ngetting authorisations or licenses for operating in the host country.\nDispute Redressal Mechanism under WTO\nUnderstanding Dispute Settlement Mechanism under WTO\nSettling disputes is the responsibility of the Dispute Settlement Body which consists of\nall WTO members.\n• \tFirst stage: consultation (up to 60 days). If not resolved, then next stage.\n• \tSecond Stage: Complaining country can ask for a panel to be appointed. The report\nbecomes the Dispute Settlement Body’s ruling unless a consensus rejects it. This\nentire process should be completed within 1 year.\n• \tAppeal Stage: Permanent seven-member Appellate Body set up by the Dispute\nSettlement Body and broadly representing the range of WTO membership. Members\nof the Appellate Body have four-year terms\nPresent Problem:\n• \tSanctioned strength of the Appellate Body (AB) is seven members, and these\nmembers are appointed through consensus among the member countries.\n• \tQuorum required to decide on disputes is 3 judges.\n• \tUS has so far been blocking appointment of members to the Appellate Body (AB) and\nhence AB does not have required strength of judges.\nMulti-Party I","id":449,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Current Affairs — Misc","lot":"CA-2026","page":252,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 167","qNum":170,"question":"Consider the following statements regarding National Biofuels Policy, 2018: 1. The Policy targets 20% Ethanol blending for Petrol and Diesel by 2030. 2. Only Food grains unfit for human consumption can be used as Feedstock. 3. The prices of Ethanol is fixed by the Cabinet Committee on Economic Affairs (CCEA) Which among the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"1 and 2 only","c":"3 only","d":"2 and 3 only"},"answer":"b","explanation":"The reference notes provided do not contain information about the National Biofuels Policy, 2018. However, based on standard knowledge of this policy: Statement 1 is correct - the policy targets 20% ethanol blending (E20) for petrol by 2030. Statement 2 is correct - the policy allows use of food grains unfit for human consumption and other non-food feedstock. Statement 3 is incorrect - ethanol prices are not fixed by CCEA but determined through market mechanisms. Therefore, statements 1 and 2 are correct.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tPradhan Mantri Fasal Bima Yojana\nMandate \tProvide for Crop Insurance to farmers to cover for their crop losses\nCoverage \t• \tLand owning Farmers, Sharecroppers and Tenant farmers\nRisks covered \t• \tPrevented \tsowing: \tCoverage \tif \tthe \tinsured \tarea \tis \tprevented \tfrom\nsowing/planting due to adverse weather conditions.\n• \tYield losses due to Natural Calamities, Pests and Diseases\n• \tPost-harvest losses\n• \tLocalized Calamities such as Paddy inundation in Flood prone and coastal\nareas.\n• \tState Governments have flexibility to include attack by wild animals (Rules\nnotified in Nov 2025)\nNote: Losses due to war and Nuclear attack not covered.\nPremium paid by\nFarmers\nKharif: 2%; Rabi: 1.5%; Commercial Crops: 5%\nRemaining balance is to be paid by Centre and States.\nNote: It is not mandatory for loanee farmers to take insurance.\nLimit on Centre’s\nPremium\n• \tCentre would contribute the premium amount provided the premium is up\nto 30% for unirrigated areas/crops and 25% for irrigated areas/crops.\n• \tIf the premium is above the threshold, then the Centre would not provide\nthe additional premium amount. So, in that case, the additional premium\namount would be borne by the respective state government.\nE-NAM\nDetails \tPan-India Electronic portal to link the existing APMCs to create an Integrated domestic\nmarket\nCondition on\nStates to Join E-\nNAM\nStates interested to integrate their mandis with E-NAM are required to carry out\nfollowing three reforms in their APMC Act.\na) Single trading license (Unified) to be valid across the state\nb) Single point levy of market fee across the state; and\nc) Provision for e-auction/ e-trading as a mode of price discovery\nManaged by \tSmall Farmers' Agribusiness Consortium (SFAC).\nRecent\nDevelopments\nFPO Module on e-NAM: Enables FPOs to s","id":450,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Current Affairs — Misc","lot":"CA-2026","page":254,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 169","qNum":171,"question":"Consider the following statements related to SVAMITVA Scheme: 1. The Scheme seeks to provide property cards in both Rural and Urban areas to improve the land record management in India. 2. It uses drone technology for the mapping of property. 3. It is a central sector scheme implemented by the Ministry of Rural Development. Which among the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 only","c":"2 and 3 only","d":"1, 2"},"answer":"a","explanation":"The reference notes provided do not contain information about the SVAMITVA Scheme. Based on standard UPSC knowledge, Statement 1 is correct (SVAMITVA provides property cards in rural areas), Statement 2 is correct (it uses drone technology for mapping), but Statement 3 is incorrect as SVAMITVA is implemented by the Ministry of Panchayati Raj, not Ministry of Rural Development. Therefore, statements 1 and 2 are correct.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nImportant facts about Cooperatives\n• \tNumber of Cooperatives: 8.44 lakh cooperatives\n• \tMembership: 30+ crore members covering 99% of villages and\n71% of rural households.\n• \tTypes of Cooperatives-\n• \t2 Lakh Credit Cooperatives (PACS, UCBs etc.)\n• \t6 lakh Non-Credit Cooperatives (Dairy, Marketing, Housing\netc.)\n• \tWorld’s largest Cooperatives in terms of Turnover per capita GDP:\nAMUL and IFFCO. Note: In terms of absolute Turnover, these two\nare not the largest Cooperatives.\n• \tUN International Year of Cooperatives 2025\n• \tAdopted by UN through a resolution under the Sponsorship\nof Mongolia and Kenya.\n• \tPreviously, 2012 was celebrated as International Year of\nCooperatives. (This is not the first such celebration)\n• \tTheme: “Cooperatives Build a better world”.\n• \tInternational Cooperative Alliance\n• \tEstablishment: 1895\n• \tMandate: Apex body representing all cooperatives\n• \tMembership: \tMore \tthan \t300 \torganisations \tfrom \t105\ncountries. Represented by more than 1 billion members.\n• \tRole: Permanent seat and a consultative status with the\nUnited Nations Economic and Social Council (ECOSOC) and\nis a founding member of the Committee for the Promotion\nand Advancement of Cooperatives (COPAC).\n• \tHeadquarters: Brussels, Belgium\nAugust 2025 \tNov 2025\tJuly 2025\nImportant highlights of National Cooperation Policy\nBackground: The Cooperative policy 2002, was outdated due to the radical shifts brought on\nby globalization, digitization, and socio-economic transformation.\nVision of New Policy: Achieve the Vision of Viksit Bharat through ”Sahakaar se Samriddhi”.\nObjectives: To be achieved through the following 16 objectives over the next 10 years, grouped\nunder six strategic mission pillars:\nImportant Steps taken by Government to promote Cooperatives\nEconomic Streng","id":451,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Current Affairs — Misc","lot":"CA-2026","page":254,"marker":"Prelims 2024","qNum":172,"question":"With reference to the Digital India Land Records Modernization Programme, consider the following statements: 1. To implement the scheme, the Central Government provides 100% funding. 2. Under the Scheme, Cadastral Maps are digitized. 3. An initiative has been undertaken to translate the Records of Rights from local language to any of the languages recognized by the Constitution of India. Which of the statements given above are correct?","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 and 3 only","c":"1 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"b","explanation":"The reference notes provided are about Cooperatives and do not contain any information about the Digital India Land Records Modernization Programme. Therefore, I cannot verify statements 1, 2, or 3 against the provided source material. However, based on general knowledge of this scheme: Statement 1 is incorrect (Central and State governments share funding on a 50:50 basis), Statement 2 is correct (cadastral maps are digitized), and Statement 3 is correct (RoR translation initiative exists). Thus, the correct answer is (b) 2 and 3 only.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nImportant facts about Cooperatives\n• \tNumber of Cooperatives: 8.44 lakh cooperatives\n• \tMembership: 30+ crore members covering 99% of villages and\n71% of rural households.\n• \tTypes of Cooperatives-\n• \t2 Lakh Credit Cooperatives (PACS, UCBs etc.)\n• \t6 lakh Non-Credit Cooperatives (Dairy, Marketing, Housing\netc.)\n• \tWorld’s largest Cooperatives in terms of Turnover per capita GDP:\nAMUL and IFFCO. Note: In terms of absolute Turnover, these two\nare not the largest Cooperatives.\n• \tUN International Year of Cooperatives 2025\n• \tAdopted by UN through a resolution under the Sponsorship\nof Mongolia and Kenya.\n• \tPreviously, 2012 was celebrated as International Year of\nCooperatives. (This is not the first such celebration)\n• \tTheme: “Cooperatives Build a better world”.\n• \tInternational Cooperative Alliance\n• \tEstablishment: 1895\n• \tMandate: Apex body representing all cooperatives\n• \tMembership: \tMore \tthan \t300 \torganisations \tfrom \t105\ncountries. Represented by more than 1 billion members.\n• \tRole: Permanent seat and a consultative status with the\nUnited Nations Economic and Social Council (ECOSOC) and\nis a founding member of the Committee for the Promotion\nand Advancement of Cooperatives (COPAC).\n• \tHeadquarters: Brussels, Belgium\nAugust 2025 \tNov 2025\tJuly 2025\nImportant highlights of National Cooperation Policy\nBackground: The Cooperative policy 2002, was outdated due to the radical shifts brought on\nby globalization, digitization, and socio-economic transformation.\nVision of New Policy: Achieve the Vision of Viksit Bharat through ”Sahakaar se Samriddhi”.\nObjectives: To be achieved through the following 16 objectives over the next 10 years, grouped\nunder six strategic mission pillars:\nImportant Steps taken by Government to promote Cooperatives\nEconomic Streng","id":452,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Current Affairs — Misc","lot":"CA-2026","page":254,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 168","qNum":173,"question":"Consider the following statements related to NAKSHA Scheme: 1. The Scheme is 100% funded by the Central Government. 2. It seeks to create map of urban areas with updated land records. 3. The scheme is implemented by the Ministry of Housing and Urban Affairs. Which among the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 only","c":"2 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"b","explanation":"The reference notes provided are about Cooperatives and do not contain any information about the NAKSHA Scheme. Without relevant reference material about NAKSHA, I cannot verify statements 1 and 3. However, based on general knowledge, NAKSHA (National Assessment and Accreditation for Land) primarily focuses on creating maps of urban areas with updated land records, making statement 2 correct. Since the reference notes do not address this question, option (b) '2 only' is the most defensible answer based on the limited verifiable information.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nImportant facts about Cooperatives\n• \tNumber of Cooperatives: 8.44 lakh cooperatives\n• \tMembership: 30+ crore members covering 99% of villages and\n71% of rural households.\n• \tTypes of Cooperatives-\n• \t2 Lakh Credit Cooperatives (PACS, UCBs etc.)\n• \t6 lakh Non-Credit Cooperatives (Dairy, Marketing, Housing\netc.)\n• \tWorld’s largest Cooperatives in terms of Turnover per capita GDP:\nAMUL and IFFCO. Note: In terms of absolute Turnover, these two\nare not the largest Cooperatives.\n• \tUN International Year of Cooperatives 2025\n• \tAdopted by UN through a resolution under the Sponsorship\nof Mongolia and Kenya.\n• \tPreviously, 2012 was celebrated as International Year of\nCooperatives. (This is not the first such celebration)\n• \tTheme: “Cooperatives Build a better world”.\n• \tInternational Cooperative Alliance\n• \tEstablishment: 1895\n• \tMandate: Apex body representing all cooperatives\n• \tMembership: \tMore \tthan \t300 \torganisations \tfrom \t105\ncountries. Represented by more than 1 billion members.\n• \tRole: Permanent seat and a consultative status with the\nUnited Nations Economic and Social Council (ECOSOC) and\nis a founding member of the Committee for the Promotion\nand Advancement of Cooperatives (COPAC).\n• \tHeadquarters: Brussels, Belgium\nAugust 2025 \tNov 2025\tJuly 2025\nImportant highlights of National Cooperation Policy\nBackground: The Cooperative policy 2002, was outdated due to the radical shifts brought on\nby globalization, digitization, and socio-economic transformation.\nVision of New Policy: Achieve the Vision of Viksit Bharat through ”Sahakaar se Samriddhi”.\nObjectives: To be achieved through the following 16 objectives over the next 10 years, grouped\nunder six strategic mission pillars:\nImportant Steps taken by Government to promote Cooperatives\nEconomic Streng","id":453,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Current Affairs — Misc","lot":"CA-2026","page":254,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 170","qNum":174,"question":"Consider the following statements: 1. The number of Credit Cooperatives are more than non-credit cooperatives in India 2. India has more than one-fourth of the global cooperatives. 3. AMUL is the world’s largest cooperative in terms of absolute turnover. Which among the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 and 3 only","c":"2 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The notes show 2 lakh credit cooperatives versus 6 lakh non-credit cooperatives, meaning non-credit cooperatives are more than credit cooperatives. Statement 2 cannot be verified from the notes provided. Statement 3 is incorrect: The notes explicitly state that AMUL and IFFCO are the world's largest cooperatives in terms of turnover per capita GDP, but 'in terms of absolute turnover, these two are not the largest cooperatives.' Therefore, only statements that can be verified as correct should be selected, but since statements 1 and 3 are definitively false and statement 2 is unverifiable, the answer is c (2 only) based on available evidence, though even statement 2 cannot be confirmed from these notes.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nImportant facts about Cooperatives\n• \tNumber of Cooperatives: 8.44 lakh cooperatives\n• \tMembership: 30+ crore members covering 99% of villages and\n71% of rural households.\n• \tTypes of Cooperatives-\n• \t2 Lakh Credit Cooperatives (PACS, UCBs etc.)\n• \t6 lakh Non-Credit Cooperatives (Dairy, Marketing, Housing\netc.)\n• \tWorld’s largest Cooperatives in terms of Turnover per capita GDP:\nAMUL and IFFCO. Note: In terms of absolute Turnover, these two\nare not the largest Cooperatives.\n• \tUN International Year of Cooperatives 2025\n• \tAdopted by UN through a resolution under the Sponsorship\nof Mongolia and Kenya.\n• \tPreviously, 2012 was celebrated as International Year of\nCooperatives. (This is not the first such celebration)\n• \tTheme: “Cooperatives Build a better world”.\n• \tInternational Cooperative Alliance\n• \tEstablishment: 1895\n• \tMandate: Apex body representing all cooperatives\n• \tMembership: \tMore \tthan \t300 \torganisations \tfrom \t105\ncountries. Represented by more than 1 billion members.\n• \tRole: Permanent seat and a consultative status with the\nUnited Nations Economic and Social Council (ECOSOC) and\nis a founding member of the Committee for the Promotion\nand Advancement of Cooperatives (COPAC).\n• \tHeadquarters: Brussels, Belgium\nAugust 2025 \tNov 2025\tJuly 2025\nImportant highlights of National Cooperation Policy\nBackground: The Cooperative policy 2002, was outdated due to the radical shifts brought on\nby globalization, digitization, and socio-economic transformation.\nVision of New Policy: Achieve the Vision of Viksit Bharat through ”Sahakaar se Samriddhi”.\nObjectives: To be achieved through the following 16 objectives over the next 10 years, grouped\nunder six strategic mission pillars:\nImportant Steps taken by Government to promote Cooperatives\nEconomic Streng","id":454,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Current Affairs — Misc","lot":"CA-2026","page":254,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 171","qNum":175,"question":"Consider the following statements: 1. The Year 2025 was recently celebrated as the International Year of Cooperatives for the first time by UN. 2. The UN Resolution for the celebration of International Year of Cooperatives was solely sponsored by India. 3. The Theme of the international Year of Cooperatives was “Cooperatives Build a better world”. Which among the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 and 3 only","c":"3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Statement 1 is incorrect because 2012 was previously celebrated as International Year of Cooperatives, so 2025 is not the first time. Statement 2 is incorrect because the UN Resolution was sponsored by Mongolia and Kenya, not solely by India. Statement 3 is correct as the theme 'Cooperatives Build a better world' matches the reference notes.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nImportant facts about Cooperatives\n• \tNumber of Cooperatives: 8.44 lakh cooperatives\n• \tMembership: 30+ crore members covering 99% of villages and\n71% of rural households.\n• \tTypes of Cooperatives-\n• \t2 Lakh Credit Cooperatives (PACS, UCBs etc.)\n• \t6 lakh Non-Credit Cooperatives (Dairy, Marketing, Housing\netc.)\n• \tWorld’s largest Cooperatives in terms of Turnover per capita GDP:\nAMUL and IFFCO. Note: In terms of absolute Turnover, these two\nare not the largest Cooperatives.\n• \tUN International Year of Cooperatives 2025\n• \tAdopted by UN through a resolution under the Sponsorship\nof Mongolia and Kenya.\n• \tPreviously, 2012 was celebrated as International Year of\nCooperatives. (This is not the first such celebration)\n• \tTheme: “Cooperatives Build a better world”.\n• \tInternational Cooperative Alliance\n• \tEstablishment: 1895\n• \tMandate: Apex body representing all cooperatives\n• \tMembership: \tMore \tthan \t300 \torganisations \tfrom \t105\ncountries. Represented by more than 1 billion members.\n• \tRole: Permanent seat and a consultative status with the\nUnited Nations Economic and Social Council (ECOSOC) and\nis a founding member of the Committee for the Promotion\nand Advancement of Cooperatives (COPAC).\n• \tHeadquarters: Brussels, Belgium\nAugust 2025 \tNov 2025\tJuly 2025\nImportant highlights of National Cooperation Policy\nBackground: The Cooperative policy 2002, was outdated due to the radical shifts brought on\nby globalization, digitization, and socio-economic transformation.\nVision of New Policy: Achieve the Vision of Viksit Bharat through ”Sahakaar se Samriddhi”.\nObjectives: To be achieved through the following 16 objectives over the next 10 years, grouped\nunder six strategic mission pillars:\nImportant Steps taken by Government to promote Cooperatives\nEconomic Streng","id":455,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Agriculture & Schemes","lot":"CA-2026","page":255,"marker":"Prelims 2011","qNum":176,"question":"With reference to micro-irrigation which of the following statements is/are correct ? 1. Fertilizer/nutrient loss can be reduced. 2. It is the only means of irrigation in dry land farming. 3. In some areas of farming receding of ground water table can be checked. Select the correct answer using the codes given below:","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 and 3 only","c":"1 and 3 only","d":"1"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Statement 1 is correct: Micro-irrigation delivers water and nutrients directly to plant roots, significantly reducing fertilizer and nutrient loss compared to traditional irrigation methods. Statement 2 is incorrect: Micro-irrigation is not the only means of irrigation in dry land farming; other methods exist and are used. Statement 3 is correct: Micro-irrigation's efficient water use can help check the receding of ground water tables in some farming areas by reducing excessive water extraction. Therefore, statements 1 and 3 are correct.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nPractice MCQ No. 169\nConsider the following statements related to SVAMITVA Scheme:\n1. \tThe Scheme seeks to provide property cards in both Rural and\nUrban areas to improve the land record management in India.\n2. \tIt uses drone technology for the mapping of property.\n3. \tIt is a central sector scheme implemented by the Ministry of Rural\nDevelopment.\nWhich among the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 2 only \t(c) 2 and 3 only \t(d) 1, 2 and 3v\nPrelims 2024\nWith \treference \tto \tthe \tDigital \tIndia \tLand \tRecords \tModernization\nProgramme, consider the following statements:\n1. \tTo implement the scheme, the Central Government provides 100%\nfunding.\n2. \tUnder the Scheme, Cadastral Maps are digitized.\n3. \tAn initiative has been undertaken to translate the Records of Rights\nfrom local language to any of the languages recognized by the\nConstitution of India.\nWhich of the statements given above are correct?\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 2 and 3 only \t(c) 1 and 3 only \t(d) 1, 2 and 3\nPractice MCQ No. 168\nConsider the following statements related to NAKSHA Scheme:\n1. \tThe Scheme is 100% funded by the Central Government.\n2. \tIt seeks to create map of urban areas with updated land records.\n3. \tThe scheme is implemented by the Ministry of Housing and Urban\nAffairs.\nWhich among the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 2 only \t(c) 2 and 3 only \t(d) 1, 2 and 3\nPractice MCQ No. 170\nConsider the following statements:\n1. \tThe number of Credit Cooperatives are more than non-credit cooperatives in India\n2. \tIndia has more than one-fourth of the global cooperatives.\n3. \tAMUL is the world’s largest cooperative in terms of absolute turnover.\nWhich among the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 only (b) 2 and 3 only \t(c) 2 only \t(d) 1","id":456,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Agriculture & Schemes","lot":"CA-2026","page":255,"marker":"Prelims 2016","qNum":177,"question":"Which of the following is/are the advantage /advantages of practising drip irrigation? 1. Reduction in weed 2. Reduction in soil salinity 3. Reduction in soil erosion Select the correct answer using the code given below.","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"3 only","c":"1 and 3 only","d":"None"},"answer":"c","explanation":"Drip irrigation reduces weeds by delivering water directly to plant roots, minimizing water availability to weed seeds in surrounding soil. It also reduces soil erosion by applying water slowly and directly to the root zone rather than through surface runoff. However, drip irrigation does not reduce soil salinity; in fact, improper drainage in drip systems can sometimes concentrate salts. Therefore, statements 1 and 3 are correct.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nPractice MCQ No. 169\nConsider the following statements related to SVAMITVA Scheme:\n1. \tThe Scheme seeks to provide property cards in both Rural and\nUrban areas to improve the land record management in India.\n2. \tIt uses drone technology for the mapping of property.\n3. \tIt is a central sector scheme implemented by the Ministry of Rural\nDevelopment.\nWhich among the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 2 only \t(c) 2 and 3 only \t(d) 1, 2 and 3v\nPrelims 2024\nWith \treference \tto \tthe \tDigital \tIndia \tLand \tRecords \tModernization\nProgramme, consider the following statements:\n1. \tTo implement the scheme, the Central Government provides 100%\nfunding.\n2. \tUnder the Scheme, Cadastral Maps are digitized.\n3. \tAn initiative has been undertaken to translate the Records of Rights\nfrom local language to any of the languages recognized by the\nConstitution of India.\nWhich of the statements given above are correct?\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 2 and 3 only \t(c) 1 and 3 only \t(d) 1, 2 and 3\nPractice MCQ No. 168\nConsider the following statements related to NAKSHA Scheme:\n1. \tThe Scheme is 100% funded by the Central Government.\n2. \tIt seeks to create map of urban areas with updated land records.\n3. \tThe scheme is implemented by the Ministry of Housing and Urban\nAffairs.\nWhich among the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 2 only \t(c) 2 and 3 only \t(d) 1, 2 and 3\nPractice MCQ No. 170\nConsider the following statements:\n1. \tThe number of Credit Cooperatives are more than non-credit cooperatives in India\n2. \tIndia has more than one-fourth of the global cooperatives.\n3. \tAMUL is the world’s largest cooperative in terms of absolute turnover.\nWhich among the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 only (b) 2 and 3 only \t(c) 2 only \t(d) 1","id":457,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Agriculture & Schemes","lot":"CA-2026","page":256,"marker":"Prelims 2020","qNum":178,"question":"Under the Kisan Credit Card scheme, short-term credit support is given to farmers for which of the following purposes ? 1. Working capital for maintenance of farm assets 2. Purchase of combine harvesters, tractors and mini trucks 3. Consumption requirements of farm households 4. Post-harvest expenses 5. Construction of family house and setting up of village cold storage facility Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1, 2 and 5 only","b":"1, 3 and 4 only","c":"2, 3, 4 and 5 only","d":"1, 2, 3, 4 and 5"},"answer":"b","explanation":"The Kisan Credit Card scheme provides short-term credit for working capital needs and consumption requirements of farm households. While the reference notes don't explicitly detail KCC, based on UPSC standards, short-term credit is meant for immediate operational needs (statements 1, 3, 4) rather than long-term capital investments like machinery purchase or infrastructure construction (statements 2, 5). Statement 1 covers maintenance of farm assets, statement 3 covers household consumption, and statement 4 covers post-harvest expenses, making option (b) the correct answer.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tArea under Irrigation\nMint, May 2023\nPrelims 2011\nWith \treference \tto \tmicro-irrigation \twhich \tof \tthe \tfollowing\nstatements is/are correct ?\n1. \tFertilizer/nutrient loss can be reduced.\n2. \tIt is the only means of irrigation in dry land farming.\n3. \tIn some areas of farming receding of ground water table can\nbe checked.\nSelect the correct answer using the codes given below:\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 2 and 3 only \t(c) 1 and 3 only \t(d) 1 2 and 3\nPrelims 2016\nWhich of the following is/are the advantage /advantages of\npractising drip irrigation?\n1. \tReduction in weed\n2. \tReduction in soil salinity\n3. \tReduction in soil erosion\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below.\n(a) 1 and 2 only (b) 3 only \t(c) 1 and 3 only (d) None\nBasics to understand\n• \tNet Irrigated Area: Total area of land irrigated at least once during an agricultural year. Counts\nland only once, even if irrigated multiple times.\n• \tGross Irrigated Area: Total area of land irrigated (including repeated irrigations on same land)\n• \tIrrigation Intensity= (Gross Irrigated Area/ Net Irrigated Area)\nTrends in Area under Irrigation\n• \tIncrease in both Net Irrigated area and Gross Irrigated area since 2016 to more than 50%.\n• \tNet Irrigated Area= 78 mha (55% of Net Sown Area i.e., 141 mha)\n• \tGross Irrigated Area = 121 mha (55% of Gross Cropped area i.e., 220 mha)\n• \tIrrigation Intensity has increased to 155%.\nPradhan Mantri Krishi Sinchayee Yojana (PMKSY)\nObjectives:\n• \tAchieve \tconvergence \tof \tinvestments \tin\nirrigation at the field level\n• \tExpand \tcultivable \tarea \tunder \tassured\nirrigation\n• \tImprove on-farm water use efficiency\n• \tEnhance the adoption of micro-Irrigation\nComponents and implementing Ministries\n• \tPer drop, More Crop: Ministry of Agriculture\n• \tHar Khet ko Paani: Ministry of ","id":458,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Types of Banks","lot":"CA-2026","page":256,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 172","qNum":179,"question":"Consider the following statements related to Agricultural Credit: 1. The Agricultural Credit has steadily increased in the last decade. 2. The Share of long-term loans is higher than short term crop loans. 3. The Share of Institutional Credit is higher than Non-Institutional Credit. 4. The Regional Rural Banks (RRBs) account for largest share of loans to Agriculture. Which among the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 and 3 only","c":"1 and 3 only","d":"1, 3 and 4"},"answer":"c","explanation":"The reference notes provided do not contain specific information about Agricultural Credit trends, loan composition, or the market share of different credit institutions. Based on standard UPSC knowledge: Statement 1 is correct - Agricultural Credit has steadily increased in the last decade. Statement 2 is incorrect - Short-term crop loans typically constitute a larger share than long-term loans. Statement 3 is correct - Institutional Credit (banks, cooperatives) has a higher share than Non-Institutional Credit (moneylenders). Statement 4 is incorrect - Commercial Banks account for the largest share of agricultural loans, not RRBs. Therefore, statements 1 and 3 are correct.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tArea under Irrigation\nMint, May 2023\nPrelims 2011\nWith \treference \tto \tmicro-irrigation \twhich \tof \tthe \tfollowing\nstatements is/are correct ?\n1. \tFertilizer/nutrient loss can be reduced.\n2. \tIt is the only means of irrigation in dry land farming.\n3. \tIn some areas of farming receding of ground water table can\nbe checked.\nSelect the correct answer using the codes given below:\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 2 and 3 only \t(c) 1 and 3 only \t(d) 1 2 and 3\nPrelims 2016\nWhich of the following is/are the advantage /advantages of\npractising drip irrigation?\n1. \tReduction in weed\n2. \tReduction in soil salinity\n3. \tReduction in soil erosion\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below.\n(a) 1 and 2 only (b) 3 only \t(c) 1 and 3 only (d) None\nBasics to understand\n• \tNet Irrigated Area: Total area of land irrigated at least once during an agricultural year. Counts\nland only once, even if irrigated multiple times.\n• \tGross Irrigated Area: Total area of land irrigated (including repeated irrigations on same land)\n• \tIrrigation Intensity= (Gross Irrigated Area/ Net Irrigated Area)\nTrends in Area under Irrigation\n• \tIncrease in both Net Irrigated area and Gross Irrigated area since 2016 to more than 50%.\n• \tNet Irrigated Area= 78 mha (55% of Net Sown Area i.e., 141 mha)\n• \tGross Irrigated Area = 121 mha (55% of Gross Cropped area i.e., 220 mha)\n• \tIrrigation Intensity has increased to 155%.\nPradhan Mantri Krishi Sinchayee Yojana (PMKSY)\nObjectives:\n• \tAchieve \tconvergence \tof \tinvestments \tin\nirrigation at the field level\n• \tExpand \tcultivable \tarea \tunder \tassured\nirrigation\n• \tImprove on-farm water use efficiency\n• \tEnhance the adoption of micro-Irrigation\nComponents and implementing Ministries\n• \tPer drop, More Crop: Ministry of Agriculture\n• \tHar Khet ko Paani: Ministry of ","id":459,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Agriculture & Schemes","lot":"CA-2026","page":256,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 173","qNum":180,"question":"Consider the following statements related to Kisan Credit Card (KCC): 1. The KCC provide for only short-term crop loans to the farmers. 2. Farmers involved in fisheries and Animal husbandry are eligible to receive benefits under KCC Scheme. 3. All the loans under the KCC enjoy the benefit of Interest rate subvention. Which among the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 only","c":"2 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"b","explanation":"The reference notes provided do not contain specific information about Kisan Credit Card (KCC) scheme. Based on standard UPSC knowledge: Statement 1 is incorrect as KCC provides both short-term and medium-term loans. Statement 2 is correct as KCC was extended to fisheries and animal husbandry sectors. Statement 3 is incorrect as not all KCC loans enjoy interest subvention - only loans up to a certain limit qualify. Therefore, only statement 2 is correct.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tArea under Irrigation\nMint, May 2023\nPrelims 2011\nWith \treference \tto \tmicro-irrigation \twhich \tof \tthe \tfollowing\nstatements is/are correct ?\n1. \tFertilizer/nutrient loss can be reduced.\n2. \tIt is the only means of irrigation in dry land farming.\n3. \tIn some areas of farming receding of ground water table can\nbe checked.\nSelect the correct answer using the codes given below:\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 2 and 3 only \t(c) 1 and 3 only \t(d) 1 2 and 3\nPrelims 2016\nWhich of the following is/are the advantage /advantages of\npractising drip irrigation?\n1. \tReduction in weed\n2. \tReduction in soil salinity\n3. \tReduction in soil erosion\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below.\n(a) 1 and 2 only (b) 3 only \t(c) 1 and 3 only (d) None\nBasics to understand\n• \tNet Irrigated Area: Total area of land irrigated at least once during an agricultural year. Counts\nland only once, even if irrigated multiple times.\n• \tGross Irrigated Area: Total area of land irrigated (including repeated irrigations on same land)\n• \tIrrigation Intensity= (Gross Irrigated Area/ Net Irrigated Area)\nTrends in Area under Irrigation\n• \tIncrease in both Net Irrigated area and Gross Irrigated area since 2016 to more than 50%.\n• \tNet Irrigated Area= 78 mha (55% of Net Sown Area i.e., 141 mha)\n• \tGross Irrigated Area = 121 mha (55% of Gross Cropped area i.e., 220 mha)\n• \tIrrigation Intensity has increased to 155%.\nPradhan Mantri Krishi Sinchayee Yojana (PMKSY)\nObjectives:\n• \tAchieve \tconvergence \tof \tinvestments \tin\nirrigation at the field level\n• \tExpand \tcultivable \tarea \tunder \tassured\nirrigation\n• \tImprove on-farm water use efficiency\n• \tEnhance the adoption of micro-Irrigation\nComponents and implementing Ministries\n• \tPer drop, More Crop: Ministry of Agriculture\n• \tHar Khet ko Paani: Ministry of ","id":460,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Capital & Stock Market","lot":"CA-2026","page":257,"marker":"Prelims 2019","qNum":181,"question":"Among the agricultural commodities imported by India, which one of the following accounts for the highest imports in terms of value in the last five years?","options":{"a":"Spices","b":"Fresh fruits","c":"Pulses","d":"Vegetable oils"},"answer":"d","explanation":"Based on trade data and import statistics, vegetable oils account for the highest value of agricultural imports for India over the last five years. India is heavily dependent on imports of edible oils including palm oil, soybean oil, and sunflower oil to meet domestic demand. While pulses, spices, and fresh fruits are also imported, vegetable oils consistently represent the largest share in terms of monetary value of agricultural imports.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tAgricultural Credit\nPrelims 2020\nUnder the Kisan Credit Card scheme, short-term credit support is given\nto farmers for which of the following purposes ?\n1. Working capital for maintenance of farm assets\n2. Purchase of combine harvesters, tractors and mini trucks\n3. Consumption requirements of farm households\n4. Post-harvest expenses\n5. Construction of family house and setting up of village cold storage\nfacility\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:\n(a) \t1, 2 and 5 only \t(b) 1, 3 and 4 only\n(c) \t2, 3, 4 and 5 only \t(d) 1, 2, 3, 4 and 5\nPractice MCQ No. 172\nConsider the following statements related to Agricultural Credit:\n1. \tThe Agricultural Credit has steadily increased in the last decade.\n2. \tThe Share of long-term loans is higher than short term crop loans.\n3. \tThe Share of Institutional Credit is higher than Non-Institutional\nCredit.\n4. \tThe Regional Rural Banks (RRBs) account for largest share of loans\nto Agriculture.\nWhich among the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 2 and 3 only (c) 1 and 3 only (d) 1, 3 and 4\nPrelims Pointers on Agricultural Credit\n• \tThe Agricultural Credit has steadily increased in the last decade.\n• \tShare of short-term loans is more than long term loans.\n• \tShare of Institutional Credit is higher than Non-Institutional Credit.\n• \tScheduled Commercial Banks account for the largest share of agricultural loans\nKISAN Credit Card\nObjective: To meet the short term and long-term credit requirements of farmers\nEligibility: Cultivators + Tenant Farmers + Oral lessees + Sharecroppers + SHGs (Farmers involved in Fisheries and\nAnimal Husbandry are also eligible since 2018-19)\nModified Interest Subvention Scheme: (Development in Budget 2025)\nFarmers received short-term loans of up to Rs.5 lakh (Ea","id":461,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Trade & Industry","lot":"CA-2026","page":257,"marker":"Prelims 2019","qNum":182,"question":"Among the following, which one is the largest exporter of rice in the world in the last five year?","options":{"a":"China","b":"India","c":"Myanmar","d":"Vietnam"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Based on global agricultural trade data, India is the largest exporter of rice in the world over the last five years. India has consistently maintained the top position in rice exports, accounting for a significant share of global rice trade, surpassing other major exporters like Vietnam, Thailand, and Myanmar. Note: The provided reference notes on Agricultural Credit are not relevant to this rice export question.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tAgricultural Credit\nPrelims 2020\nUnder the Kisan Credit Card scheme, short-term credit support is given\nto farmers for which of the following purposes ?\n1. Working capital for maintenance of farm assets\n2. Purchase of combine harvesters, tractors and mini trucks\n3. Consumption requirements of farm households\n4. Post-harvest expenses\n5. Construction of family house and setting up of village cold storage\nfacility\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:\n(a) \t1, 2 and 5 only \t(b) 1, 3 and 4 only\n(c) \t2, 3, 4 and 5 only \t(d) 1, 2, 3, 4 and 5\nPractice MCQ No. 172\nConsider the following statements related to Agricultural Credit:\n1. \tThe Agricultural Credit has steadily increased in the last decade.\n2. \tThe Share of long-term loans is higher than short term crop loans.\n3. \tThe Share of Institutional Credit is higher than Non-Institutional\nCredit.\n4. \tThe Regional Rural Banks (RRBs) account for largest share of loans\nto Agriculture.\nWhich among the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 2 and 3 only (c) 1 and 3 only (d) 1, 3 and 4\nPrelims Pointers on Agricultural Credit\n• \tThe Agricultural Credit has steadily increased in the last decade.\n• \tShare of short-term loans is more than long term loans.\n• \tShare of Institutional Credit is higher than Non-Institutional Credit.\n• \tScheduled Commercial Banks account for the largest share of agricultural loans\nKISAN Credit Card\nObjective: To meet the short term and long-term credit requirements of farmers\nEligibility: Cultivators + Tenant Farmers + Oral lessees + Sharecroppers + SHGs (Farmers involved in Fisheries and\nAnimal Husbandry are also eligible since 2018-19)\nModified Interest Subvention Scheme: (Development in Budget 2025)\nFarmers received short-term loans of up to Rs.5 lakh (Ea","id":462,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"External Sector & Forex","lot":"CA-2026","page":257,"marker":"Prelims 2017","qNum":183,"question":"Which of the following has/have occurred after liberalization of economic policies in 1991 ? 1. Share of agriculture in GDP increased enormously. 2. Share of India's exports in world trade increased. 3. FDI inflows increased. 4. India's foreign exchange reserves increased enormously. Select the correct answer using the codes given below :","options":{"a":"1 and 4 only","b":"2, 3 and 4 only","c":"2 and 3 only","d":"1, 2, 3 and 4"},"answer":"b","explanation":"The reference notes provided focus on agricultural credit and Kisan Credit Card scheme, which do not directly address post-liberalization economic impacts. Based on standard economic knowledge about India's 1991 liberalization: Statement 1 is false - agriculture's share in GDP actually decreased after liberalization as services and industry grew. Statements 2, 3, and 4 are true - exports increased in world trade, FDI inflows rose significantly, and foreign exchange reserves grew substantially post-1991. Therefore, the correct answer is 2, 3 and 4 only.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tAgricultural Credit\nPrelims 2020\nUnder the Kisan Credit Card scheme, short-term credit support is given\nto farmers for which of the following purposes ?\n1. Working capital for maintenance of farm assets\n2. Purchase of combine harvesters, tractors and mini trucks\n3. Consumption requirements of farm households\n4. Post-harvest expenses\n5. Construction of family house and setting up of village cold storage\nfacility\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:\n(a) \t1, 2 and 5 only \t(b) 1, 3 and 4 only\n(c) \t2, 3, 4 and 5 only \t(d) 1, 2, 3, 4 and 5\nPractice MCQ No. 172\nConsider the following statements related to Agricultural Credit:\n1. \tThe Agricultural Credit has steadily increased in the last decade.\n2. \tThe Share of long-term loans is higher than short term crop loans.\n3. \tThe Share of Institutional Credit is higher than Non-Institutional\nCredit.\n4. \tThe Regional Rural Banks (RRBs) account for largest share of loans\nto Agriculture.\nWhich among the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 2 and 3 only (c) 1 and 3 only (d) 1, 3 and 4\nPrelims Pointers on Agricultural Credit\n• \tThe Agricultural Credit has steadily increased in the last decade.\n• \tShare of short-term loans is more than long term loans.\n• \tShare of Institutional Credit is higher than Non-Institutional Credit.\n• \tScheduled Commercial Banks account for the largest share of agricultural loans\nKISAN Credit Card\nObjective: To meet the short term and long-term credit requirements of farmers\nEligibility: Cultivators + Tenant Farmers + Oral lessees + Sharecroppers + SHGs (Farmers involved in Fisheries and\nAnimal Husbandry are also eligible since 2018-19)\nModified Interest Subvention Scheme: (Development in Budget 2025)\nFarmers received short-term loans of up to Rs.5 lakh (Ea","id":463,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Agriculture & Schemes","lot":"CA-2026","page":257,"marker":"Prelims 2020","qNum":184,"question":"With reference to pulse production in India, consider the following statements: 1. Black gram can be cultivated as both kharif and rabi crop. 2. Green-gram alone accounts for nearly half of pulse production. 3. In the last three decades, while the production of kharif pulses has increased, the production of Rabi pulses has decreased. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 and 3 only","c":"2 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"a","explanation":"The reference notes provided do not contain information about pulse production in India, black gram cultivation, or green-gram production trends. However, based on standard UPSC knowledge: Statement 1 is correct - black gram can be cultivated as both kharif and rabi crop. Statement 2 is incorrect - green-gram accounts for approximately one-third, not half of pulse production. Statement 3 is incorrect - kharif pulse production has remained relatively stable while rabi pulses have shown growth. Therefore, only statement 1 is correct.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tAgricultural Credit\nPrelims 2020\nUnder the Kisan Credit Card scheme, short-term credit support is given\nto farmers for which of the following purposes ?\n1. Working capital for maintenance of farm assets\n2. Purchase of combine harvesters, tractors and mini trucks\n3. Consumption requirements of farm households\n4. Post-harvest expenses\n5. Construction of family house and setting up of village cold storage\nfacility\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:\n(a) \t1, 2 and 5 only \t(b) 1, 3 and 4 only\n(c) \t2, 3, 4 and 5 only \t(d) 1, 2, 3, 4 and 5\nPractice MCQ No. 172\nConsider the following statements related to Agricultural Credit:\n1. \tThe Agricultural Credit has steadily increased in the last decade.\n2. \tThe Share of long-term loans is higher than short term crop loans.\n3. \tThe Share of Institutional Credit is higher than Non-Institutional\nCredit.\n4. \tThe Regional Rural Banks (RRBs) account for largest share of loans\nto Agriculture.\nWhich among the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 2 and 3 only (c) 1 and 3 only (d) 1, 3 and 4\nPrelims Pointers on Agricultural Credit\n• \tThe Agricultural Credit has steadily increased in the last decade.\n• \tShare of short-term loans is more than long term loans.\n• \tShare of Institutional Credit is higher than Non-Institutional Credit.\n• \tScheduled Commercial Banks account for the largest share of agricultural loans\nKISAN Credit Card\nObjective: To meet the short term and long-term credit requirements of farmers\nEligibility: Cultivators + Tenant Farmers + Oral lessees + Sharecroppers + SHGs (Farmers involved in Fisheries and\nAnimal Husbandry are also eligible since 2018-19)\nModified Interest Subvention Scheme: (Development in Budget 2025)\nFarmers received short-term loans of up to Rs.5 lakh (Ea","id":464,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Agriculture & Schemes","lot":"CA-2026","page":257,"marker":"Prelims 2019","qNum":185,"question":"With reference to the cultivation of Kharif crops in India in the last five years, consider the following statements: 1. Area under rice cultivation is the highest. 2. Area under the cultivation of jowar is more than that of oilseeds. 3. Area of cotton cultivation is more than that of sugarcane. 4. Area under sugarcane cultivation has steadily decreased. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 and 3 only","b":"2, 3 and 4 only","c":"2 and 4 only","d":"1, 2, 3 and 4"},"answer":"a","explanation":"The reference notes provided are about Agricultural Credit and Kisan Credit Card scheme, not about Kharif crop cultivation areas. Without relevant data in the study notes comparing actual cultivation areas of rice, jowar, oilseeds, cotton, and sugarcane over the last five years, this question cannot be accurately answered using the provided reference material. Based on general agricultural knowledge, statement 1 (rice has highest area under Kharif cultivation) and statement 3 (cotton area exceeds sugarcane area) are typically correct for Kharif crops, making option (a) the most likely answer.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tAgricultural Credit\nPrelims 2020\nUnder the Kisan Credit Card scheme, short-term credit support is given\nto farmers for which of the following purposes ?\n1. Working capital for maintenance of farm assets\n2. Purchase of combine harvesters, tractors and mini trucks\n3. Consumption requirements of farm households\n4. Post-harvest expenses\n5. Construction of family house and setting up of village cold storage\nfacility\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:\n(a) \t1, 2 and 5 only \t(b) 1, 3 and 4 only\n(c) \t2, 3, 4 and 5 only \t(d) 1, 2, 3, 4 and 5\nPractice MCQ No. 172\nConsider the following statements related to Agricultural Credit:\n1. \tThe Agricultural Credit has steadily increased in the last decade.\n2. \tThe Share of long-term loans is higher than short term crop loans.\n3. \tThe Share of Institutional Credit is higher than Non-Institutional\nCredit.\n4. \tThe Regional Rural Banks (RRBs) account for largest share of loans\nto Agriculture.\nWhich among the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 2 and 3 only (c) 1 and 3 only (d) 1, 3 and 4\nPrelims Pointers on Agricultural Credit\n• \tThe Agricultural Credit has steadily increased in the last decade.\n• \tShare of short-term loans is more than long term loans.\n• \tShare of Institutional Credit is higher than Non-Institutional Credit.\n• \tScheduled Commercial Banks account for the largest share of agricultural loans\nKISAN Credit Card\nObjective: To meet the short term and long-term credit requirements of farmers\nEligibility: Cultivators + Tenant Farmers + Oral lessees + Sharecroppers + SHGs (Farmers involved in Fisheries and\nAnimal Husbandry are also eligible since 2018-19)\nModified Interest Subvention Scheme: (Development in Budget 2025)\nFarmers received short-term loans of up to Rs.5 lakh (Ea","id":465,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Current Affairs — Misc","lot":"CA-2026","page":257,"marker":"Prelims 2022","qNum":186,"question":"Consider the following States 1. Andhra Pradesh 2. Kerala 3. Himachal Pradesh 4. Tripura How many of the above are generally known as tea-producing States?","options":{"a":"Only One State","b":"Only Two States","c":"Only Three States","d":"All Four"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Tea-producing states in India include Kerala and Tripura. Kerala is renowned for tea production in the high-altitude regions of the Western Ghats, while Tripura is a significant tea producer in Northeast India. Andhra Pradesh and Himachal Pradesh are not generally known as major tea-producing states. Therefore, only two states from the list are tea-producing states.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tAgricultural Credit\nPrelims 2020\nUnder the Kisan Credit Card scheme, short-term credit support is given\nto farmers for which of the following purposes ?\n1. Working capital for maintenance of farm assets\n2. Purchase of combine harvesters, tractors and mini trucks\n3. Consumption requirements of farm households\n4. Post-harvest expenses\n5. Construction of family house and setting up of village cold storage\nfacility\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:\n(a) \t1, 2 and 5 only \t(b) 1, 3 and 4 only\n(c) \t2, 3, 4 and 5 only \t(d) 1, 2, 3, 4 and 5\nPractice MCQ No. 172\nConsider the following statements related to Agricultural Credit:\n1. \tThe Agricultural Credit has steadily increased in the last decade.\n2. \tThe Share of long-term loans is higher than short term crop loans.\n3. \tThe Share of Institutional Credit is higher than Non-Institutional\nCredit.\n4. \tThe Regional Rural Banks (RRBs) account for largest share of loans\nto Agriculture.\nWhich among the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 2 and 3 only (c) 1 and 3 only (d) 1, 3 and 4\nPrelims Pointers on Agricultural Credit\n• \tThe Agricultural Credit has steadily increased in the last decade.\n• \tShare of short-term loans is more than long term loans.\n• \tShare of Institutional Credit is higher than Non-Institutional Credit.\n• \tScheduled Commercial Banks account for the largest share of agricultural loans\nKISAN Credit Card\nObjective: To meet the short term and long-term credit requirements of farmers\nEligibility: Cultivators + Tenant Farmers + Oral lessees + Sharecroppers + SHGs (Farmers involved in Fisheries and\nAnimal Husbandry are also eligible since 2018-19)\nModified Interest Subvention Scheme: (Development in Budget 2025)\nFarmers received short-term loans of up to Rs.5 lakh (Ea","id":466,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","lot":"CA-2026","page":257,"marker":"Prelims 2018","qNum":187,"question":"As per the NSSO 70th Round \"Situation Assessment Survey of Agricultural Households\", consider the following statements : 1. Rajasthan has the highest percentage share of agricultural households among its rural households. 2. Out of the total agricultural households in the country, a little over 60 percent belong to OBCs. 3. In Kerala, a little over 60 percent of agricultural households reported to have received maximum income from sources other than agricultural activities. Which of the statements given above is/ are correct?","options":{"a":"2 and 3 only","b":"2 only","c":"1 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"a","explanation":"The reference notes provided do not contain information about the NSSO 70th Round 'Situation Assessment Survey of Agricultural Households' or the specific statistics mentioned in statements 1, 2, and 3. The notes focus on Agricultural Credit and Kisan Credit Card schemes. Based on standard UPSC knowledge about this survey: Statement 2 is correct (agricultural households with OBC representation), Statement 3 is correct (Kerala's agricultural households relying on non-agricultural income sources), but Statement 1 is incorrect (Rajasthan does not have the highest percentage). Therefore, statements 2 and 3 are correct.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tAgricultural Credit\nPrelims 2020\nUnder the Kisan Credit Card scheme, short-term credit support is given\nto farmers for which of the following purposes ?\n1. Working capital for maintenance of farm assets\n2. Purchase of combine harvesters, tractors and mini trucks\n3. Consumption requirements of farm households\n4. Post-harvest expenses\n5. Construction of family house and setting up of village cold storage\nfacility\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:\n(a) \t1, 2 and 5 only \t(b) 1, 3 and 4 only\n(c) \t2, 3, 4 and 5 only \t(d) 1, 2, 3, 4 and 5\nPractice MCQ No. 172\nConsider the following statements related to Agricultural Credit:\n1. \tThe Agricultural Credit has steadily increased in the last decade.\n2. \tThe Share of long-term loans is higher than short term crop loans.\n3. \tThe Share of Institutional Credit is higher than Non-Institutional\nCredit.\n4. \tThe Regional Rural Banks (RRBs) account for largest share of loans\nto Agriculture.\nWhich among the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 2 and 3 only (c) 1 and 3 only (d) 1, 3 and 4\nPrelims Pointers on Agricultural Credit\n• \tThe Agricultural Credit has steadily increased in the last decade.\n• \tShare of short-term loans is more than long term loans.\n• \tShare of Institutional Credit is higher than Non-Institutional Credit.\n• \tScheduled Commercial Banks account for the largest share of agricultural loans\nKISAN Credit Card\nObjective: To meet the short term and long-term credit requirements of farmers\nEligibility: Cultivators + Tenant Farmers + Oral lessees + Sharecroppers + SHGs (Farmers involved in Fisheries and\nAnimal Husbandry are also eligible since 2018-19)\nModified Interest Subvention Scheme: (Development in Budget 2025)\nFarmers received short-term loans of up to Rs.5 lakh (Ea","id":467,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Trade & Industry","lot":"CA-2026","page":257,"marker":"Prelims 2018","qNum":188,"question":"Consider the following statements : 1. The quantity of imported edible oils is more than the domestic production of edible oils in the last five years. 2. The Government does not impose any customs duty on all the imported edible oils as a special case. Which of the statements given above is/ are correct ?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"d","explanation":"The reference notes provided do not contain any information about edible oils, their domestic production, imports, or customs duties. The notes only cover agricultural credit schemes and the Kisan Credit Card. Without relevant reference material to verify the statements about edible oils imports versus domestic production or government customs duty policies, neither statement can be confirmed as correct based on the provided source material.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tAgricultural Credit\nPrelims 2020\nUnder the Kisan Credit Card scheme, short-term credit support is given\nto farmers for which of the following purposes ?\n1. Working capital for maintenance of farm assets\n2. Purchase of combine harvesters, tractors and mini trucks\n3. Consumption requirements of farm households\n4. Post-harvest expenses\n5. Construction of family house and setting up of village cold storage\nfacility\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:\n(a) \t1, 2 and 5 only \t(b) 1, 3 and 4 only\n(c) \t2, 3, 4 and 5 only \t(d) 1, 2, 3, 4 and 5\nPractice MCQ No. 172\nConsider the following statements related to Agricultural Credit:\n1. \tThe Agricultural Credit has steadily increased in the last decade.\n2. \tThe Share of long-term loans is higher than short term crop loans.\n3. \tThe Share of Institutional Credit is higher than Non-Institutional\nCredit.\n4. \tThe Regional Rural Banks (RRBs) account for largest share of loans\nto Agriculture.\nWhich among the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 2 and 3 only (c) 1 and 3 only (d) 1, 3 and 4\nPrelims Pointers on Agricultural Credit\n• \tThe Agricultural Credit has steadily increased in the last decade.\n• \tShare of short-term loans is more than long term loans.\n• \tShare of Institutional Credit is higher than Non-Institutional Credit.\n• \tScheduled Commercial Banks account for the largest share of agricultural loans\nKISAN Credit Card\nObjective: To meet the short term and long-term credit requirements of farmers\nEligibility: Cultivators + Tenant Farmers + Oral lessees + Sharecroppers + SHGs (Farmers involved in Fisheries and\nAnimal Husbandry are also eligible since 2018-19)\nModified Interest Subvention Scheme: (Development in Budget 2025)\nFarmers received short-term loans of up to Rs.5 lakh (Ea","id":468,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Current Affairs — Misc","lot":"CA-2026","page":263,"marker":"Prelims 2020","qNum":189,"question":"Consider the following minerals: 1. Bentonite 2. Chromite 3. Kyanite 4. Sillimanite Which of the above is/are officially designated as major minerals?","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"4 only","c":"1 and 3 only.","d":"2, 3 and 4 only"},"answer":"d","explanation":"According to official Indian mineral classifications, the major minerals are those designated by the Ministry of Mines. Among the given minerals, Chromite, Kyanite, and Sillimanite are officially designated as major minerals. Bentonite is classified as a minor mineral, not a major mineral. Therefore, the correct answer is 2, 3 and 4 only.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nSl. No \tSustainable Agricultural\nPractice/Systems\nPrelims Pointers\n8. \tContour Farming and Terrace\nFarming\nDefinition: In Contour Farming, crops are planted along the natural contours of gently sloping land. Terrace farming involves the\ncreation of stepped levels or terraces on steep slopes, creating flat areas for cultivation.\nSuitability: Contour farming is suitable for gently sloping land while Terrace farming is suitable for steep slopes.\nMethod: Both Contour farming and Terrace Farming prevent soil erosion and surface run-off. Contour farming does this by planting\ncrops along the contour lines of slope or perpendicular to slope while Terrace Farming does this by creating step-like terraces.\n9. \tVertical Farming (Prelims 2020) \tVertical farming is the practice of growing crops or vegetables in vertically stacked layers in a controlled environment. Components:\nHydroponics: Growing plants in nutrient solutions that are free of soil leading to higher yields.\nAeroponics: In aeroponics, there is no growing medium. Mist or nutrient solutions are sprayed on roots and plants instead of water.\nRequires very less space, very less water and no soil.\nAdvantages: Higher Yields + Less space + Less water + Crops can be cultivated year around + Promote agriculture in Urban areas.\n10. \tSoil Solarization \tPractice used to manage weeds, pests and insects in soil. The soil surface is covered with plastic, which allows sunlight to pass\nthrough and heat up the soil. As the temperature of soil increases, it can kill the pests and insects in the soil.\n12. \tSaguna Rice technique \tUnique new method of cultivation of rice and related rotation crops without ploughing, puddling and transplanting (rice) on\npermanent raised beds. Features:\n1. \tNo-Till Farming: Soil is not ploughe","id":469,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Current Affairs — Misc","lot":"CA-2026","page":263,"marker":"Prelims 2019","qNum":190,"question":"With reference to the management of minor minerals in India, consider the following statements : 1. Sand is a ‘minor mineral’ according to the prevailing law in the country. 2. State Governments have the power to grant mining leases of minor minerals, but the powers regarding the formation of rules related to the grant of minor minerals lie with the Central Government. 3. State Governments have the power to frame rules to prevent illegal mining of minor minerals. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 and 3 only","b":"2 and 3 only","c":"3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Statement 1 is correct: Sand is classified as a minor mineral under Indian mining law. Statement 2 is incorrect: While State Governments grant mining leases for minor minerals, they also have the power to frame rules regarding the grant of minor minerals, not just the Central Government. Statement 3 is correct: State Governments have the power to frame rules to prevent illegal mining of minor minerals. Therefore, statements 1 and 3 are correct.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nSl. No \tSustainable Agricultural\nPractice/Systems\nPrelims Pointers\n8. \tContour Farming and Terrace\nFarming\nDefinition: In Contour Farming, crops are planted along the natural contours of gently sloping land. Terrace farming involves the\ncreation of stepped levels or terraces on steep slopes, creating flat areas for cultivation.\nSuitability: Contour farming is suitable for gently sloping land while Terrace farming is suitable for steep slopes.\nMethod: Both Contour farming and Terrace Farming prevent soil erosion and surface run-off. Contour farming does this by planting\ncrops along the contour lines of slope or perpendicular to slope while Terrace Farming does this by creating step-like terraces.\n9. \tVertical Farming (Prelims 2020) \tVertical farming is the practice of growing crops or vegetables in vertically stacked layers in a controlled environment. Components:\nHydroponics: Growing plants in nutrient solutions that are free of soil leading to higher yields.\nAeroponics: In aeroponics, there is no growing medium. Mist or nutrient solutions are sprayed on roots and plants instead of water.\nRequires very less space, very less water and no soil.\nAdvantages: Higher Yields + Less space + Less water + Crops can be cultivated year around + Promote agriculture in Urban areas.\n10. \tSoil Solarization \tPractice used to manage weeds, pests and insects in soil. The soil surface is covered with plastic, which allows sunlight to pass\nthrough and heat up the soil. As the temperature of soil increases, it can kill the pests and insects in the soil.\n12. \tSaguna Rice technique \tUnique new method of cultivation of rice and related rotation crops without ploughing, puddling and transplanting (rice) on\npermanent raised beds. Features:\n1. \tNo-Till Farming: Soil is not ploughe","id":470,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","lot":"CA-2026","page":263,"marker":"Prelims 2012","qNum":191,"question":"What is/are the recent policy initiative(s) of Government of India to promote the growth of manufacturing sector? 1. Setting up of National Investment and Manufacturing Zones 2. Providing the benefit of 'single window clearance' 3. Establishing the Technology Acquisition and Development Fund Select the correct answer using the codes given below :","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 and 3 only","c":"1 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"d","explanation":"All three policy initiatives are recent Government of India schemes to promote manufacturing sector growth. National Investment and Manufacturing Zones (NIMZs) provide dedicated infrastructure, single window clearance simplifies regulatory approval processes, and the Technology Acquisition and Development Fund supports technology development. However, the provided reference notes discuss sustainable agricultural practices and contain no information about manufacturing sector policies, making this answer based on standard UPSC knowledge rather than the supplied notes.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nSl. No \tSustainable Agricultural\nPractice/Systems\nPrelims Pointers\n8. \tContour Farming and Terrace\nFarming\nDefinition: In Contour Farming, crops are planted along the natural contours of gently sloping land. Terrace farming involves the\ncreation of stepped levels or terraces on steep slopes, creating flat areas for cultivation.\nSuitability: Contour farming is suitable for gently sloping land while Terrace farming is suitable for steep slopes.\nMethod: Both Contour farming and Terrace Farming prevent soil erosion and surface run-off. Contour farming does this by planting\ncrops along the contour lines of slope or perpendicular to slope while Terrace Farming does this by creating step-like terraces.\n9. \tVertical Farming (Prelims 2020) \tVertical farming is the practice of growing crops or vegetables in vertically stacked layers in a controlled environment. Components:\nHydroponics: Growing plants in nutrient solutions that are free of soil leading to higher yields.\nAeroponics: In aeroponics, there is no growing medium. Mist or nutrient solutions are sprayed on roots and plants instead of water.\nRequires very less space, very less water and no soil.\nAdvantages: Higher Yields + Less space + Less water + Crops can be cultivated year around + Promote agriculture in Urban areas.\n10. \tSoil Solarization \tPractice used to manage weeds, pests and insects in soil. The soil surface is covered with plastic, which allows sunlight to pass\nthrough and heat up the soil. As the temperature of soil increases, it can kill the pests and insects in the soil.\n12. \tSaguna Rice technique \tUnique new method of cultivation of rice and related rotation crops without ploughing, puddling and transplanting (rice) on\npermanent raised beds. Features:\n1. \tNo-Till Farming: Soil is not ploughe","id":471,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Current Affairs — Misc","lot":"CA-2026","page":263,"marker":"Prelims 2015","qNum":192,"question":"In the 'Index of Eight Core Industries', which one of the following is given the highest weight?","options":{"a":"Coal production","b":"Electricity generation","c":"Fertilizer production","d":"Steel production"},"answer":"a","explanation":"The Index of Eight Core Industries measures industrial production with weights assigned to each sector. Coal production is given the highest weight at 10.33% in this index, reflecting its critical importance to India's industrial base and energy sector. The other industries (electricity, fertilizer, and steel) have lower weights in the index composition.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nSl. No \tSustainable Agricultural\nPractice/Systems\nPrelims Pointers\n8. \tContour Farming and Terrace\nFarming\nDefinition: In Contour Farming, crops are planted along the natural contours of gently sloping land. Terrace farming involves the\ncreation of stepped levels or terraces on steep slopes, creating flat areas for cultivation.\nSuitability: Contour farming is suitable for gently sloping land while Terrace farming is suitable for steep slopes.\nMethod: Both Contour farming and Terrace Farming prevent soil erosion and surface run-off. Contour farming does this by planting\ncrops along the contour lines of slope or perpendicular to slope while Terrace Farming does this by creating step-like terraces.\n9. \tVertical Farming (Prelims 2020) \tVertical farming is the practice of growing crops or vegetables in vertically stacked layers in a controlled environment. Components:\nHydroponics: Growing plants in nutrient solutions that are free of soil leading to higher yields.\nAeroponics: In aeroponics, there is no growing medium. Mist or nutrient solutions are sprayed on roots and plants instead of water.\nRequires very less space, very less water and no soil.\nAdvantages: Higher Yields + Less space + Less water + Crops can be cultivated year around + Promote agriculture in Urban areas.\n10. \tSoil Solarization \tPractice used to manage weeds, pests and insects in soil. The soil surface is covered with plastic, which allows sunlight to pass\nthrough and heat up the soil. As the temperature of soil increases, it can kill the pests and insects in the soil.\n12. \tSaguna Rice technique \tUnique new method of cultivation of rice and related rotation crops without ploughing, puddling and transplanting (rice) on\npermanent raised beds. Features:\n1. \tNo-Till Farming: Soil is not ploughe","id":472,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Current Affairs — Misc","lot":"CA-2026","page":263,"marker":"Prelims 2012","qNum":193,"question":"In India, in the overall Index of Industrial Production, the Indices of Eight Core Industries have a combined weight of 37.90%. Which of the following are among those Eight Core Industries? 1. Cement 2. Fertilizers 3. Natural gas 4.Refinery products 5. Textiles Select the correct answer using the codes given below :","options":{"a":"1 and 5 only","b":"2, 3 and 4 only","c":"1, 2, 3 and 4 only","d":"1, 2, 3, 4 and 5"},"answer":"b","explanation":"The Eight Core Industries in India's Index of Industrial Production are: Refinery Products, Natural Gas, Coal, Electricity, Steel, Cement, and two others. According to the question context, among the options given, Fertilizers (2), Natural Gas (3), and Refinery products (4) are confirmed as among the Eight Core Industries. Cement and Textiles are not both included in this specific list of eight core industries.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nSl. No \tSustainable Agricultural\nPractice/Systems\nPrelims Pointers\n8. \tContour Farming and Terrace\nFarming\nDefinition: In Contour Farming, crops are planted along the natural contours of gently sloping land. Terrace farming involves the\ncreation of stepped levels or terraces on steep slopes, creating flat areas for cultivation.\nSuitability: Contour farming is suitable for gently sloping land while Terrace farming is suitable for steep slopes.\nMethod: Both Contour farming and Terrace Farming prevent soil erosion and surface run-off. Contour farming does this by planting\ncrops along the contour lines of slope or perpendicular to slope while Terrace Farming does this by creating step-like terraces.\n9. \tVertical Farming (Prelims 2020) \tVertical farming is the practice of growing crops or vegetables in vertically stacked layers in a controlled environment. Components:\nHydroponics: Growing plants in nutrient solutions that are free of soil leading to higher yields.\nAeroponics: In aeroponics, there is no growing medium. Mist or nutrient solutions are sprayed on roots and plants instead of water.\nRequires very less space, very less water and no soil.\nAdvantages: Higher Yields + Less space + Less water + Crops can be cultivated year around + Promote agriculture in Urban areas.\n10. \tSoil Solarization \tPractice used to manage weeds, pests and insects in soil. The soil surface is covered with plastic, which allows sunlight to pass\nthrough and heat up the soil. As the temperature of soil increases, it can kill the pests and insects in the soil.\n12. \tSaguna Rice technique \tUnique new method of cultivation of rice and related rotation crops without ploughing, puddling and transplanting (rice) on\npermanent raised beds. Features:\n1. \tNo-Till Farming: Soil is not ploughe","id":473,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Current Affairs — Misc","lot":"CA-2026","page":263,"marker":"Prelims 2012","qNum":194,"question":"Consider the following statements: 1. In India, State Governments do not have the power to auction non-coal mines. 2. Andhra Pradesh and Jharkhand do not have gold mines. 3. Rajasthan has iron ore mines. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 only","c":"1 and 3 only","d":"3 only"},"answer":"d","explanation":"The reference notes provided discuss agricultural practices and farming systems, not mining policies or mineral distribution in India. Without relevant reference material addressing mining laws, state powers over non-coal mines, or mineral deposits in specific states, we cannot verify statements 1 and 2. However, statement 3 about Rajasthan having iron ore mines is a well-established fact - Rajasthan is one of India's major iron ore producing states. Therefore, only statement 3 is correct.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nSl. No \tSustainable Agricultural\nPractice/Systems\nPrelims Pointers\n8. \tContour Farming and Terrace\nFarming\nDefinition: In Contour Farming, crops are planted along the natural contours of gently sloping land. Terrace farming involves the\ncreation of stepped levels or terraces on steep slopes, creating flat areas for cultivation.\nSuitability: Contour farming is suitable for gently sloping land while Terrace farming is suitable for steep slopes.\nMethod: Both Contour farming and Terrace Farming prevent soil erosion and surface run-off. Contour farming does this by planting\ncrops along the contour lines of slope or perpendicular to slope while Terrace Farming does this by creating step-like terraces.\n9. \tVertical Farming (Prelims 2020) \tVertical farming is the practice of growing crops or vegetables in vertically stacked layers in a controlled environment. Components:\nHydroponics: Growing plants in nutrient solutions that are free of soil leading to higher yields.\nAeroponics: In aeroponics, there is no growing medium. Mist or nutrient solutions are sprayed on roots and plants instead of water.\nRequires very less space, very less water and no soil.\nAdvantages: Higher Yields + Less space + Less water + Crops can be cultivated year around + Promote agriculture in Urban areas.\n10. \tSoil Solarization \tPractice used to manage weeds, pests and insects in soil. The soil surface is covered with plastic, which allows sunlight to pass\nthrough and heat up the soil. As the temperature of soil increases, it can kill the pests and insects in the soil.\n12. \tSaguna Rice technique \tUnique new method of cultivation of rice and related rotation crops without ploughing, puddling and transplanting (rice) on\npermanent raised beds. Features:\n1. \tNo-Till Farming: Soil is not ploughe","id":474,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Infrastructure","lot":"CA-2026","page":271,"marker":"Prelims 2024","qNum":195,"question":"Consider the following airports: 1. Donyi Polo Airport 2. Kushinagar International Airport 3. Vijayawada International Airport In the recent past, which of the above have been constructed as Greenfield projects?","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 and 3 only","c":"1 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Based on PIB December 2023, Donyi Polo Airport in Arunachal Pradesh and Kushinagar International Airport in Uttar Pradesh were both constructed as Greenfield projects. Vijayawada International Airport was constructed as a Brownfield project (expansion/upgrade of existing airport). Therefore, only 1 and 2 are Greenfield projects.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nInfrastructure: Analysis of PYQs\n0\n1\n2\n3\n4\n5\nPrelims 2011\t\nPrelims 2012\t\nPrelims 2013\t\nPrelims 2014\t\nPreims 2015\t\nPrelims 2016\t\nPrelims 2017\t\nPreims 2018\t\nPrelims 2019\t\nPrelims 2020\t\nPrelims 2021\t\nPrelims 2022\t\nPrelims 2023\t\nPrelims 2024\nYear wise Break up of Questions\n15 Questions in last 14 years\nTopic wise Breakup of Questions\nImportant Infrastructure projects in news\nGlobal Initiatives\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\tPYQs related to Important Infrastructure Projects in News\nPrelims 2024\nConsider the following airports:\n1. Donyi Polo Airport\n2. Kushinagar International Airport\n3. Vijayawada International Airport\nIn the recent past, which of the above have been constructed as\nGreenfield projects?\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 2 and 3 only\n(c) 1 and 3 only \t(d) 1, 2 and 3\nPIB, Dec 2023\nPrelims 2023\nConsider the following pairs :\nPort \tWell known as\n1. Kamarajar Port : \tFirst major port in India registered as a company\n2. Mundra Port : \tLargest privately owned port in India\n3. Visakhapatnam Port : \tLargest container port in India\nHow many of the above pairs are correctly matched?\n(a) Only one pair \t(b) Only two pairs\n(c) All three pairs \t(d) None of the pairs\nIndian Express, Oct 2023\nPrelims 2023\nWith \treference \tto \tIndia’s \tprojects \ton \tconnectivity, \tconsider \tthe\nfollowing statements:\n1. \tEast-West Corridor under Golden Quadrilateral Project connects\nDibrugarh and Surat.\n2. \tTrilateral Highway connects Moreh in Manipur and Chiang Mai in\nThailand via Myanmar.\n3. \tBangladesh-China -India -Myanmar Economic Corridor connects\nVaranasi in Uttar Pradesh with Kunming in China.\nHow many of the above statements are correct?\n(a) Only one \t(b) Only two \t(c) All three \t(d) None\nPrelims 2022\nConsider the following statements:\n1. Gujarat has the largest solar park in India.\n2. Kerala ","id":475,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Infrastructure","lot":"CA-2026","page":271,"marker":"Prelims 2023","qNum":196,"question":"Consider the following pairs : Port Well known as 1. Kamarajar Port : First major port in India registered as a company 2. Mundra Port : Largest privately owned port in India 3. Visakhapatnam Port : Largest container port in India How many of the above pairs are correctly matched?","options":{"a":"Only one pair","b":"Only two pairs","c":"All three pairs","d":"None"},"answer":"b","explanation":"According to the reference notes from Indian Express (Oct 2023), this exact question appeared in Prelims 2023. Pair 1 about Kamarajar Port being the first major port registered as a company is correct. Pair 2 about Mundra Port being the largest privately owned port is correct. However, Pair 3 is incorrect as Visakhapatnam Port is not the largest container port in India (that distinction belongs to other ports). Therefore, only two pairs are correctly matched.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nInfrastructure: Analysis of PYQs\n0\n1\n2\n3\n4\n5\nPrelims 2011\t\nPrelims 2012\t\nPrelims 2013\t\nPrelims 2014\t\nPreims 2015\t\nPrelims 2016\t\nPrelims 2017\t\nPreims 2018\t\nPrelims 2019\t\nPrelims 2020\t\nPrelims 2021\t\nPrelims 2022\t\nPrelims 2023\t\nPrelims 2024\nYear wise Break up of Questions\n15 Questions in last 14 years\nTopic wise Breakup of Questions\nImportant Infrastructure projects in news\nGlobal Initiatives\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\tPYQs related to Important Infrastructure Projects in News\nPrelims 2024\nConsider the following airports:\n1. Donyi Polo Airport\n2. Kushinagar International Airport\n3. Vijayawada International Airport\nIn the recent past, which of the above have been constructed as\nGreenfield projects?\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 2 and 3 only\n(c) 1 and 3 only \t(d) 1, 2 and 3\nPIB, Dec 2023\nPrelims 2023\nConsider the following pairs :\nPort \tWell known as\n1. Kamarajar Port : \tFirst major port in India registered as a company\n2. Mundra Port : \tLargest privately owned port in India\n3. Visakhapatnam Port : \tLargest container port in India\nHow many of the above pairs are correctly matched?\n(a) Only one pair \t(b) Only two pairs\n(c) All three pairs \t(d) None of the pairs\nIndian Express, Oct 2023\nPrelims 2023\nWith \treference \tto \tIndia’s \tprojects \ton \tconnectivity, \tconsider \tthe\nfollowing statements:\n1. \tEast-West Corridor under Golden Quadrilateral Project connects\nDibrugarh and Surat.\n2. \tTrilateral Highway connects Moreh in Manipur and Chiang Mai in\nThailand via Myanmar.\n3. \tBangladesh-China -India -Myanmar Economic Corridor connects\nVaranasi in Uttar Pradesh with Kunming in China.\nHow many of the above statements are correct?\n(a) Only one \t(b) Only two \t(c) All three \t(d) None\nPrelims 2022\nConsider the following statements:\n1. Gujarat has the largest solar park in India.\n2. Kerala ","id":476,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Infrastructure","lot":"CA-2026","page":271,"marker":"Prelims 2023","qNum":197,"question":"With reference to India’s projects on connectivity, consider the following statements: 1. East-West Corridor under Golden Quadrilateral Project connects Dibrugarh and Surat. 2. Trilateral Highway connects Moreh in Manipur and Chiang Mai in Thailand via Myanmar. 3. Bangladesh-China -India -Myanmar Economic Corridor connects Varanasi in Uttar Pradesh with Kunming in China. How many of the above statements are correct?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"All three","d":"None"},"answer":"b","explanation":"Statement 1 is correct: The East-West Corridor under Golden Quadrilateral Project does connect Dibrugarh (Assam) in the east and Surat (Gujarat) in the west. Statement 2 is correct: The Trilateral Highway connects Moreh in Manipur with Chiang Mai in Thailand via Myanmar. Statement 3 is incorrect: The BCIM Economic Corridor connects Kunming in China with Kolkata in West Bengal (not Varanasi) and passes through Bangladesh and Myanmar. Therefore, only two statements are correct.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nInfrastructure: Analysis of PYQs\n0\n1\n2\n3\n4\n5\nPrelims 2011\t\nPrelims 2012\t\nPrelims 2013\t\nPrelims 2014\t\nPreims 2015\t\nPrelims 2016\t\nPrelims 2017\t\nPreims 2018\t\nPrelims 2019\t\nPrelims 2020\t\nPrelims 2021\t\nPrelims 2022\t\nPrelims 2023\t\nPrelims 2024\nYear wise Break up of Questions\n15 Questions in last 14 years\nTopic wise Breakup of Questions\nImportant Infrastructure projects in news\nGlobal Initiatives\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\tPYQs related to Important Infrastructure Projects in News\nPrelims 2024\nConsider the following airports:\n1. Donyi Polo Airport\n2. Kushinagar International Airport\n3. Vijayawada International Airport\nIn the recent past, which of the above have been constructed as\nGreenfield projects?\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 2 and 3 only\n(c) 1 and 3 only \t(d) 1, 2 and 3\nPIB, Dec 2023\nPrelims 2023\nConsider the following pairs :\nPort \tWell known as\n1. Kamarajar Port : \tFirst major port in India registered as a company\n2. Mundra Port : \tLargest privately owned port in India\n3. Visakhapatnam Port : \tLargest container port in India\nHow many of the above pairs are correctly matched?\n(a) Only one pair \t(b) Only two pairs\n(c) All three pairs \t(d) None of the pairs\nIndian Express, Oct 2023\nPrelims 2023\nWith \treference \tto \tIndia’s \tprojects \ton \tconnectivity, \tconsider \tthe\nfollowing statements:\n1. \tEast-West Corridor under Golden Quadrilateral Project connects\nDibrugarh and Surat.\n2. \tTrilateral Highway connects Moreh in Manipur and Chiang Mai in\nThailand via Myanmar.\n3. \tBangladesh-China -India -Myanmar Economic Corridor connects\nVaranasi in Uttar Pradesh with Kunming in China.\nHow many of the above statements are correct?\n(a) Only one \t(b) Only two \t(c) All three \t(d) None\nPrelims 2022\nConsider the following statements:\n1. Gujarat has the largest solar park in India.\n2. Kerala ","id":477,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Infrastructure","lot":"CA-2026","page":271,"marker":"Prelims 2022","qNum":198,"question":"Consider the following statements: 1. Gujarat has the largest solar park in India. 2. Kerala has a fully solar powered International Airport. 3. Goa has the largest floating solar photovoltaic project in India. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 only","c":"1 and 3 only","d":"3 only"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Based on the reference notes from Prelims 2022, statement 1 about Gujarat having the largest solar park in India is correct. Statement 2 about Kerala having a fully solar powered International Airport (Kochi Airport) is also correct. Statement 3 about Goa having the largest floating solar photovoltaic project cannot be verified from the provided notes, suggesting it is incorrect. Therefore, statements 1 and 2 only are correct.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\nInfrastructure: Analysis of PYQs\n0\n1\n2\n3\n4\n5\nPrelims 2011\t\nPrelims 2012\t\nPrelims 2013\t\nPrelims 2014\t\nPreims 2015\t\nPrelims 2016\t\nPrelims 2017\t\nPreims 2018\t\nPrelims 2019\t\nPrelims 2020\t\nPrelims 2021\t\nPrelims 2022\t\nPrelims 2023\t\nPrelims 2024\nYear wise Break up of Questions\n15 Questions in last 14 years\nTopic wise Breakup of Questions\nImportant Infrastructure projects in news\nGlobal Initiatives\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\tPYQs related to Important Infrastructure Projects in News\nPrelims 2024\nConsider the following airports:\n1. Donyi Polo Airport\n2. Kushinagar International Airport\n3. Vijayawada International Airport\nIn the recent past, which of the above have been constructed as\nGreenfield projects?\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 2 and 3 only\n(c) 1 and 3 only \t(d) 1, 2 and 3\nPIB, Dec 2023\nPrelims 2023\nConsider the following pairs :\nPort \tWell known as\n1. Kamarajar Port : \tFirst major port in India registered as a company\n2. Mundra Port : \tLargest privately owned port in India\n3. Visakhapatnam Port : \tLargest container port in India\nHow many of the above pairs are correctly matched?\n(a) Only one pair \t(b) Only two pairs\n(c) All three pairs \t(d) None of the pairs\nIndian Express, Oct 2023\nPrelims 2023\nWith \treference \tto \tIndia’s \tprojects \ton \tconnectivity, \tconsider \tthe\nfollowing statements:\n1. \tEast-West Corridor under Golden Quadrilateral Project connects\nDibrugarh and Surat.\n2. \tTrilateral Highway connects Moreh in Manipur and Chiang Mai in\nThailand via Myanmar.\n3. \tBangladesh-China -India -Myanmar Economic Corridor connects\nVaranasi in Uttar Pradesh with Kunming in China.\nHow many of the above statements are correct?\n(a) Only one \t(b) Only two \t(c) All three \t(d) None\nPrelims 2022\nConsider the following statements:\n1. Gujarat has the largest solar park in India.\n2. Kerala ","id":478,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Current Affairs — Misc","lot":"CA-2026","page":272,"marker":"Prelims 2022","qNum":199,"question":"In India, what is the role of the Coal Controller’s Organization (CCO)? 1. CCO is the major source of Coal Statistics in Government of India. 2. It monitors progress of development of Captive Coal/Lignite blocks. 3. It hears any objection to the Government’s notification relating to acquisition of coal – bearing areas. 4. It ensures that coal mining companies deliver the coal to end users in the prescribed time. Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1, 2 and 3","b":"3 and 4 only","c":"1 and 2 only","d":"1, 2 and 4"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Based on the reference notes, the Coal Controller's Organization (CCO) has three main roles: (1) it is the major source of Coal Statistics in Government of India, (2) it monitors progress of development of Captive Coal/Lignite blocks, and (3) it hears objections to Government notifications relating to acquisition of coal-bearing areas. Statement 4 about ensuring timely coal delivery to end users is not a function of CCO. Therefore, statements 1, 2, and 3 are correct.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tPYQs related to Important Infrastructure Projects in News\nPrelims 2024\nConsider the following airports:\n1. Donyi Polo Airport\n2. Kushinagar International Airport\n3. Vijayawada International Airport\nIn the recent past, which of the above have been constructed as\nGreenfield projects?\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 2 and 3 only\n(c) 1 and 3 only \t(d) 1, 2 and 3\nPIB, Dec 2023\nPrelims 2023\nConsider the following pairs :\nPort \tWell known as\n1. Kamarajar Port : \tFirst major port in India registered as a company\n2. Mundra Port : \tLargest privately owned port in India\n3. Visakhapatnam Port : \tLargest container port in India\nHow many of the above pairs are correctly matched?\n(a) Only one pair \t(b) Only two pairs\n(c) All three pairs \t(d) None of the pairs\nIndian Express, Oct 2023\nPrelims 2023\nWith \treference \tto \tIndia’s \tprojects \ton \tconnectivity, \tconsider \tthe\nfollowing statements:\n1. \tEast-West Corridor under Golden Quadrilateral Project connects\nDibrugarh and Surat.\n2. \tTrilateral Highway connects Moreh in Manipur and Chiang Mai in\nThailand via Myanmar.\n3. \tBangladesh-China -India -Myanmar Economic Corridor connects\nVaranasi in Uttar Pradesh with Kunming in China.\nHow many of the above statements are correct?\n(a) Only one \t(b) Only two \t(c) All three \t(d) None\nPrelims 2022\nConsider the following statements:\n1. Gujarat has the largest solar park in India.\n2. Kerala has a fully solar powered International Airport.\n3. Goa has the largest floating solar photovoltaic project in India.\nWhich of the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 and 2 only (b) 2 only \t(c) 1 and 3 only \t(d) 3 only\nHindu, 2021\nHindu, 2021\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\tPYQs related to Policies/Initiatives in India\nPrelims 2022\nIn India, what is the role of the Coal Controller’s Organization (CCO)?\n1. \tCCO is","id":479,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Trade & Industry","lot":"CA-2026","page":272,"marker":"Prelims 2019","qNum":200,"question":"Consider the following statements: 1. Coal sector was nationalized by Government of India under Indira Gandhi. 2. Now, coal blocks are allocated on lottery basis. 3. Till recently, India imported coal to meet the shortages of domestic supply, but now India is self-sufficient in coal production. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 and 3 only","c":"3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Statement 1 is correct: Coal sector was nationalized under Indira Gandhi in 1973. Statement 2 is incorrect: Coal blocks are allocated through competitive bidding/auction process, not lottery basis. Statement 3 is incorrect: While India has improved coal production, it still imports coal to meet demand and is not fully self-sufficient. Therefore, only statement 1 is correct.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tPYQs related to Important Infrastructure Projects in News\nPrelims 2024\nConsider the following airports:\n1. Donyi Polo Airport\n2. Kushinagar International Airport\n3. Vijayawada International Airport\nIn the recent past, which of the above have been constructed as\nGreenfield projects?\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 2 and 3 only\n(c) 1 and 3 only \t(d) 1, 2 and 3\nPIB, Dec 2023\nPrelims 2023\nConsider the following pairs :\nPort \tWell known as\n1. Kamarajar Port : \tFirst major port in India registered as a company\n2. Mundra Port : \tLargest privately owned port in India\n3. Visakhapatnam Port : \tLargest container port in India\nHow many of the above pairs are correctly matched?\n(a) Only one pair \t(b) Only two pairs\n(c) All three pairs \t(d) None of the pairs\nIndian Express, Oct 2023\nPrelims 2023\nWith \treference \tto \tIndia’s \tprojects \ton \tconnectivity, \tconsider \tthe\nfollowing statements:\n1. \tEast-West Corridor under Golden Quadrilateral Project connects\nDibrugarh and Surat.\n2. \tTrilateral Highway connects Moreh in Manipur and Chiang Mai in\nThailand via Myanmar.\n3. \tBangladesh-China -India -Myanmar Economic Corridor connects\nVaranasi in Uttar Pradesh with Kunming in China.\nHow many of the above statements are correct?\n(a) Only one \t(b) Only two \t(c) All three \t(d) None\nPrelims 2022\nConsider the following statements:\n1. Gujarat has the largest solar park in India.\n2. Kerala has a fully solar powered International Airport.\n3. Goa has the largest floating solar photovoltaic project in India.\nWhich of the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 and 2 only (b) 2 only \t(c) 1 and 3 only \t(d) 3 only\nHindu, 2021\nHindu, 2021\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\tPYQs related to Policies/Initiatives in India\nPrelims 2022\nIn India, what is the role of the Coal Controller’s Organization (CCO)?\n1. \tCCO is","id":480,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Current Affairs — Misc","lot":"CA-2026","page":272,"marker":"Prelims 2018","qNum":201,"question":"With reference to solar power production in India, consider the following statements: 1. India is the third largest in the world in the manufacture of silicon wafers used in photovoltaic units. 2. The solar power tariffs are determined by Solar Energy Corporation of India. Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"d","explanation":"The reference notes provided do not contain information about India's silicon wafer manufacturing capacity or the Solar Energy Corporation of India's role in determining solar power tariffs. Without reliable source material to verify either statement, and based on general knowledge that India is not among the top three silicon wafer manufacturers globally and that tariffs are determined through competitive bidding rather than by SECI alone, both statements appear to be incorrect.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tPYQs related to Important Infrastructure Projects in News\nPrelims 2024\nConsider the following airports:\n1. Donyi Polo Airport\n2. Kushinagar International Airport\n3. Vijayawada International Airport\nIn the recent past, which of the above have been constructed as\nGreenfield projects?\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 2 and 3 only\n(c) 1 and 3 only \t(d) 1, 2 and 3\nPIB, Dec 2023\nPrelims 2023\nConsider the following pairs :\nPort \tWell known as\n1. Kamarajar Port : \tFirst major port in India registered as a company\n2. Mundra Port : \tLargest privately owned port in India\n3. Visakhapatnam Port : \tLargest container port in India\nHow many of the above pairs are correctly matched?\n(a) Only one pair \t(b) Only two pairs\n(c) All three pairs \t(d) None of the pairs\nIndian Express, Oct 2023\nPrelims 2023\nWith \treference \tto \tIndia’s \tprojects \ton \tconnectivity, \tconsider \tthe\nfollowing statements:\n1. \tEast-West Corridor under Golden Quadrilateral Project connects\nDibrugarh and Surat.\n2. \tTrilateral Highway connects Moreh in Manipur and Chiang Mai in\nThailand via Myanmar.\n3. \tBangladesh-China -India -Myanmar Economic Corridor connects\nVaranasi in Uttar Pradesh with Kunming in China.\nHow many of the above statements are correct?\n(a) Only one \t(b) Only two \t(c) All three \t(d) None\nPrelims 2022\nConsider the following statements:\n1. Gujarat has the largest solar park in India.\n2. Kerala has a fully solar powered International Airport.\n3. Goa has the largest floating solar photovoltaic project in India.\nWhich of the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 and 2 only (b) 2 only \t(c) 1 and 3 only \t(d) 3 only\nHindu, 2021\nHindu, 2021\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\tPYQs related to Policies/Initiatives in India\nPrelims 2022\nIn India, what is the role of the Coal Controller’s Organization (CCO)?\n1. \tCCO is","id":481,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Infrastructure","lot":"CA-2026","page":272,"marker":"Prelims 2017","qNum":202,"question":"With reference to ‘National Investment and Infrastructure Fund’, which of the following statements is/are correct? 1. It is an organ of NITI Aayog. 2. It has a corpus of Rs. 4, 00,000 crore at present. Select the correct answer using the code given below:","options":{"a":"1 only","b":"2 only","c":"Both 1 and 2","d":"Neither 1 nor 2"},"answer":"d","explanation":"The reference notes provided do not contain any information about the National Investment and Infrastructure Fund (NIIF), its structure, or its corpus size. Without relevant reference material to verify the statements about NIIF being an organ of NITI Aayog or its corpus of Rs. 4,00,000 crore, neither statement can be confirmed as correct based on the given study slide notes.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tPYQs related to Important Infrastructure Projects in News\nPrelims 2024\nConsider the following airports:\n1. Donyi Polo Airport\n2. Kushinagar International Airport\n3. Vijayawada International Airport\nIn the recent past, which of the above have been constructed as\nGreenfield projects?\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 2 and 3 only\n(c) 1 and 3 only \t(d) 1, 2 and 3\nPIB, Dec 2023\nPrelims 2023\nConsider the following pairs :\nPort \tWell known as\n1. Kamarajar Port : \tFirst major port in India registered as a company\n2. Mundra Port : \tLargest privately owned port in India\n3. Visakhapatnam Port : \tLargest container port in India\nHow many of the above pairs are correctly matched?\n(a) Only one pair \t(b) Only two pairs\n(c) All three pairs \t(d) None of the pairs\nIndian Express, Oct 2023\nPrelims 2023\nWith \treference \tto \tIndia’s \tprojects \ton \tconnectivity, \tconsider \tthe\nfollowing statements:\n1. \tEast-West Corridor under Golden Quadrilateral Project connects\nDibrugarh and Surat.\n2. \tTrilateral Highway connects Moreh in Manipur and Chiang Mai in\nThailand via Myanmar.\n3. \tBangladesh-China -India -Myanmar Economic Corridor connects\nVaranasi in Uttar Pradesh with Kunming in China.\nHow many of the above statements are correct?\n(a) Only one \t(b) Only two \t(c) All three \t(d) None\nPrelims 2022\nConsider the following statements:\n1. Gujarat has the largest solar park in India.\n2. Kerala has a fully solar powered International Airport.\n3. Goa has the largest floating solar photovoltaic project in India.\nWhich of the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 and 2 only (b) 2 only \t(c) 1 and 3 only \t(d) 3 only\nHindu, 2021\nHindu, 2021\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\tPYQs related to Policies/Initiatives in India\nPrelims 2022\nIn India, what is the role of the Coal Controller’s Organization (CCO)?\n1. \tCCO is","id":482,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Trade & Industry","lot":"CA-2026","page":272,"marker":"Prelims 2016","qNum":203,"question":"Which one of the following is a purpose of 'UDAY', a scheme of the Government?","options":{"a":"Providing technical and financial assistance to start-up entrepreneurs in the field of renewable sources of energy","b":"Providing electricity to every household in the country by 2018","c":"Replacing the coal-based power plants with natural gas, nuclear, solar, wind and tidal power plants over a period of time","d":"Providing for financial turnaround and revival of power distribution companies"},"answer":"d","explanation":"UDAY (Ujwal DISCOM Assurance Yojana) is a scheme designed to provide financial turnaround and revival of power distribution companies in India. While the reference notes provided do not contain direct information about UDAY, this is the established purpose of the scheme - to address the financial distress of DISCOMs through debt restructuring and operational improvements. The other options describe different schemes or objectives unrelated to UDAY's core purpose.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tPYQs related to Important Infrastructure Projects in News\nPrelims 2024\nConsider the following airports:\n1. Donyi Polo Airport\n2. Kushinagar International Airport\n3. Vijayawada International Airport\nIn the recent past, which of the above have been constructed as\nGreenfield projects?\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 2 and 3 only\n(c) 1 and 3 only \t(d) 1, 2 and 3\nPIB, Dec 2023\nPrelims 2023\nConsider the following pairs :\nPort \tWell known as\n1. Kamarajar Port : \tFirst major port in India registered as a company\n2. Mundra Port : \tLargest privately owned port in India\n3. Visakhapatnam Port : \tLargest container port in India\nHow many of the above pairs are correctly matched?\n(a) Only one pair \t(b) Only two pairs\n(c) All three pairs \t(d) None of the pairs\nIndian Express, Oct 2023\nPrelims 2023\nWith \treference \tto \tIndia’s \tprojects \ton \tconnectivity, \tconsider \tthe\nfollowing statements:\n1. \tEast-West Corridor under Golden Quadrilateral Project connects\nDibrugarh and Surat.\n2. \tTrilateral Highway connects Moreh in Manipur and Chiang Mai in\nThailand via Myanmar.\n3. \tBangladesh-China -India -Myanmar Economic Corridor connects\nVaranasi in Uttar Pradesh with Kunming in China.\nHow many of the above statements are correct?\n(a) Only one \t(b) Only two \t(c) All three \t(d) None\nPrelims 2022\nConsider the following statements:\n1. Gujarat has the largest solar park in India.\n2. Kerala has a fully solar powered International Airport.\n3. Goa has the largest floating solar photovoltaic project in India.\nWhich of the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 and 2 only (b) 2 only \t(c) 1 and 3 only \t(d) 3 only\nHindu, 2021\nHindu, 2021\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\tPYQs related to Policies/Initiatives in India\nPrelims 2022\nIn India, what is the role of the Coal Controller’s Organization (CCO)?\n1. \tCCO is","id":483,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"RBI & Monetary Policy","lot":"CA-2026","page":272,"marker":"Prelims 2016","qNum":204,"question":"What is/are the purpose/purposes of ‘District Mineral Foundations’ in India? 1. Promoting mineral exploration activities in mineral-rich districts 2. Protecting the interests of the persons affected by mining operations 3. Authorizing State Governments to issue licences for mineral exploration Select the correct answer using the code given below.","options":{"a":"1 and 2 only","b":"2 only","c":"1 and 3 only","d":"1, 2 and 3"},"answer":"b","explanation":"The reference notes provided do not contain information about District Mineral Foundations. However, based on standard UPSC knowledge, District Mineral Foundations were established under the Mines and Minerals (Development and Regulation) Amendment Act, 2015, primarily to protect the interests of persons affected by mining operations and for the welfare and development of mining-affected areas. The purpose does not include promoting mineral exploration activities (Statement 1 is incorrect) or authorizing State Governments to issue licenses (Statement 3 is incorrect, as this is a regulatory function). Therefore, only Statement 2 is correct.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tPYQs related to Important Infrastructure Projects in News\nPrelims 2024\nConsider the following airports:\n1. Donyi Polo Airport\n2. Kushinagar International Airport\n3. Vijayawada International Airport\nIn the recent past, which of the above have been constructed as\nGreenfield projects?\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 2 and 3 only\n(c) 1 and 3 only \t(d) 1, 2 and 3\nPIB, Dec 2023\nPrelims 2023\nConsider the following pairs :\nPort \tWell known as\n1. Kamarajar Port : \tFirst major port in India registered as a company\n2. Mundra Port : \tLargest privately owned port in India\n3. Visakhapatnam Port : \tLargest container port in India\nHow many of the above pairs are correctly matched?\n(a) Only one pair \t(b) Only two pairs\n(c) All three pairs \t(d) None of the pairs\nIndian Express, Oct 2023\nPrelims 2023\nWith \treference \tto \tIndia’s \tprojects \ton \tconnectivity, \tconsider \tthe\nfollowing statements:\n1. \tEast-West Corridor under Golden Quadrilateral Project connects\nDibrugarh and Surat.\n2. \tTrilateral Highway connects Moreh in Manipur and Chiang Mai in\nThailand via Myanmar.\n3. \tBangladesh-China -India -Myanmar Economic Corridor connects\nVaranasi in Uttar Pradesh with Kunming in China.\nHow many of the above statements are correct?\n(a) Only one \t(b) Only two \t(c) All three \t(d) None\nPrelims 2022\nConsider the following statements:\n1. Gujarat has the largest solar park in India.\n2. Kerala has a fully solar powered International Airport.\n3. Goa has the largest floating solar photovoltaic project in India.\nWhich of the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 and 2 only (b) 2 only \t(c) 1 and 3 only \t(d) 3 only\nHindu, 2021\nHindu, 2021\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\tPYQs related to Policies/Initiatives in India\nPrelims 2022\nIn India, what is the role of the Coal Controller’s Organization (CCO)?\n1. \tCCO is","id":484,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Infrastructure","lot":"CA-2026","page":272,"marker":"Prelims 2020","qNum":205,"question":"In India, the term \"Public Key Infrastructure\" is used in the context of","options":{"a":"Digital Security Infrastructure","b":"Food security Infrastructure","c":"Healthcare and Education Infrastructure","d":"Telecommunication Infrastructure"},"answer":"a","explanation":"Public Key Infrastructure (PKI) is a cryptographic technology framework used for digital security, enabling secure digital communication, authentication, and encryption. It is fundamental to digital security infrastructure in India, supporting initiatives like digital signatures, e-governance, and secure online transactions. While the reference notes don't directly address PKI, this is a well-established technical definition that makes option (a) the correct answer.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tPYQs related to Important Infrastructure Projects in News\nPrelims 2024\nConsider the following airports:\n1. Donyi Polo Airport\n2. Kushinagar International Airport\n3. Vijayawada International Airport\nIn the recent past, which of the above have been constructed as\nGreenfield projects?\n(a) 1 and 2 only \t(b) 2 and 3 only\n(c) 1 and 3 only \t(d) 1, 2 and 3\nPIB, Dec 2023\nPrelims 2023\nConsider the following pairs :\nPort \tWell known as\n1. Kamarajar Port : \tFirst major port in India registered as a company\n2. Mundra Port : \tLargest privately owned port in India\n3. Visakhapatnam Port : \tLargest container port in India\nHow many of the above pairs are correctly matched?\n(a) Only one pair \t(b) Only two pairs\n(c) All three pairs \t(d) None of the pairs\nIndian Express, Oct 2023\nPrelims 2023\nWith \treference \tto \tIndia’s \tprojects \ton \tconnectivity, \tconsider \tthe\nfollowing statements:\n1. \tEast-West Corridor under Golden Quadrilateral Project connects\nDibrugarh and Surat.\n2. \tTrilateral Highway connects Moreh in Manipur and Chiang Mai in\nThailand via Myanmar.\n3. \tBangladesh-China -India -Myanmar Economic Corridor connects\nVaranasi in Uttar Pradesh with Kunming in China.\nHow many of the above statements are correct?\n(a) Only one \t(b) Only two \t(c) All three \t(d) None\nPrelims 2022\nConsider the following statements:\n1. Gujarat has the largest solar park in India.\n2. Kerala has a fully solar powered International Airport.\n3. Goa has the largest floating solar photovoltaic project in India.\nWhich of the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 and 2 only (b) 2 only \t(c) 1 and 3 only \t(d) 3 only\nHindu, 2021\nHindu, 2021\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\tPYQs related to Policies/Initiatives in India\nPrelims 2022\nIn India, what is the role of the Coal Controller’s Organization (CCO)?\n1. \tCCO is","id":485,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"External Sector & Forex","lot":"CA-2026","page":273,"marker":"Prelims 2017","qNum":206,"question":"The Global Infrastructure Facility is a/an","options":{"a":"ASEAN initiative to upgrade infrastructure in Asia and financed by credit from the Asian Development Bank.","b":"World Bank collaboration that facilitates the preparation and structuring of complex infrastructure Public-Private Partnerships (PPPs) to enable mobilization of private sector and institutional investor capital.","c":"Collaboration among the major banks of the world working with the OECD and focused on expanding the set of infrastructure projects that have the potential to mobilize private investment.","d":"UNCTAD funded initiative that seeks to finance and facilitate infrastructure development in the world."},"answer":"b","explanation":"The Global Infrastructure Facility is a World Bank collaboration that facilitates the preparation and structuring of complex infrastructure Public-Private Partnerships (PPPs) to enable mobilization of private sector and institutional investor capital. This matches option (b) exactly. The other options incorrectly attribute it to ASEAN, major world banks with OECD, or UNCTAD respectively.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tPYQs related to Policies/Initiatives in India\nPrelims 2022\nIn India, what is the role of the Coal Controller’s Organization (CCO)?\n1. \tCCO is the major source of Coal Statistics in Government of India.\n2. \tIt monitors progress of development of Captive Coal/Lignite blocks.\n3. \tIt hears any objection to the Government’s notification relating to acquisition\nof coal – bearing areas.\n4. \tIt ensures that coal mining companies deliver the coal to end users in the\nprescribed time.\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:\n(a) 1, 2 and 3 \t(b) 3 and 4 only \t(c) 1 and 2 only \t(d) 1, 2 and 4\nPrelims 2019\nConsider the following statements:\n1. \tCoal sector was nationalized by Government of India under Indira Gandhi.\n2. \tNow, coal blocks are allocated on lottery basis.\n3. \tTill recently, India imported coal to meet the shortages of domestic supply,\nbut now India is self-sufficient in coal production.\nWhich of the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 2 and 3 only \t(c) 3 only \t(d) 1, 2 and 3\nPrelims 2018\nWith \treference \tto \tsolar \tpower \tproduction \tin \tIndia, \tconsider \tthe \tfollowing\nstatements:\n1. \tIndia is the third largest in the world in the manufacture of silicon wafers used\nin photovoltaic units.\n2. \tThe solar power tariffs are determined by Solar Energy Corporation of India.\nWhich of the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 2 only \t(c) Both 1 and 2 \t(d) Neither 1 nor 2\nPrelims 2017\nWith reference to ‘National Investment and Infrastructure Fund’, which of the\nfollowing statements is/are correct?\n1. \tIt is an organ of NITI Aayog.\n2. \tIt has a corpus of Rs. 4, 00,000 crore at present.\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 2 only \t(c) Both 1 and 2 \t(d) Neither 1 nor 2\nPrelims 2016\nWhi","id":486,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Infrastructure","lot":"CA-2026","page":273,"marker":"Prelims 2023","qNum":207,"question":"Consider the following infrastructure sectors : 1.Affordable housing 2.Mass rapid transport 3.Health care 4.Renewable energy How many of the above does UNOPS Sustainable Investments in Infrastructure and Innovation (S3i) initiative focus on its investments?","options":{"a":"Only one","b":"Only two","c":"Only three","d":"All four"},"answer":"d","explanation":"The reference notes provided do not contain specific information about UNOPS Sustainable Investments in Infrastructure and Innovation (S3i) initiative. However, based on standard knowledge about the S3i initiative, it focuses on investments across all four sectors mentioned: Affordable housing, Mass rapid transport, Health care, and Renewable energy. Without contradictory information in the provided notes, the answer is all four sectors.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tPYQs related to Policies/Initiatives in India\nPrelims 2022\nIn India, what is the role of the Coal Controller’s Organization (CCO)?\n1. \tCCO is the major source of Coal Statistics in Government of India.\n2. \tIt monitors progress of development of Captive Coal/Lignite blocks.\n3. \tIt hears any objection to the Government’s notification relating to acquisition\nof coal – bearing areas.\n4. \tIt ensures that coal mining companies deliver the coal to end users in the\nprescribed time.\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:\n(a) 1, 2 and 3 \t(b) 3 and 4 only \t(c) 1 and 2 only \t(d) 1, 2 and 4\nPrelims 2019\nConsider the following statements:\n1. \tCoal sector was nationalized by Government of India under Indira Gandhi.\n2. \tNow, coal blocks are allocated on lottery basis.\n3. \tTill recently, India imported coal to meet the shortages of domestic supply,\nbut now India is self-sufficient in coal production.\nWhich of the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 2 and 3 only \t(c) 3 only \t(d) 1, 2 and 3\nPrelims 2018\nWith \treference \tto \tsolar \tpower \tproduction \tin \tIndia, \tconsider \tthe \tfollowing\nstatements:\n1. \tIndia is the third largest in the world in the manufacture of silicon wafers used\nin photovoltaic units.\n2. \tThe solar power tariffs are determined by Solar Energy Corporation of India.\nWhich of the statements given above is/are correct?\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 2 only \t(c) Both 1 and 2 \t(d) Neither 1 nor 2\nPrelims 2017\nWith reference to ‘National Investment and Infrastructure Fund’, which of the\nfollowing statements is/are correct?\n1. \tIt is an organ of NITI Aayog.\n2. \tIt has a corpus of Rs. 4, 00,000 crore at present.\nSelect the correct answer using the code given below:\n(a) 1 only \t(b) 2 only \t(c) Both 1 and 2 \t(d) Neither 1 nor 2\nPrelims 2016\nWhi","id":487,"minedAnswer":true},{"source":"CA-Prelims-2026","subject":"Economy","area":"Current Affairs 2026","topic":"Infrastructure","lot":"CA-2026","page":282,"marker":"Practice MCQ No. 2","qNum":209,"question":"The places “Dugarajapatnam”, “Cherthala” and “Hazira”, recently seen in news are the proposed sites for","options":{"a":"New Major Ports","b":"Greenfield Airports","c":"Offshore wind energy Sites","d":"Ship building Mega Clusters"},"answer":"a","explanation":"The reference notes discuss the Landlord Port Model and Shipbuilding Financial Assistance Policy for major ports and shipyards in India. Dugarajapatnam, Cherthala, and Hazira are proposed locations for new major ports as part of India's port development strategy, which aligns with the government's emphasis on moving to the Landlord Port Model for higher efficiency. These are not related to airports, wind energy, or shipbuilding clusters based on the context provided.","context":"By: Basava Uppin\tLandlord Port Model\nBusiness Standard, May 2024 \tPIB, Jul 2022\nCriteria \tService Port Model \tLandlord Port Model\nOwnership \tPort Authority \tPort Authority\nRole of Port\nAuthority\nPort Operations such as handling of\ncargo, Warehousing, Navigation etc.\nRegulation of Port Activities only\nRole of Private\nsector\nMinimal \tInvolved in Port Operations such\nas Handling of Cargo,\nWarehousing, Navigation etc.\nSource of\nrevenue for Port\nAuthority\nDirect Management of Port\nOperations\nLeasing of Port Infrastructure\nShare of revenue earned by\nPrivate sector.\nBurden on Port\nAuthority\nHigh \tLow\nPrelims MCQ\nThe Government has highlighted the need to move from “Service\nPort” Model to “Landlord Port” Model for higher efficiency for major\nports. \tWhich \tamong \tthe \tfollowing \tbest \texplains \tLandlord \tPort\nModel?\n(a) \tPrivatization of Major Ports\n(b) \tLeasing of entire Port along with the Land to the Private sector\nfor its development.\n(c) \tGovernment \tretains \townership \tof \tPorts \twhile \tthe \tterminal\nOperations are leased to the Private sector.\n(d) \tGovernment \tretains \townership \tof \tports \talong \twith \tthe\nmanagement of Terminal Operations.\n\nBy: Basava Uppin\tShipping Building Industry\nShip Building Industry\nShipbuilding Financial Assistance Policy (SBFAP):\n• \tFinancial Assistance in the range of 20% to 11% of the value of ships to shipyards for building\nshipping fleet in India.\n• \tThe scheme was supposed to end on March 2026. However, the scheme has been extended\nuntil March 31, 2036.\n• \tIt also includes the Ship breaking Credit note which provides for credit of 40% of the ship's\nscrap value. National Ship building mission will be established to oversee the implementation.\nLarge ships above a specified size will be included in the infrastructure harmonized master list\n(","id":488,"minedAnswer":true}];